<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S RECOVERY STARTED WITH COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three weeks ago, they were on the brink of NCAA
Tournament elimination, they had lost six of seven, and they were
spiraling toward one of the worst seasons in modern school history.
The players were confused and discouraged. The coaches were under
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the UCLA Bruins have a six-game winning streak. They're
in the tournament as the No. 6 seed in the Midwest, and they're one
of the hottest teams in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   How have they turned it around? Just as JaRon Rush's 24-game
absence wasn't the only reason for their struggles, his return
isn't the only reason for their success.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching has something to do with it. In particular, four moves
have fueled UCLA's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The practices: Since the Bruins staggered home from Arizona,
their practices have been more efficient and more demanding.
Attention to detail is at a three-year high. Intensity is soaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches' preparation helps our preparation, and they've
really been on their game,'' forward Rico Hines said. ``We were
focused at the beginning of the season, but the last three weeks
there's been a sense of urgency. That's the biggest turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Lavin's best move was dusting off the grueling
``60-point game,'' an old favorite designed to improve
ballhandling. There are two teams of five. Offense gets one point
per pass. No dribbling allowed. Possession changes on turnovers.
Loser runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drill is about passing, cutting, staying low and
pivoting,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   After the 45-turnover weekend in Arizona, Lavin ordered the
60-point game for the first time this season. In the six games
since, the Bruins have cut their turnovers to 15.6 per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a little crazy sometimes,'' Rush said, ``and the
60-point game has taught us to take care of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense: The Bruins installed a new offense in October (the
1-4 high) that's designed to exploit big men Dan Gadzuric and
Jerome Moiso in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   In early February, after weeks of inconsistency, UCLA returned
to the freewheeling motion offense it had used for years.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, the Bruins ran nothing but motion - and committed 45
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   After Arizona, Lavin re-committed to the 1-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard offense, and it takes time to learn,'' said
assistant Jim Saia, who oversees the offense. ``The guys struggled
with it and didn't believe in it. But once we got back from Arizona
and showed them the 1-4 is how we beat North Carolina and Purdue,
they bought into it. They were searching for answers, and we had a
reference point for success.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 1-4 attack the Bruins have run recently is not the 1-4
they ran earlier in the season. After the Arizona trip, Saia and
Lavin made two crucial adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   First, they stationed players in predetermined spots around the
3-point line - instead of letting them float to openings. This has
allowed Gadzuric and Moiso to make instantaneous passes when the
double-teams arrive - they don't waste time locating teammates -
and greatly enhanced offensive flow.
</P>
<P>
   Second, they eliminated stagnation by ordering Gadzuric and
Moiso to dive from the top of the key, where they aren't threats to
score, to the low post, where they do the most damage. Both have
thrived in the revised attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson we learned is that instead of abandoning the 1-4,
we needed to fix it,'' Saia said. ``The way the offense looked at
Stanford is the way it's supposed to look.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense: Just as the Bruins committed to the 1-4 offense
when they returned from Arizona, so did they commit to an
aggressive defense. The compact 2-3 zone deployed earlier in the
season is gone. Pressure man-to-man - a long-standing UCLA approach
- is back.
</P>
<P>
   The results are irrefutable: Pac-10 opponents shot 46 percent
from the field in the first 12 games; in the last six, they're
shooting 41.3 percent. (UCLA's improved ballhandling has helped the
defense, since fewer turnovers mean fewer fast-break opportunities
for the opponent.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The zone worked against a few teams, but some were able to
pick it apart,'' said assistant Steve Spencer, who oversees the
defense. ``In the last few weeks, coach Lavin has really emphasized
ball pressure. We've increased it all over the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, when you're backed into a corner like we were, you come
out swinging, and for us, that means ball pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The point guard: No player has improved more in recent weeks
than point guard Earl Watson. During the six-game winning streak,
Watson has 37 assists and 16 turnovers, and he's shooting
44.4-percent from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive adjustments have helped. So did inserting point
guard Ryan Bailey into the lineup for several games; his presence
reduced Watson's ballhandling responsibilities and allowed him to
relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even his demeanor with his teammates has been different, and
his on-court conversations have been different,'' assistant Michael
Holton said. ``Once Earl relaxed, the team did the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important ingredient in Watson's development
was a series of discussions with Holton, who played point guard for
UCLA from 1980-83. They talked about leadership, decision-making
and point-guard philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've definitely helped,'' Watson said. ``The information he
gives me is as important as my experience. When things weren't
going well earlier, it was a real challenge. Talking with Coach
Holton has made me feel more comfortable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
