<HEADLINE>
MARICHAL PITCHER PERFECT AS MARTINEZ ROLE MODEL 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ This is how it was in the
old days: You're a 20-year-old Dominican whose prior travel
experiences consisted of trips to Puerto Rico, Aruba, and Mexico.
Now you find yourself being paid to play baseball in Michigan City,
Ind. The April weather, of course, was a nightmare. But that wasn't
the worst of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two of us Dominicans on the team,'' recalls the
young man in question. ``Myself and Jose Tartabull. We didn't even
know how to say `glass of water.' We would go to a restaurant and
look to see what was on people's plates. If we saw something we
liked we would point to it and ask for the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching was always the easy part for Juan Marichal. He won 21
games for that 1958 Michigan City team (``Don't forget the two wins
in the playoffs''), and that was the springboard to Cooperstown.
Marichal remains the most decorated Latin American pitcher who has
ever lived. He won 243 games. He was a six-time 20-game winner. He
was a supreme stylist. And he is the only Latin-born pitcher to be
enshrined in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   What pleases him now is the knowledge that he will not be the
last.
</P>
<P>
   What pleases the Red Sox is that they enjoy the services of
another Dominican-born pitcher who, barring injury, someday will be
a Hall of Fame member.
</P>
<P>
   And what further pleases Marichal is that he can claim a measure
of responsibility for Pedro Martinez's success on more than one
level. He certainly served as a model by becoming the first
successful Dominican pitcher in the big leagues, and he even played
a role in Pedro committing himself to the Red Sox after the trade
that brought him from Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Duquette came here and talked to me,'' Marichal said. ``He
wanted me to talk to Pedro to see if I could convince Pedro to sign
with the Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, this seems like a reach. Marichal wasn't Luis
Tiant. He didn't spend seven-plus years in Boston, as Looie did. He
wore the Red Sox uniform briefly in 1974; that's all. But they
apparently were good days.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time the Red Sox had Roger Moret, Luis Tiant, and
Diego Segui,'' Marichal says. ``We had a group of Latin pitchers,
and we were all treated very well. To me, the Red Sox were one of
the best organizations back then, and I know Dan (Duquette) very
well, and he's a gentleman.''
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn might disagree, but we digress . . .
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is hardly the second coming of Marichal, style-wise.
Then again, no one is. Marichal was noted for his extraordinarily
high leg kick, and for his variety of release points. He could
throw straight overhand, three-quarters, or sidearm. Pedro's motion
is more conventionally compact.
</P>
<P>
   But the elder master maintains there definitely is a major
similarity between himself and the new Dominican Dandy in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Pedro prepares himself for every game very well, and I
used to do that, too,'' Marichal says. ``I used to go to bed early
the night before I pitched. I used to take care of myself and keep
myself in top condition. You have to make sacrifices in your
lifestyle, give up the discos and things like that. In order to be
successful, you have to give up a lot of things, and Pedro is
willing to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Marichal had the standard repertoire, enhanced by his variety of
release points. But he says his out pitch, the one that kept him in
the majors so long, was his screwball. That pitch is supposed to be
an arm-killer, but Marichal says throwing it never bothered him
because ``I threw it by using my shoulder to turn, and not just by
using my arm from my wrist to my elbow.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been well-documented, Pedro's out pitch is his
devastating changeup, which Marichal admires because it starts out
low and then drops even lower. Beyond the equipment, Marichal says
he and Pedro have the same understanding of how to get guys out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret of pitching is to throw strikes, to study the
hitter, to throw the ball where he can't hit it, or, if he does hit
it, to make sure he doesn't hit it with power,'' said Marichal. ``I
think Pedro has studied everything about pitching. That's why he's
so great.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is 27, with 107 career wins. He is getting better and
better, with a 42-11 record in Boston and two Cy Young Awards in
the past three years. Marichal never won a Cy Young Award himself,
primarily because some of his prime years were spent competing with
the likes of Sandy Koufax and Bob Gibson, but there are many who
believe he was the best righthander of the past four decades. As
the years go on, the comparisons between the two will become more
and more compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Marichal is no old fuddy-duddy, extolling the superior virtues
of the old vs. the new. He is proud to have played in a wonderful
baseball era, but he is very willing to give Pedro his just due.
``I would rank Pedro right at the top of the list,'' Marichal said.
``He is right up there with everyone. If Pedro were playing in our
days, I think he would be doing the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Times are different for the young Dominican ballplayers. If they
are selected to attend one of the many baseball academies, they get
to spend a couple of years studying English, learning about good
nutrition, and, of course, honing their baseball skills before
being sent to the United States. Teams are far more enlightened and
sensitive to the cultural travails of the young Dominicans than
they were in Marichal's day.
</P>
<P>
   But not knowing anything about America didn't stop Juan Marichal
from becoming Juan Marichal, who was great not just because of what
hung from his right shoulder, but also because of what beat inside
his chest.
</P>
<P>
   That's another reason Marichal can identify with Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I played, I felt like I was in heaven, because I was
playing baseball,'' Marichal says. ``There are some players who do
it because they get paid. You look at Pedro and you can see he does
it because he loves it.''
</P>
<P>
   Please remember that, as good as Pedro is, he's still got a ways
to go before he becomes Juan Marichal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
