<HEADLINE>
DESPITE OFFENSIVE WOES, KINGS STAY IN CHASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The last time Vancouver followed Calgary on their
schedule, the Los Angeles Kings were rolling on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Back on Feb. 23 the Kings routed the Flames 7-2, then came back
and beat the Canucks 5-2. It gave them four victories in the first
six games on their last road trip. But it also marked the end one
of their better scoring stretches of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kings continue to head toward a Western Conference
playoff spot, their scoring drought has in some ways overshadowed
their success.
</P>
<P>
   They are 3-3-1 since their victory in Vancouver, a pace that
virtually guarantees them the sixth seed and a first-round matchup
with either Colorado or Edmonton. Not bad for a team that has
failed to reach the postseason five of the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is that lack of playoff experience that keeps the Kings
bandwagon from filling up. Heading into tonight's game against the
Canucks at Staples Center, the Kings are 2-1 in their last three
games. They also have had a five-on-three power play four times and
failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to block out everything that is said and keep
working hard,'' Luc Robitaille said. ``I think we've done a good
job of that. We're not scoring, but we're winning games. I'll take
that anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's workout in El Segundo, Kings coach Andy Murray
answered repeated questions about the faulty power play until
stopping to ask, ``We did win last night, didn't we?''
</P>
<P>
   But since scoring three power-play goals against Calgary almost
three weeks ago, the Kings have three in the last eight games. They
went 0 for 8 Saturday vs. the Flames, are 0 for 19 in their last
three games and are in a 2-for-35 slump.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the Kings are holding steady in the standings is
their penalty-killing unit, In the last six games, they have killed
off 26 of 30.
</P>
<P>
   But a closer look at the offense shows the Kings' top
goal-scorers have not been producing overall. Robitaille does not
have a goal in four games and just one in his last eight. Ziggy
Palffy scored the Kings' first goal Saturday, but it was his first
in five games. Second-line center Bryan Smolinski had an
empty-netter Thursday, his first goal in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Against Calgary, Murray inserted his checking line into the
power-play rotation, playing Ian Laperriere, Craig Johnson and
Marko Tuomainen. They didn't score, but Murray liked their energy
on the ice and said he wouldn't mind doing it again.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Kings virtually play every other day for the rest of
the regular season, there is little time for on-ice power-play
tinkering. It was brought up in Sunday's team meeting, but Murray
has been trying to conserve the team's energy by keeping them off
the ice between games.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, the Kings held often-grueling practices
between games and lightened up on the day-of-game morning workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we go harder on the days of games,'' Murray said. ``We're
in a playoff run. No one said it would be easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
