<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-76ERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDEN STOPS KEEP CELTICS ON GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Suddenly, it's fun to watch the Celtics again. After a
season of mostly despair, they are making converts of those who
only a week ago refused to believe they had a legitimate, although
slim, playoff possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Before a sellout crowd of 18,624 Sunday, the Celtics had no
trouble in a 93-77 matinee rout of the Philadelphia 76ers. It was
Boston's fourth straight victory, tying a season high. The 76ers
fell behind early and were never a serious threat again as the
defense-minded Celtics (27-35) smothered Allen Iverson and Co. like
few have done this year.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Paul Pierce and Antoine Walker led the Celtics'
offense, combining for 54 points. Walker had 25 points and 13
rebounds, shaking off the effects of a sore left foot that cost him
about eight minutes in the second quarter. Boston also got an
11-point effort off the bench from Tony Battie.
</P>
<P>
   But this win was mostly about the defense, led by Calbert
Cheaney, who was all over Iverson (21 points, 8-of-18 shooting).
The Celtics had 14 steals. Toni Kukoc, recently acquired by
Philadelphia from Chicago, played 25 minutes and scored just 6
points. The 76ers are a solid playoff team. But the Celtics have
vowed that nobody is going to dominate them in their home. However,
seven of the next nine games, including Monday night's in Detroit,
are on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had been playing like this the whole season,'' said
Walker. ``Every time they made a run, we made a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Celtics ran away from the Bulls, 104-74, and
few expected they could improve on that performance. But when
Boston rolled to a 31-21 lead after the first period, it became
clear the Celtics had continued their emphasis on defense.
Philadelphia got within 6 in the third period, 61-55. But Boston
went on a 12-2 run for a 73-57 lead and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played better than us,'' said Philadelphia coach Larry
Brown. ``We shot 50 percent from the line and they (hurt) us on the
boards. You can't be a pro team and shoot 50 percent from the line.
I think the Celtics played with a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheaney and Dana Barros were on Iverson like glue. By being
aggressive, switching off, and keeping Iverson from penetrating the
middle, the Celtics were able to keep the 76ers off their normal
game. They made it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philadelphia is a wonderful team that if you play half-court
against, you're going to come up losers,'' said Boston coach Rick
Pitino. ``We had to play the up-tempo game against them. We're a
very good team when we have time to go over the other team's
offense. We can cover for each other. But there is nobody else who
can excel one-on-one better than Calbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the team evolving into something that I didn't see in
the first half of the season. Steals are the result of knowing the
other team's offense, having good vision, and putting good pressure
on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure could have been on the Celtics. Walker had to leave
at 11:23 of the second after suffering a sprain of his left foot.
At 4:35, Walker strolled back onto the court with a smile on his
face. His teammates had built a 15-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, they said it was like (Danny Fortson's) injury,''
said Pitino, ``A possible fracture. I'm glad it was only a sprain.
I'm not surprised he came back. Some players play with pain, some
don't. Since I've known him at Kentucky, he's always played in
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Good defense is no accident, added Pitino, who pointed out
Philadelphia's lack of second-chance points.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this stretch, we have played great team defense,'' he said.
``When someone came down the lane, we choked it down. We waited so
long for this, to set up in the lanes. To have five men react.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said he's played in pain before. ``It's just something I
had to block out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce said if the Celtics expect to make the playoffs, they
must do it with the kind of effort of the last four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, it's been a lot of fun,'' he said. ``We're really
coming together. The guys are helping out each other. We're
listening to our coaches and then going out and executing. We don't
get down when we lose Antoine. All that means is that other guys
have to step up, and that's what we're doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
