<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ENJOYING THEMSELVES LATELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rob Tallas can't pinpoint exactly when the day came,
only that he knows it arrived recently. He can't put his finger on
the single moment, the final straw, the split second when the
Bruins got so tired of losing, so weary of negativity, so fed up
with every god-awful thing that has happened to the club this year.
</P>
<P>
   The young goalie can't say just when that happened, only that it
did, and for the last three games the Bruins have decided the
pressure is off. They've decided they're going to enjoy themselves
rather than brood over what could've been. It took a long time to
get there, but there they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a point and we've talked about that point,'' said
Tallas, who backstopped Boston to a 5-3 win over the Canadiens in
Montreal Saturday night. ``We've tried to address it, going back
months, saying, `Let's try to relax and have fun.' Then all of a
sudden, something happens wrong and everything tightens up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy is so high right now. You have to remember, a lot
of these guys played in Providence last year on a championship
team. They're up here getting a chance and they're flying. We've
done that the last three games, it's awesome to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the laughter and how much fun the guys are having and
it's real fun. Before, we were making it up and trying to (force
it). It was fake fun. Now, it's for real and it's enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathematically, the Bruins still have a shot at making the
playoffs. Realistically, it's the longest of long shots since
Boston is six points out of a playoff spot with 13 games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Tallas said no matter what happens, there are no long faces,
there is no moping. There was the stunning period when Ray Bourque
announced he wanted to be dealt away from Boston after nearly 21
years, but the team weathered that loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the game and we know about trades,'' said Tallas.
``With Ray, I think we were just more or less happy to see him go
somewhere to get an opportunity rather than think, `We have really
lost a big part of our team, we're in trouble.' We were already in
trouble. So it was `Congratulations, Ray, and good luck to you.' I
don't think there was a lot of sadness or a down point.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns, under fire for much of the year, has seemed
much more relaxed lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a lot of pressure on us,'' said Burns. ``The
pressure is a lot on the other teams. (Our players are) having fun.
I let them have fun. I tried to put in a system that's a little bit
easier for them. We've changed so many times this year, we've had
so many players. We've had 38 different players playing on our
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to have a system that everybody understands and
everybody believes in when you have 38 guys going through one
hockey club. We've tried to put something together and they believe
in it. Until the other team figures it out, we'll have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can be sure if, in their last three games, during which
the Bruins earned five of a possible six points, their opponents
took them lightly. But perception, as well as the Bruins' play,
could have had an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a team like us coming in, they look at our lineup and
they go, `They've got seven or eight guys from the American League,
this is going to be easy,' '' said Burns. ``All of a sudden, we go
out there and play our hearts out and you win hockey games.''
</P>
<P>
   But can they win enough to extend the season beyond April 9? It
seems highly unlikely, but the team is feeling optimistic enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this team were to make the playoffs . . . what a turnaround
and what an experience for all of us,'' said Tallas. ``We would
officially be the Bad News Bears if we did make the playoffs. I
think guys are just enjoying it. No one is really talking about the
playoffs. It's more about keeping the feeling we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The newest Bruin, Mike Knuble, who came to Boston from the
Rangers in exchange for Rob DiMaio, made his debut against Montreal
and logged more than 20 minutes and picked up an assist. It was a
lot more work than he was getting with the Rangers and it left
Knuble sucking serious wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not used to getting all the ice time,'' said Burns with a
chuckle. ``Every guy I seem to get that plays on the third or
fourth lines on other teams end up on the second line of our club.
They're playing power plays and killing penalties and their tongues
are sticking out. But they'll adapt.''
</P>
<P>
   Knuble said it's early, but he feels very comfortable with his
new team despite the fatigue factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last bit in New York, I hadn't played nearly that much,''
said Knuble. ``But it was great. I enjoyed every second of it. It
was fun. It was a while since I've had fun playing hockey. The guys
played their hardest. I was pretty impressed. To come here and get
a chance, it's great. That's what you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said the addition of forward Brian Rolston, who came from
Colorado in the Bourque deal, has made a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian has been really good for us,'' said the coach. ``He's
fit in well and he's shown a little bit of leadership which we
needed. He's not a centerman. I'm playing him there because I don't
have any right now. I asked him if he could do the job and he said,
`I'll do anything you want me to do,' and he's been doing a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Knuble said he was more used to being across the ice from
Rolston rather than on the same side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always kicking our (butt),'' said Knuble. ``His team
always seemed to get the better end when I was at Michigan and he
was at Lake Superior State. He's a hell of a player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
