u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-OVERTON-B     03-13 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-OVERTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERTON EATS UP THIS ASSIGNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Saturday night, Philadelphia-born-and-bred Doug Overton
went to dinner with some of his old friends from the 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   Around 2 o'clock Sunday, though, Overton handed the visitors
their lunch _ a long 3-point jumper late in the third quarter that
so upset former teammate Eric Snow that he slammed the basketball
to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Sixers coach Larry Brown, who waived Overton last fall, called a
quick timeout, but the damage had been done. What had been a Philly
comeback that cut an 18-point Celtics lead to 6, was blunted by
Overton's bomb that increased Boston's lead to 67-55, part of a
10-0 Boston flurry en route to its 93-77 victory at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   With Kenny Anderson in early foul trouble and Dana Barros also
picking up three quickies, Overton logged 19 minutes, including the
key third-quarter stretch. He played more minutes than Anderson
(15) or Barros (14).
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old veteran, who played at Dobbins Tech and La Salle
University in his hometown, could afford to joke about his
otherwise bricklayer-like performance _ just 1 for 11 from the
floor _ while taking pride in his only points of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was really looking at me and I'm glad I made it because
I missed everything else, I had nothing to lose,'' said Overton,
who was signed as a free agent Nov. 8 and who appeared with
Orlando, Philadelphia, and New Jersey last season. ``It was a good
play at the right time, though. We built some momentum from that
play on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That felt good, being from Philly, and my job was to just get
out there and run and help keep the tempo up,'' added Overton, who
dribbled out the final seconds, then stopped near the Sixers bench
and offered a friendly wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a playoff team that's fighting for home position,''
said Overton, a second-round pick of the Pistons who was with
Philadelphia for the 1996 and 1997 seasons. ``We should be proud of
the way we played against them, especially Cal Cheaney and the job
he did on Allen Iverson.''
</P>
<P>
   Overton sees many of the Sixers every summer, and adds, ``I've
got a lot of friends on that team. We hung out together last night.
I learned a lot from Coach Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Being third man in at the point is tough, he acknowledged, ``but
that's the beauty of a day like this. It makes you feel good, and
besides there are still a lot of guys who'd like my job. I've just
got to be ready at all times. Unfortunately, Kenny and Dana got in
foul trouble, but it gave me a chance to play.''
</P>
<P>
   That was just the role Celtics general manager Chris Wallace
envisioned for Overton, who was urged by captain Antoine Walker to
keep taking the ball to the basket and keep the Sixers' defense
off-balance. Walker said Overton played a ``huge'' game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to come in at a moment's notice and being a third guard
is a lot different than being a third quarterback holding a
clipboard,'' said Wallace. ``Kenny had injury problems in the past,
as had Dana, and that's the reason we brought an experienced point
guard like Doug in and let (rookie) Wayne Turner go. We looked
around at the experienced point guards and we felt more comfortable
with his overall package, not to mention his several thousand
minutes in the NBA pilot's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He not only helped hold the fort today, he was in there when
we lengthened the lead,'' Wallace added. ``And, of course, he knows
that team so well.''
</P>
<P>
   And Overton, who said, ``I've got a lot of love for those guys
from Philly,'' proved it Sunday with his 3-point goodbye kiss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
