<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA DEBUT A HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Start the season tomorrow, Nomar Garciaparra
said, and he'd be ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   After missing the team's first 10 days of games because of a
sprained collateral ligament in his right knee, it took Garciaparra
just three pitches Sunday to collect his first hit of the spring, a
line single to center field off Phillies starter Paul Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not fully ready,'' Garciaparra said, ``but if the season
were opening tomorrow, I probably would have played in some games
last week. But we were just playing it safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, the defending American League batting champion, is
not scheduled to travel with the team to Jupiter Monday for its
game with the Expos, but will be back in the lineup Tuesday, when
Jimy Williams may have a chance to unveil the lineup he'll use on
Opening Day April 4 in Seattle. Don't be surprised to see
Garciaparra hitting cleanup behind Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it doesn't matter,'' said Garciaparra, who had expressed
to Everett a preference for hitting in the No. 4 hole, which is
where he hit last season. ``Maybe Jimy will sit down with us and
ask us, see what he wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The game takes on a certain rhythm for a player depending on
where he hits in the order, Garciaparra said. If he prefers the
4-hole now, he said, it's only because ``I'm used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Sox batting around in a seven-run first, Garciaparra,
who was hitting leadoff, popped to short on his second turn through
the order, then came out of the game after three innings. That was
the plan all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to see him out there,'' said Sox pitcher Tim
Wakefield, ``although on a couple of throws it looked like he
hadn't picked up a ball in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was charged with an error when he bounced a throw to
novice first baseman Gary Gaetti on Kevin Jordan's grounder in the
first, and was spared another error when Gaetti dug out another low
throw on Jordan's grounder in the third. But on the next play,
Garciaparra went into the hole and delivered one of his patented
across-the-body throws while on the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an easier ball, if you ask me,'' said Garciaparra, who
attributed the error to feeling ``antsy'' before his first game
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was asked about Pat Burrell, the Phillies phenom who
was No. 1 overall in the 1998 draft and hit a double and home run
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a great player and he's a good guy,'' said
Garciaparra, who first met Burrell when Burrell was still at the
University of Miami. ``And he has good size. Geez, they keep making
'em bigger. That's why I keep busting my butt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
