<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, March 13.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WINE (Shanghai) _ Red wine is the drink of the moment in
China, and winemakers around the world are feeling the effects.
Demand for wine picked up after the government began promoting
fruit-based alcohol a few years ago, and Western winemakers rushed
in, shipping wine in giant 22,000 liter containers. But now the
Chinese want domestic wine, so much of the Western supply is being
sold at happy-hour prices by Customs after sitting for months in
government warehouses. This isn't doing much for the wine
exporters, and it isn't exactly helping the Chinese develop a taste
for the grape. It's common for Chinese wine drinkers to mix red
wine with Sprite and white with Coke and to drink the concoctions
in gulps. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-COMMUNISTS (Moscow) _ The March 26 election to pick a new
president finds Russia's Communists once again in a swelter about
the pasting they are about to receive and what to do about their
future. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HUDSON-VALLEY-INDUSTRY (Undated) _ Decades after smokestack
industries largely disappeared from the Hudson River valley,
leaving behind an environmental and economic mess, plans are afoot
to build more than a dozen industrial plants in the region. Some
welcome the return of manufacturing. Others say it threatens to
undermine years of effort to reclaim the Hudson from industrial
pollution. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-KIDS (Detroit) _ A couple of Detroit lawyers have
chucked their law careers to start an unusual bait-and-switch
program that helps poor children join the information age. They
lure hundreds of children into after-school sports leagues, then
offer older children 20 free hours of computer training. The
children learn not only how to use the computers, but how to take
them apart, fix them, and put them together again. The trophy the
children bring home is a used computer _ there are enough for
everyone on the sports teams who is interested in getting one. By
Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-PRIMARIES (Atlanta) _ The primary season effectively
ended last week, when the leading challengers in the Republican and
Democratic parties dropped out after losing on Super Tuesday,
leaving uncontested races on both the Republican and Democratic
sides. But to the disgust of many in the South, the already
scheduled presidential primaries in Florida, Tennessee,
Mississippi, Louisiana, Oklahoma and Texas will still go on, even
though they no longer serve any practical purpose. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIRWAVES _ As the airwaves grow ever more congested with modern
wireless communications, the federal government is developing plans
to open up the spectrum by, in effect, treating its frequencies as
commodities to be bought and sold as routinely as pork bellies or
soybeans in the open market. Exclusive. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   WHITEWATER-REPORT _ Beginning as early as this week, the special
prosecutor for Whitewater matters, Robert W. Ray, will begin filing
a series of final reports. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   RICHARDSON-PROFILE _ Profile of Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson. By Philip Shenon.
