<P>
   RUSSIA-JOURNALISTS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Swashbuckling Soviet
journalist, who emulated Michael Herr's style in writing about the
war in Afghanistan, dies in a plane crash this week. In the early
days of glasnost, he was given free rein to cover the front. In
contrast, a Russian journalist was recently punished for his frank
coverage of Chechnya. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-CIRCUS (Changjon, North Korea) _ The circus has been a
very popular form of entertainment in socialist countries,
particularly in the former Soviet Union, because everyone,
including laborers and farmers, can easily understand and enjoy it,
unlike operas and classical music performances. Whatever its
function in a Communist country, the Moranbong Circus, which has
won international acclaim for its artistry and acts of skill and
daring, lived up to its billing in a recent 90-minute performance
of eye-popping acrobatics that seemed to thrill the audience. By
Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   HEADE-PROFILE (Washington) _ A look at the first big Martin
Johnson Heade survey in 30 years and only the second ever
assembled. It has been organized by Theodore E. Stebbins Jr., a
leading Heade scholar and former curator at the Museum of Fine Arts
Boston, where it was seen last fall. The show comes with a detailed
catalog and coincides with the publication of Stebbins' magnum
opus, ``The Life and Work of Martin Johnson Heade: A Critical
Analysis and Catalogue Raisonne.'' The show and books provide a
great deal of information about Heade (pronounced heed), who was a
busy man and turned out not only hundreds of paintings but dozens
of articles for the magazine Forest and Stream under the pen name
Didymus. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NY-THEATERS (New York) _ In the late 1970s, when Times Square
belonged to the prostitutes and peep shows, a collection of theater
companies moved into a handful of stages carved out of shuttered
massage parlors on West 42nd Street. In the years that followed,
the theaters suffered through stickups, recessions and aborted
development projects and survived to see a renewed Midtown rise
around them. But now the redevelopment of 42nd Street is altering
the theaters' future. The local development corporation that helped
create the strip now known as Theater Row is closing four of the
playhouses as it prepares to break ground on an apartment tower and
collection of new stages west of the area. By Julian E. Barnes.
</P>
