<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER NO. 1 DOESN'T FAZE UCONN 
</HEADLINE>
 WOMEN'S TOURNEY-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Let others whoop and holler. The nation's No. 1 women's
team treated Selection Sunday just as nervelessly as it would an
overmatched opponent in a regular-season game.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there were hands slapped and glasses raised across
the country as the 64 participants in the NCAA women's basketball
tournament were revealed Sunday, but in Storrs, Conn., it was a
relaxed group of Huskies who watched the ESPN telecast and learned
that they were being joined by five other New England schools.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, it was a windfall for schools within the six-state
region, but for Boston College, hopes of hosting a sub-regional
were dashed when the Eagles were seded fifth in the Mideast
Regional and forced to travel to Knoxville, Tenn., and a
first-round game against Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The near-annual ritual of gaining a No. 1 seed, which has been
awarded to UConn six of the last seven years, along with a host
site for the first two rounds, hasn't created any drama for either
the Huskies or their near-obsessive fans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at times it appeared the UConn players and coaches were
taking notes in class rather than learning who they'd be playing as
their chase for a national championship begins to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   How casual was it? A 30-1 record and start-to-finish No. 1
ranking prompted Geno Auriemma to break a cardinal rule for any
coach _ to look past his team's potentially first four tournament
games and to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that it is in Philadelphia makes it special,'' said
Auriemma, a native of the city. ``It also brings more pressure. Now
we have a chance to win the national championship . . . in front of
my family and friends.'
</P>
<P>
   Still, the news that the Huskies drew 16th-seeded Hampton in
Friday's first round of the East Regional at Gampel Pavilion
elicited the requisite responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to know that not only are we in the
tournament, we're the No. 1 seed,'' said junior Shea Ralph, who
celebrated her 22d birthday Sunday. ``To know we're going in as the
No. 1 team in the nation for the entire year, it gives us a little
bit of confidence, and hopefully we'll play like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are uncontrollables in the tournament,'' said Auriemma.
``Any team that wins the tournament has to feel they got a break.
I'm like everyone else, I've got my fingers crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to believe that the Huskies are fretting about the
prospect of playing the Lady Pirates, who have only been a Division
1 team since 1995. They're in the tourney with a 16-14 record
thanks to winning the first Mid-Eastern Athletic title.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play all season long to get to the NCAA tournament,''
Auriemma said. ``Our players are ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know anything can happen,'' said sophomore forward Tamika
Williams. ``You just have to go up and play every night.''
</P>
<P>
   For UConn, which is making its 12th NCAA appearance, the tourney
will afford the opportunity to make up for last year's
disappointing postseason. The Huskies nearly lost a second-round
game in Storrs and were blown out in the Round of 16 by Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies' second-round opponent would be the winner of No. 8
Drake (23-6) and No. 9 Clemson (18-11). The winner moves on to play
in Richmond. There are no rematches with any regular-season
opponent on the Huskies' tourney schedule _ except for potentially
one.
</P>
<P>
   If UConn does go to the Final Four for the third time _ but
first since 1996 _ and win its second national title, there is the
potential for a championship game against Tennessee, the No. 1 seed
in the Mideast Region.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols, who are a top seed for the 13th time and a
six-time national champ, handed the Huskies their only loss by a
point in late January at Gampel Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the seedings were as easy as 1-2-3-4. Tennessee (28-3),
the nation's No. 2 team, was joined as a No. 1 seed by third-ranked
Louisiana Tech (28-2) in the Midwest and fourth-ranked Georgia
(29-3) in the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern Conference, as usual, has the most teams with
six, but the Big 12 matched that. It's the first time since 1992
that another conference has as many teams as the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic Coast Conference landed five teams. The Big East,
Big Ten, and Pacific-10 each has four.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee and Louisiana Tech are the only teams to play in all
19 NCAA tournaments since the women's division started play in
1982. Georgia will be playing in its 17th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
