<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAATOURNAMENT-BO     03-13 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH NO CLEAR FAVORITE, IT'S OPEN SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
 TOURNAMENT-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ So now it is crunch time in the college basketball
season, the one-and-done phase known as the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Moreso than any other season in recent memory, it truly seems to
be an ``open'' tournament, with as many as nine teams capable of
putting together a six-game winning streak starting Thursday or
Friday and concluding three weeks hence in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates? Start with Duke, still regal after all these
years, able to come back from the early defection of the core of
last year's national runner-up to climb back to No. 1, not only in
the Atlantic Coast Conference, but perhaps in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils breezed through the ACC regular season and
topped that off Sunday with a tough win over Maryland in the ACC
tournament final.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Michigan State, the preseason No. 1 in many
corners, back near the top after adjusting to an early-season
injury to All-America point guard Mateen Cleaves, then adjusting
again when he came back.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the champion will emerge from the West Coast, where
Stanford and Arizona staged a season-long duel that Arizona won in
the final week. Both have the credentials, the coaching necessary
to at least reach the Final Four, and No. 1 seeds, Arizona in the
West, Stanford in the South.
</P>
<P>
   For sentimentalists, there is Temple, coached by wise old Owl
John Chaney, who may have his best team and his best chance to
reach the elusive Final Four. Temple is always tough and ornery but
this year's team can shoot, and that is a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   Before last Thursday, the odds-on favorite to win it all was
Cincinnati. But when All-American and Player of the Year candidate
Kenyon Martin suffered a broken leg during a Conference USA
tournament loss to Saint Louis, the Bearcats became damaged goods
in many minds. Cincinnati was tucked in as the No. 2 seed in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps another magical story will be written out of Storrs,
Conn., this season. Coach Jim Calhoun's Connecticut Huskies started
out on top as defending national champions, went through a
midseason slump, and have started to pick up the pace to a
championship level again, their 80-70 loss to St. John's in the Big
East tournament final Saturday night notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine,'' Calhoun said after the loss to St. John's. ``We
just came up empty emotionally, which happens when you play four
games in four days. But that's behind us now. We're playing well
and I think we're ready to make another run.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the Huskies do, they will have to do it coming
from off the pace. They are the No. 5 seed in the South, which
could be worse because UConn probably matches up best against the
South's Stanford among the No. 1 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   If not UConn or one of the top seeds, then who? Maybe the Final
Four will again have a New England flavor with the presence of Ohio
State, featuring coach Jim O'Brien and guard Scoonie Penn, both
formerly of Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   The Buckeyes surprised most by reaching the Final Four last
season. They have not lost much and have gained experience. Don't
bet against them making a strong run, coming out of the South,
although they will have to contend with in-state rival Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Also look out for St. John's, dubbed Team Turmoil by some after
all the internal squabbling and NCAA investigations of guard Erick
Barkley. The Red Storm, seeded second in the West, are talented
enough to beat anyone, but whether they have the depth and poise to
handle it all remains uncertain. Thus far, they seem to have the
right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe a sleeper will emerge. But remember: Since the NCAA
started seeding its tournament in 1979, only three teams seeded
lower than No. 4 have won it all _ No. 6 North Carolina State beat
Houston in 1983, No. 8 Villanova beat Georgetown in 1985, and No. 6
Kansas beat Oklahoma in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   So the field is set. Fill out those brackets, sit back, and
enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   March Madness is back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
