<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CENTRALCONNECTICUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYCLONE WARNING FOR CENTRAL CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. _ This is for certain: They didn't want
Temple.
</P>
<P>
   When members of the Central Connecticut State basketball team
saw that the second-seeded Owls were playing 15th-seeded Lafayette
in the first round of the NCAA tournament, they rendered a
collective sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Devils players were more upbeat _ though not elated _ when
they saw the school name flash across the screen as the 15th seed
in the Midwest, slated to play second-seeded Iowa State Thursday in
Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Central, in its 14th season as a Division 1 team, earned an
automatic bid last Monday when it won the Northeast Conference
tournament. The Blue Devils, who ran off a 15-game win streak this
season, are 25-5, which is a far cry from the team's 4-22 campaign
of two seasons ago while competing in its first year in the
Northeast Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Central, which has approximately 12,000 students, will be making
its first trip to the tournament since moving up to Division 1.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some folks were surprised the Blue Devils didn't show much
emotion when their school's pairing was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because our name was beside Iowa State's,'' said point
guard Rick Mickens. ``They're a team not to be jumping up and down
about playing. They're a good team and they're a No. 2 seed for a
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Still Central players and coaches said they enjoyed Sunday's
festivities. About 200 fans were on hand in the gym to help
celebrate the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the players said they watched Sunday's Iowa
State-Oklahoma contest for the Big 12 championship and were
impressed by the Cyclones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that whoever we played, they were going to be a great
team,'' said coach Howie Dickenman, who was once an assistant at
UConn. ``(The Big 12 is) one of the top conferences, and Iowa State
is the best team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickenman said the team will leave for Minneapolis Tuesday. ``We
going to work hard, and we will be mentally prepared, emotionally
prepared, and physically prepared for the game,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
