<HEADLINE>
DUKE SHOULD MEET MATCH IN TEMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The top half of the bracket should provide Duke with
enough tests to get ready for the bottom half, which will be
extremely tough for the Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   In Winston-Salem, N.C., Duke can relax in its first-round game
against Lamar (No. 16) and the winner of the game between DePaul
(No. 9) and Kansas (No. 8) won't be much of an obstacle. Both teams
are soft and Duke is too good, too quick, and too well-coached.
</P>
<P>
   But the action in Buffalo will be like a combat zone. Temple
(No. 2) is there and the Owls are primed. Lafayette (No. 15) will
be in for a short stay. (Did you check out the first half of the
Owls' win over St. Bonaventure in the Atlantic 10 final?) Then
comes a challenge. Both Oregon (No. 7) and Seton Hall (No. 10) are
dangerous. Seton Hall has not been playing well and Oregon is an
unknown to much of the country. The Ducks won't be after they beat
Seton Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the bracket has a legitimate sleeper in
Oklahoma State (No. 3). Watch out. Eddie Sutton's teams always play
well in March. They are tough, physical, and well-coached. Hofstra
(No. 14) can stay with them, but only for a while. After that, the
winner of Indiana-Pepperdine looms. And watch out for Pepperdine
(No. 11). The Waves can play defense and shoot, and could beat
Indiana (No. 6). They can't beat Oklahoma State, however.
</P>
<P>
   That sets up a massive battle of Oklahoma State and Temple in
the regional semifinal at Syracuse, along with a Duke-Florida
pairing. Sort of beauty and the beast of college basketball. Duke
should be able to handle Florida, but it won't be easy. If Florida
has its running and shooting games going, the Gators could be tough
to handle. But Duke also can play that style and should win in a
shootout of epic proportions. Oklahoma State and Temple will be a
stark contrast and we think the Owls will have enough outside
firepower to overcome the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Temple-Duke. Sounds familiar, doesn't it?
Duke won that matchup a year ago in the East final at the
Meadowlands in a cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   This will be anything but. Duke is not as good. Temple is
better. The Owls can and will win this one and John Chaney can
dance all the way to Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Teams to watch: Pepperdine, Florida
</P>
<P>
   Upset special: Pepperdine over Indiana
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Syracuse: Duke, Florida, Oklahoma State, and Temple
</P>
<P>
   Regional champ: Temple
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
