<HEADLINE>
EASY TRIP AWAITS SPARTANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Someone on the NCAA committee loves Michigan State. How
else to explain this region, which is tilted to the top-seeded
Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   They start with two warmup games in Cleveland. No. 16 Valparaiso
will merely show up and the winner of the game between No. 9 Saint
Louis and No. 8 Utah should not produce much of a challenge. In the
bottom half of the bracket, we have more Jell-O. No. 4 Syracuse has
been struggling. Let's see if the Orangemen can get their game
faces back. They should do it against St. Bonaventure (No. 12) and
probably can beat No. 5 Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Out in Minneapolis, we have more uncertainties. No. 6 UCLA plays
No. 11 Ball State in the first game. The Bruins look like they are
back in form, but that should only last a game as No. 3 Maryland
should be waiting for them. Normally, we're not real high on Gary
Williams's teams in March, but we'll take a flyer and see if they
can beat UCLA, although this one could be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   On the bottom half of the draw, Iowa State sits at No. 2. How
good are the Cyclones? Tough to figure. No. 15 Central Connecticut
could beat them, but could lose by 40. No. 10 Creighton is the team
to watch and is another dangerous opponent in the second-round
game.
</P>
<P>
   The wild-card team here is No. 7 Auburn. The Tigers made a
pretty good run in the SEC tournament without Chris Porter, but ran
out of energy against Arkansas. Or maybe they were saving it.
That's a key question. Auburn, even without Porter, is pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't really matter after that, however, as we'll stick
with some form and assume Maryland and Iowa State emerge. Edge? The
ACC we feel, which will put the Terps in a regional final. That
hasn't happened since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Now things really toughen up for Michigan State. The regional
moves to Auburn Hills, which happens to be in . . . Michigan. The
Spartans should find Syracuse waiting. Michigan State is a team
Syracuse would have trouble beating in Beverly Hills. Maybe that's
too harsh. Jim Boeheim is a better coach than a lot of people
think. But it won't be enough to prevent Michigan State from
getting to the regional finals. And as much as we think Maryland
will play up to the level of its talent, we will not lose our
senses completely. Maryland will not be in the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Team to watch: Creighton
</P>
<P>
   Upset special: Creighton over Auburn
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Auburn Hills: Iowa State, Maryland, Syracuse, and
Michigan State
</P>
<P>
   Regional champ: Michigan State
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
