<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAATOURNAMENT-SOUTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCE SHOULD BE AN ALLY FOR BUCKEYES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Stanford got a No. 1 seed. Fine. But we still feel the
Cardinal (26-3) are the softest of the No. 1s and not as good as
some of the second seeds.
</P>
<P>
   We will find out quickly once play starts at Birmingham, Ala.
Facing No. 16 South Carolina State should be no problem. But after
that things could get dicey. Unless North Carolina (No. 8) is
fooling everyone with its play, the Tar Heels look like a
one-and-done team. Missouri (No. 9) is poised and tough and hungry.
The Tigers win that one and face Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out for an upset. And we haven't even gotten to the other
half of the bracket, much less the winners from the bracket in
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk about UConn. Are the fifth-seeded Huskies ready for a
run? We say yes. It starts with a game against Utah State (No. 12)
and that's dangerous. Utah State is better than people think. After
that, it gets tougher. Tennessee (No. 4) is a strange team to
figure, but the Volunteers should have their act together against
Louisiana-Lafayette (No. 13). Whether the Vols will have it against
UConn remains to be seen. UConn should survive and move on with . .
. Missouri to Austin, Texas, for the regionals.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the draw is filled with danger as well. Ohio
State (No. 3), Cincinnati (No. 2), and Miami (No. 6) are capable of
runs, although the Bearcats without Kenyon Martin remain a question
mark.
</P>
<P>
   UNC-Wilmington (No. 15) will not be much of a problem for
Cincinnati after the game's first few minutes, but Tulsa (No. 7)
and UNLV (No. 10) will be. We love Tulsa's toughness, and the
Golden Hurricane should beat the Runnin' Rebels in a shootout and
will be primed and ready for Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State, which is ready for another Final Four run, got a
decent draw. Appalachian State (No. 14) will be a nice warmup, but
the Buckeyes have too much experience in the backcourt with Scoonie
Penn and Michael Redd. The winner of the Miami-Arkanas game will be
a challenge, however. Miami (No. 6) plays some nasty defense and
Arkansas (No. 11) is on a roll. The good thing for the Buckeyes is
that the winner won't have a whole lot of time to prepare for them.
Advantage: Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   Now we move to Austin. Ohio State vs. Tulsa will be an all-out
war. The difference will have to be in the backcourt. Penn and Redd
again have an edge and don't underestimate the power of coach Jim
O'Brien in close games. He can coach, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in the other half should be UConn, which will be
thanking Missouri for doing its grunt work by taking care of
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies will take care of Missouri, setting up a rematch of
last year's national semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, we feel the edge is with the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   Teams to watch: Missouri, Ohio State, and Utah State
</P>
<P>
   Upset special: Missouri over Stanford
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Austin: Missouri, UConn, Ohio State, and Tulsa
</P>
<P>
   Regional champ: Ohio State
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
