<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA SHOULD AVOID UPSET SPECIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Remember when Arizona was the losing team in everyone's
upset special? Well, those days appear to be over. The top-seeded
Wildcats have turned themselves into a pretty tough team and they
should prove it this year.
</P>
<P>
   First-round game in Salt Lake City: No. 16 Jackson State. Move
on.
</P>
<P>
   Second-round game: the winner of No. 8 Wisconsin and No. 9
Fresno State. Both made surges to get into the NCAA as at-large
entries. Both are decent. Both aren't as good as Arizona. Move on.
</P>
<P>
   That gets the Wildcats to Albuquerque, which is where they will
wait to see who also shows up.
</P>
<P>
   In the other half of the bracket, we think it will be a surprise
team, Indiana State. No Larry Bird is not back. But the No. 12
Sycamores are going to win a game or two. They start with No. 5
Texas. Can't fathom the Longhorns, but Rick Barnes coaching in
March raises some alarms and we say those alarms will be ringing
loud Thursday afternoon when Indiana State turns in the first
Cinderella upset of the tournament. The problem with upsets is that
they use so much energy. And when the second round arrives
Saturday, with some team like No. 4 LSU waiting, there will be
nothing left in the tank.
</P>
<P>
   Down in Tucson, there are some interesting challenges
developing. Start with No. 2 St. John's. Despite all the trouble of
the past few weeks, the Johnnies are good. They should roll over
No. 15 Northern Arizona _ if no one takes a leave of absence _ then
will find an interesting second-round game awaiting them. No. 7
Louisville is always an enigma. Let's take a chance and say the Red
Storm will play No. 10 Gonzaga. Doing it two games in a row? Nah.
Edge to St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   The other half has a few quality teams. No. 6 Purdue and No. 3
Oklahoma should emerge from their first-round games. No one seems
to give Purdue and coach Gene Keady any credit. He's the Jim
Boeheim of the Big Ten. But the man can coach and he should win.
Not once, not twice, but three times, which means that he will find
himself in the regional final.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting should be Arizona. The Wildcats will be able to handle
LSU in their regional semifinal and they are more talented than
Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Teams to watch: Purdue, Indiana State
</P>
<P>
   Upset special: Indiana State over Texas
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Albuquerque: Purdue, LSU, Arizona, and St. John's
</P>
<P>
   Regional champ: Arizona
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
