<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY SLOWED BY FLU, DOUBLE TEAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CALVIN WATKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He is the Mavericks' lone All-Star, but Michael Finley
has been anything but that of late.
</P>
<P>
   Finley leads the team with 22 points per game, but he hasn't
been dominating games as he did in the first half of the season,
when he earned the all-star selection.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday night's victory against Phoenix, coach Don Nelson
said Finley was struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finley hasn't played well in two weeks,'' Nelson said. ``He's
in a slump. He's trying, but he's not getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley has been slowed with his recovery from the flu and by
constant double teams from opponents. He also leads the NBA in
minutes played per game at 41.7.
</P>
<P>
   ``The double team has been there every time I got the ball,'' he
said. ``In an isolation situation or a postup situation the double
team has been there, and it's making it difficult for me to get
good looks at the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   For the season, Finley has shot 44.5 percent from the field and
in the past five games, he has led the team in scoring only once.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to my teammates to make the open shot, and I have
confidence in my teammates that they can do that,'' Finley said.
``Hopefully it can work in my benefit. You don't want one guy to
beat you on this team. I guess I'm that guy when I get double- or
triple-teamed, it's respect. I've just got to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley has been getting open looks at the basket, but that's
after getting through a double- or triple-team.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Finley made a 3-pointer in the waning moments of
the Mavericks' 104-99 victory against Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he didn't take over the game.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Erick Strickland led the way with a career-high 36 points.
Finley finished with 22 points on 7-of-13 shooting in 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been the same in a long time,'' Nelson said. ``I
don't know what the reason is. We have a hard time winning unless
he has a big game for us.'' BRADLEY PLAYS WELL
</P>
<P>
   With Cedric Ceballos slowed with a broken left pinky finger,
Shawn Bradley has raised his game a notch.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has scored 43 points and grabbed 21 rebounds the past
two games.
</P>
<P>
   With his five blocks Saturday, Bradley became the Mavericks'
all-time leading shot blocker with 616.
</P>
<P>
   After missing two games because of the flu two weeks ago,
Bradley has struggled. He scored only seven points combined against
Seattle and Sacramento last week. But he led the team in scoring
with 26 points in a loss to Minnesota on Thursday and he recorded a
double-double Saturday with 17 points and 12 rebounds against
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just go out there and try to have some fun every night,''
Bradley said. ``I know the other guys are trying hard too.''
BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Los Angeles Lakers and Milwaukee Bucks coach Del Harris
attended Saturday night's game, leading to speculation that he
could join the Mavericks' coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nelson said the team is still looking to add another
frontcourt player. The Mavericks are down to 11 playersafter the
release of Dennis Rodman last week.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mavericks improved their record to 11-4 Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   _ Erick Strickland had a career night on Saturday. Besides his
36 points, he had career highs in free throws made (13), free
throws attempted (17) and field goals attempted (19). He also tied
his career-high of field goals made (11).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
