<SLUG> BC-BKW-LOSANGELES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE, UCLA MAKE IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The odds were long, Mark Trakh knew. Still, he
figured, what the heck.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepperdine women's basketball coach gathered his team to
watch the NCAA Tournament selection show Sunday, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   As the tournament's Mideast region unfolded, Trakh joked that
13th seed had the Waves' name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, it did.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (21-9) made the NCAA Tournament for the first time
and will play No. 4 Virginia (23-8) at Charlottesville, Va., on
Friday. The winner will play either No. 5 Boston College or No. 12
Nebraska on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   There was no surprise for UCLA. The 18-10 Bruins earned the
Mideast's 10th seed and will open Friday at South Bend, Ind.
against No. 7 George Washington (25-5). Second-seeded Notre Dame
and No. 15 San Diego also are there.
</P>
<P>
   USC's women made the Women's National Invitation tournament for
the first time. The Trojans, who finished fifth in the Pacific-10,
open Thursday at Santa Clara. A win would pit them against either
Arizona State or Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge didn't make either tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine's task beating a seeded team on its home court
</P>
<P>
   is daunting. Right now, the Waves don't care. They celebrated
for 10 minutes after seeing their name.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' Trakh said. ``We jumped and danced and
hugged each other. Some were crying.... half those kids, they
could've dunked.''
</P>
<P>
   Even senior Jody Sackville, whose career is complete after
suffering three concussions this season, couldn't contain her
giddiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing well. Very well. Couldn't be better,'' Sackville
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves did what the NCAA liked - they finished strong,
winning 17 out of their last 20 games and earned respect despite
losses to quality teams such as Connecticut, UCLA and Mississippi
State.
</P>
<P>
   After the celebration came the work.
</P>
<P>
   Trakh spent Sunday night and was to spend part of this morning
calling every team on Virginia's schedule looking for game tape.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA didn't have to look as far for tape of George Washington.
Assistant coach Pam Walker has a friendship with a GW coach,
something that partially explains the fist slamming on a table when
she and the Bruins learned of their fate.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins don't mind their draw - it's better than Arizona
traveling to top-seed Tennessee or Stanford heading to Georgia,
another top seed - but falling all the way to a 10th seed after
being a preseason top-four choice can be tough to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we set up for ourselves,'' forward Maylana Martin
said. ``We've been really inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries had everything to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   From point guard Erica Gomez's torn labrum and LaCresha
Flannigan's knee before the season began to Michelle Greco's
concussions and thigh bruises to Carly Funicello's stress fracture
in her foot, UCLA players missed 30 games to injury.
</P>
<P>
   The results led to the Bruins falling out of the top 10, then
out of the Pac-10 race and finally out of the top 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they expect much from us,'' Martin said. ``I
think we might be able to sneak up on them. But not George
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   USC in NIT: After winning seven of its final nine games, USC
(15-13) was selected to play in the Women's NIT, and will travel to
Santa Clara on Thursday for a 7 p.m. opening-round contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real happy for the team and for the statement it makes
about what our team accomplished after finishing last a year ago,''
USC coach Chris Gobrecht said.
</P>
<P>
   This will be USC's first postseason appearance in Gobrecht's
three years as head coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
