<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAATOURNAMENT-NEWENGLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT BASKS IN OLD GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Keith Cieplicki was in the background as an assistant
coach when Vermont posted back-to-back perfect regular seasons and
participated in NCAA women's basketball tournament in 1992 and
1993.
</P>
<P>
   When head coach Cathy Inglese accepted a similar job at Boston
College, Cieplicki went along and watched as his former assistant
partner, Pam Borton, led the Catamounts to another NCAA berth the
following season.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Cieplicki has his turn in the NCAA spotlight as Vermont
earned the 11th seed in the Mideast and a date with Tulane Friday
in a first-round game at Lubbock, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real credit to the year we had, to be playing a 6,''
said Cieplicki, in his third year. ``It feels great, and as a
native Vermonter, it means a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Catamounts earned an automatic bid by routing Maine by 27
points in the America East title game Saturday. They were joined in
the NCAA tourney by the Black Bears, who were awarded a 12th seed
in the West Region as an at-large team.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross (Patriot League) and Dartmouth (Ivy), along with
Boston College (at-large) and Connecticut (Big East), are the other
New England representatives in the NCAA, matching the record six
accomplished last season and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Inglese's Catamounts created a frenzy for women's basketball in
Burlington, and this season's team (25-5) has brought back the
glory days with players like 6-foot-2-inch Karalyn Church, who led
the NCAA in field-goal percentage this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the the crown jewel for her,' said Cieplicki, who said
he knows little about his first-round foe except that it has ``one
exceptional player. I'll start looking at the tapes (Sunday
night).''
</P>
<P>
   After losing to Vermont Saturday, Maine repeated its feat of a
year ago by being chosen as an at-large team out of a less-visible
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears play North Carolina, the 1994 national champion
from the Atlantic Coast Conference, Saturday in Santa Barbara,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always grateful that we were chosen, since so many good
teams don't get in,'' said Joanne Palombo-McCallie, who is coaching
her sixth NCAA tourney team. ``It's a validation by the committee
of the teams we beat and the teams we played.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine defeated Weatern Athletic Conference champ Rice and took
No. 1 seed Georgia to overtime. Last season's first-round defeat of
Stanford and a close second-round loss to Old Dominion also played
a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the variables came together,'' said Palombo-McCallie.
</P>
<P>
   For Holy Cross, tournament selections are beginning to resemble
a given. Try three straight years, five of the last six, and eight
overall, second only to UConn for most NCAA appearances for New
England teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never disappointed when you're in the NCAAs,'' said
coach Bill Gibbons, whose team plays host Rutgers Friday. ``We're
at the point where we're going down there to win, not to just not
be embarrassed or just to make a good showing.''
</P>
<P>
   In its fourth appearance, Dartmouth (20-7) was granted the
highest seed for an Ivy women's team _ 13th _ to play defending
national champion Purdue Saturday at the Boilermakers' home court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not going to get No. 1 then we'll take No. 13,'' said
coach Chris Wielgus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the adversity that we are going to have to overcome,
and we know the environment that we are going into.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
