A5030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKW-NCAATOURNAMENT-BO     03-13 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAATOURNAMENT-BOSTONCOLLEGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEDING POINTS EAGLES AWAY FROM HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There was a festive atmosphere in the Conte Forum
meeting room where the Boston College women's basketball team
gathered Sunday to eat pizza, drink soda, and watch ESPN's NCAA
selection show on a wide-screen television with the hopes of
earning a high enough seed to host the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood quickly turned dour when the Eagles learned they
had been seeded fifth in the Mideast Regional and dispatched to
Charlottesville, Va., for a first-round game Friday against
12th-seeded Nebraska. It will be the first meeting between the
schools. The starting time has yet to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   BC coach Cathy Inglese quickly tried to perk up her players when
she said, ``We're going to Virginia, ladies!''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Eagles had their hearts set on playing in Conte
Forum, where they were undefeated in 14 games this season. Last
year, BC earned its first NCAA berth as the No. 8 seed in the East
Regional in Knoxville, Tenn., where the Eagles were ousted in the
second round by the top-seeded Volunteers, 89-62.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, all 16 teams that hosted the first two rounds
advanced to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, obviously the kids wanted to play at home,'' said
Inglese, who believed her team had a strong enough ranking in the
ratings percentage index (16th) and a good enough overall (25-8)
and conference record (12-4) to merit consideration as a host
school. ``I think we had a great chance to play at home, because we
had been playing wonderfully at home. We also wanted to do it for
the fans. We think it would've been great to bring super NCAA
basketball here to Boston. We also knew that it would be really
close and coming in fifth was really close. We don't mind going on
the road and playing. We started out with the Preseason NIT. We did
a lot of traveling, so we're used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the BC-Nebraska game will face either No. 13
Pepperdine or No. 4 Virginia Sunday night. Virginia earned the
right to host despite having an RPI ranking (23d) lower than BC's
and a 2-1 record against common opponents Duke, Kent, and Syracuse.
BC went 4-0 against those teams, including two victories against
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting that Bernadette McGlade, an assistant
commissioner with the Atlantic Coast Conference, served as chair of
the NCAA women's selection committee. The Big East, which had three
other teams (No. 1 seed Connecticut and No. 2 seeds Rutgers and
Notre Dame) make the field as host schools, were represented on the
selection committee by Carol Sprague, Pittsburgh's senior associate
athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if UConn's reputation for drawing large crowds to Gampel
Pavilion may have had an influence on the committee's decision to
ship out the Eagles, Inglese said, ``I don't think that played a
part in it, but you never know. You kind of try to guess what the
committee is thinking, but I don't think that was an idea. If it
is, it shouldn't. It should be your RPI, your strength of schedule,
and the fact you won 25 games _ and 25 games against very good
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're disappointed, but we don't mind going on the road.
We're ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cal Bouchard, BC's leading scorer at 16 points per game,
``When we were sitting there and saw that N.C. State did not get a
home date and that Auburn did not get a home date, we knew that
there were some slots open and we started getting our hopes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we saw where we were going and what we were seeded,
yeah, there was some disappointment in the room,'' Bouchard added.
``We would've liked to have been a four (seed), but still we're
excited about getting to travel. That's the fun part of the
tournament. It's going to places you've never been to before.''
</P>
<P>
   Although BC had other ideas about its postseason plans,
traveling to Virginia certainly beats not playing at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
