<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LATIMES-TRIBUNE-NYT &LR;      03-13 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIMES-TRIBUNE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBUNE CO. IS SEEN IN TALKS ON UNION WITH TIMES MIRROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: The following story is also being transmitted
with an ``a'' category code) 
(sw) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The boards of the Times Mirror Co., a media giant whose flagship
newspaper, The Los Angeles Times, shaped and dominated Southern
California for 119 years, and the company that publishes The
Chicago Tribune were in advanced talks Sunday night on a possible
combination, according to a Times Mirror executive.
</P>
<P>
   Although details were scarce, if the two companies were to
combine, either in a merger or acquisition, the result would form a
media conglomerate with 11 dailies, 22 television stations and a
combined market value of $11.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A joined company would hardly be the largest in a landscape that
includes the merged America Online-Time Warner. Still, it would
have enough heft, with $6.3 billion in combined annual revenues in
1999, to keep unwanted suitors at bay and to continue the Tribune
Co.'s acquisition strategy and its push into Internet properties.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement, which could come as early as Monday after a
weekend of intensifying rumors, would end five years in which Times
Mirror was reshaped by the cost-cutting zeal and combative optimism
of its chief executive, Mark H. Willes. After arriving in the
spring of 1995, Willes presided over the closing of both The
Baltimore Evening Sun and New York Newsday and began asset sales
that left the company pared largely to its basic newspaper
operations.
</P>
<P>
   His determination to see his papers buck the economic tide, win
new readers and lead Times Mirror to new profit, won Wall Street's
favor for his first two years, but this strategy appeared to falter
over the last 18 months, as circulation growth came in smaller
increments and profits at the flagship newspaper fell below
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Any combination would raise questions about the new company's
ownership of both a newspaper and a television station in the
markets of New York, Los Angeles and Hartford, Conn., an
arrangement ordinarily prohibited by federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The company's options would include seeking a Federal
Communications Commission waiver of this requirement or divesting
itself of some of the properties involved _ The Los Angeles Times
and KTLA, a Warner Brothers affiliate; Newsday and WPIX a Warner
Brothers affiliate in New York; and The Hartford Courant and WTIC,
a Fox affiliate in Hartford, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 0120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
