<SLUG> BC-BKW-BENTLEY-STROSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. ROSE SENDS BENTLEY PACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDONVILLE, N.Y. _ Thirty-three times this season, the women of
the College of St. Rose went to the well and 33 times they quenched
their thirst.
</P>
<P>
   Trip 34 was no exception. This one, though, was more satisfying
than the others because it came when it counted most.
</P>
<P>
   The top-ranked Golden Knights tripped Bentley, 82-72, Sunday
night in the Division 2 Northeast Regional at the Marcelle Center,
giving St. Rose its first berth in the NCAA Elite Eight, which
begins March 22 in Pine Bluffs, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   That's something that had been the exclusive domain of Bentley
(27-4), which was the Northeast representative the past four
seasons _ three times at the expense of St. Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Knights proved that their perfect record and fifth
straight New York Collegiate Athletic Conference title were no
flukes. They are the real deal with a wealth of talent.
</P>
<P>
   All five starters _ led by tournament MVP Nicole LaRocque (25
points) _ hit double figures. Mbuyi Mukendi had 17 and her
Congolese compatriot Nana Ngalulu Lukengu had 11, as did Kristin
Zeh and Colleen Sheridan.
</P>
<P>
   St. Rose stifled Bentley's high-powered inside game, effectively
shutting down twin towers Kelly Barker (14 points) and Lauren
Fuller (6), and forcing the Falcons to the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get enough inside and that (outside shot) appeared
to be our only weapon,'' said Bentley coach Barbara Stevens. ``They
did a great job defensively, they harassed us all night and kept
Fuller from getting any kind of decent position down low.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, she's a major key to our success. We were able to go
to second options, but we needed a force inside, which we didn't
have. That's a credit to their defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentley point guard C White (22 points, 18 from well outside the
3-point arc) agreed with Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our inside and outside game is on, we're a team that's
hard to beat,'' said White, who played 38 minutes. ``Tonight we'd
get it inside and couldn't get the position that we wanted. That
forced us to the perimeter and when just one asset of your game
isn't working, it's going to be tough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons scored half of their points (36) from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   After a rugged first half, Bentley held a 37-36 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the fourth time this season that St. Rose had
trailed at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we weren't concerned, we knew we'd come out strong,'' said
Bailey. ``We've played some of our best basketball this season in
the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   LaRocque opened the half with a driving layup to give St. Rose
the lead for good. When Bentley pulled to within 43-42 with 15:52
to play, LaRocque went on a 10-point tear that left Bentley
staggering.
</P>
<P>
   In less than 2 minutes, she drained back-to-back treys, hit a
pair of free throws, and stole an inbounds pass and went in
unmolested for a layup. In a blink, St. Rose led, 53-45.
</P>
<P>
   St. Rose, the nation's only undefeated team in either Division 1
or 2, never trailed by less than 7 from that point on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for a word to describe how I feel, call it
euphoric,'' said Bailey. ``We've made four straight Sweet 16
appearances and lost all four by a total of 14 points. We know the
feeling of disappointment. Finally, we experienced the joy of
winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, in terms of the future of this program, we can go into a
postseason tournament and not have to deal with the fact that these
kids choke and can't win the big one. We dispelled that myth
tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
