<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NIT-UMASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMASS GETS NIT DATE WITH SIENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ University of Massachusetts men's basketball
coach Bruiser Flint arrived in his office from a recruiting trip
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night at 8, then sat and waited to find out whether the
Minutemen's season would continue.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, the fourth-year coach still didn't know whether
UMass had been selected to the National Invitation Tournament, and
that left him to respond to a dozen phone inquiries like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, how you doin'? . . . No, we don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Flint got the call he was waiting for at 10:15 p.m. and it was
the news he wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   UMass (17-15) was selected to play in the NIT, and, as many
expected, will play at Siena (23-8) in the first round. The contest
is scheduled for 7 p.m. Thursday. The winner will meet the winner
of the first-round contest between Penn State and Princeton March
20 or 21.
</P>
<P>
   UMass had been an NCAA participant for so many years (seven
straight in the 1990s) that Flint couldn't remember what it was
like to wait to discover whether his team was going to the NIT. He
said he was pleased to make the field and happy that his team,
notably his seniors, reached postseason play. But the wait was
another story. ``This is more nerve-wracking than the NCAA because
with this you don't know anything,'' said Flint. ``I mean, we've
been in here for more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get in here and work and watch some tape on
(Siena) and get going. I know they like to run up and down the
floor, they shoot well on the perimeter, and they like to press.''
</P>
<P>
   It marks the third time UMass has made the postseason in Flint's
tenure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
