<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IGNORED TROJANS CAN'T BELIEVE IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC braced itself for the worst possible scenario
this week, but when the news came Sunday night that the Trojans had
been ignored by the National Invitation Tournament, it didn't go
down any easier to a stunned group of players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NIT doesn't care who deserves to be in the NIT, all they
care about is making money,'' USC forward Brian Scalabrine said.
``I just don't believe it. Cal is in? Are you serious? I can't
believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine was upset that the NIT selected California (16-14,
7-11), which finished two games behind the Trojans (16-14, 9-9) in
the Pacific-10 Conference standings. Arizona State (18-12, 10-8)
also made the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Cal did sweep the Trojans this season, and is the defending NIT
champion. But more importantly, the Golden Bears offer the NIT a
virtual guarantee of 12,000 fans for home games, and making money
is the tournament's top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have 12,000 fans that come out,'' USC coach Henry Bibby
said. ``How does the NIT justify taking Cal? I don't know their
reasoning. It wasn't in the cards to be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to be more Cal winning the thing and that Cal can host
games. You can't say they're more deserving than we are. I thought
we had a better chance to make it than Cal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bibby didn't place too much blame on the NIT, instead
focusing on the Trojans' shortcomings, which included losing eight
of their final 12 games, not to mention a mediocre 7-5
nonconference record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have controlled it,'' Bibby said. ``We can't blame
the committee. They have their reasons. We can't be upset with
them. It never should have come to that. If we do what we're
supposed to do, we don't have this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   USC hoped if it swept the Washington schools last weekend, it
would have enough momentum to secure a bid with 16 victories. Last
year, the Trojans were selected to the NIT with a 15-12 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did we get in last year and not this year? I can't believe
any of this,'' Scalabrine said. ``We won our last game, and now our
season is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The NIT was just one more casualty of the Trojans' problems once
forward Sam Clancy went down with a broken foot in late January,
and USC dropped seven of 10 games in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably a different ball game with Sam Clancy,'' Bibby
said. ``You win at least two more games. Of the five games we lost
by five points or less, I'd say we win two of those.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year's done. You think the committee would say they do
have Sam Clancy back. He played really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's injury came when USC was tied for first place in the
Pac-10 with a 6-1 record. After spending the final two months of
the season hoping for an at-large berth to the NCAA Tournament, the
Trojans suffered a greater indignity by failing to make any
postseason tournament for the second time in Bibby's four years as
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``To miss both tournaments is very disappointing,'' guard Jeff
Trepagnier said. ``I was pretty sure we were in. We'll have to work
hard to not have a season like this. I've thought about six or
seven games that we could have won.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our season started sliding, we still thought we would get
to the NIT.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Scalabrine was selected to the All-Pacific-10 team....
Laguna Beach High guard Travis Hanour, who committed to USC last
month, visited Arizona over the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
