<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME NCAA TOURNAMENT OBSERVATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Three things are perfectly clear from the
64-team NCAA men's basketball tournament bracket revealed Sunday
afternoon:
</P>
<P>
   __Long Beach State's 24-5 basketball team wasn't even on The
Bubble.
</P>
<P>
   __The Big West is to the NCAA as Pluto is to our solar system.
</P>
<P>
   __The selection committee envies the weather teams on the west
coast enjoy, and punishes them by sending them packing during the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   There's also validity to the belief that the committee could
have done a better seeding job by picking names out of a cap, but
local things first.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the committee's tendencies and the national disregard
for the Big West, no one in 49er-ville held out any real hope that
Wayne Morgan's team would get a bid, especially when teams like St.
Louis (fifth in its division of Conference USA), Creighton (fourth
in Missouri Valley) and Arkansas (7-9 in SEC play) won post-season
tourneys to grab an automatic berth.
</P>
<P>
   But when you look at the wins and schedules of a few teams that
grabbed at-large bids, you can at least create an argument.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin (8th seed in West, 18-13) had a win over Temple, but
it also lost to Wake Forest (by 19), Seth Greenberg's South Florida
squad, Northern Illinois, and Penn State twice. The Badgers got
their boost from the Big Ten's overall power rating.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri (9th, South, 18-12), a sixth entry from the Big XII,
had just one win against a winning team in Big XII play, and four
non-league wins were against Princeton, UNC-Asheville, Western
Carolina and Morgan State. The Tigers were 2-10 against Top 30
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall (10th, East, 20-9), the last of four teams from the
Big East, had just two notable wins, over St. John's and Syracuse,
while piling up victories against east coast versions of Dominguez
Hills and Monterey Bay -- Quinnipiac, Drexel, St. Peter's,
Columbia, Army, Stony Brook and Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   DePaul (9th, East, 21-11) beat St. John's and lost to Duke by
one, but it also had wins against Howard, American-Puerto Rico,
South Carolina, Chicago State, Monmouth, Nicholls State, Northern
Illinois and Elon. The Blue Demons were 2-6 versus Top 30 teams.
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure (12th, Midwest, 21-9) beat Temple (as well as
Florida International, Cleveland State and Niagara) but lost to
Fordham -- twice. Another 12, Indiana State (Midwest, 22-9) has one
good-looking win (Indiana) to go with Montana State, Western
Illinois, Eastern Illinois, North Texas and Tennessee State. The
Sycramores also lost a game to Southern Illinois by 19, a team the
49ers beat in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no short cuts,'' said Bill Shumard, the 49ers
Athletic Director. ``You have to play good teams and do well when
you do. We reached our first goal, to be one of the (96) teams
playing in March (NCAA and NIT). We'll keep upgrading our
schedule.'' The 49ers play Cal in the NIT first-round Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly would help the 49ers and other Big West teams if
they had an advocate or lobbyist working on their behalf. For the
seventh straight year, the conference will only have one team in
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Big West coincidentally hasn't had an official on the
selection committee over the same span. Its lack of influence and
stature is visible by the placement of Utah State. The tournament
champ has more wins (28) than 59 other teams in the field, but they
were seeded 12th in the South.
</P>
<P>
   That's quite a slap. Out-of-nowhere entrants like Saint Louis
(9) and Arkansas (11) were seeded higher, and so were teams with
double-digit losses, like Wisconsin (8), Missouri and DePaul (9s).
</P>
<P>
   One can make the case that Utah State is better than the tourney
champs of the WAC and Mountain West. UNLV (23-7), seeded 10th in
the South, built its record on wins over Mississippi Valley State,
Fairfield, Austin Peay, Cal Poly SLO, Eastern Kentucky, Florida
Atlantic and something called High Point. It also lost to BYU twice
and suffered losses by 14 (Oklahoma State), 24 (North Carolina, 40
(Cincinnati) and 44 (Utah).
</P>
<P>
   Utah State beat Fresno State. With apologies to Jerry Tarkanian,
the Bulldogs' schedule included twinkies like Georgia State,
Florida International, Florida Atlantic, Wagner, Cornell and good
old High Point. He also suffered losses to Northridge, USF and UAB.
</P>
<P>
   ``The politics are what they are: The football schools rule the
roost even when it comes to basketball,'' said Shumard. ``If you're
in one of the other conference, it's almost like you're held to a
different standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Big West deserved more bids or higher seeds,
the same committee prejudice against the west coast continues. One
shouldn't be fooled by seeing Stanford and Arizona earn No. 1
seeds. Those placements were a function of Cincinnati losing Kenyon
Martin and other top ten teams (Syracuse, Ohio State, Tennessee)
taking their conference tournaments lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford and Utah State will both play in the South Regional,
starting in Birmingham. Las Vegas also goes south to the other
bracket in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 third place team Oregon and WCC at-larger Pepperdine must
open the East Regional in Buffalo. Should they survive, they then
go back to Syracuce.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is stuck in the Midwest Regional, opening against Ball
State in Minneapolis. Utah, also in the Midwest, opens in
Cleveland, both teams hoping to advance to another beautiful city,
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four area teams blessed to be in the West Regional,
there's one contender (Arizona) and three longshots from the bottom
half of the 64-team draw, Fresno State, Northern Arizona and
Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Only three high-seed teams have comparable travel logistics:
Oklahoma State (Buffalo, East), LSU (Salt Lake City, West) and St.
John (Tuscon, West). One might include Ohio State (Nashville,
South) and Connecticut (Birmingham, South).
</P>
<P>
   Given the opportunity, the 49ers (24-5) would be happy to play
in Buffalo, Birmingham or even Beijing. Instead, they'll try to
make a statement in the NIT finals in New York and wait for next
year's Final Four guide, which will add them to the list headlined
``Teams with fewest losses not to make tournament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
