<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-REWR     03-13 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WIN 18TH STRAIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Push it, stretch it, fold it over backward and
flex it to the point of snapping under the strain. No measure of
abuse seems to put a permanent crease in the Los Angeles Lakers'
winning ways.
</P>
<P>
   Their latest winning streak was pushed to the brink Sunday
evening by the multitalented and ever-unpredictable Sacramento
Kings. It was ready to crack and crumble, but the Lakers'
foundation proved stronger than anything the Kings could muster.
</P>
<P>
   Meet the foundation: Shaquille O'Neal, MVP. And his friend mini-
MVP, Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   The pair combined for 79 points as the Lakers fought back from a
16-point deficit to pull out a remarkable 109-106 victory in front
of 18,997 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' said coach Phil Jackson, ``what a game. That was a
pretty exciting ball game for our team, and for our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Folded, spindled, nearly mutilated, The Streak survived, growing
to 18 consecutive games, tied for the third longest in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're playing at a top level right now,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   If ever it was going to end, Sunday seemed like the time, and
the Kings seemed like the team. They had won three of the last four
meetings and present all manners of matchup problems for the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   That was in evidence, as Chris Webber (24 points), Predrag
Stojakovic (22 points) and Vlade Divac (15 points) took command
from the opening tip, and the Kings led continuously until late in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bryant and O'Neal took over, combining for 27 points in the
fourth quarter, and making another bit of history.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant finished with a career-high 40 points (on 15-of-24
shooting) to go with 10 rebounds and eight assists. O'Neal finished
with 39 points, 20 rebounds and five assists. It was the first time
since March 5, 1976 that two Lakers scored 35 points or more in the
same game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq has played like an MVP all year,'' said Rick Fox, ``and
Kobe joined him tonight for the game. You know that you have two
guys, one who should win the MVP this year and one who probably
will eventually down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   They needed both MVPs. Third option Glen Rice struggled early
and sat out the last 16 minutes of the game. He went to the bench
having hit 3 of 11 shots for six points.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bryant of the two-man game, ``It's good, because you keep
the defense off-balance, kind of play them a little bit. ... They
don't know if they should slide in or stay with Shaq or whatever it
may be. We just wanted to take whatever they gave us. It was that
simple. We just wanted to play for the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the Lakers (52-11) made their defensive stand. Fox checked
Stojakovic and Corliss Williamson. Brian Shaw and Derek Fisher took
turns hounding Jason Williams. And Robert Horry confounded Webber
into 2-for-7 shooting as the Lakers held the Kings to 31.8 percent
shooting in the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energy,'' Bryant said of the turnaround. ``We were able to dig
deep and find some energy, and rotate a lot quicker (on defense).''
</P>
<P>
   It just took longer than usual to do it. The Lakers got their
first lead of the game, 93-91, on Bryant's 7-foot jumper with 5:12
left. Stojakovic tied it again, 100-all with 1:20 remaining. Then
O'Neal took the game back. He hit a bank shot over Webber, then at
the other end blocked a Stojakovic jumper, with the Kings claiming
goaltending.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's jam and 3-point play with 28.5 seconds left effectively
put the game away, 105-100, as the Kings tossed up a flurry of
errant 3-point tries in the waning seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers extended their home winning streak to nine games and
for the moment dispelled the hex the Kings have on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding a way to win is a must for good teams,'' Fox said.
``Guys that aren't considered good teams, they fold after being
down 16 points, and against a team like Sacramento, where they
didn't let up, it was up to us to pressure defensively and to find
ways to score. You learn a lesson by losing sometimes more than you
do by winning, but at this stage of the season, you take a win like
that as a learning experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
