<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIT SNUBS NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Try telling Oregon's men's basketball team Cal
State Northridge is not one of the top 100 teams in the nation this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the Fresno State players if the Matadors are
postseason-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN beat both those NCAA Tournament teams in December. But it
wasn't enough for the National Invitation Tournament committee,
which passed on Northridge Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors were traveling when the NIT field was announced.
Earlier in the day, coach Bobby Braswell talked about the potential
impact of the first postseason berth in the school's 10-season
history in Division I.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a huge step for the program,'' Braswell said from
his hotel room in Missoula, Mont., where CSUN lost in the Big Sky
Conference tournament final the night before to Northern Arizona in
overtime 85-81. ``The players deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the NIT selection committee looks for attractive matchups,
and the domino effect of upsets in conference tournaments forced
some NCAA Tournament bubble teams into the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   And that ripple effect hurt CSUN, which had a No. 94 ranking in
the NCAA's Ratings Percentage Index (RPI) entering the tournament
final.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Long Beach State's loss in the semifinals of the Big
West tournament. The 49ers were not going to get an NCAA at-large
bid, so they went to the NIT and gobbled up a West Coast slot that
could have gone to Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gut-wrenching process,'' said Braswell, who went to the
NIT while an assistant at Oregon in 1996, just before becoming
CSUN's coach. ``You just don't know. Literally, it's a group behind
closed doors (making the NIT field). I told our guys last night
that we still had a great season.''
</P>
<P>
   There were several arguments for CSUN getting in:
</P>
<P>
   --Its victory mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors finished 20-10, and teams from mid-major
conferences usually get into the postseason with 20 wins. The Big
Sky is on the cusp of respectability, earning an RPI ranking higher
than the Big West this year.
</P>
<P>
   But there was precedent for the NIT snubbing CSUN: Northern
Arizona went 21-8 last year and didn't get an invitation
</P>
<P>
   and the Lumberjacks lost in the Big Sky title game.
</P>
<P>
   --Quality wins.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge clearly played one of the toughest schedules in the
Big Sky; the Matadors' 19 wins against Division I teams were the
most in the conference. And they beat Oregon and Fresno State and
had two wins over Oral Roberts (ORU handed No. 17 Tulsa one of its
four losses).
</P>
<P>
   The wins over the Ducks and Bulldogs were also on the road,
which the NIT likes. CSUN would not have hosted an NIT game at
1,600-seat Matador Gym.
</P>
<P>
   --A strong finish.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to NAU ended a five-game CSUN winning streak, the
longest in the Big Sky up to that point. To get to the final,
Northridge eliminated the defending champion (Weber State) and the
tournament host (Montana).
</P>
<P>
   In the tournament, the Matadors were the second-best offensive
team and the best defensive team.
</P>
<P>
   All of this looked like a bid. Braswell thought so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we deserve it? Absolutely,'' he said after Saturday night's
game. ``To be quite honest with you, the NIT is very political.
I've seen some very strange things. Our goal was to get to the NCAA
Tournament and try to take care of our own business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a definite disappointment for these guys (if there
was no NIT bid).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
