A5068 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKC-LONGBEACH-LADN     03-13 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LONGBEACH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH STATE HEADED TO NIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ D'Cean Bryant was all smiles Sunday evening
at the Pyramid upon learning Long Beach State's men's basketball
team's season was not over, that the 49ers had been selected to
play in the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from Bryant's emotions the other evening in
Reno, Nev., after the 49ers had lost in overtime to New Mexico
State in the Big West Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to cry,'' Bryant said. ``Other guys were crying, and
I wanted to. But I couldn't. I was in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we can show America what we have . . . prove that we are a
good team,'' Bryant said. ``We can show people that we are not a
fluke, that we have a good program here at Long Beach State.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``proving,'' as Bryant calls it, begins Wednesday night at
7:30 when the 49ers take on the University of California in a
first-round game at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Cal is the defending NIT champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another season,'' said 49er forward Antrone Lee. ``If we
can win the NIT it will make up for (losing in) the Big West
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing in the Big West tournament meant losing out on an
automatic bid to the more prestigious NCAA Tournament. And losing
in the semifinals meant losing any shot at an at-large bid.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Wayne Morgan, the 49ers' coach, said he was still holding
out hope as he watched the NCAA pairings being unveiled Sunday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long shot hope,'' Morgan acknowledged, ``but I was
hoping something would happen, that somebody would recognize that
we've won 22 of our last 24 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone did. The NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at (the NIT) as a postseason tournament,'' Morgan
said. ``It's an opportunity to play more basketball and to bring
more respectability to Long Beach State.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what we had in mind,'' said Lee, one of four seniors
on the team. ``But we're going to try to go out and win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited that we accomplished some of our goals,'' Lee
added. ``We won 20 games and we won the Western Division.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers take their 24-5 record against Cal (16-14), which
finished seventh in the Pac-10 with a 7-11 conference record.
</P>
<P>
   It's a similar situation to last season for Cal. The Bears were
just 8-10 in the Pac-10 and tied for fifth. Yet they went on to win
the NIT and finished with a 22-11 overall record.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers and Golden Bears have never faced one another on the
basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will meet the winner between Virginia and Georgetown
in the second round next week.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Braun, the Cal coach, insisted its a major plus to be
selected for the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited,'' he said Sunday night. ``There are some
outstanding teams in this tournament. Any notion that this is a
loser's bracket tournament is dispelled when you look around and
see so many quality teams, and Long Beach State is certainly one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen them, and I've been very impressed how well they've
played. No question, they're a quality team.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers played one Pac-10 team earlier, beating USC, 76-66, at
the Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know SC came away impressed,'' Braun said.
</P>
<P>
   Cal played two Big West teams this season and won them both,
beating Pacific, 76-72, on Nov. 27 and beating UC Irvine, 88-61, on
Dec. 18.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the 49ers' first appearance in the postseason in five
years, since they won the Big West tournament in 1995 and then lost
to Utah in the first round of the NCAA Tournament. They will be
making their fifth NIT appearance but first in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico State, which knocked the 49ers out of the Big West
tourney last week, is also in the NIT and will meet Arizona State
in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   One sidebar to a Cal-Long Beach State matchup is Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams would like to land Bryant's brother, Travon, a
standout at Jordan High.
</P>
<P>
   Braun admitted as much, saying, ``I've seen Long Beach play
several times . . . one reason is that we're recruiting the brother
of one of their players.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Cal is one of them,'' Bryant said, smiling. ``And he
hasn't closed the door on coming here (to Long Beach State),
either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
