<HEADER>
A5090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     03-13 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 19)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE TIMES OF MY LIFE: And My Life With The Times &LR;  By Max
Frankel. Delta, $15.95. The former correspondent and later
executive editor of The New York Times looks back on over 40 years
at the paper, a remarkable career shaped by the Cold War and his
family's escape from Nazi Germany when he was a youth. ``It's a
smart, tough, scrupulous book,'' Ward Just wrote in The New York
Times Book Review in 1999. ``Every reader will learn a very great
deal about how a newspaper works.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTH OF THE BORDER, West of the Sun &LR;  By Haruki Murakami.
Vintage International, $12. This spare, erotically charged tale by
the author of ``The Wind-Up Bird Chronicle'' tracks the intertwined
lives of two Japanese lovers who connect briefly as 12-year-olds
before drifting apart in adolescence. When they meet again as
adults, they still have vivid memories of each other but their
worldly crassness prevents them from recapturing the lost
perfection of their youth. Murakami ``manages, in his sexual
explicitness, to make intimacy real _ appealing and unembarrassing,
innocent even,'' Mary Hawthorne said in The New York Times Book
Review last year. ``This wise and beautiful book is full of hidden
truths.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEAR GENIUS: The Letters of Ursula Nordstrom &LR;  Collected and
edited by Leonard S. Marcus. HarperCollins, $16.95. The children's
book editor who nurtured writers like E.B. White and Maurice Sendak
reveals her wizardry in nearly 50 years' worth of correspondence,
collected by Leonard S. Marcus. Much of it was composed during her
long career as director of Harper &AMP; Row's Department of Books for
Boys and Girls. Her ``genius glows from these letters,'' Rebecca
Pepper Sinkler wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; MARGARET WISE BROWN: Awakened by the Moon &LR;  (Quill/Morrow,
$14), Marcus profiles one of the most famous authors cultivated by
Nordstrom, the prolific and eccentric creator of children's
classics like ``Goodnight Moon.'' In 1992 the reviewer Edith
Kunhardt Davis called this ``an absorbing biography.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEAVY WATER: And Other Stories &LR;  By Martin Amis. Vintage
International, $12. The author displays startling bravado and
cleverness as he imagines a world in which heterosexuals are
oppressed by the homosexual majority, poets bask in money and
celebrity and a Martian robot knows the fate of the world. ``Amis
applies his comic timing, his perfect pitch and his curatorial eye
to some of the burning issues of our time,'' A.O. Scott wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RIPLEY BOGLE &LR;  By Robert McLiam Wilson. Ballantine, $12.95.
Ripley Bogle is a downtrodden but acutely perceptive Belfast native
who wanders the streets of London recalling the hell of his
childhood and his descent into poverty. In 1998 the reviewer Liam
Callanan called this an uneven novel that details ``the painful
minutiae of homeless existence with aching accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAWSON'S WILL: The Greatest Polar Survival Story Ever Written &LR; 
By Lennard Bickel. Steerforth, $15. In 1912 an Antarctic expedition
led by the Australian geologist Douglas Mawson faced disaster when
one of its members disappeared into a crevasse 300 miles from base,
along with a team of dogs and most of the supplies. This is ``a
riveting account'' of their struggle to survive, The New York Times
Book Review wrote in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, Robert Falcon Scott was searching for
the South Pole, a journey that ended with the death of Scott and
four others on the return trip, just 11 miles from safety. In  &UR; A
FIRST RATE TRAGEDY: Robert Falcon Scott and the Race to the South
Pole &LR;  (Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $14), Diana Preston, a British
journalist, portrays Scott as both a bungler and a genuine hero. In
1998 the reviewer Robert R. Harris called this ``a concise and
readable account'' of Scott's adventures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SECOND HAND SMOKE &LR;  By Thane Rosenbaum. St. Martin's Griffin,
$13.95. This novel is about a son of Holocaust survivors who grows
up in a home dominated by his tormented mother and later becomes a
Nazi-hunting lawyer. ``The author exhibits considerable grace in
interweaving themes and time frames,'' Richard Lourie wrote in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LANGUAGE OF CLOTHES &LR;  By Alison Lurie. Owl/Holt, $22.50.
This quirky, illustrated history of fashion and its uses in Western
society was originally published in 1982 and has been reissued with
a new introduction by the author. ``Lurie's contribution ...
appears mainly in the form of droll observations and pithy asides,
especially about sex,'' Walter Goodman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EAST BAY GREASE &LR;  By Eric Miles Williamson. Picador USA, $13.
T-Bird Murphy, the teen-age narrator of this first novel, takes
refuge from his hard-bitten parents and their world of bikers and
auto garages by combing Oakland's waterfront bars and playing
trumpet. Williamson's ``prose cuts loose in torrid rhythms that
evoke the peril and exuberance of jazz,'' Sally Eckhoff wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WIVES OF THE FISHERMEN &LR;  By Angela Huth. Bard/Avon, $12.50. This
novel explores the lifelong friendship between two women _ one
plain, the other beautiful and flirtatious _ in a secluded fishing
village in Scotland. In 1998 the reviewer Julie Gray praised Huth's
``precise and piquant'' prose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
