</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14; HarperPaperbacks, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of the nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a
</P>
<P>
   single crew.
</P>
<P>
   11. GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) THE ORCHID THIEF, by Susan Orlean. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) A journalist's account of a man who was caught
</P>
<P>
   pilfering 200 rare orchids.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) HIS BRIGHT LIGHT, by Danielle Steel. (Delta,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) The novelist recalls the life of her son Nick,
</P>
<P>
   who suffered from manic depression and died at 19.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) THE ELEGANT UNIVERSE, by Brian Greene.
</P>
<P>
   (Vintage, $15.) A presentation of superstring
</P>
<P>
   theory, which attempts to mediate between
</P>
<P>
   quantum mechanics and general relativity.
