behind him, a catamaran for provisions and naps. Presumably he
doesn't have e-mail, but, yes, there is a Web site
(www.stoeffler.com) that, for French speakers, helps track
``l'homme qui marche sur l'eau.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoeffler, a French food company, is sponsoring Bricka's
7,800-mile, six-month slog from Los Angeles to Sydney. The company
provided 22 pounds of sauerkraut.
</P>
<P>
   How did Bricka explain his quest? ``Our time goes quickly,'' he
said. ``I will use my time to realize my dream.'' How did
bystanders react? ``He's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Dow Takes a Sharp Drop While Nasdaq Hits a New High  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tale of two stock markets continued to confound investors.
It was the best of times for the Nasdaq Composite, which surpassed
the 5,000 mark for the first time on rising technology stocks. But
the more established companies in the Dow Jones industrial average
fell, bringing the average down to 9,796.03 on Tuesday. The split
in the two markets reflects investors' ardor for so-called new
economy stocks, thought to be immune to the ill effects of rising
interest rates. But market strategists doubt that hot technology
companies can remain a safe haven forever.
</P>
<P>
   _ By GRETCHEN MORGENSON
</P>
<P>
   The Price for Taking Bribes
</P>
<P>
   China executed Hu Changqing, a former provincial vice governor,
for taking $600,000 in bribes. The government is seeking to
demonstrate its resolve in cracking down on high-level corruption,
which is damaging the Communist Party's reputation. Hu was the
highest official ever put to death for corruption. An investigation
has already linked dozens of relatively high-level local officials
with a $10 billion smuggling ring in Xiamen in southern China. But
many Chinese are skeptical that China's leaders will pursue the
campaign to the top party ranks. When the Xiamen investigation was
about to implicate the wife of the Beijing party chief, Jia
Qinglin, party propaganda departments sprang to life, professing
her innocence.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL
</P>
<P>
   Gassing Up Goes Up
</P>
<P>
   American drivers will have plenty of gasoline this summer, say
Energy Department analysts. And they'll pay plenty for it: a
national average $1.56 for a gallon of regular unleaded, much more
in high-cost areas like New York City and California. By 2001,
prices will be on their way down, the analysts said, assuming that
oil countries step up production, as expected, and that there is no
war in the Middle East. Those are big ifs.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID STOUT
</P>
<P>
   Police Torture Verdict, Part 2  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three New York City police officers were found guilty of
covering up the vicious assault on Abner Louima in the restroom of
a Brooklyn station house three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The officers _ Charles Schwarz, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese _
were convicted of obstructing justice by lying about Schwarz's role
in the attack. At a previous trial last year, Schwarz was found
guilty of restraining Louima while another officer, Justin A.
Volpe, sodomized him with a broken broomstick.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALAN FEUER
</P>
<P>
   Sinkhole, Boston Style  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston's ``Big Dig,'' the monumental project to sink the city's
raised Central Artery underground, is presenting even more of a Big
Bill than expected. Its overseers were grilled by lawmakers about
why the federal- and state-financed project will cost at least $12
billion, not the supposedly set-in-stone $10.8 billion, and why
they did not reveal the overrun earlier. They responded that not
everything is controllable when an undertaking is the most complex
urban infrastructure project in the country's history. They have
until Wednesday to come up with a plan to pay for the overrun.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: CAREY GOLDBERG &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Small Step for Womankind  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women shoppers have often found it hard to find a bargain on
shoes made by Nine West Group. The company agreed to pay $34
million to settle charges by federal and state investigators that
it had illegally fixed shoe prices since 1988. Unable to find all
women who may have paid too much for shoes, the governments said
the money will be divided among the states and dedicated to women's
health, educational and safety programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MELODY PETERSEN
</P>
<P>
   A Charge of Faking It  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Key tests for the military's planned $27 billion anti-missile
system were deliberately faked by a top contractor, TRW, a former
senior engineer at the company charged. The company and the
Pentagon denied any doctoring. But the engineer, Dr. Nira Schwartz,
who was on the company's anti-missile team in 1995 and 1996 and
sparked more than three years of federal inquiries after being
fired, said cheating was so rampant the costly anti-missile effort
is destined to fail. Settling the dispute will probably take
further investigations, perhaps by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WILLIAM J. BROAD
</P>
<P>
   Sheltered in Bermuda  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Six small American insurance companies moved to Bermuda in the
past year to avoid paying income taxes, prompting four big ones _
Chubb, Hartford, Kemper and Liberty Mutual _ to ask Congress to
close the loophole, which threatens 4 cents of every dollar of
corporate income tax. At a hearing on tax shelters, Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., asked whether ``we are entering an era of
corporate expatriation'' to move profits beyond the reach of the
IRS.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   California Votes In Conservative Initiatives
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by a surge in conservative primary voters, two of the
most controversial measures on the California ballot were
overwhelmingly approved: a ban on the recognition of same-sex
marriages and tough new penalties for juveniles who stray from the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 21, the juvenile crime initiative, allows
prosecutors to try 14-year-olds charged with violent crimes as
adults without a judicial review and makes it easier to incarcerate
youths with adult inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 22, the ``limitations on marriage'' initiative,
anticipates that one day marriage between same-sex couples may be
sanctified somewhere and allows California the right not to
acknowledge those unions.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EVELYN NIEVES
</P>
<P>
   Policing Cyber Music  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a matter of months, a free software program called Napster
has turned millions of law-abiding citizens into music pirates.
Developed by a 19-year-old college dropout, the program compiles a
master list of all the songs on the computers of all of its users,
making it easy to find and copy almost any musical selection, free.
A trade association representing the major record labels is suing
the start-up company that distributes the program for contributing
to copyright infringement. But if it loses, the music industry may
have to sue the college students who are Napster's most avid users
_ or else figure out how to make money without selling quite so
many CDs.
</P>
<P>
   _ By AMY WALDMAN
</P>
<P>
   Close Call for Oscar
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if some glittering Oscar presenter intoned, ``The
envelope, please'' and got a brown envelope that read, ``You
absolutely, positively have a chance to win $10 million!'' An Oscar
moment indeed. Such a tableau was conjured by word that more than
1,000 of a missing 4,200 Academy Award ballots addressed to
California members were found in a warehouse, mistaken for junk
mail. The academy may just have to send out more ballots. And soon.
The awards are March 26.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
