<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 08:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5099 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-HACKER-HANDLES-REVIEW     03-13 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-HANDLES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKNAMES ON THE NET: BIGGER BARK THAN BITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating)  (The Week in Review)  
(bl) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A young man who goes by the nickname Kaos confided several
months ago that he wouldn't mind being perceived as a bad-guy
computer hacker, but reputation-wise, things weren't working out.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the menacing image his moniker might conjure, the
19-year-old Kaos wore a retainer and his voice squeaked when he got
excited. ``Even if you're not capable of instilling fear, you think
your alter ego has to be able to,'' said Kaos, whose mom knows him
as Corey.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that computer vandalism is a serious threat, as
evidenced by the arrest last week of Denis M. Moran, 17, for
allegedly hacking into the Web site of the anti-drug organization
DARE, and also by the recent rash of attacks on major e-commerce
sites.
</P>
<P>
   But the fascination with malicious hacker culture has spawned a
profusion of wannabes whose bark is far worse than their bite. They
tend to be adolescent denizens of online chat rooms and Internet
junkies who assume nicknames meant to convey tough-guy personas
with superhero powers but whose actual intimidation factor is
closer to Super Geek.
</P>
<P>
   Their real threat to national security might be starting a run
on acne medication, but judging from their online handles, you'd
think they could wipe out the Kremlin with a keystroke while
bench-pressing Rush Limbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely important _ your nickname defines who you
are,'' said 25-year-old Brian Hansel, a k a Noid, at last summer's
Defcon, an annual gathering of serious computer hackers,
enthusiasts and hangers-on held in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Hansel explained that his nom de Net derived from an impish
character in a Domino's Pizza advertising campaign, which may say
more about his diet than his hacking prowess. Like many
self-proclaimed hackers, Hansel says he has burned through more
than one ``nick.'' He originally called himself Punisher, but
decided it was too run-of-the-mill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can call themselves Deathmonger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem that someone who calls himself Deathmonger would
carry a heavy burden of dishing out death on a whim, but V1RU5 cast
doubt on that theory. ``You know Evil Pete?'' asked V1RU5, whose
name refers to computer viruses but who signs his checks Robert
Lupo. ``He's one of the nicest guys in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people with the most menacing names are the nicest
people,'' said the 30-something V1RU5, who added that hackers take
their names much less seriously as they age. ``The people with the
least-menacing names are the biggest jerks.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably an overgeneralization, though Moran's screen
name, Coolio, doesn't sound especially threatening. And Analyzer,
who was arrested in 1998 in Israel in connection with an attack on
U.S. and Israeli government computer systems, chose a nickname that
makes him sound less like a hacker than a psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Or take Death Veggie, whose nickname seems fairly benign unless
you happen to be a zucchini. Yet the group to which he belongs,
Cult of the Dead Cow, has published software used to break into and
control computers installed with Microsoft's Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   It goes to show that you can't tell much about a person from a
handle _ though in some cases what you see is what you get. Squeak,
a young man no older than 16, said he chose his nickname because of
his high voice. Another teen-ager, Sloth, confessed to being pretty
lazy.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, what you get is more like Walter Mitty. Mistress
Evyl, 21, acknowledged that she's been known to show her unfriendly
side only if someone messes with one of her inner circle. And Spew
said he's had his nickname for a long time, even though he's never
really hacked into anything and frankly isn't very computer savvy.
``Really, I'm more into playing games,'' he said shyly, standing
around with Sloth at Defcon.
</P>
<P>
   Some purists don't like nicknames, whether or not they are apt.
True hackers do constructive work, they say, not by trespassing in
computer systems but by taking apart software programs and
improving them. These hackers don't require the bravado associated
with flashy, ostentatious nicknames.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Raymond, president of Open Source Initiative, a group that
promotes the free publication of computer programming languages
owned by corporations, said real hackers give their names readily
while wannabes and malicious types ``try to build a mystique
through concealment and secrecy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Raymond and others probably don't have much to fear from the
likes of Kaos and Spew, whose real assault is on traditional syntax
and spelling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 0856EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
