<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN15-CO     03-13 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Lonely in right field
 &HT;    (For release March 15, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have just come from a kiddie baseball game in which the left
fielder was hit in the head by a ground ball. (Picture it!) The
event, however brief, was documentation that outfielders do get
balls hit to them. How they are fielded is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   This was very important. The right fielder on the team is my
grandson, and he's yet to have the opportunity to stop a grounder
with his skull _ or even his oversized glove.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin has been wailing ever since his Khoury League season
began. Being ostracized to the outfield is, to him, a disaster of
immense proportion, likely an indignity that will affect the
remainder of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Just 9 years old, Kevin has been moping about being shipped to
right field. As one who decades earlier was ostracized to the same
location, I can commiserate with him. I split my time between
second base and right field in my sandlot baseball days _ the
determination not based so much on my ability to field grounders
but on my paltry batting average.
</P>
<P>
   In the kid leagues, if you don't hit, you go to right. Not left,
not center, but right.
</P>
<P>
   This is not how it works in the big leagues. Usually, the most
fearsome of hitters are out there. Based on that, I tried to build
the prestige of an adolescent right fielder by telling him about
the great ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know that Roberto Clemente played right field?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried again.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, you heard of Babe Ruth, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, well Babe Ruth played right field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He did?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Indeed he did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And Pete Rose, he played right field too.''
</P>
<P>
   This revelation brought nothing but a blank stare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever hear of Hank Aaron?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he played right field too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin may have heard of Hank Aaron, but he didn't know who he
was. Much the pity, much the time warp.
</P>
<P>
   We did not drift over to center field, where Willie Mays, Ty
Cobb, Joe DiMaggio and Mickey Mantle once ruled and where Ken
Griffey Jr. now rules. Kevin never has been awarded center field
because, in addition to his being sluggish, there is not a center
fielder, per say, on the team. There are two of them, one in left
center and one in right center; a picket line of dubious fielding
talent. Like the right fielder, they cannot hit either. And the
only thing the left fielder seems to be able to hit is his head _
up against a ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   In two games over the weekend, I watched Kevin come to bat six
times. He walked five times and struck out once. With the exception
of a swing at the third strike in his last time up, Kevin never
took the bat off his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   It's not so much that Kevin can't hit, it's that he won't hit.
If he can be convinced to swing at the pitches, he might connect _
thus earning his ticket out of right field.
</P>
<P>
   That's his ambition: to get away from the outfield, where few
balls come out to you and you spend time watching a game on the
other field. Nothing I can say about the baseball greats who
patrolled right field will convince him he is at a prestigious
position because, at his age, right field is the Siberia of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It was when I was his age and I suppose it always will be.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
