u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN15-COX     03-13 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Reserve `Nazi' for the Nazis
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bristly New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is hard to love
even from a safe distance several states away, but he doesn't
deserve this: to be portrayed as a Nazi in the Whitney Museum's
biennial show of cutting-edge American art.
</P>
<P>
   But there the mayor is, in the company of Hitler and other Nazis
with the recorded sound of marching boots in the background, all
parts of an installation by artist Hans Haacke, with assorted
quotes written in that Gothic typeface that is one of the homages
our neo-Nazi web sites pay to the originals.
</P>
<P>
   This is payback for the mayor making a cheap-shot stink over a
piece of art in a show at the Brooklyn Museum. Giuliani nosily
denounced a depiction of the Virgin Mary as blasphemous, though
that clearly was not its intent, and threatened the museum's public
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani deserves a comeuppance for his demagoguery, but he
doesn't deserve to be cast as a Nazi, for the simple reason that
the only people who deserve that defamation are other Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Grant the Nazis their uniqueness. Their Holocaust had rivals in
its century _ Stalin's devastation of Russia's kulaks, the Khmer
Rouge's mass murder of fellow Cambodians _ but it had no equals.
</P>
<P>
   No other social or political crime set out to kill every man,
woman, child and infant just because of who they were _ Jews _ at
the moment of their birth. And certainly no other crime came so
horrifyingly close to actually achieving that.
</P>
<P>
   It cheapens the sacrifice of the Holocaust's victims, and
trivializes the Holocaust's evil, to make glib slanders from that
awesome tragedy. Giuliani's political grandstanding against a minor
work of art is a piffling offense in comparison to this work of
art's implied claim that the act was on a par with Nazism.
</P>
<P>
   _ Poor George W. He can't get John McCain's endorsement and he
can't get rid of Pat Robertson's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vice President and pending Democratic presidential nominee Al
Gore has declared for campaign funding reform.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, Good. What it is not, is Believable.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Republicans, most Democrats have talked a good
funding-reform game. They have yet to play one, however. Democratic
rhetoric is strongest in the years when Democrats fail to control
either the White House or Congress and can plead political
impotence. They somehow forget about reform when they have the
power to enact it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore particularly has a steep hill of skepticism to crest on the
issue. There is no evidence he was personally culpable for the
funding excesses at that Buddhist temple hustle in the '96
campaign, at any mention of which the GOP draws itself up into
pious indignation, but he was very much a part of unseemly
money-grubbing throughout that season.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's conversion might be more credible if he and
the congressional Democratic leaders drafted specific legislation
that could be examined and debated this year and pledged themselves
to its enactment if they prevail in the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
