<HEADER>
A5177 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN14-COX     03-13 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small town paper allows escape from everyday drama
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR KEY, Fla. _ I'm tired of current events. Politics and
other general stupidities have lost their luster. That's why I'm
sitting here on my rented porch counting pelicans and watching the
tide roll in. No television and no newspapers _ except for the
local weekly.
</P>
<P>
   I do not wish to read another word about George W. and his visit
to Bob Jones University. Frankly, if I'd been writing that headline
it would have read: Dumb and Dumber go to college.
</P>
<P>
   And the details of candidate McCain's alienation of non-meat
eaters with his naive pronouncement that he doesn't care where his
votes come from, interest me not at all. It's not my problem if he
goes around saying stupid stuff like: ``I welcome support from
across the social spectrum _ Independents, Democrats,
</P>
<P>
   Libertarians, and vegetarians.''
</P>
<P>
   American politics, folks, is adrift in a sea of ennui.
</P>
<P>
   And so is television. Do any of us honestly want to hear another
word about the maybe-or-maybe-not millionaire, Rick Rockwell, and
his ``add money and stir'' instant bride? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   But for those of us who still enjoy the smudge of print on our
fingers, there is a solution. Subscribe to a small town weekly,
like the one I'm reading this morning and for a change, enjoy the
news.
</P>
<P>
   The lead story in this week's Cedar Key Beacon, is about a
contest of a different kind. A front page photo shows an award
ceremony being held in the city park's gazebo to honor a local
garden club woman for ``leading the charge against Brazilian pepper
plants,'' a non-native, and highly invasive pest that's trying to
take over the island.
</P>
<P>
   The program was followed by a ``work morning in the Fenimore
Mill area'' and a plea for more volunteers to help in the battle
against the exotic nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   On page 3 is a column by the publisher/managing editor. ``Monday
morning,'' she writes, ``I strolled into work, sat down to my
computer, looked up and there was this gigantic spider hanging on
my curtain. I mean this spider was as big as my foot!''
</P>
<P>
   Now this is the kind of news with which ordinary folks can
identify, particularly the part about how when she hollered for
help, the paper's circulation manager came to the rescue _ more or
less. While he dithered about whether to shoot the hairy-legged
invader or just catch him, the bug got away only to show up a
couple of days later in the publisher's desk drawer. At last
report, ``Spider Man'' is still on the loose.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing news on page 5 tells us ``sheepshead are running
real big on the offshore reefs, some up to 10 to 12 pounds,'' and
the ``best action from the pier this week has been the run of black
drum, which have been running 40 to 60 pounds, and should keep it
up through March.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer closes with sage advice for all fishermen: ``Early to
bed, early to rise. Fish like hell, and make up lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I missed ``Waffles and Art'' at the Cedar Key
Arts Center where folks were invited to come for breakfast and
bring their works-in-progress for helpful critique.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a graduate of the Boston Museum School of Fine Arts
hosts ``Basic Drawing Classes'' for the community. Next year a
couple of totem carvers from Oregon will be bringing their work to
town.
</P>
<P>
   Page 13 offers a recipe for baked soft-shell crabs; rinse,
drain, drizzle with butter and lemon juice, and top with a sprinkle
of parsley. Simple enough, but I don't cook anything that's looking
at me or still wearing its wigglers.
</P>
<P>
   On page 19 is the picture of a stilt house for sale. Has its own
elevator. If I could afford to, I'd buy it and move here, since I
already like the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, I like it so much that I've been toying with the
notion of stopping in and swapping a few small-town newspapering
stories with the Beacon folks _ just as soon as I hear they've
caught the spider.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett (AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5178 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-TECH-GAMER14-COX     03-13 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest demolition game lets you be a `Crazy Taxi' driverBy Staff
Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE:
</P>
<P>
   If you're searching for an awesome demolition game that includes
a bit of racing, look no further than Sega's Crazy Taxi ($50,
www.crazytaxi.com). This game is the best smash 'em, crash 'em
console game since Playstation's ``Demolition Derby.'' In ``Crazy
Taxi,'' you become one of four taxi driver personas cruising the
streets of San Francisco. Each driver has a different car with
different attributes. Some cars might handle better but have lousy
acceleration. After choosing your ride, you hit the streets,
picking up and dropping off fares as quickly as possible. This
means mowing down whatever is in your way. ``Crazy Taxi'' is a
blast to play and the best joy-ride to hit the console world in
quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP:
</P>
<P>
   Old school gamers will appreciate Nox ($50, PC,
www.westwood.com), Westwood Studios' new game that combines the
top-down perspective of ``Diablo'' with old-fashioned
monster-hunting and simple quests. The action/adventure game puts
you in the body of a regular guy living in a trailer who is
transported to a medieval fantasy world in which he must stop the
busty-but-evil Queen Hecubah. With easy action (drag your right
mouse button around to move your character, click with your left to
hack at monsters), the game is a breeze to play. And with lots of
spells, characters and environments to explore, it's deeper than
expected. The game's flaw, if any, is that the storyline is a
little too cheeky (although it's a nice reprieve from dark
``serious'' games) and the game never inspires the awe of the game
it most resembles, Blizzard Entertainment's original ``Diablo.''
But until ``Diablo II'' ships later this year, this is a fun and
breezy way to kill time, either in single or multiplayer modes.
</P>
<P>
   You might never think that a M1A2 tank could be used in a subtle
fashion, but NovaLogic's pixel-pushing tank simulation does well to
educate gamers on the finer nuances of tank command in Armored Fist
3 ($20; PC; www. novalogic.com). Game play is initially daunting in
spite of an excellent tutorial. However, most multifaceted elements
of tank operation and squad command can be optionally automated,
which makes this game potentially as simple and straightforward as
a sledgehammer. NovaLogic has opted to utilize its famous/notorious
``voxel'' technology for this offering, rather than the modern-day
rendered polygons. While that can make for brilliant graphics and
glorious gaseous explosions, it also causes frame-rate bogs if
things get busy _ which is exactly when speed and fluidity of
battle is paramount. Finding adversaries online is difficult too,
though there are a few out there banging around in fun but
frivolous death matches. We came. We saw. We blew up stuff. A
sledgehammer is cheaper and never bogs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
