</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low-end, with an upside
 &HT;    By Shaun Conlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It seems everybody and her Barbie is coming out
with an ``affordable'' (read: ``cheap'') digital camera these days,
and KBGear is no exception. The JamCam ($90; www.kbgear.com) offers
tolerable photographic quality to anyone with a home computer and
penchant for fun and frivolous photography. Nearly useless in low
light and with a misaligned viewfinder at close range, the JamCam
nevertheless serves up quick pics of Junior's 1st birthday ready to
e-mail to reluctant friends and relatives who've managed to avoid
slide shows for years. With its bundled software the JamCam can
also capture that great stunt your pal just pulled at the
skateboard park and paste it onto a customized bubblegum card. Even
the struggling, cost-minded Realtor can now display that massive
walk-in closet all over the Web. It's a low-end digital camera that
doesn't purport to be anything else.
</P>
