<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wireless now name of the game
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was once a big deal when a business installed a
computer network. The laying of the wires for that network signaled
a real advance in the way people worked.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, wires are out; wireless is in. You'll see exactly why
and how that is happening in the April issue of PC Computing. One
of the cover stories, ``The Wireless Revolution,'' says the key to
increased productivity now ``is cutting the cables. Smart companies
are using wireless technologies to work from anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In that same issue, look at the complex and sometimes mystifying
world of Internet domain names. If you're selling widgets, then the
Internet address of www. widgets.com (already taken, by the way)
can become a real asset to your business.
</P>
<P>
   The article is called ``The Name Game,'' and you'll learn why
some companies are paying as much as $7.5 million just for the
rights to use a specific name. You'll also find out how at least
one man is getting rich because of that.
</P>
<P>
   ON CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Big brother just got some help watching the e-mail you send from
work. There's a new program, aimed at businesses, called
MailMarshal (from Networking Technologies) that watches for leaks
of confidential information and personal abuses by ``customized
filtering of all incoming and outgoing e-mail and attachments.''
</P>
<P>
   While you are unlikely to buy the product to use at home, you
may want to know about it if you are an employee or an employer.
Networking Technologies says the program is in use at
Scientific-Atlanta, Campbell Soup and Volkswagen of America.
</P>
<P>
   Oh baby! Now you can buy what is described on the package as a
``virtual bundle of joy.'' It's a program called Babyz from
Mindscape Entertainment, and what you get is an on-screen baby who
can learn to talk and who lives in a virtual computerized house.
Users design their own baby's appearance and then watch him grow.
The program is available for PCs with at least a Pentium
166-megahertz processor and sells for about $40.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   It's mid-March and almost time for the swallows to come back to
Capistrano. Legend has it that the swallows first came to an old
mission in the California city ``seeking sanctuary from an
innkeeper who destroyed their nests. ... They return to the site
each year to nest, knowing their young can be safe within the
mission walls.''
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to make sure that the swallows get home in good
shape this year, you can follow the progress at
www.sanjuancapistrano.org/theswallows.htm.
</P>
<P>
   If you're trying to do a better job investing your money but
need a little help in these volatile times for the stock market,
check out a Web site at
www.ragingbull.com/mboard/boards.cgi?board &QC; QA.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be able to leave questions and get answers. However, keep
in mind that the accuracy of those answers from other investors may
be suspect. The really successful ones may be out on their yachts,
not typing answers on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
