<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest demolition game lets you be a `Crazy Taxi' driverBy Staff
Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE:
</P>
<P>
   If you're searching for an awesome demolition game that includes
a bit of racing, look no further than Sega's Crazy Taxi ($50,
www.crazytaxi.com). This game is the best smash 'em, crash 'em
console game since Playstation's ``Demolition Derby.'' In ``Crazy
Taxi,'' you become one of four taxi driver personas cruising the
streets of San Francisco. Each driver has a different car with
different attributes. Some cars might handle better but have lousy
acceleration. After choosing your ride, you hit the streets,
picking up and dropping off fares as quickly as possible. This
means mowing down whatever is in your way. ``Crazy Taxi'' is a
blast to play and the best joy-ride to hit the console world in
quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP:
</P>
<P>
   Old school gamers will appreciate Nox ($50, PC,
www.westwood.com), Westwood Studios' new game that combines the
top-down perspective of ``Diablo'' with old-fashioned
monster-hunting and simple quests. The action/adventure game puts
you in the body of a regular guy living in a trailer who is
transported to a medieval fantasy world in which he must stop the
busty-but-evil Queen Hecubah. With easy action (drag your right
mouse button around to move your character, click with your left to
hack at monsters), the game is a breeze to play. And with lots of
spells, characters and environments to explore, it's deeper than
expected. The game's flaw, if any, is that the storyline is a
little too cheeky (although it's a nice reprieve from dark
``serious'' games) and the game never inspires the awe of the game
it most resembles, Blizzard Entertainment's original ``Diablo.''
But until ``Diablo II'' ships later this year, this is a fun and
breezy way to kill time, either in single or multiplayer modes.
</P>
<P>
   You might never think that a M1A2 tank could be used in a subtle
fashion, but NovaLogic's pixel-pushing tank simulation does well to
educate gamers on the finer nuances of tank command in Armored Fist
3 ($20; PC; www. novalogic.com). Game play is initially daunting in
spite of an excellent tutorial. However, most multifaceted elements
of tank operation and squad command can be optionally automated,
which makes this game potentially as simple and straightforward as
a sledgehammer. NovaLogic has opted to utilize its famous/notorious
``voxel'' technology for this offering, rather than the modern-day
rendered polygons. While that can make for brilliant graphics and
glorious gaseous explosions, it also causes frame-rate bogs if
things get busy _ which is exactly when speed and fluidity of
battle is paramount. Finding adversaries online is difficult too,
though there are a few out there banging around in fun but
frivolous death matches. We came. We saw. We blew up stuff. A
sledgehammer is cheaper and never bogs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
