<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A little tough to tackle
 &HT;    By Dale Roe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Humongous Entertainment's Junior Sports division
has a new addition to the lineup. Backyard Football ($20,
www.humongous.com) lets kids organize pick-up games with some
familiar Junior Sports Backyard Bunch characters and adds
Humongously rendered kid versions of real NFL stars such as John
Elway and Jerry Rice. The game's interface is comparable to other
Junior Sports games (Backyard Baseball, Backyard Soccer) but play
is more difficult to master, perhaps because children in the game's
target age range (5-10) are less familiar with football than these
other sports. As in Backyard Baseball, kids can choose different
neighborhood fields on which to play, but the ability to designate
weather conditions is a fun, new feature exclusive to Backyard
Football. Humongous' new Junior Sports Network allows players with
Windows systems to play real-time with other children over the
Internet _ fun for them but a bummer for kids with Macs. We were
hoping for another Humongous touchdown, but this title might be
spending more time on the bench than in the CD-ROM drive.
</P>
<P>
   Backyard Football for Windows 98/95 requires a Pentium 90 or
better processor, 16MB RAM and a 4x CD-ROM. On a Macintosh, you'll
need a 133 Mhz or better PowerPC, System 7.5.3 or newer, 32 MB RAM
and a 4x CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
