<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0314-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A couple of tricks can help expose elusive path name
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Responding to a column about using the Windows Find
tool to locate files on your hard drive, a reader says he has
trouble determining the path name of something this handy program
has located.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that the path name of a file a couple
of directories deep is partially obscured by the Size and Type
columns.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of simple work-arounds for this.
</P>
<P>
   The Find Files window is usually about 5 inches square. All you
need do is click the enlarge box in the upper-right corner to zoom
it up to full screen, which will reveal the entire path name.
</P>
<P>
   If enlarging the window isn't feasible, put your cursor on the
dividing line between the In Folder column and the Size column. It
will turn into a four-way arrow. Click, hold, and move the dividing
line to the right, squeezing the Size and Type columns out of
sight, or nearly so. This will generally reveal enough of the path
name to locate the file.
</P>
<P>
   Another reader says that he recently upgraded Microsoft Internet
Explorer to Version 5 and in doing so seems to have lost the
ability to print. What to do? Well, that's hard to say, since he
didn't give details. I assume the problem is universal and not
confined to printing from Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't an uncommon problem across the board. I've had my
printer go west after installing a program, and it had nothing to
do with Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing one needs to know is exactly what happens when
you try to print. Do you get an error message? Probably not, in my
experience. Nothing at all happens. Go to the Control Panel
(Settings on the Start menu), select printers and click on the icon
of the selected printer.
</P>
<P>
   This should bring up the print queue. See if the file you're
trying to print is in the queue and what the status is. If printing
is suspended, turn it back on.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, go back to the Control Panel and select
System. From the System window, select Device Manager. When the
list of devices appears, click on printer. Select the driver tab.
Mostly likely you will see that the printer driver has wandered
off.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the task at hand is to reinstall the printer
driver. You do this with the Update Driver button at the bottom of
the driver window.
</P>
<P>
   This can be a maddening task due to the software routines, which
appear to have been designed by people who don't like us and want
to make us feel bad.
</P>
<P>
   However, in the case of printers, direct the program to the
folder containing your printer utility software. This will
generally get the ball rolling.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't, well ... good luck.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
