<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0314-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some lessons on e-mail
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometimes I think I should give e-mail lessons. For
one thing, just because I've been using e-mail for more years than
some of my readers have lived, I have a lot of practice. For
another, I have made a living writing for a long, long time.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of that writing was at big advertising agencies,
convincing people to buy everything from bags of charcoal to boxes
of fruit. You've got to figure that, if I had been a bricklayer for
30 years or so instead of a writer, that even a slow student would
learn a few skills along the way. If a person does that sort of
work long enough and survives, he learns a little bit about using
words in an effective way.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us would like to do that with e-mail. But judging from
the e-mail I get, a lot of people out there don't take the time to
do it well. Whether you're using e-mail _ as I did the other day _
to complain to an airline about lousy service, or to network with
potential employers, or even just to stay in touch with friends,
there are some ways to do a better job.
</P>
<P>
   So today, I'll take off my techno-guru hat, put on my writer hat
and give you some advice about simple ways to make your e-mail more
fun and more effective.
</P>
<P>
   Rule One: Have something to say and say it positively. Spend a
little time trying to figure out how to craft what you want to say.
Since e-mail is such an instant communication, some people type
without thinking. This rule is especially important with business
mail. If you react angrily, or with a mean spirit, you've made
things worse. Remember that, with this type of e-mail, you are
often trying to accomplish something, to convince someone. And _
just as is true in face-to-face conversations _ insults or
posturing seldom accomplish much in a positive way.
</P>
<P>
   Rule Two: Use simple and direct sentences. There's nothing worse
_ and I get plenty of e-mail like this _ than a wordy e-mail that
leaves me wondering what that person is trying to say. I've
literally gotten some where I can't tell if the person is
complaining, praising or asking a question. Remember that, unlike
in spoken conversation, the reader can't ask what you mean, can't
see your expression (or in my case, the way I'm waving my arms
around), so if you have to choose between clarity and drama, pick
clarity. Use complete sentences, and read your mail back to
yourself to see if it would make sense to you if you'd never met
the person sending it.
</P>
<P>
   Rule Three: Be friendly, even when you don't feel that way. Some
people believe that _ to demonstrate their strong feelings _ they
have to start off an e-mail with an insult. That makes it difficult
for the reader to absorb the rest of the message with an open mind.
Unless the whole notion of the e-mail is to show how angry you are
(and there are times when that's appropriate), try to sound
reasonable and friendly. If you are trying to convince someone to
do something or think something or to listen to you, you'll
accomplish more by coming across as a reasonable person. You can
still disagree strongly without insulting someone. Let's say the
rental car folks messed up. In a face-to-face encounter you
wouldn't (I hope) stalk up to the car rental counter and say:
You're an idiot, and I want you to help me. You know that wouldn't
get you much help. Instead, you'd try to win the person over, get
him or her on your side. The same rules apply in e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Rule Four: Rely on facts, not just opinions. It's just another
way of saying: Back up what you say; prove it. Don't just make
empty claims.
</P>
<P>
   Rule Five: When you have had your say, shut up.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to follow Rule Five right now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
