<HEADER>
A5198 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0314-COX     03-13 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0314-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _Q: Last-minute question!
<TEXT>
My two boys are learning Spanish. I'd like to reinforce that by
taking them to Mexico for three to four days during spring break.
They would like to see some ancient Indian ruins, but none of us
has a passport. Any suggestions? _ K.S.W.
<P>
   A: Valid passports are the best form of citizenship
identification. However, it is possible to travel to Mexico without
one. Each traveler needs a certified copy of a birth certificate
and photo identification. Traveling without Dad? A notarized
consent from the other parent is necessary when children travel
with one parent, alone or in someone else's custody.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for a catalog that had T-shirts that when you
wear them, it looks like you're wearing a bikini back and front. _
B.F.
</P>
<P>
   A: These T-shirts are available for $29.95 (plus shipping and
handling) through Caribbean Tan. To order the bikini T-shirt
(regular or XL) and other ``trompe l'oeil'' beach wear (for
example, ``He-Man'' T-shirt or the Mermaid T-shirt), visit
www.sexybikinis.com or call (612) 938-7799
</P>
<P>
   Q: The PBS television show ``Ballykissangel'' lists in its
credits that it is filmed/taped in parts of Ireland. Is there a
place called Ballykissangel? If so, where is it? _ Les Bearss
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, yes and no. No town in the Republic of Ireland is
actually named Ballykissangel although there is a Ballycastle, a
Ballymoney (in Northern Ireland) and a Ballyshannon. This popular
BBC-distributed series about the lusts, loves and lives of a rural
Irish community is filmed in Avoca, County Wicklow (south of Dublin
in eastern Ireland) _ at least the exterior shots are. Interiors
are filmed at Ardmore Studios just outside Dublin. Avoca has been
besieged by tourists, says KLRU's Maria Rodriquez, since the
series' inception.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I design needlepoint canvases with a religious theme. I have
a question regarding St. Jude. A small flame is present on his
forehead in all the paintings I have seen of him _ the prayer card,
his statue at the hospital for children. In all my research I have
found no explanation for it. _ Judy Harper
</P>
<P>
   A: The flame is the traditional sign of Pentecost, an event in
which the Holy Spirit descended upon the Apostles 50 days after the
Resurrection of Jesus, on the ancient Jewish festival called the
``feast of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Because St. Jude was one of the 12 Apostles, many depict him
with this flame, says Helen Osman, spokeswoman for the Catholic
Diocese of Austin. St. Jude is the patron saint of lost causes and
desperate situations because he sent a letter to the faithful
admonishing them to persevere during difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are having a baseball theme wedding and a reception with
ballpark food. I would like to give out miniature key chain bats _
ideally with personalized bats. I could surf the Web, but I'm not
that savvy or that patient. If the bats are not available, then
personalized baseballs or pennants would be fun, too. I am not
going with baseball caps because I have more than 300 guests and am
trying to keep favors below $2. _ G.M.E.
</P>
<P>
   A: Wearing white and donning a tux are not enough for some
couples. Here are items that fit your requirements (about $2 each
with imprint when you purchase 300) from ADnet (339-9695): baseball
bat key tags, baseball bat pens or baseball and bat combination key
chains. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During the latter part of April my family will visit our
nation's capital. I've read that tours of public buildings and
monuments are free but passes are required that can be obtained
through my local representatives. Whom do I need to contact, and if
possible could you send my family of four tour passes? _ Hope
Rogers-Eldridge
</P>
<P>
   A: Fresh out of tickets, and you may be too late to get them
from officials like senators or representatives. Most require two
months' advance notice. Try calling your senator's Washington
office and ask for the tour officer. Special or advance tours may
be arranged for sites such as the Bureau of Engraving and Printing,
the Federal Bureau of Investigation, the Kennedy Center, and the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are having an argument about the reptiles in the Budweiser
advertisements. Someone says they are chameleons; I say they are
not. _ O. Patton
</P>
<P>
   A: They're not chameleons; they are not even lizards. These
creatures are the creation of the product designers, claim the
folks at Anheuser-Busch. Did you bet on their names? Frank and
Louie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My daughter moved into a previously owned home with carpeting
less than two years old. She reports a strong pet odor, apparently
from dogs left inside. The carpeting has been steam-cleaned
professionally, but the smell lingers. Any suggestions? She left
Austin with heels dragging, and I would like to make this
experience as pleasant as possible.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeri Porter
</P>
<P>
   A: Odor neutralizers include ammonia or vinegar in diluted
quantities (rinse well). Odor may linger in the padding or the
porous concrete slab _ even if the carpet is replaced. Cleaning and
sealing the slab before recarpeting may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
