<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5199 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN14-COX     03-13 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   FACING UP TO MUSTACHELESS LIVING
</P>
<P>
   Allow me to make this clear: I am not a candidate for public
office.
</P>
<P>
   If nominated, I will not run; if elected, I will not serve. I
will not
</P>
<P>
   accept contributions of hard money, soft money, firm money,
fluffy
</P>
<P>
   money or beer money.
</P>
<P>
   This must be said up front because I took an action that could
be
</P>
<P>
   open to all manner of misinterpretation and malicious
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Something that traditionally is a sure tip-off someone is about
to
</P>
<P>
   enter the political arena.
</P>
<P>
   I shaved my mustache.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign consultants routinely force their clients to lose
beards,
</P>
<P>
   mustaches and even overabundant eyebrows before they form the
</P>
<P>
   first exploratory not-quite campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't had a president with a mustache since William Howard
</P>
<P>
   Taft. And although the Florida governorship went reliably to men
</P>
<P>
   with mustaches from 1901 to 1913 the Golden Age of Public
</P>
<P>
   Servant Mustaches the tradition came to an end with the bland,
</P>
<P>
   clean-shaven face of Park Trammell, never to return.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what killed the mustache from American political
life
</P>
<P>
   after World War I, but it's the Republic's loss.
</P>
<P>
   We are told that voters find a mustachioed man untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Albert Schweitzer, Gandhi and Captain Kangaroo wore
</P>
<P>
   them. Perhaps it's because the public detects the smile of a
</P>
<P>
   straddler underneath the lip hair. A man who wants it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who craves both the respectability of the clean-shaven
</P>
<P>
   and the rakishness of the bearded. Somehow, being partly
</P>
<P>
   untrimmed suggests you're a trimmer.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of the mustache has even moved into more flamboyant
</P>
<P>
   world entertainment, Tom Selleck and even Weird Al Yankovic have
</P>
<P>
   stopped fighting the cultural tide and come clean.
</P>
<P>
   In my own case, credibility is not an issue. I'm a columnist.
People
</P>
<P>
   only half-believe any of us on a good day. Nor am I slavishly
</P>
<P>
   following fashion. The fashion sense of the average American
</P>
<P>
   journalist vies with that of software engineers, physicists and
</P>
<P>
   people who serve beer in places that have broken cue sticks
</P>
<P>
   strategically placed beneath the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   No, I blame spring. The urge for a new beginning, a new
identity.
</P>
<P>
   We overestimate the way a face can be overhauled by the removal
</P>
<P>
   of facial hair. In movies, an escaped convict, a man on the run,
a
</P>
<P>
   secret agent who must be on the next plane across the border
will
</P>
<P>
   slip into a washroom, shave his mustache and be utterly
</P>
<P>
   transformed. As unrecognizable as if he grew a new head. (Maybe
</P>
<P>
   this is a reason why we won't vote for mustached men: we don't
</P>
<P>
   want them to escape us undetected.)
</P>
<P>
   Shearing myself before the bathroom mirror, I imagined the ease
</P>
<P>
   with which I'd sneak out of the country unrecognized. ``He
looked
</P>
<P>
   like that guy, only older and not as trustworthy,'' witnesses
would
</P>
<P>
   say pointing at me.
</P>
<P>
   The urge for a new face is a difficult thing to explain. When
people
</P>
<P>
   ask why I did it, I have no ready answer. The proper pose is to
</P>
<P>
   make it sound like a spontaneous, no-big deal kind of decision.
In
</P>
<P>
   truth, there are only 10 reasons one can legitimately give for
</P>
<P>
   shaving a mustache. These are, in order of popularity of use:
</P>
<P>
   -- I just got tired of it. (The hands-down champ. It is simple
and
</P>
<P>
   can't be gainsaid. It denies, without any specifics, that there
was
</P>
<P>
   anxiety, second-thoughts or girlfriend-generated pressure
</P>
<P>
   associated with the move.)
</P>
<P>
   -- Beer gets in it.
</P>
<P>
   -- It gets all itchy in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't tell anyone but I have a job interview.
</P>
<P>
   -- I don't want to look like the photo in the post office.
</P>
<P>
   -- So viewers will know that I'm the one who is the good twin.
</P>
<P>
   -- It made it impossible to really rock out on the trombone.
</P>
<P>
   -- I'm sick of the Saddam Hussein jokes.
</P>
<P>
   -- Interferes with my space suit's respirator.
</P>
<P>
   -- To show solidarity with Burt Reynolds in these difficult
times.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. Anything else sounds vain or pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the real reasons, I am enjoying a newfound taste for
ice
</P>
<P>
   cream and the half-second of nonrecognition that strikes me when
I
</P>
<P>
   first appear before the mirror each morning.
</P>
<P>
   It feels like a new face. And it's a lot cheaper than surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.) News-
</P>
<P>
   Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
