<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5207 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0314     03-13 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN0314-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who wants to harry a network?
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Pondering the schlock TV scandal that has had
tongues wagging for what seems like forever, we have to wonder why
this pathetic two-hour spectacle of bad taste and sexism has become
such a Big Deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants To Marry a Multimillionaire?'' certainly wasn't the
first trash TV special and, despite Fox's protestations to the
contrary, won't be the last. Depending on whether you're judging on
morality or grossness, it's not even the worst.
</P>
<P>
   If Fox finally crossed a line, whose and what line was it? Was a
marriage contest, based solely on looks and wealth, really so much
worse than a disgruntled restaurant worker spitting into an
unsuspecting customer's food? Or a sweet-faced pooch suddenly
turning on its owner and chewing up his face?
</P>
<P>
   Viewers weren't terribly offended by any of the above, least of
all ``Multimillionaire.'' They tuned in by the millions _ 23
million to be exact _ when the show aired Feb. 15. It was the first
program to beat ABC's red-hot game show ``Who Wants To Be a
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seemed to be publicly troubled until the mainstream media
told them to be. The backlash started with the New York Times,
which discovered that multimillionaire Rick Rockwell (a) might not
be the real estate tycoon he said he was and (b) may have slapped
and threatened to kill a former fiancee. So if Rockwell had been a
bona fide fat-cat with no hint of impropriety, this farcical
marriage would have been OK?
</P>
<P>
   Unearthing the dirt on Rick was a legitimate news story, but the
revelations gave the Big Three networks an opportunity to have a
major conniption. Without missing a beat, they jumped in and
started braying about ``Multimillionaire'' and Fox's penchant for
trash TV. Was it coincidence that they managed to capitalize on a
competitor's screw up? Not a bit.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Three love to bash Fox because it makes them feel
superior _ despite the fact that CBS has two potentially
exploitative reality shows planned for summer and NBC was once
caught staging a truck explosion on ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox has a reputation as an upstart, and the Big Three have felt
threatened by it for years. Besides the ratings-grabbing reality
specials, Fox has produced some innovative programs, including the
much-talked-about ``Ally McBeal,'' the long-running classic ``The
Simpsons,'' the genre-bending ``X-Files'' and the red-hot newcomer
``Malcolm in the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Who Wants To Marry a Multimillionaire'' had been on ABC or
NBC, would it have provoked such a stink? Probably not, at least
not on the so-called legitimate TV news programs. The other
networks stretched the controversy into a week-long gala of
Fox-bashing, exploiting the exploiters for their own gain. In the
heart of the February sweeps, ABC and NBC were able to reap the
rewards of the Fox scandal while seeming to stand above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Sawyer, breathlessly asking about consummation,
practically salivated while grilling bride Darva Conger on ``Good
Morning America.'' This hand-wringing went on for two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was thinking clearly,'' Darva whined. ``This
was a terrible mistake in judgment on my part, but it does not
represent who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dateline NBC'' sounded like it had broken a political scandal
when it crowed about having nabbed failed stand-up comic Rockwell.
Good 'ol Rick lived up to his reputation as a jerk by grinning when
asked if he'd ever threatened to kill his fiancee. The next act in
the Rick-and-Darva Circus found him sobbing on ``Entertainment
Tonight.'' ``I'm really hurting right now,'' he sniveled.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fall-out coverage actually tried to generate
sympathy for the unhappy couple. What in the world for? Both got
what they deserved and, indeed, what they asked for. They made a
mockery of an institution many people consider sacred. The
producers may have dreamed up the notion of turning holy matrimony
into a blind date, but these two profited from it. Even after the
anticipated annulment, Darva will walk away with $100,000 in
prizes, and Rick will have enough publicity to jump-start his
stand-up career.
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassing mess also became fodder for newspaper
editorials. Jumping on their anti-TV bandwagons, they banged their
drums for days.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe wrote: ``Who wants to take a shower after
watching 'Who Wants To Marry a Multimillionaire?' ... All culture
needn't be Shakespeare and Virginia Woolf. But television should at
least aim for outrageousness without the high-glitz humiliation of
parading around like cattle to win a husband who may or may not
have a criminal record.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orlando Sentinel chimed in: `` 'Multimillionaire' reduces
male-female relationships to their most primitive, stereotypical
essence: Girls want a guy with money. Boys want a looker for sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, sure it was an awful show, but whose fault is it that TV
is littered with such trash? Is it the TV networks or the viewers?
It's both, but we can only take responsibility for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   For TV programmers, cheap-to-produce reality shows that generate
big buzz and big ratings are a narcotic. It's a dog-eat-dog world
out there, and reality specials are tasty Milk-Bones. Last week's
pledge from Fox chairman Sandy Grushow to ditch all exploitative
reality shows was disingenuous at best. After all, he made the same
promise in January before a roomful of TV critics. Even as he
spoke, his network was screening hundreds of potential
multimillionaire grooms and thousands of potential golddigger
brides.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Grushow also said last week he would ``get to
the bottom'' of how ``Multimillionaire'' wound up on Fox to begin
with. Oh, please. Does anyone really believe the head of the
network doesn't know what's on his schedule? Of course he knew, and
he was probably thrilled when his publicity department bragged the
next day that the Rick and Darva Show was ``the most-watched
marriage ceremony since Charles and Diana.''
</P>
<P>
   I stayed away from the the Fox spectacle, even though I probably
should have watched it as part of my job. But there is a line I'm
unwilling to cross, and ``Multimillionaire'' was on the other side,
along with most of the other trash specials. My stomach can only
take so much. The networks may not have a line, but viewers should.
</P>
<P>
   I've said this a thousand times, and I'll say it again: Ignore
this trash, and it will disappear. If Diane Sawyer and the other
network stars want to wallow in this slop, fine. But the rest of us
shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
