<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5209 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-FEATURE-STOCKMARK     03-13 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-STOCKMARKET0314-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grab the stock market by the horns
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Do your parents ever seem nervous when they're
watching TV news about the stock market?
</P>
<P>
   It's probably because they own stock. When you buy stock, you
buy a small part of a large company. You are one of the owners of
the company. But so are thousands of other people, known as
stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 million Americans own stock, known as ``shares,'' in
more than 10,000 companies. Not all companies sell shares, but most
of the big ones do.
</P>
<P>
   But all of this doesn't explain why your parents are worried,
does it? Your parents own lots of stuff, but you don't see Dad
nervous about the hedge clippers he bought last week, do you?
</P>
<P>
   One difference is that when you buy stock, it's hard to know if
you made the right choice. There are thousands of stocks available,
from companies such as Coca-Cola, Home Depot, Toys ``R'' Us,
Wal-Mart and the Gap. The value of all these stocks goes up and
down constantly.
</P>
<P>
   When people buy stock that goes down, they lose money _
sometimes a lot of money. But people who bought stock in Atlanta
companies Coca-Cola and Home Depot years ago made a good buy. Some
of them are now millionaires!
</P>
<P>
   BUY CAREFULLY
</P>
<P>
   Buying stock is different from buying other things. Most people
don't buy stock to keep it. Instead, they hope to sell it later for
more money than they paid. That's called an investment.
</P>
<P>
   If they made a smart investment, they will make money _ a profit
_ when they sell the stock. If they bought the wrong stock, they
made a bad investment. When they sell the stock, they'll get less
money than they paid. Instead of a profit, they'll have a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Buying and selling stocks can get very complicated. People who
talk about the stock market sometimes use lots of strange words to
describe it.
</P>
<P>
   LEARN THE WORDS
</P>
<P>
   Some of the terms they use, such as ``bear market'' and ``bull
market,'' can be pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   A bear market is when the prices of many stocks go down, and
many investors sell their stock because they're afraid prices will
go even lower.
</P>
<P>
   A bull market is when the prices of many stocks go up, and many
investors buy stock because they hope the prices will go even
higher.The stock market is also known as ``Wall Street,'' the
street in New York City where the New York Stock Exchange is
located. These days, people buy and sell stock in many ways, often
by telephone or over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If you're interested in the stock market, there are Web sites
that explain the stock market to young people.
</P>
<P>
   The Young Investor site (www.smgww.org) is great because it also
has ``The Stock Market Game.'' In the game, you pretend that you've
invested $100,000 in the stock market. You can research the
companies first, then place your bets.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 weeks, see what your stock is worth. You might be a
``millionaire.'' Or, if you chose some bad stocks, you might have
``lost'' a lot of money in the game and wonder why.
</P>
<P>
   Why did I buy that stock?
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't I put all my money into hedge clippers?
</P>
<P>
   If I had, I'd be so much happier!
</P>
<P>
   HOW MUCH IS GRIFFEY WORTH?
</P>
<P>
   One simple way to understand how the stock market works is to
compare it to trading baseball cards.
</P>
<P>
   Like stock, a baseball card is really a popularity contest. The
more people want a card, or a stock, the more they are willing to
pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   The Ken Griffey Jr. rookie baseball card is a great example of
that. In 1989, Griffey's first year in the major leagues, you could
buy his Upper Deck card for $3. Because he became such a superstar,
today that card is worth $150!
</P>
<P>
   Another good example is the baseball card of Mark McGwire. Even
though McGwire has always been a star, he wasn't as popular as
Griffey until two seasons ago, when he broke Roger Maris' season
home run record.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, according to Bryan Theis, the owner of Ballpark
Cards in Germantown, Md., McGwire's rookie card sold for only $5.
Try to buy one today, and it will cost $200!
</P>
<P>
   No wonder, then, that your parents may be so interested in the
news about Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices usually change every day, every hour and sometimes
every minute. If your parents' stock went up today, Wall Street
news can be the most fun show on television. If the stock went
down, it can be the scariest show on television.
</P>
<P>
   But tomorrow everything could change!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
