<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's down to Gore and Bush
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ U.S. Sen. John McCain and Bill Bradley, a former
senator, dropped out of the presidential race Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was running against Texas Gov. George W. Bush for the
Republican nomination. Bradley was running against Vice President
Al Gore for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates compete in state primaries to win delegates to
their party conventions, held in the summer. At the conventions,
the delegates vote on who will be their party's candidate in the
presidential election in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Super Tuesday,'' which was last Tuesday, was the biggest day
for primaries. McCain won four of the 13 Republican primaries held
Tuesday, and Bradley didn't win any primaries. Both candidates lost
in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley ``endorsed,'' or said he would support, Gore. McCain did
not endorse Bush but wished him well.
</P>
<P>
   DOGS RACE ACROSS ALASKA
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Doug Swingley set a blistering pace down the
Yukon River over the weekend to reclaim the lead in the Iditarod
Trail Sled Dog Race in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   A record 81 dog sled teams began the 1,150-mile race across
Alaska on March 5. The icy trail goes from Anchorage to Nome. The
race was begun to commemorate the lifesaving relay of medicine to
Nome by mushers in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   The first 30 finishers will share in a $525,000 purse, the
largest ever. The winner gets $60,000 and a new pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   The race record was set in 1995 by Swingley, who finished in
nine days, two hours and 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about the race, sled dogs and mushers, check out
teacher.scholastic.com/iditarod/home.htm. You also can see each leg
of the trail on an interactive map.
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE PRICES RISING
</P>
<P>
   Drivers across America can expect to pay more to fill their gas
tanks this spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   The countries that produce oil decided to cut down on
production, because they felt that oil prices were too low. Now
there is less oil being produced, so the price is rising. Because
gasoline is made from oil, the price of gasoline also is going up.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for gasoline in the Atlanta area range from about $1.34
to $1.40 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
