<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u a BC-NEW-AMERICA-BUSH-EQUA     03-13 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-BUSH-EQUALS-CONVENIENT-COMPASSION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE W.'S POLITICS OF CONVENIENT COMPASSION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By JAMES E. GARCIA  
 &HT;    Early in his campaign, Republican presidential candidate George
W. Bush routinely promoted himself as a ``compassionate
conservative.'' He often still does _ even as he has grown less
compassionate by the day.
 &HT;    The truth is I never bought Bush's line about being
compassionate to anyone but those who march in lock step with his
views, and his campaign tactics over the past few months have
confirmed my initial instincts.
 &HT;    First, consider Bush's reaction to the barrage of criticism he
received after his speech at Bob Jones University. The South
Carolina school prohibits interracial dating _ unless students have
a note from their parents. The school's leaders have labeled
Catholicism a ``satanic cult.''
 &HT;    Asked why his speech did not condemn the university for its
bigoted policies, Bush insisted that that wasn't the purpose of his
appearance.
 &HT;    Three weeks later _ and only days before a primary election in
which he needed the support of Catholic voters _ Bush finally
acknowledged in a letter to New York Cardinal John O'Conner: ``On
reflection, I should have been more clear in disassociating myself
from anti-Catholic sentiments and racial prejudice.''
 &HT;    Bush says he is not anti-Catholic or racist. I believe him. But
I am disturbed by Bush's apparent willingness to offend minorities
and Catholics for the sake of winning a few extra right-wing votes.
 &HT;    To tolerate bigotry, Bush, is to encourage it.
 &HT;    Bush also has shown little compassion for another minority
group: gays and lesbians.
 &HT;    While Bush didn't think twice about delivering a speech at Bob
Jones University, he refused for months to meet with the Log Cabin
Republicans, a national organization of gays and lesbians who
support the GOP. Only now, after Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has
dropped out of the race and Bush is virtually assured of winning
the GOP nomination, has the candidate agreed to meet with the
group's leadership.
 &HT;    Bush also refuses to say if he would knowingly appoint a gay
person to his administration.
 &HT;    If Bush is truly compassionate, he would support pending federal
legislation that bans discrimination against homosexuals. He would
also take the time to meet with the leaders of other national gay
and lesbian organizations to hear what they have to say.
 &HT;    On the subject of affirmative action, Bush minimizes the plight
of women and minorities. He opposes affirmative action. He suggests
that all Americans now have an equal opportunity when applying for
jobs or university admissions. Bush is wrong.
 &HT;    Discrimination against women and people of color may be illegal,
but it is still part of the fabric of our society. Far more action
needs to be taken to counter it. Women still get paid less than men
for the same jobs. There are still glass ceilings in hiring and
promoting Latinos, African-Americans and other minorities. And many
states, including Texas, still have laws on the books that sanction
discrimination against homosexuals.
 &HT;    It is because of affirmative action programs and
anti-discrimination laws that hundreds of millions of women and
people of color have been able to climb in the ranks of American
society.
 &HT;    No matter what Bush claims, affirmative action is not about
setting racial, ethnic or gender quotas. The courts ruled long ago
that hiring or appointing a minority just to meet a numeric quota
is discriminatory and unconstitutional.
 &HT;    Furthermore, affirmative-action that ensures that a given pool
of job seekers, university students or judicial nominees includes
qualified women and minorities is not only legal, but fair, just
and, yes, compassionate.
 &HT;    To argue that affirmative action is no longer needed is
shortsighted and ultimately harmful to the noble goal of achieving
equality for women and people of color.
 &HT;    And how can we forget the controversy surrounding the
Confederate flag in South Carolina? Bush still refuses to criticize
those who say it's all right, even honorable, to fly the flag over
that state's capitol.
 &HT;    Confederate-flag supporters say it is a symbol of states'
rights. They're correct. The flag is a symbol of the Confederacy's
claim that it had a right, among other things, to enslave human
beings.
 &HT;    Bush's silence on the matter is an affront to the millions of
African-Americans whose ancestors suffered the brutality of slavery
and still suffer as a result of its legacy. And it is an affront to
anyone who considers that era as one of the most shameful in U.S.
history.
 &HT;    Throughout his campaign, Bush has insisted that he wants more
racial and ethnic minorities to join the GOP. It is a worthy goal.
This cannot happen until his party becomes genuinely more
inclusive.
 &HT;    So far, Bush's actions have not matched his words. He has done
more to divide us than unite us, and has exhibited little true
compassion.
 &HT;    So far, the compassion he has exhibited has proven to be little
more than the politics of convenient compassion.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (James E. Garcia is editor and publisher of Politico, a national
weekly newsletter focusing on U.S. Latino politics. E-mail
Politico1 at aol.com.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 James E. Garcia 
