<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-SAPPHO-SCREEN-WORKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK 2 ME SOME MORE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By AKILAH MONIFA  
 &HT;    Given the sky-high ratings for the recent HBO film presentation,
``If These Walls Could Talk 2: An Intimate Look at the Lesbian
Experience In America Through Three Decades,'' one wonders if
lesbians are coming back in style. Is a ``Year of the Lesbian''
lurking nearby? Or will lesbian characters in film and television
once again fade from the screen?
 &HT;    Positive change appeared to be on the horizon when, in 1997,
Ellen DeGeneres uttered the now famous words on her television
sit-com, ``Hi, I'm Ellen and I'm gay.'' It was a coming-out
triple-header _ for DeGeneres personally, her TV character and for
network prime time.
 &HT;    Many assumed it was only a matter of time before the small
screen lit up with lesbian shows and characters. At last we would
see ourselves _ albeit little blips at first _ on the cultural
radar known as television.
 &HT;    Instead, ``Ellen'' was unceremoniously dumped by ABC, and
DeGeneres' career plummeted. The ``Ellen'' backlash had begun.
Lesbian characters disappeared from prime time. DeGeneres was
marginalized: For the next two years, she appeared sporadically in
small film roles.
 &HT;    Fortunately the story has a happy ending.
 &HT;    Just when the chances of finding a major lesbian character on
television were on par with seeing a quark, DeGeneres returned with
three made-for-TV lesbian films. In addition, CBS is rumored to be
giving DeGeneres her own Carol Burnett-style comedy show.
 &HT;    DeGeneres may have personally righted career wrongs, but the
playing field remains far from even for lesbian characters and
stories in the entertainment business on the whole. According to
Scott Seomin, entertainment media director of Gay and Lesbian
Alliance Against Defamation, ``lesbians have been relegated to
small marginal roles and gay people of color are almost
nonexistent'' on the small screen.
 &HT;    GLAAD's findings report 29 lesbian, gay or transgender
characters on broadcast and cable networks for the 1999-2000
season. That represents about a 5.3 percent portrayal rate out of a
total of 540 lead or supporting characters.
 &HT;    This portrayal rate includes kisses between straight female
characters. Currently, no regular lesbian lead character appears on
television. ``Xena'' _ a cult favorite _ contains cryptic
references but innuendo hardly counts.
 &HT;    ``Talk 2'' contained three separate stories set in three years _
1961, 1972 and 2000. For me, the most compelling segment was
``1961, '' in which Vanessa Redgrave and Marian Seldes dealt with
the death of a partner after a closeted 50-year relationship. The
universal theme of the story appealed to Redgrave.
 &HT;    ``I think it's a wonderful thing when people can learn the truth
about human life. Without melodrama, without cliche, but with all
those complicated and simple human touches that life is really
about. Although it's a very particular story about these two older
women, I think the script is everybody's story,'' Redgrave said.
 &HT;    ``Talk 2'' was many things to many people. For lesbians and
gays, it was celebrated, `must-see' TV. For our families, friends,
allies and open-minded strangers it offered a chance to learn more
about our lives. It also offers a potential learning curve for
folks who are unsure or uneducated about lesbianism. Ideally in the
viewing of such a program myths are dispelled, prejudices are
lessened and tolerance is enhanced.
 &HT;    Sharon Stone, who co-starred with DeGeneres in one of the
stories, talked about the effect the show had on her parents.
 &HT;    ``They were very supportive and visited me on location. If my
parents, a mainstream, middle-class couple in the middle of
Pennsylvania, think that this is good, then this isn't going to
scare people. This is going to open people's hearts.''
 &HT;    Or take the frat boy who attended a screening of ``Talk 2''
hoping to see a ``lesbian flick.''
 &HT;    ``I thought this was a lesbian movie,'' he said, ``this is just
about love.''
 &HT;    Therein lies the aim of the filmmakers who want people to
understand on a visceral level that lesbians are people too. As
Stone says, ``I am exactly like a gay woman except that I don't
sleep with women.''
 &HT;    Hopefully we will not have to wait another two years to see
another lesbian on the small screen.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Akilah Monifa is a free-lance writer in Oakland, Calif.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Akilah Monifa 
