<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-AID-TO-INDIANS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCREASED FEDERAL FUNDING FOR INDIANS: A SMALL STEP IN THE RIGHT
DIRECTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By KAREN LINCOLN MICHEL  
 &HT;    Among the many traditions of American Indians, one that grew out
of the 18th and 19th centuries was for our leaders to gather in the
nation's capital for treaty talks aimed at protecting the welfare
of tribes amid white expansion into our territories.
 &HT;    At least that was our view of treaty talks.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, the U.S. government's position was to negotiate the
purchase of Indian land for as little as possible, with no
intention of honoring that agreement later.
 &HT;    Those broken promises translate today into billions of dollars
in aid to the country's 2.4 million Indians.
 &HT;    Just two weeks ago, the tradition of journeying to Washington,
D.C., was carried on by current tribal leaders from across the
country. This time they met with President Clinton at the White
House to hear his plan for fulfilling the nation's monetary
obligation to America's 558 recognized tribes.
 &HT;    Clinton told tribal politicians and native leaders that his
fiscal 2001 budget proposal geared toward Indian tribes calls for
increased spending by 12 percent, bringing the total to $9.4
billion for new and existing programs.
 &HT;    It is a $1.2 billion hike over this year's budget, and the
increase addresses important issues in the areas of education,
housing, health care, the environment and crime prevention.
 &HT;    While $9.4 billion is nothing to sneeze at, some native leaders
say the budget falls considerably short of helping American Indians
and Alaska natives pull themselves out of poverty.
 &HT;    Susan Masten, president of the National Congress of American
Indians and chairwoman of the Yurok Tribe of California, reportedly
said that although Clinton's proposal is a good start, it ``does
not begin to address the Third World conditions on our
reservations.''
 &HT;    At the risk of sounding ungrateful, I agree with Masten. The
increase is a step in the right direction. But it is so long
overdue that it would take more of an Olympic long jump to catapult
spending where it ought to be.
 &HT;    Native-Americans continue to rank among the highest in terms of
suicide, teen pregnancy and high school dropout rates. Clinton
himself cited some grim statistics, saying that native people are
twice as likely as other Americans to be victims of violent crime,
that unemployment on reservations sometimes reaches as high as 70
percent and that one-third of Indians live in poverty.
 &HT;    Although the budget proposal certainly will not alleviate all
these problems, it does attack some of the underlying issues.
 &HT;    For instance, six schools run by the Bureau of Indian Affairs
(BIA) will be replaced with new facilities, and $171.2 million is
proposed to complete repair and maintenance work at existing
schools. The total request for construction programs for schools is
$300.5 million, an increase of $167.3 million over the current
level.
 &HT;    As part of Clinton's nationwide initiative to hire 100,000
teachers to reduce class size to an average of 18 children in the
first three grades of elementary school, the 2001 budget calls for
$6 million for BIA-funded schools to recruit, train and hire more
teachers.
 &HT;    Tribal colleges also will see a $3 million increase to help fund
operations, bringing that total to $38 million. Some of the funds
are earmarked for information technology in an effort to help
tribes gain access to the digital age.
 &HT;    The budget also includes $46 million more for the Commerce
Department to fund public-works projects on reservations, $60
million more for building and repairing reservation homes, $103
million in new spending on Indian law enforcement and $229 million
more for health care through the Indian Health Service.
 &HT;    Of that increased amount for health care, $35 million will
provide additional services to address diabetes, cancer, heart and
infectious diseases; community violence prevention; elder, maternal
and child health; emergency medical services and injury prevention;
mental-health issues; substance-abuse prevention; and dental
health.
 &HT;    Obviously without federal funding, American Indians and Alaska
natives would be subject to greater societal risks than they are
now.
 &HT;    Some people consider the federal appropriations a handout. But I
think about the native people of generations past who sacrificed
their lives, their land and many things they held sacred in the
belief that the U.S. government would keep its word.
 &HT;    I am a descendant of one of the Ho-Chunk treaty-signers whose
name was translated to English as Rogue. I am sure he understood
the magnitude of his actions as he traveled by horseback from our
homelands in Wisconsin to present-day Washington, D.C., to try to
secure a decent future for generations to come.
 &HT;    Knowing what he gave up then, I am sure he believed he was
setting into motion the right for his descendants to build better
lives today.
 &HT;    Hopefully Clinton's proposed budget will begin to help some
native people experience that better life.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Karen Lincoln Michel, past president of the Native-American
Journalists Association, is co-owner of News from Indian Country.) 
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Karen Lincoln Michel 
