<SLUG> BC-NEW-AMERICA-INTERRACIAL-MARRIAGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLESSED ARE THE YOUNG  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By ELAINE H. KIM  
 &HT;    Sometimes my students ask me personal questions as they grapple
with their own life decisions. Some ask about the seeming paradox
of being deeply interested in their Korean heritage while planning
to marry a non-Korean, which they fear may cause some people in the
Korean-American community to reject them.
 &HT;    Young Korean-Americans today are indeed blessed, living in an
era when old ideas about who can be American are giving way to
possibilities for new American identities, thanks in part to many
people repeatedly challenging race and sex discrimination over the
decades.
 &HT;    What younger Korean-Americans and I have in common is the
experience of growing up as Korean-Americans in a society that is
obsessed with race, but paradoxically refuses to admit to its
obsession, pretending instead to be ``colorblind.'' We have been
faced with the non-choice of being different and inferior on the
one hand and ``just like us'' but invisible on the other.
 &HT;    But unlike the struggles of young Korean-Americans today, my
childhood and young adult experiences were poisoned and disfigured
by the kind of apartheid life that Asian-Americans on the East
Coast often had before the civil-rights movement of the 1960s.
Those were the ``good old days'' about which so many Americans wax
nostalgic, when life was simpler and people were honest, before the
idyll started being disturbed by uppity, demanding black folks and
waves of messy brown and yellow immigrants.
 &HT;    For me, though, they were very ``bad old days.'' In high school,
no one asked me out on a date, even though I was considered
exceptional ``for an Oriental.'' I was not only a student
government officer, but also a cheerleader _ no mean feat for an
Asian-American in the blonde, blue-eyed 1950s.
 &HT;    I sat at the lunch table with the other cheerleaders, but I was
only a mascot. Even then I was asked about what to order at Chinese
restaurants.
 &HT;    Looking into the mirror, I thought I was beyond ugliness. When
you are too young to know better, you start to become what people
make of you. I would have been mortified to be lumped together in
my classmates' minds with other Asians, especially Asian men. Not
having seen very many Asians besides Fu Manchu, Charlie Chan and
Mr. Moto, all played by white actors with scotch tape on their
eyelids, I thought Asian men were singularly unappealing. I only
dreamed about James Dean and other movie stars.
 &HT;    It was not until I visited Korea, and later moved to California,
that I really began to experience Asians and Asian-Americans as
human beings. It has taken me many years to ``kill'' the white man
inside my head, the standard that ruled Asians and people of color
as inferior and everything white as superior.
 &HT;    During those years, I could barely speak with white people, let
alone keep company with a white man. It was as if even contact with
them would rivet me back into the paroxysms of self-hate that
racism had created.
 &HT;    Gradually I have been able to relax my vigilance and open my
heart, but it has been difficult, and it has taken a long time. The
bright side is that I have been fortunate enough to live in a
multiracial locale where it was possible to establish strong
relations with other Korean-Americans, other Asian-Americans and
other people of color while I was struggling with the white demons
inside my head.
 &HT;    Somehow, being made aware of the diversity and complexity of
these communities has helped me question the false notion of
monolithic white homogeneity. Although we are faced with different
manifestations of social inequality, it is certainly true that
there are many more options for people of color in the United
States today. Hopefully in the future, our children won't
experience the kinds of psychic and material damage we faced.
 &HT;    Among the teen-agers and 20-somethings I encounter in my albeit
very racially diverse environment, I have noticed increasing
acceptance of multiplicity, hybridity and heterogeneity, and less
interest in congealed, mandated identities and communities of
taste.
 &HT;    Today's communities of color are rebelling against the old
colored-white binaries that have dominated American thinking about
race up till now.
 &HT;    Because I experienced those ``good old days,'' I think I
understand why some people feel so defensive about interracial
marriage. Perhaps it's not about interracial marriage at all, but
about Asian-white intermarriage, because that can imply Asian
desire for whiteness in a white supremacist society.
 &HT;    But I don't agree with the people who disapprove of
Korean-Americans marrying people of other races and ethnicities. I
oppose the tendency among some Korean-Americans to try to regulate
Korean-American identity. In the end, they can't really know what
each individual might need and want, let alone why.
 &HT;    And in fact, they don't really care. Whether the would-be
arbiters of Korean-American identity like it or not,
Korean-Americans will be marrying people from many different
backgrounds in the 21st century _ not just whites, but Latinos,
African-Americans, other Asians and people of various mixed
heritages.
 &HT;    When people with different backgrounds get together, they can
bring twice as much to a relationship. Interracial marriage can
create exciting new possibilities.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Elaine H. Kim teaches Asian Studies and Comparative Ethnic
Studies at UC Berkeley.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 KoreAm Journal 
