<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-EXECUTION (San Francisco_ There's a short stretch of
Interstate 5 that brings back the pain for Sharon and David
Tidwell. It's where 22 years ago the Tidwells' 11-year-old
daughter, Annette Selix, was thrown to her death. Darrell Keith
Rich, 45, the man convicted of raping Selix and then tossing her
off the bridge 100 feet to her death, is scheduled to be executed
early Wednesday. He will be the eighth person to die in
</P>
<P>
   California since capital punishment resumed in 1992. By JIM
HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   WOMAN-COP (San Antonio) _ While her husband, ex-police union
boss Harold Flammia, based his career on strong-armed politics _
and ended up in prison for bribery _ Rose Mary Flammia was rising
through the San Antonio police ranks on intelligence and ability.
She did it, being sworn in as deputy chief. By JOE HOLLEY and BILL
HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   US-MEXICO (San Antonio) _ Explosive growth along the U.S.-Mexico
border demands a radical approach to fixing health and
environmental problems, and ignoring the international boundary
might be the first step, according to representatives from border
cities. By JEANNE RUSSELL.
</P>
<P>
   TAHOE-FACELIFT (South Lake Tahoe, Calif.) _ This mountain town
of 22,000 _ hugely popular with tourists, despite its shoddy '60s
countenance _ is planning a colossal face lift. It's a task as big
as the lake next door. Beginning May 1, buildings at the north end
of town will be bulldozed by the dozens. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONVERSE-SHOES (Undated) _ Thanks to the legendary basketball
star Chuck Taylor, Converse Inc. has been a top-scorer in the
business of athletic shoes. Lately, however, market bullies named
Nike and Adidas have been taking Converse to school. As a result,
the North Reading, Mass., company is counting on its new helium
shoe to revive the company's stature. By IHOSVANI RODRIGUEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The ultimate Bay Area bike
ride _ a loop of 475 miles in nine counties _ will feature the best
of the best: the coast, ridge lines, mountains and remote valleys.
By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Pity the families of Silicon
Valley, suffering from a horrible new disease called Sudden Wealth
Syndrome. Before you roll a crisp hundred into a green ribbon and
pin it on your lapel, rest assured that the disease is treatable.
Much the way many alcoholics treat their alcoholism with more
alcohol, the disease of Sudden Wealth Syndrome is being treated
with its cause: overdoses of money. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The man's voicemail message said
he just wanted information. ``You describe John McCain as
'anti-choice.' I assume that you mean he is against abortion, and
not that he is against people exercising their ability to make
choices about any number of issues,'' he said. When and why did
pro-abortion people started using ``choice'' instead of
``abortion?'' By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   CLARENCE-DARROW (Danville, Calif.) _ March 13 is the anniversary
of the death of Clarence Darrow, regarded by many as America's
greatest attorney and a man whose cases and crusades remind us how
intractable our ``new era'' problems really are. By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
