<SLUG> BC-CANADA-DIAMONDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA'S FRIGID OUTBACK ENTERS A NEW STONE AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EKATI DIAMOND MINE, Northwest Territories _ When the mercury
drops down to minus 40 degrees and below, steel bulldozer blades
scraping rock sometimes shatter like a champagne bottle flung
against a ship's bow. Great walrus tusks of frozen breath dangle
from the beards and nostrils of miners in the immense open pit,
where the blink of an eye can bring blindness as eyelashes freeze
instantly to the lower lid, as if spot-welded.
</P>
<P>
   At these temperatures, even the swaggering drillers working on
the Koala and Misery ``pipes'' _ ancient funnel-shaped vertical
veins packed with kimberlite, the detritus of long-dead volcanos _
will allow that there is a real nip to the winds roaring down from
the High Arctic.
</P>
<P>
   But the digging goes on around the clock and in all weather at
North America's only diamond mine, barely a year old but already
producing more than $1.3 million a day in precious gems.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoth earth-moving machines, including trucks with 218 tons of
capacity, whose drivers perch three stories above the iced tundra,
rumble beneath the eerie flare of the aurora borealis _ the
northern lights _ while the flat crack of high explosives
reverbrates across a terrain so bleak and forbidding that the
Indians call it the Barren Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes 10,000 tons of rock to yield a ton of kimberlite
ore,'' said Serge Pelletier, a Quebec-born engineer and operations
overseer at the Ekati mine. ``And that ton of kimberlite will yield
just a single carat, on average.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of rubble to sift, scrub, and scan for the saucy
wink of gemstone to grace a neck, finger, or earlobe. But diamonds
are magic as much as they are stone _ the sparkling bits of
crystalline carbon possess the power of wealth and beauty. Or
avarice and vanity. The power, in any event, to compel humans to
brave one of the planet's most brutal environments.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most diamond mines, the Ekati's bounty is almost entirely
in diamonds of gem quality, not industrial diamonds, and nearly all
will wind up adorning women in North America, Europe, and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly among the richest diamond mines in the world,''
said Graham Nicholls, spokesman for BHP Diamonds Inc., operator of
the mine. ``Perhaps the richest.''
</P>
<P>
   Most diamonds come from Africa, and for the past 100 years the
industry has been inseparable from De Beers Consolidated Mines
Ltd., which produces 50 percent of the world's diamonds from its
mines in southern Africa. The firm also controls 70 percent of the
international supply of the raw gems through its sales cartel in
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's emergence as a major producer is shaking up the closed,
cozy world of big diamonds. By the end of the decade, some analysts
reckon, this nation may be the source of 12 percent of the world
supply.
</P>
<P>
   That's an extraordinary change, given that only a few years ago
Canada produced as many diamonds as it does coconuts _ none.
</P>
<P>
   Although a few geologists insisted the country's frigid outback
must contain deposits, De Beers and other major diamond mining
companies had for years scoured ``North of 60'' _ as inhabitants
refer to their hinterland above 60 degrees latitude _ without
hitting a glint of paydirt. The quest, always a long shot, came to
seem futile, even a little loopy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking about finding diamonds in Canada was like talking
about going to Mars,'' said Charles E. Fipke, a
geologist-prospector from British Columbia whose obsessive pursuit
of northern diamonds mostly drew hoots of derision in the rowdy
taverns of Yellowknife, the territorial capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought you were crazy, or pulling some kind of scam,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Long after the diamond heavies wrote off the north as a bad bet,
Fipke kept tracking elusive glacial trails across the barrens,
riding bush choppers and rubber rafts to the far corners of this
realm of caribou, ravenous wolves, and croaking ravens.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in November 1991, he dug up a micro-diamond near Point
Lake, Northwest Territories. The find triggered the biggest
prospecting stampede in Canada since the Klondike Gold Rush of the
1890s, as more than 72,000 square miles _ a territory the size of
New England _ were staked by mining outfits in a matter of months.
Dozens of possibly rich kimberlite pipes were located, most covered
by lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Fipke's exploratory company, Dia Met Mineral Ltd., joined with
BHP Diamonds, a subsidiary of Australian mining giant Broken Hill
Proprietary Co., to develop the Ekati site, located 120 miles south
of the Arctic Circle and 110 miles from the nearest human
habitation, the Dogrib Dene Indian hamlet of Wekweti.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Ekati is the only diamond mine up and running on this
continent. The project's huge indoor processing plant, the housing
complex for workers (flown into the site for two-week,
12-hour-a-day shifts), and machinery sheds are the largest
construction north of the Canadian treeline.
</P>
<P>
   Even more impressively, the Ekati has catapulted this country
into the major leagues of diamond mining, with more than $400
million in annual production, tying Australia as the fifth largest
producer of the glittery element by value, after Botswana, Russia,
South Africa, and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   ``From nowhere, the (territory) is already producing 6 percent
of the world's diamonds,'' said Martin Irving, director of diamond
projects for the territorial government. ``That's from a single
hole in the ground. It's a pretty exciting thing for Canada, and
for the diamond industry.''
</P>
<P>
   As BHP Diamonds scoops its fabulous bounty from the kimberlite
at a rate of more than 225,000 carats a month, competing diamond
interests are stamping impatiently in the wings. Diavik Diamond
Mines Inc. is ready to start a $1 billion excavation on an island
in Lac de Gras, just across the ice from the Ekati lode. The
discovery of the Diavik kimberlite pipes was made by Canadian
geologist Eira Thomas, one of only a handful of women to earn a big
reputation in the hairy-chested world of international mineral
prospecting.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the Diavik mine was supposed to begin last
month. Massive gear-hauling trucks were ready to head out on the
winter-ice road leading from Yellowknife, the only overland route
to the region, a trail of frozen rivers, lakes and tundra passable
only until late March.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists and native groups tossed a last-minute
monkey wrench into the project, claiming the mine could interfere
with the migration of caribou and might contaminate Lac de Gras,
which feeds the Coppermine River, source of drinking water for
several native hamlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens when 400,000 caribou meet 250 million tons of
waste rock? What will be the effect on water of the Coppermine
River?'' asked John Crump, head of the Canadian Arctic Resources
Committee, an environmental group based in Ottawa. ``The answer is,
`Nobody knows.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the company has held 300 public meetings, committed
itself to costly ecological safeguards that won approval from
Canada's Ministry of the Environment, and pledged to recruit 40
percent of the mine workforce from the aboriginal population of the
region. Roughly half the vast territory's 40,000 people are Dene
Indian, Eskimo, or mixed-race Metis.
</P>
<P>
   Diavik hopes to be producing diamonds by 2003. ``This could be a
big and crucial business for northern Canada,'' said spokesman Tom
Hoefor.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for Yellowknife, the discovery of diamonds seemed a
godsend, coming as the territory's traditional economic mainstays,
gold and government, were on the decline. The gold mines are
shutting down and public sector jobs have been slashed by Ottawa,
which administers the territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamonds could be the difference between boom or bust,'' said
David Lovell, mayor of Yellowknife, which is home to nearly half
the inhabitants of the territory. ``These gems are our future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Dene language, Ekati means ``fat lake,'' and refers to
the white granite outcroppings that Indians say resemble big scoops
of caribou fat, a symbol of wealth to people surviving in a lean
land.
</P>
<P>
   Territorial leaders seem generally enthusiastic about diamond
mining, which, properly done, is far cleaner than other forms of
mining, using few chemicals and producing waste that is essentially
just water-scrubbed gravel. But they also warn that mining
companies better be prepared to invest heavily in the territory's
isolated and impoverished native communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't see clear benefits for aboriginals, the diamonds
can stay in the ground,'' said Stephen Kakfwi, provincial premier
and a Dene, stressing that he supports mining development, but also
believes in moving cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ekati mine blazed the way,'' he said, ``and we've got good
relations. BHP is a class act. But some diamond mining people come
in with a redneck attitude, expecting us to roll over. We want to
develop mining, sure, but our most important dream is to develop a
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only jurisdiction in North America with diamonds,''
Kakfwi said. ``And our people are going to share in the wealth of
those stones.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
