<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PROTEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION PROTEST INCITED IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Fed up with what they maintain is a lack of choice in
the presidential election and biased media coverage, protesters
here are calling on Russians to vote for ``none of the above'' and
boycott Russia's two main television networks.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, on a square across the street from the stately
Bolshoi Theater in downtown Moscow, one group made that point with
a crash. Two men heaved a decades-old television into a statue of
Karl Marx. The picture tube exploded with a loud pop and
Mohawk-sporting punk-rockers and self-styled ``anarchists'' in
black ski masks violently kicked and stomped the mangled TV's
remains.
</P>
<P>
   With a presidential vote two weeks away and a victory for Acting
President Vladimir V. Putin a near certainty, some Russians have
said the election looks more like a coronation. According to this
small, but vocal, minority, Russia's fledgling democracy and
hard-won freedoms have been hijacked by Putin, a former KGB spy who
became acting president when Boris Yeltsin abruptly resigned on New
Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Fawning state-run television stations, politically connected
businessmen and a brutal war against separatist rebels in Chechnya,
they said, have aided Putin's drive to power. Calling the elections
a farce and fearing that civil liberties are in danger, some people
are taking to the streets in protest.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, scores of demonstrators, carrying signs with
slogans like ``Last Days of Freedom'' and ``Vote Against Everybody
or the Kremlin Will Steal Your Vote,'' applauded the TV smashing
heartily. As a rock band blared out guitar feedback, a young man
shouted, ``Down with the state, down with the war, down with
Putin'' into a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Stern police officers stood menacingly behind the protesters and
took notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is expected of us is not a vote but our participation in
our own execution,'' read a statement distributed by the protest's
organizers. ``The politicians are putting on a mere appearance of a
contest, knowing the results in advance. No matter how we vote they
will decide things their own way.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators encouraged Russians to either boycott the
elections or vote for ``none of the above'' _ an option in Russian
elections _ in the country's March 26 presidential poll. For the
election to be valid, 50 percent of eligible voters must cast
ballots. Likewise, should the number of votes for ``none of the
above'' exceed the leading candidate's total, the election would be
declared invalid and a new poll would be scheduled for four months
later.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the protesters called for boycotts of Russia's two
main state-owned television stations _ which they claimed
shamelessly promoted Putin _ and of companies that advertise on
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to be ashamed to participate in this farce they
are calling an election,'' said Boris Kagarlitsky, an author and
political activist who organized the protest.
</P>
<P>
   When the festivities were over, police briefly detained and
questioned Kagarlitsky.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's protest was organized by one of several groups
fighting the Putin juggernaut. The most prominent of these is the
so-called ``Nyet Campaign,'' headed by Moscow-based political
analyst Vladimir Pribylovsky and Sergei Grigoryants, head of the
Glasnost Defense Fund, a free-speech advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Pribylovsky said he is against an election boycott, which he
claimed would make it easier for the Kremlin to tamper with unused
ballots and falsify the results. Instead, he called on voters to
choose ``none of the above,'' which would allow democrats four
months to regroup and find a strong candidate to oppose Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Putin leading 12 presidential candidates with over 50
percent support. His closest competitor, Communist leader Gennady
Zyuganov, has about 20 percent. Liberal economist and lawmaker
Grigory Yavlinsky is running third with about seven percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most current opinion polls don't show figures for ``none of the
above.'' According to official results from past national
elections, three to five percent of the electorate have chosen that
option.
</P>
<P>
   Pribylovsky conceded that his campaign had little chance of
success, but said he nevertheless wanted to send a message to
Russia's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show the authorities that they don't have carte
blanche,'' said Pribylovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently they have gotten the message. Last week, Russia's
Electoral Commission announced that it was investigating the
legality of openly campaigning for ``none of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as most candidates used free television time to run
campaign advertisements, Putin said he would forego the privilege.
Putin _ who as acting president has enjoyed extensive and positive
news coverage _ said he disdained the idea of advertising himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
