<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5256 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r l BC-MONICA-LEWINSKY-WEIGH     03-13 1821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-LEWINSKY-WEIGHT-BATTLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`YOU DON'T HAVE TO LIKE ME ...' 
</HEADLINE>
   (FOR USE: Thursday, March 16, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: To purchase this ``separate-buy'' feature
article from Redbook magazine, please contact one of the following
New York Times Syndicate representatives:  
 &HT;    --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.) 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By DEBRA BIRNBAUM  
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``Hi, I'm Monica Lewinsky,'' she says, rising from a sofa to
greet me as I enter her suite in the luxurious Four Seasons Hotel
in Beverly Hills. As if any such introduction were necessary.
</P>
<P>
   She may be newly svelte _ having recently shed some 30 pounds _
but with that helmet of black hair, alabaster skin and
orthodontically perfect smile, she's still instantly recognizable
as the reluctant star of the tawdry Oval Office scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from her tete-a-tete with Barbara Walters last March and
her star turn on Kenneth Starr's witness stand, Lewinsky mostly
kept to herself in the months after the story of her affair with
Bill Clinton broke.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in late December, she announced that she'd struck a deal
to be the new spokeswoman for the weight-loss program Jenny Craig.
Though she won't reveal the financial details of her contract
(rumor has it she's getting paid $10,000 for every pound she
loses), she will be appearing in national TV commercials for the
diet company she credits with finally helping her get in shape.
</P>
<P>
   As part of this new public role, Lewinsky agreed to talk to me
about her lifelong battle with an unhealthy body image.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   In reading ``Monica's Story,'' which author (and Princess Diana
confidante) Andrew Morton wrote for her, on the flight to
California, I was struck by the extensive role Monica Lewinsky's
insecurity about her weight played in her disastrous liaison.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why she didn't dry clean the infamous blue dress, for
example, she recalled that Linda Tripp told her she looked fat in
it, so she left the dress in her closet. (Under the burden of that
insult, how many women wouldn't have done the same?)
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's comment struck a deep nerve, one that has plagued
Lewinsky throughout her 20-odd years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andrew noted in the book how when I was going through my
pictures with him, I marked everything by my weight: `Here I was 20
pounds heavier,' `Here I was 20 pounds thinner,''' she recalls.
``It was interesting to me that one of the constructs of how I view
my life is my weight. I found it disturbing _ and, of course, he
wouldn't change it, which annoyed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for her, it is also how the public came to view
her. Dubbed the ``portly pepperpot'' by the New York tabloids, her
public battle to protect her privacy became an equally public
struggle with the scale. For two years, reporters have gleefully
critiqued her wardrobe and chronicled every morsel that has crossed
her lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time it's not even true!'' she says, laughing.
``The joke among my friends is, whatever is the most fattening
thing ordered at the table is what I ate, and I probably also had
what everyone else ate, too! I saw Calista Flockhart at a
restaurant once, and I wanted to say to her, `We're the Laurel and
Hardy of the tabloids!'''
</P>
<P>
   So why, I ask, would she invite further attention by signing on
with jenny Craig?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I've found something that's helped me and might be
able to help others,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics may point to the financial rewards of the deal (which
indeed will go a long way toward paying her legal bills), but
Lewinsky also has a genuine desire to connect with other women
who've struggled with their weight. On her book-signing tour, she
says, countless women came up to her saying that they identified
with her pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``For other people to feel comfortable sharing with me was very
touching, because it's still difficult for me to be open about
that.''
 &UR; HOW SHE'S HEALING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's abundantly clear that she's been in therapy _ ``It's no
secret that I'm working on myself,'' she says. She talks repeatedly
of trying to find ``balance'' and defuse the ``compulsive control''
that food has held over her.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've started to see is that weight for me has been a
control issue, whatever my weight has been,'' she says. ``I have
very black-and-white feelings about food _ that something's good or
something's bad, or if I eat this I'm a bad person, if I eat that
I'm a good person. I'm trying to have a more forgiving attitude and
not be as militant with myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have issues that I'm working on and I'm not there yet,
but I'm aware of a lot more.'' Those issues, she says, are ones
she's been wrestling with since as early as second grade. ``There
are things I deal with in therapy now that have nothing to do with
anything that's happening to me now or in the past few years,'' she
says, ``but are all a result of things that happened in high school
or grade school. You think, that was 10 or 15 years ago, that's
ridiculous. But those are the formative years, when you're so open
to impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in image-conscious L.A., she says, also had a
tremendous impact on her, as did her parents' eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom has always been conscious of her weight,'' she says,
``and I watched her being controlled by that in different ways on
different diets. But even if you don't see it with your own mom,
you see it at your girlfriend's house with her parents. You just
can't escape it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents' separation _ and subsequent divorce, when she was
15 _ sparked an emotional trigger for her overeating, setting a
pattern of yo-yo dieting that would last into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my problems in the past was that I would either not get
to my goal because it was unrealistic, or I'd get there and,
because I'd struggled so hard, I'd stay there for five minutes,''
she says. ``I've probably gained and lost 20 people in my life!''
Now, she says, ``It's about keeping it off.''
</P>
<P>
   But her biggest hurdle, she says, is dismantling her
``all-or-nothing'' attitude. ``I think being able to go out and
know that it's OK to have a little bit of this or a little bit of
that stops me from saying `I blew it' and having 12 drinks or a
whole cake,'' she says. ``I'm working on managing depression, too,
so I need to be able to go out with my friends. If that means that
I have a drink, then I work that into my food budget.''
 &UR; THROUGH THICK AND THIN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does she think the press would have treated her differently if
she had been thin?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would have changed some of it,'' she says, with a
touch of regret. ``There were a lot of cruel things that people
said to me, and my weight handed them one more thing to be cruel to
me about. Especially in the beginning, when there was a lot of
uncertainty about what the relationship really was, my weight
played a negative role, because people would look at me and say,
`She's heavy _ why would anybody be interested in her?''
</P>
<P>
   She admits her search for love has been a bit, well, misguided.
(``That hasn't been undocumented!'' she laughs.) ``I fell prey to
someone I shouldn't have gotten involved with,'' she says quietly.
``But one of the positive things that came out of that was that
because I was with somebody who thought I was beautiful and sexy no
matter what size I was, I was able to discover that sexuality comes
from within. Even when I don't like to look at myself in the
mirror, my body has always felt good to me. But there's a catch-22
for me, because the person with whom I discovered my own sexuality
and sensuality was a bad emotional influence on me, and yet he gave
me this wonderful gift.''
</P>
<P>
   As she dabs at her tears, I can feel the pain of her heartbreak.
We've all made mistakes, I tell her; we've all done foolish things
in the name of love. ``Unfortunately,'' I joke, ``my friends have
long memories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just make sure none of them have tape recorders!'' she fires
back.
</P>
<P>
   I'm stunned at her ability to defuse the emotional moment with a
joke, especially one at her own expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously,'' she continues, ``I'm blessed to have some of the
most amazing friends in the world. I don't really consider Linda
(Tripp) a friend; I don't think she ever was.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if not for Tripp and her tape recorder, we might never
have known the name Monica Lewinsky. Whatever Lewinsky's admitted
lapses of judgment, she never intended to gain fame from her
entanglement with the president _ certainly not this kind of fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people forget I made the mistake of confiding in
someone privately,'' she says, ``but I went to pretty great lengths
legally to not have those conversations come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Her desire to reveal the truth was the reason she agreed to be
interviewed by Barbara Walters. But what she had to say was instead
dwarfed by what she was wearing _ namely, the lipstick whose sales
immediately skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I designed it or owned it, that'd be great.'' She pauses,
then adds, ``Who knows, maybe I'll do my own lipstick someday!''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, she's brought her business sense to the fashion
world, having launched last summer a line of handbags under the
name The Real Monica Inc., with sellout success. But, she says, ``I
really just want to find the right person and get married and have
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Eligible bachelors will now find this 26-year-old living in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the seasons and the diversity and that you just sort of
blend in,'' she explains. More than anything, it seems, she
desperately wishes that she might regain some semblance of a
normal, quiet life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some kooky decisions and had some kooky things happen
to me, but I'm a real person,'' she says. ``What's special about me
is that people know my name, but other than that, I'm just like
everybody else. You don't have to like me _ sometimes I don't like
me _ but at least judge me on the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does she think the history books will treat her?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think I will probably be just a footnote. My name may
not even be mentioned,'' she says, perhaps more optimistic than
realistic. ``What I'm hoping is that people come to judge me not
for how the story began, but for how it ends.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Debra Birnbaum is deputy editor of Redbook magazine.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
