<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5258 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX     03-13 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
WHAT'S THE FiRST AMENDMENT FOR? TO BOTHER PEOPLE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I fear that too often we take for granted the words of those
precious documents that guarantee our freedom: the Declaration of
Independence, the U.S. Constitution and the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   You don't believe me? Let me tell you a sad tale.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, a reporter in Madison, Wis., asked 112 people
to sign a petition that consisted exclusively of sections from the
Declaration of Independence and the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Only one person was willing to sign the petition.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty of those invited to sign asked the reporter if he was a
Communist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the hell out of here with that Communist stuff,'' said
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see you are using the old Commie trick, putting God's name
on a radical petition,'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, an attorney in Austin, Texas, introduced a
resolution at a precinct meeting that read:
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of
religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging
the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people
peaceably to assemble, and to petition the government for a redress
of grievance.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was quickly tabled as being too controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Would you have voted to table? I hope not, for those words make
up the First Amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, although I'm disappointed about such occurrences, I am
not all that surprised.
</P>
<P>
   For many years I have given talks on the press clause of the
First Amendment. Often these speeches were directed at gatherings
of journalists because many of them, I'm sad to say, did not have a
clear understanding of that clause.
</P>
<P>
   I think it appropriate to talk about these matters because next
Saturday, First Amendment devotees pause to mark the anniversary of
the birth of James Madison, the principal author of that amendment
and the rest of the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, some folks tried to make a First Amendment
case out of the punishment handed out by baseball commissioner Bert
Selig to Atlanta Braves relief pitcher John Rocker. (Selig fined
Rocker $20,000 and suspended him for spring practice and the first
30 days of the season.) The outspoken Rocker had stirred up a
ruckus because of some hateful and demeaning remarks he had made
during an interview for a magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   Some folks began to howl that Selig had violated Rocker's First
Amendment rights by trying to silence him.
</P>
<P>
   Bull.
</P>
<P>
   Selig was simply exercising his authority as baseball's head
man. (Later, an arbitrator drastically reduced the punishment to a
fine of $500 and a 14-day suspension.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, if an agent of the government had tried to silence Rocker,
that would have been a violation of the pitcher's First Amendment
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The press clause of the First Amendment is simple. It says that
the government cannot tell the owners of a newspaper or a broadcast
station what they can or cannot print or broadcast. (The Supreme
Court has established some exceptions, mainly in the area of
national defense, but such exceptions are few.)
</P>
<P>
   The press clause imposes no responsibilities on the news media.
Most of the standards and principles that the mainstream press
abide by today have been self-imposed. In approving the First
Amendment, Madison and the other Founding Fathers did not do so
with the expectation that the press would be fair, balanced or
objective.
</P>
<P>
   Their purpose was to make sure that the citizens of a new nation
would have a variety of viewpoints available to them without
government interference. The Founders knew that this was one of the
basic ingredients of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   They also knew they were providing protection for irresponsible
and objectionable publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some degree of abuse is inseparable from the proper use of
everything,'' Madison wrote. ``And in no instance is this more true
than that of the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has accordingly been decided by the practice of the States,
that it is better to leave a few of its noxious branches to their
luxuriant growth, than by pruning them away to injure the vigor of
those yielding the proper fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Today we are surrounded by such ``noxious branches.'' You find
them in the form of the sensational tabloids stacked near the
checkout counters in supermarkets; you find them in the form of
sleazy publications on magazine racks; you find them on late-night
cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Madison and his colleagues probably would be stunned at the
proliferation of the ``noxious branches.'' But he undoubtedly would
not deny them the protection of the First Amendment. For the
Founders realized that once the wall of protection is breached,
freedoms can be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   As Sir Thomas More _ or St. Thomas More, if you prefer _ once
said, ``I would give the devil the full protection under the law,
because the day it is denied to him, the next day it may be denied
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the price of liberty. It is a high price to pay, but pay
we must.
</P>
<P>
   We are frequently bothered by some of those ``noxious branches''
afforded the protection of the First Amendment. That, too, is the
price of liberty.
</P>
<P>
   When U.S. Supreme Court Justice Anthony Kennedy once heard an
attorney argue that people were bothered by members of a religious
cult handing out literature in an airport, he replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the First Amendment is for, to bother people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram and is the newspaper's professional in residence at
Texas Christian University's Journalism Department. He can be
contacted at precord(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
