<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5269 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MAPLE-SYRUP-PITCHERS-     03-13 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAPLE-SYRUP-PITCHERS-LIFEBEAT-ART-829&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR COLLECTORS, VINTAGE SYRUP PITCHERS ADD PANACHE TO PANCAKES
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (ART ADV: Color photos of
syrup pitchers are available in JPEG format by calling William
Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.)  (tlk)  Ellen M. Plante writes for
``Country Living.''
 &HT;    
 By ELLEN M. PLANTE 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   Homespun favorites such as pancakes, griddle cakes, hot cakes or
flapjacks are not so humble when they're smothered in maple syrup,
but until the mid-19th century, the earthenware or tin pitchers in
which this ambrosia was dispensed hardly did it justice.
</P>
<P>
   The Victorians, with their penchant for ornamentation and their
strict code of dining room etiquette, were the first to think about
this problem. They came up with silver-plate and pressed-glass
pitchers for formal breakfast tables and ironstone for more casual
repasts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, collectors benefit. Maple-syrup pitchers provide happy
hunting for aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   Ornamented, silver-plate pitchers, which first appeared on
Victorian tables during the late 1800s, were marvelous to behold.
Manufacturers such as Meriden Silver Plate Co. and Rogers, Smith
and Co. created syrup dispensers with embossed botanical designs,
matching plates or underliners and ornate lids.
</P>
<P>
   White ironstone, produced by firms such as Meakin Brothers &AMP; Co.
and Wooliscroft, was available with both unadorned and embossed
designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironstone syrup pitchers with embossed flower and fruit motifs
were quite common during the 19th century,'' said William Durham,
of Home Place Antiques, in Belvidere, Ill. Today, however, these
decorative examples have become scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``A syrup pitcher, or simply 'syrups' as some collectors call
them, with a basketweave design would truly be a rare find,''
Durham pointed out, adding that while embossed syrups were usually
fitted with pewter lids with thumb catches, it is not unusual for
plain ironstone examples to have slide-on lids made from tin.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1800s, the advent of pressed glass, milk glass,
etched glass and art glass manufactured by companies both in the
United States and abroad resulted in some striking and highly
collectible syrup pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful syrup pitchers help me envision the breakfast tables
of the past,'' said collector Kathleen Krause of Wisconsin. While
she owns numerous antique milk-glass and ironstone pieces, she is
especially drawn to crystal or clear-glass examples because they
often feature a patent date.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, a changing economy caused Victorian formality to be
abandoned, creating a need for everyday dishware. By the beginning
of the 20th century, syrups were being made from enamelware.
</P>
<P>
   American manufacturers churned out upright syrups with metal
lids in mottled or marbled patterns, while European firms often
decorated their syrups with floral, checked or striped designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``An incredible variety of colors and patterns were produced
early in the 1900s,'' said David Pikul, of the Chuctanunda Antique
Co. in Amsterdam, NY.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1930s through the 1950s, companies such as Hocking and
the Hazel Atlas Co. produced inexpensive colored-glass syrups.
</P>
<P>
   While so-called Depression-glass pieces sporting the familiar
colors of the era often came fitted with glass lids or hinged metal
lids with thumb mechanisms, clear-glass examples from the same
period sometimes featured Bakelite lids or tin lids with Bakelite
handles. Depression-glass syrups could also be accompanied by
matching saucers or underliners.
</P>
<P>
   Inexpensive plain crystal or clear-glass syrups have been
produced continuously since the 1930s. In the 1950s, chrome and
plastic began to replace the tin and Bakelite that had been used
earlier to make lids and handles.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the current market for these plastic-detailed
examples, Carol Levison, of Once Upon a Table, a vintage-tableware
business based in Pittsfield, Mass., pointed out, ``Yellow or
yellow-trimmed items are eagerly sought by collectors. Red, a
common color for early plastic housewares, runs a close second.''
</P>
<P>
   Stores specializing in vintage kitchenware make the best hunting
grounds for syrups. Victorian ironstone, pressed-glass and
silver-plate pieces tend to be valued according to rarity, size and
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Depression-glass syrups are easier to find than 19th-century
examples, owing to the sheer quantity produced. Examples with
colorful plastic lids and handles from the 1950s and '60s are also
abundant at flea markets and yard sales.
</P>
<P>
   Coming across a fine maple-syrup pitcher can bring joy to the
collector twice over. Not only will it look good on the shelf _ it
can still be used.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   PITCHER PRICES
</P>
<P>
   According to William Durham, of Home Place Antiques, embossed
ironstone syrup pitchers can usually be found in the $200 to $300
range, while a plain example sells for around $75. Collectors drawn
to Victorian glass and silver-plate syrups will find that prices
start at around $100.
</P>
<P>
   David Pikul of the Chuctanunda Antique Co. said that simple,
white enamelware pieces made in the United States fetch $40 to $60;
highly decorated syrups or ones with rare patterns can bring $350
or more.
</P>
<P>
   Common Depression-glass syrups sell in the $40 to $80 range,
while rare colors and patterns can cost more than $200. Clear-glass
syrups with chrome or colorful plastic lids can still be found for
$8 to $15.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
