<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFLEXOLOGY-LIFEBEAT-ART-1,277&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARING MY SOLES: AN EXPERIMENT WITH REFLOXOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (ART ADV: A photo of feet
painted with symbols for reflexology points is available in JPEG
format by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 (tlk)  Donna Bulseco writes for ``Country Living's Healthy
Living.''
 &HT;    
 By DONNA BULSECO 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   I have funny feet.
</P>
<P>
   They've amused my friends and family for many years. Even at
elegant dinner parties, I've been asked to take off my shoes for a
laugh. The laughter is always uproarious.
</P>
<P>
   What's funny are my ridiculously long second toes, ``a sign of
brilliance and creativity,'' I've been told. But that's no
consolation for the fact that I can't wear sandals without being
teased.
</P>
<P>
   So the idea of placing my feet in the hands of a total stranger
for an hour of reflexology was truly disquieting. But when a
lingering bout of the flu left me tired and aching a month after
the sniffles had passed, I was ready to try anything. A good friend
(and reflexology enthusiast) had sent me a gift certificate to
Angel Feet in New York City; she was sure that a session of
reflexology _ which holds that stimulating specific points on the
foot encourages corresponding areas in the body to heal _ would
return me to my perky old self. ``It's all the stress you're
under,'' she said. ``Your immune system can't function; reflexology
will wind you down completely so that your body can go into repair
mode.''
</P>
<P>
   The promise of deep relaxation, improved circulation and major
stress relief overpowered my self-consciousness. If the
reflexologist were a real professional, there should be no
snickering, right?
</P>
<P>
   Relaxing Step by Step
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most body treatments, reflexology doesn't require that
you disrobe. You take off your coat, shoes and socks and perhaps
roll up your pants to mid-calf. At Angel Feet, I sank into a cushy
chair as the reflexologist, Jessie Meegan, soaked my feet in warm
water, wrapped them in a heated towel and placed them on an
ottoman. Candles lit the cozy space and I listened to a tape
playing the soothing sounds of nature.
</P>
<P>
   During the first five minutes or so, the reflexologist will use
relaxation techniques to put you and your vulnerable feet at ease.
Meegan softly pressed the bottoms and then the tops of my feet; I
was floating. She cradled my heels in her palms and, supporting my
ankles, stretched my legs gently toward her. She rocked my feet
from side to side, then firmly rubbed my ankles and up and down my
calves. Next, she grasped my feet and pressed the center of the
ball of each _ the point said to correspond to the solar plexus _
with her thumbs, gently releasing the diaphragm, breathing's
command central. Then she sprayed my feet with peppermint and
rosemary essential oils.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solar plexus [located around the lower part of the
diaphragm] is referred to as the 'nerve switchboard' of the body,''
says Inge Dougans, author of ``Reflexology: A Practical
Introduction.'' ``It is the main storage area for stress. Applying
pressure to this reflex point will always bring about a feeling of
relaxation.'' Meegan applied steady pressure, and after a moment,
my whole body seemed to let out a satisfied sigh of relief
</P>
<P>
   Cradling one foot with both hands, Meegan used her thumb to
``walk'' over the entire sole. After repeating that several times,
she used her thumb to circle clockwise to the heel, then worked
back up to the toes. Like a magician wowing an audience with trick
after amazing trick, a skilled reflexologist segues smoothly from
one move to the next, twisting, stretching, rotating, wringing,
slapping and stroking the feet with feathery fingertips until
there's no resistance.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the session, Meegan asked me which areas of my
body might need attention, and during the warm-up, plotted a course
of pressure points on which to focus. During the treatment, she
watched my reactions and my breathing, pressing on the solar plexus
reflex point as I breathed out to achieve maximum tension release.
</P>
<P>
   A reflexologist can also tell if it hurts; if you wince, the
pressure may be too intense. (It's important to understand,
however, that a sore spot can be just that _ it doesn't necessarily
mean that there's tension in the corresponding area of the body.)
Meegan told me that I grimaced only once. I left Angel Feet walking
on air.
</P>
<P>
   Healing from the ground up
</P>
<P>
   Most practitioners don't make miraculous claims for reflexology,
but they do believe in its power to help in the healing process.
Kevin Kunz, a reflexologist for 25 years in New Mexico, posts a
bibliography of research studies on his Web site, the Reflexology
Research Project (www.reflexology-research.com). ``Not many MDs
understand reflexology and what it can do, but studies from China
and Denmark have demonstrated its beneficial effects,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Books such as Laura Norman and Thomas Cowan's ``Feet First: A
Guide to Foot Reflexology'' and Dwight Byers' ``Better Health with
Foot Reflexology'' allude to its ability to help in weight loss,
solve infertility problems and enhance athletic performance. Byers,
head of the International Institute of Reflexology in St.
Petersburg, Fla., tells how he found relief from asthma and hay
fever when his aunt, Eunice Ingham, practiced her theories on his
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Ingham, who died in 1974, has been called ``the mother of modern
reflexology'' because of her work in charting the feet in relation
to the zones of the body. ``But there's no instant or permanent
cure for a condition like asthma. Reflexology can't 'cure' it; it
can only alleviate the condition by building up the immune system
or helping a sufferer relax during an attack,'' says Byers.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the healing arts today, reflexology addresses more
than bodily aches and pains. ``When I work with people, it's on all
levels _ physical, mental, emotional and spiritual,'' says Laura
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Norman starts each session in her tranquil studio in New York
City by asking people to think about a specific, concrete goal.
Affirmations put a positive spin on the healing experience. For
example, Norman suggests that you might say, ``I breathe deeply and
fully from the diaphragm'' as a positive affirmation if you have
had asthma in the past. A simple ``I want to stay healthy this
year'' set the appropriate positive tone for me when I visited her
for a session.
</P>
<P>
   As I relaxed on a soft massage table, I looked up at a ceiling
painted with blue sky, fluffy clouds and cherubic feet. Norman
started the session by rubbing citrus-scented essential oils on my
feet and then moved on to reflex points that related to areas that
we agreed needed work.
</P>
<P>
   Again, I felt immense relief and a deep sense of relaxation when
she put pressure on the solar plexus reflex point. Surprisingly, I
also experienced a feeling that I can only describe as pure joy.
``When you go into a deep state of relaxation, you're more
receptive to change,'' says Norman.
</P>
<P>
   I did feel relaxed, more balanced and energized after my
reflexology sessions, and the lingering flu symptoms were
completely gone three days after my second visit. As an unexpected
bonus, I also feel better about my freakish feet. The big toe, I
learned, corresponds with the brain. Now my feet feel absolutely
brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   READING YOUR FEET
</P>
<P>
   Reflexology is based on the principle that feet are miniature
maps of the human form, with areas that correspond to every organ,
gland and body part. Reflexologist Laura Norman, who has written
two books on the discipline and trains others in it at her center
in New York City, identifies 10 energy zones, or meridians _ five
on each foot _ that run the length of the body from head to toe.
</P>
<P>
   Reflexologists claim that stimulating particular points on the
feet cause tension and stress in the corresponding areas of the
body to be released. ``There are over 7,200 nerve endings in each
foot that reach every part of your body,'' says reflexologist
Barbara Morrison. ``By stimulating these reflex points, you relax
tension and release toxins, improve blood circulation and balance
the whole body. And when your body is relaxed, it can heal
itself.''
</P>
<P>
