<SLUG> BC-MAPLE-SUGARING-LIFEBEAT-ART-1,048&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE MAPLE TRAIL, `MUD SEASON' PROVIDES SWEET MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text.  (ART ADV: Photos of maple
sugaring are available in JPEG format by calling William Gonzalez
at 212-499-3355.) 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Monica Michael Willis is travel, nature and environment editor
for ``Country Living.''
 &HT;    
 By MONICA MICHAEL WILLIS 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   Sugaring season is one of the finest, though most underrated,
times to visit New England. Lodging prices are discounted, and the
crowds that flock to the region during summer and fall have
thinned, making it easy to witness the first shades of spring in
peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Although the weather can be unpredictable _ the six-week cycle
of alternating thaws and freezes is affectionately referred to in
these parts as ``mud season'' _ it can also prove spectacular. The
air is crisp, the snow that dusts the fields begins to melt and the
skeletal maples, elms and birches sprout tentative buds. On the
region's back roads, anonymous outbuildings become bustling,
maple-producing sugar shacks. And, if you breathe deeply you can
detect the familiar scents of wood smoke and maple in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Determining the exact day or week when the maple syrup season
will commence can be difficult, so travelers with hopes of taking
to the woods to participate in the centuries-old ritual of sugaring
should be fairly flexible and keep a constant eye out for the
telltale weather patterns (freezing temperatures at night and
relatively balmy 40 degree-days) that get the sap moving and kick
off the season.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by the threat of slush or mud, my family made a
three-day visit to Vermont (ground zero for maple syrup) last March
to participate in sap collection and learn more about sugaring.
Bearing in mind that we might spend a lot of our time plodding
through snow and/or mud, we each packed several jackets of varying
weight and brought along sturdy insulated boots, which, as things
turned out, we took off only to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The Trapp Family Lodge, a 93-room hotel that has been operated
since 1950 by the Austrian family immortalized in Rodgers and
Hammerstein's ``The Sound of Music,'' served as our base camp.
Perched on a hillside in the ski town of Stowe, the 2,700-acre
resort has a traditional sugarhouse where a wood-fired evaporator
transforms hand-gathered sap into classic Vermont maple syrup.
</P>
<P>
   The wood-fired evaporator _ a machine that reduces the water in
maple sap and concentrates its sugars _ allows visitors to
experience what sugaring would have been like in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Although sap buckets hanging from maples are still a common
sight along country byways, many sugarers now transport the sap
from their trees to the sugarhouse via plastic tubing, a
time-saving invention that relies on gravity and vacuum pressure
instead of manpower. Using fuel oil instead of firewood is another
way sugarers save time and money _ and also forgo chopping the
cords of wood used to stoke the evaporator as it turns the sap to
thick, rich syrup.
</P>
<P>
   It's still possible to find independent farmers as well as inns
and hotels that continue to collect sap by hand, a time-honored
collection method that is slow in cadence and rich in history. For
kids and adults alike, these farms demonstrate how to gather sap
and make syrup, a skill most children might otherwise learn about
only in one of Laura Ingalls Wilder's memoirs. And while most
people mention Vermont or New England when they think of maple
syrup, the midwestern states Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin are among
America's top maple syrup producers.
</P>
<P>
   At the Trapp Family Lodge, sugarer Jonathan Pryor oversees a
crew of five as well as Jill and Massie, mares that pull a sleigh
specially designed for retrieving sap deep from the sugar bush
(which in Maple Country is any large stand of sugar maples).
Besides being more charming than a four-wheel-drive truck, the
workhorses leave less of a footprint on the forest floor and can
navigate between the trees with more ease than your average sport
utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   During sugar season, guests at the lodge (and anyone else who
might be in the area) are invited to take a horse-drawn sleigh ride
to the sugarhouse, where they can help collect sap from the 900 or
so trees that have been tapped. The maples on the property have
been tapped on and off for about 50 years. When done carefully, the
taps have little or no adverse effect on the trees.
</P>
<P>
   After collecting bucket upon bucket of the colorless sap from
the bush, we returned to the sugarhouse to start the evaporation
process. In keeping with its mission to re-create an authentic
19th-century mapling experience, the Trapp Family Lodge's
sugarhouse is not electrified, and the evaporator there is fueled
solely by firewood.
</P>
<P>
   A platform allows kids and adults to view the sap-boiling
process (maple syrup results just before the ``jelly' stage) and
observe Pryor as he tests batches of the sweet syrup for color,
density and flavor.
</P>
<P>
   If you need to refuel after a day in the field and it happens to
be Saturday, stop by the Trapp Family Lodge's sugarhouse for a
Sugar on Snow party. A throwback to the time when neighbors got
together at the end of the sugaring season to celebrate the
harvest, these parties traditionally feature sugar on snow (a
taffy-like maple candy made by pouring hot syrup over clean, fresh
snow), dill pickles and old-fashioned cake doughnuts. It may sound
odd, but the sour pickles and yeasty doughnuts complement the
intense sweetness of the maple taffy. And children can't seem to
get enough of the chewy candy.
</P>
<P>
   Only after a day spent in the sugar bush will you fully
understand the pride folks from states like Vermont, New York,
Maine, New Hampshire, Massachusetts and Connecticut take in their
maple syrup. Although sugar makers in Vermont are largely
self-regulated, they all subscribe to a grading system established
by the Vermont Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Fancy is light amber in color and delicate in flavor.
Grade A syrup comes in Medium and Dark Amber, with the darker
varieties being more robust and full-bodied. Usually harvested late
in the season, Vermont Grade B syrup is generally sold for
commercial use to bakers and candy makers and is the darkest, most
``mapley'' of all the syrups.
</P>
<P>
   As you might imagine, lugging and emptying several dozen metal
pails heavy with fresh sap helps put the premium price maple syrup
garners into perspective. Roughly 40 gallons of sap are required to
produce a single gallon of the aromatic, caramel-colored liquid,
which explains why a gallon jug of Grade A syrup typically costs 25
times more than a gallon of unleaded gas. After a weekend spent
sugaring, I now know it's worth every penny.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL SIDEBAR MATERIAL FOLLOWS
</P>
<P>
   MAPLE MADNESS
</P>
<P>
   Many inns and hotels have begun to recruit travelers during the
sugar season by offering them the chance to traipse through the
woods, collect sap and participate in making maple syrup. To find
out about vacation options in the top maple-producing states, call
the (1) Vermont Department of Agriculture, (802) 828-2416; (2) New
York Division of Tourism, (800) CALL-NYS; (3) Maine Office of
Tourism, (800) 533-9595. To contact the Trapp Family Lodge about
sugar-season rates, call (802) 253-8511 or (800) 826-7000.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a pancake breakfast or a citywide maple festival,
nearly every town in New England (and parts of the South and
Midwest, too) sponsors a maple-related event during the winter
thaw. One to consider:
</P>
<P>
   The 33rd annual Vermont Maple Festival will take place April 28
to 30 in Saint Albans. Pancake breakfasts and maple demonstrations
are scheduled, as are an antiques show, a maple cooking contest, a
parade, and a variety show; (802) 524-2444.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
