<HEADER>
A5272 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-Q&AMP;A-PARENTING-LIFEBEA     03-13 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Q&AMP;A-PARENTING-LIFEBEAT-1,000-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERT ADVICE ON A CHILD'S FIRST TWO YEARS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Carol Hagan is a contributing editor to ``Child'' and the mother
of two. &HT;    
 By CAROLYN HAGAN 
 c.2000 Child Magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   LIVING WITH A PEANUT ALLERGY
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 11-month-old broke out in hives after eating peanut butter
on bread. The doctor says we have to conclude he has a peanut
allergy and avoid anything with peanuts for the rest of his life.
Do you have any more advice?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. Before you come to that conclusion, have your son
formally tested for a peanut allergy, says Dr. Scott Sicherer,
assistant professor of pediatrics at Mt. Sinai School of Medicine
in New York City and a researcher at Mt. Sinai's Jaffe Food Allergy
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breaking out in hives is consistent with a peanut reaction,
but it's important to confirm that particular allergy through a
skin or blood test. That way, you rule out the possibility that the
hives were a reaction to another food or substance,'' he says. A
peanut allergy is worth confirming because it can be lifelong and
extremely inconvenient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peanuts can be hidden in sauces, or peanut oil can be used for
fried foods. There are a number of unexpected sources,'' Sicherer
adds. And some foods that don't expressly contain peanuts, such as
Asian food or many cookies and candies may still have trace amounts
if they were made with the same equipment used for
peanut-containing foods. As a result, accidentally consuming
peanuts is not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   If your child is allergic to peanuts, you may need to carry an
epinephrine injection to halt an allergic response. A mild reaction
can sometimes escalate and cause swelling of the throat or a
dangerous drop in blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   LEARNING GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Q. Now that my child can sit up, I try to play more games with
him. What are the best ones to enhance the cognitive skills of a
6-month-old?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are three games that are especially good for a baby
this age, says Alice Sterling Honig, professor emeritus of child
development at Syracuse University in Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The first activity, called ``aah-boom,'' goes like this: While
sitting face-to-face with your baby, lean forward (saying ``aah'')
and touch your forehead gently against his, with a joyful ``boom.''
This simple exercise will key into your son's ability to anticipate
the next event in a pattern, and he'll begin to lean forward to
meet you halfway.
</P>
<P>
   The second game, called ``turn-taking talk,'' encourages your
child's developing language ability. Again, sit face-to-face with
your baby and vocalize back and forth, mimicking the sounds he
makes. When you repeat your child's side of the conversation, he
feels listened to, plus he learns both the structure and emotional
power of conversational language.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you can play up your baby's interest in exploring his
world with the game ``What's my sound?'' Find a short picture book
of animals or create one by pasting photos onto separate pieces of
cardboard. Start with familiar animals your child has seen in the
yard or at a nearby farm. As you hold up each picture, teach your
child the sound the animal makes. Dogs, cats, birds and cows are
usually winners with babies.
</P>
<P>
   NIX THE NIGHT-LIGHT?
</P>
<P>
   Q. I heard of a study that says using a night-light is bad for a
baby's eyes. How am I supposed to change a diaper during the night?
Is a hall light OK?
</P>
<P>
   A. The research to which you're referring did find that sleeping
with a light on can hamper a child's eye development. Experts at
Children's Hospital of Philadelphia found that 35 percent of kids
who slept with a night-light on during the first two years of life,
and 55 percent of kids who slept with a lamp lit during this
period, were nearsighted in later childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eyes seem to need a period of total darkness to grow
properly. Without it, the cornea may become less curved, the lens
may change shape and eye length may be affected _ factors that
determine near- or farsightedness,'' says Dr. Graham Quinn, a
pediatric ophthalmologist and one of the study's authors.
</P>
<P>
   While total darkness seems to be the optimal sleeping
environment, it's fine to turn on a light whenever it's needed.
``Don't risk bumping into furniture or dropping a child just to
keep the room dark'' says Quinn. And of course, ``a medically
fragile child who needs continuous monitoring should have his room
lit, if necessary. His current medical needs take precedence.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, try to avoid a hall light during the first two years of
life; enough light from it would enter the room to have the same
negative effect on the eyes. But for older kids who have fears of
the dark, a hall light is OK. ``There's no evidence that a hall
light is problematic after the first two years,'' says Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING KIDS TO SHARE
</P>
<P>
   Q. When, and how, should I teach my child the importance of
sharing?
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't even try until she's about 2 years old, says Burton
White, a child development specialist in Newton, Mass. ``Urging
18-month-olds to share is like trying to turn away the tide with a
spoon. It's incompatible with their nature at that point,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   To learn to share, a child first must be able to process the
idea of sharing and be capable of some rationality. While these
abilities start to emerge around age 2, your child has a better
chance of success if you wait until 25 or 26 months of age. A child
with a closely spaced sibling will be slower to share at first,
since the daily vying for toys will likely make her more
territorial, says White. Ditto for kids in group-care situations.
</P>
<P>
   When organizing a play date, set it up so kids have a better
chance of learning to play together and ultimately to share, says
White. Meet on neutral territory, such as a playground; kids have a
harder time sharing on their own turf. Once there, divide some of
the toys before setting the kids down.
</P>
<P>
   Respect that a child's favorite toy is ``sacred'' and not to be
shared unless the owner offers it. When a child grabs a toy from
another, explain that when her pal is finished playing, she'll get
a turn. Turn-taking is best because it respects the idea that a
child isn't expected to interrupt her play the instant another
child horns in.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
