<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5277 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-US-MEXICO-HNS &LR;      03-13 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAYORS OF BORDER CITIES URGE COOPERATION TO EASE GROWING
PAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JEANNE RUSSELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Explosive growth along the U.S.-Mexico border
demands a radical approach to fixing health and environmental
problems, and ignoring the international boundary might be the
first step, representatives from border cities said.
</P>
<P>
   One approach, they suggested, would be to view sister cities
like Matamoros, Mexico, and Brownsville, Texas, both among the most
rapidly growing in their respective countries, as a single
mushrooming metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Free trade has meant fast-paced expansion along the border, and
cities on the Mexican side often balloon even more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A factory that offers 2,000 jobs and pays taxes can translate
into an immediate need for that many homes,'' Ignacio Mendoza
Hernandez, the director of health from Matamoros, said Sunday
during the first day of the International Consortium for the
Environment's ``Border Health: Making a Difference'' conference in
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The frantic pace of economic activity prevents the government
from providing electricity, water and sewerage to the shantytowns,
known as colonias, that spring up around the factories, Mendoza
said. Local governments must also deal with problems such as tire
dumping, substandard housing and contagious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The conference continues through Wednesday, with sessions on air
and water quality, funding opportunities, industrial growth,
emerging diseases and public health.
</P>
<P>
   Many participants attending the opening session agreed with
Ronald Kendall, the director of Texas Tech University's Institute
of Environmental and Human Health and the symposium's co-chairman,
who said the conference will succeed even if it only encourages new
relationships and partnerships between the participating government
and academic agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza called health problems a ``co-responsibility,'' saying
border cities can't deny the benefit of new jobs and taxes, nor
were environmental problems as serious as often painted.
</P>
<P>
   He was among many who described a region where poverty, low
academic achievement and contagious diseases coexist with economic
opportunity, biculturalism and a long life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   One in three people works for a maquiladora _ or foreign-owned
factory _ in Ciudad Acuna, the city across from Del Rio, Texas,
Mayor Eduardo Ramon said. Steady growth means not enough houses,
hospital beds and drinking water, he added. The sewage system of
Ciudad Acuna collapsed, Ramon said, showing slides in a
matter-of-fact plea for infrastructure to keep up with a population
explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Davila of the Benedictine Resource Center in San
Antonio challenged the benign portrayal of the maquiladoras in a
set of questions, then apologized for becoming emotional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the maquilas operating in your cities participate in
finding solutions?'' Davila first asked. After being told some
companies helped build baseball fields or fund scholarships, she
returned to the microphone to ask specifically if they were helping
fund a $38 million water treatment plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the main reason we're here, because they pollute, they
contaminate,'' Davila said. ``They should be the major players in
the clean up because they're the ones who have been dumping.''
</P>
<P>
   Her attack prompted an angry response from Fay Mainhart,
representing Delphi Automotive Systems, a company that supplies
auto parts.
</P>
<P>
   Her company recently received an award for its environmental
record in Mexico, Mainhart said, and in Laredo maquiladoras are
monitored by the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get very upset when I hear people slam dunk the industry,
because we are so highly regulated,'' Mainhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1224EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5282 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     03-13 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT MAKES FOR A GREAT PRESIDENT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Presidential candidates should ponder how much people, sometimes
unreasonably, expect of a president.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency may be at once the most honored and most
criticized office on earth. It is surely the most consequential and
the most nearly impossible to do justice. To Thomas Jefferson it
was a ``splendid misery'' and to Theodore Roosevelt a ``bully
pulpit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon B. Johnson said it made of everyone who occupied it,
``however small, bigger than he was, and, however big, not big
enough for its demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans have a tendency to nit-pick live presidents and to
venerate, even sanctify, our dead ones. Harry Truman is a prime
example.
</P>
<P>
   Truman's job ratings were abysmally low during his last couple
of years in office. Jokes abounded depicting our chief executive as
a lowbrow. Baylor University, after inviting the president to speak
at a commencement, uninvited him because he admittedly drank and
sometimes swore.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean War had grown increasingly unpopular. Truman's firing
of Gen. Douglas MacArthur brought a backlash. In 1952, many
Democratic candidates didn't want Truman's public endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a half-century later, we rarely hear anything but praise
for the blunt-spoken little warrior. The nation's historians, in
fact, are rating Truman fifth among all who've occupied our highest
office.
</P>
<P>
   Judged by American historians for the enduring legacies of his
leadership, Truman ranks ahead of all except Lincoln, Washington,
Jefferson and Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Modern presidents often begin pining and maneuvering about
midway in their second terms for a rung somewhere in the upper half
of history's ladder of greatness. Most know realistically that, if
they're to make it at all, recognition will come only after they
are dead.
</P>
<P>
   Historians judge presidents by the lasting effects of their
leadership on the country, and its lingering influence on how
people live and think today. By these criteria, Lincoln stands
ahead of all the rest, closely followed by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Those two differ widely in upbringing, style and personality.
Both had convictions. Each presided over historic choices. Each is
revered today.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln led the nation through the greatest threat ever to our
national survival, the Civil War. He saved the Union. He abolished
slavery. He preached reconciliation. Lincoln's words, as those of
no other American leader, are woven into the fabric of our
language. Ordinary people identify with him as with no other.
</P>
<P>
   Washington led the troops that won our independence. He
organized our first government in patterns that we follow today.
His ``Cabinet'' included some of the best brains of his time. And
he fathered the two-term tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Embedded in our national psyche are the images of Washington
praying in the snow at Valley Forge and 'fessing up to his father
after chopping down the cherry tree. Whether these things happened
or not, they are part of our legacy. After leaving office,
Washington once said he'd rather be dead than back in the
presidency suffering attacks in the press. Hardly anyone today is
aware that he was criticized.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson and Franklin D. Roosevelt are tied for third
and fourth places in the historians' pantheon of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt led us through the Great Depression and World War II,
the 20th century's two most cataclysmic events.
</P>
<P>
   Paralyzed by polio, he came to symbolize the nation's
indomitable spirit. He made my generation really believe that the
only thing we had to fear was fear itself. He was our only
three-term president, and he was elected to a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, probably our most intellectually gifted leader, was
our most uncompromising champion of individual liberty. To him,
more than any other, we owe the guarantees of free speech, press,
assembly and religion.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote the ringing affirmation of our Declaration of
Independence. His bold, unilateral decision to transact the
Louisiana Purchase doubled our national domain. He made what had
been a thin ribbon settlement along the Atlantic seaboard into a
continental power.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the three most historically consequential actions
undertaken by American presidents on their own recognizance were
Jefferson's Louisiana Purchase, Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation
and Truman's decision to drop the atom bomb. Some might add FDR's
embarking on Lend-Lease.
</P>
<P>
   Truman, like Lincoln, was of the people. He thought their
thoughts. He symbolized the honest directness of the common man. In
him there was no pretense.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed by lack of family wealth or college education, Truman
never hesitated to make the big decisions. ``The buck stops here,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Marshall Plan, the Berlin airlift, the Greek and Turkish aid
programs, standing up to aggression in Korea _ the whole panoply of
Truman's postwar leadership decisions stopped the aggressive spread
of communism. They shaped the world in which we live today.
</P>
<P>
   These were five men of different family backgrounds,
personalities, temperaments. They lived in different times, faced
different problems. Two were blessed with personal wealth; two came
from hardscrabble; Jefferson inherited an impressive plantation but
spent his energies on the country and died impoverished.
</P>
<P>
   What united them? Of what does greatness consist? In a sense,
their lives were defined by the problems they faced _ and
conquered.
</P>
<P>
   Each had the courage of his own convictions. Each had a
passionate love for this country. Each risked boldly. Each had a
vision.
</P>
<P>
   The graceful patina of time has polished their images, and
history's sandpaper smoothed their rougher corners. It would be
unfair to measure today's candidates against these icons.
</P>
<P>
   But not unfair to bear in mind that the office itself deserves
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1232EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
