<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDIES JUST CAN'T BE EXPLAINED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a recent Friday, a little girl _ this one just 5 years old _
was raped and left clutching her cleats in a sporting-goods store
bathroom in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy D. Moore, the 44-year-old ex-con she identified as her
assailant, went back to work after the alleged attack, like nothing
had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently he followed her into the bathroom, forced her into
a stall and sexually assaulted her,'' a police officer was quoted
as saying. ``This is a travesty. This is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words might describe the entire week in crime, but the
shooting death three days earlier of 6-year-old Kayla Rolland near
Flint, Mich., particularly comes to mind. While her first-grade
teacher and classmates watched, a 6-year-old boy pulled a gun and
shot Kayla in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, who lived with his uncle in a crack house, then put the
gun in a desk and walked away. Kayla was rushed to the hospital,
where she died less than an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't possibly recount in one column every news story I've
read in recent months about children fatally shot or sexually
abused by an adult who should know better. But every time I read
one, I feel as though I owe the child an apology.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea what I might say because, as often as they occur,
these tragedies are inexplicable to me.
</P>
<P>
   Just as inevitable are the questions parents raise about an
apparent lack of morals among youth.
</P>
<P>
   This makes no more sense, though, than the tragedies. I always
believed that children, for better or worse, mimic their parents.
The acorn doesn't fall far from the tree, as the saying goes.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, raising questions is healthy. Finding the
answers, though, requires honest soul-searching and a commitment to
turn from those things that cause us harm, that negatively impact
our children.
</P>
<P>
   If you wondered how a 6-year-old boy got a gun and shot his
classmate, the answer soon followed as news reports described the
conditions in which the boy lived. Crack house. Dad in jail. Mom
God knows where.
</P>
<P>
   And what can we make of Jimmy Moore? Ex-con. Convicted of
attempted rape and attempted kidnapping. You have to wonder if
Moore has a history of being sexually abused.
</P>
<P>
   Proverbs 22:6 says, ``Train a child in the way he should go and
when he is old he will not turn from it.'' I read an interesting
twist on that proverb recently in my study Bible and it went
something like this: ``Train a child in the way he should go _ and
go there yourself once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've got questions, if you were wondering how to have a
moral and lasting effect on your children, that in essence is the
sum of God's advice to us.
</P>
<P>
   It is up to us to accept it and apply it to our lives.
</P>
<P>
   That is the wonderful thing about Scripture. While some might
see it as outdated, the answer to every problem we might face in
this life can be found there.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you remember from the book of Deuteronomy: ``O Israel,
listen: Jehovah is our God, Jehovah alone. You must love him with
all your heart, soul and might. And you must think constantly about
these commandments I am giving you today. You must teach to your
children and talk about them when you are at home or out for a
walk; at bedtime and the first thing in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to passing on our faith is not lecturing our children or
giving them good books to read or taking them to church. The key is
making ourselves the example we want them to follow.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7400, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
