<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5294 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CONVERSE-SHOES-HNS &LR;      03-13 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVERSE-SHOES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONVERSE BANKS ON NEW HELIUM LINE TO PUMP UP SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By IHOSVANI RODRIGUEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are a part of American culture, the Harley-Davidson of
tennis shoes, a fashion icon for eccentrics and nonconformists.
</P>
<P>
   The distinguished Chuck Taylor star has adorned the ankles of
many an American boy and girl. And it seems to be mandated
somewhere that All-Star high-tops be worn beyond the fixative
powers of duct tape, then flung, in that end-of-summer ritual, up
on a telephone wire.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the legendary basketball star Chuck Taylor, Converse
Inc. had been able to hang on in a big-money business, consistently
making the top 10 list of the nation's best-selling athletic shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, market bullies named Nike and Adidas have been
taking Converse to school. As a result, the North Reading, Mass.,
company that for more than 80 years has made its mark by selling
the Great American Sneaker is fading. To reverse the slide,
Converse has placed its hopes on helium.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the company launched a new line of basketball
sneakers called All Star He:01. The shoes, which sell for $100,
have helium-filled heels. The product Converse's attempt to rise
above the noise of the high-tech sneaker race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always thought of Converse as a technical shoe
company,'' said Michelle Poole, the company's marketing director.
``We've decided to put all of our technology into one shoe, and
hopefully it would roll out from there. We're following a strategy
similar to what Nike did with their `Air' shoes years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to give the He:01 a push this month when it
releases a whole line of helium-filled shoes targeting
skateboarders. A second style for basketball players will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Converse's decline can be traced back five years. The company
has reported more than $135 million in losses over that period.
</P>
<P>
   Converse's stock value has remained so low that the manufacturer
is in danger of being taken off the New York Stock Exchange for not
meeting minimum standards.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, company officials say they are sticking to their
game plan of pushing the new technology and have little planned for
promoting Chuck Taylor All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Converse has pumped out different styles of the
trademark All-Star brand _ new colors, a Batman theme, camouflage _
to boost sales. Poole said she was not aware of any plans for a new
Chuck Taylor model this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Chuck Taylor All-Star shoes have become collectibles and may
become even more valuable if the company folds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years they've become big collector's items. I suspect
they'll become even bigger,'' said Buddy Sanchez, who sells used
sneakers through his San Antonio-based Web site
(www.secondstepsneakers.com).
</P>
<P>
   Orders for used Chuck Taylor All-Stars have come from as far as
Japan, Sanchez said. About 50 percent of his business from Asia and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about sneakers that have been around forever.
What article of clothing or brand can say that?'' Sanchez said. ``I
would lump it there with apple pie and baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sneaker industry analysts say another reason there continues to
be a market for All-Stars is consumer confusion over the abundance
of flashy, high-performance shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything it's a back-to-basics thing. People are
getting turned off or even scared off by all the contraptions and
designs,'' said Fred Foley, a sporting goods industry analyst with
New York-based Mazurek and Dullnig Partners. ``With Chuck Taylors
you get a basic sneaker.''
</P>
<P>
   But most consumers of Chuck Taylor shoes are adults, perhaps
feeling nostalgic for their youth. The industry as a whole,
however, has headed in a direction aimed mostly at teens.
</P>
<P>
   But as many companies have discovered, teens aren't choosing
sneakers as much as they once did. The National Sporting Goods
Association reported that basketball shoe sales in the United
States totaled $999.5 million last year, plunging to the 1995
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read about all these kids being out of shape and not being
active, and you have to figure they're not out there buying
shoes,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not buying Air Jordans, they're certainy not
buying Chuck Taylors.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though Americans have been buying and wearing Chuck Taylor
All-Stars for more than 80 years (60 percent of all Americans own
or have owned at least one pair), most people don't know who Chuck
Taylor was.
</P>
<P>
   In 1908, the popularity of basketball was on the rise, and a
company called Converse Rubber Corp. opened with the objective of
manufacturing shoes for athletes, particularly basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   After some research, the first version of the All-Star
basketball shoe was produced in 1917. The rubber-soled shoes were
made of canvas and reached the ankles. Like the Model T, they came
only in black. It was the first mass-produced sneaker in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   Yet sales didn't catch on. In fact, many basketball players
didn't even like the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   All except one, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck H. Taylor was a high school basketball star in his
hometown of Columbus, Ind. After finishing high school, Taylor
played professionally, before the organization of leagues as we
know them, with teams in Fort Wayne, Ind., and Detroit. He also
barnstormed around the country with the original Celtics and played
for the Buffalo Germans and Akron Firestones.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, he wore All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   This was long before the days of the million-dollar contract, so
while in Chicago one morning, Taylor decided to visit the Converse
sales office to apply for a job.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year after being hired, Taylor's personal input led to
a slight restyling of the All-Star, making the sneaker more
suitable for playing basketball. Two years later, in 1923, Taylor's
signature was added to the All-Star ankle patch in recognition of
his contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor later served in both the Navy and the Air Force during
World War II as a consultant on physical fitness and as the coach
of the Air Force basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Taylor made his earnings on the road, driving to
towns all over the United States to conduct clinics and sell shoes.
Soon, almost every basketball coach in America knew the traveling
salesman who did as much for the promotion of the sport of
basketball as he did for the shoes he peddled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968 Taylor retired. He was inducted into the Basketball Hall
of Fame a year later. He died that same year at age 68.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1246EST &QL; 
