<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5297 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-13 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHO WANTS TO CURE A MILLIONAIRE? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pity the families of the Silicon Valley,
suffering from a horrible new disease called Sudden Wealth
Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Before you roll a crisp hundred into a green ribbon and pin it
on your lapel, rest assured that the disease is treatable.
</P>
<P>
   Much the way many alcoholics treat their alcoholism with more
alcohol, the disease of Sudden Wealth Syndrome is being treated
with its cause: overdoses of money.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists, counselors and philanthropic investment experts
are making sudden silicon wealth their own, giving parents and kids
guidance on how they can survive the epidemic of ``affluenza.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago the Bay Area's army of counselors had to scrape for
money amid the wreckage of marriages and recovered memories of
sexual abuse. Now they can mine money at the source, from families
damaged by dot-coms, IPOs and stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Freud made his fortune and fame treating rich people, but he
couldn't just flat out say Anna O.'s problem was that she was rich.
Conversion hysteria, that was the problem, caused by unresolved
childhood sexual conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays Silicon Valley kids have unresolved investment
conflicts _ buy or sell, take the stock options or the cash?
</P>
<P>
   Their parents, afflicted with the grim liberalism typical of
Palo Alto, want their kids to grow up with social consciences at
the top of the social ladder. Thus the parents are caught between
two impulses.
</P>
<P>
   First, they lobby the schools to abolish recess so kids can
spend more time in class in order to get into Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Then they take the kids to group therapy sessions to hug and
talk about how when they were young the only start-up they ever
heard of was starting up the lawn mower to make some extra cash.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to teach the kids about the responsibilities of
being silicon Rockefellers.
</P>
<P>
   The basic symptoms of Sudden Wealth Syndrome in children are the
following:
</P>
<P>
   _ Arguments in the cafeteria about MarketWatch.com versus
TheStreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Posters of Bill Gates on bedroom walls instead of Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting lost trying to find the bedroom because the parents
built the monstrous house right out to the lot lines.
</P>
<P>
   _ Playing with Ann Winblad dolls instead of Barbie dolls. (If
you don't know who Ann Winblad is, your family is in no danger from
Sudden Wealth Syndrome.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Engaging in start-up-related activities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hiding Fortune magazines inside textbooks during class.
</P>
<P>
   _ After schoolyard fights, the cry, ``You'll hear from my
attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Teachers bribed with Apples.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vested by 7th grade, retired by 12th.
</P>
<P>
   The disease of Sudden Wealth Syndrome can be treated by the
intensive counseling mentioned above or, less effectively, by
self-esteem reduction classes in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter, a teacher explains the history of the South Sea
Bubble and the Great Depression, while telling the kids that
dot-coms are a giant Ponzi scheme that soon will come crashing down
like those avalanches they see in Gstaad.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, by the end of the class, the teacher is usually
shouting that the kids didn't earn those Lexuses in the parking
lot, and Neons get better mileage anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The kids leave class paging their venture capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow I don't think Jerry Lewis will be hosting a telethon for
Sudden Wealth Syndrome. In the Silicon Valley and the rest of the
Bay Area, you'll find more sympathy for those suffering from Sudden
Dearth Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   That's most of us, people who once proudly called ourselves
middle class. Now we're among the 73 percent of Bay Area residents
who can't afford to buy a home at the median price of $365,000.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, we have a dearth of places to live, and a dearth of
dining experiences beyond having it Burger King's way. Our children
suffer socially in school because they're on the other side of the
Nasdaq divide.
</P>
<P>
   Perpetual Poverty Syndrome has always been with us, by
definition. It's the worst, of course. Psychologists don't even
bother treating Perpetual Poverty Syndrome because it doesn't pay
and, well, it's so perpetual.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, no one I know would think of seeing a psychologist for
the disease of having too little money. You'd end up with even less
of it.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem with Sudden Wealth Syndrome is that it isn't
communicable enough. Spreading it around would solve a lot of
people's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Do I want to cure a multimillionaire? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   Where's that dusty degree in psychology? Let me relieve you of
some of your burdens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
