<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING FROM THE `REAL' PEOPLE AT LAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ The town hall meeting will never replace the
television commercial as the main weapon of the modern presidential
campaign, and that's too bad.
</P>
<P>
   Issues and presidential qualifications aside, John McCain made a
commendable contribution to this year's White House race if for no
other reason than he invited thousands of people _ from all walks
of life and political persuasions _ to come ask him questions.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, McCain's town hall meetings were partly campaign gimmicks.
But the questioners were not screened, and the events were a
refreshing source of candidate-voter contact in an age when that
has all but disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings also were highly effective in New Hampshire, where
the senator from Arizona held 114 of them en route to a surprise
thumping of Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   They alone weren't responsible for McCain's victory in the
first-in-the-nation primary. Thousands of independent voters and a
poor Bush campaign effort also were instrumental. But New Hampshire
was small enough for the personal contact between voter and
candidate at which McCain excelled.
</P>
<P>
   Town hall meetings were fewer and less of a factor in the larger
states, where wholesale campaigning in the form of television ads
and endorsements mostly replaced the more-intimate retail
politicking. The increasing frequency of primaries also made the
change in campaign style inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his race, which ended last week in a string of
key Super Tuesday losses, McCain's use of the town hall meeting had
become, one aide admitted, mainly ``emblematic,'' a symbol of the
senator's anti-establishment campaign. But the day before his
surprise victory in the Michigan primary last month, a town hall
meeting that McCain hosted in Traverse City had all the markings of
the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate spent more than an hour delivering his stump
speech and answering more than two dozen questions from about 1,000
people, many of whom had traveled a number of miles to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the apparent Republican nominee, also has sometimes hosted
his version of the town hall meeting. But most of what will pass
for candidate-voter ``contact'' during the remainder of the
presidential campaign will be well-scripted events.
</P>
<P>
   There will be rallies and chamber of commerce dinners with
canned stump speeches, tours of schools and high tech plants and
other photo opportunities designed to rally support by getting a
candidate shown on television, purportedly interacting with voters.
The actual interaction, however, will be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the questions posed to McCain at his town hall meetings,
admittedly, were repetitive and predictable. His views on
education, Social Security, veterans' benefits, abortion and
international affairs were repeatedly solicited, giving him
numerous opportunities to deliver well-rehearsed answers that
expanded on his basic campaign pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But, often, people asked questions about issues, such as health
care and environmental protection, that obviously are important to
many Americans but weren't getting a lot of attention in the
Republican presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also occasionally encountered protesters or hecklers,
trying to confront the senator on controversial issues, such as
Native American affairs in Arizona or the legalization of marijuana
for medicinal purposes, over which they and McCain disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   And McCain was not above turning a question on health care, say,
into a mini-filibuster on campaign finance reform _ his cornerstone
issue _ or dodging an answer entirely.
</P>
<P>
   At a town hall meeting in South Carolina, for example, he
refused to say what he thought about that state flying the
Confederate flag over its statehouse. The flag was a local issue to
be decided by South Carolinians, he said, repeating his and Bush's
standard response to that particular hot button.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is all an exercise in nostalgia over a bygone era.
But town hall meetings can be informative, and they can be
entertaining, and there is certainly nothing wrong with either
quality in a presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps most important, they afford a candidate for the
White House an opportunity _ in an age dominated by media-image
packaging _ to hear from ``real'' people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
