<HEADLINE>
FUNDS TRY TO INDEX HIGH-TECH NASDAQ 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NASDAQ composite index closed above 5,000 last week,
reaching that milestone just 10 weeks after hitting the 4,000 mark
and four months after surpassing 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid ascent of the index, which tracks all the stocks
trading on the electronic Nasdaq stock market, should have devout
index investors wondering how they can get in on the action.
</P>
<P>
   And who wouldn't want to?
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Qualcomm and Cisco Systems trade on the National
Association of Security Dealers Automatic Quotation System. These
are the big dogs of the ``new economy,'' the buzz phrase for the
faster way workers make, sell and buy products and services because
of the technology explosion that created the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Run with them and you will make money, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the safe bet for stock investing has been buying an
index fund based on the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
<P>
   Index funds use computers to buy and hold shares in the same
companies, in the same proportions, as those in the benchmark
measures of the stock market's performance.
</P>
<P>
   By buying an index, you can't beat the market, but you also
can't do worse than the market, either.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known index is the Dow Jones industrial average. It's a
price-weighted average that totals the stock prices of 30 of the
country's largest companies and divides by value that adjusts for
stock splits and dividends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`OLD ECONOMY' A DRAG ON S&AMP;P &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's obvious limitations in a universe of more than 8,000
publicly traded stocks led to the ascendancy of the S&AMP;P 500 as the
market standard.
</P>
<P>
   It tracks the most actively traded stocks on the Nasdaq, the New
York Stock Exchange and the American Stock Exchange and comprises
the stocks of 400 industrial, 40 utility, 40 financial and 20
transportation companies.
</P>
<P>
   But ``old economy'' sectors have been a drag on the index as
investors suck money out of Proctor &AMP; Gamble and other blue chips
to funnel it into just about any and every dot-com company that
goes public.
</P>
<P>
   From the first of the year, the S&AMP;P 500 is down about 4 percent,
while the Nasdaq is up more than 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity grows when the indexes' returns are compared to
levels of a year ago. The S&AMP;P 500 is up nearly 10 percent since
March 1999; the Nasdaq is up 110 percent for that period.
</P>
<P>
   It's a gap so large that many of you are thinking you should
sell your Vanguard Index 500 fund right now and put the cash on the
Nasdaq. However, don't call your fund family or discount broker
just yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WAYS TO GET IN THE GAME &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As of now, there isn't a no-load fund that will let you invest
in the entire Nasdaq index.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq has so many small, over-the-counter issues it would
be cumbersome for an index fund to manage the buying and holding of
all of them in their proper proportions. Plus, the tech-heavy index
can be so volatile that fund companies avoid it because most index
investors want no-frills, low-cost dependable return.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, other ways to get in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq 100 tracks the largest 100 non-financial stocks in
the composite. Technology stocks make up about three-fourths of
this index, and about half of its total dollar value comes from the
top 10 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Rydex OTC is the oldest Nasdaq-100 index fund and is monitored
by Morningstar, the mutual fund rating company in Chicago. Ranson
Nasdaq-100 Index Fund was started in December by Ranson &AMP;
Associates, a fund company in Wichita, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Another route is to buy QQQ (the ticker symbol for the Nasdaq
100 Share) on the American Stock Exchange. The Amex lists about 30
of these index-linked securities.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Q'' allows investors to buy and sell the index throughout
the day, rather than take a buy-and-hold approach with an index
fund. It reached a new high price of $230 Thursday and closed the
week at $229.
</P>
<P>
   Total return on the stock for the year to date is 20.84 percent,
compared with the Nasdaq 100 index's return of 21.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you're dreaming of getting rich, I want to caution you
to concentrate on not going broke. If technology companies don't
produce healthy earnings in the not-so-distant future and the
sector tanks, people solely invested in Nasdaq will lose big time.
</P>
<P>
   Keep some cash in lukewarm indexes. They may keep you from
getting burned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
