<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, PRACTICE WHAT YOU PREACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problem with asking to be forgiven for unspecified sins, as
Cardinal Bernard Law must know, is that the devil is in the
details.
</P>
<P>
   A schoolgirl comes in from recess in tears because the boys
refused to let her join their soccer game. If the teacher accepts a
reflexive apology, how will the boys learn that their sin was not
as simple as making someone cry, but as odious as excluding someone
because of gender?
</P>
<P>
   A teenager spray-paints swastikas on gravestones in a Jewish
cemetery. If police treat it as vandalism, how will the offender
learn the difference between a prank and a hate crime?
</P>
<P>
   A prince of the Catholic Church seeks forgiveness for acts of
racism, sexism, and anti-Semitism by Catholics in Boston. If he
does not cite particulars, how will victims know that a lesson
really has been learned?
</P>
<P>
   On this first weekend of the penitential season of Lent,
Cardinal Law is asking those who have been hurt by the prejudice of
Catholics to accept on faith that he hears their cry, that he
understands their pain.
</P>
<P>
   He apologizes not for the Catholic Church, which he asks us to
believe is without sin, the Crusades and the Inquisition
notwithstanding. He asks forgiveness, instead, for the sins of
individual Catholics against blacks, Jews, women, and those who
subscribe to other religious beliefs. That distinction requires
some mental gymnastics. Where, after all, did individual Catholics
learn disrespect for other religions if not from the church that
taught them they would be struck dumb, if not dead, if they set
foot inside a Protestant sanctuary? Where did they learn
anti-Semitism if not from the church that taught them that Jews
killed Christ?
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping, yet vague, nature of the cardinal's mea culpa
stands in stark contrast to the specificity of the grievances
nursed for generations by Boston's Catholics. It's a familiar
litany, the repetition of which has given shape and meaning to
Catholic history in Boston: the No Irish Need Apply signs, the
burning of the Ursuline Convent in Charlestown, the forced recital
of Protestant prayers in public schools, the long refusal of Boston
City Hospital to allow priests to visit their sick, the
Know-Nothing Legislature's Nunnery Committee and its bogus
investigation of Catholic convents.
</P>
<P>
   It is the flip side of that Catholic experience for which
Cardinal Law now seeks absolution. Catholics, history makes clear,
gave as good as they got. Like Cardinal Law, his predecessors on
Lake Street condemned anti-Semitism and racism in general, but
about the particulars they were less vocal.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, Mayor James Michael Curley once declared, was the
``strongest Coughlin city in America'' during the Great Depression.
Father Charles Coughlin was the Michigan priest who railed over the
radio every Sunday against a conspiracy of Jewish bankers that he
claimed was responsible for our economic collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal William O'Connell had no use for Coughlin's virulent
views, but he did not prohibit followers from selling his
hate-filled rag on the steps of Catholic churches after Mass.
Neither did he rein in Catholic schoolboys who, during the same
era, terrorized Jews on Blue Hill Avenue _ more popularly known in
Catholic neighborhoods as ``Jew Hill Avenue.''
</P>
<P>
   When Frances Sweeney, the crusading liberal Catholic editor of
the Boston City Reporter, chastised O'Connell for his failure to
stop the attacks on Jews, he summoned her, not to make common cause
but to try to silence her.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Boston had a home-grown version of Coughlin in
Father Leonard Feeney, a Jesuit who took to a soapboax on Boston
Common every Sunday to warn non-Catholics that the Kingdom of
Heaven was open only to members of the One True Church. Cardinal
Richard Cushing liked Feeney no better than Cardinal O'Connell
liked Coughlin, but he, too, kept publicly silent about a fanatic.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, when Boston erupted in violence in response to
school desegregation, Cardinal Humberto Medeiros asked his flock to
obey the law and to forswear racism. Then, he watched his directive
thwarted as Catholics seeking refuge from busing enrolled in those
parochial schools willing to wink.
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness, as the Cardinal knows, requires contrition. The
first test comes next week. Gay Catholics should expect to be
embraced at the St. Patrick's Day parade by fellow marchers,
freshly penitent for their past sins of prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
