<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5311 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-NORTH-BOS &LR;      03-13 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NORTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAMATIC ALASKAN FRONTIER IS BACKDROP FOR SUSPENSEFUL TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
TRUE NORTH 
By Kimberly Kafka 
Dutton, 273 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, springtime in Alaska _ when daylight returns, grizzlies and
mosquitoes wander in search of flesh and blood, and young men's
thoughts turn to panning for gold.
</P>
<P>
   In Kimberly Kafka's riveting first novel, ``True North,'' the
Alaskan frontier is blinding beauty and unforgiving beast. Unlike
Franz (her first cousin twice removed), this Kafka has a penchant
for straightforwardness. She reflects on human nature, Mother
Nature, and current issues such as native rights and eco-tourism
while drawing readers into the world of Ingalik Village, population
125, four hours by air from Anchorage and a third of a world away
from the other United States. In this icy frontier, float planes,
ATVs, and motorboats serve as steeds while white folks and Ingaliks
are cowboys and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The author, who divides her time between Alaska and Wisconsin,
knows the 49th state's terrain and its people. So it's
disappointing that the characters, though not without depth,
nonetheless fall victim to cliche. However, there's enough
adventure and tension here to minimize the damage. If the setting
were a little warmer, ``True North'' would be a perfect beach book.
</P>
<P>
   There's protagonist Bailey, 35, a self-reliant Maine native who
escapes a painful past by buying a rustic camp 80 miles from
Ingalik. ``To her, people were like the proverbial albatross; if
she could control the amount of contact she had, life was
bearable.'' No one expects her to survive the first winter, but she
does.
</P>
<P>
   Kash, 48, is the US ambassador, so to speak, a
Dartmouth-educated Ingalik, ``pro-native but a realist,'' who heads
up one of the regional corporations established by Congress in the
'70s to deal with land disputes. He's also the Yukon's most
eligible bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of Kash's first eco-tourists in disguise
(they've really come to pan for gold), he and Bailey become
involved in helping the New Englanders set up camp while keeping at
bay the redneck locals who hate the idea of hosting foreigners in
their wild. Already there was chemistry between Bailey and Kash, so
the reader knows what's in store. Nevertheless, the passion seems
so uncontrived that the romance is a thrill.
</P>
<P>
   The real action starts when Bailey flies her red Cessna to Lake
Hood in Anchorage (``busiest float plane base in the world'') to
pick up Zach and Alpha. The hapless couple brings too much gear to
fit in the small plane, and Bailey later gets roped into delivering
the excess stuff to them at a lodge 5 miles from her cabin.
Meanwhile, human trouble brews in the village and grizzly trouble
waits in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Zach, 25, and his mousy girlfriend is
humorous and dark in a ``Thelma &AMP; Louise'' sort of way. Zach is the
one who cooks up the get-rich-quick scheme without comprehending
the many forces (not to mention the law) that would be against
them. Alpha eventually toughens up in reaction to her cocky,
chauvinist boyfriend, and in part thanks to Bailey's literal and
figurative compass. (A subplot involving Bailey's deceased sister
and her possible relation to Alpha is unbelievable and unnecessary.
Kafka should have saved it for another novel.)
</P>
<P>
   What really drives ``True North'' and gives it substance is the
almost constant suspense, whether between man and woman, bear and
human, gold panner and river, or native and white person. Even if
the characters move in predictable directions, there's always the
background of Alaska itself _ remote, grand, and dramatic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
