<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTLESS ON LAURELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fantasy: One day you'll make so much money you won't have to
work.
</P>
<P>
   The reality: You'll probably work, even with the pile.
</P>
<P>
   When Jeremy Weiner, 24, sold his first company for over $1
million last fall, he could have done anything _ traveled, partied,
tried to read Proust on the beach, or just sat. What he did was
start his second company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat for a day and made no phone calls,'' he says of his
flirtation with leisure. Then he got busy with Schooljam, begun two
months ago in a cramped, no-frills Brighton office suite with a
fellow 1997 Babson graduate, Mike Gleeson. The company, scheduled
for launch in May, will allow consumers to stipulate that a
percentage of what they spend at participating merchants go to a
designated school.
</P>
<P>
   Weiner's first company, Cover-It, provided book covers free to
schools nationwide _ his profit came from companies advertising on
the covers. He was doing $3 million in sales when he sold the
operation to a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   One of his professors advised him to relax after the sale and
``go play pinball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first five quarters,'' Weiner says, ``I called him
and said, `This is really boring.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Hoffstein took the summer off 10 years ago after selling
MicroAmerica Inc., his computer products distribution company in
Marlborough, Mass. He took 18 months off in 1996 after selling his
second successful venture, PC Compleat Inc., a mail-order personal
computer business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' he says of both breaks. ``I read. I played
golf. I played basketball with my boys and spent more time with my
wife. We went to a dude ranch. We went to Steamboat Springs.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses in his rapid-fire delivery and asks, ``But you know
what made it so great? I knew it would end.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, at age 46, not having to work ever again,
Hoffstein looked around for a start-up to run, and found it in Be
Free Inc., an Internet marketing services provider for online
merchants. The company was formed by brothers Sam and Tom Gerace in
1996. Hoffstein was hired as president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job was to take the foundation and build the house,'' says
the entrepreneur, who had interviewed with 35 companies before
joining Be Free. He was seeking not only a challenge, but a job no
farther than five miles from his Southborough home so that he could
spend more time with his family. He wanted a start-up because he
likes the excitement of ``being on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the small team,'' he says. ``I like it when people on
the outside say, `You'll never do that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Metcalfe _ inventor of Ethernet, the networking magic that
links computers, and founder of 3Com Corp. _ understands. But his
mantra is: Inventor reinvent thyself.
</P>
<P>
   When he left 3Com at age 44 in 1990, he set about not doing what
came naturally. He spent a year as a visiting fellow at the
University of Cambridge, England, and then went into publishing,
becoming a columnist for Info-World magazine and a director and
vice president of technology for International Data Group in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalism is dominated by young Luddite Marxists,'' he says.
``It needs an old right-wing engineer. At least one.''
</P>
<P>
   At 53, he is the not-so-old man on the-mountain, the often
contrarian philosopher and self-proclaimed ``technology pundit''
who is working on a book, lecturing, organizing conferences, and
inviting people to ``salons'' in his Beacon Street town house. He
is also spending more time with his two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it's all about,'' says Bruce Male, 58, holding a
photo of him and his 22-year-old son seated in a racing car with
their arms around each other. Male is the founder of TravCorps
Inc., a national nursing placement service in Malden, Mass. After
selling it, he was able to indulge his passion for racing antique
cars. The family grew closer enjoying the hobby together, he said.
Their trips to races in Italy led to the founding of American
International Bakeries in Parma _ because the country didn't have
bagels. Male says being financially independent has allowed him to
put more time in on corporate and charitable boards _ ``give
back,'' he calls it. He is about to market a beauty supply product
and form an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't work,'' Male says, smiling and relishing the
power of serendipty, ``it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. Her e-mail is
trausch(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
