<HEADER>
A5315 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-13 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE GENESIS OF `PRO-CHOICE' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The man's voice-mail message said he just wanted
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``You describe John McCain as `anti-choice.' I assume that you
mean he is against abortion, and not that he is against people
exercising their ability to make choices about any number of
issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've researched it but can't pin down when and why
pro-abortion people started using `choice' instead of `abortion.'
Do you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, here's what I remember.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1973, when the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that abortion was
included in a woman's constitutional guarantee of privacy, I
probably identified myself as ``pro-abortion.'' Pro and anti were
the only terms used to distinguish between people of opposing
views: Those who believe that a woman should determine what does or
doesn't occur in her own uterus, and those who believe the
government must decide.
</P>
<P>
   Was being pro-abortion like being pro-democracy, pro-Hubert
Humphrey or pro-49ers? Did I consider it a wonderful thing that I
hoped would rise to dominance?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. Abortion isn't like anything else _ not even capital
punishment or war, two things it is often likened to because, as
some folks see it, ``It's all killing.''
</P>
<P>
   People like me, who acknowledge that abortion has been around as
long as pregnancy has, believe it should be safe and legal. But we
will be happiest when it is unnecessary and therefore extinct.
</P>
<P>
   In the first years after Roe vs. Wade decriminalized women and
the doctors who performed abortions on them, there wasn't much pro
and anti talk. Women whose birth control, calendar keeping or
passion governor failed (or women who were raped by a husband or
stranger) privately went about the sad, heavy business of
terminating their unwanted pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   The first and most ardent suitor of the ultra-conservative
Christian right, President Reagan won that faction's heart by
declaring war on Roe vs. Wade. And for eight years, with every
appointment and veto he made, with every state attorney general he
persuaded to challenge some aspect of legal abortion, he waged a
savage war.
</P>
<P>
   Then he passed the torch to George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush had only four years, but he didn't waste them.
One of his most impressive moves was to deny millions of dollars to
the United Nations Population Fund because one of its 130 recipient
countries _ China _ mandated abortion for population control.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that this abortion policy hadn't kept Bush from
helping China receive most-favored-nation trading status.
</P>
<P>
   Women's reproductive systems had taken their place alongside the
Strategic Defense Initiative, illegal immigration, universal health
care and the capital gains tax as one more pawn on the big
political chessboard.
</P>
<P>
   By then, it was obvious that abortion was about much more than a
private medical procedure. It was about a powerful minority using
elected officials to enforce its view of morality on an entire
country.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the man left his voice mail, I put his question
to Kate Michelman, the president of the National Abortion Rights
Action League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think, throughout this struggle, that we've ever
defined ourselves as `pro-abortion,''' Michelman said. ``It is
those who oppose the right of a woman to choose who have tried to
define us that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelman, who has three children, said NARAL's research shows
there are legions of Americans who ``would never choose to have an
abortion, but who do not believe that any government body should
force a woman against her will to get pregnant, stay pregnant or to
have an abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   To be ``pro-choice'' means just that. It is not a
reality-denying, comfy euphemism for advocating ``baby killing,''
as many anti-abortion proponents charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a set of ethics and principles that begins with the value
of a woman's life. And it includes the value that should be but
isn't placed on child bearing in our society,'' Michelman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we women can conceive and bear children does not
mean we should, no matter our economic, social and psychological
circumstances. Our biological ability to be mothers should not be
the only imperative. The essence of `pro-choice' is respect for all
the complexities of each woman's decision about child bearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the years, as Michelman has watched politics strip
away the protections of Roe vs. Wade, she has noticed a theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these restrictions are designed to intimidate and send a
message to women: `You're not capable of deciding your own
reproductive destiny. You're not responsible. We _ Congress, state
legislatures _ need to put limits on you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``In the meanwhile, they've done nothing remotely comparable to
make abortion less necessary. No one has declared war on the
conditions of unintended pregnancy. Imagine what progress we would
make if we focussed as a nation on that instead of abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   I hope this information helps the man who left the voice-mail
message. I should add, though: Yes, I did mean that John McCain,
like George W. Bush, is against abortion. But, as both men have
made clear, that also means they are against some people _ women _
exercising their ability to make a choice about on every important
issue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
