<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING FOR RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I've just paid off my mortgage, freeing up $700 a month. I'm
debt-free and would like to retire at 62, though 65 seems more
realistic. Where would you suggest I invest? Between my
contributions, the company match, and a profit-sharing plan, 25
percent of my salary goes into my 401(k) plan. Of my $169,405 total
savings, all but about $45,000 is in various tax-advantaged
accounts. I have been considering SSgAs Growth and Income, Fidelity
Blue Chip Growth, and Vanguard Balanced funds. Should I invest in
an overseas fund?
</P>
<P>
   J.P., Shelburne Falls, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, if you add the $700 a month to your savings, and if
annual returns average 8 percent, the pool of money would grow to
$483,564 over seven years and to $697,471 over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose current living costs, excluding mortgage expense,
are about $36,000. If inflation is 3.5 percent a year on average
for the next 10 years, you would need to have $45,802 in seven
years and $50,781 in 10 years to buy what $36,000 buys today. You
can combine those figures with whatever you might expect from
Social Security to determine whether retiring at 62 or 65 is
better. My guess is that the bigger pool at age 65, combined with
the higher Social Security benefit you will get if you wait, will
make the latter alternative the most attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, it's nice _ and necessary, I think _ to have
retirement funds that will offset the effects of inflation in the
later years of your retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The stock side of your portfolio has an unusually nice balance,
though I agree an international fund would make it even better. If
you determine that retirement at 65 is more likely, though, you
might want to be a little bolder, perhaps directing less of your
401(k) money to the fixed-income side and/or giving your
supplemental investments a heavier stock/bond tilt.
</P>
<P>
   As for where to put that extra savings, now that you have paid
off your mortgage, a fund such as Fidelity Overseas would be a good
addition. Why not put 25 percent there, another 25 percent in SSgA
Growth and Income, and the rest in Vanguard Balanced Index?
</P>
<P>
   These moves will diversify your portfolio, without dramatically
increasing risk. (But if you want to keep the risk more or less at
the current level, putting all of the supplemental savings in
Vanguard Balanced Index would roughly match the current allocation
between stocks and fixed-income holdings).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I have just begun thinking hard about
retirement. He'd like to retire at 55 or 56. By then, our home will
be paid for and we will have no major expenses.
</P>
<P>
   K.H., Orange, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Just keep plugging away, and _ thanks to that handsome
pension your husband has earned _ you should be pretty comfortable.
Most people calculate they can live satisfactorily in retirement on
about two thirds of the income they required while they were
working, for a number of reasons: the end of work-related expenses,
having time to do minor chores that might have been paid for
before, the fact that the savings period is over for most people,
and in your case, the end of mortgage payments.
</P>
<P>
   You might need about $40,000 a year in retirement. Five years
from now, your current savings of $147,000 would grow to $248,519
if you continue your current contributions and if you achieve
average market returns of 8 percent; the figure would be $286,456
if you wanted until age 56. Your fixed-income investments _ half of
the 401(k) balance, plus the CDs and money market account _ will
prove more than adequate to supply the supplemental income stream;
you could leave the balance of your savings in stock funds such as
those you now hold, to protect you against long-term inflation.
</P>
<P>
   You should be particularly comfortable because at just about the
time inflation might begin to really bite _ after you've been
retired for six or seven years _ Social Security benefits will kick
in. (If inflation averages 3.5 percent for 12 years, you would need
$60,442 to buy what $40,000 buys now.)
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, you will be in good shape whether you
decide to retire at 55, 56, or later, with the situation steadily
getting even better if retirement is deferred.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I was born in October 1928, and I want to start IRA
withdrawals this year, but not with an automatic scheduled amount.
I have IRA accounts with three companies. I would like to retain
the option to take the required withdrawal from whichever of the
three accounts I choose. I've had no luck obtaining a life
expectancy table. Can you point me in the right direction?
</P>
<P>
   W.M., South Pasadena, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's a good thing you want to take your first IRA withdrawals
this year _ because you have to. The first withdrawal must be made
by April 1 of the year following the year in which you reach age 70
1/2, which in your case is about seven weeks from now.
</P>
<P>
   The rule for withdrawals when you have multiple IRA accounts is
that you simply add up the balances of all of the accounts,
determine the amount that must be withdrawn, and then take the
money from the account or accounts you prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the IRS for its Joint and Last Survivor Life Expectancy
tables, in Publication 590 (available free) or find it in
publications such as J. K. Lasser's ``Your Income Tax 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Money Musings: When this column was written, in the middle of
last week, a lot of people were watching the stock market with
horror, calculating its effect on their portfolios. That's
understandable, particularly if you have speculative investments.
But it also the climate to which people who have established a
steady investment pattern must steel themselves. Even if you
contribute only $166 a month to an IRA, the thing to remember is
that you are basically involved in a dollar-cost-averaging program.
</P>
<P>
   Resist the temptation to hold off sending this month's IRA
contribution a little late, thinking you might buy more shares if
the market wobbles more. Resist even more strongly the temptation
to skip this one entirely and double up next month. The markets
might not wobble; you'd then have lost the opportunity to buy
relatively cheap shares during the dip.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, dollar-cost averaging is a discipline, and the trick
in markets like these is to bite your lip and write the check. It
will pay well over the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
