<HEADER>
A5321 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS &LR;      03-13 0217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Inventing Al Gore'' by Bill Turque (Houghton Mifflin, $25). An
excellent unauthorized biography, tracing the personal history that
shaped the probable Democratic nominee. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Barbarians Are Coming'' by David Wong Louie (Putnam,
$23.95). Both hilarious and moving, this first novel traces the
journey toward wisdom of a Chinese-American son of immigrants. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mountains Walked'' by Kate Wheeler (Houghton Mifflin,
$23). A remarkable first novel about a young American woman's
discovery of herself in Peru. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A Heartbreaking Work of Staggering Genius'' by Dave Eggers
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23). This memoir-of-sorts, about a young man
raising his younger brother, is hip, funny, wildly intelligent, and
full of narrative energy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Bridget Jones: The Edge of Reason'' by Helen Fielding (Viking,
$24.95). She's back, still keeping a diary recording her obsessions
(calories, cigarettes, and romance), still engaging our unlikely
sympathy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple Stories'' by Ingo Schulze (Knopf, $25). A novel in 29
interlocking stories about life in a small East German town,
astringently written and brilliantly crafted.
</P>
</TEXT>
