<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5323 &Cx1f; sci-z
r l BC-SCIENCE-OF-PERFUME-AR     03-13 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-OF-PERFUME-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRAGRANT REVOLUTION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT KUNZIG  
 c.2000 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``Your grandmother loved all the Guerlain perfumes _ Shalimar,
Jicky. But I could never wear Jicky _ it just didn't go with my
skin.''
</P>
<P>
   My mother is telling perfume stories over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time your father and I went into the Guerlain shop in
Paris, and I tried on some Jicky. The girl had to take me back to
the employee washroom and scrub it off with strong soap. She wasn't
going to let me leave Guerlain smelling like that.''
</P>
<P>
   One perfume is much like another _ or so I used to think. Each
of the many odor receptors high in our nostrils can, in principle,
trigger thousands of different nerve-signal patterns that our brain
interprets as distinct smells.
</P>
<P>
   But we don't all make the same use of that equipment. In fact,
many of us have noses that are just face furniture _ which is a
shame, because we're living through a fragrance revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Our olfactory environment has been radically altered by
synthetic substances emerging from the labs of organic chemists.
Some of them are noxious, but the ones in perfumes are often
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime after her set-to with Jicky, my mother settled into a
long relationship with Lanvin's Arpege. She chose the perfume with
the perfect name. A pretty scent is like a melody _ an arpeggio of
chemical notes, each one a compound of carbon, hydrogen and oxygen
atoms strung together in a ring, a chain or a combination of the
two.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens or hundreds of ingredients in a perfume, but
they evaporate on the skin and waft into the nose in three distinct
stages, or ``notes,'' called top, middle and base, depending on how
big and volatile their molecules are.
</P>
<P>
   Top notes are flighty molecules that come off within minutes and
then vanish _ citrus-peel molecules like bergamot, for instance.
Base notes may linger for a day or more. In the old days _ before
prices skyrocketed and customers revolted against the practice _
the base was often made from animal secretions such as musk (with
which the Tibetan musk deer marks its territory) or ambergris (a
kind of sperm-whale excretion).
</P>
<P>
   In between top and base lies the heart of the perfume, which
drifts off the wearer for hours and is often a harmony of floral
scents.
</P>
<P>
   When Arpege was released in 1927, it helped consolidate a
revolution that had been launched a few years earlier by Chanel No.
5. Both perfumes contain traditional essences of jasmine and rose.
But both rely for their impact on straight-chain carbon molecules
called aldehydes that have no equivalent in nature-pure laboratory
creations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Arpege, you have a floral bouquet,'' says Elisabeth Carre,
a chemist at L'Oreal, the French cosmetics giant that now owns
Lanvin. ``But it's thrown into a radically different light by the
massive addition of aldehydes, which make the floral notes fresher
and more brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then perfume creation has been a partnership of artist and
chemist. And the artists, who can remember a thousand smells and
compose new scents in their heads, do not resent the intrusion of
science.
</P>
<P>
   ``A century ago perfumers had 20 or 30 synthetic products to
work with,'' says Olivier Cresp, a perfumer at Firmenich, a Swiss
fragrance company. ``Today we have 3,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with so many odor molecules on their palette, companies
like Firmenich are under pressure to find new ones. But the
chemists face a fundamental problem: No one knows why things smell
the way they do. No one knows what happens when an odor molecule
meets a receptor in the nose. Thus you can't design a new odor from
first principles.
</P>
<P>
   What you can fall back on are empirical rules of thumb. If
you're looking for a new fruity note, for instance, it's a good bet
to start with an ester, an odorous compound common in fruits that
forms when an alcohol reacts with a carboxylic acid.
</P>
<P>
   What if a perfumer is looking for a molecule that will evoke,
say, jasmine and the sea, perhaps for a perfume targeted at young
women who are in touch with their femininity and nevertheless show
a self-confident, adventurous spirit?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what you want for a jasmine smell, roughly, is a
molecule with a central carbon atom that's surrounded by three
different things: a highly polar group, a weakly polar group and a
long chain of carbon atoms,'' says Charles Sell, head of organic
chemistry at Quest International, another fragrance firm. (A polar
group has a slightly positive charge at one end of its molecular
bond and a slightly negative charge at the other.)
</P>
<P>
   Nitriles _ molecules that contain a nitrogen atom triple-bonded
to a carbon _ are compounds that sometimes smell of algae. If you
were to stick a nitrile into the polar slot of your jasmine
template, Sell says, you just might get a scent of
jasmine-by-the-sea.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, fragrance chemists can also leave the lab to seek
novelty in nature. That's the specialty of Roman Kaiser of Givaudan
Roure in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   More than 25 years ago Kaiser helped pioneer headspace
technology, in which a glass dome is placed over a flower or other
odor source to capture all the volatile molecules the chemist's
nose would capture if his head were in that space. The chemist can
then synthesize the molecules and try to reconstitute the live
scent.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser's passion is capturing scents in the wild. He has trapped
and later reconstituted the smell of carnations wafting off an
island near Brittany. A few years ago he even nosed around above a
tropical rain forest in a hot-air balloon.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one of our first flights from the camp in French Guiana,''
Kaiser recalls, ``we saw a tree that was covered in white blossoms.
When we got closer, it turned out to be a vine that was blooming,
not the tree itself. The smell reminded me right away of vanilla
ice cream with hot raspberry sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   The tasty smell of that vine, reconstituted in his lab, has
since become a component of a new line of women's shower gels and
shampoos.
</P>
<P>
   Food smells are popular these days. Cresp helped start that rage
a few years ago with Angel, a perfume that smells of chocolate and
roasted almonds. Apparently, food smells remind many perfume buyers
of their childhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd never felt a bond to any smell, edible or not _
until I visited the offices of L'Oreal, and Elisabeth Carre gave me
a whiff of Arpege. It was an odd and even troubling experience:
Suddenly, I felt the presence of my mother.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the aldehydes or the fruity undecalactone. Or maybe
it was the rose notes rising from the heart. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Kunzig is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
