<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-13 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WANTS TO BE THE NEXT KATHIE LEE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day soon a plume of white smoke will issue forth from the
corporate production offices of ``Live! With Regis and Kathie Lee''
indicating that Kathie Lee Gifford's successor has been named.
</P>
<P>
   Who will it be? Joy Philbin? Joan Lunden? Hillary Rodham
Clinton? Susan Sontag? Miss Piggy? The late Totie Fields?
</P>
<P>
   To millions of viewers it doesn't matter who will be sitting
there nattering with Regis. If it's not Kathie Lee, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   She could change her mind. Her fans are begging her to stay.
Please don't go, Kathie Lee. What will we do without you?
</P>
<P>
   Not that we'll ever really be free of Kathie Lee. The woman is
everywhere, what with her signature clothing, home furnishings, and
skin-care lines, her CDs, her books, her TV movie with little Cody,
her singing dates on and off Broadway, her job plugging Carnival
Cruise Lines, her charities. I could go on and on, but we have
limited space.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Lee is quitting ``Live!'' when her $6 million contract
expires in August. Cynics have suggested that she's leaving because
she's envious of Regis Philbin, now the hottest thing on the box as
host of ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' This is nonsense, of
course. In fact, Kathie Lee is very concerned about the toll the
game show is taking on her co-host's health. ``I worry because I
love him,'' she told People magazine. ``He's tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Lee is tired, too, not physically tired, but bored.
Kathie Lee has ennui. She confided to People that the job has
ceased to amuse her: ``About a year ago I was interviewing Lily
Tomlin for probably the 10th time and thinking, I don't want to do
this one more time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how Lily Tomlin felt about being interviewed by
Kathie Lee for the 10th time, but I'm sure it must have been just
as thrilling for her as it was on the very first occasion. After
all, Tomlin is merely a run-of-the-mill comic genius whereas Kathie
Lee is Kathie Lee. There's no comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Kathie Lee hopes quitting ``Live!'' will preserve her children's
privacy. To some, this may sound hypocritical coming from a woman
who, day after day, has shared the most intimate details of her
childrens' lives with millions of viewers. But Kathie Lee's critics
fail to understand how fiercely protective she is of her children,
even as she thrusts them into the limelight. The last straw came
when one tabloid characterized adorable little Cody as ``a
monster.'' Imagine. Kathie Lee is suing. Who can blame her?
</P>
<P>
   The media, particularly the tabloids, have made life difficult
for the Gifford family. We remember the low point, when the tabloid
Globe (not this Globe, thank you) paid a woman to lure Frank
Gifford to a hotel room. Their tryst was secretly taped and
subsequently splashed all over the tabloid's pages. It was a
scurrilous episode. Everyone involved should be ashamed of
themselves, everyone except Kathie Lee, who was blameless. She
thought she had the perfect marriage. Hadn't she said so many times
on ``Live!''?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the Giffords were able to work through their pain
and now their marriage is better than ever, according to Kathie
Lee. ``We stayed at home, we stayed in the word of God, we stayed
in bed,'' she told People.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder she's America's self-appointed sweetheart, the
idol of millions? Maybe she could host her own game show, ``Who
Wants to Be Kathie Lee?'' Because who wouldn't want to be Kathie
Lee?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
