<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MCCANN-BOS &LR;      03-13 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MCCANN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALANCNG DEATH AND BEAUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
EVERYTHING IN THIS COUNTRY MUST 
A Novella and Two Stories 
By Colum McCann. Henry Holt. 
150 pp. $21. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much talk has been made in recent years of an Irish renaissance
in fiction; the usual writers who emerge in such conversations are
masters of dark wit, particularly Roddy Doyle and Patrick McCabe.
But none seems to me so finely imbued with the lyrical melancholy
of the old masters _ of Joyce and Yeats and, later, William Trevor
_ as Colum McCann. As with the sensibility of his forebears, his
fiction is equal parts death and beauty, its inescapable realism
uplifted by an exquisitely soulful and visual prose. His last
novel, ``This Side of Brightness,'' rendered the story of a man
living in the subway tunnels of New York _ a sovereign, secret home
where his ``cartography of darkness'' helped him chart his bearings
in the world. The small but piercing ``Everything in This Country
Must'' possesses a similar tribute to the power of place _ as both
anchor and chain, as the homeland that defines you and as the heavy
yoke that must be shed.
</P>
<P>
   McCann lives in New York, where he learned firsthand about the
residents of the subway tunnels; authenticity is all over his
fiction, but it's seamless enough that you scarcely notice its
stamp. The two stories and novella of ``Everything in This Country
Must'' are set in his native Ireland _ in Galway, in Derry, in the
stony rural countryside where political allegiances are as quiet
and essential as breath. The impact of these three tales lies in
their sweet specificity: in a girl watching her father suffer, then
enact, the agonies of Northern Ireland; in a son trying to save his
father by betraying him; in a boy on the verge of adulthood _ he is
only 13 _ torn between rage and desire.
</P>
<P>
   And yet tragedy is general all over Ireland. The newspapers tell
the stories: A soldier shoots an old woman whose umbrella he
mistakes for a rifle; a rubber bullet strikes a little girl on her
way home with milk. A Roman Catholic farmer finds his herd of
cattle with their throats slit, their carcasses arranged to form
the word ``NO.'' These sorrows may belong to strangers, but it
doesn't matter: They indicate the relentless atmosphere of random
grief that infects these characters and the country they love and
hate in equal measure. Often the death foretold appears as a mere
shadow of suggestion, but it still feels imminent as rain. In the
title story, a girl tries to help her father rescue his favorite
horse from drowning, but her efforts are hardly aided by hope: ``I
was wearing Stevie's jacket but I was shivering and wet and cold
and scared because Stevie and the draft horse were going to die
since everything in this country must.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice of the title story has about it a Faulknerian
gloominess, much like that of Benjy's narration in ``The Sound and
the Fury'': It's the innocent perspective of children, delivered
with the unstoppable poetry of doom. In ``Wood,'' the youngest son
of a man felled by a stroke has to work at night with his mother to
hide their labors from the father: They are making flagpoles for a
Protestant march, and they need the money. Both these stories are
spare etchings of emotion and history; McCann's more elaborate
canvas is reserved for his novella, ``Hunger Strike,'' in which the
nephew of a political prisoner in Derry keeps vigil from afar while
his uncle slowly starves to death.
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to the force of McCann's fiction is the manner in which
his plots are rendered by his crystalline use of symbols: a bird
trapped in an icy river; a man dying or flourishing underground;
the loyal boy of ``Hunger Strike,'' refusing, too, to eat, shaping
his dinner bread into lumpy chess pieces and then learning how to
use his knight. Kevin has fled Derry with his widowed mother for
County Galway; they wait there for news of the imprisoned uncle,
whose weight drops a pound or two with each telephoned report. We
learn these statistics as Kevin does, and they take on the cold
rhythms of a titrated obituary _ ``It'll be today or tomorrow,''
his ma tells him; then, later, ``Today or tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin's walks on the beach are driven by a child's fury, aimless
and too young and thus ill-spent, and the imagery surrounding them
is cruel: The God who has failed him is a ``sly and complicated
bastard''; a stone wall jetty runs ``like a bad suture towards the
sea.'' But while Kevin's internal odyssey is defined by his uncle's
lethal protest, it is the larger, kinder choreography of the story
that makes ``Hunger Strike'' memorable. An old man in a kayak
caught Kevin's eye when he arrived in Galway; the boy's rage and
frustration could easily take aim at such a vulnerable target.
Instead he seeks out the man, who offers both succor and
instruction _ who has his own scars, it turns out, and his own ways
of forgetting. This careful dance is one of violence eclipsed by
grace, and its redemptive presence makes Kevin's education
bearable: ``Darkness doesn't fall,'' he thinks, ``it rises up out
of the bottom of the sea and begins to breathe around us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in This Country Must'' has one real limitation, and
the burden for that must go to McCann's publisher as well as to
him. It's absurdly short, a work that might, had it been printed
with normal margins, constitute half a collection. It was not so
long ago that publishers restrained themselves from charging ahead
with a book until the entire book, in fact, existed; nowadays,
though, the fashion is to slam into hardback any text over 80
pages. At $20 a pop for a new hardcover, this trend seems as greedy
as it is precipitate. I would go out of my way to read Colum McCann
regardless of the packaging, but I suspect most readers would
prefer to do so without having to grumble about publishing's
miserly fare.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
