A5332 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      03-13 0254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   !! 1/2 ``Mission to Mars'' Brian De Palma's big-budget throwback
to the innocent, campy sci-fi of the 1950s. More shipshape than
trail-blazing, its plainness helps nudge it into guilty-pleasure
territory as it tracks a rescue mission after all but one crew
member of the first mission is mysteriously wiped out. Tim Robbins,
Gary Sinise, Don Cheadle, and impressive Red Planet visuals are the
stars. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR) ! ``The Ninth Gate'' Johnny Depp seems flat and muffled as a
book-finder hired to locate a volume in which Lucifer is said to
have had a hand. Roman Polanski's ponderous, self-immolatingly
campy supernatural thriller is not super, not natural, not
thrilling. (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!!! ``Not One Less'' Simple but enticing movie from Zhang Yimou. A
13-year-old girl pressed into service as a substitute teacher in a
remote Chinese village proves her mettle when she goes to the big
city to bring a young dropout home. Zhang had to conceal his camera
to keep his nonprofessionals loose and spontaneous. It works. (G)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``Orphans'' Peter Mullan delivers a vigorously unruly
ensemble piece. Four adult siblings in Glasgow pass a stormy night
grieving, in their fashion, for their dead mother, whose funeral is
to be held the next morning. Some episodes take off, some spin
their wheels, but the film makes a strong debut for writer-director
Mullan. (Unrated)
</P>
</TEXT>
