<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5333 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-VIDEO-DIRECTOR-EXTRAO     03-13 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-DIRECTOR-EXTRAORDINAIRE-INTERVIEW-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR'S CUT  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from Women's Wear
Daily, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE showing Madonna in a scene from the video for
``Rain'' is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of this article.
The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please specify that
you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JANET KINOSIAN  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mark Romanek, one of the last decade's most
prolific music video directors, is sitting in an overstuffed chair
in the lobby of the Chateau Marmont, thumbing through the images in
his new book, ``Mark Romanek: Music Video Stills.''
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, in from the sun-streaked garden steps REM's
Michael Stipe, the flesh-and-blood embodiment of the image on page
115. The director and the pop icon hug warmly _ they're clearly
friends _ and Stipe says, ``I heard the book was great,'' as he
lands on a close-up of his shaved head.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of Hollywood moment with which Romanek is all too
familiar, having created a vast and elegant portrait gallery _ in
videos and now in stills _ of MTV luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   There's Madonna, shivering in blue in ``Rain'' and haloed by a
sunflower in ``Bedtime Stories''; Janet and Michael Jackson coming
unglued in ``Scream''; Lenny Kravitz in the cool and sanitized
world of ``If You Can't Say No''; and a starkly sexual Fiona Apple
in ``Criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an enviable client list: Beck, Sonic Youth, Iggy Pop, En
Vogue, David Bowie, Nine Inch Nails and k.d. lang have all turned
up in Romanek's studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very lucky because I knew when I was very young what I
wanted to do,'' Romanek explains. ``To be a film director. And I
went to a school that helped me know what that was.''
</P>
<P>
   Romanek attended a progressive high school in Winnetka, Ill.,
where many of his teachers were graduates of the School of the Art
Institute of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``And here they were, showing us Kenneth Anger films and God
knows what. I doubt the powers that were knew what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   The edgy sensibility Romanek cultivated there still informs his
video work _ and can be felt in the stills that populate his new
book.
</P>
<P>
   Now Romanek says he's ready for the broader arena of feature
films. He's been spinning around the idea of a silent picture and
has spent several years writing a screenplay about photographer
Diane Arbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to know what's so fantastic about her?'' he asks.
``Do you have a full day?''
</P>
<P>
   While Romanek presses in new directions, the book documents his
contribution to the advancement of the genre he knows best. In the
last half-decade, traditional wiggle-the-butt music videos have
given way _ with the support of artists like Madonna _ to more
thoughtful and often highly inventive video making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Madonna to cut off her hair for the `Rain' video, and
she agreed,'' Romanek recalls. ``But that morning, she chickened
out. She said, `Mark, but that's a big deal.' And I said, `I
know.'''
</P>
<P>
   So they arrived at a compromise _ and Madonna was fitted with a
short, black wig that drove her nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scratching her all day, and in the last shot I told
her, `Wait, we need another take!' She just pulled the wig off and
threw it at me. I think it was her way of saying, `That's a
wrap.''' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Janet Kinosian is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
