<HEADER>
A5335 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-13 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY ISSUE LIKELY TO BECOME HOTTER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM BARLOW 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mass production is dying. We're entering the era of mass
customization. No more one-size-fits-all products. Each must be
tailored to fit the needs and desires of the individual customer.
</P>
<P>
   Business must learn all about its customers for mass
customization to work. At the same time, business must respect
customers' privacy. It is being warned about gathering too much
information when building profiles of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, business can't do it both ways. Consumers who want
products tailored to their individual needs can't expect business
to do that without learning a lot about them.
</P>
<P>
   All of us surrender a lot of our privacy by entering the
marketplace. If you've ever bought a house, you know how much the
lender learns about you before a decision about granting a loan is
made.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the most intrusive forms I've ever seen are the ones
that must be filled out to obtain a state alcoholic beverage
license or a license to operate a radio or television station.
</P>
<P>
   However, most people would be amazed at how much information
about us is available in either public records or semiprivate ones
such as those maintained by a credit bureau.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DOUBLECLICK BACKS OFF _ FOR NOW &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here in the United States, we're still much more open about
business use of personal data. In Europe the laws are much more
restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   We could adopt those laws and give all of us a much greater
degree of privacy. However, it would come at a price.
</P>
<P>
   Take the current poster child of those who worry about privacy _
an Internet company called DoubleClick. Critics jumped all over its
program to match consumers' names with the sites those people
visited on the Internet. DoubleClick wanted to sell that
information to marketers, who would try and sell those consumers
products based on their Web visits.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick has put that effort on hold, after an outcry.
However, Kevin O'Connor, the top guy at DoubleClick, says he's just
supporting free access on the Internet. Those who maintain Web
sites must get paid for their effort. That now mostly comes from
selling advertisements _ and advertisers want to know who sees
their ads. If Web sites can't make money with ads, they will charge
fees to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Most people don't seem to mind data collection by a company if
they've been doing business with it for a while. If you regularly
stay at a particular chain of hotels, the odds are you like the
fact that it knows you might need a special pillow because of an
allergy.
</P>
<P>
   Or that Dollar Rent A Car System tracks the number of times
customers rent from them. If you rent three times, they know it and
might offer an upgrade or other incentive to keep you coming back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
UNKNOWN HAWKERS ARE BOGEYMEN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the trouble comes from prospective marketing _ that is,
a company assembling information about a non-customer to better
pitch a product to that person.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of marketing was the impetus behind a change in the
law last November that allowed banks, securities firms and
insurance companies to form one-stop financial organizations.
Instead of just selling you an insurance policy, for example, your
company also could offer you annuities, certificates of deposits,
stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Financial companies fought, and won, the right in the
legislation to allow them to share information about customers with
affiliates. So, your bank can take the information gleaned from
your checking, savings and certificate-of-deposit accounts. It can
then match your spending and saving habits with the financial
products its affiliates sell, or even design new ones, to grab more
of your business.
</P>
<P>
   What really seems to irritate people, however, are companies
buying information from various sources and pitching products to
people with whom they have absolutely no relationship. Remember the
great credit card wars of a few years ago? If you had acceptable
credit, or sometimes even if you didn't, every week there were two
or three mailed pitches urging you to accept a new credit card.
That was followed in a few days by someone making a ``courtesy
call'' to make sure you had received the mailing.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the privacy debate is below the radar for most
Americans. Expect it to become more visible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
