u a BC-MAINE-BALLOT-BOS &LR;      03-13 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-BALLOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE INITIATIVES MET WITH GLEE, FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For John Michael, a man none too pleased with the professional
lawmakers in Augusta, the certification this month of Maine's
highest-ever number of citizen ballot initiatives was the occasion
for some populist muscle-flexing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We forced their hand!'' said Michael, whose initiative for the
repeal of a state tax on snack foods could well face a vote early
in the Legislature, circumventing the popular vote. ``We got the
signatures. Because if you shine a little light on cockroaches,
they start scurrying.''
</P>
<P>
   The glee within the Don't Tax Food Coalition _ or a more
restrained form of it _ is shared by backers of the other
initiatives that will appear on Maine's November ballot: measures
to legalize assisted suicide, restrict clear-cutting of forests,
and legalize video lottery machines at harness-racing tracks.
</P>
<P>
   What unites them is despair that elected officials would ever
satisfy their demands, and faith in Maine's 92-year tradition _
shared on the East Coast only by Massachusetts and Florida _ of
allowing citizens to make laws or amend the state Constitution by
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   But during the last decade, as a nationwide citizen initiative
movement began to set broader public policy at the ballot box, some
critics have charged that the process allows deep-pocketed lobbying
groups to hijack the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   Maine is no different. With the backing of Secretary of State
Dan Gwadosky, legislators have made a series of attempts to
restrain the signature-gatherers, warning that Maine is seeing the
beginnings of an initiative industry like the multimillion-dollar
one that has come to dominate California politics.
</P>
<P>
   This year's large crop of initiatives has fueled Gwadosky's
fears that Maine will begin to attract national lobbies looking to
rack up victories.
</P>
<P>
   Gwadosky's prime example of the professionalization of the
process is the snack-tax crusader himself. Michael, who served six
terms as a Democratic legislator in Augusta before returning to
Auburn, Maine, in disgust, is the first person in the state to
parlay signature-gathering into a career. He pays his employees 50
cents to $1 for each signature. And, said Gwadosky, the snack tax
repeal is only one of a dozen ballot questions that Michael
``shopped around'' in advance of the November election, looking for
interest groups willing to back the effort. ``You started to have
individuals who really went into the business of gathering
signatures for profit,'' said Gwadosky.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Legislature voted to prevent petitioners from
paying signature-gatherers by the signature _ a law that was struck
down by a federal judge last December.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes pushed unsuccessfully in the Legislature include
prohibiting signature-gathering within 250 feet of a ballot box and
establishing a minimum of 50,000 signatures.
</P>
<P>
   But Gwadosky and the legislators who sponsored the bills are
encroaching on a tradition close to the populist hearts of Mainers.
The processes of initiative and referendum, which allow voters to
repeal legislative acts, are primarily a phenomenon of the Western
states, born during the first decades of the last century out of
disillusionment over legislatures controlled by monied interests.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the institution of a citizen's vote has been used by
those same interests _ the business community defeated Maine's
nine-hour-workday law by referendum in 1915, according to labor
historian Charles Scontras _ it's cherished in Maine as a tool of
direct democracy.
</P>
<P>
   And no one better embodies that tradition than the earnest
volunteer striding into the secretary of state's office with a
sheaf of signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Adams of Garland said she will never forget that moment in
1997 when her ``love affair'' with the initiative began. A
35-year-old mother of two with no background in politics, she was
so protective of the 50,000 signatures she had gathered in support
of a push to repeal Maine's property tax that she slept with them
in her bedroom at night.
</P>
<P>
   But she didn't feel the ``awesome'' power that she had as a
citizen until she dropped off the signatures at the secretary of
state's office, said Adams, who runs her own online political
newsletter, The Adams Report. That moment, she said, sent shivers
down her spine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old movie I saw as a kid, called `Thirteen Lead
Soldiers,' and when they found the 13th lead soldier and put it in
the right place after several death-defying acts, the door opened
up in the side of the mountain and all the debris and dirt fell
down, and there was the treasure that no one had seen for hundreds
of years,'' she said. ``That's just the way I felt when I saw that
thing work. I felt as if we had found the 13th lead soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's also true that in Maine, as in the other 23 states that
use the process, citizens' initiatives have been put to
dramatically different use in recent years. Between 1908, when the
provision was passed, and 1998, only 38 citizen-initiated petitions
made it onto Maine's ballot. The surge dates back to Proposition
13, which California voters approved in 1978. The tax-cutting
initiative, financed with $2 million by two businessmen, limited
increases in assessments on homes until they were resold, and built
in brakes to raising property taxes. It also sparked what
Washington political columnist David Broder, in his book
``Democracy Derailed: Initiative Campaigns and the Power of
Money,'' describes as a snowballing voter rebellion against state
legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   But in Maine, where only 13 citizen initiatives have become law
in 92 years, those fears seem exaggerated, said Dane Waters,
president of the Initiative and Referendum Institute, which
advocates for freer use of the process nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   That point is not argued by state Senator Richard ``Spike''
Carey, a Democrat who sponsored the bill to set the higher
signature threshold. The way he sees it, some policy decisions just
don't belong in the hands of amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the campaigns are usually not very truthful on
either side,'' said Carey, offering, by way of example, the
clear-cutting initiative set to face voters in November. ``A person
who lives in the city who knows nothing about forestry is swayed
one way or the other by whoever talked to them last.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
