<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIT-DONATIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH BOOM GIVES MIT NEW CACHET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acceptance letters for admission to both Harvard and MIT threw
Jonathan Sheffi into a whirl of indecision last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard? MIT? Harvard? MIT?
</P>
<P>
   Sheffi was facing the biggest decision in his 18 years, and a
combined 1,580 SAT score was not helping. He paced. He roused his
parents at 2 a.m. to talk. He studied college rankings on the
Internet. Finally, he accepted at MIT, then withdrew. He accepted
Harvard's invitation and withdrew that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's allure, he said, is its prestige. MIT is ``where the
real stuff is happening,'' Sheffi, now a freshman, said on a balmy
March afternoon in his laundry-strewn dorm room at MIT. ``I'm so
glad I resisted Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University has always out-graced and overshadowed the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, a clunky compound where
whiz-kid engineers hunch over arcane gadgetry.
</P>
<P>
   But the ascendancy of ``geek chic'' throughout society has given
technology-based research universities, such as MIT, a cachet once
reserved for Ivy League schools supported by blue-blooded
benefactors. During the 1990s, undergraduate applications to MIT
shot up 66 percent, more than Harvard's, which rose 53 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the middle of a technical revolution,'' and MIT is
among ``the schools that are benefiting right now,'' said Arthur
Levine, president of the Teachers College at Columbia University.
``This is their moment, this is their time, this is their
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   From its perch on the Charles River, Harvard may not admit to
being engaged in a spirited, always polite, rivalry with MIT. But,
things are happening so fast at MIT that, surely, some heads must
be turning at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's $14.4 billion endowment is the largest for a
university in the country. But, MIT has suddenly become a magnet
for the money gushing from the white-hot centers of high-tech,
biotechnology, and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A former MIT student and computer-publishing magnate, Patrick J.
McGovern Jr., and his entrepreneur wife, Lore Harp McGovern,
recently presented MIT with a $350 million gift. The donation _
trumpeted by newspapers, including the Harvard Crimson, as the
biggest in US academic history _ occurred mere months after an MIT
student-turned-entrepreneur, Kenan E. Sahin, dropped $100 million
on his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard will always be Harvard, clinging to traditions such as
the Harvard-Yale football game. And its celebrity scholars, in
fields ranging from physics and the classics to medicine and
African-American studies, are unmatched. Thirty-seven Nobel Prizes
have been awarded to Harvard faculty since 1914.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about MIT's momentum, Harvard's spokesman, Joe Wrinn,
hewed to tradition. ``You're really comparing apples and oranges,''
he said. ``We're bigger and older, but it's not a competition.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, MIT's apples seem to shine just as brightly as
Harvard's oranges.
</P>
<P>
   In annual college rankings by U.S. News &AMP; World Report, Harvard
has, year after year, placed first among ``national universities,''
those offering a range of undergraduate and graduate degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine discourages comparing rankings, due to changes in
its methodology each year. But, the academic community took note
when MIT, in the newest ranking, elbowed into the top tier, placing
third among 228 national universities and nipping at the heels of
No. 2 Harvard. The California Institute of Technology ranked first.
</P>
<P>
   MIT's cachet runs deeper than geek chic, but there's that, too.
Take the institute's role in the 1997 movie ``Good Will Hunting,''
about a genius MIT janitor, played by Matt Damon, who solves a math
problem thought to be unsolvable. But there was the 1970 movie
``Love Story,'' starring Ali McGraw and Ryan O'Neal, two sorry
lovebirds on the Harvard-Radcliffe campus.
</P>
<P>
   What about the universities' choices of commencement speakers?
Harvard hosted Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve Board chairman,
in June. MIT's graduation speakers last year: ``Car Talk'' radio
show hosts Tom and Ray Magliozzi.
</P>
<P>
   And, while Harvard grabbed headlines for a recent flap over
reclaiming its proud name from a health maintenance organization in
receivership, Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, MIT basks in the success
of math professor Tom Leighton. Wall Street has watched in wonder
as the value of Leighton's Internet company, Akamai Technologies,
soared above $27 billion in four months since going public.
</P>
<P>
   MIT's selection of architect Frank Gehry to design the Stata
computer center seemed an expression of its newfound hipness. Gehry
is the award-winning designer of the free-form Guggenheim Museum in
Bilboa, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course MIT is cooler than Harvard,'' exclaimed Nancy
Kanwisher, who came to MIT from Harvard 2 1/2 years ago as an
associate professor in the brain and cognitive science department.
</P>
<P>
   Kanwisher's work on visual activity in the cortex and colleague
Susumu Tonegawa's work on memory are the kinds of research going on
at MIT that persuaded the McGoverns to designate that their
donation be used to establish the Institute for Brain Research.
</P>
<P>
   MIT, founded in 1861 as a school of arts and industrial science,
has historically excelled in the sciences. A 1995 survey by the
National Research Council placed MIT at the top _ for the quality
of its faculty and effectiveness of its doctoral programs _ in
engineering, cell biology, computer science, and materials science,
among other fields. MIT is among a handful of research
organizations worldwide on the verge of cracking the code for the
human genome.
</P>
<P>
   But, MIT also rated high for linguistics _ Noam Chomsky is on
the faculty _ and for its star-studded economics faculty. The
humanities program overall is also considered top drawer: History
professor John Dower won a 1999 National Book Award for ``Embracing
Defeat: Japan in the Wake of World War II.'' MIT boasts only one
Pulitzer; composer John Harbison won in 1987. But its faculty,
since 1964, have won 19 Nobel prizes. (Add to that 16 Nobels won by
MIT alumni.)
</P>
<P>
   Edmund P. Russell III, a professor of technology and culture at
the University of Virginia, explained that the growing importance
of technology in society has given the public a greater
appreciation of what goes on at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, he said, has sped up the process by demonstrating
``the importance of the so-called geeks to our national well
being.''
</P>
<P>
   And MIT, long stereotyped as a haven for white men with pocket
protectors, has diversified. Nearly half of the entering freshmen
last fall were women, up from 30 percent a decade ago. Minorities
rose from 7 percent to 18 percent of the student population.
</P>
<P>
   Emilie Croisier, a freshman math and neuroscience major, said
she prefers MIT life. ``I'm sure I could visit more museums at
Harvard, but the people here are just so, so dynamic.''
</P>
<P>
   In technology, Harvard is behind in a race led by MIT. Harvard
is forging more links with private industry and teaching
undergraduates how to be entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   It has become cliche, in business circles, to note that William
H. Gates dropped out of Harvard to devote himself to Microsoft
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Would Gates have dropped out if he had gone to MIT instead?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
