<HEADLINE>
MORE WOMEN ARE EMBRACING JEWISH EDUCATION AND WORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mention the study of the Torah or Talmud, and one almost
inevitably pictures a group of bearded men huddled over the ancient
Jewish texts.
</P>
<P>
   But that picture increasingly is inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   A new study of American Jews, done at Brandeis University, finds
that among involved but non-Orthodox Jews, women are more likely
than men to be studying their faith.
</P>
<P>
   The findings are being hailed by scholars of gender and Judaism,
who say they mark a reversal of two millenia in which serious
Jewish scholarship was almost exclusively the province of men.
</P>
<P>
   The scholars say that the American Jewish community has come to
resemble the Christian community in the increasing importance of
women at worship and in religious classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the extraordinary results of Jewish feminism is that
there has been a real sea change in attitudes toward girls and
women studying traditional texts, so that for the first time in
2,000 years of Jewish history girls and women now have access to
the basic tools for (Jewish) cultural literacy,'' said Sylvia
Barack Fishman, co-director of the Hadassah International Research
Institute on Jewish Women, which is releasing the study. ``This
brings Jews more in line with the patterns we see in other American
religions, where the typical pattern is male clergy but a vast
majority of worshipers . . . are women.''
</P>
<P>
   Judaism has historically emphasized the study of the Torah and
rabbinic texts, such as the Talmud, as a virtue for men, and texts
such as the Talmud feature almost entirely male voices. With some
prominent exceptions, women have been exempted from, and in some
cases prohibited from, participating in the study of such texts.
</P>
<P>
   The new research, conducted by sociologist Steven M. Cohen of
the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, defined Jewish study broadly to
include a variety of learning experiences, including text study,
lecture attendance, and Internet research.
</P>
<P>
   The study, a survey of 1,302 American Jews, found that among all
Jews, the rate of adult Jewish learning is equal among men and
women, but that if the Orthodox and the unaffiliated are excepted,
women are ahead of men. The study found that men continue to have a
slight lead in the study of traditional texts _ a complex pursuit
that generally requires an ability to read Hebrew and Aramaic _ but
that women are ahead in many other types of Jewish learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is significant in that it points to the central role of
women in Jewish life,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   He also cited the influence of the broader Christian society,
saying that ``throughout the West, women are more involved in
churches and religious life.''
</P>
<P>
   The increasing involvement of women in Jewish study is also an
inevitable byproduct of the women's movement, scholars say.
</P>
<P>
   ``As women became more educated secularly, you had rabbis
understanding that if you didn't educate women Jewishly, they were
going to leave the fold,'' said Erica Brown, of the Combined Jewish
Philanthropies of Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The trend can be seen in numerous ways. About 60 percent of the
participants in Me'ah, an intensive adult learning program for Jews
in the Boston area, are women, said David M. Gordis, president of
Hebrew College in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   One leader in the study of rabbinic texts by women is Deborah
Kram of Brookline, who at age 40 left her career as a literary
agent to launch Ma'ayan, a Jewish learning program for women in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have women who are CEOs and doctors and lawyers, in
addition to homemakers, where their general education is
outstanding but they want to catch up on their cultural and
religious heritage,'' she said. ``It has definitely increased my
sense of belonging to the Jewish community to be in touch with
these Jewish texts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
