<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TORPEDOED-SHIP-ART-BO     03-13 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORPEDOED-SHIP-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WHAT SANK THE EAGLE? DIVER SAYS IT WAS GERMAN SUB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a sunny Monday outside Maine's Portland Harbor, World War
II was all but over and the seas were calm when Johnny Breeze, a
machinist aboard the USS Eagle, started working on a crossword
puzzle, and literally got blown out of his shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Breeze and 12 shipmates survived the explosion, but the
remaining 49 crew members went down with the ship on April 23,
1945, just days before the war in Europe ended. The force of the
blast lifted the 200-foot long ship three feet in the air and
snapped it in half.
</P>
<P>
   The blast continues to reverberate 55 years later as relatives
of some victims continue to suspect a Navy coverup.
</P>
<P>
   The US Navy insists that a boiler explosion was to blame. But
Paul Lawton, a diver, wreck researcher and lawyer from Brockton,
Mass. who has spent almost three years sleuthing through records
and interviewing people who remember the blast, is convinced the
ship was hit by a torpedo from a German submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton is trying to raise money for a diving expedition this
summer to inspect the wreck, which lies five miles off Cape
Elizabeth, in about 200 feet of water. He said he hopes to inspect
the boiler, rule it out, and even find shards of the torpedo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Navy, Lawton said, has not made his investigation easy.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago he started writing naval archives for copies of
the Navy's 1945 investigation into the sinking. Each request
brought the same response: Files lost. Then last fall, copies of
all the files he was searching for arrived in an unmarked envelope.
Someone, Lawton concluded, did not want to own up to the Eagle
story.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the question may seem academic; accident or act of war,
it's history. But to the one living survivor and a host of
relatives of those killed, proving the Eagle was torpedoed would
mean that the sailors were victims of enemy action, and entitled to
the Purple Heart.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton's interest in the case was ignited by his friend Robert
Westerlund, a retired Brockton firefighter whose father, Ivar, died
aboard the Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may not realize, despite all the years, how such
emotions can fester,'' Westerlund said. ``I have always lived with
shame that a mistake left Ma on her own to bring up four children.
Now there's hope that Dad did not die in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Matt O'Neal, a Navy spokesman unfamiliar with the
ship, said that while it is difficult to reconstruct events from
more than 50 years ago, the record will be corrected if there is
proof that the Navy has it wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that could obviously include the awarding of Purple
Hearts, an honor we take seriously,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagle was a submarine chaser living out the end of the war
pulling decoy targets for student pilots armed with harmless water
bombs. On April 23, 1945, the Soviets were in Berlin and Adolf
Hitler had disappeared. His U-boat _ or submarine _ fleet was no
longer considered a viable threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had any doubt that the war in Europe was days from
ending,'' recalls Elaine Mitchell of Cherry Hill, N.J. In 1945 she
was 16 years old, her brother, Harold Rodman, was 21 _ ``a
wavy-haired hero,'' she said. Harold had survived invasions of
North Africa, Italy, and France. Just home from Europe, he told his
little sister: ``What could be safer than Portland Harbor?''
</P>
<P>
   Moments before he died, Harold Rodman was aboard a ship idling
between maneuvers. Breeze was in the aft crews quarters with his
puzzle. About the moment Breeze put a match to the Sir Walter
Raleigh tobacco in his pipe, the world blew up. When Breezecame
down from the ceiling, he was shoeless. Scenes come back to him
like images in a film loop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight lunging steps to the ladder . . . 12 steps up . . . a
crew member shouting, `I'm gonna die' . . . no life jackets . . .
crawling up stern.''
</P>
<P>
   With him were four or five mates including Oscar Davis, a friend
and survivor who died a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' Breeze recalls Davis saying to the group as they
paused on the upright stern, ``there's the sub.''
</P>
<P>
   Black and fully surfaced so that the length of its deck was
visible, the U-boat was several hundred yards to the east,
according to Breeze. Then the men jumped into the 38-degree water.
</P>
<P>
   Breeze recalls little after his jump except trying to swim away
before suction pulled him under. He grabbed onto a piece of wood.
About 20 minutes later, the destroyer USS Selfridge, which had been
conducting exercises in the area, arrived and picked up survivors.
Then the Selfridge got one strong ``ping'' on its sonar indicating
a target below. But after several depth charge attacks produced
nothing, the ship returned to Portland. Within an hour of Eagle's
sinking, almost a dozen Navy vessels were sweeping the area, but to
no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days later, a German U-boat sunk a coal freighter off
Newport _ and then got pounced upon and sunk by American
subchasers. (The hulk of the U-853 lies 12 miles off the coast.) By
this time, Breeze was home in Seattle on a leave; he never had to
return because, on May 8, the war in Europe was over _ painfully so
for one Phyllis Westerlund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply regret to inform you,'' the Navy telegram to the wife
of Ivar Westerlund began shortly after the sinking, ``as a result
of an explosion . . . there is no hope for (your husband's)
survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Today she is remarried with a new name and a residence in
Wilksborough, N.C. But she said the memory of the sinking still
affects her deeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall precisely when the Navy officially attributed
the death to a boiler explosion, but it did, and I lived with it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   And as sometimes happens, had it not been for two buddies on bar
stools gabbing away, the matter would have rested there.
</P>
<P>
   On a summer evening in 1997, Robert Westerlund, Ivar's son, and
Paul Lawton, a recreational diver, were drinking beer at Doyle's
Gourmet Deli and Pub in Brockton when Westerlund mentioned what he
considered the ``darnedest curiosity.'' He had grown up thinking an
accident killed his father. But while he was in Rhode Island, he
came across a small history book claiming the U-853 probably sank
the Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton returned home to check his submarine archives. His German
records concurred. Something, indeed, did not add up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mind you, I'm not one of these conspiracy nuts,'' the
36-year-old bachelor explained the other day, sitting on a
living-room rug cluttered with so many nautical charts and plotting
instruments it resembled a ship's navigation room. ``I'm a Yankee,
skeptical until I'm clubbed with facts.''
</P>
<P>
   He put a small classified ad in the Globe 18 months ago asking
for help locating Eagle survivors. A relative in the Boston area
contacted Breeze on the West Coast, who called Lawton and
eventually shared his tale of survival. Breeze's descriptions
matched those of other witnesses; the ferocity of the explosion
simply could not have come from boiler failure, they say. From 1945
until Breeze spoke with Lawton last spring, Breeze had assumed the
Navy attributed the sinking to a torpedo.
</P>
<P>
   When Lawton finally received the Navy's record of the
investigation, he _ a civil litigation lawyer _ immediately spotted
indications that investigators had steered witnesses toward a
mechanical mishap and away from submarines. The telltale kicker was
this: The Navy did not issue any advisories on how a similar
accident could be avoided on other ships.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton's theory?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably total embarrassment by an American commander led to a
coverup,'' Lawton answered. ``Here was a U-boat that had penetrated
defenses at the end of the war, practically docked in Portland,
inflicted casualtites, then scooted away.''
</P>
<P>
   On a wall of Robert Westerlund's living room hangs a framed poem
that concludes:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So goodnight my love, and my children, too
</P>
<P>
   . . . I hope and pray that there will come a day
</P>
<P>
   that I'll be home safely to you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was written by Robert's father and mailed with the last
letter home. A Purple Heart, says Robert, would mean closure. At
least a part of his Dad would be safely home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
