<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5349 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-WEB-SITES-ART-     03-13 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-WEB-SITES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8 WEB SITES MAKE TRAVEL PLANNING SIMPLE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. ONE COLOR SLIDE, AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE, CAN BE
SENT TO YOU ELECTRONICALLY. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER  
 &HT;    There are hundreds of Web sites that claim to make travel
better, cheaper and faster. But no one needs to visit all of them
to plan a trip. The fact is that many of these sites duplicate each
other, others are blatantly commercial and many are just not very
good.
 &HT;    To keep life simple on the Internet, here are eight travel sites
worth bookmarking. They each do one thing very well. But
paradoxically, in doing so, they're the veritable Pandora's box
that a good Web site should also be.
 TRAVELOCITY.COM AND EXPEDIA.COM  
 &HT;    The first thing everyone needs in their travel tool kit is a
proactive site, so start with an online travel agency.
 &HT;    Travelocity.com and Expedia.com are the best of the bunch. Both
of them are easy to use, with relatively uncluttered home pages and
clear graphics. They have information that a user can access at a
glance, without spending a lot of time trying to figure out the
site. At this stage of research, travelers need less to read, not
more.
 &HT;    Both Travelocity.com and Expedia.com have a rare and welcome
professionalism. Their fare-finders, the meat and potatoes of such
sites, allows users to plan round-trip flights, as well as
itineraries with multicity stops.
 &HT;    They give users the power to quickly change the time, date and
airport, and they come loaded with the fares of all the major
carriers, which saves travelers the considerable trouble of
visiting half a dozen airline-owned Web sites in the hunt for the
lowest fare.
 &HT;    Travelocity's ``Been There,'' a section written by Travelocity
employees, is like getting a postcard from a friend reporting on
their trip and brings a welcome narrative voice. Their ``Mountain
Resort Guide'' gives instant fares and snow depths from a home city
to ski destinations.
 &HT;    Users can quickly read the different airline's baggage
restrictions at a glance and learn how to grab the seat of their
choice when they book a flight.
 &HT;    Expedia's Fare Calendar allows users to look months ahead to
find the cheapest fares between two airports. The site's Airport
Survival Guide is an airport-by-airport guide that shows
restaurants, gate locations and airport hotels.
 &HT;    Expedia.com also offers a fare-finder to a vast range of hotels,
thanks to the company's recent acquisition of travelscape.com. They
now have access to thousands of hotels at so-called ``preferred
rates'' of 20 to 70 percent off the published rate.
 &HT;    Their new Golf Travel section, done in conjunction with
TheGolfer.com, means that golfers can book travel and tee time to
more than 11,000 courses around the country.
 SMARTERLIVING.COM  
 &HT;    Most active travelers are already receiving free e-mail
notifications from airlines such as American, Continental,
Northwest, TWA and U.S. Airways.
 &HT;    Every week, these airlines offer many international and domestic
sale fares, mostly last-minute deals for quick getaways. But as
convenient as that may seem, it's still necessary to scroll through
dozens of fares, regulations and restrictions in order to reach
those that apply to a traveler's home airport. That's why every
busy traveler should sign up for free e-mails from
Smarterliving.com (smarterliving.com).
 &HT;    This site culls and collates e-fares from most major carriers
and only sends out those that depart from a single airport or from
multiple airports near the traveler's home.
 &HT;    It also sends out deals from carriers such as Icelandair,
airlines that may not have weekend-only fares but offer
longer-lived specials with fewer restrictions.
 DIGITAL CITY  
 &HT;    Digital City (www.digitalcities.com) is easily the best city
guide on the Web. The site hones in on the dining, shopping and
movie listings for more than 60 cities nationwide, with links to
local papers and local reviewers. It's a great site for travelers
who want to feel like a local.
 &HT;    If someone wants to know what's playing off-Broadway, or when
the Cleveland Indians are in their hometown or where to find the
best Mexican food in Phoenix, this is the place to go.
 QUIKBOOK  
 &HT;    For a city weekend getaway, check out the discount hotel broker
Quikbook (www.quikbook.com). Figure on discounts from 15 to 40
percent off published rates in major U.S. city hotels in 15 cities
(based on availability, of course).
 &HT;    New York, Orlando, San Francisco and Seattle are among the towns
in which they operate. They have competition, of course, like Hotel
Reservations Network (http://www.180096hotel.com), but Quikbook
seems better informed, with a Web site that cuts to the chase.
 CULTUREFINDER.COM  
 &HT;    CultureFinder.com (www.culturefinder.com) can tell travelers
who's starring in the Indiana Repertory Theatre, what the Alhambra
Dinner Theatre in Jacksonville is performing or how to find New
York City Opera tickets, with more than 350,000 events listed.
 FAMILY.COM  
 &HT;    For family travel, Family.com (www.family.com) is Disney's site
and has vacation advice of all kinds, helping parents plan trips by
location and by type. It's smart and savvy, for those traveling
with teens or tots.
 YAHOO.COM  
 &HT;    Finally, for travelers who need to find the British Tourist
Authority, a fly-fishing guide in Montana or a ferry schedule for
Monhegan Island, Maine, there's Yahoo (www.yahoo.com).
 &HT;    Yes, there are loads of other search engines, from Lycos
(www.lycos.com) and Dogpile (www.dogpile.com) to Infoseek
(www.inforseek.com), Ask Jeeves (www.askjeeves,com) and Alta Vista
(www.altavista.com). But Yahoo is a powerful timesaver _ and saving
time is really what it's all about.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Everett Potter is a New York City-based free-lance travel
writer.) 
 ---- 
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
<TEXT>
