a vacation destination because it enables them to immerse
themselves in local culture, try local foods, stay in
bed-and-breakfasts or inns and talk with the people who actually
live and work in the region. It is an intimate form of travel that
stresses camaraderie of small groups and gives those who
participate the feeling of personal accomplishment.
 &HT;    A number of travel companies offer walking journeys. Some
specialize in trips just for those ages 50 and over, or just for
women, while others concentrate on particular regions, such as the
English Lake District, or areas of special interest, such as
gardens, wines or architecture.
 &HT;    Some companies, such as Abercrombie &AMP; Kent, are large; others
are operated by a one-person group leader who has an in-depth
knowledge of a country or a hobby. And the company names are
wonderful: Walking the World, Back Roads, Walk Your Way Into the
Heart of England, Country Walkers, Look Again Tours, English
Ramblers, The Wayfarers.
 TOURS FOR THE SENIOR SET  
 &HT;    Ask your travel agent to help you find the right walking tour
for your interests and abilities. The following companies offer
tours created especially for mature travelers:
 &HT;     _ Walking the World  has hiking trips just for seniors with
destinations that include Utah's parklands, Hawaii's volcanos, New
Zealand's Milford Track and Provence, France, among others. For
more information: (800) 340-9255; www.walkingtheworld.com.
 &HT;     _ Walk Your Way into the Heart of England.  Rosemary Quick, who
grew up in England, leads a few low-key hikes through places such
as the Cotswolds, Dorset Villages and the Lake District. Most trips
are easy _ more like strolls than walks _ and many are described as
``circular walks,'' which means they begin and end in the same
village and average five miles. Quick's walking tours for 2000
start with a trip on the Isle of Wight from May 11 to 22. For more
information: (970) 881-2709; Rosemary Davenport Quick, P.O. Box
231, Red Feather Lakes, Colo. 80545.
 &HT;     _ ElderTreks'  series of worldwide trips, which are limited to
active seniors, often includes backpacking and camping out in
places such as the Australian Outback, Borneo and the Galapagos
Islands. The 2000/2001 brochure showcases 36 trips, each rated by
the level of activity. For more information: (800) 741-7956;
www.eldertreks.com.
 &HT;     _ Mount Robson Adventure Holidays' ``Fifty Plus Adventures'' 
include short scenic walks in the shadow of Canada's highest peak,
plus birdwatching, canoeing and rafting. While tour dates haven't
been finalized for 2000, tours are likely to take place toward the
end of June. Each 14-day trip, priced at $719, double occupancy,
includes a canoe trip, a rafting float trip and guided hikes. For
more information: (250) 566-4386.
 &HT;     _ Nifty Over-Fifty Tours , led by Jan Coyle, bring participants
to New Zealand. This year, Coyle is expanding her company's
offerings with a ``Springtime in Australia'' tour from Oct. 13 to
27. For more information: (650) 595-2090; www.pacificpathways.com.
 &HT;     _ Look Again Tours of Sacramento  offers annual walking trips
to the British Isles for those ages 50 and older. For more
information: (916) 448-7202; e-mail lookagain(AT)midtown.net.
 &HT;     _ Going Places  develops walking trips for women ages 50 to 55.
A dozen walking trips are planned this year, from Scotland on June
2 to Vermont (to see the turning of the leaves) in late September.
 &HT;    The easiest trips offered by Going Places require less than
eight miles of walking per day on flat or rolling terrain. For more
information: (707) 935-0595; www.goingplacestours.com.
 YOUR STAMINA  
 &HT;    Each travel company works hard at educating prospective
tour-goers about the amount of walking that is required for each
trip and the geography to be covered. Many evaluate the difficulty
of their own tours. For example, a typical scale from one of these
companies might rate a trip ``easy'' if it covers four to six miles
per day on gentle terrain, such as the Coast of Maine or the
Galapagos Islands.
 &HT;    A ``moderate'' walking trip might require five to 10 miles of
walking per day over rolling to hilly terrain, with some ascents to
1,200 feet.
 &HT;    A ``challenging'' tour might include six to 12 miles each day
over hilly, rugged terrain that can hit altitudes beyond 1,200
feet. The pace is calculated at about 2.5 miles an hour.
 &HT;    A leader of a well-run tour will match the day's walk to the
group's abilities, weather and the terrain to be found underfoot.
 &HT;    One enthusiast described the lodges where he stayed each night
as ``real hotels'' _ inns or bed-and-breakfast establishments with
an owner on site who knew the area.
 &HT;    Support vans and wagons carry tour-goers' luggage, with one van
often designated as the ``sag wagon'' to transport those who find
the day's activities too rigorous.
 &HT;    Some walking trips are combined with other aspects of travel.
For example, walking tours on the Galapagos Islands are often
combined with island cruises. A walk in the French countryside
might include a barge trip on a river through wine country. Many
walking tours give travelers a day off during the week so that they
can take a tour, ride a boat or rent a car for some personal
explorations.
 &HT;    With nearly 30 million pairs of walking shoes sold in the United
States, and with nearly 15 million Americans claiming to be fitness
walkers, walking tours may very well be the future of leisure
travel.
 &HT;    -----
 SIDEBAR: TRAINING AND GEAR  
 &HT;    _ Before booking any walking tour, consult your doctor about
your physical fitness and the difficulty of your tour of choice.
 &HT;    _ Three to four weeks before the trip, take walking tours of
your own neighborhood in some measured fashion. Use your car's
speedometer to determine the actual length of your walks. These
local strolls will help build your endurance _ and break in your
walking boots.
 &HT;    _ Think about what you'll need to purchase before taking your
tour. Items to consider: a backpack or fanny pack, rain gear, a
camera and binoculars. 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.) 
