<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5361 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CALIF-EXECUTION-HNS &LR;      03-13 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-EXECUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COMMUNITY SHOWS LITTLE SYMPATHY FOR CONVICTED RAPIST, KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COTTONWOOD, Calif. _ There is a short stretch of Interstate 5 in
Northern California that brings back the pain for Sharon and David
Tidwell.
</P>
<P>
   It is a nondescript freeway bridge over a steep ravine just
south of Mount Shasta where 22 years ago the Tidwells' daughter,
Annette Selix, was thrown to her death at age 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't drive by with getting hurt by the memories,'' David
Tidwell said. ``It's just too much for us. I can't bear to go by
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Keith Rich, 45, the man convicted of raping Selix and
then tossing her off the bridge 100 feet to her death, is scheduled
to be executed early Wednesday. He will be the eighth person to die
in California since capital punishment resumed in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Rich grew up about mile from the Tidwells' home in Cottonwood, a
community south of Redding. Plenty of people knew Rich, but no one
knows how he turned out so bad.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1978, he killed Selix and three women and raped
five others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a reign of terror,'' said Shasta County Sheriff's Lt.
Bradd McDannold, who also grew up in Cottonwood and knew both the
Rich and Tidwell families. ``Women were being attacked that summer
at random. He terrorized everyone in this community. People were
panic-stricken. We never had much crime here, and then all the
sudden women are disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many residents of Redding, Cottonwood and other small towns in
Shasta County recall the case.
</P>
<P>
   Rich was adopted and grew up in Cottonwood, an unincorporated
ranching community about 220 miles northeast of San Francisco and
18 miles south of Redding.
</P>
<P>
   McDannold said that Rich's father ran a welding shop and
repaired farm equipment for just about every family in the area.
After high school, Rich worked for his dad and did other odd jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew him,'' McDannold said. ``He did some of the rowdy
things kids do at that age, but there wasn't anything real violent
in his background.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 23-year-old Rich erupted with sexual violence during the
summer of 1978. He started by raping a woman on June 13. Then he
sexually attacked two others in the next two weeks. On July 4, he
committed his fourth rape. Later that day he struck again, this
time killing his victim. He raped Annette Edwards, 19, then bashed
in her skull.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, he grabbed a 15-year-old girl who was riding
her bike in Red Bluff. He raped and beat her, but she survived.
</P>
<P>
   That August, he sexually assaulted and killed two women,
Patricia ``Pam'' Moore, 17, in Redding and Linda Slavik, 27, whom
he met in a bar in Chico. He killed her after showing her Moore's
body.
</P>
<P>
   Slavik's parents, Waldo and Twyla Yates, said they had
nightmares about her death.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Chris Slavik, declined to be interviewed. But he wrote
a letter to the Board of Prison Terms stating his opposition to
Rich's plea for clemency. He was 9 at the time of his mother's
death and spent years in therapy. He said the killing had caused
him to lose both parents because his grief-stricken father had
drifted into a life of alcohol and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Annette Selix was Rich's final victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the one crime that offended people here the most,''
McDannold said. ``How could he kill that little girl?''
</P>
<P>
   McDannold and his colleague Rusty Brewer caught Rich after the
killer reported to the police that he had innocently stumbled onto
the bodies of Slavik and Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't believe him,'' McDannold said. ``We were suspicious
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   They got a detailed confession from Rich 10 days after Selix
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he never told me why,'' McDannold said.
</P>
<P>
   There is little sympathy for Rich in Cottonwood.
</P>
<P>
   The Tidwells, the Yateses and many others testified in favor of
executing Rich in a hearing last week in Sacramento before the
Board of Prison Terms, which then made a confidential
recommendation to Gov. Gray Davis on whether to approve Rich's plea
for clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for me to envision a more worthy candidate for
the death penalty than Mr. Rich,'' said Shasta County District
Attorney McGregor Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, denied the clemency request Friday, making it
nearly certain that Rich will die on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely nothing about Mr. Rich's brutal behavior
that warrants clemency,'' Davis said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   No governor has accepted such a plea in the eight years since
executions have returned to California.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, when the jury convicted Rich and ruled that he
should die, Rich has had little success in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``To even the most hardened eye, the crimes were almost
unimaginably brutal _ savage attacks on defenseless young women,
all sexually ravaged,'' a federal appeals judge, Michael Daly
Hawkins, wrote in a March 1999 ruling upholding Rich's death
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The last Californian to be executed was Manuel Babbitt, killed
by injection last May for killing a 78-year-old Sacramento woman
during a robbery and attempted rape in 1980.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
