<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW AMERICA, SAME OLD POLITICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then there were two. ``Super Tuesday'' has left America,
predictably, with a choice between Al Gore and George W. Bush. They
won by showing that they are regular party animals. And that, for
the United States, is where the problem lies. The country is
undergoing its greatest social and demographic changes in a
century. Neither political party has come to terms with these
changes. Curiously, the oldest man running for president, John
McCain, was the one who most clearly understood the future. But now
he is gone, and it's back to ``politics as usual.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-DINOSAUR-POLITICS-US-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PINOCHET AND CHILE'S UNFINISHED JUSTICE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was not quite the most miraculous recovery since Lazarus. But
when General Augusto Pinochet arose from his wheelchair to greet
his army buddies at Santiago's airport on March 3, he was sprightly
enough to embarrass two governments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CHILE-NEEDS-CLOSURE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TERMS OF ENDEARMENT: SPAIN'S AZNAR DESERVES ANOTHER CHANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the death of General Franco in 1975, Spain has been a
stirring success story and it will surely continue to be so,
whoever wins the general election on March 12. Spain under Jose
Maria Aznar is generally riding high. Politically stable,
economically prosperous, it is gaining respect in the world. Odd,
then, that Aznar is not assured another term. History, it seems,
determines that Spain's heart still beats on the left. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE: March 12 Election, Spain) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-OLE!-JOSE-SPAIN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANGST, NOT AMBITION, GIVES EUROPEAN BANKS THE URGE TO MERGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank's planned takeover of its Frankfurt rival,
Dresdner Bank, to form the largest bank in Europe, is only the
latest in a rash of huge recent deals that have certainly made
investment-banking advisers delirious. But the truth is that the
deals have usually been defensive, done out of fear not ambition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...RE: Deutsche-Dresdner Bank Merger) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-EUROBANK-BLUES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEORGE II VS. ALBERT II: THE DANGER OF DYNASTIC POLITICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Super Tuesday'' saw more than just the triumph of the two
establishment candidates. It saw the triumph of the ultimate
establishment: dynasticism. Political dynasties are in retreat in
most of the rest of the world. The Nehrus no longer rule India.
Britain is retiring its hereditary peers. Indonesia has kissed the
Suhartos goodbye. But in the country that was born of a revolution
against George III, the next presidential election will be fought
between two crown princes, George II and Albert II. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 300 words; 1,100 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-REDWHITE'N'BLUEBLOODS-ECONOMIST-600&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This week's droll ``Primary Color'' column) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Humor, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-PRIMARYCOLOR-COLUMN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LUMBERJACKS, GREENS AT LOGGERHEADS IN NORTHERN MINNESOTA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In local mythology, the vast woods of northern Minnesota were
once patrolled by a huge lumberjack named Paul Bunyan. Legend had
it he was ten times taller than the tallest trees. Now, for more
prosaic reasons, the lumberjack lifestyle that created the myth of
Paul Bunyan is slowly dying out in Minnsota. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Minnesota) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 850 words; 950 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-PAUL-BUNYAN-AXED-MINN-ECONOMIST-850&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFFIRMATIVE ACTION IN FLORIDA: LOOK UNDER THE OTHER BUSH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inside Florida's legislature, he was praised as a visionary
reformer. Outside, he was called a ``crucifier'' and a ``bigot.''
As governor Jeb Bush delivered Florida's annual State-of-the-State
address on March 7, 1,100 angry protestors on the steps of the
Capitol in Tallahassee denounced his One Florida initiative, a plan
to end affirmative action in Florida's colleges. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Florida and Texas Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-JEB-BUSH-RACISM-ECONOMIST-NYTFS &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOOD NEWS: MEXICAN MEDIA ARE GETTING BOLDER, BETTER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The methods of control were more subtle, but Mexico's media long
bore more than a passing resemblance to those of Soviet Russia. No
wonder, then, that for the past seven decades the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) rarely had trouble winning elections or,
when it did, in getting away with fraud. Things are changing
though, and Mexico's media are well on the road to freedom; the
road to quality may prove to be much longer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-PRESS-MEXICO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WILL VENEZUELA'S DISGRUNTLED TROOPS TURN ON CHAVEZ? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Chavez, Venezuela's elected president, first grabbed the
attention of his countrymen in 1992, when as a paratroop
lieutenant-colonel he tried to stage a coup against a democratic
government. Could Chavez himself be ousted by a coup? Such talk
seems premature, but that has not stopped several Venezuelans from
musing aloud about the ironic possibility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-COUP-CARACAS?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10-GALLON CLOUT: TEXAS ART LOSES ITS DRAWL, STANDS TALL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Art boosters in Texas have long boasted that their state was a
``third coast'' of contemporary art in America. Yet they were never
really able to convince New York or California to take them
seriously _ until now. On March 23, the 2000 Biennial Exhibition
opens at the Whitney Museum of American Art in New York. The show
will feature nine artists from the Lone Star State, the largest
number of Texas artists ever in a Biennial, and the largest from
any one state outside of New York and California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Texas Editors...NOTE March 23, N.Y. Biennial) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 50-word trim; 900 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-HOT-TEXAS-ART-ECONOMIST-725&AMP;add-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IF YOU THINK THIS CAMPAIGN IS SLEAZY, CHECK OUT 1948'S &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks this year's American election campaign is
particularly dirty should read a new book, ``American Dreamer: A
Life of Henry A. Wallace,'' and think again. When Henry Wallace,
Franklin D. Roosevelt's third-term vice president, had the temerity
to break away from the Democratic Party and run on the Progressive
ticket in 1948, he was ruthlessly demonized as a wild-eyed fanatic
bent on destroying the American way of life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary, Book Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-DIRTY-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOBILE INTERNET: A MATCH MADE IN HEAVEN _ AND JAPAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nobody doubts it anymore. The marriage of the mobile telephone
and the Internet is a match made in heaven. Hardly a day passes in
America and Europe without an announcement of a new alliance
between dot.coms, telecoms firms and computer companies, all
jostling for advantage in the brave new world around the corner.
Yet, despite the buzz, the embarrassing truth is that while the
Americans and Europeans have been talking, NTT DoCoMo, Japan's
dominant mobile operator, has been doing: turning the wireless
Internet into reality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 600 words; 1,350 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WIRELESS-WEB-400&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GERMAN GENDER-BENDERS: BREAKING THE POLITICAL GLASS CEILING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, there is only one serious candidate left in the running
for the leadership of Germany's Christian Democratic Union (CDU).
After the withdrawal on March 5 of Volker Ruhe, Angela Merkel, the
party's general secretary, has become the hot favorite among the
rank and file. But in the eyes of the CDU leadership and of its
conservative Bavarian sister party, Mrs. Merkel suffers from two
grave drawbacks: she comes from the former communist east, and _
god forbid _ she is a woman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-`FRAU'-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE INTERNET AND FRENCH CULTURE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than any other medium in recent years, the Internet is
challenging France's vigilant attempts to control and protect its
culture. This is, after all, a cyberworld dominated by the English
language, in which French is used by only 1.2 percent of the
world's Web sites and even fewer of all international online
forums. ``Mon Dieu! To the barricades!'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CYBER-CULTUREKILLER-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARTIANS: COMING SOON TO A SCREEN NEAR YOU &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood is going out of this world. On March 10, ``Mission to
Mars,'' the first of several forthcoming Martian movies, opened in
cinemas across America. For the growing ``Mars advocacy'' movement,
these movies are more than mere entertainment. They are also a
valuable opportunity to capitalize on public interest in all things
Martian to raise support _ and cash _ for exploration of the red
planet itself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 325 words; 1,200 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-`MARS-FEVER'-700&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: This material is NOT available to clients in Canada
except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
