<SLUG> BC-OLE!-JOSE-SPAIN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERMS OF ENDEARMENT: SPAIN'S AZNAR DESERVES ANOTHER CHANCE  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE March 12 Election)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796.)  
  
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the death of dour General Franco in 1975, Spain has been a
stirring success story and it will surely continue to be so,
whoever wins the general election on March 12.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the success is that, perhaps for the first time,
few Spaniards truly tremble at the prospect of a victory by their
political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   It is a safe bet that neither Jose Maria Aznar's ruling
center-right People's Party nor decent Joaquin Almunia's Socialists
on the center-left would squander the gains of the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Socialists under Felipe Gonzalez who really got Spain
going in the 1980s, before their 14-year reign eventually dissolved
in a morass of corruption (involving, among other things,
government-linked death squads).
</P>
<P>
   It was Gonzalez who took Spain into NATO and the European Union,
and who set about freeing the economy and selling off the state. He
spruced up his party, dragged it to the middle ground and did much
to heal the wounds of history.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar has done just as well. He too has been sensitive to
history. He has continued to liberalize, while maintaining a
remarkable degree of social peace.
</P>
<P>
   He has piloted his country into Europe's single currency. And he
has reduced Spain's awful unemployment rate from 23 percent when he
took office to (a still painful) 15 percent: as many jobs have been
created in Spain under Aznar as in the rest of the EU.
</P>
<P>
   The average Spaniard is still appreciably poorer than the
average European, but the gap is closing steadily.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar, who was a provincial taxman before he entered politics,
lacks the fizz and personality of Gonzalez, and he can be ruthless.
But he is pretty straight. And he sets about the job with a
seriousness and single-mindedness that have suited the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when Aznar was bidding for power, the left
sought to paint his lot as crypto-Francoists who would slash
welfare, hurt pensioners, puff up the rich, strengthen the hand of
the Castilian center at the expense of Spain's twitchy regions,
kill off failing state businesses wholesale, and provoke
confrontation with trade unionists on the barricades.
</P>
<P>
   None of this has happened.
</P>
<P>
   Heading only a minority government, Aznar has cooperated warily
with moderate Catalan nationalists to keep his party in power. He
has gone to great lengths to build a consensus for his reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if anything, he has been too cautious over such issues
as welfare, labor law and the tax system. If he wins again, he
should be more daring.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar's main failure has been his inability to solve the Basque
problem. Admittedly, this is not easy. Over the years, the Basques,
Catalans and others on Spain's rim have been given a large measure
of autonomy; there is not much more to give.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some Basques are still not satisfied; indeed, a minority are
prepared to pursue the goal of outright independence, against the
wishes of the majority, by murder.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for any democrat to deal with such people.
Still, Aznar may have been too inflexible during a cease-fire by
the terrorists. He has refused to grant a referendum on what Basque
nationalists call self-determination, which they would lose if it
meant full independence.
</P>
<P>
   The constitution, he says, decrees that the Spanish state must
remain unitary _ and that is that.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Aznar has let the moderate Basque nationalists, who
are essential partners in any settlement, move closer to the
terrorists, to whom he refuses to talk unless they first disavow
violence completely.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins, he should quietly acknowledge that the terrorists
do, unfortunately, stand for a sizeable minority of Basques
(perhaps between a sixth and a seventh of the total, though their
boycott of this weekend's election means it will be impossible to
assess their true electoral strength); that they cannot be dealt
with purely by military means; and that the moderate nationalists
must again be solicited as crucial interlocutors.
</P>
<P>
   But in most other respects, Spain under Aznar is riding high. It
is a confident, modern-minded country that fights its corner in the
European Union with vigor and effectiveness. Politically stable,
economically prosperous, it is gaining respect in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Odd, then, that Aznar is not assured of another term. History,
it seems, determines that Spain's heart still beats on the left.
</P>
<P>
   An electoral pact between the Socialists and the Communists,
mortal enemies in Gonzalez's time, may help to broaden the appeal
of the left. The left may even win, though most opinion polls doubt
it. That would be a pity, though not a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar deserves another term. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
