<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Humor, Political Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796.)  
  
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WINNERS AND LOSERS: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``He was grinning so broadly I thought he might eat the
camera.'' (Slate's David Plotz on George W. Bush) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He won. I lost.'' (Bill Bradley) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPTIMISTIC CHORUS OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``We get knocked down, but we get up again.'' (From
``Tubthumping,'' a song chosen at John McCain's ``victory'' party
in Los Angeles) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS.COM: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Democrats made history by becoming the first Americans
to vote over the Internet in a legally binding election. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS.CON: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In a series of advertisements in New York state, Bush supporters
lambasted John McCain for voting against breast-cancer research and
not caring about the environment. Bush's own state, Texas, has one
of the worst records in the country on both counts. McCain, whose
sister had breast cancer, voted against the research money only
because it had been smuggled into a military spending bill. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSHISM OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A Canadian comic, Rick Mercer, posing as a reporter, informed
George Bush that the Canadian prime minister, ``Jean Poutine,'' had
endorsed him. ``I appreciate his strong statement,'' said Bush,
``he understands I believe in free trade.'' Canada's prime minister
is Jean Chretien; Poutine is a popular fast food in Quebec,
involving gravy and cheese curd. Foreign prime ministers do not
tend to endorse American presidential candidates. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAGNANIMOUS GESTURE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Falwell, whom John McCain denounced as an ``agent of
intolerance,'' said that ``Senator McCain would make a great
presidential running mate'' for Bush. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROFOUND ENDORSEMENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing real good. We're eating every day.'' _ Roy
Sensabaugh, a retired soldier, on why he voted for Al Gore.
(Associated Press) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROMANTIC OPPORTUNITY OF THE WEEK (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones III, president of Bob Jones University, announced that
the college will end its ban on interracial dating (provided the
cross-daters get their parents' written permission). George W. Bush
was criticized for failing to condemn the rule when he spoke at the
South Carolina university. (CNN, March 3) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROMANTIC OPPORTUNITY OF THE WEEK (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is a babe'': a poster spotted at a rally in Boston over
the weekend, where, according to The Associated Press, the vice
president sported a pullover that ``showed off the fruits of his
sit-ups.'' According to Amy Margolius, owner of the poster, ``He is
a babe. He's a smart and a handsome man. He's basically everything
you want a man to be.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROMANTIC LIMITATION OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Voting 61 percent to 39 percent, Californians approved
Proposition 22, which limits legal marriage to only ``a man and a
woman.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
