<P>
   &UR; TRIBUNE-TIMES MIRROR &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 1{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the purchase by The Tribune Co. of the Times Mirror Co.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR (Undated) _ The Tribune Co., owner of The
Chicago Tribune, will acquire The Times Mirror Co., owner of The
Los Angeles Times, for $6.4 billion, before the assumption of about
$1.4 billion in debt. The Tribune's offer is for about $95 a share
in stock and cash, double the Tribune's closing price on Friday.
The first half of the offer will be in cash, and the rest offers
2.5 shares of Tribune for each share of Times MIrror. The
acquisition will end the confrontational reign of Mark Willes at
Times Mirror. It will create a company with daily newspapers in the
three biggest United States markets and some overlaps in newspaper
and television markets. By Felicity Barringer and Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics and map.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-HISTORY (Los Angeles) _ The Tribune-Times Mirror deal
joins two venerable newspaper companies: Times Mirror, owned for a
century by the Otis and Chandler families, and Tribune, shaped for
much of this century by Col. Robert R. McCormick. The companies
have followed parallel paths for much of their existence. By Todd
S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-MADIGAN (Chicago) _ A look at Jack Madigan, the chief
executive of Tribune, who with this deal becomes a much more
visible figure in the media world, and what he plans to do with the
combined operations. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-IMPACT (Undated) _ A look at how the deal is likely to
affect other major players in the newspaper industry.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-TERMS (Undated) _ Looking at the details of the Tribune
offer for Times Mirror. By Floyd Nottis.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The advertising industry looks at
the Times Mirror-Tribune merger. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RECESSION (Tokyo) _ Japan slipped back into a recession in
the fourth quarter of last year, falling 1.4 percent in real terms
as consumers clamped their wallets closed and public works projects
stalled. The drop came in spite of astonishingly robust capital
spending by businesses. It was the biggest fall since the economy
sank 2 percent in the spring of 1997 and the third largest
contraction since World War II. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-EUROPE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ European leaders are expected
to endorse Germany's new candidate, Horst Kohlers, for president of
the International Monetary Fund. This is no surprise, but there are
questions about how solidly are they behind Kohlers and about
whether the United States will go along this time. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   CDNOW (Undated) _ CDnow, Time Warner and Sony have called off
their plan to merge Columbia House with CDnow to create a publicly
traded company. CDnow said it planned to cut costs by a third and
would explore its strategic options.
</P>
<P>
   FIAT-GM (Turin, Italy ) _ Fiat is expected to announce that it
has agreed to establish ties with General Motors. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The Dow Jones industrial average was up 27
points at noon, while the Nasdaq index was down 70, about 1.4
percent. The 30-year Treasury bond was up 18/32, yielding 6.14
percent.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-IPO (Undated) _ The NASD announces a vote on the plan to
sell shares in the Nasdaq stock market. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   SCHWAB-USTRUST (New York) _ The acquisition of U.S. Trust by
Charles Schwab, which would create the first of a new breed of
financial holding companies, is being opposed by a New York
activist group on the grounds that U.S. Trust's community
investment has been inadequate. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   AETNA (Undated) _ Developments in the wake of Aetna's decision
to split its operations instead of being acquired. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   I2-ASPECT (Undated) _ I2, whose software links manufacturers to
suppliers, has agreed to buy the Internet-commerce software maker
Aspect Development for $9.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Shanghai) _ China says it will seek to enter the
World Trade Organization with or without support from the U.S.
Congress, a move that is sure to put pressure on United States
legislators to approve permanent normal trade relations and weakens
Washington's ability to influence China on such sensitive subjects
as reunification with Taiwan. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Bankers say Sanwa Bank is in the final
stages of negotiations on joining forces with Asahi Bank and Tokai
Bank, which previously announced their intention to merge. If the
amalgamation takes place, it would create the second-largest bank
in terms of assets after the Mizuho Financial Group, which will
come to life this fall when Fuji Bank, the Industrial Bank of Japan
and Dai-Ichi Kangyo merge. It would mean that in less than one
year, the ranks of large Japanese ``city'' banks has started
shrinking to five from nine. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Acting President Vladimir Putin
announces the capture of Salman Raduyev, a notorious Chechen
warlord. The Announcement comes after string of setbacks for
Russian forces in Chechnya. By Michael R. Gordon.
