suffers its biggest one-day point drop ever on fears that governing
Nationalists will lose the presidential election on Saturday. By
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ATTACK (Dateline to kum) _ Half a dozen mortar round
slammed into a Tehran residential building next to a Revolutionary
Guards base on Monday and Iraq-based rebels claimed responsibility.
The attack was the second violent incident in the Iranian capital
in two days, following the attempted assassination on Sunday of a
leading reformer and close ally of President Mohammad Khatami. By
John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-POLITICS (Jerusalem) _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak faces
three no-confidence votes in Parliament, two from the right and one
from the left. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-ISRAEL (Jerusalem) _ Caught in a dispute over where Jesus
was baptized, Pope John Paul II will visit what Israel says is the
site as well as the place Jordan says is the site. By Joel
Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-REFORM (Austin, Texas) _ For Gov. George W. Bush, reform
has been a matter of legislative proposals rather than an
overriding political philosophy, which might explain why few people
in Texas would have picked the word reformer when asked to describe
the governor. ``He's an incremental change specialist,'' said Bruce
Buchanan, a political scientist at the University of Texas,
``sometimes in a partisan way, like tort reform, which is a big
business issue, sometimes in a bipartisan way, such as small
changes in education.'' For Bush, success has come when changes
have been modest or when he has not had to buck political interests
or popular will. When he has been boldest, he has fallen short of
his goals. By Jim Yardley and Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
