<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-CLARENCE-DARROW-HNS &LR;      03-13 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLARENCE-DARROW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     YESTERYEAR HOLDS LESSONS FOR THE `NEW ERA' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CYNTHIA BASS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ A new century, a glowing economy and
ever-expanding technological innovation are giving many Americans
not only a sense of optimism but the conviction we live in a
brand-new era.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas _ information technology, biotech _ this is
certainly true. But a look at the social problems that continue to
plague us should temper this optimism and this conception of
``newness.'' Technology can change human life _ but not human
nature.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why so many ``new era'' problems (the World Trade
Organization demonstrations, the ``digital divide,'' Internet
pornography, violent and alienated youth, convictions reversed
after DNA testing, school vouchers) are really just different
versions of the same concerns (labor rights, crime and punishment,
freedom of speech, separation of church and state, racism) that
have troubled this country for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the anniversary of the death of Clarence Darrow,
regarded by many as America's greatest lawyer and a man whose cases
and crusades remind us how intractable our ``new era'' problems
really are.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Seward Darrow (1857-1938) was born in Kinsman, Ohio.
Named after abolitionist William Seward, he grew up in a home that
became a stop on the Underground Railway for which fugitive slaves
escaped the South. After one year of law school, he passed the Bar
and moved to Chicago, where he remained for the rest of his life,
becoming _ like all good people _ a passionate Cubs fan.
</P>
<P>
   Darrow's conversion from a well-paid corporate lawyer to a
defender (often unpaid) of labor rights took place at the time of
America's first large-scale labor unrest (the Pullman strike,
1894).
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the soaring rhetoric of strike leader Eugene V.
Debs, he switched sides, defending Debs against a trumped-up
contempt charge. It was his first big case and, although Debs got
six months in jail, Darrow emerged as the lawyer for workers. The
rights he championed back then echo the demands for ``international
labor standards'' heard last year during world trade protests in
the streets of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Darrow's greatest cases all took place in the 1920s. The first,
Leopold and Loeb, is eerily familiar: two young men (17 and 18
years old) _ rich, brilliant and ``alienated'' _ confessed to
brutally killing a 14-year-old boy ``for the sake of a thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   The question was not the boys' guilt, but their punishment _ the
death penalty or life imprisonment. Darrow, who opposed the death
penalty no matter how onerous the crime, took the case.
</P>
<P>
   Today, psychiatric testimony is a given; in 1924, when Darrow
introduced it, it was exotic _ hypnotic, too, as many people heard
for the first time of Freud, and terms like ``split personality''
and ``the unconscious'' became what ``DNA evidence'' is for us
today.
</P>
<P>
   Darrow, arguing that interior forces beyond the murderers'
control had driven them to kill, succeeded in saving them from
hanging.
</P>
<P>
   The 1925 ``Monkey Trial'' was Darrow's most famous case. Again
the issue is familiar: teaching evolution in public schools.
Opposing Darrow was William Jennings Bryan, three-time presidential
candidate and one of the great orators of his day.
</P>
<P>
   Darrow did not argue whether teacher John Scopes had taught
evolution _ everyone knew he had _ but whether the state, in
forbidding him to do so, had violated the idea of separation of
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to present any expert witnesses on evolution, Darrow
eventually put Bryan himself on the stand _ ``the most amazing
court scene in Anglo-Saxon history,'' wrote the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   But Bryan's testimony was stricken from the record (a fact
seldom remembered), and the jury, at Darrow's request, found Scopes
guilty (another fact not remembered). This meant the
constitutionality of the law could be appealed. The case was
eventually dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, Darrow embarked on what he considered his most
important trial _ the Sweet murder trial. Here, as with Rodney
King, Amadou Diallo (or even O.J. Simpson), the issue was race.
</P>
<P>
   Ossian Sweet was a black dentist who bought a house in a white
Detroit neighborhood. The first night, an unfriendly white crowd
gathered out front; anticipating this, Sweet had armed himself. The
second night, a larger crowd showed up, and when rocks began
flying, shots were fired from Sweet's house and a white man was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in Sweet's house was arrested and charged with
first-degree murder. The NAACP asked Darrow to head the defense.
</P>
<P>
   His defense was straightforward. This case, he said, was a case
of racial hatred, pure and simple; had the defendants been white,
and shot a black man, ``they would have been given medals.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, having bravely faced down a mob, they were now facing
prison. A first jury deadlocked; a second jury found the first
defendant not guilty, and the other 10 were never tried.
</P>
<P>
   Darrow's trials demonstrate that, in terms of social problems,
not only do we most certainly not live in a ``new era,'' but that
our social problems, new era or old, will not be easily solved.
There is however, an optimistic spin to all this. Clarence Darrow's
long life is a tribute to what we can do if we dedicate ourselves
to the slow, good fight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cynthia Bass is a historian and columnist for the San Francisco
Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1422EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
