<P>
   NASA-MISSIONS (Undated) _ NASA is to release its assessment of
its ``faster, cheaper'' policy of space exploration. Some critics
say the policy has led to such disasters as the failed Mars Climate
Orbiter mission. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Nasdaq composite index closed above
5,000 last week, reaching that milestone just 10 weeks after
hitting the 4,000 mark and four months after surpassing 3,000. The
rapid ascent of the index should have devout index investors
wondering how they can get in on the action. And who wouldn't want
to? By SHANNON BUGGS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BARLOW-COLUMN (Undated) _ Mass production is dying. We're
entering the era of mass customization. No more one-size-fits-all
products. Each must be tailored to fit the needs and desires of the
individual customer. Businesses must learn all about customers for
mass customization to work. At the same time, businesses must
respect the privacy of their customers. By JIM BARLOW. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Vice President Gore has challenged
Gov. George W. Bush to twice-weekly debates from now until Election
Day, surely too much of a good thing. There's a catch, of course.
Gore's offer was conditioned on Bush's agreement to abandon those
30-and 60-second attack ads. Bush isn't biting; he loves those ads
and he is not keen on debating Gore, a master of the form. Pushing
the idea can make Gore look aggressive and Bush defensive, but
keeping it up until November might drive us all nuts. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Sedona, Ariz.) _ The town hall meeting will
never replace the television commercial as the main weapon of the
modern presidential campaign, and that's too bad. Issues and
presidential qualifications aside, John McCain made a commendable
contribution to this year's White House race if for no other reason
than he invited thousands of people _ from all walks of life and
political persuasions _ to come ask him questions. By CLAY ROBISON.
(Already filed.)
</P>
