   SONDHEIM ON THE MUSICAL THEATER HE HAS OUTLIVED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SONDHEIM-CENTERPIECE-NYTSF _ Stephen Sondheim, who turns 70 on
March 22, was so obscure in 1957 that he wasn't even mentioned in
The New York Times review of ``West Side Story.'' He is now the
greatest and perhaps best-known artist in the American musical
theater. But that is a somewhat empty distinction. Sondheim may be
the last major creator of Broadway musicals. He may have even
outlived the genre, which was long ago exiled by rock music from
center stage to niche status in American culture and is now barely
a going concern. By Frank Rich. (From The New York Times magazine.)
Also moved in ``c'' news file.
