rivals, is stiff and awkward. But does the important work of the
presidency resemble an hour of jousting in 45-second sound bites?
Or does it resemble the collaborative synthesis and private,
individual negotiation at which Bush excels? The good news for Bush
is that there's a case to be made for the latter theory. The bad
news is that this case will have to be made in formal settings
under hostile fire and that he's the one who will have to make it.
