<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5552 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-INFECTIONS-HOME-N     03-13 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INFECTIONS-HOME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH CARE GOES HOME, AND SO DO INFECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Carter always knows when the problem is coming back. Carter,
a 48-year-old quadriplegic who uses a catheter to empty his
bladder, begins to feel fatigued. His urine changes in appearance.
And his muscles start going into spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Then he knows it is time to call the doctor for another round of
antibiotics to combat yet another infection.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who lives outside of Kansas City, Mo., receives most of
his medical care at home, including regular changes of the
catheter, which causes the infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens to me many times at home,'' Carter said. ``You can
get those same hospital bugs at home just as easily as you can
anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, federal health officials issued a warning: as health
care moves increasingly from the hospital to the living room,
infection, the bane of the medical institution, is moving with it.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
speaking at a conference in Atlanta on health-care-related
infections, said that in a single month last year, about 16 percent
of 5,148 patients who received home care in Missouri had
infections, a rate that would mean that at least 800,000 such
patients a year get infections.
</P>
<P>
   And as managed care forces patients out of the hospitals
earlier, infections will occur increasingly not in hospitals, where
they can be more quickly treated, but in homes where patients may
be seen only occasionally by health professionals, the federal
health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting family members to serve as home health aides,
without training,'' said Dr. Julie Gerberding, director of the
agency's Hospital Infection Program.
</P>
<P>
   Often, health care workers say, patients are discharged from
hospitals even though their homes might be unsuitable, and the
patients and their families might lack the basic skills needed to
prevent or recognize infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have so many other issues: sanitation, pets, rodents,
insects,'' said Carolyn Crumley, a clinical nurse specialist in
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   From 1992 to 1996, the last year for which figures are
available, the number of patients discharged from home health care
grew by 150 percent, while the number of agencies providing the
services grew by more than half, to about 11,400, a trend likely to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   About 8 million Americans received care in their homes in 1996.
Some, like Carter, who hurt himself in 1980 while diving, have
spinal injuries. Many receive chemotherapy, others are recovering
from heart attacks or have diseases like multiple sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   Most agree that home treatment is good for patients who are not
in acute need, since people are usually happier and heal better
with their families. Mary St. Pierre, vice president of the
National Association for Home Care, defended the safety of her
profession. But she agreed that for home care to work, patients and
the families should be properly educated.
</P>
<P>
   Infection-control specialists said about 10 percent of home care
patients have invasive medical devices, including catheters,
feeding tubes and respirators that can be ideal gateways for
infection. Other patients are sent home with open wounds.
</P>
<P>
   One study presented at last week's conference found that
although catheterized patients were at higher risk for infection,
they received about the same number of medical visits to their
homes as patients without such devices.
</P>
<P>
   The infections can range from relatively minor localized
inflammations to life-threatening blood infections.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Maddox, a registered nurse in Missouri said that if nurses
followed good practices, especially aggressive sterilization,
patients were less likely to develop infections at home.
</P>
<P>
   But it can be a challenge, she said. Because of managed care,
nurses see ``people coming home much sicker, and much sooner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
