 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Jennifer Love Hewitt in a scene from
``Audrey Hepburn.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Jennifer Love Hewitt is having a diva moment. So far today she's
slapped a co-star and screamed at her director, and when a teen-age
girl shoves an autograph book at her, Hewitt curses, turns and ...
not!
 &HT;    No way. Couldn't be. Not our Love.
 &HT;    And indeed it isn't, because the actress who prefers to be
addressed as ``Love'' is generally agreed to suit the name
perfectly. In an industry rife with back-stabbing and rampant egos,
Hewitt has a reputation as a genuinely nice young woman, and she
likes it that way.
 &HT;    ``The greatest honor, better than any award you could be given,
is people thinking you're genuinely nice,'' says the star of
television's ``Time of Your Life'' and the ``I Know What You Did
Last Summer'' slasher flicks.
 &HT;    ``I try hard to be nice,'' she adds. ``I like people, and I
guess that comes out. People say the nicest things to me. I don't
know if I deserve it, but I completely appreciate it, and it sticks
in my heart for days when I'm having a tough time. Those comments
keep me going.''
 &HT;    Besides, she says by telephone from the Los Angeles set of
``Time of Your Life,'' she hasn't got much to get upset about.
 &HT;    ``If you look at my life,'' she says, ``it's pretty amazing.
I've gotten opportunities that most people never get in their life,
and I'm only 21.
 &HT;    ``I work with great people,'' Hewitt says. ``I have the most
wonderful family and friends around me _ for me to pull a diva
stunt would be completely out of the ordinary.''
 &HT;    And then the actress giggles.
 &HT;    ``That's not to say it won't happen one day,'' she confides,
``or to say I don't get in bad moods or don't get snippy or crabby
at times. But the extreme diva-ness you hear about is not me, and I
sure hope it never becomes me.
 &HT;    ``If it does,'' she adds, ``I know I have a lot of people around
me who will line up to slap me right across the face and say, `Get
out of it!'''
 &HT;    Playing a bitch, however, is another story.
 &HT;    ``I would love that,'' she says enthusiastically. ``I would love
that. I'm getting ready to play not the sweetest person in the
world.''
 &HT;    That would be in the upcoming comedy ``The Breakers,'' in which
Sigourney Weaver and Hewitt co-star as mother-and-daughter con
artists.
 &HT;    ``I play this really sexy con artist with a huge attitude and a
big chip on her shoulder,'' Hewitt says. ``It's going to be fun to
have a little bit of attitude.
 &HT;    ``I'll just use PMS 24 hours a day.''
 &HT;    For her most current project, however, Hewitt put on her angel
face and an executive producer's hat: She plays the title character
in ABC's ``The Audrey Hepburn Story,'' a three-hour-long biography
of the Hollywood legend that will air March 27.
 &HT;    ``It was a huge challenge, a huge decision and a huge
responsibility,'' Hewitt says, ``but I knew it was an opportunity
that would only come around once. It had always been my dream to
get to play Audrey one day in her life story, because she was my
favorite as an actor and a woman. She inspired me to act and to try
to be the adult I'm hopefully becoming.
 &HT;    ``It was a huge deal,'' the actress says. ``I'm incredibly
scared about people seeing it, but I'm also excited. I gave all of
myself, every single day, to every word that came out of my
mouth.''
 &HT;    The film follows Hepburn from her painful childhood in
Nazi-occupied Holland to her early success in Tinseltown. Along the
way, Hewitt recreates the Broadway production of Colette's ``Gigi''
(1951) and the classic film ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' (1961). She
croons ``Moon River,'' and slips into Hepburn's glamorous dresses
and hairstyles.
 &HT;    ``If I've done my job, nobody will know it's me after the first
15 minutes,'' Hewitt says. ``They'll just know it's her story.
 &HT;    ``I hope people go away from it wanting to rent every single one
of her movies at the video store the following weekend,'' she adds
exuberantly. ``For the people my age who don't know who Audrey
Hepburn is _ and you'd be surprised how many there are _ I hope
they'll want to know more about her, that they'll also go and rent
her movies.
 &HT;    ``She was a truly amazing person who handled her entire life
with elegance and grace,'' Hewitt says. ``She always accepted life
as what it was and dealt with each situation at hand, and she also
gave back as much as she got.''
 &HT;    Not long after ``Audrey Hepburn'' airs, the ``Summer of Love''
will kick off. That's the tag Fox has given to its concerted effort
to save ``Time of Your Life,'' the struggling ``Party of Five''
spinoff in which Hewitt continues as Sarah Reeves, now far from
home in the wilds of New York City.
 &HT;    The show, despite debuting to surprisingly positive reviews,
quickly went south in the ratings. Hewitt and her co-stars are
still shooting episodes, however, and Fox will relaunch the series
when the weather warms up.
 &HT;    ``What's going right is that we're working really hard to make
good episodes and we're having a good time,'' Hewitt says. ``What's
going wrong ... ''
 &HT;    Hewitt giggles nervously.
 &HT;    `` ... is getting people to watch,'' she admits after a pause.
``It's a spinoff, with a character people are used to suddenly in a
different place, with new people and doing different things.
 &HT;    ``Fox is behind us,'' she says. ``They're willing to move us to
a new time slot, to take us off the air so our episodes aren't
wasted now. We're hopeful we'll get picked up for another season,
but if we don't everyone will go on and do other things.
 &HT;    ``There's nothing we can do about it,'' she concludes. ``We've
got a positive attitude and hope things turn out the way they're
supposed to.''
 &HT;    Between films, television movies and the series, Hewitt is so
busy these days that she hardly has time for a personal life. She
and MTV host Carson Daly broke up several months ago, but Hewitt
did manage to make time for a family trip to Las Vegas to toast her
21st birthday.
 &HT;    ``It balances out,'' she says. ``I find time for a personal life
when I need one.''
 &HT;    Right now, though, Hewitt is needed back on the set of her show.
 &HT;    ``I think I'm in a good place,'' she says in conclusion.
``Truly, the only thing I've ever wanted was to continue to work
and to be happy. I want to work on things I believe in, that I can
be proud of. So far I've been able to do that.
 &HT;    ``I do think I'm in a transitional place, though,'' Hewitt says.
``I'm at that fine line between teen actress and adult actress. I'm
trying to glide into adult actress gracefully, so that I have a
long, sustaining place in this business.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
