w e BC-JOHN-CUSACK-IN-HIGH-F     03-13 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN-CUSACK-IN-HIGH-FIDELITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN CUSACK: A DIFFERENT SLANT ON STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of John Cusack with Iben Hjejle in a scene
from ``High Fidelity.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    He doesn't have a paycheck like Jim Carrey's. He doesn't have
clout like Harrison Ford's. He doesn't draw the paparazzi like Brad
Pitt.
 &HT;    And that's fine with John Cusack, who says the last thing he
wants is to be a superstar.
 &HT;    ``Celebrity can be sinister,'' the 33-year-old actor says.
``Celebrity is death. Celebrity is actually the worst thing that
can happen to an actor.''
 &HT;    After 17 years in the business, Cusack admits that he's still
uncomfortable with the hoopla.
 &HT;    ``Everyday people think their sorrows and joys aren't as
important as George Clooney's sorrows or mine,'' he says. ``People
think the laws of gravity don't really apply to actors. It's like
we breathe this rarefied air.''
 &HT;    His limited experience with fame is more than enough, the
Chicago-based actor insists.
 &HT;    ``I've been the guy on the cover of those magazines,'' he says,
``and I've slept with some of the girls on the covers of those
magazines. It's all designed to create envy, because no one really
exists in that form. I don't walk around perfectly lit and
airbrushed _ no one says just the right thing at just the right
times.
 &HT;    ``Life is complicated and messy.
 &HT;    ``I've also read those magazines when I'm on the cover,'' he
adds. ``I've said, `Oh, God, I seem so interesting _ I must really
be an amazing guy. Maybe I should hang out with myself a little
more.'
 &HT;    ``Or at least I'd like to meet that guy, because what they've
portrayed isn't the real me.''
 &HT;    The real Cusack is brash, bold, outspoken and offbeat, arriving
for an interview at New York's Regency Hotel wearing his trademark
``gangster'' look _ dark jeans, heavily tinted glasses and a long,
black trench coat that he won't take off for the next 45 minutes.
 &HT;    More than a few critics have called him the best actor of his
generation, but Cusack doesn't want to play that part.
 &HT;    ``I would rather have someone say, `the only actor of his
generation who hasn't sold out,''' he says. ``By selling out, I
mean crashing cars, pulling out guns, killing people _ stupid,
mindless scripts. That's what I never want to do.''
 &HT;    What he's doing these days is a low-budget comedy called ``High
Fidelity,'' opening March 31. The movie, which he calls ``a
romantic film about unromantic things,'' reunites him with director
Stephen Frears, with whom he worked on ``The Grifters'' (1990), and
the ``Grosse Point Blank'' (1997) writing team of D.V. DeVincentis
and Steve Pink.
 &HT;    Based on the best-selling novel by Nick Hornby, the movie casts
Cusack as the owner of a small, all-vinyl record store in Chicago.
 &HT;    ``I play someone who considers himself the ultimate connoisseur
of all music,'' the actor says, ``He's a guy who is a totally
obsessive music geek.
 &HT;    ``He's at this weird point where a guy realizes that he's not a
kid anymore,'' Cusack says, ``and he must re-evaluate his entire
life to this point, including what music and women have meant to
him.''
 &HT;    As the film's co-producer, he could also call upon his friends _
including Tim Robbins, Jack Black, Beverly D'Angelo, Harold Ramis
and Catherine Zeta-Jones _ to take supporting parts. His sister
Joan also shows up, as does Bruce Springsteen in his first-ever
film cameo.
 &HT;    It's a typically offbeat role for an actor who has made a habit
of turning down commercially promising films, including ``Apollo
13'' (1995), ``Sleeping With the Enemy'' (1991) and ``Indecent
Proposal'' (1993).
 &HT;    ``I look at acting like some sort of weird marathon,'' he says.
``You have to pace yourself to keep going for a long time.''
 &HT;    Going the commercial route, he believes, would endanger his
hopes for a long, productive career.
 &HT;    ``I'm pretty good at seeing the cycles of this stuff,'' Cusack
says. ``Every two years you're the flavor of the month again.
Everyone sings your praises and you're the next greatest thing _
again. Then next month there's someone else.
 &HT;    ``I don't even remember who was flavor of the year last year,''
he says. ``It doesn't matter. I want to build a body of work. I
don't think talent is enough _ you also must have integrity in this
business. You need a special sensibility to do this work, which is
a certain unwillingness to compromise.''
 &HT;    After growing up in a large, Irish-Catholic family in Evanston,
Ill., Cusack discovered acting when his older sister Joan began
studying at the Piven Theater Workshop, an acting school that
trained Aidan Quinn and all the Cusack kids, including John and his
sisters Susan and Ann.
 &HT;    ``We had to create a class around John,'' founder Byrne Piven
recalls in a separate interview. ``He was the youngest kid who ever
wanted to study. But we couldn't turn him away _ he refused to
leave the building!''
 &HT;    By the time he turned 12, Cusack was already logging time in
local commercials and industrial films. At 16, he got his first
movie role, acting opposite Jacqueline Bisset in ``Class'' (1983).
That led to a string of movies that has included such hits as
``Sixteen Candles'' (1984), ``The Sure Thing'' (1985), ``Say
Anything'' (1989), ``Bullets Over Broadway'' (1994), ``Pushing
Tin'' (1998) and the recent ``Being John Malkovich'' (1999).
 &HT;    But Cusack resists stardom tooth and nail. He lives in Chicago
instead of the movie-centered world of Hollywood, and in his spare
time continues to work with his Chicago-based theater group The New
Criminals. Its movie arm, run by Cusack, Pink and DeVincentis, is
dedicated to writing and producing the kind of films that Hollywood
doesn't want to make but Cusack loves to see.
 &HT;    ``I like movies that are both commercial and subversive,''
Cusack says.
 &HT;    The first New Crime Productions film, ``Grosse Pointe Blank,''
certainly qualifies _ in that surprisingly successful black comedy,
Cusack played an international assassin who stumbles into a midlife
crisis while attending his high-school reunion and preparing for
his next hit.
 &HT;    A sequel is in the works, and will probably feature Joan _ who
had one of her better roles in the original film _ and several
other Cusacks.
 &HT;    ``We don't have sibling rivalry,'' he says. ``We're supportive
of each other. There's a competitive spirit at times, but we're not
a mean-spirited family. We do this work for the joy of it.''
 &HT;    That's been the case, he says, ever since he first stepped onto
a film set.
 &HT;    ``I remember waking up and knowing that, instead of going to
school that day, I would be going to a movie set to hang out with
Jacqueline Bisset,'' he recalls. ``And I also remember thinking,
`I'm winning. The kids at school will think I'm winning.'
 &HT;    ``That's the joy of this work,'' he concludes. ``On most days, I
do feel like a winner.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
