<HEADER>
A5555 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-SINGER-MACY-GRAY-STAR     03-13 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGER-MACY-GRAY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH INTENSITY: MACY GRAY TAKES HIP-HOP BY STORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Macy Gray.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    When she was a child growing up in Canton, Ohio, the teasing she
got from other children made Macy Gray so self-conscious about her
unusual voice that she barely spoke, let along sang.
 &HT;    Guess who's laughing now?
 &HT;    That voice _ a high-pitched, youthful piping that sounds like
Melanie Griffith crossed with Betty Boop _ has made Gray one of the
new toasts of the pop-music world. Her debut album, ``On How Life
Is,'' has been certified gold and has been propelled into
Billboard's Top 20 by the single, ``I Try.''
 &HT;    She was nominated for two Grammy Awards, including Best New
Artist, and while Gray didn't win either one she wound up receiving
copious public praise from Grammy Legend Award recipient Elton
John, which may prove to have more lasting value.
 &HT;    Not bad for someone who says she still cringes at the sound of
her own voice.
 &HT;    ``I always really loved music, but I didn't start singing til I
was in college,'' says the 30-year-old Gray, whose real name is
Natalie McIntyre. ``When I was young, I always just felt like a
misfit. But I guess it kind of grew on me.''
 &HT;    The daughter of a math teacher and a steelworker, Gray grew up
surrounded by music. She soaked up her parent's favorites,
including Sly Stone, Aretha Franklin, James Brown, Marvin Gaye,
Patti LaBelle and especially Stevie Wonder, before taking an
interest in hip-hop when she was in junior-high school.
 &HT;    She also took seven years of classical piano lessons, and earned
extra money working at Canton's main tourist attraction, the
Football Hall of Fame.
 &HT;    ``I was a tour guide,'' she recalls. ``I love football. I don't
remember all the stuff, though _ we had to learn all this old
history stuff to do that job, and I don't remember it. I was a
football fan.''
 &HT;    Her first career goal was to be a filmmaker, and after
graduating from high school she enrolled at the USC Film School, in
Los Angeles, to study screenwriting and directing.
 &HT;    ``I wanted to be a hot shot,'' says Gray, whose first 8-mm.
project was about a straitjacketed insane-asylum inmate tormented
by a fly in his padded cell. ``I wanted to produce movies, sit
behind the desk and call the shots. I just wanted to be cool.''
 &HT;    Her detour into music began when a composer friend asked Gray to
write lyrics for some of his tunes. Gray began teaching her songs
to his band. One night when the singer didn't show up for a
recording session, she filled in on lead vocals.
 &HT;    She figured the tape would be erased later on, she says, but it
didn't work out that way.
 &HT;    ``They left it the way it was,'' Gray says. ``And people started
hearing it.''
 &HT;    One who heard it was the leader of a jazz band that played a
regular Sunday-brunch gig at a Los Angeles hotel. He promptly hired
Gray to perform with his ensemble _ a welcome diversion for a young
would-be filmmaker who was still struggling to get a foot in the
door, working internships and low-level jobs for production
companies and MTV.
 &HT;    The encouragement she received for her performing and
songwriting slowly persuaded her that her real talents might lie
there.
 &HT;    ``At the start I considered it a hobby,'' says Gray, who took
her professional name from a Canton friend of her father's. ``But
the whole time, it just kind of grew on me. I don't know how to
explain it _ I got more and more attached to it, then I fell in
love with it.''
 &HT;    Before long other songwriters were hiring her to sing on their
demo tapes, and she began hosting an after-hours jam session called
the We Ours at a Hollywood coffee shop. Record-company executives
began dropping in on the shows, and Gray found herself the object
of a bidding war, eventually signing with Epic Records.
 &HT;    When it came time to enter the studio with producer/manager Andy
Slater, who has also handled The Wallflowers and Fiona Apple, Gray
had plenty of material to draw from _ which was good, because she
was in the midst of a messy divorce at the time.
 &HT;    ``It was a crazy time in my life,'' she says. ``I think a lot of
the album is kind of about freedom, freeing yourself from all the
crazy things in life, all the crazy things that go on inside of
you.''
 &HT;    That gives ``On How Life Is'' an edge, particularly on songs
such as ``Still,'' which was prompted by a fight with her
ex-husband, and ``The Letter,'' inspired by the death of an uncle.
 &HT;    But it doesn't dampen the album's upbeat, celebratory vibe, a
series of sinewy grooves that slip and slide around Gray's
distinctive vocals.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't really anything I set out to do,'' she says. ``I
didn't go in and say `I want this big party record' or whatever. I
think what was going on in the studio kind of came out on the
record, just being in a studio with this big kind of motley crew of
different musicians, most of them buddies of mine.
 &HT;    ``It's what came out,'' she says with a shrug. ``We recorded 18
songs. It all happened naturally and organically, which is good.''
 &HT;    So the little girl who didn't want to open her mouth is now a
woman making a lot of noise _ and is likely to make even more, now
that she's touring in support of the album. Her two daughters and a
son, ages 4, 3 and 2, stay either in Canton with her mother or in
Los Angeles with her sister when Gray is on tour.
 &HT;    Being a single mother is no picnic, but Gray says that these are
nonetheless the best days of her life.
 &HT;    ``I'm actually enjoying getting older,'' she says cheerfully.
``My 20s were really tough. I put myself through a lot of s--t. I
was a dummy.
 &HT;    ``But now I'm growing up and figuring out things a little bit.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``On How Life Is,'' consult the
official Website at www.macygray.com. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
