<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOSHUA-JACKSON-IN-THE-SKULLS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEYOND THE CREEK: JOSHUA JACKSON PADDLES FOR THE BIG SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Joshua Jackson in a scene from ``The
Skulls.'') 
 By SIMON HOUPT  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be released in Canada until after 2 April 2000. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over there, on a sleek red banquette on the other side of this
martini lounge in New York's Greenwich Village, Liam Neeson and
Aidan Quinn are sipping drinks and laughing loudly.
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, Samuel L. Jackson nurses a beer and smiles as
people approach to say hi.
</P>
<P>
   James Gandolfini of ``The Sopranos'' is standing by the bar,
contentedly puffing away on a fat cigar.
</P>
<P>
   After a long day on the set of ``Law &AMP; Order,'' Angie Harmon's
dark beauty flashes through the pulsing, smoky din of the club.
</P>
<P>
   And right in the middle, practically jittery with glee, Joshua
Jackson feels the music pound through his body. He soaks up the
scene and thinks to himself: ``This is cool. This is very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran actors are usually blase about such moments, but while
he has been in the business for more than a decade, that
late-February party was one of Jackson's first Hollywood-style
blowouts.
</P>
<P>
   This is a season of many firsts for the 21-year-old actor. A
couple of weeks after that party, Jackson took the stage of NBC's
famed Studio 8-H to host ``Saturday Night Live,'' a program he had
grown up watching in Canada. Also for the first time in his life,
he finds himself being taken seriously as a magazine cover boy,
gracing the premiere issue of Teen Movieline.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the biggest ``first'' of all: On March 31 he'll
open in theaters nationwide as the star of the thriller ``The
Skulls,'' marking his first experience as a Hollywood leading man.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long road for the charismatic actor, whose first
major role came at age 11 in ``Crooked Hearts,'' a film drama about
a dysfunctional family. For awhile it looked as if his biggest
accomplishment would be playing the cocky hockey star Charlie
Conway in the ``Mighty Ducks'' film trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   But then, two years ago, ``Dawson's Creek'' exploded into the
popular consciousness and made instant stars of Jackson and his
co-stars James Van Der Beek, Michelle Williams and Katie Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   The other three have already headlined films, but Jackson wanted
to take some time to figure out exactly which project was best for
him. He chose ``The Skulls,'' he says, precisely because it offered
a role distinctly different from the wisecracking, emotionally
guarded Pacey Witter, whom he plays on ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Those used to the hunched stance and squeaky voice of
16-year-old Pacey may be surprised to see Jackson as a confident,
muscled college senior. They may also be surprised to see him
steaming up the screen with his pretty co-star, Leslie Bibb of
television's ``Popular.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Skulls,'' Jackson plays Luke McNamara, an Ivy League
student chosen as a member of a secret society known as the Skulls
_ closely modeled on a real Yale institution known as Skull and
Bones.
</P>
<P>
   Luke finds himself in an unfamiliar but seductively pleasant
world, but one that he gradually realizes has its own dark side.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can wax poetic here for a second,'' Jackson says, sipping
coffee at a New York restaurant, ``in a perfect world `Skulls'
would work on two levels. It would be a very fast-paced, engaging
thriller that keeps you interested from the first frame to the
last. It would also operate as a morality tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``This question posed to Luke is basically, `Do you believe in
yourself enough to adhere to what is right, or are you going to
sell your soul to achieve your goals?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make no bones about it,'' says Jackson, a smart,
talkative and charming guy who seems to lack any trace of
movie-star ego. ``I've done work simply for the paycheck and simply
because I needed to pay my rent _ I didn't believe in it from the
beginning, but it's just something I had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Having experienced that kind of Faustian deal made ``The
Skulls'' all the more enticing, the actor says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high school, or in any social situation, you're constantly
being forced to check what you believe, swallow your words and
accept the status quo,'' he says. ``I have certainly been guilty of
not speaking up when I should have.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he adds with a smile, ``in life you fail much more than
you do in movies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Skulls'' couldn't have arrived at a more timely moment.
Among its members, the real-life Skull and Bones society, which was
founded at Yale in 1833, counts presidential candidate George W.
Bush and his father, former President George Bush. The Central
Intelligence Agency is said to have been conceived within the
society's walls.
</P>
<P>
   In such a power-permeated world, says producer Neal Moritz _ who
also cast Jackson in supporting roles in ``Urban Legend'' (1998)
and ``Cruel Intentions'' (1999) _ Jackson adds a crucial element of
humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has that really likable quality that young men and young
women can relate to and admire,'' Moritz says in a separate
interview. ``He's really grounded.''
</P>
<P>
   His co-stars on ``Dawson's Creek'' agree, even though Jackson
has been known to get a little stir-crazy on the show's remote
location in Wilmington, N.C. A native of Vancouver, British
Columbia, and a passionate hockey fan, Jackson admits that he hates
being unable to follow his hometown team, the Canucks, and misses
the rest of the Canadian world in which he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the strange thing about being in America,'' he says.
``It looks the same, sounds the same, smells the same. But it's
just not the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if ``The Skulls'' does as well as many are predicting
it will, a big-screen career may open new options for Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   After all, one of Hollywood's favorite locations for shooting
blockbuster films is Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Simon Houpt is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Skulls,'' consult the
official Website at www.theskulls.net. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
