<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5561 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRAIN-LOCATIONS-2     03-13 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRAIN-LOCATIONS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST WHAT'S GOING ON INSIDE THAT HEAD OF YOURS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., N.J.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By SANDRA BLAKESLEE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two hundred years ago, the German anatomist Franz Joseph Gall
dazzled the public with his science of phrenology, the practice of
divining personality and intellect from the shape of the bumps on a
person's head. Each localized bump, he said, represented a
different characteristic, like secretiveness, acquisitiveness or
cautiousness.
</P>
<P>
   Later practitioners of phrenology even found locations for
pampering children, gluttony and Republican politics.
</P>
<P>
   Now the public is being dazzled once again by a technique called
functional magnetic resonance imaging, or FMRI, which is finding
precise brain locations related to all sorts of human traits and
activities. Among them are hyperactivity centers in children, cells
that specialize in the naming of fruits and even a spot in the
brain that lights up when a man is sexually aroused.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having their bumps ``read'' during a Victorian parlor
game, people lie down and put their heads inside a powerful magnet
device that detects certain molecules in blood flowing through the
brain.
</P>
<P>
   When a particular location of the brain is engaged in a
cognitive task like naming fruits, it requires extra energy to do
its job. The energy arrives in the form of glucose, a simple sugar,
that is carried to the fruit-naming location via increased blood
flow.
</P>
<P>
   This increase in blood flow is then detected by the magnet and
depicted on a screen as splotches of light inside the brain.
</P>
<P>
   FMRI is wildly popular with researchers, thrilled to have a tool
that can peer inside the thinking, feeling human brain, said Dr.
William Newsome, a professor of neuroscience at Stanford. Unlike
standard MRI scans that take static pictures of brain anatomy _
used when doctors search for abnormalities _ functional imaging
captures the brain in action as it plans, schemes, imagines and
hallucinates.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, each week journals report new studies of ways the brain
works based on analyses of FMRI-based splotches of light inside
human heads. But many leading neuroscientists, including Newsome,
now chide colleagues, saying they are misusing a potentially
priceless research tool on studies that are often poorly designed
and sometimes bordering on the simple-minded.
</P>
<P>
   Most researchers using the new imaging are not asking difficult
questions about brain function, these critics say. Instead of
asking how the brain works, the technology is being used to answer
simple questions that repeat what is already known about the brain
or shed little light.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Newsome said, a researcher might put someone in a
scanner, ask the person to count from 1 to 10 and later to count
backwards from 10 to 1. The end result: an area for counting
backward that lights up as a blob in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is seductively easy to use, said Dr. Christopher
Moore, a postdoctoral fellow at Massachusetts General Hospital in
Boston who is carrying out a number of imaging studies. ``You can
think of an idea, throw five friends into the scanner overnight and
write up your results the next day. People don't have to think very
hard about what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Just because an area lights up does not mean something important
was found, Newsome said. Nor will researchers understand the brain
when the entire map is filled with blobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Localization data provide little insight into the exact nature
of the signals encoded in a given structure, the computations being
performed and the interactions between different structures,''
Newsome said. In other words, knowing where something happens does
not reveal how it happens.
</P>
<P>
   Neurologists now know that the brain is a dynamic system of
cellular circuits that constantly shift as people go through the
day. So the hard part of deciphering brain function is to figure
out how cells and widespread circuits are interconnected. How do
they fire together to produce behaviors?
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, ``there's a dirty little secret that people who
publish these studies don't reveal,'' said Dr. Terry Sejnowski, a
neuroscientist at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, Calif. ``The
signals they get are highly massaged. It means they clean up their
data to make it look good, like applying makeup, for a general
audience.'' The actual data they collect are far more complex, he
said, but difficult to decipher.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that some parts of the brain seem to light up
all the time. The anterior cingulate _ found in front of the brain
near the fissure separating the two hemispheres _ is active when
people carry out scores of tasks, including, as French researchers
found, thinking about sex.
</P>
<P>
   And just because a brain area is correlated with a behavior in
FMRI studies does not mean that it causes the behavior, said Dr.
John Moore, a psychology professor at the University of
Massachusetts. Imaging studies often make this mistake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The most serious criticism of the imaging has to do with what
the researchers are measuring. Increased blood flow, as shown in
splotches of light, may not be an accurate surrogate for brain cell
function, some say. Sometimes a signal is picked up by the magnet
because the blood is draining into a larger vein and not from cells
that are using more energy. Thus, some imaging experiments may
measure what veins, not brains, are doing at any given moment.
</P>
<P>
   But all these criticisms do not mean that researchers abandon
their projects, Sejnowski said. ``Keep in mind that every time a
new technique comes along, a majority of the early studies will be
misguided,'' he said. ``FMRI has shown us things we could not have
seen any other way. It is especially useful in studying uniquely
human traits like spoken language, reading and sophisticated moral
reasoning.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, at Princeton Dr. Jonathan Cohen, a neuroscientist,
and his colleagues have used the imaging to discover a function for
the anterior cingulate that may explain its widespread activation
in imaging experiments. Many believe that this part of the brain is
responsible for controlled attention or that it responds to errors,
Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   But experiments that could have been done only with FMRI suggest
that its real role is to register conflict. This, in turn, leads a
person to pay more attention to what is happening. The distinction
is subtle but important, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Newsome, an expert in monkey brains, said an imaging experiment
in humans got results that conflicted with what was known in
monkeys. ``We went back and found that the monkey data were
incorrect,'' he said. Thus, human experiments can pay off in
unexpected ways.
</P>
<P>
   The imaging technology is improving rapidly, Sejnowski said.
Soon, it may be possible to measure blood flow in tiny areas called
cortical columns, clusters of neurons that carry out a single
function like detecting edges or direction of motion. It is
believed that these columns carry out the basic work of the
cerebral cortex, and if researchers can see how they wire and fire
together, they will have a better idea of how the brain is
organized.
</P>
<P>
   Other improvements include new methods of computer analysis that
allow researchers to distinguish meaningful signals out of
confusing experiments with the new imaging.
</P>
<P>
   Brain imaging researchers are extremely excited about efforts
under way to combine FMRI with other brain imaging techniques, like
magnetoencephalography (MEG) and electrophysiology. The new imaging
is good at finding functional locations in the brain but it is very
slow at picking up signals. While brain cells work in thousandths
of a second, functional imaging needs a couple of seconds to detect
blood flow. Other technologies like MEG and EEG are fast but are
not good at identifying where brain activity occurs.
</P>
<P>
   By combining images from all three techniques with the help of
powerful computers, researchers hope to produce ``movies'' of
thoughts inside a human head.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, ``our knowledge is akin to looking out of the window
of an airplane at night,'' Newsome said. ``We can see patches of
light from cities and towns scattered across the landscape. We know
that roads, railways and telephone wires connect those cities, but
we gain little sense of the social, political and economic
interactions within and between cities that define a functioning
society.'' The same is true of efforts to look into the human
brain, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1629EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5569 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-TAHOE-FACELIFT-HNS &LR;      03-13 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAHOE-FACELIFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ENVIRONMENTALISTS FIND ALLY IN BUSINESS AS RESORT TOWN SEEKS
NEW LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH LAKE TAHOE, Calif. _ This mountain town of 22,000, hugely
popular with tourists despite its shoddy 1960s look, is planning a
colossal face lift. It is a task as big as the lake next door.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning May 1, buildings at the north end of town will be
bulldozed by the dozens. In their place, according to proposals,
will be upscale hotels and timeshare complexes, a vast shopping
mall, gourmet restaurants, an outdoor ice rink, a convention
center, artists' studios and a movie multiplex _ all in a setting
reflective of the Sierra scenery that surrounds it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a whole new South Shore,'' said Pam Drum,
spokeswoman for the bistate Tahoe Regional Planning Agency. ``It's
going to have a rustic, but yet elegant, village kind of feel. It's
going to be a place where you can bring your whole family, where
you don't need your car to get from place to place.''
</P>
<P>
   Even its most ardent advocates admit that today's South Lake
Tahoe, which gets 2 million visitors a year, is hard on the eyes.
Built mostly in the 1960s, before the establishment of
environmental mandates, the city's 5 1/2-mile commercial strip
along U.S. 50 does not conform to the natural beauty of the vast
Tahoe Basin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's old, tired and ugly,'' said Dennis Harmon, president of
the Heavenly Ski Resort that rises from the south edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   Jaye Von Klug, the city's redevelopment manager, called the
strip ``a totally deteriorated, dilapidated physical environment
that is a blight on the landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   Low-rent motels, T-shirt stores (one hyping obscene messages)
and an endless array of ski rental outlets and souvenir shops line
South Lake Tahoe's main drag just south of the Nevada state line,
where a clutch of big casinos crowd as close to California as they
can.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four acres of that sprawl could disappear under a plan
that is grandly _ some say unrealistically _ ambitious. The total
cost of the massive makeover might rise to $750 million, mostly
from private sources. Still, the town has taken on $100 million of
bonded indebtedness to cover redevelopment expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike earlier, hotly contested Tahoe development schemes, this
one is touted as environmentally sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us want to save the lake. There's no question about
that,'' Von Klug said.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists appear to agree, marking a drastic reversal of
the traditionally bellicose relationship between the environmental
movement here and casino-dominated business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Since their battle began in the mid-1960s, any development was
energetically opposed by a litigious brigade of environmentalists.
Once, simple cabin-building permits were so restricted that they
were drawn from a bin by a blindfolded priest.
</P>
<P>
   With the blessing of those same eco-activists, 53 businesses
covering 19 acres on the mountain side of U.S. 50 soon will be
razed and, when possible, relocated.
</P>
<P>
   Once the dust has cleared, construction will start on two hotels
totaling 700 rooms, a 70,000-square-foot retail and restaurant
plaza, six-screen cinema, open-air skating rink and central transit
facility where visitors can board buses or a gondola to Heavenly.
The first and biggest phase could be finished in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Less certain is a 15.7-acre project between the highway and the
lake, abutting the state border and Harveys hotel-casino. There _
replacing a warren of vintage motels and funky retail outlets _
developers hope to construct a convention complex, 165-room
time-share hotel, child care facility, artist studios and
galleries, and an environmental education center. Work on that
phase could begin in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   South Lake Tahoe's grand renewal schemes are driven by
nationwide changes in the skiing and gambling industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 10 years ... if you look at (ski) resorts in North
America, from Canada on down, the trend is to create these alpine
villages,'' Harmon said. Also in vogue, he said, is the development
of ``ski in/ski out'' resorts, where skiers can walk from their
rooms to a nearby lift.
</P>
<P>
   The American Skiing Co., which owns Heavenly, is the primary
developer of the so-called Park Avenue project (named after the
street that forms its northern boundary). Two big hotels, the Lake
Tahoe Inn and the Grand Summit, a timeshare lodging, will be funded
by the company. So will the gondola that can carry 2,800 people per
hour up to the slopes.
</P>
<P>
   The South Shore's casino industry also suffers a competitive
disadvantage due to the spread of legalized gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got to this market 12 years ago, Tahoe was the
fifth-biggest gaming market in the country,'' said Jim Rafferty,
senior vice president of corporate marketing for Harveys Casino
Resorts. ``Now it's the 25th.''
</P>
<P>
   Harveys hopes to develop the convention center across U.S. 50
from the Park Avenue project. Rafferty said most big conventions
are held in fall and spring _ when Tahoe tourism is slowest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No two people personify Tahoe's new realpolitik better than
Rafferty and Rochelle Nason.
</P>
<P>
   Nason was a lawyer in San Francisco who found her calling when
she took a case for an environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, I was really excited about coming to work
in the morning,'' Nason said. In 1993 she left law to become
executive director of the League to Save Lake Tahoe, an
environmental organization with about 4,500 members.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1965, the league was once a paragon of radical
activism. Under James Bruner, executive director until the early
1980s, it aimed to drive casinos out of the Tahoe Basin. Their
bumper stickers read: ``Save Lake Tahoe. Gamble in Reno.''
</P>
<P>
   A gentler slogan, ``Keep Tahoe Blue,'' was adopted some years
back. Even that sentiment generated hostility among locals. Many
perceived the League and its objectives as a threat to their
economic well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little over 10 years ago, a `Keep Tahoe Blue' bumper sticker
on your car could get the air let out of your tires or worse,''
Nason said.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop Rafferty from slapping one on his fender when
he arrived at Harveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I believed in saving Lake Tahoe,'' said the
gregarious native of the Queens section of New York, who graduated
from the University of Nevada, Las Vegas and worked at an Atlantic
City casino before moving to the lake. ``I mean, I'm a child of the
'60s.``
</P>
<P>
   But ``somebody at work came up to me and said, `You've got to
take that off your car. You can't have a league bumper sticker.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dismayed, he scraped it away. ``I was still on probation,''
Rafferty recalled.
</P>
<P>
   These days, said Nason, the bumper stickers more common here.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Rafferty, ``We've come on a significant journey with
our environmental brothers. We've really come to find common
ground.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1635EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
