<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, March 14. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-ATTACK (Beirut, Lebanon) _ A day after a gunman critically
wounded one of Iran's leading democratic reformers with an attack
on a Tehran street the Iranian capital was the scene Monday of
another attack, this time involving the firing of a volley of about
six mortar bombs into a residential complex that abuts a military
base in the capital's northern suburbs. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-REFORM (Austin, Texas) _ For Gov. George W. Bush, reform
has been a matter of legislative proposals rather than an
overriding political philosophy, which might explain why few people
in Texas would have picked the word reformer when asked to describe
the governor. ``He's an incremental change specialist,'' said Bruce
Buchanan, a political scientist at the University of Texas,
``sometimes in a partisan way, like tort reform, which is a big
business issue, sometimes in a bipartisan way, such as small
changes in education.'' For Bush, success has come when changes
have been modest or when he has not had to buck political interests
or popular will. When he has been boldest, he has fallen short of
his goals. By Jim Yardley and Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR (Undated) _ The Tribune Co. and Times Mirror
Co., two media companies whose flagship newspapers helped define
the brawling, partisan days of 19th century journalism, on Monday
announced plans to merge into a media company that would bring
their trademark regionalism to the multimedia world of the 21st
century. If nothing intervenes to disrupt the merger, the new
company, to be called Tribune Company, will own 11 daily
newspapers, 22 television stations and four radio stations. Its
combined audience of newspaper subscribers and television viewers
would give it a much greater national profile. But its core
strategy would be regional, exemplified by holdings in markets like
New York, Los Angeles and Chicago, with a mandate to deliver news,
entertainment and advertising through every kind of media _ print,
television and the Internet. By Felicity Barringer and Laura M.
Holson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic and map.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RECESSION (Tokyo) _ Defying official optimistic forecasts,
hundreds of billions of dollars worth of government spending and
other financial stimulants, Japan's economy revealed its underlying
vulnerability on Monday in statistics that showed a retreat back
into recession in the final three months of 1999. The Economic
Planning Agency said the gross domestic product, the total output
of goods and services in the world's second-largest economy, fell
1.4 percent in the October-December quarter, for an annual rate of
decline of 5.5 percent. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EVOLUTIONARY-PSYCHOLOGY (Undated) _ When two scientists
proposed in a recent book that rape was best viewed as a sexual act
with its roots in evolution, it set off a squall of protest from
feminists and social scientists, won the researchers appearances on
shows like NBC's ``Dateline,'' and became the talk of the cocktail
party circuit. Even last week the controversy continued, with the
book's authors conducting a rancorous exchange over a scathing
review in the scientific journal Nature. But the case put forward
was not, as some assumed, a fringe theory developed by a pair of
renegade researchers. Rather, the arguments fit into a larger
theoretical framework, the work of a group of scientists who have
ushered Darwin into new and provocative areas, including sexual
attraction between men and women, parenting, jealousy and violence,
as well as less touchy regions like the learning of language and
the organization of perception. By Erica Goode. (3500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT7,8.
</P>
</TEXT>
