<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3RD BANK SEEKS TO JOIN MEGAMERGER IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Sanwa Bank Ltd. is negotiating to join the merger of
Asahi Bank Ltd. and Tokai Bank Ltd., a combination that would
create the third-largest bank in the world in terms of assets,
executives at the banks said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The merged bank would have about 104 trillion yen ($979 billion)
in assets, second in Japan behind Mizuho Financial Group, which
will come to life this fall when Fuji Bank, Industrial Bank of
Japan and Dai-Ichi Kangyo merge into a bank with $1.3 trillion in
assets. The proposed merger of Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank in
Germany would create the world's second-largest bank, with $1.2
trillion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   It would mean that in less than one year, the ranks of large
Japanese ``city'' banks have started shrinking to five from nine as
the industry is forced to reorganize in the wake of the financial
crisis that gripped the country in late 1997 and early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, which is itself the result of
an earlier merger, and Daiwa Bank remain unaligned, and many
analysts think Daiwa will be forced to find a partner.
</P>
<P>
   A Sanwa-Asahi-Tokai merger, which is expected to be completed in
the fall of 2001, would create Japan's first megabank aimed
squarely at Japanese consumers, a group of customers traditionally
ignored by Japan's biggest banks. Asahi, which is strong in the
Kanto region around Tokyo, and Tokai, which caters to customers in
the Tokai region between Tokyo and Osaka, had already announced a
merger that is scheduled to take place this fall. Adding Sanwa,
which is strong in the Kansai area around Osaka, would give the
consolidated bank a solid grip on the most populous part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives Asahi and Tokai the Osaka piece they've been
missing,'' said James P. Fiorillo, a senior banking analyst at ING
Barings. ``Geographically, it makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fiorillo cautioned that while the merger was likely to have
long-term benefits, it would be disruptive and difficult over the
next three to five years. Like their European and American
counterparts, Japanese banks have found that consolidation is a
bigger challenge than they had anticipated. The struggles, sometime
bordering on internecine warfare, that have troubled Citibank and
UBS of Switzerland, to name two of the more prominent examples,
have become front-page news as they struggle to mesh distinct and
often conflicting cultures and management styles.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese banks are no different. Dai-Ichi Bank and Kangyo Bank
maintained separate personnel departments for decades after their
merger into Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank in the 1970s. And Mizuho, as
Dai-Ichi, Fuji and Industrial Bank will become after their merger,
will have three presidents, all of whom are well past what
Americans would consider retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges here may be even greater because Japanese banks
face a bigger challenge in getting up to speed with information
technology. When Bank of Tokyo joined with Mitsubishi Bank in 1996,
the costs of merging their computer systems together was twice what
they had anticipated, Fiorillo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have a tendency to overestimate cost-savings and
underestimate the costs of merging systems, and that's not limited
to Japanese banks,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1647EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
