<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ark., N.C.)  (For release Sunday, March 19) 
(DW) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIKING WITH LLAMAS
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences opens its new
seven-story home on April 7 by the State Capitol in Raleigh, but
nature lovers can celebrate from one end of the state to the other.
With scores of guides and companies, the museum is sponsoring a
program called Afield but Not Afar, with 104 events and expeditions
from barrier islands to Appalachian peaks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trips _ on weekends from March 31 to May 2 _ include river
rafting, sea kayaking, rock climbing, bird-watching and llama
treks. They are as short as an hour, to view bird nests on April 8
in New River State Park, and as long as three days, to hike from
Bob Stratton Bald (elevation 5,400 feet) down to Joyce Kilmer
Memorial Forest (2,200 feet) on April 28 to 30. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the Escape to the Cape sea kayaking trip, March 31 to April
2, nights are spent in the old Cape Lookout Coast Guard Station.
Participants in a canoe exploration of Devil's Gut Swamp near
Williamston on April 8 and 9 will camp on a platform in the swamp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the events are free; most of the others cost $10
to $345 a person. Rock climbing and camping expeditions with llamas
carrying the equipment on April 9 to 11 and 16 to 18 in the Smoky
Mountains start at $645 for a family of three. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A full list of the trips is available on the museum Web site,
www.naturalsciences.org, and from (919) 783-1036. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN MODERNISTS AT THE NATIONAL GALLERY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the National Gallery of Art can get a short course
in American modernism by walking through the East Wing, where
``Twentieth-Century American Art: The Ebsworth Collection'' is on
view till June 11. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, more than 70 works collected over the past 30
years by Barney A. Ebsworth, a St. Louis business executive, and
his wife, Pam, traces the course of American art from the legendary
1913 Armory Show in New York until the 1960's. Those dates are like
bookends in American art: at the Armory Show, Americans saw the
Cubist, Fauvist and Expressionist works of Europe's avant-garde
artists for the first time, and that sparked a creative period
during which American modernists first played catch-up and then
began to dominate the world art scene. But by the late 1960's,
critics would say, painting had died. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show covers the waterfront of American modernism with works
like Charles Sheeler's ``Classic Landscape'' from 1913; Edward
Hopper's ``Chop Suey'' from 1929; Arthur Dove's ``Moon'' from 1935;
Jackson Pollock's ``Composition with Red Strokes'' from 1950; and
Andy Warhol's ``Campbell's Soup Can with Can Opener'' from 1962.
But there are surprises, too: works by lesser-known artists like
Bob Thompson, Alice Trumbull Mason and Suzy Frelinghuysen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition will travel to the Seattle Art Museum, where it
will be on view from Aug. 10 through Nov. 12. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Gallery of Art, on the National Mall between Third
and Ninth Streets at Constitution Avenue NW, is open daily.
Admission is free. Information: (202) 737-4215 or www.nga.gov. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS BOAT SINKING BRINGS SAFETY REVIEW  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Coast Guard meeting last month to discuss ``duck'' tourist
boats _ whose charm is that they can do sightseeing on land as well
as on water _ is likely to bring tighter regulations. The
conference was called in response to the sinking last summer of one
of the boats near Hot Springs, Ark. Twenty passengers were aboard;
13, including three children, died.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board, which investigated the
loss of the boat, the Majestic, said that more than 250 similar
boats, mostly of World War II vintage, were being operated as
tourist vehicles by 30 companies in 16 states.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated Feb. 18, the board, which has power only to
recommend rules, urged the operators to alter their vessels
``without delay'' to provide extra buoyancy. The Majestic, the
vessel in the fatal capsizing, had been in the water only five to
seven minutes when it swamped and sank in a minute. Passengers were
trapped inside the plastic canopy and windshields. Coast Guard data
indicate there were 18 accidents with ducks in several states
between March 6, 1991, and May 1, 1999, when the Majestic sank. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ducks in operation were designed to accommodate two
drivers and 5,000 pounds of cargo. The last parts were manufactured
in 1945. The name derives from the military designation for these
vehicles, DUKW: the ``d'' stood for the year of the design, 1942;
``u'' for amphibious; ``k'' for front-wheel-drive and ``w'' for
rear-wheel drive.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
