<HEADLINE>
DOES `STREAMING MEDIA' GIVE YOU THE SCREAMING MEEMIES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 19)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lord knows, this department tries to keep up. But no sooner is
the letter  &UR; e &LR;  fixed firmly in my mind in all its permutations as
the key to the new electronic world ( &UR; e-commerce &LR; ,  &UR; e-mail &LR; ,
 &UR; e-whatever &LR; ) than along come the jargoneers of digitese with
another letter to thrust it aside. Here comes  &UR; m-commerce &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; M &LR;  is not for the million things your mother gave you, as the
old song went. Rather, it stands for  &UR; mobile &LR; ; as the Internet
speeds up transactions, mobility is where it's at. (And  &UR; where it's
at &LR;  is no longer where it's at, either; I am on the lookout for the
latest phrase for what the French still call  &UR; au courant &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   `` &UR; M-commerce &LR;  is  &UR; e-commerce &LR;  that's done over mobile phones
and other hand-held digital devices like personal digital
assistants,'' writes The Business Times of Singapore. ``It covers
buying and selling everything from stocks to flowers, using
handphones and PDAs.'' (Just be careful of chewing gum while
 &UR; m-commercing &LR;  on Lee Kwan Yew's tight little island _ you could
wind up running from a cane.)
</P>
<P>
   Though a British outfit named Logica claims coinage in 1997, the
locution is now coming on stream. ``Just when the language has
begun to absorb the letter `e' as a prefix,'' notes Katie Hafner in
The New York Times, ``comes the latest twist on electronic money
and the language of the digital age: mobile commerce, or
 &UR; m-commerce &LR; , which promises to turn your cell phone or hand-held
organizer into an electronic wallet.'' She quotes Richard Siber of
Anderson Consulting as foreseeing the day when `` &UR; m-commerce &LR;  will
be bigger than  &UR; e-commerce &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Dunno 'bout that. (That's how impatient e-mail writers,
rat-tat-tat justlikethat, express ``I am not so sure that
linguistic prediction is well founded.'' That may bring in a lot of
 &UR; m-mail &LR; , a locution coined right here and now.)
</P>
<P>
   Both phrases use  &UR; commerce &LR;  as the suffix;  &UR; electronic &LR; , the
source for the  &UR; e &LR;  prefix, is a more general term than  &UR; mobile &LR;  and
may subsume it. Thus we would have ``mobile electronic commerce''
as against stationary electronic commerce (the sort you're involved
with when ordering kiwiburgers while parked), but that would bring
us  &UR; m-e commerce &LR; , too late for the ``me generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to mobile electronic commerce, as I get it, is the
ability to peddle while pedaling, or to buy on the fly. ``Rather
than stand in front of a soda machine fishing for a dollar bill
that is neither too faded nor too wrinkled,'' writes Hafner, ``you
may someday simply dial the phone number posted on the machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Here my with-it colleague has lapsed into an archaism.  &UR; Dial &LR; ,
the noun, originally meant ``the graduated face of a timepiece,''
as in a sundial, rooted in the Latin for ``day.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of us can remember when the verb  &UR; to dial &LR;  meant ``to turn
a disc with numbered finger holes.'' This verb was generalized, as
linguists like Sol Steinmetz say, into touching the numbers on a
touch-tone phone that has no dial. (Another such new generalization
is  &UR; to bookmark &LR; , which meant ``to place a marker in a book'' but
which has a newer sense of ``to mark the address of a Web site.'')
</P>
<P>
   Will the archaism  &UR; to dial &LR;  persevere in a dial-free age? Will
we long refer to digits on the broadcast spectrum as ``on your
radio dial''? Will marketers of the deodorant soap have to rename
their product? My guess is the verb will be replaced not by
 &UR; punch &LR; ,  &UR; poke &LR;  or  &UR; jab &LR; , which suggest dialing in anger, but by
 &UR; key &LR; ,  &UR; press &LR;  or  &UR; tip &LR; , as in ``fingertip.'' We are likely to  &UR; tip
in &LR;  rather than dial the numbers. (Where am I? Back to the future.)
</P>
<P>
   In a recent conversation in advanced digit-English with The New
York Times' new-media guru, Martin Nisenholtz, CEO of Times Company
Digital, I was told that my column might someday, in audio or video
form, be part of  &UR; streaming media &LR; . That was satisfying; I like my
prose to go with the flow.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in a 1995 Interactive Age (you were expecting maybe
Intrapassive Era?), Richard Karpinski defined  &UR; streaming media &LR;  as
delivering ``audio and video on demand, rather than requiring a
user to download a file off the Web and play it back from a local
drive.'' In that way, the simultaneous display and transfer of
sound and image can be watched and heard as the data flows in.
</P>
<P>
   And now for some  &UR; shovelware &LR; . A word association with
 &UR; streaming media &LR;  leaps to mind:  &UR; screaming meemies &LR; . This
expression, origin obscure, was first defined in The New Republic
in 1927 as a synonym for drunkenness. It soon came to mean
``hysterics'' like those in subsequent DTs, or delirium tremens. In
World War II, allied soldiers applied it to the  &UR; Nebelwerfer &LR; , a
German multibarreled rocket mortar that went off with a series of
high-pitched sounds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Shovelware &LR; , according to Eric Raymond's Jargon File, is ``a
slipshod compilation of software dumped onto a CD-ROM without much
care for organization or even usability.'' Its source, I recall
vividly, is the newspaper term ``editing with a shovel,'' applied
to editors who fail to trim copy of extraneous paragraphs used by
lazy writers who have a certain space to fill. It's nice to see
that the old ``slug it `Slay''' lingo has found a place in the
streaming, screaming media-meemie language of technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1709EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
