<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5588 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MIGRAINE-NYT &LR;      03-13 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MIGRAINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY MISS OUT ON MIGRAINE REMEDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., N.Y., Pa., Conn.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By KEITH MULVIHILL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 28 million Americans, roughly one-tenth of the population,
suffer from migraine attacks, but only 52 percent have received an
official diagnosis, according to a recent study of migraines in
America.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by the National Headache Foundation, a nonprofit
organization that promotes public awareness about headaches, found
that 32 percent of those who suffer from migraines have never
consulted a doctor about their conditions, even though in the
mid-1990s, the first over-the-counter drug was approved by the Food
and Drug Administration specifically for the treatment of migraine.
In addition, a class of highly specific, prescription drugs known
as triptans were also approved for treatment of migraines.
According to the recent study, 57 percent of migraine sufferers
still rely on over-the-counter medications of all kinds
exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   The study, the largest epidemiological study of migraines in the
United States, surveyed about 30,000 Americans and compared their
answers to those of a study 10 years ago. Over all, the current
survey found the prevalence of migraines to be roughly the same now
as it was 10 years ago, but it found that current sufferers were
not taking advantage of new treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Migraine is definitely underdiagnosed and undertreated in the
United States,'' said Suzanne Simons, executive director of the
headache foundation, which is based in Chicago. ``Treatment
patterns have not kept pace with treatment options.''
</P>
<P>
   Misconceptions about migraines are still widespread, Simons
said. ``Many people still do not understand how disabling a
migraine can be. It is not just the severe pain that people can
experience, it is also the associated symptoms like nausea and
extreme sensitivity to light and sound.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, 13 million migraine sufferers say they
have consulted with doctors, but a survey of doctor diaries found
only 3.5 million patient visits specifically about migraine in the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call this the oh-by-the-way-doc phenomenon,'' said Dr.
Richard Lipton, a neurologist at the Albert Einstein College of
Medicine in Bronx, N.Y., and the lead author of the American
Migraine Study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the patient is in the office for some other reason,
a physical or high blood pressure, for instance, and before they
leave they mention that they have headaches,'' Lipton said.
``Unfortunately, this may not register with the doctor, and the
patient leaves thinking they have had a medical consultation
regarding their migraines and the doctor does not.'' He recommends
that patients make appointments specifically for headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Many sufferers say they are misunderstood. ``People don't think
of it as a serious condition,'' said Connie Christiansen, a reading
teacher in Easton, Pa. ``They think you are a weakling.''
</P>
<P>
   Christiansen, 53, who suffered her first migraine when she was
in high school, said: ``You hate to have tell people at work that
you are leaving early because your head hurts. Some just don't get
it. They think you should be able to tough it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Migraine has been recognized as a disease for 50 years or more,
said Dr. Jes Olesen, a professor of neurology at the University of
Copenhagen in Denmark. On Olesen's initiative, the International
Headache Society, a organization of professionals that is based in
London, decided in 1985 to classify and define the various headache
diseases. The group was the first to classify migraine headaches as
a separate condition from tension-type headaches, which are milder
and often caused by constriction of blood vessels, rather than
dilation and inflammation, which causes migraines.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of the general population identified two main types
of migraine. The first, migraine without aura, is characterized by
headache attacks lasting 4 to 72 hours. The headache is usually
severe, often occurring on one side of the head and pulsating in
nature. It is also aggravated by physical activity and accompanied
by nausea, vomiting and hypersensitivity to light and noise.
</P>
<P>
   In the second type, migraine with aura, the attacks are preceded
by neurological symptoms called aura _ visual, sensory, speech or
motor impairments like tingling sensations, blurred vision or
seeing spots.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, The New England Journal of Medicine published a
landmark study that demonstrated unequivocally that migraine
attacks resulted from a series of complex neurological events.
Researchers were able to induce and document an actual migraine
with the aid of an imaging technique.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fred Sheftell, director of the New England Center
for Headache, a clinic in Stamford, Conn., the latest research
shows that a migraine attack starts in the brain cortex. Sufferers
often tend toward hyperexcitability of that brain area, he said,
setting events that lead to the release of neurotransmitters,
dilation of blood vessels, inflammation and pain.
</P>
<P>
   Sheftell said a variety of circumstances could touch off an
attack, including hormones, diet and changes in the weather, sleep
patterns or the seasons. But little is known about how those work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the majority of people have a family history,''
he said. ``Migraine is not a simple disorder. It is a complex
disorder of the brain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
