<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, March 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A potent disturbance will cross the western Gulf Coast states
Tuesday, bringing a bout of rain to the region. Many locations
along the coast will receive occasionally heavy rainfall, with
localized flooding in poor drainage areas. To the north, showers
will develop over the Red River Valley and the central plains of
Texas. Some of the high clouds from this system will spread to the
east, dimming the sun at times along the eastern Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sunshine will lead to mild readings from the Tennessee
Valley to the Middle Atlantic states as high pressure remains
overhead. Farther north, a weak disturbance passing through the
southern Great Lakes will promote some clouds along with an
isolated shower in spots. Meanwhile, northern New England will
remain cloudy with showers and flurries ahead of a fast-moving warm
front.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front sweeping across the northern Plains will bring
chilly air and scattered flurries to North Dakota, northeast
Montana and northern Minnesota. Snow will also fall in the
Bitterroots and mountains of northern Wyoming as an area of low
pressure passes through the region. Some peaks in western Montana
will receive several inches of snow. To the south, sunny skies in
the Southwestern states will lead to temperatures in the 90s in the
deserts.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore flow in the Pacific Northwest will allow coastal showers
and mountain snow showers to persist. Clouds will stretch to the
south into portions of northern California. Sunshine and offshore
breezes will keep southern California warm.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: On Its Own
</P>
<P>
   A record 10 inches of snow fell Sunday in Caribou, Maine,
eclipsing the previous record of 8.9 inches set in 1959. This
raised the seasonal snowfall to 102 inches, just half a foot shy of
the average snow in a normal year. Northern Maine is one of only a
few locations in the Northeast that has accumulated a near normal
amount of snow for the winter. A separate stream of frigid air has
regularly been sweeping east from Quebec across northern New
England this winter. Lately, the cold air has arrived in Caribou
coincidentally with moisture from the Atlantic. Another period of
snow is likely later Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
