<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV19-NYT     03-13 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUIET FOURTH OF JULY  
 TOURS OF MAINE'S COAST  
 TRAVELING FROM BORDEAUX TO LONDON  
 FESTIVALS IN TUSCANY AND UMBRIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Kans., Mo., Iowa, France, Italy) (For release Sunday, March 19) 
(DW) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. As someone who loathes the constant snap, crackle and pop of
neighborhood fireworks that seem to go on for a week preceding
Independence Day, where could I, my partner and perhaps even our
Labrador retriever go for a fireworks-free holiday? _ S.W., Kansas
City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   A. You might try a farm or a ranch vacation _ far from populous
areas where fireworks are more likely to go off. We checked on
ranch vacations and farm bed-and-breakfasts in Kansas, Missouri and
Iowa, and came up with a few possibilities:
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks and Spurs Ranch, (417) 683-2381, on the Big Beaver
Creek River in Ava, Mo., is about four hours from Kansas City. It
offers traditional ranch activities, like riding, as well as
fishing on the river. The owners promise there will be no
fireworks. A week at the ranch, including meals, is $1,100 a
person, based on double occupancy. No pets, however, so Fido will
have to stay home with his paws over his ears.
</P>
<P>
   Garst Farm Resorts near Coon Rapids, in western Iowa, (712)
684-2964, fax (712) 684-2887, has a kennel on the property and is a
five-hour drive from Kansas City. Khrushchev visited this farm in
1959. If you reserve the Woodland Carriage House ($120 a night,
with room for up to seven) on this 4,500-acre farm, you'll be about
four miles from the Coon Rapids fireworks display, according to Liz
Garst, one of the owners. No meals are included. There is canoeing,
mountain biking and horseback riding (all at extra cost). Cattle
and buffalo are raised on the farm. On the Web: www.farmresort.com.
</P>
<P>
   About two and a half hours from you, in the Flint Hills area of
Kansas, is the Homestead Ranch, a 4,000-acre working cattle spread.
It has a bunkhouse that rents for $150 a night (meals extra), with
a hot tub outside on the deck. Jennifer Maceau, who runs the ranch
program, says that she can't recall the last time she heard a
firecracker out there. Guests can go mountain biking on the rolling
hills, ride horses (extra cost), fish in the ranch's ponds or help
with the chores. Call (316) 753-3416; Web site:
www.guestranches.com/homestead. No pets allowed.
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   Iowa Division of Tourism, (888) 472-6035, www.traveliowa.com.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas Travel and Tourism Development Division, (800) 252-6727,
www.kansas-travel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Division of Tourism, (800) 877-1234, on the Web at
www.missouritourism.org.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Q. We are planning a windjammer cruise out of Rockland, Me., in
the latter part of June. Afterward, we would like a guided tour of
coastal Maine for five to seven days. Are there any bus-tour
companies operating out of Rockland or Portland providing this
service? _ E.S.L., Sarasota, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. The selections are limited, because Maine's summer tourism
season is relatively short. But two companies may be able to
provide some help, and the owner of a third offered some free
advice if you're willing to do the driving.
</P>
<P>
   Mainely Tours, 5{ Moulton Street, Portland, Maine 04101, (800)
282-1240, conducts half-day tours of the city. Its Lighthouse
Lovers tour ($25 a person) stops at four lighthouses and is offered
three to four times daily in summer. It also combines a tour of
Portland, where Winslow Homer painted, and Casco Bay for $21.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Line Tours, 184 Main Street, Portland, Maine 04106, (800)
341-0322, offers a three-day tour from Portland to Bar Harbor this
summer. The dates are June 23 to 25 and July 14 to 16. It includes
two nights at the Holiday Inn Sunspree, on Eden Street one mile
from downtown Bar Harbor, a tour of Acadia National Park, a
whale-watching cruise and a lobster bake. Prices are $289 a person,
double occupancy, for the June trip.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Hayward, who operates Harbor Light Tours, 162 North Main
Street, Rockland, Maine 04841, (207) 594-8170, usually takes large
groups on custom-designed tours. But he offered to put together an
itinerary for a driving tour, free, if you'll rent a car and do
your own driving.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am planning a driving trip in France this July. I need to
find an airline that flies from Bordeaux to London at a reasonable
fare, because we plan to drop off our rental car at the airport in
France and visit London for a few days before returning home. _
J.F., Manalapan, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. The lowest one-way fare we found by checking on Travelocity
and Expedia, using July 8 through 11 (a Saturday-to-Tuesday period)
as an example, was the same each day: $320.72 (actually, the fare
was 8 cents higher on Travelocity).
</P>
<P>
   This was on flights listed under British Airways, but flown by
Air Liberte, using a Fokker 100. The flight takes about 90 minutes,
landing at Gatwick Airport. A similar fare was offered on the
British Airways Web site. Conditions apply to this fare, including
cancellation penalties, and there is no guarantee it will still be
available when you book.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Q. A few years ago, my family and I visited Tuscany and Umbria.
While driving through the countryside, we came upon a medieval
festival. It featured the townspeople in period costumes
demonstrating traditional skills, such as papermaking, dyeing,
weaving and candlemaking _ on streets that had all traces of the
20th century removed or concealed. We will be back in the area this
June and were wondering if you could suggest any such festivals
then. _ Georgia Wood, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. There is one major medieval fair that will be held in the
region while you will be there.
</P>
<P>
   In Bevagna, a town in Umbria about 22 miles from Perugia, the
Fair of the Gaite takes place June 16 to 25. This is a re-creation
of life during the Middle Ages. Along the streets and alleyways of
Bevagna, the inhabitants of the four Gaite (town wards) will
compete with one another to reproduce the typical workshops, inns
and markets of those times. There will be shows, concerts,
exhibitions and conferences as well as an archery contest. But the
main focus of the fair is traditional craftwork; in the cramped,
dimly lighted workshops, artisans will demonstrate original
techniques. Contact the Umbrian Touristic Promotion Board, Via
Mazzini 21, 06100 Perugia; telephone (39-075) 575951, fax (39-075)
5736828.
</P>
<P>
   If you can extend your stay, you can see the Festa Medievale,
July 1 and 2, in the town of Vicopisano in Tuscany, about 9 miles
from Pisa and 18 miles from Lucca; call (39-050) 796511, fax
(39-050) 796540.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
