<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TAKING THE ULTIMATE BIKE RIDE IN THE BAY AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The ultimate Bay Area bike ride _ a loop of 475
miles in nine counties _ features the best of the best: the coast,
ridge lines, mountains and remote valleys.
</P>
<P>
   This trip will start at the Golden Gate Bridge and be routed
south to the Peninsula Skyline to Highway 9 and Los Gatos, then
loop around the Santa Clara Valley and up to Mount Hamilton, over
the top and down the other side to Livermore. Then the trip will
take riders across the Antioch Bridge, and up through the foothills
to the Napa and Sonoma Valleys, out the Russian River to the coast,
and then down to the flank of Mt. Tamalpais and across the Golden
Gate Bridge back to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It rivals the back roads of Vermont with fall colors as the most
scenic bike ride in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is this: Where to stay at night? The Bay
Area has 25 campgrounds, but none are located along the ideal
route.
</P>
<P>
   But now comes the solution. It turns out that the Greenbelt
Alliance has solved that, arranging with a half-dozen churches on
the route to allow camping during the week of April 16-22 leading
up to Earth Day.
</P>
<P>
   That is providing a one-of-a-kind chance to complete this trip
in a week, riding an average of about 70 miles a day. It is planned
as a ``group ride,'' though the term is used loosely, because
typically riders will get strung over great distances; it will be
limited to 70 participants.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the loop ride will be on roads, though even the bike
trails on the route will be paved. So riders with light road
touring bikes with skinny tires are well suited. Yet according to
Amy Tanner at Greenbelt, about half of the early sign-ups are those
with mountain bikes who have never completed a long-distance trek.
After all, for many, this will be too good to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Greenbelt is organizing this trip is to show off the
best of the Bay Area's open space, and in turn, inspire people to
join the mission to protect it. That is Greenbelt's sole mission.
About 600,000 acres in the Bay Area foothills has been preserved
for open space and recreation, according to Greenbelt, and another
600,000 acres are at risk, with the most critical areas identified
as the Hayward hills, Peninsula foothills east of Skyline, and open
space in north Marin and south Sonoma counties.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects who want to join Greenbelt on this epic Bay Area loop
ride are required to raise a $600 sponsorship to cover their costs.
For information, phone 1-800-543-GREEN.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any of the seven planned routes can be ridden or
driven at any time, perhaps to test if you are up for the
challenge, or just to enjoy the region's prettiest landscapes. Here
is a preview:
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 1: San Francisco to Los Gatos, 68 miles, featuring Golden
Gate Park, Ocean Beach, Skyline Boulevard on the Peninsula, and
Highway 9 in the Santa Cruz Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 2: Los Gatos to Evergreen College in East San Jose, 67
miles, featuring the foothill of Mount Umunhum, and the canyons of
Uvas and Coyote lakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 3: From Evergreen College to Livermore, 76 miles,
featuring the twisty but gentle grade up Mount Hamilton and over
the other side in to San Antonio Valley (wildflowers galore) and
north along Mines Road.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 4: Livermore to Fairfield, 82 miles, featuring Vasco Road,
over the Antioch Bridge in the San Joaquin Delta and through the
Montezuma foothills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 5: Fairfield to Santa Rosa, 62 miles, featuring the
Silverado Trail and Sonoma County wine country.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 6: Santa Rosa to Olema, 74 miles, featuring the Russian
River Valley out to Highway 1, then heading south on the coast past
Tomales Bay and Point Reyes National Seashore.
</P>
<P>
   _ Day 7: Olema to San Francisco, 46 miles, featuring the
Shoreline Highway south to the flank of Mount Tamalpais and then
across Golden Gate Bridge to San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
