<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL SURCHARGES ADDED TO AIR AND BUS TICKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, March 19) 
(DW) 
 By BETSY WADE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of oil is affecting travel everywhere. Surcharges of
$20 on a round trip are being added to most airline tickets.
Airport shuttle prices are inching up. Although a spokesman for
Greyhound Lines says increases in the cost of driving improve the
company's business, Greyhound has also added a fuel surcharge.
Officials in the hotel industry, noting the possibility that higher
prices will bring a downturn in travel, say there could be an
impact there, too: inexpensive motels might lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   The increases are unpredictable. Supershuttle, an airport van
service in many major cities, has added a charge of 50 cents to its
trip prices. But Gray Line, which serves airports in New York, has
not, although Lee Gelber, a spokesman, said that the fare for the
day trip to the Woodbury Common mall had increased by $1. On Feb.
2, Olympia Bus Service raised its fare from the Port Authority Bus
Terminal in midtown Manhattan to Newark Airport from $10 to $11,
but created a round-trip fare of $20. A spokeswoman called it a
fuel surcharge, but acknowledged that it was unlikely to be
withdrawn. This supports the notion that a surcharge is simply an
increase that will stay even if oil prices drop.
</P>
<P>
   Air passengers are feeling the biggest impact right now. Last
week brought turmoil in fares provoked by fuel costs, but even
before that, the major lines followed Continental's lead in adding
$10 to each one-way fare. But because Southwest Airlines has not _
although it has increased fares slightly _ some other airlines are
not adding the surcharge in areas where they compete with Southwest
or other discount lines. For example, United's service in
California does not have surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   My encounter with the fuel surcharge uncovered what appears to
be the most eccentric pattern in its application. I went to a
Continental ticket counter last month to exchange two senior
coupons for a round-trip ticket to San Antonio in April. For those
unfamiliar with senior coupons, all the lines sell them to people
over 62 for roughly competitive prices; each coupon is good for a
one-way flight in the 48 states. My coupons cost $579 for four, and
I was expecting to use two _ or about $289 worth _ for my San
Antonio trip.
</P>
<P>
   The agent said there would be a $20 surcharge, bringing my fare
to $309 for a schedule that required a connection on the way home.
This was irritating. I made another choice, a ticket for $355,
figuring I would use the coupons when they represented a greater
saving.
</P>
<P>
   Not all airlines impose the extra charge on the coupons, I
discovered when I examined the major lines' fuel-surcharge
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Continental put its $10-each-way surcharge into all domestic
markets on Feb. 1. As I found, it adds the charge to senior coupons
when they are turned into tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Both American Airlines and Trans World Airlines are adding the
surcharge to all their domestic tickets regardless of the
competition, they say. Both put the charge into effect Feb. 1;
neither adds a surcharge to senior coupons. If the tickets were
bought before the increase took effect, it is not added later. Jim
Brown, a TWA spokesman, said that when the line had a fare sale for
four days in mid-February, there was no fuel charge on those
tickets. There might be such sales again, he said. But when asked
if the surcharge was ever going to go away, he said ``no comment,''
as did every other airline spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
   American, TWA and all the others add the fuel charge if the
passenger changes an itinerary on a ticket purchased before the
surcharge went into effect. This is on top of the regular fee for
changing a ticket. The airlines contend that it becomes, in effect,
a new ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines imposes the charge in most markets, according
to Dennis Mollura, a spokesman. ``In competitive markets,'' he
said, ``we do what the competition is doing.'' Senior coupons are
not surcharged.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, according to Joseph P. Hopkins, a spokesman,
matches Continental and Southwest where it competes with them.
Senior coupons are not surcharged.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways levies the surcharge in most domestic markets, but
not on the Boston-New York-Washington shuttle. US Airways adds the
charge to tickets bought with senior coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Delta also adds the surcharge to most domestic tickets, except
where it competes with low-price airlines, according to John
Kennedy, a spokesman. The Boston-New York-Washington shuttle is
exempted, as are senior coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines disdains a fuel surcharge; Ed Stewart, a
spokesman, said, ``A fare increase is a fare increase.'' On Jan.
25, Southwest increased its ticket prices $2 for a trip of up to
600 miles; $3 for 600 to 900 miles, and $4 for more than 900 miles.
The increases are doubled for a round trip.
</P>
<P>
   Both the American Society of Travel Agents and an organization
called the U.S. Travel Agent Registry, a group formed in 1995 that
says it has 780 member agencies, sent complaints in January and
February to the Department of Transportation saying that the
airlines' computer fare displays did not show the fuel surcharges,
or other added fees, on the first screen. Sam Podberesky, in the
department's regulatory division, combined the two complaints, and
the department has asked several airlines to respond.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints can be read on the Web at dms.dot.gov. When the
``search'' box appears, enter the last four digits of the docket
identifier: OST-200-6821.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the ground, Greyhound increased fares 1.5 percent
in late January. ``Part is fuel, part is a general price
increase,'' said George Gravley, a spokesman. ``We have a lot of
trouble raising prices,'' he said. ``But we pick up passengers
because of the cost of driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Gale C. Ellsworth, president of Trailways, said that its 54
franchised operators were responding individually. ``Some are
calling it a surcharge,'' Ellsworth said, ``some are calling it an
increase.'' Peter Pan, in New England, has added 50 cents for any
one-way trip, and Adirondack Trailways in New York went up 5
percent across the board.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices for cars have taken a huge swing, from an
average of 96 cents a gallon for self-service regular unleaded in
February 1999 to $1.37 last month, according to AAA figures. Jerry
Cheske, a AAA spokesman, said prices would probably continue to
rise. But, he said, the response has been different from 1990, when
gas prices rose and in August ``tourism almost fell through the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see the kind of outrage we saw then,'' he said. The
economy is better and people are driving vehicles that use a lot
more gas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If people who drive on their vacations hold back this summer,
according to Warren J. Marr, director of hospitality and leisure
consultants at PricewaterhouseCoopers, it will affect prices at
less expensive hotels but not luxury places.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have to do business will still do it,'' Marr said,
``but there may be more aggressive pricing at the lower-priced
hotels by summer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
