<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MARS-GEOLOGY-ART-     03-13 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-GEOLOGY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPLIT GEOLOGICAL PERSONALITY OF MARS EMERGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 1 and 2 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the loss of two Mars-bound spacecraft last year, the
reliable Mars Global Surveyor keeps orbiting the planet 12 times a
day, well into the third year of its mission, and taking mapping
pictures of the landscape that are up to 50 times as detailed as
any previous photography there. The sharper focus is giving
scientists a clearer and more intriguing view of the planet's
two-faced geology.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient cratered highlands of the southern hemisphere of
Mars could not be more different from the low, flat plains of the
north, possibly the basin of a former ocean. A new gravity survey
suggests how water from the south once found its way to the
northern basin.
</P>
<P>
   Even the poles are, well, poles apart in appearance. The
differences in the size, content and seasonal change in the polar
ice caps were recognized in earlier spacecraft photography. But
more detailed pictures have now revealed something of the distinct
underlying topography at the poles and may offer clues to the
climate history of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists examining Global Surveyor's closeup pictures said the
flat, pitted texture of the north polar ice cap resembled cottage
cheese, while larger pits, holes and flat-topped mesas of the south
polar cap looked more like Swiss cheese.
</P>
<P>
   The much more extensive northern residual ice cap, the part that
survives the summer, is frozen water. The southern residual cap
seems to be made of frozen carbon dioxide, or dry ice. Scientists
said the new pictures might help them decide if the southern ice
cap was only a thin veneer or a solid block extending to depths of
more than a mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unusual shapes of the land forms on the north and south
polar caps suggest that these regions have had different climates
and histories for thousands or perhaps even millions of years,''
said Dr. Peter C. Thomas, a planetary geologist at Cornell
University.
</P>
<P>
   The new interpretations of the two faces of Mars were described
in interviews last week and in reports in the current issues of the
journals Nature and Science. Thomas was the principal author of the
Nature report on the polar ice caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``These findings indicate that the differences between the caps
are substantial (rather than reflecting short-lived differences in
frost cover), and so support the idea of long-term asymmetry in the
polar climates of Mars,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The southern region, for example, is much drier and colder than
the north and stands at a higher elevation. The Swiss cheese aspect
of the southern cap, geologists said, appears to be the result of
periodic collapses of deposited ice and dust, probably influenced
by the underlying topography.
</P>
<P>
   In another report on Global Surveyor's findings, published in
Science, a team of geophysicists led by Dr. Maria Zuber of the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology described gravity
measurements revealing the structure of the crust of Mars _ and
more evidence of the planet's split geological personality.
</P>
<P>
   The varying pull of gravity caused the spacecraft's orbital
altitude to change slightly, the motions showing up in its radio
transmissions. From these variations, scientists plotted
differences in the planet's subsurface density. They determined
that the crust was thickest under the southern highlands.
</P>
<P>
   A more refined analysis of the gravity measurements has revealed
what the scientists described as likely traces of buried channels
that could have been carved out by floods of water from the
southern highlands flowing into the northern lowlands billions of
years ago. The channels, which once were on the surface but have
since been filled and covered over by sediments, were as much as
125 miles wide and more than 1,000 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   If these are indeed water channels, scientists said, they could
be important evidence for the existence of oceans and a warmer
climate in the planet's early history, conditions that might have
been conducive to the emergence of life. In an accompanying
article, several scientists cautioned that there could be other
explanations of the gravity measurements and that it would be
difficult to test which was correct.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
