<HEADER>
A5610 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      03-13 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Also moving in the ``E'' category) &QL; 
Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``AFTERBURN'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Colin Harrison (FSG, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The thing about thrillers is that so many of them are bad.
Abysmal, even. It's a genre so plagued by hack writers and
bush-league prose that when you find one like this, you want to
call it by another name. But a thriller it is _ the long, patient
kind, with underplayed dialogue and characters who sidestep
stereotype every time it shows up to claim them. The protagonist is
Charlie Ravich, a former Vietnam fighter pilot and POW now in his
late 50s who faces crisis in his private life and in his
multimillion-dollar corporate affairs. Harrison spends much of his
book establishing a thin connection between Charlie and a young
woman named Christina Welles, who has just been released from
prison and who, with her former boyfriend, is suspected of stealing
from a mobster who really, REALLY, wants his money back. There's
sex. There's violence (we don't want to spoil your fun if you have
a taste for it, but for the sake of the squeamish, we'll mention a
little torture scene involving an electric drill and a circular saw
_ and that's not the last of it). If you can take the gore, this
book is enough to give a weak genre a good name. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``CINEMA SOUTHWEST'' &QL; 
 &UR; By John A. Murray (Northland, $21.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The photo on the cover is of John Ford making a scene from ``The
Searchers'' in 1956, but that's just the predictable side of
filmmaking in the American Southwest. Think of the alternatives. In
1965, Max Von Sydow, as Jesus, delivered the Sermon on the Mount on
Utah's Green River Overlook in ``The Greatest Story Ever Told.''
Dennis Hopper and Peter Fonda camped in Anasazi ruins on their way
east in ``Easy Rider.'' Robert Duvall turned his life around on the
Texas prairie in ``Tender Mercies,'' and in ``Bonnie and Clyde,''
Warren Beatty and Faye Dunaway robbed an actual bank in the rural
community of Pilot Point, Texas _ the same bank that the real
Bonnie Parker and Clyde Barrow had robbed about 40 years earlier.
In this book, due out at the end of the month, Murray looks at the
Southwest and its starring role in so many American films. Included
are some great photographs _ our favorite, we confess, is of John
Wayne (in ``She Wore a Yellow Ribbon'') looking grandly out at that
mist-shrouded Big Daddy of film locations, Monument Valley. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``EATING WELL FOR OPTIMUM HEALTH'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Andrew Weil (Knopf, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a chapter here in which Weil sets out to devise what he
calls ``the worst diet in the world,'' which after a few paragraphs
sounded so suspiciously like our own bill of fare that we began to
wonder whether Weil had us under surveillance. It was humbling, but
more fun to read than, say, the section called ``A Healing Story:
From French Fries to Kale,'' or ``The Macronutrients: An
Overview.'' But we are not hopeless, no siree. We love broccoli. We
love salmon. Unfortunately, we have learned from Weil that not all
salmon are equal, that we need to worry not only about our own
diets but about the diets of the fish we eat, which is one step
further down the food chain than we care to go. Eggs are another
research project. ``Eggs of chickens,'' Weil writes, ``(are) good
sources of omega-3 fatty acids if they come from free-range
chickens or chickens whose diets are supplemented with omega-3-rich
algae.'' Are we up to this task? No, but we know that Weil has made
many converts-to-wellness, so rush to the store: His new book is
out, with the author looking hale and hearty on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``TIGERS IN THE SNOW''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Peter Matthiessen (North Point, $27) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most of us know that the tiger is beautiful, but we also have
been raised with an unshakable idea of its fierceness, the
fearsome, predatory aggression of Shere Khan in Rudyard Kipling's
``The Jungle Book.'' But Matthiessen points out that the hunter,
Jim Corbett, in his book ``The Man-eaters of Kumaon,'' refers to
the tiger as ``a large-hearted gentleman of bottomless courage.''
That's what this book aims to give you _ a new look at the tiger,
at its history, its endangered habitats, its dwindling numbers, its
extreme vulnerability to poachers, and finally, at the efforts of
researchers and wildlife biologists to study and preserve it. The
book also conveys the quiet majesty of the animal, largely through
the author's eloquent interest and regard for it. With an
introduction and color photographs by Maurice Hornocker, tiger
expert and co-founder of the Siberian Tiger Project. Matthiessen's
fans should also look for ``The Peter Matthiessen Reader''
(Vintage, $14), in which editor McKay Jenkins assembles excerpts
from the author's books of non-fiction, including ``The Snow
Leopard'' and ``Men's Lives.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1735EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT     03-13 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS CAPTURE CHECHEN REBEL FIGURE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After a series of battlefield reversals, Russia has
captured one of Chechnya's most notorious warlords and whisked him
to Moscow to stand trial, Acting President Vladimir Putin said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian agents seized the warlord, Salman Raduyev, without a
fight on Sunday, Putin said. Raduyev, a Chechen commander best
known for a daring 1996 hostage-taking raid in neighboring
Dagestan, was taken to Moscow's Lefortovo prison, where he was
shown Monday night on Russian television.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was one of the most wanted men in Russia, Raduyev's
capture was not as significant as the capture of the chief rebel
leaders would be. Raduyev is not nearly as important a leader as
the rebel chief known as Khattab, an Arab and self-declared Islamic
warrior, or Shamil Basayev, who lost part of a leg in fighting,
both of whom have managed to elude Russian forces so far.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the reported arrest of Raduyev was a political gift to
Putin, an ardent proponent of the war, who has endured a week of
discouraging news from Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the recent reports by his military have not been
reassuring. Just last Friday the Russian military announced that
156 of its troops had been killed that week, one of the highest
weekly tolls during more than five months of fighting in the
breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
   The losses included 84 paratroopers from the Russian town of
Pskov, who died in a single battle after they were overrun by a
band of an estimated 1,500 militants. Russian commanders had
earlier denied that so many paratroopers had been killed, and the
disclosure has undermined the Russian government's already shaky
credibility with the Russian public.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the Russian military's humiliation, Chechen rebels
have managed to break out of the Chechen highlands, where Russian
commanders had insisted the Chechens were surrounded.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels seized the village of Komsomolskoe, on the edge of
the Chechen lowlands. After a week of Russian air strikes and
artillery raids, militants still appear to be lodged in the
village, which, like Grozny, is gradually being reduced to a ruin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war is not over,'' Col. Gen. Genndai Troshev, the deputy
commander of Russian forces in the North Caucasus, recently
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month the Russian high command had declared the war
all-but-won and had even begun to talk about bringing many of the
troops home.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent bad news has prompted a debate over the Russian
military's training and tactics. And it has spurred fears that
Russia is mired in an open-ended conflict that will continue to
send young Russians home in zinc coffins.
</P>
<P>
   The growing anxiety among the public has not been enough to
erase Putin's formidable lead in the opinion polls. But with the
presidential election less than two weeks away, Putin was
nonetheless eager to find something positive to talk about, and he
cast his report of the capture of Raduyev by a team of Russian
intelligence agents as a blow against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he is in prison, which is the right place for him,'' Putin
said. ``We would like to think this is just the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was Raduyev's capture announced that Russia's acting
prosecutor general charged him with terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will get what he deserves,'' the prosecutor general,
Vladimir Ustinov, said. ``The final decision rests with the Russian
court. So let's not try to guess whether he will be behind bars for
20 or 50 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Raduyev, 33, is a relative of Dzhokar Dudayev, the leader of the
Chechen republic who was killed during Chechnya's earlier effort to
secede, which ended with a defeat for Russian troops but without
independence.
</P>
<P>
   But Raduyev is best known for the 1996 raid he led into
Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   He seized a hospital, taking doctors and patients hostage, at
the Dagestani town of Kyzlyar and demanded that the Russians agree
to a cease-fire. He negotiated his way out of Kyzlyar and later
fought his way back to Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have also blamed him for organizing the bombing of
a railroad station in Pyatigorsk in 1997. Raduyev has also claimed
that he was behind an assassination attempt against President
Eduard Shevardnadze of neighboring Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Raduyev suffered serious head wounds during the first war in
Chechnya and went abroad last year for plastic surgery. He
reportedly signed an agreement promising not to seek retribution if
the operation failed.
</P>
<P>
   The captive's facial injuries were apparent Monday night on
Russian television, where he was shown at the Lefortovo prison, the
former KGB prison in central Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Shorn of his beard and without sunglasses, Raduyev was shown
giving his name, date and place of birth. The left side of his face
appeared battered and his eye was distended.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said that Raduyev had been arrested without a
fight near the town of Novogroznensky and that his personal guards
had been unaware of his whereabouts until it was announced by
Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said Raduyev would face trial, but Putin
talked as if he had already been convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seizure of hostages at the village of Pervomaiskoye and
the town of Kizlyar is on the conscience of this criminal,'' Putin
said. ``These terrorist actions have claimed victims among the
civilian population.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1736EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
