<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5616 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-2TAK     03-13 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG MAINTENANCE PROBLEM AT THE HMO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn.)   (Science Times)  
 (af)  
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The initials HMO stand for health maintenance organization, but
where, I'd like to know, is the ``health maintenance'' these
organizations are supposed to provide? Despite the extensive
reorganization of medical care that this country has witnessed in
recent years, the system remains penny-wise and pound-foolish. And
you, the consumer, are paying the price _ with your health as well
as through your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of negative publicity has been given to the fact that,
under so-called managed care, even people in need of urgent care
often have to take extreme measures before they get optimal
treatment or referral to an appropriate specialist. But not enough
attention has been paid to the failure of medical insurers to cover
the costs of keeping people healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Because we have long known that the best way to deal with an
illness is to prevent it and the second-best way is to detect it in
its infancy, it is time for consumers to start demanding that
managed care plans uniformly provide coverage for well-person
checkups, screening tests for early detection, programs to help
people shed unhealthy habits and more effective guidance for
dealing with chronic health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Under traditional medical policies, like major medical
insurance, doctors were routinely forced to lie on insurance forms,
claiming that their patients who saw them for health maintenance
had medical problems so that insurers would cover the cost of the
visits.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs, with their supposed emphasis on keeping people healthy to
keep medical care costs down, were supposed to put an end to all
that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are many serious and potentially costly problems,
like alcohol abuse, overweight and undue stress, and habits like
smoking, inactivity and poor diet, the treatment of which are
rarely covered by managed care.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent report the Center for the Advancement of Health, a
nonprofit health care watchdog organization in Washington, pointed
out that ``although nearly half of the nation's premature deaths
are linked to such things as unhealthy diet, inactivity or
substance abuse, few managed care plans routinely use proven
strategies to help their enrollees change these behaviors.''
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, the center reported, health plans that do
offer some services to help members modify risky health behaviors
or better manage chronic health problems simply hand out pamphlets
or brochures, a tactic ``known to be ineffectual'' in helping
people make the needed changes in their living habits.
</P>
<P>
   The center based its conclusion on a survey of medical directors
of health maintenance organizations in five states and the District
of Columbia, interviews with public and private health care
purchasers and a review of the literature on the effectiveness of
behavior-change interventions within medical settings.
</P>
<P>
   Both the HMO survey and interviews with purchasers of health
care policies investigated to what extent coverage was provided for
services intended for reducing health risks _ like smoking
cessation, exercise programs, nutritional counseling and treatment
of substance abuse _ and for managing chronic diseases like asthma,
back pain, depression and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that HMO medical directors are unaware of the
influence of people's living habits on their health. The report
found that most directors believe that health behaviors powerfully
influence health outcomes. In fact, studies have shown repeatedly
that modifiable health risks add significantly to the costs of
health care, accounting for as much as 70 percent of all medical
care spending.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the HMO directors were reluctant to include health behavior
interventions in their provided coverage in part because they were
uncertain about the cost impact of doing so, the center report
stated. Preventive efforts incur costs up-front, but their payoffs
may be many years down the line, further, apparently, than most
managed care plans are able to see.
</P>
<P>
   However, the costs of unhealthy behaviors are often incurred
short-term as well as long-term. For example, in December in The
Journal of the American Medical Association, Dr. Nicolaas P. Pronk
and colleagues at the HealthPartners Center for Health Promotion in
Minneapolis studied a random sample of 5,689 health plan enrollees
ages 40 or older to determine the short-term health care charges
related to physical inactivity, obesity and smoking.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They found that smokers had 18 percent higher medical care
charges than people who never smoked, each unit of increase in body
mass index (a BMI between 19 and 25 is considered ``normal''
weight) raised medical charges by 1.9 percent and each day of
physical activity per week reduced medical charges by 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Neither are the purchasers of health care plans in the dark
about the role of health behaviors in preventing disease and
reducing complications from pre-existing illness. Most purchasers
interviewed by the center believed that ``the managed care plans
they contract with are responsible for health behavior change
services (and) those plans are already providing such services as
part of a comprehensive health benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   However, few purchasers actually negotiate with health plans for
coverage of specific behavior change services, the survey revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is time for those who sign health care contracts to
look more closely at the services that are actually provided,
especially those negotiating contracts for employees, who remain at
the mercy of unions and employers to provide health care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps all concerned should heed the advice of the Minneapolis
researchers: ``Health plans and self-insured employers seeking to
maximize health return on each dollar spent for medical care may
wish to consider strategic investments in interventions that
effectively improve modifiable health risks. Primary prevention of
smoking and increased physical activity appear to have substantial
potential to reduce health care charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what can the health-conscious consumer do? You might
try petitioning your health insurer to cover the cost of a needed
health maintenance service, like a program to quit smoking or, for
someone at risk of heart disease or diabetes, a consultation with a
dietitian and exercise physiologist.
</P>
<P>
   A woman I know who was dangerously obese and had failed
repeatedly at various weight-reduction efforts was initially told
by her insurer that surgery to treat her obesity would not be
covered because she had no obesity-related health problem. Her
response was, ``Why wait until I'm sick? Why not treat me now so
that I can stay healthy?''
</P>
<P>
   She voiced her plea to a hearing committee set up by the insurer
and the company decided to cover the cost of her surgery, which
over the course of a year resulted in the loss of 150 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   But let's say coverage for the service you seek is denied. It is
still in your best interest to pay for the services you need, even
if that means making other sacrifices to make ends meet. It is hard
to imagine what is more important than your health, because once
you lose your health, everything else in your life is in jeopardy
as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
