</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   AETNA _ Aetna's rejection of a $10 billion takeover offer from
WellPoint Health Networks and ING Group should hearten shareholders
and investors in Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Georgia. WellPoint
is scheduled to buy Blue Cross, but its offer for Aetna, because of
regulatory concerns, had imperiled that deal. Meanwhile, Aetna
shares fell as much as 16 percent after the WellPoint bid was
turned down. (Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TURNER-NYC _ Turner Broadcasting System planted more Atlanta
roots Monday as Ted Turner said Time Warner has no plans to
relocate its subsidiary to New York. ``New York? It's bad enough to
go up and visit,'' Turner said before he helped TBS begin
construction on two buildings in Atlanta. (Wilbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERMERGER-ANALYSIS _ Analyzing the implications of the latest
newspaper merger. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ The stock market did something of an about-face on Monday
as investors returned to beaten-down blue chip stocks, while
high-tech stocks faced uncharacteristic selling pressure. Even the
shares of some blue-chip consumer stocks showed unusual gains,
including Procter &AMP; Gamble, which sank to a 52-week low last week
after warning that its profit performance this quarter won't be as
strong as expected. Colgate-Palmolive and Gillette also advanced
off last week's lows. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOILERROOM-BROKERS _ Five years ago, Daniel Porush sat atop an
empire built on deceit. Porush was president of Stratton Oakmont
Inc., one of the most profitable _ and notorious _ boiler-room
operations in the nation. Working for him were nearly 200
stockbrokers and salesmen who specialized in luring unwary
investors into risky ventures with promises of quick riches.
(Hiaasen, Palm Beach Post). 66.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SUMMIT _ FAIRFAX, Va. _ Michael Dell, chairman and CEO
of Dell Computer, addresses the 2000 Global Internet Summit, an
international Internet development conference. (Geewax, Cox News
