<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-13 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE GORE, BUSH BLAB CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W.
Bush have 34 more weeks to fill with mutual insults and assorted
accusations before we finally reach Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, dear. They may not get exhausted, but we certainly will. Ear
muffs, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   We already have heard a great deal of what they will say to each
other as they rehearsed their lines on their hapless primary
opponents. Both have made it clear they believe the end justifies
the means in this scrap. Anything goes, the nastier the better.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has repeated to Bush the offer he made to Democratic rival
Bill Bradley to hold twice-weekly debates; the catch is that it's
only a deal if the other guy agrees to abandon those 30-and
60-second attack commercials. Bradley didn't want to give up his
ads and he wasn't keen on too many debates with Gore, where he was
clearly outmatched.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore made his offer to Bradley, it was ridiculed as a
stunt, carrying the debate concept to extremes for his own selfish
purposes. Bush isn't about to take the bait any more than Bradley
did, for his own selfish reasons.
</P>
<P>
   This time the challenge isn't laughable; it is aggressive of
Gore to push debates and defensive of Bush to duck, conceding Gore
the stronger image. Debating about debates has a limited
public-interest shelf life, however.
</P>
<P>
   Previous sparring partners have discovered that debating Gore is
hard, uphill work and Bush is not yet ready. He may not be the dim
bulb he is portrayed, but his mental information retrieval bank on
both domestic and foreign affairs is not nearly as deep as Gore's.
Former GOP vice presidential nominee Jack Kemp, who proved
inadequate against a relentless Gore in their own 1996 debate,
advised Bush succinctly in a Sunday interview: ``Start preparing
right NOW.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much the news media like the idea of debates in
principle, two a week is too much of a good thing. That translates
into 68 debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy guacamole,'' as my grandson Michael likes to say. The
mind reels. How many insults and put-downs can they invent to fill
all that time?
</P>
<P>
   But those nasty, repetitive and expensive commercials are too
much of a bad thing, and any proposal to get rid of them should be
taken seriously. And that leads us into the issue of overhauling
the campaign finance laws and the soft money (the unregulated
donations to political parties and causes) that pays for most of
that advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bush have raised a lot of campaign money, although
Bush's $70 million so far takes the prize. Gore is now campaigning
to overhaul the money-raising system, even though for eight years
he willingly participated in it. Bush, who seeks more modest
changes in the fund-raising system, calls Gore hypocritical. Gore,
in turn, calls Bush a captive of his rich donors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush repeatedly raises Gore's visit to a Buddhist temple during
the 1996 campaign _ during which Democratic campaign funds were
improperly raised _ as an example of Gore's lack of ethics. Gore
insists he did not know the event was a fund-raiser and says he is
playing by the rules as they exist, just as Bush is.
</P>
<P>
   But this rapidly deteriorating argument is not all this campaign
is about. Pat Buchanan, clawing for political attention, contends
there are no basic policy differences between Gore and Bush; their
competition is a ``nothing-burger'' he says _ presumably all filler
and no beef. Buchanan, as usual, is wacky.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty to argue about here, if they would just get to
it and stop the name-calling. The two men differ on most social
issues _ abortion, judicial appointments, the treatment of gays,
the validity of the Confederate flag, protecting the environment.
They differ on education _ more direct aid for public schools
versus tax-paid vouchers to subsidize private schools.
</P>
<P>
   They differ on the size, scope and direction of tax cuts _
whether to have large cuts that mostly help the wealthy or smaller
cuts that leave money to pay for Social Security and some new
domestic programs. They differ on the substance of health care
reforms. They differ on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Where they disagree on foreign policy is still murky. The
subject doesn't come up much.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has already made some minor boo-boos on international
topics, revealing a governor's limited experience with such issues.
By contrast, Gore can be boring when he details his extensive
acquaintance with world leaders and their problems.
</P>
<P>
   But something will come up. It always does. China will thumb its
nose at us. North Korea will pull some stupid stunt. Kosovo will
deteriorate into full-scale warfare. Ireland will fall apart again.
Middle Eastern terrorists will strike. Russia will be Russia. The
candidates will be expected to understand the strategic
implications and respond accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   So there will be plenty to talk about, after all. But can we
please have a few moments of silence somewhere along the way to the
conventions?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
