<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER14-COX     03-13 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: No compromise on attacks
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to grab the fund-raising reform issue for the general
election, George W. Bush and Al Gore accused each other of
compromising for campaign cash. ``This guy will say anything to get
elected,'' Bush told high school students in Metairie, La., on
Monday. He said ``It's going to be a heck of a challenge'' to run
against such a foe but that he hoped ``the American people will see
through all the rhetoric.'' Gore was visiting a Miami-area hospital
Monday, repeating charges that Bush cares nothing for expanding
access to health insurance because it's not a priority for his
campaign financiers. Later Monday, Gore flew to Nashville, Tenn.,
to vote for himself in Tuesday's Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   MORE SNIPING OVER GUNS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, citing a ``sickness'' at the heart of the gun lobby,
blasted the NRA Monday and demanded an apology from executive
director Wayne LaPierre. A day earlier, LaPierre said President
Clinton is ``willing to accept a certain level of killing to
further his political agenda _ and the vice president, too.''
</P>
<P>
   BUT IT'S GOOD PRACTICE IN VOTING
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's Southern primaries were supposed to be the Southern
Super Tuesday, the day when the South muscled its way into the
primary calendar and showed itself as a fearsome voting bloc. But
Mike Francis now has a somewhat different name for it. ``I call it
Stupid Tuesday,'' said Francis, chairman of Louisiana's Republican
Party. ``The taxpayers of Louisiana are going to spend about $4
million so that maybe 40,000 people can show up to vote in a
meaningless primary. Isn't that ridiculous?''
</P>
<P>
   `FRESH, NEW,' AND NOT MUCH OF A CHANCE
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan said Monday that George W.
Bush hasn't shown the ``depth or capacity'' to be president and Al
Gore is marred by improper fund-raising in 1996. Buchanan said he
would be a ``fresh, new'' alternative for voters. Buchanan said he
could appeal to John McCain's voters who want an anti-establishment
candidate. Interviewed on NBC, Buchanan predicted the race would
look this way: ``Bush: same old, same old. Gore: same old, same
old. Reform Party: fresh, new.''
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE NOT THE BEST WAY TO GAIN SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan hopes to pick up supporters from John McCain's
suspended GOP campaign, but won't back away from his strong
anti-abortion stance or his call for a ``cultural war.'' Such
positions are at odds with most of the Reform Party's members and
also unlikely to appeal to the independents, moderate Republicans
and Democrats who supported McCain. Ex-party Chairman Russell
Verney, a top aide to party founder Ross Perot, said, ``The
majority would be best described as secular. They don't want the
government to take a position on those issues.''
</P>
<P>
   PATAKI READY TO LOOSEN THINGS UP
</P>
<P>
   Stung by accusations that he had tried to stack the deck in New
York's primary for George W. Bush, Gov. George Pataki is proposing
a more open primary next time around. Pataki's proposal, announced
Monday, would allow all nationally recognized Republican
presidential candidates onto the New York ballot and make the
state's primary a winner-take-all contest for the party. New York
Republicans also would get to vote directly for the candidates, not
for delegates as is currently the rule.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T QUOTE HIM ON THAT ONE
</P>
<P>
   With exit polls from the early primaries showing that some
voters are concerned about whether George W. Bush has the
intellectual heft they believe is required of a president, Al Gore
returned repeatedly to versions of the same refrain: ``Does
Governor Bush have the kind of decision-making tests under his belt
to be president?' ... the experience? ... the sense of
perspective?'' Asked in an interview with The Associated Press if
he wasn't really trying to say Bush is ``too dumb'' to be
president, Gore convulsed in laughter while taking a drink of Diet
Coke. He grabbed a towel to hold against his mouth then, finally
swallowing, insisted the tape recorder be stopped for an
off-the-record observation.
</P>
<P>
   NEW PARLOR GAME: PICK THE RUNNING MATES
</P>
<P>
   Reporters for several media outlets are discussing possible vice
presidential candidates. For Republicans, the list includes Sen.
Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, who backed John McCain in the primary
season; Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania; Elizabeth Dole, the former
Cabinet member and presidential candidate; Sen. Fred Thompson of
Tennessee, a supporter of government reform; and Dick Cheney, a
former Defense secretary. On the Democratic list were ex-Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, an articulate economics expert; Gov. Gray
Davis of California; and Sens. Dianne Feinstein of California, Evan
Bayh of Indiana and Bob Graham of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   LOW TURNOUT, MORE DELEGATES FOR GORE
</P>
<P>
   A smaller-than-expected turnout of about 11,000 people at the
first Democratic weekend caucuses in Minnesota gave Al Gore a near
sweep in a binding presidential poll. Gore also was expected to
pick up all 20 delegates at stake after a resounding victory Sunday
at caucuses in Nevada where there were even fewer voters. With 14
of 17 counties reporting in Nevada, Gore led 92 percent to 8
percent over Bill Bradley. State Chairman Rory Reid noted that
there was no chance Bradley would get the necessary 15 percent in
either of Nevada's two congressional districts to win any
delegates. More than 1,000 Nevada Democrats voted Sunday, up from
about 600 four years ago, Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING AGAINST BOB JONES U.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, eager to regain control of Congress, are trying to
tie Republicans to Bob Jones University, the fundamentalist
Christian university in Greenville, S.C. In the Senate, Democrats
pushed a resolution condemning the school, while in the House, the
party's fund-raising arm distributed a memorandum on Bob Jones'
policies and urged candidates to use it to attack Republicans.
Until earlier this month, the school had anti-Catholic statements
on its Web site and forbade interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE OF CONFIDENCE FOR INTERNET BALLOTING
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's first-of-its-kind Internet election showed online
voting can work with a relatively small population. The question
now is whether it can succeed with much larger groups. One way or
the other, critics and supporters agree that eventually most
Americans will have the option of voting by clicking a computer
mouse. The primary drew about 78,000 ballots, doubling the state's
previous turnout record. ``We opened up the gates today to people
who might not otherwise have voted,'' state Rep. Leah Landrum said
at a victory party for the Internet voting that ended Saturday.
``This is something I know is going to stick around.''
</P>
<P>
   EVERYTHING IN MODERATION
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman says the GOP must convince
voters that the extreme right wing of the Republican Party doesn't
represent the whole. ``The reality for us is we have to convince
enough of the American people, especially those who are in the
center, that our party shares their concerns and shares their
ideas,'' she told the Republican Leadership Council. Whitman
accused Democrats of portraying the party as one that has forgotten
its roots. ``That's what Al Gore and the Democrats want to do ...
persuade people that the Republican Party has left them,'' she
said. ``This year our biggest challenge is to make sure this tactic
doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   DEMONSTRATIONS IN CHAPPAQUA
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen protesters chanting ``Israel yes, Hillary no,''
demonstrated in Hillary Clinton's new neighborhood in Chappaqua,
N.Y., but roughly 40 police officers kept them away from the
Clinton home and she was in Washington. The protesters denounced
the first lady's support for the current Mideast peace process, and
claimed she was against freeing Israeli spy Jonathan Pollard. The
protesters were from groups including Kach and Kahane Chai, said
Michael Guzofsky, a protest organizer. Both groups are on the State
Department's list of terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY NIGHT FEVER
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton and Rudy Giuliani met face-to-face for the first
time since she began campaigning in New York more than a year ago.
Both were roasted at an Inner Circle spoof on New York politics
staged by political reporters Saturday night. The annual show is
renowned for its rollicking tastelessness. Many jokes, some of them
crude, were made at Clinton's expense, but the Washington Post
reported that she proved she could take a hit. Giuliani put on some
disco moves in a white suit, then dressed in drag for a skit titled
``Rudy/Rudia.'' The two candidates shook hands and exchanged
pleasantries.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
