<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARINO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONAL MARINO TAKES A PASS ON FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ In a speech marked by long pauses, deep sighs, and
throat clearing, Dan Marino announced his retirement from football
Monday at the Miami Dolphins' training facility. Marino struggled
to keep his emotions in check as he read a statement and then
answered questions in a somber auditorium filled with more than 200
reporters, family, friends, and former Dolphins. He called the
choice to retire without changing uniforms and without a Super Bowl
ring ``a family and a health decision.''
</P>
<P>
   As the most prolific passer in NFL history reflected on the
``huge loss'' he felt leaving the league after 17 record-setting
years, his face fell into a stoic grimace. He paused, pursed his
lips, puffed out his cheeks, and waited for the swell of emotion to
pass before continuing. Marino did not shed any tears, but took his
time and chose his words carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 17 years, I would like to announce my retirement from
the Miami Dolphins,'' said Marino, who has no immediate plans for
his post-football life but is considering many options, including
business opportunities and television. ``After playing the game of
football most of my life, this was an extremely difficult decision.
But I know that I have made the right decision for me and my
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud of the success that we have had as a team for
17 years as well as all my individual accomplishments. Not many
people have the opportunity to spend 17 years of their life doing
what they truly love to do. And as I stand here before you today, I
can say that I have been blessed with a career greater than I could
have imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite strained relations in recent weeks between Marino and
the Dolphins, the quarterback's retirement was intended to be a
celebratory affair. Marino had received mixed signals about how
warmly the organization would welcome him back for another season.
Conspicuously absent from Marino's lengthy list of thank yous _
which included everyone from the video man to Don Shula _ was
former Miami coach Jimmy Johnson. Marino acknowledged that he
``wasn't very happy here'' while Johnson was coaching.
</P>
<P>
   But Dolphins owner Wayne Huizenga, taking the podium after
Marino, left no doubt about how much Marino meant to the
organization. Huizenga immediately retired Marino's No. 13 and
announced plans to induct Marino into the Dolphin honor roll at the
first regular-season home game, name a street after Marino at the
stadium, and erect a statue of the quarterback outside the stadium.
The tributes brought a smile to Marino's face, but they could not
erase the bittersweet feelings the occasion evoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad for me, but I'm happy for him because he was able to
go out on his terms,'' said former Dolphins wide receiver Mark
Clayton, who caught more Marino touchdown passes than anyone else.
``I just happy to have had the opportunity to catch a pass from my
man.''
</P>
<P>
   The last passer selected in the heralded quarterback class of
1983 at No. 27, Marino was the last to retire. And he left the game
holding 25 NFL records outright and sharing five others. Marino
stands atop the list for passing yardage at 61,361 _ outdistancing
John Elway by almost 10,000 _ including a record 5,084 in 1984. He
passed for a record 420 touchdowns, including an almost
unfathomable 48 in 1984. He also leads the NFL in career pass
attempts (8,358) and completions (4,967).
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time in mini-camp when we first got Dan down here and
standing side-to-side with our other quarterbacks, it was just so
evident that he was something special,'' said Shula, Marino's first
coach in Miami. ``He had that great year in '84, which is the year
with the records that may never be broken. It's hard to say never,
but the 48 touchdown should hold up. (There was) the Super Bowl
that year, the great career and the feeling you were never out of a
ballgame with Dan Marino as your quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that he's made this decision, I'm supporting it. I think
that this is a celebration of a great career, that's how I think
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as Marino's numbers are, the lack of a
championship ring remained an issue until his very last day as a
Dolphin. The quarterback said the only reason to continue playing
would have been the chance to win a Super Bowl. A shot at a ring
was also the reason he seriously entertained the thought of playing
for the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the burning desire,'' said Marino. ``I think that I
wanted to know what it felt like as a player to win a Super Bowl,
and any time you have a chance maybe to get that, you are going to
want to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Marino took great pride in the fact that he played
his entire career for the Dolphins. And the absence of a
championship ring will not diminish what the quarterback achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a moment, you get caught up in that you won't see Dan
Marino on Sundays,'' said former Dolphin and Hall of Fame center
Dwight Stephenson. ``But then, you look at the positive side and
that's what Dan will do. Time to do something else. Whatever he
does, I'm sure it's going to be exciting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
