<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT     03-13 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK'S BELEAGUERED COALITION SURVIVES FOR ANOTHER DAY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ For the first time, poetry _ Palestinian poetry, no
less _ was used Monday to try to topple an Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
   But scores of other subjects, small and large, have been
employed as potential vehicles of dethronement. In Israel's
turbulent democratic system, where there is no such thing as an
argument without talk of divorce, parliamentary motions of no
confidence in the government are becoming more and more routine.
</P>
<P>
   Monday alone, the parliament debated two motions of no
confidence in Prime Minister Ehud Barak, one from the right and the
other from the left.
</P>
<P>
   A third was withdrawn from the floor at the last moment.
</P>
<P>
   Both motions failed, and Barak, who is facing frustration on
several fronts _ in his peacemaking efforts, the police
investigation of his election campaign and the instability in his
coalition _ remained in power. The results were not surprising
because it would have taken a two-thirds vote, or 80 out of 120
votes, for the lawmakers to remove Barak and stay in office
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak's beleaguered government endured what is becoming an
institutionalized part of the parliamentary theatrics here. It
withstood hours of verbal battering by those who choose the extreme
vehicle of seeking to bring down the government in order to seize
the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Eroding the government's authority is a side benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty dull tool, emptied of significance by overuse,
like crying wolf,'' said Yaron Ezrahi, a political scientist at
Hebrew University. ``But it's better than a regular vote because
it's a more dramatic parliamentary gesture. The media carry it.
People are tense, attentive. There is horse-trading involved. And
while it cannot really destroy a government, it can hurt it.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Likud Party argued Monday that a decision to
include five works of a nationalist Palestinian poet in the
literature curriculum for Israeli high school students was grounds
enough to declare no confidence in the government.
</P>
<P>
   Mahmoud Darwish, 58, the poet, who has written 25 volumes of
verse, received unexpected exposure in an unlikely forum. He was
the object of a raging literary criticism session in the
flat-roofed bastion of Zionism that is the parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Having perused his works, right-wing lawmakers cited verses of
his that they found inflammatory and violently anti-Zionist. And
one Labor Party legislator, Colette Avital, gave a tender reading _
in Hebrew _ of a lyrical and seemingly apolitical poem that began,
``A woman I am, no more, no less.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, addressing her colleagues, Avital said: ``Will this be an
open, pluralistic, democratic society while respecting different
traditions? Or will we keep ourselves locked up within the confines
of a kind of spiritual and intellectual ghetto? Is Darwish, whom we
have so successfully made famous because of this debate, such a
threat to our strength?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, answered, Uzi Landau, speaking for the Likud Party. ``If
you want to teach Darwish,'' Landau said, ``show him to be one who
demonizes us, but do not legitimize him. We are legitimizing our
own delegitimization.''
</P>
<P>
   Yossi Sarid, the leftist education minister, who modified the
curriculum to include several new writers, denounced ``the way that
every public debate deteriorates into a vote of no confidence,''
and said he never imagined a few poems would provoke such
``hysteria.''
</P>
<P>
   The first motion lost, 42-48. But it was supported by all the
members _ though not the ministers _ of the rigorously Orthodox
Shas party, which is the most problematic of three balky partners
in Barak's six-party coalition. The National Religious Party
members also voted against the government in which they sit, and
Yisrael Baaliyah, the Russian immigrant party, walked out before
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Likud Party officials are starting to strategize effectively for
the first time since they moved into the opposition with Barak's
election. They are pushing votes on issues that Shas, the National
Religious Party and Yisrael Baaliya cannot support without
alienating their members.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Israelis have cast separate ballots to select their
prime minister and their parliamentary representatives. A motion of
no confidence that passed by an absolute majority of 61 votes would
dissolve the entire government, forcing both lawmakers and the
prime minister to go to new elections. But unless the political
scenario is dire, few lawmakers choose that route and the bar for
removing just the prime minister remains high.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Shas was specifically voting against Sarid, the
education minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked for a connection between Darwish and Sarid and found
that their names are comprised of the same letters'' in Hebrew,
said Nissim Zeev, a Shas lawmaker, reflecting the mysticism that
many in the party attach to numbers and letters.
</P>
<P>
   Shas leaders and Sarid have been engaged in an intense battle
over the financing, management and curriculum of the parochial
schools that are the center of Shas' &UR;  &LR; growing power base among
Israel's poor and working-class Jews of Middle Eastern origin.
</P>
<P>
   But Shas, as it frequently has, was also demonstrating once more
that it considers itself a free agent. Shas' 17 votes, which the
prime minister wants desperately to back his peace efforts, can
swing for him or against him, its leaders have said repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   As if to demonstrate what would await Barak if Shas were to bolt
his coalition, the Communist Party, which mostly represents Israeli
Arabs, offered its own motion of no confidence. If Barak were to
alter his coalition or lose the three balky parties, he would be
forced to rely on the Israeli Arab parties. But they, too, as
indicated Monday, have a price.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Arab lawmakers said the government does not care about
the disparity in the way that Jewish and Arab convicts are treated.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a Jewish settler sentenced to life imprisonment for
an execution-style killing of a Palestinian terror suspect was
given parole after seven years in jail. The decision highlighted
the more lenient way that the Israeli legal system treats Jews who
have committed nationalist murders.
</P>
<P>
   After the votes, Barak rose from his seat in the parliament with
a tight, tired smile. Later, brushing off the hours of incendiary
debate, Barak said, ``Nothing that occurs in the parliament can
move this government from the mission that was imposed on it by the
nation of Israel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1807EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5647 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FEEDING-TUBE14-COX     03-13 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEEDING-TUBE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Trust intuition, love over latest medical trend
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's been seven months since my mother's
doctor said it was time to make the feeding tube decision.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding tube. An ugly phrase sure to take away your appetite.
Roll it around on your tongue, practice it. Ponder its
implications. There is a feeding tube in your future, one way or
another. Be prepared. You'll be learning lessons in pathology,
medical ethics, the law, nutrition, theology and metaphysics.
</P>
<P>
   My mother's muscles, including those in her throat, are
contorted and spasmodic with Parkinson's disease. Sometimes she
can't swallow.
</P>
<P>
   She is almost 90, so there's more, of course. Her short-term
memory loss is now total. Her vital signs are just fine, but her
dementia has removed her, for the most part, from this world. She
is prone to infections. The good news? She can't move, so she won't
be breaking a hip.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were my mother,'' her doctor said last year, ``I would
not insert a feeding tube.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, my mother was hospitalized, fighting numerous
infections, any one of which could kill her. She had a high fever
and was delirious on top of everything else. Something was going to
give. It looked like the end to us. It looked like the end to her
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   He had just taken over her care from a doctor who taught us the
first lesson: When in doubt, get answers. If you don't get answers,
get a new doctor.
</P>
<P>
   My mother's new doctor was attentive, perceptive and intuitive
(very important). He's a humanist and a scientist, too. Which is a
good thing, because he inherited a patient with enough untreated
ailments to fill a ward.
</P>
<P>
   So the stage was set. My mother was virtually comatose, perhaps
in the final stages of her dementia and Parkinson's. And we _ my
brother, sister and I _ agreed with her physician's feeding tube
philosophy. No extraordinary or artificial measures.
</P>
<P>
   But my mother had not signed a living will, so her doctor wanted
_ needed _ complete agreement on our part. Second lesson: Sign
living wills when everybody is competent. Don't wait. Your sick
mother may nod, yes, she wants to go to heaven. But does she mean
today? And are you prepared to send her?
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL JOURNALS WEIGH IN
</P>
<P>
   Just to make all of us family members feel more comfortable with
our momentous decision, medical literature was slamming feeding
tubes. The New England Journal of Medicine finally said what
doctors have known for years: Feeding tubes do not improve life for
comatose patients and the elderly in the final phase of dementia _
a terminal disease. They can cause infections and can be painful.
But not in all cases. They're overused in nursing homes, where
overworked staff save management time, money and possible lawsuits
by routinely hooking up patients to feeding tubes.
</P>
<P>
   So, our decision was simple. On the surface. We assumed we would
be called upon to veto the feeding tube, officially, within hours
or days.
</P>
<P>
   But then the doctor made a final suggestion: Let your mother's
live-in nurse take your mother home if we get the infections under
control. Maybe the infections are clouding the issue, he said. If
we can get her eating again, make her comfortable, maybe we can
stop the IV lines and get her back to a level where, possibly, she
can enjoy a limited but meaningful life. The doctor was skeptical
of his own plan, but it offered my mother a long shot, and if it
didn't work out, well, we all would have done the best we could.
</P>
<P>
   Now, here's the key to this story: My mother's live-in caregiver
and the women who fill in for her on occasion are extraordinary
women. The main caregiver _ and some glowing ember of my mother's
fiery will _ wrought a remarkable change. This woman brought my
mother back with a spoonful of mush at a time. A thimble of water
at a time, given slowly and with infinite patience. My mother's
infections are gone. Fever, gone. A change of Parkinson's
medications made for fewer problems swallowing. Within a week of
going home, my mother regained her previous state of awareness,
which isn't much.
</P>
<P>
   There's wasn't a lot of Mom left, but there was still some Mom
in Mom. More than the doctor had thought.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't often recognize her children, but then again,
sometimes she does.
</P>
<P>
   When I brought her flowers from my garden, she leaned over to
drink in the aroma. ``Nice,'' she said. ``Bring more.''
</P>
<P>
   When I asked her if she was Italian or Irish, she threw me a
hard look, as if I were the foggy one, and said, ``Irish. My
parents were Mike and Mary Quinn, from Galway.''
</P>
<P>
   When I tell her she's so small she wouldn't stand a chance
against me in a boxing match, she says, ``Try me.''
</P>
<P>
   When I brought my children to see her at Christmas, she knew
them all.
</P>
<P>
   Her doctor was surprised, incredulous actually. ``I didn't know
how strong she was,'' he said. ``And I didn't know of the
incredible power of the women who are caring for your mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, her doctor changed his mind and advised the
insertion of a feeding tube, to be used on those occasions when my
mother can't swallow. Her feeding tube is not extraordinary life
support, not a futile gesture to sustain a life already lost. Third
lesson: All feeding tubes are not the same. The medical journals
didn't present their findings in black and white, but some press
accounts paraphrased away the gray areas. Do your homework, as Mom
used to say. Read the primary sources.
</P>
<P>
   QUALITY OF CARE IS CRUCIAL
</P>
<P>
   The cost of her home care will deplete my mother's modest
estate, but it's my mother's money, no? And, my brother the tycoon
makes up the shortfall each month, to the tune of many thousands of
dollars each year. But not everyone has a tycoon for a son, or a
live-in nurse from central casting, or a wise and contemplative
doctor. Fourth lesson: Quality of life is wrapped up in quality of
care.
</P>
<P>
   My mother's quality of life? Diminished, to say the least. But
it's her diminished life. Whatever dreams she dreams are hers. Her
memories, visions, no matter how clouded they seem, are hers. She's
not in pain; her vital signs are good.
</P>
<P>
   Her dementia will get my mother some day. A clot, a final
hideous infection, kidney or liver failure. Something. No amount of
care or money can change the final chapter. She will cross a
boundary into a region of near-death where feeding tubes may well
have no place. But she's not there yet.
</P>
<P>
   Thing is, had we gone with the new conventional wisdom on
feeding tubes, she'd already be there and gone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
