<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5648 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOCHCO14-COX     03-13 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOCHCO14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once and again, `NYPD Blue' is red hot in ratings
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Danny Sorensen is a fidgety,
night-sweating mess, burdened by some secret in his past. Lt. Fancy
is reaching out to a fellow African-American officer who's burning
out big time. The new guy, Detective Baldwin Jones, has brought an
urbane and brooding presence to the 15th Precinct house, as well as
a willingness to doff his shirt on camera.
</P>
<P>
   And fans of ``NYPD'' have been glomming on to each new episode
like a snitch on a C-note. The cop show's audience has increased
more than 10 percent this season _ from 14.4 million viewers last
season to 16.2 million _ almost unheard of for the seventh season
of a TV drama.
</P>
<P>
   You could argue that it's been the compelling story-telling
(Jimmy who?). But it hasn't hurt that ABC delayed the season
premiere of ``Blue'' until January and is in the middle of running
22 straight episodes through the end of May, without a single rerun
or pre-emption.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years we've fielded hundreds of letters and phone calls
from people p---ed off at the erratic scheduling of `NYPD,''' said
Steven Bochco, ``Blue's'' co-creator. ``It's on for two weeks, it's
off for three weeks, it's on for four weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The rerun-free run is ``a big plus for our viewers, and it
really galvanized our audience.''
</P>
<P>
   At 56, Bochco is an elder statesman of TV producers (he gave
David E. Kelley his first job in television back in the 1980s), who
still wears jeans and denim shirts around the office and puts on a
tie only when he has to. He's the antithesis of a network suit,
even though he almost became one. In 1987 he was offered the
presidency of CBS, but he decided to go on being a producer.
</P>
<P>
   Time for reinvention
</P>
<P>
   Bochco has been a constant critic of the way the networks
continue to do business, both in their outmoded economic models and
in their aversion to risk. One of his messages is that networks are
losing their audience because they won't try edgy, adult programs
such as HBO's ``The Sopranos'' and ``Sex and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to sit on the sidelines. If I were running a network
today, I certainly wouldn't have only `The Sopranos' and `Sex and
the City' and `NYPD Blue.' But I certainly would insist on making
room for that kind of program.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at so much of what is on television, so much of
it isn't very good that it's hard to justify leaving it on. If we
don't get serious and change our game, we're going to be left in
the dust,'' he warned. ``We ought to be reinventing the medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't reinvent it at the expense of one of his shows. The
reason ABC waited until January to go ``Blue'' was that it was
keeping the new drama ``Once and Again'' in ``Blue's'' home, 10
p.m. Tuesdays, and was even considering booting ``Blue'' to another
slot completely. That sign of disrespect made Bochco go ballistic,
and months later it still rankles him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the move worked for ``Blue,'' still the most grown-up show
on network television in terms of realistic street language and
partial nudity. When it debuted in 1993, advertisers rebelled
against the profanity, and ABC was nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to put something on network TV the likes of which
you could only see on cable. We had no net,'' Bochco recalled
recently on the 20th Century Fox lot, sitting in his office at the
production company he owns. ``If for some reason people hadn't
tuned in, that show would have been gone instantly, in three
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``NYPD'' racked up Emmy Awards and became a Top 20 show;
advertisers line up to get on. What it didn't do, however, was open
up network dramas to more adult content, the way many predicted it
might if it was successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really see what's changed, and I'm surprised at
that,'' Bochco said. ``To me, `NYPD Blue' exists in its own little
world. I don't know that it's opened up any floodgates.''
</P>
<P>
   Bochco's other show, ``City of Angels'' (8 p.m. Wednesdays on
CBS), hasn't fared as well. A hospital drama with a predominantly
black cast and writing staff, it launched in January with a huge
buildup as the ``great black hope'' of prime-time television. But
it has sunk to 89th in the Nielsen rankings, averaging an
unimpressive 8.8 million viewers a week.
</P>
<P>
   The show is getting a face-lift to try to appeal to more
viewers. The lighting is brighter, the gospel music on the
soundtrack has given way to more modern music, and stories are
being punched up.
</P>
<P>
   Even failures are interesting
</P>
<P>
   Bochco is no come-lately to writing about African-Americans. One
of his pre-``Hill Street'' shows was ``Paris,'' a short-lived ABC
series that starred James Earl Jones as a criminologist. And Henry
Simmons has brought a smoldering presence and strong black
consciousness to ``NYPD'' as Baldwin Jones. In a throwaway line
several weeks ago, he quietly explained that he was named after
writer James Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Steven Bochco Productions, the producer's private office
is dominated by a large, disturbing painting by Joel Pace titled
``Falling,'' inspired by a James Dickey poem about a stewardess
sucked out of an airplane door; it shows a woman in midair free
fall, her clothes being sucked off by the friction. On a window
seat is a large, stuffed collie, one of Lassie's late stand-ins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It freaks actors out when they come in,'' Bochco explained,
referring to the dog, not the painting.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Bochco Productions is as proud of its failures, though,
as it is of its hits. In the large, open foyer, there are big
advertising banners for ``Cop Rock,'' the 1990 experiment at
blending ``Hill Street Blues'' with musical theater, and ``Murder
One,'' the post-O.J. drama that followed one murder case for an
entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``His failures are as interesting as his successes,'' said David
Marc, author of ``Prime Time, Prime Movers.'' That's an accolade
``usually reserved for great novelists and European film directors,
but almost never for TV producers.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
