<SLUG> BC-COLONCANCER-WEB14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Couric on colon cancer crusade
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'll be seeing a lot of TV personality Katie Couric this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, her husband, Jay Monahan, died at age 42 of colon
cancer. Shocked to learn that this little-discussed disease is the
second-leading cause of death from cancer _ and that it is
substantially preventable _ Couric vowed to increase public
knowledge and funding.
</P>
<P>
   The first fruit of her efforts was getting March named the first
National Colorectal Cancer Awareness Month. The awareness campaign
includes a series about the cancer that ran on NBC's ``Today'' show
last week and can still be viewed online (at www
</P>
<P>
   .msnbc.com/news/todaycoloncancerfront
</P>
<P>
   .asp). The campaign also includes celebrity appearances on
television and in print media.
</P>
<P>
   Colon cancer strikes 130,000 Americans every year and kills
55,000 of them, one in four of whom are under age 50. When caught
in its earliest stages, more than 90 percent of cases can be cured.
The American Cancer Society advises all men and women 50 or over to
have a yearly fecal occult blood test, plus flexible sigmoidoscopy
every five years, or colonoscopy every 10 years, or a double
contrast barium enema every five to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some additional Web sites with information about colon
cancer:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.nccra.org/ _ The site for Couric's charity, the National
Colorectal Cancer Research Alliance. Also includes general
information about the disease and its treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.preventcancer.org/colorectal.htm _ Explains the monthlong
national awareness campaign, which is sponsored by the Cancer
Research Foundation of America.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www3.cancer.org/cancerinfo/loadcont
</P>
<P>
   .asp?ct &QC; 10 _ The colon cancer information page from the American
Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  cancernet.nci.nih.gov/CancerTypes
</P>
<P>
   /ColonAndRectalCancer.shtml _ The National Institutes of
Health's colon cancer information page, with a useful set of
additional links.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.asco.org/people/rs/html/key
</P>
<P>
   /mkey.htm _ A page within the Web site of the American Society
of Clinical Oncologists, this offers a search engine for databases
on types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.cancereducation.com
</P>
<P>
   /cancersyspages/index.cfm?ct &QC; 1&AMP;CFID
</P>
<P>
   &QC; 258597&AMP;CFTOKEN &QC; 89344159 _ A well-designed, informative medical
portal, which can be personalized by the user.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.acor.org/ _ The Association of Cancer Online Resources, a
nonprofit site that helps cancer patients find information,
clinical trials and others who have been diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
