<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5651 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DAVID-CROSBY14-COX     03-13 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVID-CROSBY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crosby remains in harmony with today's fans
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this era of one-hit-wonder bands, it's hard to believe
Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young are touring again behind a strong new
album, ``Looking Forward,'' the group's fourth in three decades.
</P>
<P>
   More incredible, perhaps, is that David Crosby is still around
at all. His battles with drug addiction, the law and liver disease
have lately garnered the 58-year-old Rock and Roll Hall of Famer
more headlines in the tabloids than the rock press. The latest news
_ that he's the biological father of two sons born to Melissa
Etheridge's partner, Julie Cypher _ was the talk of the Grammy
Awards last month and grist for the nation's humor mill.
</P>
<P>
   We talked to Crosby by telephone from a tour stop in Dallas. Q:
Heard any good jokes lately? Seriously, were you surprised at the
response to your latest adventures in parenting?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not really. You don't have a choice about it, if you live in
the public eye. You just have to deal with it. It'll soon all be
gone. I'm really more concerned with playing music right now. If
people are looking to figure out who I am, the truth of that is in
the songs. And if they come to the concert, they'll get it. Can we
talk about the music now?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sure. How have concert audiences been taking to the new
music?
</P>
<P>
   A: The response has been unbelievable. When a band is out there
for as long as we have been, with music people know and love, you'd
think they want to hear that at the shows. But they want to hear
the new stuff. Some of the songs sound better now than when we
recorded them. (CSNY) has its own special chemistry; it's not like
CSN, or Crosby and Nash. When we started playing again, it was like
riding a bike. This may sound egotistical, but I think we sound
better now than we ever have. We're not any better looking
(laughs), but we're playing better.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you feel any connection with the Backstreet Boys and other
bands that are bringing vocal harmony-based songs back to pop
music?
</P>
<P>
   A: You listen to Boyz II Men, 'N Sync or the Backstreet Boys ...
and I like what they do with harmony, but those groups are mostly
constructions. They're put together by a producer and they don't
write the music. So they're very different from us. We construct
the music ourselves, and it's more organic. I love songs that are
finely crafted and songs that are about something. And I listen to
a lot of weird stuff, man. There's a great vocal group out there
called Kitka that you've never heard of. And I like Shawn Colvin
and Marc Cohn, Dave Matthews, Michael Hedges ... Venice. I love
songs that make people feel something.
</P>
<P>
   Q: CSNY has a history of recording a new album every 10 or 15
years or so. Will there be another CSNY record, and when?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have about half an album already in the can, so I think it
will come sooner than that. I've also got half of a CPR album done
also. So we'll probably finish that one and get CPR on the road
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   In Concert
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, Stills, Nash &AMP; Young
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. tonight. Philips Arena. $32.50-203 at Ticketmaster,
404-249-6400
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
