<HEADER>
A5652 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ELTON-JOHN14-COX     03-13 0400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELTON-JOHN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shine wears a bit thin on Elton's formulaic `El Dorado'
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he was pounding out ``Rocket Man,'' Elton John could not
have predicted his second career would be as the Richard Rodgers of
the preteen set. But after two Oscars, three Grammys and 10 million
in sales for the soundtrack to Disney's warm-fuzzy classic ``The
Lion King,'' it's not surprising that the '70s pop star would do it
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road to El Dorado'' (Dreamworks), John's second CD of
tunes written specifically for an animated film, arrives in stores
today.
</P>
<P>
   Once more, the 52-year-old artist teams with ``Lion King''
lyricist Tim Rice and composer Hans Zimmer on 14 tracks of sweeping
soundtrack music, this time penned for cartoon characters in search
of the lost City of Gold. Like ``The Prince of Egypt,'' also made
by Dreamworks Pictures, ``El Dorado'' uses radio-friendly pop tunes
to move the action, along with voices by actors such as Kenneth
Branagh, Kevin Kline and Armand Assante.
</P>
<P>
   John must really like this line of work. Of the 11 tunes he's
written here, including the single ``Someday Out of the Blue,''
only six are actually used in the movie. Three of these `bonus
tracks' are songs that were composed for the film but not included;
two tracks are songs written specifically for the album.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by hit singles such as ``Can You Feel the Love Tonight,''
John's ``Lion King'' soundtrack spent nine weeks at No. 1 on
Billboard's pop album chart. But this CD is nothing to roar
about.Though Dreamworks is mimicking that film's winning formula ,
the tunes here are as indistinguishable as bowling pins.
</P>
<P>
   As a showtune writer, John sounds like he's cutting these
melodies out on deadline from the same pattern tissue he used
before _ swelling piano, dramatic ``Candle in the Wind'' vocal
styling, even the required goofy duet (this time with Randy Newman)
that's become standard fare in every animated film made since Baloo
sang ``Bare Necessities'' in ``The Jungle Book.'' Though there's
twice as much material here, the album sounds like ``The Lion
King'' CD stuck on random play.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they should have named it ``Return to Simba.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road to El Dorado''
</P>
<P>
   Elton John. Dreamworks. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
