<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5653 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSTAND14-COX     03-13 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gays making progress fighting bias, report says
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You wouldn't know it by listening to talk-radio celebrity Dr.
Laura Schlessinger, but gays are gaining ground in their battle
against discrimination. In a 14-page investigation, Newsweek
($3.50) reports that a majority of Americans no longer considers
homosexuality a sin. Forty-six percent say it is, but that figure
is down from 54 percent in 1998. The Newsweek poll also shows
support for gays as high school teachers (63 percent), in the
military (69 percent) and political officeholders (71 percent). In
a separate poll of gay males and lesbians, most surveyed say their
main goals are getting equal rights in job opportunities, housing,
health insurance and employee benefits for gay spouses.
</P>
<P>
   The report includes a series of profiles demonstrating how gays
and straights are interacting in schools, the workplace, the
military, and the church. And, in a sidebar, Dr. Laura responds to
gay criticism of her stand against homosexuality by saying she
never meant to ``contribute ....to an atmosphere of hate or
intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jane and more: Talk ($3.50) dishes up quite an appetizing
issue this month, with a cover story on Tom Cruise, a fascinating
portrait of the chain-smoking 12-year-old terrorist twins Luther
and Johnny Htoo, and a short but interesting feature on Atlanta
pastor Gerald Durley . Touted by Talk as ``the man who saved Jane
Fonda,'' Durley remains mum on his relationship with Ted Turner's
estranged wife. ``All I can say is that I admire Jane,'' he says.
``I believe she is on a sincere, honest search for spiritual
wholeness.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The big four-oh. If you're turning 40 soon, don't worry.
You're not alone. According to U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($3.50),
the biggest class of baby boomers are hitting the midlife mark this
year. Unlike their parents, this group of soon-to-be
fortysomethings are healthier and more adventurous. For example:
Atlanta resident Arlene Vincent-Mark decided to quit her sports
marketing job at 40 and enroll in a Ph.D. program in international
relations. Now 45, Vincent-Mark, who ran the marathon in the 1988
Olympics for her native Grenada, plans to graduate in December.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hooray for Hollywood: Vanity Fair ($3.95) pays tribute to the
impending Academy Awards with a 470-page issue devoted primarily to
the movies. Articles include a 44-page portfolio of the great and
the glamorous, from Ashley Judd and Jude Law to Al Pacino and
Sidney Poitier, as seen through the lenses of Annie Leibovitz, Herb
Ritts, Bruce Weber and other acclaimed photographers. Most
impressive is a group shot of nearly every living writer and actor
who had been blacklisted during the McCarthy era. Also of note is a
fun piece by James Wolcott on the Rock Hudson-Doris Day romantic
comedies of the early '60s. The plots may have been as synthetic as
the fabric of that era, Wolcott writes, but films such as ``Pillow
Talk'' and ``Lover Come Back'' remain martini-and-fur-muff
classics.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Redesigned America: Time ($3.50) looks at the shape of things
and concludes that function is out and form is in. A new generation
of designers are leaving their mark on everything from
candy-colored computers to futuristic toothbrushes. Design used to
be considered ``precious,'' but now, says Time writers Frank Gibney
Jr. and Belinda Luscombe, it's available to all _ ``from the crowd
that shops at Target to those aesthetes who can pick out an Enzo
Mari from 20 paces.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Post mortem: The New Yorker ($3) writer mixes style and
substance its fashion issue. Michael Specter profiles Manolo
Blahnik, the famous Milan shoe designer who provides footware for
Madonna, and Susan Orlean offers her take on one of the
eye-catching elements at the Paris shows _ hot pants. On the
substance side, Jeffrey Toobin interviews Washington Post publisher
Donald Graham about the newspaper after Watergate. The Post, Toobin
says, ``is no longer the scrappy, irreverent paper it once was.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Publishing notes: Good news for those who can't get enough
celebrity news from People and Entertainment Weekly. Beginning
Friday, US magazine will become a weekly
publication....Cosmopolitan has surpassed TV Guide as the magazine
with the largest newsstand circulation. Cosmo reports its paid
circulation as 2.85 million with newsstand sales of 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
