<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5656 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN14-COX     03-13 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Worry not, or make your life a living `Elle'
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The practical man read Elle last week.
</P>
<P>
   And liked it.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the practical man wouldn't sully his hands with
fashion magazines, for they are trivial tomes for the terminally
insecure _ and incitements to revolt for housewives everywhere. But
since his doctor doesn't subscribe to Rivet Review, he figured what
the heck, he'd do some field research from the waiting room.
</P>
<P>
   And now he's a fan. Here's why.
</P>
<P>
   The models are nude.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the practical man wrong. He's no lonely lech leering
at little girls. He's just happy to welcome converts into his camp.
</P>
<P>
   For years, fashion was a mystery to the practical man. The
clothes were designed, presumably, to make women more attractive to
men, but the zillion-dollar get-ups ignored the obvious: Men don't
care about clothes. To them, one utterly average but naked woman
inspires more adoration than a dozen supermodels besotted by
sequins.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with innocent jubilation that the practical man
flipped through Elle, eyed the topless babes, and discovered that
fashion is finally making sense.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, he also discovered something else: Women scare
easy.
</P>
<P>
   This terrible truth was revealed on page 226, where women listed
30 common fears. Among them: (7) ``I'm afraid I'll date a
Republican,'' (15) ``I'm afraid I'll never meet Prince Charming,''
(18) ``I'm afraid I don't smell good,'' (25) ``I'm afraid I'm
ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   With a heavy heart, the practical man reviewed the sad catalog.
Overcome, he resolved to help his sisters, at least with the first
five.
</P>
<P>
   1. I'm afraid I'll be alone _ forever: The practical man urges
women to dispel their No. 1 fear as follows: Lower your standards.
</P>
<P>
   While it may seem untenable at first, this brilliant stroke
actually poses little risk, for once married, almost every Romeo
becomes a Ralph _ a probably fat and certainly self-centered dufus
primarily interested in sex and food. Aim directly at this target
from the get-go, and you won't be alone for long.
</P>
<P>
   2. I'm afraid I'm too clingy with men I like: Fear not, ladies,
for you can easily determine whether you are too clingy by quizzing
yourself as follows: Am I clingy at all? If the answer is yes,
you're too clingy.
</P>
<P>
   3. I'm afraid I made a lame career choice: You have made a lame
career choice. The practical man knows this because, had you chosen
wisely, you wouldn't be wondering.
</P>
<P>
   But while poor judgment is no cause for fear, it is cause for
action. So go back to school. Get another job. Keep trying till
you're content. A woman who has 15 jobs before she settles in for
the long haul is wiser than the dolt who drones on at one while
secretly moping about her ``career choice.''
</P>
<P>
   4. I'm afraid I'm losing my hair: There there, child. It's going
to be all right. Lean in close and let the practical man coo
consolation in your ear and calm those fears with well-chosen words
of wisdom. Ready? Here goes: SWEET JESUS, GROW UP!
</P>
<P>
   If you're losing your hair to chemotherapy, you've got something
to fear. Otherwise, bah! Let the locks fall and press on with
pride.
</P>
<P>
   5. I'm afraid I'll have to fake orgasms for the rest of my life:
Then don't.
</P>
<P>
   Fake anything infuriates the practical man, but there is no more
pathetic charade than faked sexual pleasure, which makes a mockery
of life's main event.
</P>
<P>
   Remedy: Stop faking and start talking. Once you've wised him up,
your guy will likely care enough to treat you right. If not, get a
new guy. Life is too short to keep your mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   READER Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: I'm sure mine is not the only response to
your blathering about Hooters. That guy took his son to Hooters
because he was too lazy to explain things himself; and he waited
about six years too long to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the real question: How would you classify a mother who
takes her daughter to a similar place for women to keep the girl
from muddling through puberty? Certainly not ``mother of the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Come on, be practical, Practical Man. Cut out that double
standard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathy Hickok, Delray Beach
</P>
<P>
   A. The only double standard the practical man admits is this: He
gets doubly ticked when people assume he has something against
women because he's ``practical.''
</P>
<P>
   If he saw a mom and Girl Scout at a beefcake bar, he'd write the
same column. But it's not his fault he doesn't join in on girls'
night out _ he is, after all, the practical man.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: Please weigh in (pun intended) on the ``Do I
look fat?'' question. Several days ago, my girlfriend asked me if
she looked fat. I said no, but she wouldn't believe me. She swore
she wanted an honest appraisal, so I told her she wasn't fat but
might be a little out of shape. Ever since, she's been saying
things like ``I guess I can't wear these jeans because they'll make
me look even fatter,'' and she glares at me. How does the Practical
Man respond to that question?
</P>
<P>
   A. Before the practical man blinds you with his brilliance, let
him confess that his insight into this thorny matter was hard won.
</P>
<P>
   In his early years, he assumed his fair maid actually wanted the
truth. Thus, he concentrated on gentle ways to deliver it _ riffs
like ``O Honey, I love your chub!'' He blames himself for the
ensuing tears, for he didn't understand what was being asked.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he drew up a wiser, two-pronged strategy.
</P>
<P>
   If his darling had put on a few pounds, he assumed she wanted to
know not the truth, but whether he found her attractive despite her
extended girth. Thus, his reply of choice became ``Don't be
silly!'' followed by a kiss juicy enough to keep her from pressing
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   If she was not fat, the practical man assumed she desired not a
mere statement of the obvious, but some suitably fawning
acknowledgment of her fatlessness. He would parry appropriately,
perhaps with ``Fat? Pshaw! The only thing you have in excess, my
dear, is beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   These were OK and pried the practical man out of many a sticky
situation, but he was still unsatisfied. A more elegant solution
would consist of a single, all-purpose response. He leaned his
brain into it, and crafted a master stroke:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I look fat?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweetheart, the question is meaningless. Women heavier than
you are fat. Those lighter, too thin. For in my eyes, you remain
perfect no matter what you weigh.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: About old discarded workers, I can identify
with your thoughts on this matter. I found myself on the outside
looking in after many years in the corporate world. I learned the
shoe maker trade and have been doing it full time for the past 15
years. I am 76 years old and work every day. I think it beats hell
out of golf and bowling and gives me a sense of doing something
that helps make the world go around.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anonymous, via e-mail
</P>
<P>
   Send questions and comments to The Practical Man, Accent, The
Palm Beach Post, P.O. Box 24696, West Palm Beach, Fla. 33416. Or
e-mail PracticalMan (at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
