A5662 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-EDIT-BRADLEY-AZR &LR;      03-13 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BRADLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY: HIS VOICE WAS WORTH LISTENING TO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Bill Bradley was crushed in the race for the
Democratic nomination. Al Gore won all Democratic primaries and
caucuses, with the coup de grace coming on Super Tuesday this week.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley has nothing to be ashamed of. In fact, he has much
to be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   The pundits will talk in the days ahead of the tactical errors
the former U.S. Senator from New Jersey made, and he did make his
share.
</P>
<P>
   He should have bypassed Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   He shouldn't have invested as much time and money in Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   He should have gotten tougher sooner and responded more
forcefully to criticism of his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't act quickly enough when his health became an issue.
</P>
<P>
   He should have been a more animated and spirited speaker and
campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   All true enough, but a campaign is not just about strategy,
pithy sound bites and style. Bradley helped inject thoughtful ideas
worth discussing into the race.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed an assault on children's poverty. Though the
remaining candidates can differ on how this should be accomplished,
this isn't an idea that should die.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed universal health care, forwarding a common sense
approach. Again, we can differ on approaches, but the number of
people without health insurance has long been a national scandal.
</P>
<P>
   He talked seriously about stricter gun control and reminded Gore
of some of his previous softness on the issue of a woman's right to
choose on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley and Gore shared similar views on education, both wanting
to provide more teachers, make preschool available to more, reduce
class size and help more people get to college. But, Bradley
differed in that he viewed continuing education as a life-long
endeavor, proposing to make it accessible at all stages of life,
not just for high school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's appeal for racial harmony and justice resonated, even
if the topic still causes too many eyes to glaze over.
</P>
<P>
   And, though his talk of ``goodness,'' never caught on, it, too,
is not a topic that should die. Doing the right things, for the
right reasons, is a worthy goal for a country.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley will not release the 412 delegates he did win in the
primaries, ensuring he has a voice at the Democratic Convention.
</P>
<P>
   It's a voice worth listening to. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
