<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5664 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-AZR &LR;      03-13 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN: SETBACK OPENS NEW CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In his campaign for the presidency, Arizona Sen. John
McCain once again served his country well.
</P>
<P>
   One valuable service his candidacy appears to have served,
largely unremarked upon, is to finally heal the nation's wounds
over the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The nation learned about and celebrated a hero from that war.
The nobility of McCain's sacrifice for his country overwhelmed the
dispute over whether the cause was worthy. McCain's manifest and
unaffected love for his country was a reminder and an example to
the rest of us of what is truly important.
</P>
<P>
   Because of McCain's candidacy, American foreign policy in the
future is likely to be much less clouded by the Vietnam War and the
sharp divisions in the country it caused.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign also raised the profile of a fundamentally
important issue: campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Money plays a disproportionate role in choosing our candidates
and influencing public policy. It causes the American people to
feel disaffected from their government.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is right that the stakes are high. If the American people
believe that their democracy is rigged, and increasingly they do,
it will be hard to enlist them in important national issues and
causes.
</P>
<P>
   In his comments announcing that he would no longer be an active
candidate for the Republican nomination for president, McCain
accurately identified how he can best serve his country in the
future: continuing to provide leadership on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   But if McCain is to ultimately succeed and complete his new
mission for his country, he will have to develop and deploy
leadership skills that heretofore have not been conspicuous.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of the influence of money in campaigns isn't simply
a matter of evil, bad guys _ special interests _ who have to be
stopped, and toady politicians who lack McCain's vision and courage
to stand up to them.
</P>
<P>
   The actions of government affect everyone. People, causes, and
organizations have a right to speak about and try to influence
government policy. And people and organizations have a right to
express their views, even during elections, and even if what they
have to say is distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   But voters have a right to know who is speaking, and candidates
need to have the ability to communicate with voters without
depending on, or being drowned out by, special interest money.
</P>
<P>
   If McCain is truly to lead a crusade to reduce the
disproportionate influence of money, and in the process restore
confidence in the integrity and fairness of American democracy, he
will need to listen to his critics rather than simply excoriating
them. And he will have to forge new approaches that bring broader
support than his existing reform proposals, and show greater
respect for the First Amendment rights of others, even those whose
influence McCain deplores.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has shown the leadership of courage. His next challenge
is developing and deploying the leadership skills necessary to
translate vision into policy, to become a consensus builder in
addition to being a critic. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
