<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, March 14 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   IMF-EUROPE (Washington) _ President Clinton has decided to
support Horst Koehler, Germany's candidate to be the next head of
the International Monetary Fund. Earlier Monday, EU finance
ministers, meeting in Brussels, had agreed unanimously to back
Koehler. Clinton decision ends a lengthy diplomatic contest over
who would lead the institution that battles global financial
crises. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds, subs dateline and byline.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR (Undated) _ The Tribune Co. and Times Mirror
Co., two media companies whose flagship newspapers helped define
the brawling, partisan days of 19th-century journalism, on Monday
announced plans to merge into a media company that would bring
their trademark regionalism to the multimedia world of the 21st
century. If nothing intervenes to disrupt the merger, the new
company, to be called Tribune Co., will own 11 daily newspapers, 22
television stations and four radio stations. Its combined audience
of newspaper subscribers and television viewers would give it a
much greater national profile. But its core strategy would be
regional, with a mandate to deliver news, entertainment and
advertising through print, television and the Internet. By Felicity
Barringer and Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics and map.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS (Pensacola, Fla.) _ A look at vouchers in
Florida, which was the first to grant them to students whose
schools fail standardized tests. The state will soon be the
nation's largest voucher testing ground and is the model for a
national program proposed by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
likely Republican presidential nominee. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-FUNDRAISING (Washington) _ A look at Hillary
Clinton's fund-raising dealings with one group. By Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-GENES-FOOD (The Hague, Netherlands) _ In Europe, the
debate over genetically modified food is as much about theater as
it is about science. Polls show that few Americans realize that
nearly two-thirds of the products on supermarket shelves contain
ingredients from genetically altered plants. But British tabloids
routinely call such ingredients ``Frankenfood,'' and pollsters say
only 1 percent of Britons think genetically modifying plants has
any value at all. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RECESSION (Tokyo) _ Defying official optimistic forecasts,
hundreds of billions of dollars worth of government spending and
other financial stimulants, Japan's economy revealed its underlying
vulnerability on Monday in statistics that showed a retreat back
into recession in the final three months of 1999. The Economic
Planning Agency said the gross domestic product, the total output
of goods and services in the world's second-largest economy, fell
1.4 percent in the October-December quarter, for an annual rate of
decline of 5.5 percent. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
</TEXT>
