<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5669 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      03-13 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBB-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPER TUESDAY SHOWED CAMPAIGN FLAWS, INSIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT ROBB  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Notes and observations coming out of Super Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   While John McCain's campaign finance proposal is deeply flawed,
and his rhetoric about it overheated, the campaign success he
enjoyed offers an important insight into the American electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans feel that their government, and the people who
manage it, do not care about them. This is a sentiment that cuts
across the political spectrum, and applies to all levels of
government.
</P>
<P>
   Political professionals tend to discount the power of issues
such as campaign finance reform because they do not show up as
salient in polls. But that is because, for the most part, people
are skeptical about whether a politician can do much to correct
this sense of disassociation with government.
</P>
<P>
   But when it appears that a candidate might, indeed, be able to
do something about it _ McCain, Jesse Ventura _ there is a strong
response.
</P>
<P>
   This will be an important underlying force in American politics
for some time to come.
</P>
<P>
   The chattering class is peddling the notion that George Bush and
Bob Dole lost the presidency because they were too closely
associated with the right wing. For this to be valid, the American
people had to perceive that Bush in '92 and Dole in '96 were more
conservative than Reagan in '80 and '84, and Bush in '88, when he
ran as Reagan's younger brother. Methinks not.
</P>
<P>
   The chattering class also thinks that the strategy that
backfired on McCain, assaulting the Religious Right, will work
wonders for Al Gore. The reality is that most Americans don't find
people who go to church and take their faith seriously all that
deplorable or alarming.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Religious Right is an unsteady part of the
Republican coalition, sometimes difficult to get out. One estimate
is that there was over a 20 percent drop-off in its turnout from
1994, when Republicans took over Congress, to 1998, when they
nearly lost it.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's attacks on Religious Right leaders turned out this vote
for Bush in the primary. Gore may very well do the same thing for
the general election, saving Bush the need to work at it.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that McCain's support came from former Reagan
Democrats, another chattering class superstition, is nonsense.
Reagan Democrats were primarily brought over on social conservative
issues. And many of them were in the South, subsequently became
Republicans, and helped deliver the death blow to McCain's
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   There has probably not been anyone in American political history
less suited to be vice president than John McCain. Can you imagine
him loyally and effectively defending a presidential policy with
which he fundamentally disagrees? I suspect George W. can't either.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised to see both Gore and Bush pick a woman as
their vice presidential nominee. Sen. Dianne Feinstein for Gore, to
lock in California. And Elizabeth Dole for Bush, who is the ideal
vice presidential candidate: widely popular, very articulate, with
few policy ideas of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Gore looked far more presidential in his non-acceptance
acceptance speech Tuesday evening than did Bush, who, while he's
improving, still doesn't quite look ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ought to deflect Gore's call to forgo campaign ads and
debate twice a week by saying: ``If being president requires
spending that much time with Al Gore, it's just not worth it.''
Americans of all political persuasions would nod their heads in
understanding and agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Bush should begin now to mildly express concern about what Alan
Greenspan is doing with the economy. If Greenspan succeeds in
hiking consumer interest rates and talking down the stock market,
it will have broad adverse impacts, including to core Democratic
constituencies, particularly now that nearly half of all American
families own stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore administration is inextricably linked to
Greenspan, and by acting now Bush can pin to Gore concerns over the
economy that may very well develop over the next eight months. &QL; 
Reach Robb at bob.robb(at)ArizonaRepublic.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1826EST &QL; 
