<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-CAPTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARED CHECHEN LEADER RADUYEV FALLS INTO RUSSIAN HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Stung by recent battlefield losses in separatist
Chechnya, Russian officials claimed a moral victory Monday when
they announced the capture of feared guerrilla leader Salman
Raduyev.
</P>
<P>
   Known for his bravado, fierce anti-Russian rhetoric, and thick
beard and dark sunglasses that hid battle scars, Raduyev is the
first rebel leader Moscow has managed to capture since troops
entered the breakaway region last September. Russia has been eager
to capture him after he led a bold and bloody hostage-taking raid
into Dagestan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Acting President Vladimir V. Putin announced that Raduyev was
captured on Sunday in Chechnya and had been brought to Moscow to
stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Public Television showed footage of Raduyev's
interrogation. Dazed and clean-shaven, he looked a far cry from the
guerrilla commander who for years has struck fear into the hearts
of many Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most odious bandit leaders,'' Putin said at
a televised meeting with his top ministers. ``Now he's in prison,
and that's where he belongs. I would like to think that this is
only the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said Raduyev's capture, while perhaps a
badly-needed morale boost for Russian forces, is meaningless in
military terms. Russian troops, they said, are in for a long
guerrilla war from the separatists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a publicity coup for Putin but little more,'' said
Pavel Felgenhauer, a Moscow-based military analyst. ``The capture
of one warlord will have very little effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Military leaders said last month that Russian forces were firmly
in control of the rebel region. The ``active phase'' of the war was
over, they said, and troops were mopping up small groups of
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past week, Chechen fighters have inflicted heavy
losses on Russian forces with a series of lightning strikes in
areas Moscow has long claimed to control. Military officials said
156 servicemen died in combat over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting continued Monday in the southern Chechen town of
Komsomolskoye, which the rebels captured from Russian forces a week
ago. Military officials said that up to 1,500 rebels were hiding in
the town.
</P>
<P>
   News agencies quoted Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo as
denying earlier reports that the commander of those guerrillas,
Ruslan Gelayev, had escaped from the village.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military said on Sunday that a group of rebels led
by Shamil Basayev and Khattab had evaded a blockade near the
villages of Ulus-Kert and Selmentausen in the Argun gorge. Rushailo
also said that Basayev and Khattab were hiding in Chechnya's
southern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In televised comments, Nikolai Patrushev, head of Russia's
Federal Security Service, said Raduyev was captured in the Chechen
town of Novogrozninsky. Patrushev said that no shots were fired
when Raduyev and three accomplices were captured early Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first he was shocked. He didn't answer questions,''
Patrushev said of Raduyev.
</P>
<P>
   Raduyev is the son-in-law of Dzhokar Dudayev, the Chechen
president who first led the region's bloody campaign for
independence from Russia. Dudayev was killed in a June 1996 rocket
attack.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1996, during the last Chechen war, Raduyev led a
bloody raid on the town of Kizlyar in neighboring Dagestan, where
he took thousands of hostages. The attack left scores dead and
Raduyev released the hostages and retreated back into Chechnya
after a weeklong standoff with Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, he was shot in the head and seriously wounded
during an attack by Russian forces. Raduyev reportedly lost an eye
and later underwent plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Kizlyar raid, Raduyev has claimed
responsibility for masterminding the bombing of a railway station
in the Russian city Pyatigorsk, and for a 1998 assassination
attempt against Georgia's President Eduard Shevardnadze.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Public Television reported that he will be charged with
terrorism and faces 50 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
