<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TRIBUNE-AD-COLUMN-NYT     03-13 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBUNE-TIMES MIRROR MERGER POSES PROS AND CONS FOR AD AGENCIES 
</HEADLINE>
 (Advertising Column; with TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR) 
(nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Madison Avenue assesses the merger announced
Monday between the Tribune Co. and the Times Mirror Co., the
opinions reflect a belief in the power of consolidation along with
a skepticism about whether the benefits will be as extensive as
they are being billed.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Times Mirror by Tribune for about $6.45
billion is indicative of the creation of a new type of media and
entertainment conglomerate that combines disparate properties to
offer marketers additional opportunities to buy commercial time and
advertising space in the form of what are known as cross-media
packages. Among examples are the amalgamations of America Online
and Time Warner; Walt Disney and Capital Cities/ABC; CBS, Infinity
Broadcasting, King World Productions and Viacom; and Clear Channel
Communications with AMFM Inc. and SFX Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Those conglomerates also hope to increase revenue by stepping up
the cross-promotional campaigns they sponsor among their
operations, which range from Web sites to television and radio
stations and networks to print media like magazines and newspapers
to entertainment properties like film studios, sports teams and TV
program syndicators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see only more consolidation, which clearly has pros and cons
for advertising agencies,'' said Ellen Oppenheim, media director at
the New York office of FCB Worldwide, part of True North
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the degree you want to make multimedia deals, there's more
to play with,'' Oppenheim said. ``But to the degree there's less
competition, and higher pricing, it's not a pretty thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The increased costs stem from efforts to portray cross-media
packages as larger than the sum of their parts and therefore more
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience is that mergers are great, but they end up
costing us more money,'' Carla Loffredo said, laughing. She is
senior partner and director for brand communications at the New
York office of J. Walter Thompson, part of the WPP Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you buy all the pieces of a pie, the cost should be less,''
she added. ``But they believe the value of the whole pie is so much
greater than the individual pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Loffredo said, the deal makes sense from a strategic
point of view, which is for media-entertainment conglomerates ``to
be a hundred miles deep in key markets where you offer
multicommunication channels to reach consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The deep penetration in those critical markets'' like
metropolitan Chicago, Los Angeles and New York, she added, is
intended to ``surround consumers by different points of contact.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary sales pitch for the new Tribune, which is to absorb
the variegated Times Mirror properties, is likely to be rooted in
the local orientation of newspapers like The Chicago Tribune, The
Los Angeles Times, Newsday and The Orlando Sentinel in Florida as
well as broadcasters like WGN radio and TV in Chicago, WTIC-TV in
Hartford and KSWB-TV in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The merged Tribune will be the largest multimedia company in
four of the nation's five most populous states: California, New
York, Illinois and Florida. And in the fifth, Texas, the company
owns two major market TV stations, KDAF-TV in Dallas and KHWB-TV in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to take the strongest brands the company has and
surround each one with multimedia ventures,'' said Rishad
Tobaccowala, president at Starcom IP, the interactive unit of the
media services agency Starcom Worldwide, part of the Leo Group unit
of BDM Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney had ESPN, the cable network, which is being expanded to
a magazine, radio, the Internet, even bars,'' he added. ``That
allows your strongest products to become even stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are questions about how broad a scope the merged
Tribune can have when its strengths lie in local and regional
properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, all these media companies are working to vertically
integrate content on a national scale,'' said Richard Notarianni,
media planning director at the New York office of DDB Worldwide,
part of the Omnicom Group. ``But there's still a schism between
their national efforts and Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Chicago, The Trib speaks with a Chicago accent,'' he added.
``I'm not sure it'll help to bring a Left Coast and Right Coast
feel to that.''
</P>
<P>
   That point about the company's newspapers, which will increase
to 11 from four after the deal, is important to agencies. They have
long shied from spending national ad dollars for clients in
newspapers, preferring media like television and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers ``have been trying to crack that nut for years,''
said Roberta Garfinkle, senior vice president and print media
director at the New York office of McCann-Erickson Worldwide
Advertising, ``and still nobody has come up with a way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks good on paper and it sounds good,'' she added, ``but
you've got to have the children learn to play nicely together.''
McCann is part of the McCann-Erickson World Group unit of the
Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspapers are learning through the Newspaper National Network
that there's a lot of money out there,'' said Steven Greenberger,
senior vice president and director for print media at Grey
Advertising in New York, referring to a sales program coordinated
by the Newspaper Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they've got to make life simpler for the advertising
agencies by packaging themselves more neatly and easily,'' he
added. ``Times Mirror alone hasn't been able to do it and Tribune
alone hasn't been able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the merged company can accomplish that, ``it can attract more
national advertising,'' Greenberger said, and perhaps even provide
``an example of how newspaper networks can become the next big
media opportunity for national advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   If that fails, well, Tribune can always offer prospective
advertisers some Chicago Cubs tickets for the World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
