<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `New economy' seen as moral wasteland
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ``new economy'' is the hottest thing on Wall
Street, but it's also a moral never-never land, Fortune (March 27)
says in a cover story on the ethics of highflying dot-com
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune argues that today's Internet boom is much like earlier
periods of economic upheaval, when people get the sense that ``the
old rules _ and the old ethics _ no longer apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Common infractions cited by Fortune include companies that steal
one another's intellectual property, cheat employees out of
promised stock options, intercept private e-mail and engage in
``sleight of hand'' accounting that pulls revenue ``out of thin
air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Taken together, they present not only a portrait of an
industry awash in greed, but also governed by an inverted dynamic,
born of a stock market gone mad,'' Fortune says.
</P>
<P>
   A MATTER OF TIMING
</P>
<P>
   Facing the tightest labor markets in 30 years and demand that
won't quit, U.S. corporations have made a bad situation manageable
by pouring money into technology in a bid to reduce the need for
workers, Business Week (March 20) reports.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, says former Federal Reserve Vice Chairman Alice M.
Rivlin, ``we have this tight labor market just at the moment when
we have a huge explosion in technological answers to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Investment in technology is behind the huge rise in
productivity, the magazine says, and goes a long way toward
explaining why the economy continues to grow so rapidly without
inciting wage inflation.
</P>
<P>
   END OF AN ERA
</P>
<P>
   The Economist (March 17) pays homage to a disappearing
institution _ the pinball machine, a victim of high-tech video
games that offer cinematic realism and thrills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pinball virtually created the games arcade, capturing the
quarters of a generation of flipper jockeys in the 1950s and
1960s,'' says the magazine. ``And, rather like the Wurlitzer
jukebox and the 1967 Thunderbird, the pinball showpieces of that
era were masterpieces of electromechanical achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   But today's youngsters, raised on PlayStations and 3-D virtual
combat, no longer feel like leaning over a glass cabinet and
batting around a metal ball.
</P>
<P>
   With sales slumping and losses mounting, WMS Industries, the
industry leader, stopped making the machines in November.
</P>
<P>
   This year the company's latest, greatest pinball machines will
be sold _ or junked.
</P>
<P>
   WORTH MENTIONING ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Harry West has preached regional urban planning for three
decades as chief of the Atlanta Regional Commission.
</P>
<P>
   He warns in Georgia Trend (March) that metro Atlanta's economy
will start to slip if regional planning isn't adopted.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mutual Funds (April) offers a package of articles to help
investors use the Internet, complete with a guide to computer
hardware, personal finance software and Web sites with databanks
useful for financial planning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
