<HEADER>
A5683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-ATLANTIC-10-NYT &LR;      03-13 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ATLANTIC-10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPLE BUILDS CASE FOR A NO. 1  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ During the first half of the championship game of
the Atlantic 10 men's basketball tournament Saturday night, Temple,
which had not won the title since 1990, left little doubt as to
whether its drought would last another year.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the first half was drawing to a close, about the
only thing in doubt was whether St. Bonaventure would manage double
figures before halftime. St. Bonaventure guards David
Messiah-Capers and Tim Winn answered that question when they hit
back-to-back 3-pointers to make the score 34-12 with 3 minutes 33
seconds remaining. Temple then took a 37-12 lead into the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some sloppy play in the second half, Temple (26-5)
rolled to a 65-44 victory over St. Bonaventure (21-9) to win the
conference tournament at the First Union Spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't talk to them much like I really do and make them
nervous,'' Temple Coach John Chaney said. ``I let them stay out
there for 30 minutes and warm up and I didn't talk to them that
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Chaney is onto something heading into the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament next week.
</P>
<P>
   Temple, ranked No. 6 in the nation, could be a No. 1-seeded team
in the national tournament, but Chaney said he was not worried
about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we've earned one of 64,'' he said. ``I would much
rather play a top team and lose and come back home. I'm not
interested in playing a lowly team. I'm not concerned about seeds.
I'm not even sure how it works. Maybe being in a region where you
don't run into Duke is where you want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Temple came out in the first half Saturday, it appears
the Owls are ready for almost anything. Entering this game, St.
Bonaventure had won seven of its last eight games. It held Dayton
to 36 percent shooting from the field in the semifinal game here
Friday night. Saturday night it was a different story. The Bonnies
were completely steamrolled by Temple. Temple's defense held St.
Bonaventure to just 17.9 percent shooting from the field in the
first half. The 12-point total was a record low for an Atlantic 10
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Temple was outstanding tonight,'' St. Bonaventure
Coach Jim Baron said. ``They played like a Final Four team. They're
terrific. They have so many guys who can step up, particularly on
the perimeter, and they're tough inside. It seems like they've been
waiting for this one for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Owls jumped out to a 23-2 lead before St. Bonaventure could
break a sweat. Quincy Wadley, who was the tournament's most
valuable player, had 11 points at the midway point of the first
half. He finished the game with 16 points and was 4 of 5 from
3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good feeling as a shooter knowing I have teammates
around me who will get me the ball when I'm shooting like that,''
Wadley said. ``I know any time I find a crack and get open that
Pepe will get me the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepe Sanchez is Temple's point guard. He had six assists and did
a good job of breaking down St. Bonaventure's press when the
Bonnies tried to slow down Temple's offense. It didn't help. The
Owls shot 50 percent from the field in the first half (46.9 percent
for the game) and pulled down 31 defensive rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure center Caswell Cyrus, who averages 12.5 points
and 6.3 rebounds a game, was limited because of a stomach virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could barely walk this morning,'' Winn said. ``I didn't
even think he could play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyrus played 30 minutes, but he was not a force inside. He was 1
of 6 from the field and had just three rebounds. Maybe if Cyrus had
been healthy, things would have been different in the one-sided
first half.
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure managed to climb back into the game in the
second half, pulling to within 50-36 on a 3-point basket by J.R.
Bremer with 6:08 to play. But that was as close as the Bonnies got.
</P>
<P>
   The game that Temple played against St. Bonaventure will give
some teams in the NCAA tournament something to think about wherever
the Owls are seeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we played to the best of our ability,'' Wadley said.
``If we're granted the No. 1 seed, so be it. Our objective is to
put ourselves in the best position, and that would be the No. 1
seed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
