<HEADER>
A5691 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-POLLUTION-CLIMATE     03-13 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-POLLUTION-CLIMATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLUTION TAKES TOLL ON CLOUDS AND RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The microscopic particles of atmospheric dust, sea salt and
smoke known as aerosols are meteorological and climatic
will-o'-the-wisps _ now here, now not, materializing somewhat
randomly in a given parcel of air and then disappearing in a few
days. But they are essential to the formation of clouds and the
production of rain and snow, and they also have a considerable
cooling influence on the earth's temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The evanescent character of aerosols has made it especially
difficult for scientists to pin down their effects on weather and
climate. The task has been complicated further by industrial
pollution, a relatively new source of aerosols with shifting
distribution patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Now researchers have turned up evidence that seems to confirm a
longtime suspicion: that the flood of aerosols loosed by urban and
industrial pollution suppresses rainfall and snowfall downwind of
the pollution source. In the process, clouds become brighter,
reflecting more sunlight. They may also stay around longer, and the
combined effect is to exert extra cooling on localities and regions
underneath those particular clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The extra particles cast aloft by the modern industrial economy
prevent cloud moisture from condensing into water droplets large
enough to fall to the ground before evaporating, according to a
study by Dr. Daniel Rosenfeld, a cloud physicist at the Hebrew
University of Jerusalem. The study appears in the current issue of
the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld examined precipitation patterns discerned by
instruments aboard an earth satellite launched in late 1997 to
measure global rainfall. He found that in ``pollution tracks''
downwind of pollution sources like cities, power plants, lead
smelters and oil refineries, virtually all precipitation was shut
off because the clouds in those atmospheric swaths were composed of
abnormally small water droplets.
</P>
<P>
   In order for raindrops to form, there must be some nucleus on
which atmospheric water vapor can condense. Aerosols provide the
nuclei. The resulting droplets of condensation create clouds. When
enough of the droplets collide and coalesce _ it takes about a
million of them _ a precipitation-sized drop of water forms and
falls to earth.
</P>
<P>
   But when the atmosphere is flooded with extra aerosols produced
by industries and cities, there are many more nuclei on which
moisture can condense. Consequently, the droplets are smaller and
never become heavy enough to fall to earth.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the new study ``indicate that human activity may
be altering clouds and natural precipitation on a global scale,''
Rosenfeld wrote in Science.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, measurements of smokestack emissions from ships at
sea, taken by satellites and airplanes, provided the first evidence
that aerosols could change cloud structure by redistributing water
onto a larger number of smaller droplets. Presumably, scientists
thought, the same thing might happen on land. But in many
industrial areas, aerosols from air pollution are so pervasive that
it was difficult to discern clearly their effect on precipitation.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld selected study sites where pollution tracks were
somewhat isolated in a broader region of less polluted air, and
thus stood out clearly. These included sites in Canada, Turkey and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The results showed for the first time that downwind of pollution
sources, clouds are brighter, said Dr. Owen B. Toon, an atmospheric
scientist at the University of Colorado at Boulder, who wrote a
commentary on the findings in Science. The clouds were brighter, he
said, because the increased number of droplets, though smaller,
reflected more sunlight, cooling the area under the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   In those bright cloud plumes, said Toon, ``there's no rainfall,
whereas the clouds surrounding the plume are raining. People had
thought this might happen, but there was no clear evidence of it
happening before.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the clouds do not produce as much rain, he said, they
probably persist longer; until a large-scale atmospheric system
like a cold front moves them out, they continue to cool the earth
beneath.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how widespread the pollution-induced precipitation
reduction and the cooling effects are, Toon said. Many scientists
believe that to some extent, the cooling effect of industrial
aerosols counteracts whatever global warming is being produced by
heat-trapping waste industrial gases like carbon dioxide. But they
have found it difficult to establish the magnitude of the aerosol
cooling.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the amount of pollution-generated aerosols in
the atmosphere varies from time to time and place to place; since
they fall out of the atmosphere in days or weeks at most, their
effect is regional, spotty and short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts believe that aerosol-producing pollution is
lessening in industrialized countries as they place controls on
emissions, and that in North America and Europe it may therefore
become less important as an influence on climate and weather.
Meanwhile, this sort of pollution is believed to be increasing
rapidly across Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The net global effect of aerosols on both precipitation and
temperature is thus a shifting target for scientists. Toon, along
with many other experts, says he believes that over the next few
decades, as controls are placed on pollution by aerosols, their
diminishing climatic effects will be overshadowed by the warming
effect of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases: While aerosols
disappear from the atmosphere quickly once controls are placed on
them, greenhouse gases persist for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The climatic role of both aerosols and clouds may become
markedly clearer in the next few years, said Toon, as new earth
satellites designed to measure them are launched. The first such
satellite, called Terra, went into orbit last December and should
begin collecting data in the next few months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
