<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POPE-ISRAEL-NYT &LR;      03-13 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE WILL VISIT TWO COMPETING SITES OF THE BAPTISM OF JESUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Treading carefully among competing interests on his
pilgrimage to the Holy Land next week, Pope John Paul II is adding
a visit to a traditional site of Jesus' baptism in a West Bank area
under Israeli military control, Israeli officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The March 22 trip to the site on the Jordan River near
Palestinian-ruled Jericho has been termed a private visit that will
be brief _ about 15 minutes _ and without television cameras,
officials said. The pope will be flown there by helicopter from
Jerusalem before proceeding to Bethlehem, which is under
Palestinian control, they added.
</P>
<P>
   Like other stops on the pope's six-day visit to Israel and the
Palestinian-ruled areas, the trip to the baptismal site is a
delicate matter, laden with significance for the Palestinians,
Israel and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months Jordan has been promoting a rival baptismal
site on its eastern bank of the Jordan River. The pope plans to go
to the Jordanian site immediately before his arrival in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   At the Vatican last month, Yasir Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
urged that the pope extend his visit to Palestinian-ruled areas to
include Jericho and its adjacent baptismal site. But the baptismal
site remains under Israeli control, and it is unclear whether there
will be any official Palestinian presence there. There is no plan
for the pope to go to Jericho itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visit will be under Israeli supervision and control,''
said Aviv Shiron, the Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman. Yet
Arafat evidently hopes that the pope's visit will prove a magnet
for pilgrims in years to come, when the area might be transferred
to Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   The West Bank site has been revered for centuries by some
Christian denominations as the place where Jesus was baptized by
John the Baptist at the beginning of his public ministry. Several
Catholic and Orthodox churches and monasteries were built in the
area, dating to the Byzantine period.
</P>
<P>
   After Israel captured the site in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, it
declared it a closed military area along the border between the
West Bank and Jordan. But under interim accords with the
Palestinians, Israel agreed to annual pilgrimages there by
Palestinians under their own flag. And since January, Israel has
opened the area to visits by foreign pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   Both Israel and the Palestinians have a common interest in
promoting the area as a pilgrimage site to offset efforts by Jordan
to draw pilgrims to its competing site on a tributary across the
river. The Israelis are planning to refurbish the West Bank site,
whose churches and monasteries have crumbled during more than 30
years of neglect behind mines and barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   The Jordanian site is about a mile east of the West Bank site,
at Wadi Kharrar, where there are also remains of an ancient church.
Citing a New Testament verse locating John the Baptist east of the
Jordan, Jordanian officials successfully lobbied for the pope to
visit Wadi Kharrar, in the hope that this would draw new
generations of pilgrims there in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1844EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
