<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-SCAM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-13 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SCAM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRIME STORIES': GIVE ME YOUR MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the pre-Giuliani era, before street crime was
abolished, some blocks along Broadway were home to operators of a
diversion known as three-card monte or follow the queen. The
enterprise required only a bottom-side-up cardboard box, three bent
playing cards and a few accomplices and visiting suckers. The
venturesome tourist or atypical New Yorker with more cash than
sense was challenged to place a bet on which of the three cards
placed face down on the box was the queen. No one, except a shill,
ever came away a winner.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first of Tuesday night's ``Rip-Offs and Scams''
explored by Ricky Jay, a chronicler of conjuring, and other experts
on how even New Yorkers can be gulled by sleight-of-hand artists
and other people with more talent than scruples. Jay demonstrates
convincingly and entertainingly that his hand is a lot faster than
your eye. He advises that if you're looking for a square deal from
a street gang, with its implicit threat of muscle, forget it.
</P>
<P>
   The hour also offers examples of pickpocket tactics, like the
``bump and stall,'' in which a band of villains distracts a victim
as a pocket is being emptied or a purse is lifted. Then there are
those popular county-fair games that defy victory, whether they
involve knocking down milk bottles or scoring baskets. (The bottles
may have lead bottoms that resist falling; the baskets may have
bent rims.) The lesson here is ``Play to play, not to win.'' Since
the prizes tend to be worthless to boot, it sounds like good
advice.
</P>
<P>
   A less common example of human fallibility, one must hope, is
the ``sweetheart scam,'' in which a lovelorn target is wooed and
won by a professed lover, who then runs through the beloved's bank
account. One woman reports that she lost more than $30,000 to the
man to whom she had already lost her heart. I'm afraid she seemed
excessively dim, like the customers for people who claim to tell
fortunes or possess other psychic powers. ``I'm feeling your
aura,'' one says, which is awfully personal.
</P>
<P>
   Other temptations to be avoided are greed (don't believe a
telephone caller's announcement that you've won a million dollars)
and sympathy (don't swallow heartbreaking pleas for financial
assistance without checking on the auspices). Also beware of the
Internet. The elderly and the lonely seem to be especially
vulnerable to plausible pitches, but a little stupidity doesn't
help.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL; 
`CRIME STORIES' &QL; 
Rip-Offs and Scams  &QL; 
At 10 p.m. ET Tuesday on Court TV &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jinny Schreckinger, director and executive producer. For Court
TV: Carolyn Kresky, executive in charge of production; Doc Jarden,
vice president, documentaries and specials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
