<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRITAIN-NAZI-ART-NYT &LR;      03-13 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-NAZI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEIRS REGAIN A PAINTING TAKEN BY THE NAZIS IN 1938 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A painting that was left behind by a Jewish woman
fleeing Vienna during World War II, taken by the Nazis and held for
most of the intervening years in storage at a museum in Munich was
returned Monday to the heirs of the original owner.
</P>
<P>
   The return of the work, ``The Three Stages of Life'' (1898), a
triptych by Count Leopold von Kalckreuth, part of a traveling show
at the Royal Academy of Arts here called ``1900: Art at the
Crossroads,'' is the first restitution of a painting on view in a
British institution, said Anne Webber, co-chairwoman of the
Commission for Looted Art in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this sets an important precedent for all museums
holding looted work,'' Webber said at a news conference here.
``These are not just important objects but family treasures with
huge symbolic and emotional meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of how to return the tens of thousands of works
confiscated outright by the Third Reich or seized as spoils of the
Second World War has bedeviled institutions throughout Europe as
the decades have slipped by and the original owners have grown
infirm and died off. Recently a number of British museums and
galleries listed some 300 works with murky provenances that they
said may have been looted by the Nazis and appealed to the public
for help in determining where the works had been during the war.
</P>
<P>
   In this case the work's owner, Elizabeth Glanville, died in 1983
after years of trying to recover it. As documentation she offered a
photograph of the work on the wall of her apartment in Vienna,
which she fled in 1938 with her husband and children.
</P>
<P>
   The painting has been on loan to the Royal Academy from the
Bavarian State Collections, which bought it from a private Viennese
collection in 1942. New research by the Bavarian State Collections
in Munich and the Commission for Looted Art in Europe showed that
the work had been taken illegally by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Glanville's children, Ernest Glanville, 75, and Marietta
Glanville, 70, were on hand Monday for a reunion with the painting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's joy is tinged with regret that my mother is not
here,'' said Marietta Glanville, who said she remembered the
painting, showing a woman in youth, in the prime of life and in old
age, from the time it dominated the dining room of her childhood
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has meant a lot to us,'' she said. ``It is an icon of our
childhood, and has great sentimental value, in that it was given to
my mother as a wedding present from our grandparents.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture is to remain on view here until April 3, when it is
to be transferred to the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum in New York.
In September it is to be returned to the Glanvilles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
