A5704 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-13 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; STARTING A GEORGE W. COLLECTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TomPaine.com, which bills itself as an online journal of
opinion, has started a list of Republican contender  &UR; George W. &LR; 
 &UR; Bush &LR; 's malaprops, taken from the  &LR; transcripts of appearances and
press conferences. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was coming up,'' said George W. at Council Bluffs,
Iowa, on January 22, ``it was a dangerous world, and we knew
exactly who the they were. It was us versus them and we know
exactly who them was. Today, we're not so sure who the they are,
but we know they're there.''
</P>
<P>
   Personals, being an equal-opportunity finger-pointer, recalls
that  &UR; Al Gore &LR;  once took credit for inventing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. A profile in the Washington Times reveals that George W.
and  &UR; Laura Bush &LR;  have a dog they named  &UR; Spot &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CREDITS CALLS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Independent filmmaker  &UR; Johnny White &LR; , who is making ``the
faktz,'' a ``science fiction modern suspense drama filmed as a
1950s genre piece,'' is fairly desperately trying to raise the
$400,000 budgeted for the project.
</P>
<P>
   White is offering the contributor of $100 the opportunity of
putting a name into the credits; $200 includes the credit mention,
autographed script and video of the movie; $300 includes all of the
above and a daily e-mail from the set; $500 adds the right to spend
a day on the set ``as a visitor, personal assistant or extra''; and
$1,000 adds the privilege to give a character in the movie the name
of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   More information is at www.cubertfilm.com, or Joseph at (312)
315-0339.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CASTING ANSWERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Looking for understudies for their show, ``New Wrinkles,''
 &UR; Morrie Bobrow  &LR; and  &UR; Jerry Nachman &LR;  attended Theatre Bay Area
general auditions recently, at which directors from many plays have
a chance to see the skills of many performers.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ``special skills'' listed on the resumes of various
actors:
</P>
<P>
   ``Drive stick-shift,'' ``photographs well,'' ``untrained but
very fluid dancer,'' ``nice hands,'' ``great cook,'' ``incurable
optimist,'' ``woman of great strength and power,'' ``certified
hypnotherapist,'' ``hot-blooded Latin lover,'' ``flashy
bartending'' and ``can imitate a squirrel.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WHISTLE-BLOWER'S PERSONAL ARMORY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago,  &UR; Jeffrey Wigand &LR; , the former tobacco company
officer whose testimony was the subject of ``The Insider,'' was
placed under a restraining order from his then-wife; his guns were
confiscated by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Wigand's cache of weapons, as documented by MSNBC: 12 rifles,
two shotguns, seven semi-automatics, six revolvers, 58 containers
of ammunition (including 2,885 rounds, and 32 pounds of gunpowder.
That restraining order was set to expire several days ago; Wigand's
former wife was petitioning the court last week to extend it.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post reports that Wigand called the Academy of
Motion Picture Arts and Sciences to request a ticket for the Oscars
ceremony but was told the event ``isn't the Super Bowl.'' According
to MSNBC, he wasn't invited because  &UR; Russell Crowe &LR; , the actor who
plays him, went to talk with him before shooting the movie and
didn't like him.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``In civilized society, a burrito is not an entree; it is a
symbol of man's inhumanity to man.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Alan Richman  &LR; in GQ magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If childhood obesity truly is `an epidemic in the U.S. the
likes of which we have not had before in chronic disease,' then
places like McDonald's and Winchell's doughnut stores, with their
endless racks of glazed and creamy goodies, are the San Francisco
bathhouses of said epidemic, the places where the high-risk
population indulges in high-risk behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Greg Critzer &LR;  in a Harper's story about obesity in America.
</P>
</TEXT>
