<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCEDES-SALES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M-CLASS TAKES OFF FOR MERCEDES-BENZ  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SHANNON THOMASON   
 The Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCE, Ala. _ Sales of the Mercedes-Benz M-Class in North
America are up nearly 43 percent from last year, but officials here
at the company's only American plant have taken the demand in
stride.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth consecutive month, the M-Class has been the
top-seller for Mercedes-Benz USA Inc., said Mercedes spokesman
Austin Dare.
</P>
<P>
   The M-Class recorded its highest February sales ever, with 4,605
vehicles sold, according to figures released by the company. That
represents almost one-third of the total 15,546 new vehicles sold
by the company in North America last month.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,900 employees at the Vance plant are keeping up with the
consumer craving for the M-Class, Dare said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, 77,692 M-Classes were built in Vance; 68,732 were built
there in 1998. Although Dare said he could not predict how many
will be built this year, he did say that the company anticipates an
increase in production.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting to realize growth this year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The car is also manufactured in Austria. The Steyr-Daimler-Puch
plant in Graz is producing as many as 30,000 of the vehicles a year
to meet European demand.
</P>
<P>
   February's total Mercedes vehicle sales in North America show a
26 percent increase over February 1999's sales record of 12,257.
This was the 10th consecutive month Mercedes posted year-over-year
sales gains, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Second to M-Class sales were sales of the E-Class, with 3,550
vehicles sold. C-Class reported a 3 percent decrease in sales with
2,182 vehicles sold.
</P>
<P>
   (Shannon Thomason writes for The Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News. The
Tuscaloosa News is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5713 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CAMPFIN-BOS     03-13 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CAMPFIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL CAMPAIGN REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Campaign finance reform has quickly emerged as the first big
issue separating George W. Bush and Al Gore in the general
election. This focus is itself cause to celebrate _ for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity for real reform will be lost just as quickly if
the candidates continue to use the issue for political advantage
rather than for constructive change. The issue must produce bricks
to strengthen our most precious democratic institution, not
brickbats to be hurled between the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Both have plenty to prove. Gore has a record of support for
various improvements, including early advocacy for public
financing, but he and President Clinton have achieved nothing
substantial, even when Democrats controlled Congress. Gore's own
fund-raising lapses, some of which he now acknowledges were
mistakes, raise a suspicion that Gore's sudden emphasis on reform
is essentially a defensive move. What Gore needs to do now is to go
well beyond support for the McCain-Feingold bill and put out a
comprehensive plan of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Bush clearly likes the current system, which has served him
well. The changes he advocated in South Carolina were minimal _
barring soft money from corporations and unions, but not from
individuals, and requiring instant disclosure. However, thousands
of John McCain voters are looking for a home. And as more stories
circulate about the cushy and sometimes lucrative appointments that
have gone to some of his big contributors in Texas, Bush may feel
the need to embrace more reform.
</P>
<P>
   The leading advocates are pleased with the new spotlight on
campaign finance, but rightly want more substance. ``I believe in
conversion,'' says Ellen Miller of Public Campaign, but ``whether
Gore is credible or not depends on what he comes up with.'' And
Scott Harshbarger of Common Cause says Gore must ``show how he's
different from Clinton _ will he make any kind of a fight for it?''
Both dismiss Bush's recent proposal, Miller calling it ``deform.''
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans believe that Washington is lubricated by
big money to the detriment of average citizens. Gore and Bush have
a chance to change that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1857EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5717 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TRIBUNE-TERMS-NYT &LR;      03-13 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-TERMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANDLERS SACRIFICED LONG-TERM GAIN, ALL TO AVOID TAXES
</HEADLINE>
   (Market Place Column; with TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR) 
(nk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chandler family built the Los Angeles Times and Times
Mirror, and in the end they sold the company out from under the
manager they had hired to run it.
</P>
<P>
   While the planned sale to the Tribune Co. will be a windfall for
Times Mirror shareholders, the Chandlers would have enjoyed a far
bigger gain had they not engaged in three separate transactions
with the company over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Those transactions, criticized at the time because they gave the
family deals not available to ordinary shareholders, were designed
to maximize current income for the Chandler family while minimizing
the family's tax bill and allowing it to diversify its investments.
In that, they succeeded. But the cost to the family was a real one.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Tribune transaction, the Chandlers appear to have
negotiated a deal that will protect them from paying taxes _ but
will give them a lower price for their stock than will be available
to public shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the transactions appear to have provided short-term
benefits to the Chandlers at the expense of their long-term
financial interests _ at least in hindsight now that the takeover
is going to occur.
</P>
<P>
   None of which is to say the Chandlers are going to suffer. The
Chandler family trusts now own 14.5 million shares of Times Mirror
stock, which will be exchanged under terms of the takeover for
36.25 million shares of Tribune Company stock, worth $1.1 billion
at Monday's closing market price. They also have substantial other
investments, thanks to the transactions with Times Mirror, that are
worth hundreds of millions more.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's merger agreement was negotiated in large part by
Chandler family interests, with Mark Willes, the chief executive of
the company, effectively left on the sidelines. It appears that he
will be out of work after the merger is completed, although he will
get a severance package. Although the Chandlers own a minority of
the stock, they control the company because their shares have
super-voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   But back in 1994, before the blizzard of deals began, the
Chandler family trusts owned 39.4 million shares. Had they simply
held on to them, they would have received less income in the
intervening years but probably would be wealthier now, after the
Tribune takeover. Monday, Times Mirror stock rose $37.6875 to
$85.625.
</P>
<P>
   The first deal, announced in 1994 and completed in the spring of
1995, came when Times Mirror needed to reduce the generous dividend
it had been paying. The quarterly dividend was cut from 27 cents a
share to 6 cents. Such a cut was potentially devastating to some
members of the extended Chandler family, whose dividend income was
about $42.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The solution was to give the Chandler family trust a new issue
of preferred stock, paying $33 million a year in dividends. Their
income was preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary shareholders did not get the preferred. But they did
get shares in Cox Communications, which bought the cable operations
of Times Mirror in a related transaction. The Cox shares they got
were then worth about $10 a Times Mirror share. Now they are worth
about $52, although they have never paid dividends. The value of
the preferred stock the Chandlers took instead of the Cox shares
has not risen, although the dividends have continued to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   The second transaction came in 1997. Then the Chandler family
and Times Mirror engaged in an unusual deal in which the family
effectively traded part of its common and preferred stock holdings
in Times Mirror for a diversified stock and bond portfolio and a
stake in real estate that had been owned by Times Mirror, and which
Times Mirror then leased back. The deal was structured in a way
that let the family avoid capital gains taxes on the stock that was
traded for the other assets.
</P>
<P>
   To evaluate that deal completely would require knowledge of how
the cash in the deal did after it was invested _ information that
is not public information. Times Mirror stock had performed poorly
since that transaction _ on Friday it closed just below the 1997
level _ but it soared Monday on the takeover news. Although the
Chandlers had higher current income than they would have had if
they had not done the transaction, it is probable that they would
have done better overall if they had kept the shares to be tendered
in the current takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The third transaction came last September. The structure of that
deal was similar to the 1997 one, with the Chandlers effectively
trading another large block of Times Mirror stock for the income
from other assets, in this case securities issued by real estate
investment trusts and other investments to be made with cash
contributed by Times Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, evaluating that deal is impossible without
information on the investments made with the cash put in by Times
Mirror. Some of the money went into a venture capital fund that has
made a number of Internet investments, whose value will become
clear only with time. But, once again, Times Mirror stock is up
more than 40 percent since then, thanks entirely to the takeover,
and it is unlikely that the other investments, as a group, have
done as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the transaction announced Monday, the Tribune Company agreed
to pay up to $95 a share for 41 percent of the outstanding Times
Mirror shares, and to exchange 2.5 Tribune shares for the remaining
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune stock fell $6.375 to $30.8125 Monday, indicating the
value of the stock portion of the deal is $77.03 per Times Mirror
share. Unless Tribune stock rallies sharply, most shareholders will
opt to take as much cash as they can. But the Chandlers agreed to
exchange their shares for stock. That leaves more cash for other
shareholders, but assures that the Chandlers will not have to pay
capital gains taxes on the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Chandlers have managed to do a deal that will
not bring a tax bill to the family. But they are doing so in a way
that leaves them with less value than they might have received if
taxes were not so feared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
