<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5718 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      03-13 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFESAVER TAKES A LIFE  
 A TICKLING TUMOR  
 IRREGULAR HEARTBEAT  
 BAD CREDIT  
 ILLITERACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) (DW) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a heart attack victim is rushed to the emergency room,
chances are that among the array of treatments doctors administer
will be one of the drugs known as clot-busters. But in many of
those cases, because doctors have to make crucial dosage decisions
on the fly, the drugs may be doing more harm than good, a new study
finds.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Brigham and Women's Hospital, the Harvard
affiliate, found that as many 16 percent of the 260,000 patients
treated each year with the drugs are given improper doses, which
can result in complications that include death.
</P>
<P>
   The risk was especially high for women. Over all, the mortality
rate for patients given incorrect drug treatment was twice as high.
</P>
<P>
   But they also found that newer versions of the drugs, called
thrombolytic agents, which are given not through transfusion but
with two simple injections, have a far lower error rate, 5 percent
or lower, said Dr. Christopher P. Cannon, the author of the study.
The findings were presented last weekend to a gathering of the
American College of Cardiology.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Cannon said, lies not so much in the older forms of
the drugs, which have been credited with saving many lives, as with
the setting in which they have to be administered. With heart
attacks, emergency room doctors need to act quickly to remove the
blockage that is causing the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner you open up the artery, the less complicated the
heart attack is and the lower the death rate,'' Cannon said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the older clot-busters require doctors to factor in weight _
a frequent source of dosage errors, the study said _ and to make
decisions about how long to continue the transfusions and at what
rate. Too little of the drug, and the blockage may not disappear;
too much and the patient could have complications from bleeding,
including stroke.
 &QL; 
WHEN AN IRREGULAR BEAT SPELLS TROUBLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A common heart condition, irregular heartbeat, which under
normal conditions poses little problem, may have more serious
consequences if a heart attack strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have found that people who have atrial fibrillation,
as an irregular heartbeat is known, have higher rates of death and
disability when they have heart attacks. The findings were reported
in a recent issue of Circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The study involved 106,780 people 65 or older who had heart
attacks, 22 percent of whom were found to have had irregular
heartbeats.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said they were surprised at the rate of atrial
fibrillation, which they said appeared to put patients at increased
risk for stroke, congestive heart failure or a second heart attack.
They also needed to stay in the hospital longer. About half the
patients studied who had irregular heartbeats had the conditions
before their heart attacks. The rest developed them afterward.
A TICKLING TUMOR AND AN URGE TO LAUGH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neurologists are reporting several cases in which small,
tumorlike masses can cause people to feel as though they have to
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The patients, whose conditions were described in a recent issue
of the journal Neurology, said that the sensation was not
unpleasant, but that it could be unnerving. One 24-year-old woman
described the feeling as being ``like a tickling in my head'' that
lasted 10 to 15 seconds and occurred 10 times a day. A 25-year-old
man said he would suppress the urge to laugh unless it appeared
appropriate to his surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   The condition is caused by a noncancerous mass called a
hypothalamic hamartoma. The lesion also caused the patients to have
mild epileptic seizures. The seizures can usually be controlled
with medication; the laugh cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Patients with larger hamartomas often have more serious
symptoms, including changes in mental ability and behavioral
problems. While a patient who reports an urge to laugh might well
not be taken seriously by a doctor, the study said it could be a
sign of a small lesion.
</P>
<P>
   It said these patients should be given MRI scans, which should
be thoroughly scrutinized, since the growths are so small.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCHERS LINK BAD DEBT TO BAD HEALTH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that serious credit card debt is bad for one's
financial health, but it could also be bad for physical health.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologists writing in the journal Social Science &AMP; Medicine
say they have found evidence that people who owe money on their
credit cards tend to be in poorer health.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the dark side of the economic boom,'' said Dr.
Paul J. Lavrakas, director of the Center for Survey Research at
Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers conducted telephone surveys of about 1,000 Ohioans
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The people surveyed were asked about subjects like the amount
they owed on credit cards, the number of credit cards they used,
whether they were in default and how their debts compared with
their incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Then they were asked some standard questions used to measure
stress and health, including how much they worried about their
debt, how much they weighed and how well they could perform simple
tasks like walking up stairs or carrying groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Although not all their theories were borne out, the researchers
said they had found significantly more health problems reported
among those with the worst debt-income ratio.
</P>
<P>
   For doctors trying to assess a patient's overall health,
Lavrakas said, the findings suggest that they consider asking about
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Credit card companies, he said, should consider changing ``the
ease with which they're making and aggressively going after
opportunities to let people put themselves in debt.''
</P>
<P>
   TACKLING THE PROBLEMS OF HEALTH ILLITERACY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the instructions for someone facing a barium enema
exam are not very complicated: follow the diet guidelines and take
the medicine to help empty the lower intestine. The procedure is
straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   But for many patients, doctors say, the first hurdle is not the
enema itself but the written instructions, which many people cannot
fully understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not aware how large this problem was when we started
looking at it,'' said Dr. William H. Mahood, a gastroenterologist
and the president of the American Medical Foundation, which has
just begun a program to try to counter what it calls health
illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, the philanthropic arm of the American Medical
Association, has raised $350,000 so far to develop ways to make
sure that patients who cannot read, or who read poorly, clearly
understand how to use the drugs they are prescribed or the
treatments they are being given.
</P>
<P>
   Foundation officials cited a recent study finding that 27
percent of English-speaking patients at a public hospital could not
read their appointment slips and that 42 percent did not understand
all the details on their prescription bottles.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors also pointed to a 1992 national adult literacy study
that found that 21 percent of Americans adults could not read the
front page of the newspaper, and that 48 percent had trouble
reading a bus schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
