  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: DRUG SUSPECT QUIZZED
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Labra Aviles, who authorities say was the top financial
operative of a powerful drug gang run by the Arellano Felix
brothers, was taken to Mexico City for questioning by federal
narcotics police after being arrested in Tijuana. He was seized at
his son's high school football game after trying to flee during a
routine police sweep for illegal weapons and is being held on an
old warrant for drug money-laundering.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: LEADERS LOOK TO U.S.
</P>
<P>
   In their efforts to restore the province's power-sharing
government, Ulster's politicians and Irish and British leaders will
hold inter-party talks in Washington this week and consult with
President Clinton and administration officials on the fringes of
St. Patrick's Day celebrations. London suspended home rule on Feb.
11 after the Irish Republican Army failed to make any moves to
start disarming.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: OMAGH BOMBING
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's police commissioner, Pat Byrne, said terrorists behind
the 1998 bombing in Omagh, Northern Ireland, that killed 29 people
will ``sadly, possibly and maybe probably'' escape prosecution. The
police have identified those responsible, Byrne told the
Belfast-based Irish News, but do not have evidence that can be used
in court. The Real IRA, an Irish Republican Army splinter group
based in Ireland, says it carried out the attack.
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: ACCUSED AIDE QUITS
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Bram Peper resigned, saying he wanted to fight
full-time against accusations he had misused public money. A Dutch
newspaper reported last year that he had used city money to pay for
personal purchases and travel while he was mayor of Rotterdam
between 1982 and 1998. Peper denies the report and has threatened
to sue the paper. Results of an independent inquiry are due on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: JAILED GUERRILLA SUES
</P>
<P>
   Mustafa Dirani, a Shiite Muslim guerrilla leader who has been
imprisoned by Israel since 1994, filed a lawsuit against the
government. He seeks $1.5 million in damages for what he said was
rape and sodomy during a torture-filled interrogation by Israeli
security officers after he was kidnapped from his home in Lebanon.
Dirani is being held without trial, one of 14 Lebanese ``bargaining
chips'' for Israeli soldiers missing in Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
