<P>
   &UR; TRIBUNE-TIMES MIRROR &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 1{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the purchase by The Tribune Co. of the Times Mirror Co.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR (Undated) _ The Tribune Co. and Times Mirror
Co., two media companies whose flagship newspapers helped define
the brawling, partisan days of 19th century journalism, on Monday
announced plans to merge into a media company that would bring
their trademark regionalism to the multimedia world of the 21st
century. If nothing intervenes to disrupt the merger, the new
company, to be called Tribune Co., will own 11 daily newspapers, 22
television stations and four radio stations. But its core strategy
would be regional, with a mandate to deliver news, entertainment
and advertising through print, television and the Internet. By
Felicity Barringer and Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics and map.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-HISTORY (Los Angeles) _ The Tribune-Times Mirror deal
joins two venerable newspaper companies: Times Mirror, owned for a
century by the Otis and Chandler families, and Tribune, shaped for
much of this century by Col. Robert R. McCormick. The companies
have followed parallel paths for much of their existence. By Todd
S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-NEW-MEDIA (Chicago) _ Here in Chicago, the Tribune Co.
has been quietly transforming itself in recent years into what top
executives say is a new media company, which is funneling old media
content and ideas into television, cable, radio and internet
ventures. Before the deal, it had more than 16 television stations,
reaching more than a third of U.S. households. There were four
radio stations, an entertainment unit, a venture capital arm and an
educational publishing unit. The company was an early investor in
America Online and Yahoo, and owns a 25 percent stake in the WB
television network and a 29 percent stake in cable television's
Food Network. By David Barboza. (550 words)
</P>
<P>
   (Budgeted earlier as TRIBUNE-MADIGAN.)
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-REACT (Los Angeles) _ Reaction in Los Angeles to the
sale of the Times Mirror company. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-IMPACT (Undated) _ The Tribune Co.'s agreement to buy
Times Mirror spelled nothing but bad news for Tribune shareholders
on Monday. Already battered on fears that the newspaper industry is
headed for lower earnings growth, Tribune fell more than 17
percent. But some media investors and analysts said the sharp drop
in Tribune stock puzzled them. If approved, the deal will give
Tribune both a newspaper and a television station in the three
largest advertising markets in the United States -- New York, Los
Angeles, and Chicago. That combination should be attractive to
advertisers and give Tribune a head start in the furious
competition to build local-interest Web sites. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBUNE-TERMS (Undated) _ The marketplace column: The Chandler
family built the Los Angeles Times and Times Mirror, and in the end
they sold the company out from under the manager they had hired to
run it. While the planned sale to the Tribune Company will be a
windfall for Times Mirror shareholders, the Chandlers would have
enjoyed a far bigger gain had they not engaged in three separate
transactions with the company over the last five years. By Floyd
Norris. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   Eds, this is tonight's marketplace column.
