<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BASIL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     03-13 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASIL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BASIL STREET BLUES': THE FATHER AND MOTHER OF THE BOY GROWN UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes at end of review) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The grandparents' household where young Michael Holroyd lodged
after his parents' divorce was quarrelsome to the point of
hysteria. The parrot in their conservatory repeated the finely
accented British howls and shrieks.
</P>
<P>
   Michael took quiet refuge at the town library, where he read
biographies: Hesketh Pearson on Wilde and Hazlitt, Hugh Kingsmill
on Dickens and Samuel Johnson. They allowed the boy, whose present
was bewilderingly chaotic, ``to find out what was going to happen
next in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a fair description of what Holroyd would come to write:
vividly narrative biographies of Lytton Strachey, Augustus John and
George Bernard Shaw. The impressive detail and agile reflection
rarely choke the flow of what would happen next. Biography as
resurrection, not the lavish 800-page interments conducted by quite
a few recent behemoths. (I did think that the Shaw was long, worked
rather conspicuously at resuscitating and answered more questions
than the Recording Angel itself might want to ask.)
</P>
<P>
   The soul of a biography should be not what do I (plus index
cards) know, but what don't I know? Holroyd's new book, ``Basil
Street Blues'' makes a wonderfully illuminating use of `I don't
know'.
</P>
<P>
   It is not his most finished work _ it hardly could be _ but it
may be his most remarkable. It is the biographer's equivalent of
``Physician heal thyself.'' Cursing the dawn church bells, the
French round demands: ``When will they toll the bell-ringer's
death?'' When will the biographer turn his questions on himself?
``My identity was shaped by what I wrote, though this identity was
concealed behind the people I wrote about,'' Holroyd tells us. No
longer. This biography of his parents and family barely conceals an
autobiography. If it is hard to strip yourself naked, try lace
pajamas, extensively ripped. What Holroyd knows about his parents
has gaping holes in it. Instead of patching, he asks, What do I see
through them? He peers in and out, interrogating his materials and
himself as he interrogates them. His double journey through his
parents' lives and his own lacks the safety of a destination or a
conclusion but it is more revealing for it.
</P>
<P>
   Basil Holroyd and Ulla Knutsson-Hall were two parts that never
made one parental whole. He was an English eccentric and she a
Swedish one, each of an opposite type. Basil, in a line of
dwindling fortunes (his grandfather was a major general, his father
a gentlemanly and inefficient businessman), carried faith in a
rational center to daffy extremes. He was a King Canute standing
firmly on the shores of practicality and repeatedly getting washed
away.
</P>
<P>
   Over his 80-year-life he embarked upon one plausibly argued
scheme after the other, none of which worked out. After a spell in
his own father's failing business he rolled up large orders selling
concrete structures for a company unable to produce them. He went
into carbon paper, then building lumber. He wrote five unpublished
novels and collaborated with Michael _ still looking for his own
literary path _ on a history of the world in hexameters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave the impression of someone who had overshot success and
landed somewhere else,'' his son writes of a father who to the end
figured in his own mind as a fount of sober paternal instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Ulla, from a powerful and aristocratic Stockholm family, emitted
no shred of instruction other than, perhaps, to be happy and keep
fed. Her eccentricity was free-form without the slightest nodding
reference to a center. Sailing to England at 18, ostensibly to
study English but mostly to have fun, she was captivated by an
unstoppable talker buzzing about the captain's table. Basil got her
to marry him. They did have fun in London for a while; then when
the war began and Michael was 4, Basil took them to live with his
parents in the country. ``Disaster!'' Ulla wrote in a retrospective
note. ``END really of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was the end of a detour. Beautiful and
sought-after, she worked for a while as a model while taking up
with several wealthy protectors, two of whom she married and
divorced. It was not the money she was after but the pleasure:
travel, parties, good hotels, nice things. There was an innocence;
she dug virtually no gold out of her consorts. This not impractical
grasshopper ended, nevertheless, as hard up as Basil the wildly
impractical ant.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, was divorced three times. It took five marriages for
them to produce one child, Holroyd reflects: himself. Through the
turbulence and in no way reducing it we get remarkably limpid
portraits of Ulla, Basil and the son who searches their lives.
</P>
<P>
   There is Michael as life-preserving mouse, skittering about his
grandparents' sinking ship. It is the shipwreck of old age,
finally, portrayed with comedy and a splinter of anguish. There are
his school days at Eton (who would have thought a fresh account
could still be made?), his splendidly thoughtful discussion of a
biographer's ethics _ brought to ground dealing with his own family
_ and his patient, wryly painful care of his parents in their
declining days.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of their lives, Holroyd asked Ulla and Basil to
write what they could remember of their lives, offering to pay them
for ``research.'' His mother took the money blithely; his father
refused it. ``He wanted to give money and receive praise; he found
it impossible to receive money and give praise.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 70s this painfully prickly man would visit his crippled
sister weekly to fix meals she didn't like and offer advice she
liked less. ``Unfortunately, to help people, he had to make sure
that they were worse off than he was. This was increasingly
difficult. He was so impoverished now that being the target of his
help became a peculiarly depressing experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Holroyd does not force or inflate his search through memory. His
speculative urgency _ who were these parents and who am I? _
recognizes the limits of answers. He possesses emotional elegance.
His sentences possess clean lines and a shapely balance. Difficult
and elusive, Basil and Ulla make movingly human claims upon their
son and through him upon us.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL; 
`BASIL STREET BLUES'  &QL; 
By Michael Holroyd  &QL; 
Illustrated. 306 pages. W.W. Norton. $24.95.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
