<HEADER>
A5733 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-EXTINCTION-HOTSPO     03-13 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EXTINCTION-HOTSPOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `HOT SPOT' APPROACH TO SAVING SPECIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
(ms) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many conservationists, prospects for maintaining the earth's
biological diversity are dim at best.
</P>
<P>
   People and their activities are forcing plants and animals into
extinction at 100 to 1,000 times the natural rate.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, once ecosystems lose key species, they are not likely
to recover their full function and biotic variety in less than
about 10 million years, according to a new analysis by Dr. James W.
Kirchner, an earth scientist at the University of California at
Berkeley, and Dr. Anne Weil, a vertebrate paleontologist at Duke
University. The scientists, who based their conclusion on studies
of fossils, reported their findings in the current issue of the
journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   But other scientists say that there may be a practical way to
stem the tide of extinction markedly, by concentrating conservation
efforts and funds on a relatively small number of highly vulnerable
``hot spots'' that each contain a large concentration of species
found nowhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that there are species hot spots is not new; it was
proposed some years ago by Dr. Norman Myers, an ecologist based at
Oxford University's Green College in England. But now, in recent
study published in Nature, he and four colleagues have tried to
delineate the hot spots more precisely. The results are delineated
on the map above.
</P>
<P>
   Hot spots were defined in the study as places having the
greatest concentration of what are called endemic species _ those
found nowhere else _ while at the same time experiencing
exceptional loss of habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Loss of endemic species accounts for most modern-day
extinctions, and the hot spots therefore constitute ``the front
line in the battle to save biodiversity,'' said Dr. Russell A.
Mittermeier, the president of Conservation International, a
conservation group that advocates the hot spot approach.
Mittermeier was one of Myers' co-authors.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis found that as many as 44 percent of all species of
vascular plants and 35 percent of major vertebrate species lived in
25 hot spots comprising just 1.4 percent of all the land on earth,
predominantly tropical forests.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, the researchers wrote, open the way for ``a
`silver bullet' strategy on the part of conservation planners.''
The researchers said that about 40 percent of the land involved was
already under protection, and that $500 million over the next five
years _ about twice the cost of a single Mars pathfinder mission _
``could go far toward safeguarding the hot spots.'' That, Dr.
Mittermeier said, is an achievable goal.
</P>
<P>
   The hot spot strategy, he said, ``makes the biodiversity crisis
a bit more manageable,'' and so it ``makes sense to concentrate a
significant portion of our resources and effort on these areas.
Conversely, if we let the hot spots degrade further, we're going to
lose a large proportion of global biodiversity regardless of how
successful we are elsewhere.'' The study assumes that protecting
plants and vertebrates will also protect the majority of
invertebrate species like insects, which account for at least 95
percent of all species.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies have shown that the richness of one group of
species cannot necessarily be predicted from the richness of
another. But if the researchers have captured 30 percent to 50
percent of all plant and large animal species in their hot spot
analysis, ``it means they're probably going to capture pretty much
30 to 50 percent of everything,'' said Dr. Stuart Pimm, an
ecologist at Columbia University, who wrote a commentary on the
Myers paper in Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The study was done with ``extraordinary care and numeric
detail,'' he said, adding that the result is ``one of the most
remarkably optimistic statements about biodiversity that we have
ever seen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
