<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reports may spell future for interest rate hike
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wall Street braced today for the first of a series of
economic reports that may add impetus to another interest rate
increase, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The government's February retail sales report is expected to be
a strong 1.1 percent, and even a brisk 0.6 percent without auto
sales. The January increase was 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a negative for stocks if it is perceived as
additional ammunition for the Federal Reserve to raise interest
rates again when it meets March 21.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has indicated that the
Fed is particularly concerned about consumer spending, and will
raise rates until economic activity slows to a less inflationary
pace. The Fed has raised rates four times since last June.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's market was mixed, opening with widespread losses
following news that Japan's economy had dropped back into a
recession. The 2.8 percent drop in Japan's Nikkei stock average
triggered selling in Asia and Europe before U.S. markets opened.
</P>
<P>
   But the blue-chip Dow Jones industrial average rallied during
the day as investors shopped for bargains among recently hard-hit
consumer stocks, including Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-loaded Nasdaq composite fell 2.8 percent,
however, as investors converted last week's technology gains into
profits. The Nasdaq topped 5,000 last week for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Prudential Securities analyst Michelle Girard
said both producer (Thursday) and consumer (Friday) price indexes
for February ``will be boosted by a rise in food and gasoline
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1928EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
