<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5744 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-TEXAS-POLLS-COX     03-13 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-POLLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush, Gore to wage war for dwing states
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ While Texans vote in today's ex-post-facto
presidential primaries, the men who already have sewn up the
nominations are looking toward the key states that could determine
November's winner.
</P>
<P>
   Most national polls show a tight race between Republican Gov.
George W. Bush and Democratic Vice President Al Gore. But those
surveys are measuring numbers that do not count.
</P>
<P>
   Come November, all that matters are electoral votes. It's a
50-state presidential battle that could be decided by swing states
that have swung Democratic in recent White House races.
</P>
<P>
   The targeted key states include California, Ohio, Michigan,
Missouri and Pennsylvania, which offer a total of 127 electoral
votes. All five went Democratic in 1992 and 1996 after siding with
the GOP in 1984 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Four of those states already have held primaries, complete with
exit polls that offer a glimpse of what's going in voters' minds.
So far, the numbers show ups and downs for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in another potential swing state, Florida, head to the
polls for primaries today. Also on today's primary schedule are
Louisiana, Tennessee, Oklahoma and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   On the GOP side, 341 delegates are available today, more than
enough for Bush to top the 1,034 needed to clinch the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, 566 delegates will be awarded today and
Gore could top the 2,170 needed for nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The races ended last week when Democrat Bill Bradley and
Republican John McCain gave up the chase. Former Ambassador Alan
Keyes remains in the GOP battle, but has collected only a handful
of delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Texas voters today also will be picking nominees for the U.S.
Senate, two Railroad Commission seats, several statewide
judgeships, half the state Senate, the entire Texas House, the
30-member congressional delegation and local posts.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP ballot also includes a non-binding question on whether
student-initiated prayer should be allowed at school sporting
events.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush and Gore, the focus is beyond the primary season that
ends June 6. Both sides are working to put together the 270
electoral votes needed.
</P>
<P>
   The battle starts with an assumption that Bush should carry the
19 states (with 159 electoral votes) that unsuccessful GOP nominee
Bob Dole got in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent polls around the nation show Bush leading in
states with 284 electoral votes. Gore leads in states with 193.
</P>
<P>
   California, with 54 electoral votes, is the big prize. Electoral
College math says Gore cannot win without carrying California. Bush
can, though the task becomes more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes a high-tech core in Silicon Valley, combined with
a chance to do better among Hispanics than Republicans ever have,
can add up to a November victory in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore went head-to-head, sort of, in last Tuesday's
California primary. In the nonpartisan ``beauty contest'' open to
all voters, Gore collected 2.3 million votes (35 percent of those
cast) to Bush's 1.9 million (28 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Republicans might be able to crunch that into a victory by
figuring that the 1.6 million (23 percent) Californians who voted
for McCain are likely to be Bush backers in November.
</P>
<P>
   But a Monday missive from Mississippi shows how that could be
faulty math. Jim Bass, former Mississippi director of the McCain
campaign, is endorsing Gore as the candidate ``more in line with
the values and priorities'' of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls from California also offered a glimpse of potential
November problems for Bush. Sixty-five percent of the voters said
abortion should be legal ``always'' or in ``most cases.'' Bush
believes abortion should be legal only in cases involving rape,
incest or a threat to the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential November factor is that 54 percent of the
California voters who said abortion ``always'' should be legal
voted for McCain, which means, on that issue, they are more likely
to back Gore than Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Another indication that California might not be Bush country:
Exit polls showed Gore beating Bush 51 percent to 43 percent in
November. The same polls showed McCain would have beaten Gore by
five points.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls from recent primaries also offer some data about what
might happen in Missouri and Ohio (where Bush and Gore won their
primaries) and Michigan, where Bush lost to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Among the interesting exit-poll numbers from last Tuesday's
Missouri primaries: Seventeen percent of the GOP voters said they'd
back Gore in a Bush-Gore November battle.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, 15 percent of the voters in last week's GOP primary
said they would vote for Gore over Bush in November, a number that
shows the challenge Bush faces in recruiting McCain backers.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan also presents a swing-state problem for Bush. Despite
the backing of Gov. John Engler, Bush was beaten by McCain in
Michigan. Exit polls there showed 31 percent of the Republican
primary voters saying Bush does not know enough to be president.
</P>
<P>
   In Pennsylvania, where Bush is backed by popular Gov. Tom Ridge,
a Keystone Poll in late February showed Bush in a dead heat with
Gore. Pennsylvania's GOP presidential primary is set for April 4.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Big Five swing states, others in the
up-for-grabs category include Illinois and New Jersey.You may
contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
