<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-LIBEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S SUIT CLAIMS WEB LIBEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BENJAMIN WALLACE-WELLS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elevating a local political feud into a national test case of
truth and the Internet, Mayor John Barrett has sued two political
opponents who created a web site accusing him of being a liar, a
thief, and a child abuser.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, who has been at the center of North Adams, Mass.
political life for decades, including 17 years at mayor, filed the
suit Monday in Berkshire Superior Court, accusing a North Adams
landlord, John Choquette, and a retired city police detective,
William Davis, of defaming him.
</P>
<P>
   Choquette and Davis say they have evidence to back up their
claims, and that they plan to defend the suit on conventional libel
grounds, where truth is an absolute defense.
</P>
<P>
   But legal specialists say Barrett's suit could take on greater
significance if Choquette and Davis are proven wrong, because
courts have so far been reluctant to rein in debate on the Internet
by holding it to the same standards as newspapers and magazines.
Though words put on line are nominally held to the same libel
standards as traditional print media, specialists say that only a
handful of public figures have even tried to sue Internet operators
for libel.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett wants a stricter application of that standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government doesn't step in and start protecting the
rights of people to privacy, as much as the Internet has benefited
us, it could also be a very destructive communication network,''
said Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Legal specialists say the question is intriguing _ whether to
treat the Internet like a publication or like a telephone. Some ask
if it is reasonable to expect website operators to possess the same
legal knowledge as publishers, whose law departments could often
comprise regiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It poses a very interesting question,'' said Jonathan
Zittrain, executive director of the Berkman Center for the Internet
and Society at Harvard Law School. ``When the barriers to getting
speech out there are so low, do we really expect the law to keep
applying the same standard?''
</P>
<P>
   What is for Zittrain an abstract question of law is a case with
deeply tangible political ramifications for people in North Adams _
a city of 14,000 people where political grievances can swiftly turn
personal.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett has been elected mayor eight times, the last time with
63 percent of the vote. Five years ago, Barrett says, he
antagonized some downtown business owners, spawning an opposition
campaign that eventually included Choquette and Davis. After the
most recent mayoral challenge, by City Councilor John Gwodz, failed
to unseat Barrett, Choquette and Davis took their campaign on line.
</P>
<P>
   Their site, www.northadamsfree.com, which they operate on behalf
of a larger anti-Barrett group calling itself The Guardian Angels,
charges that the mayor got a mortgage on highly favorable terms;
that he drives a car bought with city money that the City Council
never approved; that he forged signatures on city documents; that
he verbally abused his staff; that he has a criminal record; and
that, while a North Adams school teacher, he physically abused
students.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett denies all these allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who maintains all the charges are true, says in a small
city like North Adams, where one political hand can easily wash all
others, the Internet can be the only way for dissident political
views to surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barrett's control of the media is nearly absolute,'' Davis
said. ``If you had a gripe, they ain't gonna print it. What's the
alternative? Not much.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis says the flexible format of the Internet allowed his group
to make a well-documented case that it would not have been able to
present by phoning radio shows or writing letters. The website
relies heavily upon the public record _ including articles from
local newspapers, copies of mortgage certificates, even an
automobile registration card.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to establish credibility, especially with 16 years of
propaganda to go up against,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Choquette, who owns the website, says that the very fact of its
existance is useful to the public, since citizens with complaints
now have a place to air them.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the stuff on the website comes from people who have
seen our website and have written in telling us about their
personal experiences with Barrett,'' Choquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett, for his part, calls Choquette a ``screwball'' and says
all the allegations are demonstrably false.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open up the books _ I've got nothing to hide,'' Barrett said.
``My record speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's lawyer, Victor Polk, says that the larger point of the
mayor's suit is to ensure that the law can accommodate the
practical challenges posed by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet makes this kind of defamation so much easier,''
Polk said. ``In the old days you had to have a publisher. What
we've done with a computer is make everyone with a computer a
publisher. While there's good things about that, people sometimes
seem to think they can abuse their rights of free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   At Berkshire Superior Court in Pittsfield, Mass. Monday, a judge
granted Davis and Choquette's lawyer, Robert Isacoff, a week's
extension to give him more time to prepare his case.
</P>
<P>
   While the lawyers in North Adams sweat through their briefs,
however, specialists say the same issues are emerging in other
cases across the country. Most of them are so-called John Doe cases
_ litigants seeking the identities of potential defendants who
often go by chat handles, user names, and other technological
veils.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of this John Doe stuff, there is growing discussion
about whether the rules should be the same'' for Internet
publishers as for traditional publishers, said Christopher Hansen,
a senior counsel at the American Civil Liberties Union. ``It's
almost surely the case that the rules will be at least as
protective. There is some possibility that some additional
protections could be recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle to cases, however, is the Supreme Court rule that
criticism of public figures deserves less scrutiny than that of
private figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upshot is that public figures very rarely sue over libel,
because their chances of winning are so low,'' Zittrain said.
``They have to prove, essentially, not only that the person
attacking them was factually wrong, but also that he had compelling
reasons to know that he was factually wrong, and he went ahead with
the attack anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barrett says while this may be a fair standard for
traditional media, the Internet has changed the profile of the
publisher, so that the law can now be twisted to permit reckless
attacks, pressed onto the Internet without fact-checking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got the so-called scholars out there saying it's
difficult to prove libel,'' Barrett said. ``But in this case he
said I was convicted of a crime and I haven't been. He said I'm a
pedophile, which I'm not. He said I was fired from Green Mountain
racetrack, and I wasn't. He said I settled a suit with a city
councilor in 1984, and that was another mayor. I don't think this
is going to be difficult to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Cases like Barrett's are pending around the country. Specialists
point to a Pennsylvania judge's suit against a website accusing her
of corruption, and a California police officer's suit against a
site accusing him of various abuses.
</P>
<P>
   In five years, Zittrain says, the precedents from these cases
may put Internet libel questions in a new light. But for now, they
need to be trudged through, case by case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sifting out people who are John Hinckley from people who are
Thomas Paine is the trick,'' Zittrain said. ``And there's no easy
way to do that, particularly when the act of suing them may run
them out of business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1933EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5750 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-EVOLUTIONARY-PSYC     03-13 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EVOLUTIONARY-PSYCHOLOGY-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 UNDATED: any evidence.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REAL QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   NOT A SIMPLE MATTER OF NATURE/NURTURE
</P>
<P>
   The nature/nurture dichotomy, however, is in many ways spurious.
No evolutionary scientist would dispute that culture is a powerful
influence, or that environmental forces shape behavior. Darwin
himself was in a sense a ``nurturist'': it was the environment,
after all, with all of its threats, possibilities and
complications, that in his theory ultimately determined which
traits were ``successful'' and passed on to future generations, and
which were not.
</P>
<P>
   A more sophisticated debate, and one central to many of the most
knowledgeable critiques of evolutionary psychology, revolves around
more subtle distinctions, like the timing of evolutionary change,
the criteria used to decide whether something is an adaptation.
Then there is the question of the relative balance of culture and
genes in determining how humans behave.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmides and Tooby argue that the complex mechanisms, or
``design features,'' that they believe make up the structure of the
human mind evolved over millions of years, as combinations of genes
proved successful at reproducing themselves, and gradually spread
through the species, eventually becoming universal.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, they assert, it makes little sense to study
traits that vary from group to group, or society to society. Humans
are basically all the same, they argue, with only a `'dusting'' of
difference. Nor, they say, is it worthwhile to ask whether a
particular behavior is adaptive _ in the sense of producing more
offspring _ in the modern world. Doing so, they say, can lead
scientists wildly astray.
</P>
<P>
   In an example given by Cosmides, a scientist might argue that
smoking cigarettes is ``adaptive'' for teen-age girls because it
causes boys to think they are cool. The boys are then more likely
to choose them as sexual partners.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, researchers should ask what purpose behavior might have
served during the period in which it evolved, a time evolutionary
psychologists refer to as the Environment of Evolutionary
Adaptedness and sometimes pinpoint in the Pleistocene Era, when
human ancestors lived in hunter-gatherer groups.
</P>
<P>
   In the modern world, Cosmides, Tooby and others argue, humans
are not ``fitness maximizers,'' continually strategizing to make
the most of their chances at reproduction and survival.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they are ``adaptation executors,'' carrying out programs
written into the mind's machinery long ago. ``The machinery doesn't
know its own programming,'' Cosmides and Tooby are fond of saying.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists, however, object that this view is much too
narrow, that it requires assumptions that are impossible to test
and ignores the possibility that evolution might in some cases have
proceeded at a faster pace.
</P>
<P>
   They also find the notion of studying only universal traits
perplexing: in studies of animal behavior, a standard procedure is
to study how traits vary in different environmental circumstances
and to explore the effects of different traits on reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a time machine,'' said Dr. Patricia Adair
Gowaty, professor of ecology at the University of Georgia. ``We
don't even know for the Pleistocene what the social and
environmental conditions were. The only evidence we have for these
things is the behavior itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The work of Gowaty, who studies birds, Dr. Sarah Hrdy, a
professor emerita at the University of California at Davis who
studies primates, and other researchers, some of whom study humans,
offers an evolutionary view of male-female relations that differs
sharply from that painted by evolutionary psychologists like Buss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is frustrating to me,'' Gowaty said, ``when I read
these evolutionary psychologists saying that you can't look at
selective process in real-time environments, because these novel
environments might not be like environments of the past. That might
be so. Then again, that might not be so.''
</P>
<P>
   THE DISSENT
</P>
<P>
   IMPACT OF CULTURE GIVEN A GREATER ROLE
</P>
<P>
   Other critics complain that evolutionary psychologists often
underemphasize the extent to which culture influences human
behavior, and ignore equally plausible cultural explanations for
their data.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alice Eagly, for example, a social psychologist at
Northwestern University, has been critical of Buss' research
showing that women rank wealth and status higher in choosing a
sexual partner, while men put a higher priority on physical
attractiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't argue that there are no differences between men and
women,'' Eagly said. ``But there remains a big question whether
things as specific as a preference for money are built in
genetically.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd, of UCLA, also said that culture's impact on behavior was
often underplayed in evolutionary psychologists' work.
</P>
<P>
   While Tooby, Cosmides and others have written extensively about
the ways in which culture might be shaped by the mental mechanisms
humans have evolved, for example, they have spent far less time on
the reverse proposition, that culture itself transmits knowledge
about how to solve problems from generation to generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my research perspective,'' Boyd said, ``evolutionary
psychologists place a much smaller emphasis on cultural variation
than I think is empirically going on. I'm inclined to think of
cultures as evolving over fairly long periods of time, accumulating
information, some of it adaptive, some not adaptive. I still take
an evolutionary perspective, but I don't think we have to have it
all coded in the genes.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Cosmides and Tooby respond that theirs is ``the
first intellectual community that does know what to do with
culture,'' and that can truly address the way biology and culture
interact in creating human societies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Tooby said, he entered graduate school in anthropology
at Harvard in part because ``I was interested in cracking the
problem of culture, in what was the underlying mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the word ``mechanism,'' is in itself controversial. The
notion that the mind is specialized may considered gospel by the
``Santa Barbara Church,'' as one scientist jokingly referred to
Tooby, Cosmides and their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But many researchers remain skeptical that the same
specialization that has been demonstrated for some brain functions
_ vision, for example _ holds when it comes to complex patterns of
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd, for example, said: ``I am convinced that we don't
understand the brain well enough to make these assumptions. I've
read the two sides of this argument, and it seems to me that it's
an open question.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   A YOUNG FIELD STILL TAKING SHAPE
</P>
<P>
   Many scientific disciplines are riddled with internal
disagreements. Physicists fight about why particles have different
masses. Climatologists do battle over global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the intensity of emotion that infuses any discussion of
evolutionary psychology is unusual, even among scientists.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the reason may be that the star actors in this
scientific drama are human beings, and the question at issue is the
nature of being human.
</P>
<P>
   Tooby says he sometimes worries ``that evolutionary psychology
will die because of sociological reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all that anyone has heard about evolutionary psychology
has to do with sex and violence,'' he said. ``But there is insight
to be found for hundreds of really critical topics.''
</P>
<P>
   Other evolutionary scientists who study human behavior say they,
too, are worried: they worry that the controversy is dividing
researchers who should be working together, and that the work of a
relatively small group of scholars is inviting a hostility that the
field _ just recovering from two decades of embattled debate _
hardly needs.
</P>
<P>
   The antidote to such fears, many say, is the faith that
constructive scientific argument often leads to greater knowledge,
and the belief that, for a field still in its infancy, patience is
a virtue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we really know how to do evolutionary psychology
yet,'' said Dr. Randolph Nesse, director of the Evolution and Human
Adaptation Program at the Institute for Social Research at the
University of Michigan. ``I think we have great trouble formulating
our hypotheses, and even more trouble figuring out how to test
them. We know we have a powerful principle, that will eventually
provide a foundation for a deeper and richer psychology. But we
have a lot of work to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
