u a BC-EVERGLADES-EEL-NYTR &LR;      03-13 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-EEL-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN EEL CONFOUNDS SCIENTISTS WHO TRY TO BAR IT FROM EVERGLADES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TOM BAYLES   
 Herald-Tribune (Sarasota, Fla.)   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ A yard-long, gender-bending eel from somewhere
near Vietnam is the latest exotic creature to threaten the
Everglades National Park. And it's really, really hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very voracious predator,'' said Sue Perry, an
Everglades fishery biologist. ``It eats lots of other organisms,
and the area of the park it is likely to enter is very similar to
its habitat in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of the eels were discovered in December in a canal
near Homestead, within slithering distance of the park's boundary.
If they make it into the wide expanse of the Everglades, the
aggressive and highly territorial eels could crowd out bass and
other native fish and gorge on crayfish, worms and frogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Everglades has been under attack by foreign species for
years; Florida is the port of entry for most shipments of live
animals and plants coming into the country. The 1.4 million-acre
reserve is now a virtual exotic nursery and pet shop.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists suspect that the first eels were either exotic pets
dumped in the canal or creatures put there to start a makeshift
farm. Some people consider the olive-brown eel quite tasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began doing field research on them trying to find some
chink in their armor or some weakness we could exploit to control
or eliminate them,'' said Leo Nico, a U.S. Geological Survey
biologist. ``But most of what we've learned about them shows us
that they are less likely to be controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 30 foreign fish species have invaded Florida, but most
are limited to specific habitats like a canal or pond.
</P>
<P>
   The eels' mobility and love of marshes mean that ``potentially,
given decades, these eels could invade large portions of the
U.S.,'' Nico said.
</P>
<P>
   Simply removing the creatures from the canal is not as easy as
it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The eel doesn't seem affected by the most common fish-killing
poison, and a stronger agent such as cyanide can't be used because
the canal is connected to the Floridan aquifer, the source of water
for millions of people. Using chemicals to deplete the oxygen in
the canal's water won't kill the eels because they breathe air like
a dolphin.
</P>
<P>
   Divers can't pick the eels out by hand because they hide in
limestone crevices. Draining the ditch won't work either, because
the eels can burrow into the ground and hibernate for months. The
concussion from a dynamite blast can kill fish by collapsing
pockets of air in their bodies, but the eels don't have any air
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're brainstorming constantly trying to figure it out,'' said
John Curnutt, a biologist with the U.S. Geological Survey's Florida
Caribbean Science Center in Miami. ``This is the time. If you want
to control an exotic species, you jump on it before the population
gets too big.''
</P>
<P>
   A genetically different but similar-looking Asian eel was first
discovered in 1995 in a nature center's pond in Georgia. The pond
was isolated, so scientists didn't become especially alarmed until
two years later, when the eel showed up in water-filled ditches
north of Palmetto and in a canal near Pro Player Stadium in North
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The highly adaptable creatures can survive in nearly any
freshwater habitat with a few inches of water. Because the eels
breathe air, they can survive long dry spells. They can also
survive long periods without food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much is known about the way they work,'' Curnutt said.
</P>
<P>
   Curnutt said the eels are born female, but some change sex as
they mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them switch over to being males as they get quite
large,'' he said. ``You never find a small male, but some of the
big ones are male.''
</P>
<P>
   Other foreign animals already lurking in the Everglades include
rhesus and macaque monkeys, feral pigs, fire ants and Asian tiger
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Among the non-native plants that have popped up in the park are
the melaleuca tree, first introduced into the region in 1906 as an
ornamental plant; Brazilian pepper; Australian pine; Chinese
tallow; skunk vine; air potato; and tropical soda apple.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists hope that an event that could cause flooding, such as
a hurricane that might make the canal become a temporary part of
the Everglades, does not hit before they figure out how to stop the
exotic crawler.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to try to think like an eel,'' Curnutt said.
</P>
<P>
   Nico is less optimistic about keeping the eels out of the
Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are not there now,'' he said, ``they probably will be
within a year or two.''
</P>
<P>
   (Tom Bayles writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
