A5752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AETNA-NYT &LR;      03-13 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AETNA SHARES DECLINE 9 PERCENT AFTER BID IS REJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Disappointed investors drove shares of Aetna Inc.
down $5.25 Monday, or 9 percent, to $50.75, after Aetna rejected an
offer to hold discussions on a tentative takeover bid valued at $70
a share by Wellpoint Health Networks and the ING Group of insurance
and financial services companies.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Donaldson, chief executive of Aetna, said there would
be antitrust and other problems in combining with Wellpoint which,
he said, is ``a much smaller'' health insurer than Aetna. He
insisted that his team, which plans to split Aetna into two
independent companies, could do a better job than Wellpoint and ING
of reviving Aetna's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Wellpoint, based in Thousand Oaks, Calif., covers 7.3 million
health care subscribers, 70 percent of them in California. Aetna,
the nation's largest health insurer, has 22 million members
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ING, a huge Dutch company, said Monday it was still interested
in buying the nonhealth business of Aetna, which has also attracted
other potential bidders. Wellpoint bowed out, saying it was
disappointed by the rejection.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts, Donaldson put rough price
tags on some of his plans. He said Aetna hoped to sell some
international units for $500 million to $1.5 billion. Aetna has 35
overseas units in 17 countries, including joint ventures in Mexico
and Brazil that it has hinted might be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Cooperman, chairman of Omega Advisers, a money management
firm, urged the company to go further and sell assets worth $3.5
billion. Cooperman wants the money returned to shareholders in a
stock buyback at $70 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said that tax rules would limit a stock buyback.
Aetna's plan to spin off independent health and financial services
companies to shareholders on a tax-free basis could become taxable
if company stock was also repurchased, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson also said he expected cost-cutting measures to save
$100 million to $150 million before taxes this year. Some of the
savings would come from a hiring freeze. He said Aetna loses 16
percent of its 48,000 employees through attrition each year, and
many would not be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   He added that other savings might come from shutting some
unprofitable Medicare health maintenance organizations. Aetna
Medicare HMOs have 700,000 members, including 177,000 in New York
and New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
