<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0361 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5753 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NEWSPAPER-MERGER-BOS &LR;      03-13 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPER-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA POWERHOUSE SEEN IN TRIBUNE-TIMES MIRROR DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not quite rival the Time Warner-America Online megamerger
in buzz and bucks, but the Tribune Co.'s stunning $8 billion
proposed acquisition of Times Mirror Co. will create a powerhouse
``old media'' empire anchored in New York, Los Angeles, and
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've created the premier multimedia company in
America,'' said Tribune Co. chairman John Madigan, who will head up
the new company, in a conference call with reporters Monday.
``What's important here is that we'll have a major presence in the
three largest markets in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprise agreement, reached over the weekend, landed like a
bombshell in the media world, reinforcing the idea that bigger is
better and that almost every news outlet is theoretically in play.
The agreement sent Times Mirror stock climbing nearly 80 percent to
$85.625 Monday while Tribune Co. shares dropped nearly 20 percent
to $30.8125.
</P>
<P>
   ``Media companies believe they cannot stand alone,'' said media
critic Jon Katz. ``They're all trying to build up as much
synergistic muscle in new and old media as they can . . . I think
the biggest ethic here is size.''
</P>
<P>
   The new entity, which is still subject to shareholder approval,
will own 11 daily newspapers _ including the Los Angeles Times,
Newsday, the Chicago Tribune, and The Hartford (Conn.) Courant _
and 22 television stations, including WGN-TV in Chicago, WPIX-TV in
New York, KTLA-TV in Los Angeles, and WLVI-TV in Boston. With a
combined circulation of 3.6 million, the new Tribune company will
rank third among newspaper publishers. Having amassed a total of 80
Pulitzer prizes, it also can boast of uniting trusted journalistic
brands.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune Co. officials also stressed the burgeoning online giant
being created, noting that the combined Interent operations attract
an estimated 3.4 million unique monthly visitors and are expected
to earn roughly $55 million in 2000 revenues.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, much of the attention is focused on the
potentially powerful pairing of Times Mirror newspapers with
Tribune Co. TV stations in the same markets. And among those
leading the cheers is John Sturm, president of the Newspaper
Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   The deal proves, ``that newspapers are still a very viable part
of the landscape,'' Sturm said. He was also heartened by the sale's
creation of three new newspaper-television combinations in New
York, Los Angeles, and Hartford, since his association has been
lobbying the Federal Communications Commission to drop its ban on
one company owning a broadcast and newspaper outlet in the same
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketplace has now run right past the FCC and the
antiquated rule it has,'' he says. Tribune Co. officials stated
their belief that FCC policy allows them to maintain the new
broadcast-print combinations until the TV licenses come up for
renewal later this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Tribune Co. _ which already owned four
newspapers, 22 TV stations, two cable stations and the Chicago Cubs
_ has solid reasons for moving on Times Mirror. The company now
becomes a multimedia player in Los Angeles and New York, where it
once owned the New York Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune Publishing president Jack Fuller acknowledged that
``we're very excited about getting back into the metropolitan
market there. New York is a great place to be in journalism and
we're glad to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're buying an incredible franchise'' in the Los Angeles
Times and Newsday, added Tom Rosenstiel, director of the Project
for Excellence in Journalism. ``So you take instant content, the
possibility of convergence, and these incredible assets'' for a
``pittance compared to the Time Warner-AOL deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The motives may have been simpler at Times Mirror, which owns
the Times, Newsday, the Courant, The Sun in Baltimore, several
smaller papers, and a number of magazines. After several tumultuous
years under the leadership of CEO Mark Willes, the owners may have
been happy to ``get rid of Willes and cash out at a high level,''
said Rosenstiel.
</P>
<P>
   News of the Times sale saddened the paper's former publisher,
David Laventhol. ``From the community standpoint, I think it's a
real loss,'' he said. ``I spent 30 years with the Times and you
hate to see it vanish in the mist.'' But, he said, ``the Tribune
people are competent, straightforward people.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are differences in the two corporate cultures. When
Willes arrived at Times Mirror, he shored up investor confidence
with a series of cost-cutting measures. In recent years, however,
he became a lightning rod for controversy by talking about tearing
down the ``wall'' between business and editorial operations. Last
year, the Times _ which has a longstanding reputation as one of the
nation's best and most ambitious papers _ became embroiled in an
ethical nightmare when it shared advertising profits with the
Staples Center sports arena. According to a story in Monday's
Times, Willes, who was ``totally surprised'' when he first learned
of the merger negotiations a few weeks ago, does not plan on
staying on with the newly merged company.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune Co., which has made Fortune's list of ``most admired
companies,'' is a centrally managed operation known for its
corporate efficiencies. On roughly the same 1999 revenue as Times
Mirror, the Tribune Company enjoyed a much larger margin, with a
net income of $1.48 billion that includes a one-time return of $1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company has turned the Chicago Tribune newsroom into a
``newsbucket'' of synergy, utilizing its radio station, TV station,
and cable outlet to deliver the Tribune brand in a variety of
modes. While the paper is respected, it is seen in some quarters as
a journalistic underachiever.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller was careful to insist that the company wouldn't take ``a
cookie-cutter approach,'' toward its new properties. But he did vow
to look ``for operational efficiencies'' to boost the Times Mirror
profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune officials downplayed the significance of the 20-day
period in which additional bidders could try to better their offer
for Times Mirror. Yet, as Madigan himself indicated, this is the
kind of merger that is likely to become more commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if other people look at the future of the business the
way we have, they'll see consolidation will come in this world
where the media has fragmented significantly,'' he said. ``I would
see definitely, further consolidation in the newspaper industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes think we're going to end up with one media company
that's going to run everything,'' added Katz, who decries the
growing conglomerates. ``Let's get it over with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1936EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
