<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-PAPERMERGER-ANALYSIS1     03-13 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPERMERGER-ANALYSIS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Old media' companies merge, blending newspaper, broadcast
assets
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First we had the blockbuster marriage made in new
media heaven, with America Online asking the hand of Time Warner.
On Monday, in a realignment of old media, Tribune Co. of Chicago
agreed to a $6.38 billion merger with Times Mirror Co., the biggest
newspaper deal in years.
</P>
<P>
   The deal brings together a host of broadcast stations, including
WATL in Atlanta, and the Chicago Cubs. The deal creates the third
largest newspaper company in the United States, ending 100 years of
independence by the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the merged company would have its headquarters in
Chicago, headed by John Madigan, chairman of the Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   While the proposed merger sent a buzz through the media
community, Wall Street was not won immediately, with Tribune stock
plunging.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the transaction, shareholders of Los
Angeles-based Times Mirror would have a choice of taking $95 per
share from Tribune Co. or exchanging each of their Times Mirror
shares for 2.5 shares of Tribune stock.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative merger, though small by comparison, comes on the
heels of the massive, pending $163-billion merger of American
Online and Times Warner, and is another apparent step in the
consolidation and realignment of media.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some troubling developments in the newspaper
business in recent weeks,'' said Jay Smith, president of Cox
Newspapers, parent of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and other
newspapers. ``But I see as positive the move by Tribune Co., a very
smart media company, to invest in publishing through its purchase
of Times Mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that diversified media organizations like Cox
Enterprises are, in effect, a model for long-term growth, bridging
the ``old media'' of newspapers as primary news gatherers, and the
``new media'' distribution of information over the air, through
cables and on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Along with its newspaper division, Cox Enterprises owns cable
television systems and high speed data delivery; radio and
television stations; and a growing interactive media service.
</P>
<P>
   Though players in the same business, Tribune Media and Times
Mirror differ in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune firm owns the venerable Chicago Tribune,
Sun-Sentinel of South Florida, Orlando Sentinel and Daily Press of
Hampton Road, Va. It will bolster its print reach through by Times
Mirror holdings that include the Los Angeles Times, Newsday of Long
Island, the Sun of Baltimore and Hartford Courant _ each dominant
in their primary markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune also owns the Cubs and 22 television stations, which
could present some regulatory difficulty. Companies are foreclosed
from owning print media and broadcast stations in the same markets.
However, federal law provides that conflicting properties are not
required to be disposed for a year or until broadcast licenses
expire.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune television stations cover many major markets,
including Chicago, New York, Los Angeles, Philadelphia, Boston,
Houston, Seattle, Denver and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its stable of major newspapers, Times Mirror also
publishes a wide array of magazines including Field &AMP; Stream,
Popular Science, Golf Magazine, Yachting, Skiing and others.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandler family has withdrawn from direct daily control of
the Los Angeles Times operation, with control going to Chairman
Mark Willes since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Willes regime has increased the profitability of the
newspaper handsomely, but has stirred newsroom and industry debate
with its strategy of breaking down barriers between the news
operation and the business and advertising side.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters and editors have acted with suspicion at the blocks
that traditionally have prevented advertisers from trying to
influence news coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The new era of cooperation was dealt a blow recently when it was
disclosed that the newspaper privately entered a revenue sharing
agreement with the new Staple entertainment center. The disclosure
damaged the newspaper's credibility and drew criticism from the
Chandler family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am encouraged by aspects of the proposed merger,'' said
James Naughton, president of the Poynter Institute, a newspaper
training and think tank in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was concerned at the sale of all its domestic
newspapers by Thomson Newspapers and a sell-off of some small
papers by others, which he saw as possible evidence of sliding
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Tribune Company has acted positively by extending its
reach through the merger and creating better synergy between its
assets and the new print outlets.''
</P>
<P>
   News services contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
