<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-NYC14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TBS starts two buildings to renew Atlanta ties
 &HT;    By Tony Wilbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Turner Broadcasting System planted more Atlanta roots
Monday when Ted Turner said Time Warner has no plans to relocate
its subsidiary to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York? It's bad enough to go up and visit,'' Turner said as
TBS began construction on two buildings at its Techwood campus.
</P>
<P>
   The Time Warner vice chairman said the company has exerted no
pressure on TBS to move its executives to Columbus Centre, a huge
real estate project in New York where Time Warner is planning a new
world headquarters. ``No way,'' he said of being forced to move
TBS. ``No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbus Centre will house the headquarters of AOL Time Warner,
the new company that will be formed by the merger of America Online
and Time Warner, a Time Warner spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Since TBS merged with Time Warner in 1996, the company has
invested in several Atlanta projects, including Turner Field,
Philips Arena, the renovation of CNN Center and expansion of the
Techwood campus, TBS Chairman and Chief Executive Terry McGuirk
said. ``We've done so much investing in this city. It's another
statement of the vitality this merger (brings) to Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   With its commitment to the new buildings at Techwood, TBS has
invested more than $600 million in capital projects in Atlanta
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The two new facilities will total 330,000 square feet at the
20-year-old Techwood campus. The 185,000-square-foot network
operations building will support the Turner Entertainment Group.
The 145,000-square-foot administrative building will accommodate
TBS' rapid growth. An underground parking garage also will be part
of the $160 million project.
</P>
<P>
   TBS currently has 1,500 employees at its 35-acre Techwood
campus, where it has about 350,000 square feet of office space. The
company expects to have 2,200 employees at the site by the time the
two new buildings open in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   McGuirk said some of the new businesses created by AOL Time
Warner will be in Atlanta. ``Atlanta is a beneficiary. Turner
Broadcasting is a beneficiary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
