<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREAN-FILMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FILM BOOM RATTLES SOUTH KOREA'S VIEW OF ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ It has never taken much to get the
nationalist juices flowing in this country, where even driving a
foreign-made car is seen by some motorists as nearly tantamount to
treason.
</P>
<P>
   So when the government announced the easing of quotas limiting
the screening of foreign films here in 1999, the instinctive
response of the South Korean film industry was to put together a
campaign of demonstrations against the impending flood of Hollywood
imports.
</P>
<P>
   But if South Korea witnessed a predictable flourish of street
protests over the lifting of quotas, what then ensued was far less
expected and far more interesting: a boom in popular and
groundbreaking Korean films.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, South Korean filmmakers are filling the seats of the
country's movie houses with a bumper crop of thematically
provocative films. And where Korean movies once seemed quaint or
artistically static, many of the best recent features have been
made with the kind of production values more typically associated
with Hollywood or Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swiri,'' a tingling espionage tale, has surpassed ``Titanic''
as the biggest box office earner ever in South Korea. What is more,
the movie has won major commercial exposure for Korean film in
foreign markets, doing well throughout much of the Far East. When
it was released in Japan recently it burst out of the gate, winning
the top ranking at the box office in its first week in the
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swiri'' exemplifies the new Korean filmmaking not only in its
commercial success, its Hollywood-like action scenes and strong
script, but also because of its willingness to take on themes that
only recently were forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   The plot revolves around the romantic relationship of a South
Korean intelligence agent and a seemingly innocuous female office
worker who _ unbeknownst to him almost until the guns-blazing end _
is a North Korean mole. The female lead, moreover, is at the heart
of a diabolical terrorist plot by renegade northern agents bent on
bringing about a war to reunify the divided peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Stories of tangled allegiances like these were systematically
banned in South Korea before President Kim Dae-jung began his
so-called sunshine policy of constructive engagement with the
hardline communist government to the north. Sympathetic treatments
of northerners are as rare as direct peace talks between the
estranged countries. And even Kim was recently taken to task by the
opposition for having called his North Korean counterpart a
``serious'' leader.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop the director, Kang Jae-kyu, from giving a
human side even to ``Swiri's'' North Korean villains. ``Young drunk
kids here, yelling in the streets,'' says the leader of the North
Korean infiltrators in a taunting and pitiful telephone call to his
pursuers from downtown Seoul. ``While people in the North are
starving to death, people here have waste building up in their
bellies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kang said: ``The theme of my film is not ideology, which remains
really controversial in Korea. I just wanted to depict something
the way it is. North Koreans are human beings, from the very same
race that we are. I wanted to understand the characters in terms of
who they are and what they are and not simply treat them as the
enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kang's movie is among the first in a rush of titles dealing with
the face-off between North and South Korea. Others include ``The
Spy,'' a humorous tale about a northern agent who is so clueless
that the police won't believe he is really a spy, and ``Phantom,
the Submarine,'' another thriller.
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War may have faded from Western movie screens, but it
is still a grim reality here, never far from daily life. And the
best of these new films have not only had to struggle with taboos,
but also avoid scaring _ or boring _ away moviegoers with themes
that bring people depressingly back to earth.
</P>
<P>
   ```Swiri' succeeded ultimately because it is good
entertainment,'' said Jae Hyung-jang, 47, who teaches film at
Dongkuk University in Seoul. ``It is an embrace of the Hollywood
style, in terms of dynamic directing, tight plots and, most of all,
suspense.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest success among recent Korean films was
``Lies,'' a film that instantly became controversial because of its
abundant and provocative use of sex. ``Lies'' has been a box-office
hit, although it suffered initially from government attempts at
censorship and black market sales of the film on video.
</P>
<P>
   In matters of public morality and social mores, Confucian South
Korea easily ranks among the most conservative industrialized
societies in the world. And in both his subject matter and his
cinematography, Jang Sun-woo, the movie's director, delivers what
can only be called a withering attack on this world.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a novel that was once banned here and whose author was
jailed, ``Lies'' is the story of an obsessive, sadomasochistic love
affair that develops between an 18-year-old high school girl and a
famous 38-year-old sculptor whose wife is away studying in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the 115-minute film is consumed by the increasingly
unconventional sex between the two, including intense beatings that
the man, named J, administers to the young woman, named Y.
</P>
<P>
   Jang said that the sex in the movie was ultimately meant to be
boring and that the couple's pursuit of erotic pleasure was
intended as an illustration of the emptiness of upper-middle class
life in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The extensive nudity and profanity alone would themselves make
this an unusual and daring film for South Korea. But subtly,
cumulatively rather than by preaching, the movie makes many other
points that few Korean movies have ever made so forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues range from the growing phenomenon of adult sex with
school-age girls, to the compulsive industriousness of Koreans, to
the systematic subordination of women to men through Korea's
codified, honorific-filled language. Two images that seem to have
brought pangs of conscience were early scenes that showed Y in her
school uniform casually talking about sex with an adult and later
scenes when she drops the use of humble speech to address her lover
and finally assumes the sadist's role.
</P>
<P>
   Some people reduce the film to its sexual content, buying
underground copies because of it or condemning it and urging that
the film be banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cultural changes we are undergoing here in Korea are like
a runaway train,'' said Kuk Won-shin, a professor of philosophy at
Chongshin University who leads a citizen's group that urged the
banning of ``Lies.'' ``The core of this movie is cultural guerrilla
warfare,'' he said. ``You have two sides lined up at the front, and
this movie is trying to create a new front, way off in the
distance. We must somehow bring things back in line.''
</P>
<P>
   Comments like these bring a smile of satisfaction from Jang, who
replied: ``This movie can be compared to salt. For some living
things it is a tonic or a preservative. For others, it is a
poison.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
