<HEADLINE>
BARBARA COONEY, 83; WROTE AND ILLUSTRATED BOOKS FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barbara Cooney of Damariscotta, Maine, an author and illustrator
of more than 100 children's books, died Friday in Maine Medical
Center in Portland. She was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Cooney won many awards for her work. In 1959, she was
awarded the Caldecott Medal for children's book illustration for
``The Chanticleer and the Fox, '' a retelling of Chaucer's
cautionary tale about the rooster who bests his wily friend. She
won a second Caldecott Medal in 1980 for her illustrations of
Donald Hall's poem, ``Ox-Cart man.'' She won the American Book
Award for children's literature in 1982 for ``Miss Rumphius,'' the
story of an elderly woman who scattered lupine seeds wherever she
walked to make the world more beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   In a story published in The Boston Globe on Sept. 14, 1986, Miss
Cooney explained: ``In the beginning was the word. That is the most
important thing to remember. It isn't your pictures. It is what is
said. It's like a string of beads: if you don't have the string it
won't hang together.''
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Room 1127 of the Hotel Bossert in Brooklyn,
N.Y., which was built by her maternal grandfather. She was raised
on Long Island and spent summers in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Smith College, she studied at the Art
Students League in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked to read,'' she said in 1986, ``so I thought it would
be perfect to do book illustrations. I never thought of it as a
secondary art. Many people do, of course, because it is
reproduction. But when you stop and think about it, when you think
of all the people who illustrated the Bible and all those people
who illustrated Homer, all those vase painters and so forth, I
really do think it is an art. You have the capacity to reach so
many, many people.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Cooney served in the Women's Army Corps during World War
II. She was discharged for ``the convenience of the government,''
according to her discharge papers, when she became pregnant with
her first child.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, Miss Cooney gave $550,000 to the Damariscotta
Library, to be used in part to raise money for a new library on the
condition that it remain downtown. ``Libraries are the custodians
of civilization,'' she said, later increasing her gift by $300,000.
Groundbreaking for the new library is next month.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, she was declared a ``living treasure of the State of
Maine'' by Governor Angus King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara's death is a tremendous loss to the literary community
and to the people of Maine,'' King said Monday. ``As the father of
five children, I consider myself a connoisseur of children's books
and I would put `Miss Rumphius' in the stratosphere of the top five
children's books, which would include `Where the Wild Things Are,'
`Goodnight Moon' and anything involving Curious George.''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves her husband, Charles Talbot Porter; two daughters,
Gretel Porter of Freeport, Maine, and Phoebe Porter of Conway,
Mass.; two sons, Barnaby Porter of Damariscotta and Charles T.
Porter Jr. of Puerto Williams, Chile; two brothers, Daniel Cooney
of Darien, Conn., and David Cooney of Arlington Heights, Ill.;
three grandchildren, and a great-grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
