<SLUG> BC-PARKS-FIRING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA PARKS WORKER FIRED AFTER GLOBE PUBLISHES COMMENTARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona state park officials fired an employee last week after
he wrote an opinion piece for the Boston Globe criticizing the
artificiality of a popular new state park.
</P>
<P>
   Parks director Kenneth Travous said the article brought
``discredit and embarrassment to the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for a Washington employee whistleblower group are
challenging the dismissal of Matt Chew, charging that Arizona has
violated his right to free speech. Before this incident, Chew had
favorable job reviews for seven years at the parks department, the
attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite appearances to the contrary, Arizona state employees
remain American citizens,'' said Jeff Ruch, director of Public
Employees for Environmental Responsibility, which is defending
Chew. ``Bureaucratic tin despots like Ken Travous cannot run a
gulag Arizona where dissidents are summarily exiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Bilbrey, a spokeswoman for the department, declined to
comment because she said Chew's firing is a personnel matter.
</P>
<P>
   In Chew's piece, which appeared in the Globe's Focus section
Feb. 6, he criticized the Kartchner Caverns State Park, a cave
filled with bats where scheduled tours are sold out into the
spring. Chew said the parks department had to ``civilize'' the cave
to allow the public in, making entrances easier and adding lights
to eliminate the pitch blackness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took something unimaginable and reduced it to what we could
imagine, the predictable product of an unremarkable mindset,'' said
Chew, the natural areas program coordinator and planner for Arizona
State Parks.
</P>
<P>
   But Travous said that Chew should not have identified himself in
the article as a parks employee and said he misused the state
computer system in e-mailing it to the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your misconduct also wrongfully sought to bring discredit and
embarrassment to the state,'' wrote Travous in a Feb. 24 letter
informing Chew that he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Chew denies that he did anything wrong by disclosing his title
in the article, which Globe policy requires, or that he misused the
state computer system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a constitutional right to express my opinion and I did
not intend, nor do I believe my essay does, bring any discredit on
the state or the people who work for it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 1944EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
