<SLUG> BC-AETNA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aetna action brings relief to some
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Aetna's rejection of a $10 billion buyout offer by
WellPoint Health Networks and a second company should ease some
sudden jitters for investors and shareholders in Blue Cross and
Blue Shield of Georgia's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   The bid for Aetna, launched in late February, had appeared to
imperil WellPoint's pending $500 million acquisition of Cerulean,
parent of Blue Cross.
</P>
<P>
   State or federal regulators could have decided not to let
California-based WellPoint hold both Blue Cross' and Aetna's
memberships in Georgia. Together, they could encompass more than 50
percent of metro Atlanta's managed care enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   If the WellPoint purchase of Blue Cross of Georgia goes through,
several groups stand to benefit, including Cerulean shareholders,
private investors, a health care foundation, and more than 250 Blue
Cross employees.
</P>
<P>
   That deal has been delayed for months by a legal question of
determining the number of Cerulean shareholders. State Insurance
Commissioner John Oxendine also must approve the WellPoint
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint and Cerulean remain ''firmly committed'' to closing
their transaction as soon as possible, Charlie Harman, a company
vice president, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   WellPoint and a unit of Dutch-based ING Group offered $44 in
cash and $26 in WellPoint common stock for each share of Aetna. ING
Group, a financial services company, owns Life of Georgia, an
Atlanta-based life insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   While rejecting the offer, Aetna said Sunday it will split into
separate financial services and health care businesses, each
publicly traded. Aetna said it will also likely sell off parts of
its international business.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's shares fell $5.25 Monday to $50.75 in New York Stock
Exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analyst Kenneth Abramowitz of Sanford C. Bernstein
predicted Aetna will be worth more, by the end of the year, than
the $70 per-share offer.
</P>
<P>
   Abramowitz added that splitting the company into two ``generally
leads to a rejuvenation of both companies.''
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Edmund Kroll of SG Cowen &AMP; Co. noted that there were
not many details available about Aetna's restructuring plan.
``Investors are showing their skepticism,'' said Kroll, though he
added the split could end up benefiting Aetna. ``It would separate
the financial services from the taint of the HMO business,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford-based Aetna's shares had plummeted for about a year
before the news surfaced of WellPoint's acquisition bid.
</P>
<P>
   While saying it's open to other ``responsible'' offers, Aetna
announced plans to sell up to $1.5 billion in international assets,
to consider spinning off an Internet site and related businesses,
and to cut costs by $100 million to $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at all our options, this is the best way to maximize
our assets,'' said William Donaldson, Aetna's chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna will study ways to improve the operations of its health
insurance unit, whose struggles with higher costs have depressed
the share price, Donaldson told investors during a conference call.
``Everything is on the table,'' said Donaldson. He replaced Richard
Huber, Aetna's chairman and chief executive, who resigned last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Other problems for Aetna include class-action litigation and
frayed relations with physicians and hospitals, including in metro
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said the offer from WellPoint and ING was too low and
brought problems with integration. ``There were problems in the
areas of legality and antitrust as well as the problem of a
competitor coming in and looking at our books,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna's board was also concerned because WellPoint, while well
managed, doesn't have enough experience outside its home base of
California, Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   Wellpoint, which said it is ``disappointed'' by Aetna's
decision, added in a statement that it continues to believe that
the offer represents ''outstanding value for Aetna's
shareholders.'' ING said it's still interested in a transaction
with Aetna.
</P>
<P>
   The WellPoint-Blue Cross of Georgia acquisition, if completed,
would lead to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Thousands of Blue Cross policyholders who own Cerulean shares
getting cash and/or shares of stock in WellPoint.
</P>
<P>
   _ A group of private investors, who sank about $50 million into
Cerulean, netting a profit of $60 million in WellPoint stock.
</P>
<P>
   _ About 280 Blue Cross employees sharing a total of $28 million
in incentive bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   _ The endowment of a new nonprofit health care foundation with
$80 million in cash and WellPoint stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Cross shareholder issue will be addressed next week by
a three-judge panel of the Georgia Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Wire services contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
