<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-NOTALK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis limo riders want immunity before talking
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At least two passengers in the limousine with pro
football star Ray Lewis during a Buckhead stabbing incident are
refusing to talk to prosecutors unless they are given immunity,
their attorneys said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance of the witnesses to talk _ and others are
apparently seeking similar deals _ displays the difficulty
prosecutors face in building a solid case against Lewis in the
stabbing murders, their attorneys say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells me they indicted (Lewis) too quickly,'' said Atlanta
attorney Bruce Morris, who also is seeking an immunity deal for his
client Kwame King, a friend of Lewis who was in the limousine in
the early morning hours of Jan. 31. Morris said King has not yet
talked to police or prosecutors, although he has spoken with Lewis'
defense team.
</P>
<P>
   King fears being charged with a crime if his account of the
scene does not fit the prosecution's theory, Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the prosecution expects a certain statement''
supporting the prosecution, said Morris. ``Then they are
disappointed and question the veracity of that statement. My client
has no wish for that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris said prosecutors have assured him that King is not a
suspect. ``But I want that in writing'' before he talks, Morris
said. Witnesses don't have to talk to police but can be forced to
testify at trial. However, lawyers always want to know what a
witness will say before he takes the stand.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard declined to comment,
citing a gag order.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 24, an All Pro linebacker, was indicted Feb. 11 on murder
and assault charges in the stabbing deaths of Jacinth Baker, 21,
and Richard Lollar, 24, both of Decatur. Two of Lewis'
acquaintances, Reginald Oakley, 31, of Baltimore and Joseph
Sweeting, 31, of Miami also were charged with murder. Trial is set
for May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, out on $1 million bail, has been working out at the
Baltimore Ravens' training complex near Baltimore. His two
co-defendants remain jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County prosecutors gave immunity 10 days ago to Jessica
Robertson, a woman who was with Lewis in the limousine and later in
his hotel room. She turned over nine garment bags of Lewis'
clothing, which is being tested for blood. She was also the first
of about 10 passengers in the limo to talk with prosecutors. (Lewis
talked briefly with police the day of the killings.) She named the
other passengers, some of whom have hired lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors felt ``let down'' by what Robertson told them, said
Atlanta attorney Dwight Thomas, who represents another passenger in
the vehicle. ``They didn't hear what they wanted to hear,'' said
Thomas, who claims his client, an unidentified Texas law student,
had a better vantage point of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said his client, who was in Atlanta Monday, was
``spooked'' when Fulton County district attorney's investigators
and Houston homicide detectives went to his client's mother's home
this weekend, Thomas said. Thomas said investigators showed the
woman pictures of the dead men lying in the street and the made
``questionable representations'' to her, telling the woman her son
doesn't need an attorney to talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   The incident only fueled fears that prosecutors may charge him
with a crime, Thomas said. Prosecutors are reluctant to give
immunity to any other witnesses, especially to men who were in the
vehicle that night because they don't know what involvement those
other passengers may have had in the deadly fight. ``It's
(prosecutors') theory the males are somewhat involved,'' he said.
``But with that in the back of their minds, I don't want my client
talking without (immunity).''
</P>
<P>
   RAY DUFFEY / Tallahassee Democrat
</P>
<P>
   Kwame King (left) is not a suspect, his lawyer says prosecutors
assured him.
</P>
<P>
   wfears talking with prosecutors, his attorney says.
</P>
<P>
   Pic of Kwame King, who is seeking immunity to testify in Lewis
case
</P>
