   EUROPE-GENES-FOOD (The Hague, Netherlands) _ In Europe, the
debate over genetically modified food is as much about theater as
it is about science. Polls show that few Americans realize that
nearly two-thirds of the products on supermarket shelves contain
ingredients from genetically altered plants. But British tabloids
routinely call such ingredients ``Frankenfood,'' and pollsters say
only 1 percent of Britons think genetically modifying plants has
any value at all. By Donald G. McNeil Jr. (Scheduled to move by
8:15 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 2,100 words.
