   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-IMMIG (Sagamihara City, Japan) _ Little known to its
inhabitants, who include a sprinkling of Chinese and Southeast
Asians, this otherwise unremarkable town an hour outside of Tokyo
could soon be known as a forerunner of Japan's 21st century
immigration boom. Shrinking faster than any other nation, this
country's population is projected to decline by 17 percent during
the next half century. Government experts, demographers and
economists say that as Japan loses people _ and workers _ the only
way for it to maintain its lofty living standards is to quickly
begin accepting immigrants in far greater numbers and to abandon
the age-old comfort of its near-uniform ethnicity. By Howard W.
French. (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,800
words.
