<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5772 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-MARINO-MIAMI-1STL     03-13 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARINO-MIAMI-1STLD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH FLORIDA FANS RECALL MARINO'S BOYISH EXUBERANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs to correct copyright date)  
(See also FBN-MARINO) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT3 and NYT4 are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Miami Dolphins' millionaire quarterback was beloved
for his heart-squeezing comeback drives, for his quick release and
his perfect, arching spiral, and for his toughness, for playing
with a battered body that seemed as if it would fall to pieces if
he untied all the knee braces, ankle splints and rib protectors he
wore into battle.
</P>
<P>
   But what Mike Vogt, a fan, will miss most is the feeling that,
every time he saw the famous Dan Marino at work, he was seeing a
boy at play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we all loved about him was he had this boyish
joy,'' said Vogt, after he learned Monday that the National
Football League's record-shattering passer and South Florida's most
famous sports celebrity had finally, officially retired. ``We all
felt that.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino would smile and even hop in the air like a little boy
when he completed a long pass, and would pout and fret, his face a
bright, shining red, when he was intercepted or a receiver dropped
the ball, recalled the Dolphin fans who were really, at heart,
Marino fans.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if, depending on the situation, he was always on the
verge of either snatching up the ball and going home, or
celebrating with a glass of chocolate milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he'd throw the ball, he'd just grin like a 10-year-old
would,'' said Vogt, a computer programmer in Boca Raton who has
been a Marino fan for all of his 17 years as a Dolphin. ``He was
magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino, who threw the football down field, with varying results,
more times than anyone in professional football ever has, will not
throw for the Dolphins _ or for anyone else _ ever again. And in
South Florida, even though his retirement had been rumored for
months, people who followed Miami football reacted with a mix of
gloom and relief.
</P>
<P>
   After a disappointing year in which he played injured and played
as a mortal, not the superstar who built a legend, he chose to
retire at age 38 rather than attempt a comeback with the Dolphins
or another team. He watched a young, strong backup win games in his
place, and it became clear that the future did not include him here
in the city that worshiped him, at least not in an aqua-and-orange
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sundays will not be the same,'' said Richard Molinary, a
customer service representative who works in Hollywood, north of
Miami in Broward County.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be like something's not quite right,'' said Molinary,
who has a fame of his own in Florida sports circles as the
often-photographed ``Miami Fanatic,'' because he paints his face in
Dolphin colors and wears a Dolphins towel like a cape. ``I started
my career when he started his, in 1983, so I've watched him game
after game for all these years. They've been some of the best years
of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Molinary and other fans winced as injuries to Marino's knees and
ankles took their toll, as their hero took the field in football
cleats that were so built-up and padded that they looked more like
the boots worn by Frankenstein's monster. At times, it seemed like
Marino was so tightly bound and strapped that the only thing that
really moved was his arm.
</P>
<P>
   It does not matter to people who loved him that Marino's last
game was a 62-7 playoff loss at Jacksonville. ``He is the Babe Ruth
of football,'' Molinary said, standing outside the Dolphins'
training camp in Davie Monday, as inside, Marino announced his
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Marino did not cry; he just seemed as if someone had let all the
air out of him, even as the Dolphins' owner, H. Wayne Huizenga,
told him he would have a statue erected of Marino outside Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to miss Sunday afternoons,'' Marino said.
</P>
<P>
   Marino became a superstar when Miami was a greatly different
city, when English, not Spanish, was still the principal language
and the region had only the Dolphins _ there was no professional
basketball, hockey or baseball in Miami then.
</P>
<P>
   Now Miami is generally regarded as the financial, cultural and
entertainment capital of Latin America, where international soccer
crowds fill the Orange Bowl. In downtown Miami, where the
storefront signs are mostly in Spanish and the pedestrians, many of
them new Americans, talk of everything but football, Marino's
retirement was barely noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could care less about football or Dan Marino,'' said Lydia
Martin, speaking in Spanish at a courtyard restaurant in downtown
Miami. ``They make him sound like he's God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make a difference in my personal life,'' said
Martin, who was born in Colombia and has been living in Miami for
three years.
</P>
<P>
   While his retirement was covered by Spanish-language television,
radio and newspapers, Marino's fan base has mostly moved north to
Broward and Palm Beach counties, along with most of the region's
Anglos. Even the Dolphins' stadium itself has moved north, from the
Orange Bowl in downtown Miami to up near the Broward line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's part of the old Miami,'' said Tony Segreto, an anchor for
WTVJ, the NBC affiliate in Miami, and co-host of Marino's
television show. But, said Segreto, he also drew many new fans from
the new Miami, in the way only a superstar athlete could. ``I don't
think an athlete can ever have the same impact on this town.''
</P>
<P>
   After every famous athlete's retirement, fans and media exhaust
superlatives in creating their legend. But in Miami, say longtime
fans and friends, Marino will be remembered almost as much for what
he did not do as for what he did.
</P>
<P>
   He never won a Super Bowl, ``the burning desire, what I played
for,'' said Marino, who lost his one chance in a 1985 loss to Joe
Montana and the San Francisco 49ers, 38-16.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike so many sports superstars of the past decade, he
never embarrassed himself in the community he represented. He was
never arrested driving drunk, doing or buying cocaine, soliciting a
prostitute, resisting arrest at a wild party or become entangled in
a nasty paternity suit, said fans. ``He's the kind you want to
emulate,'' said Kenny Dorsey, the freshman starting quarterback at
the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of making headlines with the police, Marino made them by
adopting a Chinese baby, Niki Lin, with his wife, Claire, rescuing
the child from an orphanage. He spent and raised millions for
charities. In 1992 he established the Dan Marino Foundation to
benefit children's charities, and did television commercials with
his autistic son, Michael, to help raise money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's become more than just the guy who throws the ball,'' said
Jimmy Cefalo, who played football with the Dolphins and Marino as a
wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   His former coach, Don Shula, summed up his quarterback's time in
Miami this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``You just want to applaud.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
