<SLUG> BC-DABRAT-AMBUSH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rapper may have been shooters' aim
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the people shot in a stretch limousine in the
parking lot of an apartment complex Sunday morning may have been
mistaken for local rapper Shawntae Harris _ known as Da Brat _
police and one of the limo's passengers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the nine passengers in the black Toyota limousine were
shot by two men just outside Harris' town house in Buckhead,
Atlanta's upscale residential area and entertainment district.
Investigators said the shooters may have mistaken the ambushed
vehicle for one Harris rents occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not ruling anything out at this time,'' said Sgt. Rick
Chambers. ``The shooters may or may not have been after Harris.
This happened in her apartment complex and the limousine looks like
one she rents.''
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation against Harris also has not been ruled out as a
motive for the shooting, Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of March 7, Harris and another woman alledgedly
were involved in a fight inside the Chili Pepper nightclub in
Buckhead. Rezue Robateue said Harris struck her across the eye with
a .22-caliber gun after a companion of Harris' told Robateue to
leave the club's VIP lounge, said Robateue's attorney, Jim Lewis.
Harris' attorney, B.J. Bernstein, said her client is innocent and
has no connection to Robateue, described by Lewis as an aspiring
rapper.
</P>
<P>
   Police at the Sunday shooting scene said one of the limousine
passengers said the incident may have been retaliation for the
Chili Pepper brawl.
</P>
<P>
   One of the passengers in the limousine said the vehicle entered
the Post Chastain complex about 3:40 a.m. Sunday to drop off
another member of the party who lives there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea Da Brat also lived there,'' said Carmille
Plummer. ``We had gone to a birthday party and we were going back
home dropping off people at their apartments. When we all got back
into the limo and started to drive off, we were about to turn
around in the parking lot when we were confronted by two men who
got in front of the limo and just started shooting at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer said she is not sure whether the two men followed the
limousine inside the gated complex or were already waiting in the
parking lot facing Harris' building. They shot at the vehicle 13
times, striking chauffeur Rodney Kemp and passengers Steve Bennet,
Fray Gordon, Sonya Kelley and Pamela Johnson. Only Bennet had been
released from Grady Memorial Hospital by Monday afternoon,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Originally police said the shooters left the complex in a
late-model Ford Thunderbird. But Monday, Chambers said it's not
clear what kind of car the men were driving.
</P>
<P>
   The incident has prompted management at Post Chastain to beef up
security, said Michelle Toups, vice president of Atlanta-based Post
Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein and Harris' publicist, Tresa Sanders, said Harris is
in Cancun filming a video and is staying abreast of developments in
the shooting case.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is not getting the news in Mexico, but we're talking to
her regularly,'' Bernstein said. ``She is innocent of the charges
filed against her in last Tuesday's incident, but if this
(shooting) is retaliation against her, then it just shows the
instability of the people who were involved in that fight and are
accusing her.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
