<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A CASE FOR JANET RENO
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's becoming increasingly clear that Al Gore came within an
inch of acquiring his own personal special prosecutor last year.
But Attorney General Janet Reno wimped out at the last minute,
ignoring the pleas of her own assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God for Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   She has not been one of your all-time great attorneys general.
In the future, America may best remember Reno as the picture on the
wall of Director Skinner's office in ``The X-Files.'' Still, she's
a grown-up serving in an administration full of adolescent
personalities, and the most adult decision of her life was to say
no when she was asked to sic a special prosecutor on the vice
president at a time when the president himself was already well on
his way to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has a lot to answer for when it comes to the way he
scrounged money for the 1996 Democratic campaign, particularly the
fact that he seemed to like it. ``Is it possible to do a
reallocation for me to take more of the events and the calls?'' he
asked during a White House strategy meeting. Our Al, always with
his hand up. Will the kid never stop volunteering?
</P>
<P>
   Come November, people are going to have to think very hard about
whether they want a president who enjoys calling up rich people and
asking them for money. We've survived one chief executive with
unseemly ideas of what constitutes a good time, but this may be
going too far.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gore got into trouble with the Justice Department over
something far more specific, and far less disturbing. He made
fund-raising calls from his White House office. There's an old law
barring federal employees from soliciting campaign contributions in
federal buildings. Nobody's sure if it applies to the vice
president, but if Gore had gone outdoors and used the family cell
phone, we would not be having this conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general decided this wasn't a job for a special
prosecutor. But like everything involving the law and this
benighted administration, things got more complicated. Reno had
relied on assurances that the vice president was raising ``soft
money'' for the Democratic Party, not ``hard money'' for the
Clinton-Gore campaign. It turned out that wasn't true.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he didn't realize any of the money he was collecting
had gone to his own campaign. But then a memo surfaced. He said he
hadn't read it. It turned out he had attended a meeting where the
subject came up. He said he wasn't listening. Leon Panetta told
investigators the vice president had looked pretty attentive to
him. Gore said he had been drinking a lot of iced tea and therefore
might have been answering a call of nature when the incriminating
discussion took place.
</P>
<P>
   People, you are also going to have to decide whether you want a
president who has to go to the bathroom just when the most critical
moment of a meeting occurs. But when you pare down the legal issue
Reno was considering, it was whether somebody lied about something
that was peripheral to the original issue, which wasn't all that
big a deal to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's real offense wasn't picking up the wrong phone, but
allowing his office to become mired in sleazy fund-raising ventures
that he should have kept at arm's length out of a simple sense of
propriety. He isn't off the hook for that. The Republicans are
already preparing the ads. This fall you'll see so many pictures of
the vice president making nice with donation-bundling Buddhists,
you'll think it's a new TV series. There'll be endless tapes of him
trying to weasel out of the phone call thing by babbling about
``controlling legal authority.'' He understands how much trouble
he's in _ witness his sudden re-emergence as a born-again reformer,
the Saul of Tarsus for campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   If the ethical slovenliness of the Clinton administration costs
him the presidency, the Democrats will have learned a lesson. If he
wins, perhaps the Republicans will wonder if they made a mistake
nominating a guy who's deep in the money pit himself.
</P>
<P>
   Not the most attractive choice the American voters have ever
faced, but when we make it, we won't have to wait for a special
prosecutor to tell us whether or not it was OK. Thank you, Janet
Reno. We owe you one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
