A5782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES14-COX     03-13 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millwood quickly becomes a mainstay of Braves staff
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRADENTON, Fla. _ No one is ever going to accuse Kevin Millwood
of being in a hurry. The native of Bessemer City, N.C., walks
slowly, talks slowly and doesn't seem to be fazed by much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's your basic laid-back country boy,'' said Chipper Jones,
who should know. ``Everything's in slow motion for him. He's just
one of those guys who gets really focused really fast when it's
time to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to pitching, Millwood has been in fast-forward
ever since he stepped on a major-league mound. This spring is no
exception.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two seasons, Millwood has gone from fifth to fourth
and now third in the Braves rotation. The most recent move came a
week ago with word that John Smoltz would miss the season because
of a torn elbow ligament.
</P>
<P>
   But before he gets ahead of himself, Millwood, coming off his
first All-Star Game appearance and the best season on the Braves'
vaunted pitching staff, just hopes that not much changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole goal this year is the same as it was last year,''
Millwood said. ``I just want to give us a chance to win every time
I pitch. If I do that, then the numbers are going to come. That's
not something I really have to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Going to the All-Star Game ``in my second full season is pretty
special,'' he said, ``but I don't want the first one to be my last
one. I can't have a lack of concentration and think I've got this
game whipped. When you think you're bigger than the game, then one
year or another it's going to jump up and bite you, so I'm just
trying to stay on an even keel and keep working hard and try to
make myself better every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three springs ago the name Millwood didn't register with
Bobby Cox. Then, on a rainy day in West Palm Beach, Fla., Cox
wandered into the indoor batting cages to watch some of the younger
pitchers in camp. He saw Millwood, then a 22-year-old minor-league
pitcher who never had thrown above the A level. Cox immediately was
impressed and began talking him up. Millwood was in Atlanta by the
middle of that season.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1997, Millwood was the Braves' fifth starter. And
unlike the steady stream of arms to follow Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine
and Smoltz in recent years, he has stuck around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stays under control. He doesn't get rattled,'' Cox said.
``He's the same all the time. Great makeup. Great disposition.
Great competitor. He's a nice kid, but he'll compete with
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Millwood broke into the starting rotation for good Aug.
30, 1997, he has won 38 games and posted a 3.28 ERA. He has 35
victories in his first two full seasons. Smoltz won 26 his first
two full seasons, Maddux 24 and Glavine 21.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was different, though. Millwood had won 17 games in
1998 despite a 4.08 ERA. Last year, he won 18 with a 2.68 ERA. He
flirted with three no-hitters, held opponents to a
major-league-leading .202 batting average and finished second to Cy
Young winner Randy Johnson (2.48) among the National League ERA
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the two years?
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience, innings,'' Maddux said. ``Spend more time doing
it, learning what restaurants to go to on the road, how to get to
the parks, how to pitch hitters better.... He knows how to use his
pitches to take advantage of his stuff, where a lot of guys
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood was the best Braves starter for long stretches last
season. He also pulled the Braves even in their best-of-five
Division Series against the Astros with a one-hitter in Game 2, the
first postseason appearance of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had success early, but not that much that early.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants so bad to do so good to get his piece of the pie,''
Maddux said. ``That's a great motivating tool. Once you get your
piece, you get to look for other reasons to stay motivated. He'll
find some. Pride is a big, big motivator.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood will make a modest $420,000 this season in the final
year before he is eligible for salary arbitration. Then, he will
command millions.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it will change him much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not reading every paper he can get his hands on or
staying up late to see SportsCenter 10 times,'' Maddux said. ``He
takes things in stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Not content just to repeat what he did last year, Millwood spent
the offseason trying to improve his change-up, a pitch he has not
used to get outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still learning, still trying to make myself better,''
Millwood said. ``I'm not saying I'm going to lead the league in
batting-average-against again, but I think I have a pretty good
chance at having another good year.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only place Millwood has lagged behind his fellow
starters is on the golf course. He's not as attached to golf as his
fellow starters, and apparently it shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrible,'' Maddux said. ``Quit snap-hooking. Ever try a fade
once in a while? You make adjustments on the mound, why can't he do
it on the course? I'm tired of trying to find his balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
