<SLUG> BC-RODALE-HEALTHY-PARENTING-ADV21-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV21 
 MINIMIZING POST-OP DISORIENTATION FOR ELDERLY PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by RODALE clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text.) 
 (FOR RELEASE MON., MARCH 21, 2000) 
 (EXCERPTED FROM PREVENTION) 
 (Includes electronic art.) 
 By DR. MARK S. LACHS with PAMELA BOYER 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Often our parenting responsibilities extend beyond our children
to include our elderly parents. The following reader wondered what
could be done to help an elderly parent's recovery following
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: My dad had elective hernia repair and became quite
confused following the surgery. This lasted for several days and
was quite alarming. Why did he react this way, and could we have
prevented it?
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: The story you tell is both common and upsetting. The
older parent is admitted to the hospital for a seemingly minor
medical procedure that goes off without a hitch. Then, a day or two
later, he becomes confused and agitated. He may have hallucinations
or be unable to have a normal conversation from start to finish.
And often, just when it seems that things are starting to improve a
bit, the process begins again.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned family members will justifiably ask the doctor
``What's happening?'' and may not get a satisfactory answer.
Perhaps a CT or MRI of the head is performed, which reveals no
stroke or other abnormality. This is, of course, reassuring, but it
doesn't resolve the basic question: What's going on?
</P>
<P>
   Your dad was likely suffering from what geriatricians call acute
confusional state (ACS) or delirium. You might be surprised to
learn that when older adults are admitted to the hospital for any
reason and are carefully followed and assessed for delirium, as
many as half may show some manifestations of it.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know exactly what causes delirium, but we have some
ideas. Do you remember learning that we never use the majority of
our brain cells? Gerontologists call this extra capacity
physiologic reserve _ extra fuel, which in this case is brainpower.
We don't need it unless we are ``taxed'' or stressed in some
unusual way and forced to reach into our bank of extra brainpower
to keep functioning.
</P>
<P>
   Acute illness or surgery is such a stress. In addition to
surgery, there may be other hospital-related stresses on the older
person, such as postoperative fever, blood imbalances in
electrolytes and minerals, steep disruption and medications given
in the hospital _ such as those intended to aid with anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   Younger people may tolerate these incursions just fine. But the
normal aging process is associated with a loss of physiologic
reserve, meaning that there's less extra brainpower to tap during
stressful situations such as surgery or acute medical illness. The
result is delirium. The good news is that there are ways to
minimize its duration and impact.
 &UR; PUTTING AN END TO THE CONFUSION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first step in diagnosing and treating delirium should be
taken by the doctor. He needs to identify and treat all the medical
factors that could influence a person's mental state. These include
any medications being taken (patients with delirium should have
their medicines carefully reviewed), common infections in older
people such as those types seen in the lungs or urine, and all
blood abnormalities such as remarkably high or low blood sugar. And
aggressively treating other discomforts such as pain and fever can
also help to reduce the stress.
</P>
<P>
   Once all medical problems are either ruled out or treated,
there's an important role for the family: assisting the nursing
staff. Using clearly visible clocks and calendars to orient the
person as to the date and time can help restore the sleep/wake
cycle. Often, hospitalized patients are awakened throughout the
night for other procedures or because a roommate is ill and needs
attention. These alterations in the biological clock can contribute
to disorientation.
</P>
<P>
   Many geriatric inpatient units also encourage family members to
bring familiar possessions from home, such as a photograph or
favorite pair of pajamas. Familiar items and surroundings may help
to orient the older person. You should be aware that low-grade
delirium can persist for many weeks after hospital discharge,
though the familiarity of home tends to have a beneficial
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Persistent confusion at home, however, requires further
evaluation by a physician skilled in geriatric medicine to make
sure that something else isn't at the root of the problem.
 &UR; OPTIONAL SIDEBAR: DELIRIUM VERSUS DEMENTIA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Delirium has several features that can help the doctor
differentiate it from dementia or other neurological illnesses.
First, it usually has an abrupt onset, such as when the older
person developed a fever or got a medication he could not tolerate.
This is in contrast to Alzheimer's disease, which typically runs a
slow course.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful, however: Patients with Alzheimer's are at higher
risk for delirium when they are hospitalized. (It's possible to
have both.) Once it starts, delirium tends to manifest itself in
certain ways. Inattention _ the inability to focus on a particular
task at hand _ may be prominent. Thus, patients may be unable to
focus on a logical thread of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature of delirium is a waxing and waning course. Just
when it seems that they've snapped out of it, they revert to
confused behavior. As a general rule, patients with delirium don't
have what neurologists call focal neurological findings (e.g.,
weakness on one side of the body, one pupil that's dilated more
than the other), which are more common with conditions such as
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Quick tip: A family photo placed within easy sight may help to
orient and relax the older person.  &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 2000 Rodale Press Inc. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Visit Prevention's Healthy Ideas Web site at www.healthyideas.com. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
