<SLUG> BC-RODALE-KEEPING-FIT-ADV21-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV21 
 BEST &AMP; WORST EXERCISES FOR BAD SHOULDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by RODALE clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text.) 
 (FOR RELEASE MON., MARCH 21, 2000) 
 (EXCERPTED FROM PREVENTION) 
 (Includes electronic art.) 
 By MICHELE STANTEN 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Achy shoulders can make everything more difficult, from grocery
shopping to putting on a coat. Two of the most common causes are
poor posture and weak muscles. Sitting or walking with your head
forward and shoulders rounded can put stress on muscles and tendons
whenever you lift your arms, says Jeffrey Young, MD, a psychiatrist
at the Hospital for Special Surgery in New York City. Practice
pinching your shoulder blades together when you're sitting and
standing.
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to strengthen the often-overlooked muscles
in the back of your shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tend to focus on your chest and biceps because you can see
them, but then the muscles in the back can become weak,'' Young
says.
 &UR; BEST EXERCISES TO DO &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do eight to 10 repetitions of each exercise, two or three days a
week, unless otherwise noted.
</P>
<P>
   Modified bent-over row: Bend at your hips, and place your right
hand on a chair or bench. Keep your back flat. Holding a dumbbell
in your left hand, let your left arm hang straight. Slowly lift the
weight by squeezing your shoulder blades together. Hold, then
slowly lower. Repeat on the right side.
</P>
<P>
   Pushup plus: Do a pushup, either on your knees or toes. At the
top of the move, when your arms are extended, lift yourself up a
bit more by rounding your upper back. Hold, then slowly lower. If
you have trouble doing the pushup, you can do the ``plus'' portion
by itself while lying flat on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Reverse fly: Holding a dumbbell in each hand, lie face-down on
the floor with a pillow under your chest. Start with your arms out
to the sides. Squeeze your shoulder blades and slowly lift your
arms a few inches off the floor. Hold, then slowly lower.
</P>
<P>
   Shoulder stretch: Standing against a wall or lying on your back,
bring your right arm across your chest. With your left hand, grab
your right elbow and slowly pull your right arm until you feel a
gentle stretch in your shoulder. Hold for about 20 seconds. Do it
three or four times, then repeat using the opposite arm.
</P>
<P>
   Shrug: Stand with your feet about shoulder-width apart, holding
dumbbells at your sides. Without moving your arms, lift your
shoulders toward your ears. Hold, then slowly lower.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer stretch: Kneeling in front of a chair, place your elbows
on the seat with your palms together. Slowly sit back toward your
heels, dropping your chest below the seat and allowing your head to
bow forward until you feel a gentle stretch under your shoulder
blades. Hold for about 20 seconds. Do it three or four times.
 &UR; EXERCISE WITH CAUTION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lateral raise is a great shoulder strengthener, but doing it
incorrectly can do more harm than good. Do the exercise with your
arms bent at 90-degree angles to take stress off your shoulders. To
avoid pinching the tendons, never lift your arms above your
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Another exercise that requires extra care with technique is the
bench press. Don't let your elbows drop below the bench when
lowering the weight. If it still bothers your shoulders despite
this precaution, try it with the dumbbells parallel to each other,
and be sure that your elbows are pointing toward your feet.
 &UR; WORST EXERCISES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Avoid at all costs: Overhead press, overhead triceps extension,
upright row, behind-the-neck lat pulldown and dip. &QL; 
