<HEADLINE>
$ADV21 
 HEALTH BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by RODALE clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text.) 
 (FOR RELEASE MON., MARCH 21, 2000) 
 (EXCERPTED FROM PREVENTION) 
 (Includes electronic art.) 
 BEST VITAMIN C SKIN CARE  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the correct amounts and in the right formulation, vitamin C
(ascorbic acid) can stimulate collagen and elastin production,
firming skin and eliminating fine lines and wrinkles. The
antioxidant powerhouse also lightens skin, reducing blemishes and
brown spots and protects against future sun damage. Unfortunately,
vitamin C is often no longer active in skin care products by the
time you get them home _ or may not have been present in an
effective formula to begin with. But new research has found the
formula for stable, effective vitamin C _ and cosmetics companies
are taking note.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent Duke University Medical Center study, researchers at
the Durham, N.C., school found that vitamin C is best absorbed into
the skin when delivered in a 20 percent concentration of L-ascorbic
acid at a low pH. Based on this research, at least one company has
already revised its vitamin C formula. SkinCeuticals' new Primacy
Serum 20. For availability, call (800) 811-1660. While other
companies are bound to do likewise, check products carefully for
L-ascorbic acid concentration and pH levels.
</P>
<P>
   Do not assume that a higher concentration of L-ascorbic acid is
better. The Duke study found that 25 percent and 30 percent
solutions were significantly less effective.
 &UR; SKIP BOTOX BARGAINS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cut-rate anti-wrinkle therapy can mean complications. Bargain
prices for Botox _ the injectable substance used to smooth out
wrinkles by relaxing, or paralyzing, specific facial muscles _ are
heavily advertised these days. But when you see a $99 special on
this treatment (typically costing $400 to $500), odds are that
you're not getting a bargain, explains Ronald Moy, MD, associate
clinical professor at the University of California in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Botox, which is distributed to medical professionals in powder
form, is normally diluted with saline solution, yielding enough to
treat two or three patients. But some doctors have been adding more
saline and stretching the same amount to treat up to 10 patients.
Although the immediate results may look fine, you'll need a new
injection every 3 weeks _ instead of the standard 3 to 6 months _
to maintain the improvement.
</P>
<P>
   This practice may also increase the chance of complications.
</P>
<P>
   ``By putting a large watery volume into a very small muscle,
there could be a greater risk of spreading the solution and
paralyzing nearby muscles that you don't want affected, which could
cause a droopy eyelid or brow,'' Moy says. ``A smaller volume of
Botox at a higher concentration is more precise.''
</P>
<P>
   Avoid being misled. Ask your doctor how much Botox he is
injecting per area. Most doctors charge by the Botox unit. For best
results, use these guidelines: 15 units for the forehead, 10 to 20
units for frown lines, 6 to 10 units for crow's-feet and 1 to 2
units for mouth wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   At full strength, Botox is safe, with only a 1 percent chance of
serious side effects.
 &UR; CLICK HERE TO END WORLD HUNGER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can help fight world hunger every time you're online. At
www.thehungersite.com, one click of the mouse donates a serving of
food to starving nations _ at no cost to you. Corporate sponsors
provide the food in exchange for free advertising. Since its
start-up last June, the site has sent the United Nation's World
Food Program enough money to purchase more than 34 million servings
of dietary staples. Bookmark The Hunger Site, and make your clicks
count.
 &UR; EXERCISE IS AS GOOD AS DRUGS FOR DEPRESSION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People who exercise are less likely to be depressed. Now a new
study shows that walking or jogging for 30 minutes, three times a
week, can actually treat major depression just as well as
medication.
</P>
<P>
   When 156 depressed people, average age 57, were treated with
antidepressants, exercise, or a combination of both, they all had
similar results. After 16 weeks of treatment, 60 percent to 70
percent of each group were no longer clinically depressed. One
difference: The people taking medication got quicker results.
</P>
<P>
   But about one-third of people with depression don't respond to
drugs, says study author James Blumenthal, PhD, a psychologist at
Duke University Medical Center in Durham, N.C. For these people _
and others who want to avoid the side effects of medication or who
want a more natural approach _ exercise is a viable option. As
always, check with your doctor before you stop taking any
medication and before beginning a vigorous exercise program. &QL; 
