<HEADLINE>
$ADV21
</HEADLINE>
  NO WILLPOWER, NO PROBLEM Part II  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by RODALE clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text.) 
 (FOR RELEASE MON., MARCH 13, 2000) 
 (EXCERPTED FROM PREVENTION) 
 (Includes electronic art.) 
 By SARAH ROBERTSON 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week we talked about that elusive force of determination,
willpower, which, believe it or not, is not the answer to your
losing weight!
</P>
<P>
   Gary McClain, a psychologist and co-author of ``The Complete
Idiot's Guide to Breaking Bad Habits'' (Macmillan, 1998), says
``weight loss is not about gritting your teeth and saying 'no.'''
We discussed four of the most common stumbling blocks to weight
loss _ and their easy, proven solutions. Consider the final three
no-willpower tools when you find yourself having a hard time saying
no to your favorite indulgences.
 &UR; LOW-FAT COOKIES ARE MY DOWNFALL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Not Needed: Willpower &QL; 
 &UR; Needed: Flavor &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you can satisfy a craving with a low-fat product _ meaning
that you can control your portions _ that helps you to cut calories
effortlessly. But be careful: If a low-fat product isn't as
satisfying as the regular version, you may eat more to compensate _
as if you'll find what you really wanted at the bottom of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Flavor plays a big part in why some low-fat foods satisfy you
while others don't. In a taste test at the University of Missouri
in Columbia, participants liked the low-fat and regular chocolate
ice creams equally, but they didn't like the low-fat vanilla as
much as the regular vanilla. Many compounds combine to ``carry''
chocolate flavor, so it's easier to mask any alterations that occur
when the fat is reduced, explains Ingolf Gruen, assistant professor
of food chemistry and expert on the study.
</P>
<P>
   Lovers of dark chocolate, especially, will find this a
satisfying switch: ``We found that the low-fat chocolate ice creams
had more of the bitter or semisweet aspects of the chocolate
flavor,'' Gruen says.
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla has one chemical compound responsible for flavor,
whereas chocolate has many, so vanilla doesn't mask fat reduction
as well. Bottom line: You're less likely to be satisfied by a
low-fat version. If vanilla ice cream or another vanilla-flavored
food is your must-have indulgence, for the sake of your
satisfaction _ and, ultimately, your weight _ you may want to treat
yourself to the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is personal preference. Some people prefer the
taste of low-fat foods that make up for a less-than-creamy texture
with an extra burst of flavor, Gruen says. So a normal-size portion
of those foods will satisfy them.
 &UR; COUNTING CALORIES IS NO FUN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Not Needed: Willpower &QL; 
 &UR; Needed: Movement &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Being active boosts your calorie bum so you don't have to obsess
about every bite you take. Exercise can also keep your appetite in
check _ naturally. You can literally walk away from cravings.
</P>
<P>
   To make exercise a natural part of your day, use other
commitments or tasks as a way of getting and staying active.
Setting up a tennis date with your best friend _ instead of a lunch
date _ works as well for keeping the two of you in touch, but now
exercise is part of the habit too.
</P>
<P>
   Busy with kids? Don't just babysit _ play with them. Set out on
your next trail walk in search of beautiful views and fresh air.
Try to combine multiple benefits in one activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaching your daughter's soccer-team allows you to spend time
with your child, serve your community, socialize, have fun _ and
exercise too,'' explains James Prochaska, a psychologist at the
University of Rhode Island in Kingston.
</P>
<P>
   Appreciate how your body moves _ how it feels to whirl your legs
on a bicycle, for example. Rhythmic activities such as walking and
dancing can also ease you into a stress-relieving meditation or the
pleasure of ``flowing'' energy. When you're doing activities that
you love, exercise becomes automatic.
 &UR; ONCE I SLIP, I JUST GIVE UP TOTALLY &QL; 
 &UR; Not Needed: Willpower &QL; 
 &UR; Needed: Rebounding &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you've eaten the Chex mix, the nachos and the brownies at a
party, the tendency is to throw in the towel. But temptations and
setbacks are a normal part of weight loss. It's what you do
afterward that determines how quickly you get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   First, think back to what stimulated you to overeat. Then ask
yourself what that pepperoni pizza represented. If it was comfort
food because you were feeling overwhelmed at work, talk about it
with someone instead. And if you back up another step before the
episode occurred _ before whatever triggered your overindulgence _
you'll discover the situation that caused the trigger itself to
emerge.
</P>
<P>
   For example: You ate the pizza because you were frustrated and
angry. You were frustrated and angry because you had to stay late
at the office and miss your workout. You had to stay late because
your boss overwhelmed you with requests. But you let yourself get
overwhelmed because you didn't want to say no, even though you were
already doing as much work as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might see that you're actually setting yourself up for
those slips,'' McClain says.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've thought it through, you can discuss your
responsibilities and career goals with your boss _ not with the
pizza. Choose a relationship with people over a relationship with
food, and you won't be dialing for takeout after hours. You'll be
heading home, relishing a job well done that day.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to manage slip-ups: Become a matter-of-degree (MAT)
thinker. In a different study led by Smith, those who learned MAT
thinking reported significantly fewer problems with overeating than
did rigid, all-or-nothing thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: If a MAT thinker eats a small plateful of
nachos at a party, she'll quantify it by actually attaching a
number to it, such as 200 calories.
</P>
<P>
   ''And that is exactly all she really had,'' Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   She then accommodates it by cutting back on her drinks for the
evening or walking an extra 20 minutes over each of the next two
days. If you slip up by skipping your regular evening walking
routine for a week employ some of these strategies: Substitute an
apple and string cheese for a less-than-healthy snack or fit in a
few extra lunchtime strolls or early-morning swims. And examine why
you missed your after-work exercise in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe your schedule has changed and now your son needs a ride to
karate lessons in the evenings. In that case, a midday walk or
before-work swim would fit better into your life and keep you
committed to your exercise routine. By using these seven
no-willpower tools, you can build yourself a pleasurable, powerful
life _ and it won't take an ounce of willpower to get there. &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Rodale Press Inc. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Visit Prevention's Healthy Ideas Web site at www.healthyideas.com. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC; 
