<HEADER>
A5789 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-13 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FLYING ELEPHANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A broker friend of mine who specializes in trading Internet
stocks called me the other day and left a two-word message on my
answering machine: ``Panic buying.''
</P>
<P>
   He was trying to describe the frenzy that was going on around
him on the trading floor, and the only two words he could come up
with were ``panic buying'' _ moms and pops calling and asking to
buy any Internet stock. Now my friend is a believer in the Internet
space _ ``I've taken the Kool-Aid,'' he regularly warns me. And he
knows that the stocks he's trading are volatile: ``I sell rocket
fuel,'' he avers. ``You want regular stocks, I'm not your guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But even my friend finds the current Internet stock frenzy
troubling, because never have more people been investing in more
stocks of companies about which they don't have a clue _ not a
clue. People who two months ago thought B-2-B stood for ``Bed and
Breakfast'' now can't get enough of B-2-B (business-to-business)
Internet stocks. Clearly the Internet is for real. Clearly it will
produce some new companies of great value. But clearly many others
won't make it. Which means there is something inherently dangerous
about so many people taking their money out of traditional stocks
they know and panic-buying stocks they don't have a clue about.
</P>
<P>
   The best description I've seen of today's rocket-fuel Nasdaq
comes from Rick Barry, whose respected Black Bear Fund has
regularly made money both buying and holding tech stocks and
shorting them. These days, short-selling tech stocks is one of the
most dangerous things you can do, but it tells you a lot about the
zaniness of the market.
</P>
<P>
   You make money short-selling by carefully studying companies,
finding out which ones are flawed, phony or overpriced, and then
shorting their stocks, which means betting that they will go down,
not up. But what happens when you are in a market when everything
seems to go up _ even the junk?
</P>
<P>
   ``My business depends on people calling garbage garbage and good
things good,'' said Barry. ``But we now have a market in which
people are calling garbage good. No consideration is being given to
value. Instead of trading pieces of businesses, we are now trading
pieces of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   In a wickedly funny letter to his shareholders, Barry explained
the bizarre world he is now investing in, where elephants seem to
fly. Certain tech stocks his firm has shorted _ because they have
no fundamentals or earnings prospects and are simply hyped by
analysts and bankers _ go up in price as they rack up losses,
thanks to panic buying. Meanwhile, the non-tech value stocks he
bought, in order to hold, go down in price the more they rack up
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's review,'' said Barry. ``Our shorts go up when there is
bad news, and our non-technology longs go down when there is good
news. Are you still with us?''
</P>
<P>
   Barry compared this upside-down world to Groucho Marx's old TV
quiz show ``You Bet Your Life.'' Before the show started
contestants were kept in a booth offstage, while a ``secret word''
was revealed to the audience. When the contestants then came on
stage, if one of them uttered the secret word a duck would come
down from the ceiling and the contestant was awarded $100.
</P>
<P>
   Barry said when he watches shows like CNBC's ``Squawk Box,'' he
is struck by the parallel. Tech execs are interviewed about their
companies. When one of them utters the secret words _ ``genomics''
or ``business-to-business e-commerce'' or ``Linux-based software''
_ their stock prices soar within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such positive reinforcement causes contestants [on CBNC) to
say the secret words early and often,'' said Barry. ``And sure
enough, the duck comes down and $100,000 bills are passed out to
both the executive and the audience in the form of rising stock
prices. Part of the fun is to watch the short-seller's reaction as
he realizes that it is his money that contestants and viewers are
winning. Occasionally, short-sellers are allowed on the air to
offer their view, but they are often treated the same as carnival
clowns at a dunk tank.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone is going to get hurt here. In the long run, notes Barry,
those who make money in markets are those who pay attention to the
price paid for each idea _ buying ideas that are undervalued and
selling ideas that are overvalued. Panic buyers beware: Elephants
don't fly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
