<HEADER>
A5790 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-SEAN-ELLIOTT14-CO     03-13 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SEAN-ELLIOTT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emotional welcome awaits Elliott
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Sean Elliott asked a friend the other day if his
comeback tonight will be a circus. The answer is yes.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's parents, Robert and Odiemae, his brothers, Bobby and
Noel, other relatives, friends, his doctors and fans will be in the
Alamodome tonight when the Spurs forward makes a historic comeback
eight months after having a failing kidney replaced with one
donated by Noel.
</P>
<P>
   That the Atlanta Hawks also will be in attendance is merely
prerequisite for the event: It requires a lamb.
</P>
<P>
   With upwards of 25,000 cheering, Elliott will enter tonight's
game mid-to-late first quarter or the start of the second quarter.
Throat lumps will swell and tears will run like the rain-swollen
San Antonio River. Elliott is a well-liked athlete, and videotape
of him smiling wanly from a wheelchair is as fresh inthe memory as
his winning 3-pointer in a Western Conference finals playoff game
with Portland in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks' Jim Jackson was a Portland player then. ``Playing
against him in that series,'' Jackson said, ``you never knew there
was anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Spurs miss him. If the season ended today they
would be no better than the No. 4 seed in the West as they set out
to defend their NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   ``An incredible up and a down,'' David Robinson said about the
dizzying spin last summer from championship celebration to harsh
medical reality. ``After we won, we were at the top of the world.
The next week, I'm in the hospital, standing by his bed, praying
with him. That's a tough situation. It puts things back in
perspective. Your life is pretty important compared to some of the
other things. There's no question (we miss him).''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, 32, feels no pain from the surgery. The only reminder
is that he must take medication twice daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm under 10 pills a day,'' he said, smiling. ``At first, it
was 30 a day.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked recently why he would test medical boundaries by
returning for an 11th season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheryl Miller (of Turner Sports) asked me that,'' Elliott
said. ``And I said, `What would your brother (Indiana's Reggie
Miller) do?' She didn't say another word. She just looked at me and
goes, `OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott had kidney problems as a younger adult. They worsened
last winter when much of his renal function was lost. Without a
transplant, doctors said, he would need constant dialysis
treatment. Noel Elliott agreed to be his donor, and they went to
surgery in August. Elliott battled pneumonia, and his strength was
slow to return. But he finally was able to start practicing in
January.
</P>
<P>
   The reason he can play is that the new kidney was inserted
behind his pelvic bone so that it has a much stronger natural
shield than his abdomen would afford. He has signed a waiver of
responsibility for the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm the world's most famous organ donor now,'' Noel
Elliott, a stock clerk, said, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for Noel,'' Sean Elliott said, ``I wouldn't be
doing this. I might still be on dialysis, waiting for a donor.''
</P>
<P>
   As for all the fuss, don't worry about Elliott. He knows what
he's doing. ``My heart rate is going to get up, and my kidney is
going to regulate the composition of my blood and the waste in my
blood. When you run, it probably puts stress on a lot of your major
organs. But at the same time, exercise is good for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for perspective, Elliott said, ``It's not a heart
transplant.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
