<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBUNE CO. TO MERGE WITH TIMES MIRROR IN $6.45 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: 2nd Take to follow; for a list of sidebars, see
TRIBUNE-ADVISORY-NYT.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of the nation's four largest newspaper companies, the
Tribune Co. and Times Mirror Co., which both built around
newspapers that helped define the brawling, partisan days of 19th
century journalism, Monday announced plans to combine, giving the
merged company a broader base from which to compete in the
fast-changing media world of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Their idea is to create a network of regional media hubs where
advertisers are matched with audiences through newspapers,
television broadcasts and Internet sites. The new company would
seek to replicate in cities like New York and Los Angeles the
Tribune's success in offering many kinds of media to the Chicago
market.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which will retain the Tribune Co. name, will own 11
daily newspapers, 22 television stations and four radio stations.
The company's newspapers would have a combined circulation of 3.6
million copies, ranking third among newspaper companies after
Gannett and Knight Ridder. Tribune's television stations reach 38.4
million households.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger of the two companies, whose stocks had been
trading near their 52-week low, was greeted with deep skepticism by
investors; Tribune Co.'s stock, which had closed Friday at $37.875,
fell swiftly to $27.75 as trading opened, and closed at $30.75,
down 26.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Monday ends 119 years of ownership of the Los
Angeles Times by the Otis and Chandler families. In effect, the
Tribune's corporate heirs of Robert McCormick and James Patterson,
whose pugnacious conservatism often enraged their barrel-chested
union town of Chicago, are buying out and the corporate heirs of
Gen. Harrison Gray Otis and Harry Chandler, who used The Los
Angeles Times as a political hammer, helping fashion the southern
California desert into the nation's second-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune's offer of $6.45 billion in the stock and cash deal _
not including the assumption of $1.8 billion of Times Mirror debt _
also puts an abrupt end to the mercurial five-year stewardship of
the Times Mirror chairman, Mark H. Willes. A former cereal company
executive, he brought an almost religious fervor to his quest to
streamline the company, challenging the newspaper industry to
reinvent itself, increase its audience, and toss out its
shibboleths _ notably the historic separation of the news and
business divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The essential details of the deal were arranged by members of
the Chandler family, without Willes' knowledge, according to both
Willes and Thomas Unterman, the former chief financial officer of
Times Mirror who was a primary adviser to the Chandler family
trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Friday's closing stock prices, the offer for Times
Mirror consists of $3.79 billion in common stock and $2.66 billion
in cash. The cash represents a tender for about 28 million shares
at $95 per share, The remaining 40.8 million shares would be
exchanged, with Tribune offering 2.5 shares for each share of Times
Mirror.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2008EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5794 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BKN-ELLIOT14-COX     03-13 1630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ELLIOT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ There was the kidney transplant recipient
who was kicked by a horse. Another who was gored by handlebars in a
motorcycle wreck. Several high school basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   They took their shots. Their kidneys survived.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Sean Elliott will add one more person to the list: himself.
Sometime after 7:30 p.m. today, when San Antonio faces Atlanta in
the Alamodome, the Spurs forward will become the first athlete in
professional sports to return from a kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll look back at this 20 years from now and it will be no
big deal,'' Elliott, 32, said after his workout Monday. ``Somebody
has to go first.''
</P>
<P>
   His cautious coach, Gregg Popovich, tried to erect ``every
roadblock I can think of.'' Teammates wished him a great life _
away from basketball. But Elliott, who underwent the transplant
last Aug. 16, listened to his own voice and to his doctors. After
all, if a transplant recipient can fall on the handlebars of a
motorcycle without suffering damage to his new kidney, well,
Elliott figures an NBA forward should do just fine. Danger? What
danger?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of faith in my doctors,'' Elliott said. ``They've
done hundreds of these. I don't think about it at all, not even one
second.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who returned to practice on Feb. 2, has since convinced
even the most skeptical and concerned Spurs that he is ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worked very hard and has earned and deserves this
opportunity,'' said Popovich, who will restrict Elliott to 10 to 12
minutes a game at the beginning. ``He's ready to go. Sean's doing
something that's pretty heroic and pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Said teammate and longtime friend Steve Kerr, ``We're so used to
having him around that we take it for granted. We don't even think
about it anymore. That's the way he wants it. From day one his
resolve was so strong. He was driven every day. He didn't miss a
day coming here to work out. In my mind, he's already won. But he's
not satisfied yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from that, Elliott wants to again be a highly competitive
player, an inspiration such as Lance Armstrong, winner of the 1999
Tour de France after beating testicular cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``By going out and playing, I can wipe away a lot of
misconceptions people have,'' Elliott said. ``I'm not coming back
just for me, but for people who had transplants like this, to give
them hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'll be the guru, the Dalai Lama of kidney
transplants.''
</P>
<P>
   As Elliott was finishing his workout on Monday, he received a
big hug from former Spurs owner Red McCombs, who was visiting
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a story of the medical greatness we have in this country,
which not only allows a guy to live but allows a guy to participate
in one of the most grueling games there is,'' McCombs said. ``When
you put it all together, it ends up being a story of heart, rather
than a story of kidney, because Sean has got the heart of a lion.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the kidney, the risk is small, said Dr. Francis Wright,
who performed the surgery at Methodist Specialty and Transplant
Hospital in San Antonio with a kidney from Elliott's brother, Noel,
33. Wright said approximately 1,500 kidney transplants have been
performed at his hospital in the last 15 years and none of the
former patients have since suffered serious trauma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving into uncharted waters in terms of professional
basketball, but it's not that difficult a decision,'' Wright said.
``It's not something I lose sleep over. Probably if he were a
football player, I might be less encouraging for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said the kidney is well protected, tucked behind Sean's
pelvic bone on the right side, providing more protection than would
the abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions are about stamina, whether he has lost a step,
things like that,'' Wright said. ``He played under more stressful
conditions last year.''
</P>
<P>
   1993: the diagnosis
</P>
<P>
   Elliott first learned in 1993 that he had focal segmental
glomerular sclerosis, a disease that prevents the kidneys from
properly filtering waste from the blood. His condition deteriorated
last March.
</P>
<P>
   Despite health problems, Elliott remained the Spurs' best
defender on the perimeter, a physically taxing role. One day he
walked _ tightroped, really _ into the national spotlight,
converting an off-balance three-point basket from barely inside the
right sideline to beat Portland in game two of the Western
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, the Spurs had their first NBA championship,
but Elliott's joy was soon tempered when he was told a transplant
was necessary. His mother, Odiemae, was a suitable match. Noel was
a better one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very glad for that,'' said Noel, a stock clerk for an
aerospace company in Tucson, Ariz., the family's hometown. ``She's
62. She doesn't need that kind of trauma.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sean told his brother it was time for a transplant, Noel
responded ``Where do I go? When do I have to be there?''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Noel wasn't a little scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course there is apprehension when you have surgery,'' Noel
said. ``There's always the worst-case scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But he never hesitated,'' said Noel's wife, Kathy. ``They have
such a great family.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean expects his parents, divorced years ago, to attend the game
tonight. So will Noel, Kathy and Sean's other brother. Sean and
Noel have always been close.
</P>
<P>
   ``They grew up like twins,'' Odiemae said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a lot closer now,'' Sean said. ``I have one of his
organs in me.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the first time Noel, older by 15 months, rescued his
little brother. When they took Odiemae's car for a joy ride and
14-year-old Sean scraped the side against the carport, Noel allowed
his mother to believe he was the driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't fool me,'' Odiemae recalls. ``I just picked my
battles.''
</P>
<P>
   She certainly could have found one when Sean announced his
intention to play basketball again. Instead she prays for his
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's a little fearful for me,'' Odiemae said. ``But he
went in for the surgery with the idea he was going to play again.
I'm not cavalier about it, but you can get run over crossing the
street. (The kidney) is safe unless someone tries to hurt him. I
don't think he'll be on the ground letting someone step on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Odiemae, a retired critical care nurse who worked in a hospital
at which transplants are performed, said she is aware of what could
have gone wrong well before Sean attempted his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Last year an estimated 12,000 people nationwide received kidney
transplants, but Odiemae said, ``There's never a surgery that's
routine.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Odiemae looked so relieved when after her sons came
out of surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the outside, she was just fine before the surgery,'' Kathy
Elliott said. ``Later she let us know she had been a nervous
wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the surgery was complete _ six hours for Noel and 3 1/2 for
Sean _ there were moments of levity. Serious occasions can produce
good comedy, or at least gallows humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The morning after surgery, Sean walked out of intensive care
holding his catheter bag,'' Noel said. ``With this voice real gruff
from anesthesia he says, `I brought margaritas.'''
</P>
<P>
   `Mother hen'
</P>
<P>
   Sean Elliott's comeback has been difficult, sometimes
unbearable. A few times he slipped on to the court while the Spurs
practiced and Popovich was looking in another direction, only to be
ordered off or dragged away by an assistant coach or someone from
the training staff. The team was willing to pay Sean his entire
$6.2 million salary to not play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I seem like a mother hen, but if you had a son in this
position, you would want me to be protective,'' Popovich has said.
``I care about Sean. Am I ridiculously cautious? Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Popovich says, ``We know he's getting in better shape all
the time. The only thing we don't know is how long he can play.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how far Elliott has progressed. In late November, he was
running the Alamodome stairs, and he had forgotten his doctor's
advice to keep himself hydrated. Near the top, Elliott doubled over
with pain in his abdomen. He began to vomit. He ended up back in
the hospital hooked up to an IV for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, right before Christmas, Elliott returned to
the hospital with a bad case of the flu, his immune system weakened
by anti-transplant rejection drugs. He considered postponing his
comeback. But by early January, Elliott felt better, and on Jan.
20, Wright cleared him for practice. On Feb. 2, Elliott was on the
court in full-scale practice for the first time since last June.
Before returning, he signed several waivers releasing the Spurs
from liability.
</P>
<P>
   Though teammates such as Kerr and Avery Johnson had said they
would be happy if Elliott lived a healthy life without basketball,
the players welcomed him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at Sean in awe,'' David Robinson said. ``It's not
like he's doing it for the money. He's hanging in there, coming
back from life-threatening surgery, and he just wants to be on the
floor. Every time I see that kind of passion, it gives me energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven months earlier, Noel said that all he really wanted in
return for his kidney was a book contract and tickets for the
resumption of his brother's career. The book has yet to
materialize. As for the ticket request, Kathy Elliott recalls
people politely indulging her husband's confidence that Sean would
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone said, `We'll see,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And now Sean Elliott intends to show them.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner writes about pro basketball. You may reach him at
445-3958 or mrosner(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
