<HEADER>
A5795 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BIGDIG-DEADLINE-BOS &LR;      03-13 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-DEADLINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH US DEADLINE NEAR, `BIG DIG' FINANCING PLAN LACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Facing a federal deadline Wednesday, Massachusetts
officials have yet to agree on a financing plan to pay for a $1.4
billion cost overrun for the Central Artery project.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci, who met with U.S. Transportation
Secretary Rodney Slater last week, said he will present federal
officials with a bill he proposed a month ago, which calls for
covering the shortfall mostly through state borrowing.
</P>
<P>
   However, lawmakers have all but dismissed that bill, and federal
sources say the dispute over how to finance the project could
further erode the state's credibility in Washington at a crucial
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to have a plan that's do-able,'' said US Rep. J.
Joseph Moakley, who met with Cellucci, Slater, and US Sen. Edward
M. Kennedy over the issue in Washington last week. ``He can't say
this is the way I'd like to do it. It won't sell.''
</P>
<P>
   On Beacon Hill, lawmakers are still conducting hearings on the
Big Dig's funding crisis and have no plans to hammer out an
agreement with Cellucci by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the House and Senate leaders have already torn
apart the governor's plan, ``which is based on certain assumptions
that are imploding,'' one legislative source said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Those assumptions include: That the overrun will not exceed $1.4
billion and that part of a project insurance plan can be cashed to
generate $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   State officials had pledged to have a funding plan in place by
Wednesday to help restore confidence among federal officials that
Massachusetts can continue to support the highway project as it
nears its final phase, and prevent the disruption of federal
funding.
</P>
<P>
   But there appears to be a strong dispute about what is required
of the state.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Moakley, a federal transportation source told the
Globe that Cellucci was instructed during a meeting with Slater
last week to produce a plan that has won the support of legislative
leaders, not simply a proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secretary Slater told Governor Cellucci that the date for a
new finacial plan was non-negotiable,'' the source said. ``We're
expecting a plan. One that's feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, in a statement released Monday, Federal Highway
Administrator Kenneth Wykle indicated that Washington authorities
are expecting ``a revised finance plan that is due to FHWA on March
15.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci has a different view and said Slater will be
satisfied with a completed plan by the end of March. That's when a
team of federal auditors is expected to release its own report on
the Big Dig's financial condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the one who met with him,'' the governor said of Slater.
``He told me he recognizes that the Legislature will act. He says
it's not something we should take a lot of time at. But he does not
expect the Legislature to act before they complete their hearings
and before they've had the benefit of the federal audit. Why would
we do the audit and not wait for its results?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Slater knows that the House and Senate oppose his plan,
Cellucci said, ``I told him the Legislature might have a different
idea. I said I felt we would be able to close the gap. I have no
pride of authorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is correct, it is clear leaders on Beacon Hill are far
from consensus. In response to Cellucci's plan, the House and
Senate have each floated financing proposals, starkly different
from the governor's.
</P>
<P>
   The House's plan would generate $750 million -- or half the
overrun -- to keep construction underway through 2001. The House
calls for the Turnpike to contribute $200 million and for the sale
of $600 million in state bonds, which would be repaid by revenues
from driver's license fees. Those fees were scheduled to be phased
out, and $200 million in cash reserves from the Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan calls for devoting this year's state budget
surplus, which could top $700 million, to the project. The proposal
also calls for the Turnpike, which oversees the Big Dig, to
contribute between $200 million and $350 million in cash while the
Massachusetts Port Authority would kick in more than $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   There are other signals that compromise may not come easily or
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how to pay for the Central Artery shortfall has
become entangled in the dispute over Cellucci's income tax cut
ballot initiative, which would cost over $1 billion and Senate
President Thomas F. Birmingham sharply opposes.
</P>
<P>
   And federal and state officials met with the Metropolitan Area
Planning Council, which oversees road and bridge projects in
eastern Massachusetts, and assured the agency it could also
scrutinize the governor's financing plan to make sure it did not
imperil municipal transportation projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
