<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5798 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TYNAN-SONG-ART-2TAKES     03-13 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TYNAN-SONG-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BALLAD OF RONAN TYNAN, A TENOR'S TRIUMPH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT6, is being sent to New York Times photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He walks onstage with the slight sway of a metronome
and gives a mischievous grin made all the more impish by his
fullback's frame. When he finally stops before the microphone,
there comes a vague sense that a very public mistake is about to
occur, that your man has somehow passed through the wrong door.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ronan Tynan sings.
</P>
<P>
   Through his clear tenor voice, tired Irish ballads ache with the
passion of their ancient birth: dirty Dublin streets echo with
Molly Malone's haunting cry; Danny Boy's snow-hushed valley becomes
as sacred as a church. All the while Tynan's large hands beckon the
audience to draw near and listen to his gift.
</P>
<P>
   These days that gift is for the taking. Tynan is one of the
three Irish tenors, along with Anthony Kearns and Finbar Wright,
now making the St. Patrick's Day rounds in American concert halls
and on public television. The trio has become an unlikely musical
phenomenon, resurrecting Irish parlor songs and adding luster to
ballads more often heard in smoke-choked pubs.
</P>
<P>
   But the most unlikely element is Tynan himself, for reasons he
grudgingly acknowledges carry the glow of inspiration. He was born
with a congenital condition that required him to wear bulky leg
braces into early adulthood. At 20 he chose to have both legs
amputated below the knees in favor of prostheses. He became a
dominant athlete in international competitions for the disabled, an
accomplished horseman and a doctor specializing in sports medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 30 the determined Tynan decided to have a go at singing,
the way others breezily take on golf or stamp collecting. Before
long he had won several competitions, including Ireland's
prestigious John McCormack Cup for tenors. Now, nine years later,
the horses are in the paddock, the practice is on hold, and Tynan
is singing for a living with a child's glee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very happy man, extremely so,'' he says. ``I get up in
the morning, and once I can get into these legs, man, I'm in
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Ronan Tynan is now part of modern Irish lore. He
grew up on a dairy farm in County Kilkenny, in southeastern
Ireland, where his father's scratchy 78s filled the house with the
disembodied voices of Nelson Eddy, Jussi Bjorling and especially
Mario Lanza. There was McCormack, yes, but those recordings were
comparatively poor. So a farm boy grounded by heavy blocks for
shoes soared to the sounds of ``The Student Prince'' and ``Rose
Marie.''
</P>
<P>
   That boy's determination hardened as his condition worsened. By
age 14 he was traveling by himself to have his legs checked
periodically at a London hospital. He moved from cantering on
ponies to full-fledged steeplechases. When sudden pain roared
through his legs and up his back, he would grit his teeth and wait
for the paralysis to pass.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 19 and a student at University College in Dublin,
Tynan made another trip to London. This time two consultants
decidedly lacking in warmth informed him he had but one solution:
bilateral amputation. Tynan's mother, Therese, did not want to
entertain the thought; his beloved father, Edmond, said the
decision was Ronan's own but softly advised, ``If you have them
amputated, you can't ever have them put back.''
</P>
<P>
   His father ``couldn't see the outcome,'' Tynan said gently. But
the farmer's son could; he felt he had no choice. The devices he
was wearing at the time _ leather boots with thick steel bars and
rivets that cut into the bottoms of his feet _ kept breaking. He
saw artificial limbs as the tools to a certain freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after the procedure, Tynan was pre-fitted with
prostheses. He instantly began to wonder whether women would still
find him attractive. So, against medical advice and common sense,
he shoved some foam into his pants legs, affixed artificial limbs
to still-raw sutures, and went dancing that night.
</P>
<P>
   The sutures ruptured overnight, a considerable amount of blood
was lost, and Tynan spent the next eight months in a wheelchair.
``I paid for that big time,'' he said. But the incident seems to
reflect an inner strength that often tests the borders of
recklessness; soon he was applying ethyl alcohol spirits to his
stumps, a trick he said he learned from toughening up the hides of
horses.
</P>
<P>
   Edmond Tynan, dead now two years, remains central to his son's
stories. ``And I remember coming back to him,'' Tynan recalled, the
reference to ``him'' a given. ``And when he saw me without the
sticks, and when he saw me progressing from the wheelchair to the
limbs, he said to me, `You know, you were right.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: `Yeah, I think I was. But who was to know?'''
</P>
<P>
   By now Tynan had developed a mind-set: ``No reverse. Forward.''
Sometimes he colorfully describes how he wanted to show up those
who had doubted, pitied or vexed him. That attitude steeled him to
the obvious discomfort his presence caused some classmates and
spurred him on to exceed _ not merely meet _ the minimum
requirements for his physical education classes. The international
athletic awards he subsequently earned are many; suffice to say
that he became one of the best collegiate shot put throwers in all
of Ireland, able-bodied or not.
</P>
<P>
   One day while he was singing ``Ave Maria'' with Pavarotti on his
car's radio, Tynan's voice abruptly changed. The sweet sounds of a
boy now carried a man's resonance. He was 22, he said, ``and after
that I wouldn't shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to pubs, especially a place called Dirty Nelly's in
Limerick, and sang for pints of beer for himself and his friends.
He sang happy songs, sad songs, songs about oppression and songs
just heard on the BBC. He sang ``Rose Marie,'' and he sang rugby
rhymes. He took familiar songs and laced them with naughty words of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice had the ability to draw attention,'' he said. ``And
I hadn't a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   The competitive drive forged by his childhood condition had not
subsided. Tynan studied under Veronica Dunne, a well-known Irish
vocal coach, then entered a national singing festival in Dublin.
With friends from medical school cheering him on as though they
were at a football match, he recalled, he won the prize for tenor.
He and his mates drank that night from the John McCormack cup.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the next few years experiencing triumph and humility in
the reserved world of classical music. He showed up for an
international singing competition in France without formal attire,
borrowed a suit from a doorman and won the overall male award. He
sang in a performance of Bizet's ``Jolie Fille de Perth,'' but his
French mispronunciations turned the mundane into the salacious. In
Ireland he appeared in Puccini's ``Madama Butterfly,'' a
performance he freely admits was awful.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Tynan continued to study and to seek his proper
voice. After a disastrous flirtation with becoming a ``big voice''
tenor _ an Irish Pavarotti _ he finally found his niche as a lyric
tenor, straddling that world between light opera and popular
standards. He said he had not forgotten the imploring words of his
father: Sing what people want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a smart direction for him to go in,'' advised
Brian Kellow, the executive editor of Opera News. Kellow said that
while Tynan did not seem to be the next McCormack, ``he does have a
very sweet voice, and people like it.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing Tynan's solo engagement at a Manhattan nightclub in
December, Stephen Holden of The New York Times praised the Tynan
package of voice and earnestness: ``The performances convey a
purity untainted by sanctimony.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways Tynan seems beyond fretting about critical reviews
or his place in music. About the only critique he does not want to
hear is that he sings like an angel.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to put me on this pedestal,'' he said. ``They feel
that `oh, he's this, or he's that.' But I'm absolutely no different
than you. I have the same bad thoughts that everybody else has.''
</P>
<P>
   Then as if to underscore the point he responded irreverently to
a question about his height. ``I'm 6-foot-4,'' he said. ``But
that's adjustable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If his musical career were to end today, he said, he would be
more than satisfied with his medical practice, his horses, his
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very content with Ronan Tynan,'' he said. ``He's an OK
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   A glimpse of how he feels can be seen on the videotape,
frequently broadcast on public television, of the Irish tenors'
performance last month in Belfast. As his colleague Kearns sings a
ditty called ``Phil the Fluther's Ball,'' Ronan Tynan performs a
sure-footed dance of joy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CDNOW-NYT &LR;      03-13 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDNOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CD NOW AND COLUMBIA HOUSE DROP MERGER PLANS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The online retailer CDNow and the direct-mail music giant
Columbia House announced Monday that their planned merger had
collapsed for financial reasons, leaving both companies scrambling
to find new strategic partners in the rapidly evolving market for
recorded music.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Olim, president and chief executive of CDNow, said the
companies last week determined the merger no longer made financial
sense. He said Columbia House had too little cash flow and too much
debt to finance the growth of a loss-laden Internet startup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their financial position had weakened sufficiently that it was
insufficient for us to achieve our objective,'' Olim said.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, however, it is online sales of CD's by CDNow,
Amazon.com and other online retailers that are in part responsible
for Columbia House's weakened financial position.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Flanders, chief executive of Columbia House, which is
owned 50-50 by Sony Corp. and Time Warner, said he did not dispute
Olim's analysis. But he said the larger problem for Columbia House
was that regulatory hurdles were slowing down the merger and
Columbia could not afford to wait to put its catalog of music
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to move our business online,'' Flanders said. ``We
have strategic partnerships that were being delayed because of the
merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbia House said it now plans to invest $51 million in CDNow,
which would represent about 15 percent of equity, the parties said.
At the same time, Olim said CDNow had committed itself to a ``new
operating plan'' _ aimed at drastically reducing its costs _ to try
to attract a new partner.
</P>
<P>
   Announced last July, the merger envisioned creating a new public
company to capitalize on the Internet savvy of CDNow and on
Columbia House's broad reach in selling low-cost music by direct
mail. CDNow would have owned 26 percent of the joint venture, with
Sony and Time Warner splitting the other 74 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, the deal came at a tumultuous time for both companies,
amidst the light-speed change in the Internet industry. A prime
example is Time Warner's deal to merge with America Online, which
will give Time Warner a huge new online outlet for its labels.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Columbia House, with annual revenue around $1.4
billion, has long been a significant source of cash flow for Sony
and Time Warner. Its However, the company and the direct-mail music
business in general ``has come under significant pressure'' in the
last year, said Ken Cassar, an analyst with Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Cassar said the business had relied heavily on people ordering
compact discs to replace their old albums and cassette tapes, but
that such sales were becoming less lucrative because many people
had already replaced their collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a positive business, but not as positive as it once
was,'' he said. ``My guess is Sony and Time Warner don't want
`Internet return, Internet risk.' They want Columbia House's good
old cash.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, Columbia House announced a reorganization aimed at
moving the business online and decreasing the expense of sending
voluminous catalogs every several weeks to its 16 million members,
Flanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, CDNow is looking for a way to turn a profit in the
commodity music business. The company is one of the top music
retailers on the Net, with $53 million in sales in the fourth
quarter, which ended Dec. 31. But in the same period it had $34.5
million in operating losses.
</P>
<P>
   As is typical in the Internet industry, where companies spend
large sums on marketing to build a brand, CDNow spent $26 million
in the fourth quarter on marketing, roughly 50 cents of every
dollar in sales.
</P>
<P>
   But Olim said Monday that the company planned to reduce
marketing costs to $15 million a quarter. In particular, he said,
the company will offer fewer discount coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said CDNow would try increasing its efforts to gain
customers through its affiliate program. That entails getting
referrals to CDNow from several hundred thousand sites on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   But Olim said the company, and its investors, should expect to
see a reduction in revenues in the short term. He said it was still
too early to estimate how much the drop would be.
</P>
<P>
   He said he felt CDNow's brand name was now recognized enough to
be able to shift costs away from marketing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
