<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5802 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-EUROPE-GENES-FOOD-2TA     03-13 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-GENES-FOOD-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN PROTESTS AGAINST GENETICALLY MODIFIED CROPS ARE BECOMING
MORE ANIMATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Britain, Switzerland)  (js) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ At the big conference on genetically
modified food here in January, the discussion among 300
participants in the hall was serious science _ intelligent, earnest
and a bit dull.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, things were livelier. Two protesters dressed as
headless chickens strutted. A gorilla wailed over his pox-speckled
bananas, and a mutant apple in a radiation suit passed out
leaflets. The demonstrators played a tape of bubbling cauldrons and
vile belches, and the perfect fillip was the stench that hung in
the air _ which was not even their idea, just dumb luck that a
sewer crew was working nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the television cameras lingered on the protesters,
who numbered fewer than 20.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the debate over genetically modified food is as much
about passion as it is about science. British newspapers routinely
call ingredients from genetically altered plants Frankenfood, and
pollsters say just 1 percent of Britons think that genetically
modifying plants have any value at all. Environmental advocates in
Europe have destroyed fields of test plants.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in the United States such ingredients have entered
into nearly two-thirds of the products on supermarket shelves, a
trend that has come to the attention of few Americans.
</P>
<P>
   For Europeans, ``It's not at the level of a rational discussion
any more,'' said Francois Perroud, a spokesman for Nestle, the
world's biggest food company, which is based in Switzerland. Nestle
has stopped buying any grain from genetically altered seed for its
European operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become a battle of doctrines, of religious beliefs, of
inanities,'' Perroud said. ``But unfortunately more and more
retailers have jumped on the bandwagon and banished these products
from their shelves.''
</P>
<P>
   Legally, the European Union requires labels on any food with 1
percent or more of genetically modified ingredients. Planting,
importing or selling any genetically altered seeds or foods has
virtually stopped, because farmers will not plant the seeds,
consumers will not buy the foods and stores decline to stock them.
Regulators have approved no new seed strains for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   Total U.S. corn and soybean exports slipped briefly, but U.S.
farmers are undeterred. Early indications this year from seed
companies are that they are not significantly cutting back on the
seeds, because big food processors have agreed to buy modified
grains and keep them separate from traditional ones.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the fury is a technology that borrows a genetic
code from plants or animals and transfers it to a plant. Modified
seeds, for instance, can produce their own pesticides, reducing the
amount used in the fields. The seeds are now used throughout North
and South America, China and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents concede that no one has ever been harmed by
genetically modified food. But there are questions about
environmental threats. Will genes from herbicide-resistant corn get
into weeds, creating ``superweeds''? Will benign insects like
Monarch butterflies be killed by pollen drifting from bug-killing
corn?
</P>
<P>
   Many Europeans fear the food itself, and some supermarket chains
won't sell it. Those who object to the science argue that enough
research has not been done on the food's long-term safety.
</P>
<P>
   Many factors are at work: a mysterious science that takes place
at the submicroscopic level; jingoism about food; scare campaigns
by environmentalists; arrogant U.S. responses; and one bit of bad
timing when freighters loaded with the 1996 U.S. soybean crop
sailed just as British mad cow disease, which has nothing to do
with genetically modified food, was terrifying Europe.
</P>
<P>
   There is also an anti-U.S. element. Demonstrators' signs often
portray America and its agro-chemical companies as one and the
same, but Guy le Fur, an expert on biotech food at the
Confederation Paysanne, a radical farmers organization that has
destroyed silos full of modified grain, drew a distinction.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that there were European giants in gene-technology,
too, although most of their work is in pharmaceuticals. He added,
``I don't see it as a national issue _ it is colonization by three
or four companies who want total control of what goes onto the
plates of people across the planet and who want to make a lot of
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Lellouche, a Gaullist member of the French Parliament's
committee on environmental safety, said there was deep mistrust
specifically of U.S. assurances that the food was safe. ``The
general sense here is that Americans eat garbage food, that they're
fat and they don't know how to eat properly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   U.S. endorsements, he added, were ``like the British beef thing
_ the British government is still screaming that their beef is
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not European fears will spread to America is unclear.
Biotech seed accounts for 36 percent of America's corn, 55 percent
of its soybeans and 43 percent of its cotton, and some Americans
wonder how dozens of supermarket items, from infant formula to cola
to muffin mix could contain biotech products without their knowing
it.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. seed producers like Monsanto and DuPont's Pioneer Hi-Bred
International are under pressure not just by environmental
activists but by food makers like H.J. Heinz, Gerber and Frito-Lay
that have stopped using biotech ingredients, and by corn farmers
who switched to the seeds and then saw consumer fears shake
European markets.
</P>
<P>
   Grocery Manufacturers of America, the trade group representing
big food-making companies, thinks much of the concern is overblown.
``It's barely a blip on the radar screen,'' said Brian Sansoni, the
group's spokesman. ``It's just not an issue that's front and center
with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The protests in Europe also stem from lingering cultural
differences in the ways Americans and Europeans look at food.
</P>
<P>
   Since World War II, despite raised eyebrows from the academic
elite, Europeans have eagerly lapped up most U.S. culture, from
blue jeans and computers to movies and music. But, though the older
generation remembers the chewing gum handed out by American G.I.s,
other U.S. culinary innovations, from frosted cereals to
marshmallows, meet with less enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Every traveler knows the strawberries and asparagus in America
look beautiful but have no flavor,'' said Professor Marc van
Montagu, a professor of genetic science at the University of Ghent
in Belgium. ``They're bred for shelf-life.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the European Union bought only about $1 million worth
of U.S. corn, down dramatically from $305 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Europe buys about 25 percent of the U.S. soybean crop, worth
about $2.6 billion in good years. Purchases dropped to $1 billion
last year, according the U.S. Agriculture Department. That decrease
largely reflects price-cutting by exporters in Brazil and
Argentina, the American Soybean Association said. Now those prices
are rising.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-biotech movement affected soybeans less because most
imported beans are used to make animal feed and cooking oil. Under
European law, food for animals is not labeled, and because
processed oil contains no DNA, it does not have to be labeled
either.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union is debating making those laws stricter.
</P>
<P>
   While Europeans fear the ``GM'' label, scientists like Chris
Somerville, a Stanford University plant biologist, say that genetic
technology is ``hundreds of times more predictable than traditional
means,'' like cross-breeding plants or mutating seeds with
radiation or heat. The fear of creating unpredictable monsters is
``largely unfounded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among U.S. shoppers, surveys show they have confidence in the
Food and Drug Administration and Agriculture Department. Europeans,
on the other hand, having faced mad-cow disease and scandals over
dioxin and sewage sludge in animal feed, have no such confidence in
their regulators.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Also, a debate over gene-splicing technology took place in the
United States in the mid-1980s, a decade before seeds were widely
planted. Jeremy Rifkin, an anti-biotech campaigner, raised the
alarm, but it blew over like the population bomb scare of the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Through a chance meeting in Washington in 1986, Rifkin made a
convert of Benedikt Haerlin, then an official of Germany's Green
Party and now the head of a campaign by Greenpeace, an
environmental protest group, to stop bioengineered food.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a decade later, just as mad-cow disease struck, the first
U.S. crop with some herbicide-resistant soybeans was on its way
across the ocean. Activists still talk about the 1996 crop as if it
was the Normandy invasion. ``Now we had concrete targets,'' said
Mika Railo, a spokesman for Greenpeace. ``We had to hit the ground
running.''
</P>
<P>
   British tabloids leapt into the fray, and soon British companies
were asking U.S. exporters for unmodified grain. Big shippers
initially refused.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, some Americans were insulting. Bill Wadsworth, the
technical manager for Iceland, a British frozen-food and
supermarket chain that is leading the fight against biotech food
there, attended a 1997 meeting of the American Soybean Association
and American farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them our customers wanted choice, and if they would
supply us with one bucket, just one bucket of non-G.M. beans, then
we'd make some product without,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his presence, he said, an association speaker referred to him
as ``a backward European'' and assured the farmers that ``European
objections are irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I organized a separate chain of supply from
Brazil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Europeans often see the U.S. government, aggressively free trade
and keen on technology, as a co-conspirator.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said the
administration would use all legal remedies to compel Europe to
accept U.S. soybeans and corn even if that meant punitive tariffs.
In the same speech, he conceded for the first time that the
administration wanted long-term studies of the food's safety. He
has since modified that tone considerably.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. resistance to labeling, though, rankles some Europeans, who
say it looks suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   In January in Montreal, 130 countries hammered out the first
international treaty on the issue by agreeing that shipments of
modified grain be labeled. Under the treaty, which 50 nations have
yet to ratify, countries can prohibit imports of a crop deemed a
threat to the environment. The treaty does not deal with the
labeling of consumer packages.
</P>
<P>
   European governments and scientists worry about another form of
backlash. Genetic science is becoming a huge industry. If Europe
gets a reputation for Luddite reactions to new fields, they fear,
it will continue to lose its best scientists and thousands of jobs
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say we're playing God,'' said Daniel Vasella, the
president of Novartis, a Swiss-based pharmaceutical and biotech
giant. ``But that's what they said about Icarus and flying, or
Prometheus and fire, or Galileo. You put the old order to rest and
you're told you've questioned the rule of God and you will now be
punished like the fall of the tower of Babel.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Haerlin, leader of the Greenpeace campaign, made a strongly
worded speech at The Hague conference. To an audience of
scientists, he said that many scientists were liars and that
``smarter science and smarter scientists'' were needed to improve
organic farming.
</P>
<P>
   He was criticized by an African official of the U.N. Food and
Agricultural Organization, who said ``organic farming is practiced
by 800 million poor people in the world because they can't afford
pesticides and fertilizers _ and it's not working.'' In remarks to
reporters afterward, Haerlin dismissed the importance of saving
African or Asian lives at the risk of spreading a new science he
considered untested.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace's position, he said, was that research could go on as
long as no seeds or animals are ever released _ which would make
the research pointless for biotech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Europeans agree. Swiss voters, for example, have twice
rejected by large margins referendums that would have banned all
genetic research or put a 10-year moratorium on field trials or
sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
