<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5805 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OSCAR-LUNCH-COLOR-LAD     03-13 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-LUNCH-COLOR-LADN </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On days like this, I love my job. Maybe it's because I just did
lunch with Tom Cruise.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it was me and a few hundred others at the 19th annual
Academy Awards nominees' luncheon at the Beverly Hilton Hotel. But
I was the reporter who, by random drawing, was seated with Tom
Cruise, to the envy of every woman in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise, nominated as best supporting actor for ``Magnolia,''
jumped up when Richard Farnsworth ambled by his table, introduced
himself and complimented Farnsworth's work. It's nice to know that
celebrities who leave the star-struck in their wake still are awed
by their own idols.
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of shop talk, to be sure. At the Cruise table
(or No. 33, for those who sneer at name-dropping), writers talked
computer scripting and designers talked fabric. But it still was a
party.
</P>
<P>
   Director Lasse Hallstrom laughed with ``The Cider House Rules''
writer John Irving, who later was deep in conversation with
director Sam Mendes (``American Beauty'').
</P>
<P>
   Chloe Sevigny (supporting actress, ``Boys Don't Cry'') appeared
ill at ease in the crowded, very chatty room.
</P>
<P>
   Same for Farnsworth (best actor, ``The Straight Story''). The
79-year-old former stuntman stood still in a dense crowd before
lunch was served, clearly wanting to escape it but too polite to
nudge someone aside with a loud ``excuse me.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were an award for best entrance, it would go to Michael
Clarke Duncan (supporting actor, ``The Green Mile''), who bounded
into the luncheon late, just as the nominees were posing for their
``class photo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my housekeys last night _ I didn't have anyplace to
sleep,'' he explained. ``I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Levy of the motion picture academy followed through with
the punchline: ``This may be the first time we've had a homeless
person at the nominees' luncheon.''
</P>
<P>
   Child actor Haley Joel Osment (supporting actor, ``The Sixth
Sense'') actually skipped across the stage after getting his
nomination certificate.
</P>
<P>
   If Oscar odds were determined by an applause meter at the
luncheon, it would be hard to know where to place bets. Some names
would have moved the needle a little farther to the right (such as
Annette Bening, Cruise, Osment, Farnsworth, Kevin Spacey, Denzel
Washington and Hilary Swank). But mostly there was sincere
congratulatory applause that suggested it really !ital!is an honor
to be nominated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5806 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-IRAN-ATTACK-NYT &LR;      03-13 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFTIST GROUP TAKES CREDIT FOR MORTAR ATTACK ON TEHRAN SUBURB
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ A day after one of Iran's leading democratic
reformers was critically wounded in a shooting on a Tehran street,
the Iranian capital was the scene of another attack on Monday when
several mortar shells were fired into a residential complex
abutting a military base in the capital's northern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   In messages to news agency offices elsewhere in the Middle East,
a radical leftist group that bases itself in Iraq, the Mujahedeen
Khalq, the People's Holy Warriors, claimed responsibility for the
attack, which wounded two civilians, one of whom, a gardener, was
reported to have lost both his legs. The group said its target was
an adjacent base of the Revolutionary Guards, a powerful military
force that is one of the pillars of Iran's system of Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
   The leftists' claim of responsibility for the mortar attack
appeared to separate the incident, at least in terms of the likely
perpetrators, from the shooting on Sunday of Saeed Hajjarian, a
47-year-old newspaper publisher and close associate of Iran's
reformist president, Mohammad Khatami. Before Monday's attack, the
Mujahedeen Khalq denied having anything to do with the shooting of
the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   He remained in a coma at Sina hospital in Tehran, on a life
support system, with what one of the doctors involved described as
``irreversible brain damage'' resulting from oxygen starvation in
the immediate aftermath of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   As Iranians absorbed the shock of the two attacks, it became
clear that last month's parliamentary election, far from settling
Iran's political future, has in some ways moved the country into a
still more volatile period. The attack on Hajjarian, in particular,
appeared to have caused deep anxiety among Iran's 65 million
people, whose choices in the parliamentary balloting _ a popular
vote of about 70 percent for reform candidates, resulting in a
sweep of three-quarters of the decided seats in the 290-seat
parliament _ reflected a deep yearning for relief from two decades
of overbearing Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
   Many Iranians rated the election outcome as potentially the most
important change in the political landscape since the Islamic
revolution that overthrew Shah Mohammed Riza Pahlevi in 1979, and
saw Hajjarian, who has been one of the reformers' principal
strategists, as a major standard-bearer for their hopes. According
to leading reformers, few men, if any, have had more influence on
the political strategies of Khatami, who won the presidency, an
office with sharply limited powers, in a landslide victory of his
own in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the country faces still more uncertainty. Apart from
what the attack on Hajjarian may say about the willingness of
Islamic hardliners to turn to violence in their bid to hang on to
power, even the election win may mean less than seemed at first.
Last week, a conservative-dominated supervisory body, the Council
of Guardians, threw out the election of three reform candidates who
won seats in provincial cities, without any attempt to justify or
explain the action. Reformers were left to worry that further
disqualifications may follow.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this, the prospect of a second round of voting on April
21, to settle more than 60 seats that were thrown to run-off
ballots by the first round, and a further period of weeks after
that before the new parliament meets, has left the country facing
an extended period in which both reformers and conservatives have
been left to maneuver and calculate how a new power alignment will
work. Iranian political analysts, in telephone conversations on
Monday, said they viewed the situation as primed for trouble, and
feared that the attacks of the past two days may only be a prelude
to others.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing the aftermath of the attack on Hajjarian to mount an
attack, the analysts said, the Mujahideen Khalq group was not
likely to have been motivated by sympathy for the democratic reform
movement, which it holds in equal contempt to the Islamic
conservatives, seeing both as committed, in different ways, to
upholding the Islamic system that the leftists despise. Rather, the
analysts said, the leftists probably hoped to engender panic and
push Iran closer to a political cataclysm that could open new
opportunities to the leftists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
