<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TRIBUNE-HISTORY-2TAKE     03-13 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-HISTORY-2TAKES(1000)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO 19TH - CENTURY PUBLISHERS BUILT THEIR PAPERS INTO EMPIRES
</HEADLINE>
  (With TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR) 
(nk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A strange kind of symmetry marks the histories of
The Los Angeles Times and The Chicago Tribune, major metropolitan
newspapers and regional power-brokers that in the heyday of such
institutions were ruled by strong-willed, conservative publishers.
These men brooked no dissent and played crucial roles in
determining the shape, growth and self-image of their respective
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Robert R. McCormick, the willfully eccentric publisher of
The Tribune, who mounted fierce feuds with luminaries like Franklin
Roosevelt and Henry Luce and whose editorial page was an often
angry voice of conservative Republicanism, was once described as
``one of the greatest minds of the 14th Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Harrison Gray Otis, a large and often overbearing man who
steered The Los Angeles Times along a similarly conservative path
and who made almost as many enemies as McCormick, passed along the
newspaper to his son, Harry Chandler, and grandson, Norman
Chandler, in an unbroken, century-long chain of right-wing,
Republican domination in Southern California. One political enemy,
Sen. Hiram Johnson, once described Otis as having ``a gangrene
heart and rotting brain, grimacing at every reform, chattering
impotently at all things that are decent.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCormick and Otis built immensely influential institutions
that became virtually synonymous with the cities where they rose _
creating visions of those cities that to a large extent endure to
this day.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick saw his beloved ``Chicagoland,'' a term he coined, as
a kind of ultra-normal, common-sense alternative to the excesses of
the East and West coasts. His vision of the Midwest as a place
apart, a calm heartland of bedrock American values, is one that
took root in the 1940s, when the Tribune was said to be the most
widely read newspaper in America.
</P>
<P>
   For Otis and the Chandlers, Southern California was a kind of
real estate paradise, where ordinary, hard-working people could own
their own homes, perhaps with an orange tree or a swimming pool in
the back yard, and the weather was almost always perfect, a kind of
20th Century fulfillment of the American Dream, the nation's just
reward for manifest destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are two of a kind,'' said Richard Norton Smith,
director of the Gerald R. Ford Library and Museum in Grand Rapids,
Mich., and author of ``The Colonel: The Life and Legend of Robert
R. McCormick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I don't think the colonel would want to have seen his
Chicagoland sullied by being linked to Los Angeles,'' Smith said.
``He always used to refer to California as the nuttiest state in
the Union, with Wisconsin a close second.''
</P>
<P>
   Both papers also had a similar kind of renaissance in the last
quarter of the 20th century, shedding their hidebound cocoons and
becoming among the best and most respected papers in the country.
The change was particularly striking in The Los Angeles Times, once
widely reviled as the nation's worst (a vote of Washington-based
reporters in 1937 named it the nation's ``least fair and reliable''
publication). Under Otis Chandler, the general's great-grandson,
The Los Angeles Times was transformed in the 1960s and 1970s from a
near-laughingstock into one of the country's two or three best
newspapers, eschewing its long-held conservatism for a more
mainstream and cosmopolitan style.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Powers That Be,'' his 1979 book about the founders of
several media empires, David Halberstam wrote of Otis Chandler that
``no publisher in America improved a paper so quickly and on so
grand a scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McCormick was the most colorful and, in the long run,
probably the most influential head of The Chicago Tribune, he was
not its first great publisher. That was Joseph Medill, a Canadian
whose family moved to Ohio in 1832 and who, with his siblings,
bought the local Conshocton Whig and renamed it the Republican. In
1855, after he had founded other Ohio newspapers, including the
Cleveland Leader, Medill bought an interest in the Chicago Tribune,
which had been founded in 1847, and ran it as editor and publisher
from 1874, when he assumed a controlling interest.
</P>
<P>
   It became the most important voice for the abolition of slavery
in the Midwest, and some credit Medill with coming up with the name
for the new political party, the Republicans. In the run-up to the
Civil War, Medill was perhaps the first great champion of Abraham
Lincoln and was instrumental in helping the lawmaker from
Springfield, Ill., become a national political figure dedicated to
preserving the Union.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick, a grandson of Medill, carefully crafted his public
image from the time he took over the Tribune in 1911, becoming
probably the nation's best-known conservative voice for much of the
first half of the century.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really believed, as crackpot as it seems to us today, that
he could influence American foreign policy, that he had a right to
choose who was president,'' Smith said. ``It seems overreaching to
us, but it gave a kind of fierce energy to what he was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the family that ran The Los Angeles Times, McCormick
created no dynasty, dying childless. But he was an empire-builder,
too, expanding the company's interests to include the New York
Daily News and the Washington-Times Herald.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times was first published in 1881 and was
gradually taken over during the next five years by Otis, who used
the paper both as a local power base and as a trumpet to sell
sun-starved Easterners on his growing city, a passion that came
easily to the Ohio-born publisher. He despised labor unions and the
Democratic Party, and the feeling was mutual. In 1910, three union
members confessed to setting a bomb at the paper's downtown Los
Angeles headquarters that killed 21 of Otis' employees.
</P>
<P>
   By 1917, when Harry Chandler fully succeeded his father-in-law
as publisher, The Los Angeles Times was the most powerful voice in
Southern California and a political force to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both Harry Chandler and his son, Norman Chandler, continued the
paper's bedrock Republicanism and often saw nothing wrong with
letting their political biases bleed over into the news columns. At
times, it was said, the publishers would not allow the names of a
Democratic official or union leader to appear undisparaged in the
newspaper. But the paper grew with the city. In 1922, it opened the
first radio station owned by a newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Under Norman Chandler, who took the reins in 1941, the paper
continued to prosper with the city and, after he handed control of
The Los Angeles Times to his son, Otis, in 1960, Norman Chandler
became the chairman of Times-Mirror, the paper's parent company. In
that capacity, he saw the first stages of corporate expansion that
eventually saw Times-Mirror purchase newspapers like Newsday, The
Dallas Times-Herald (later sold and closed), The Denver Post (also
later sold), The Hartford Courant and The Baltimore Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The first major signs of change in the paper's editorial
direction came soon after Otis Chandler assumed control, when he
published a series of articles critical of the John Birch Society,
a right-wing organization with many adherents among the myriad of
Chandler cousins who shared majority control of the corporation
under the terms of Chandler's will.
</P>
<P>
   After Chandler stepped down as publisher and, later, as chairman
of the Times-Mirror board, his most immediate successors largely
carried on in the tradition that he engendered. But in 1995, at the
urging of the remaining Chandler cousins on the board, among
others, Mark Willes, an executive from General Mills who had no
prior newspaper experience, was brought in as chief executive,
vowing to break down long-standing separations between the paper's
business and editorial sides in an effort to ``reinvent the Los
Angeles Times,'' as he often said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0406 </DOCNO>
