<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-TRIBUNAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL OPENS ON SERB GENERAL ACCUSED IN SREBRENICA MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ The trial of a Bosnian Serb general
accused of overseeing the largest single massacre of the war in
Bosnia opened here Monday with prosecutors contending that
determined resistance from U.N. peacekeepers might have prevented
the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Rene Ruez, the lead investigator into the killings in 1995
of an estimated 7,000 Bosnian Muslims during and after the fall of
the U.N.-declared safe area of Srebrenica, said that Bosnian Serb
forces at first did not intend to take the town.
</P>
<P>
   But after Gen. Ratko Mladic, the Bosnian Serb commander,
encountered paltry resistance from the Dutch U.N. peacekeepers,
Bosnian Muslims and NATO warplanes defending the town, he drove his
forces forward, the prosecutor contended. He said he based his
statements on Bosnian Serb documents seized in a raid.
</P>
<P>
   The town's fall has been widely blamed on the reluctance of U.N.
commanders to press for NATO air attacks and the failure to provide
enough troops to defend it.
</P>
<P>
   The trial that opened Monday is for Gen. Radislav Krstic, the
second in command in the attack, who has been charged with
genocide, crimes against humanity and violating the laws of war. He
is the only Bosnian Serb arrested for the attack and has pleaded
not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Krstic, 52, swallowed and stared at his hands when pictures of
corpses in mass graves were flashed in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested by American soldiers in 1998. His superior and
the commander of the Srebrenica attack, Mladic, remains at large
and is believed to be in Belgrade under protection of the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Because Bosnian Serb forces are alleged to have killed nearly
all the men they captured, this case may reflect prosecutors' best
opportunity to win a conviction for genocide in the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors have long complained of the slow pace of the
investigation of the killings. Identification of bodies has been
hampered by a lack of resources, and survivors complain that NATO
troops have been slow to arrest suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
