<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
  
 
 &HT;    If we're lucky, we'll be able to sneak a few french fries  
 By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My experience with political fund-raising is pretty much limited
to diverting milk money from my fourth-grade classmates' pockets
years ago to buy construction paper to make campaign signs for a
school election. But _ call me naive _ some things still seem
elementary when it comes to running for office.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, it seems fair to say that $250 million is a heap
of milk money. That's how much has been spent on the current
presidential campaign thus far. It's a record.
</P>
<P>
   By this point four years ago, the contenders for Bill Clinton's
chair had spent $183 million. At this pace, the only people who
will be able to afford to run in, say, 2020 will be Bill Gates,
Donald Trump and maybe Britney Spears, and if that's not an
argument for campaign finance reform, I don't know what is.
</P>
<P>
   My math has never been terribly good, but according to my
calculations, for $250 million we could hire roughly 4,000 people
to serve the next four years as president at the proposed minimum
wage of $6.15 an hour and still have enough left over to hire Jesse
Helms and Hillary Rodham Clinton to flip burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, at those salaries, we wouldn't be able to attract
presidential candidates who possess a great deal of political
know-how, but at least we'd get leaders who are accustomed to
living on a budget.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect the minimum-wage crowd could pass along a few tips to
George W. Bush on managing money.
</P>
<P>
   Is anybody else a little worried what might happen when this
fellow gets his hands in the national till? I mean, he started out
with a whopping $70 million in his campaign account, enough _ many
people thought _ to blow away his competition in the primaries and
the general election. A few months later, he's down to a piddly few
million and is panhandling his illustrious Pioneers for more.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's Al Gore, who one day last week challenged
Bush to join him in a moratorium on collecting unregulated ``soft
money'' contributions from corporations, rich people and unions.
The following day, his campaign unveiled a program to immediately
raise $35 million in soft money contributions.
</P>
<P>
   If this keeps up, we may all end up milling around Buddhist
temples, shaking down impoverished monks for milk money.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates who bowed out last week were, of course, the
chief proponents of campaign finance reform in this year's race.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts are attributing John McCain's loss to, among
other things, his characterizing Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell as
rulers of an evil empire. I don't know how much that hurt him, but
I certainly grew weary of him comparing himself to Luke Skywalker
at every available opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's said that the Chewbacca of the campaign, Bill
Bradley, faltered in part because he never really opened up
emotionally to voters. A New York Times story last week cited a
moment, early in the campaign, when Bradley failed to hug his
second-grade music teacher at a campaign rally. Criminy, we've had
a slew of leaders lately, notably Bill Clinton and Newt Gingrich,
who wouldn't stop at a hug. Skip the Leo Buscaglia shtick. I'll
take emotional distance.
</P>
<P>
   From here on out, it looks as if we'll be treated to video
footage and photos of candidates hugging voters. Off camera,
they'll be embracing corporate executives, wealthy Americans and
union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last year, the candidates had raised $100 million
in soft money contributions. Before it's all over, they're expected
to collect a half a billion _ and that's on top of run-of-the-mill,
$1,000-donations and hefty supplements from federal election funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the fund-raising equivalent of Sherman's
march through Georgia,'' Fred Wertheimer, president of the watchdog
group Democracy 21, told The New York Times. ``Donors beware _ they
are coming for you and the sky's the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, no chance whatsoever _ wink, wink _ that
the winner will be beholden to the folks who helped buy his entry
into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-huh. If I were running either campaign, I'd order up a few
million pounds of construction paper emblazoned with the words,
``Special orders don't upset us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
