<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman says she now fears rapper
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A woman who tangled with rapper Da Brat at a Buckhead
nightclub had nothing to do with a shooting outside the singer's
Buckhead townhouse, her attorney said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client was horrified when she heard about this,'' attorney
Jim Lewis said of his client Rezue Robateue. ``She does not condone
this kind of behavior and she was very afraid after she learned
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say the shooting may be connected to a fight between
Robateue and rapper Shawntae Harris at the Chili Pepper nightclub
in Buckhead last week. Both women were charged as a result of the
brawl: Harris with battery, Rezue with midsdemeanor simple battery.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said Robateue, a wannabe rapper, once idolized Harris. Now
she fears her, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rezue is lying low right now,'' Lewis said. ``She left town
because she fears she might be a target and because she thinks Da
Brat might be upset with her. She also wants to recover from her
injuries until she appears in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Robateue was hurt last Tuesday night at the Chili Pepper
nightclub when she and Harris brawled, police said. Lewis said
Harris was angered when Robateue was disrespectful to Harris'
female companion, a slight blonde woman.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was accused of striking Robateue across the eye with an
object _ possibly a shot glass or a .22 caliber handgun, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta detectives say the shooting at Harris' apartment complex
Sunday morning may have been in retaliation for the fight at Chili
Pepper. A black limousine was riddled with bullets in the parking
lot just outside Harris' townhouse. The rapper is known to rent
limousines regularly. Investigators have not ruled out that Harris
may have been the intended target of two hit men who somehow drove
into the gated community at the 4100 block of Roswell Road. The
passengers inside the limousine that was hit do not know Harris,
police said Monday, and could be the victims of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old Robateue is a New York native who moved to
Atlanta five years ago. She lives in the city with relatives and is
an aspiring rapper and musician who frequents the Buckhead
nightclub scene, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client is trying to be a musician,'' Lewis said, ``but
she's really more a club patron. I know she is trying to work in
the music industry. She is trying to make a CD.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris' publicist, Tresa Sanders, who also is the publicist for
So So Def Records in Atlanta, the company that discovered Harris,
said she has never heard of Robateue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
