<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore back in Florida for rally tonight
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Vice President Al Gore, making second campaign visit to
the Sunshine State in less than two weeks, on Monday once again
pushed his plans for extending health care to poor children,
protecting Medicare, making prescription drugs easier to obtain for
the elderly and passing a patient's bill of rights so medical
decisions are made by patients and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Heading home to Carthage, Tenn., Gore said he would vote in the
primary there today, have breakfast with his mother, meet with his
staff in Nashville and then come back to Florida for a primary
night rally at high school in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is very much in play,'' said U.S. Sen. Bob Graham,
D-Miami Lakes. ``I think there is a very realistic chance that
Democrats can win this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats are suggesting that if Gore wants to all but
guarantee a November victory here, he should choose Graham to be
his running mate. Asked if he is interested in the job, Graham said
only that he is ``happy to serve the people of Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time that Graham has been on the list of
possible running mates. In 1992, he was a finalist until Bill
Clinton settled on Gore.
</P>
