A5829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-MARS-NASA-NYT &LR;      03-13 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-NASA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL YOUR JETS, NASA, TWO REVIEW PANELS URGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Recent failures in two Mars missions suggest that
NASA is pushing too hard to do more with less money, and
jeopardizing success by paying inadequate attention to risks, two
review panels said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NASA's recent philosophy of conducting more ``faster, better,
cheaper'' space missions instead of a few large ones appears sound
and should continue to be a part of planning, experts on the panels
said. However, they said, this approach has limits and many
projects need to be more closely managed to assure success.
</P>
<P>
   In its second report to the agency, the review board that
examined the failure of the Mars Climate Orbiter mission last year
said that lessons learned from that mishap and other failures with
the quicker, cheaper approach indicated there may have been too
much emphasis on cutting costs and doing missions quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of `faster, better, cheaper' is tempered by the
fact that some projects and programs have put too much emphasis on
cost and schedule reduction,'' said the panel, the Mars Climate
Orbiter Mishap Investigation Board, a group of NASA experts led by
Arthur G. Stephenson, director of the Marshall Space Flight Center
in Alabama. ``At the same time, they have failed to instill
sufficient rigor in risk management throughout the mission life
cycle. These actions have increased risk to an unacceptable level
on these projects.''
</P>
<P>
   This group issued a report last November that said the Climate
Orbiter perished when it flew too close to Mars on Sept. 23 because
the spacecraft contractor and NASA engineers had failed to catch
errors in converting from English to metric measurements. After the
initial report, in which the panel blamed poor communications and
teamwork for the failure, the group was charged to look at similar
projects to see if the same problems existed.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report, also released Monday, Tony Spear, a
retired NASA project manager who supervised one of the greatest
successes of the new approach, called for training better, more
experienced managers who are willing to say when a mission cannot
be done properly under certain schedule and cost restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Spear, who managed 1997's Mars Pathfinder mission, which put a
rock-sniffing rover named Sojourner on the planet's surface, said
early faster, better, cheaper missions had a realistic scope for
the schedule and money they had to work with. Now, he said,
planners are trying to do too much by mounting unusually
challenging missions within arbitrary schedule and cost caps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge bar was raised too high for some of the
second-generation missions,'' he wrote in his report. ``The cost
cap challenges were made too great, along with a mix of unstable
funding and escalating requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Spear said he had interviewed hundreds of people inside and
outside NASA, and no one felt the space agency should retreat from
the faster, better, cheaper approach if it was to remain viable.
NASA should slow the planning and implementation of these smaller
projects, he said, and install ``better reality checks'' on the
feasibility of doing certain missions with the money allowed.
</P>
<P>
   In a few years, NASA has moved from having a few missions to
other planets and other solar systems to having many in various
stages of planning and operation, Spear said. This has diluted
management attention across many missions and not allowed time to
develop experienced project managers, engineers and others with
expertise, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Climate Orbiter investigations board recommended that NASA
adopt a new component to the faster, better, cheaper paradigm
called ``Mission Success First.'' Under this approach, the costs
and requirements of mission success should be studied independently
of other factors, and NASA should consider not financing or
canceling projects that are inadequately financed to overcome risks
to success, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Projects should not only pay more attention to risk assessment,
it said, but also be better designed to provide engineering data to
understand mission failures so subsequent missions do not repeat
them. The Mars Polar Lander, for example, disappeared without a
trace last Dec. 3 as it was beginning its computer-controlled
descent, and engineers still have no clue as to what went wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
