<HEADER>
A5832 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-FLORIDA-PREZ-COX     03-13 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-PREZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parties say primary system needs overhaul
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are among the least-populated states in the nation, yet
once again Iowa and New Hampshire have had more to say about the
next president than every state in the South except South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Republicans and Democrats agree on little, but as voters
go to the polls today for a largely ceremonial presidential vote,
leaders of both parties say the nation's primary system must
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this serves the interests of the nation well,''
says U.S. Sen. Bob Graham, D-Miami. ``Too few voters have a voice
and it has happened so fast that I don't think voters have enough
time to get to know and evaluate the candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   As governor from 1979 to 1987, Graham tried to change the
system. He worked with other Southern governors to form the
original Super Tuesday. The idea was for a southern regional
primary on the second Tuesday of March that would force the
candidates to spend a lot time here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped that it would spark a national movement toward
regional primaries,'' said Graham. ``But the desire of states to
get in as early in the process as possible has overwhelmed that.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's primary lineup became a free-for-all with states
battling for position up until the last moment. No one fights
harder to be first than New Hampshire, which has a state law that
requires its primary to be seven days before any other primary.
</P>
<P>
   Many states resent it and a few always try to get in front of
New Hampshire, but then always back down. Graham says improving the
primary system is so important that he would just go ahead and let
Iowa and New Hampshire remain alone and then go into a series of
regional primaries that are from two to four weeks apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee is looking to make a change at
this year's convention. Al Cardenas, a member of the committee and
chairman of the Florida GOP, said there is a move to divide the
nation into five, 10-state primaries. There would be a primary a
month for five months. The key to this plan is that the states
would be divided by population with the 10 smallest states going
first and the 10 largest states going last.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not part of the decision-making process and that needs
to be changed,'' said Cardenas. ``I think there is an understanding
even in Iowa and New Hampshire that we can't continue to leave the
majority of the voters out of the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the National Association of Secretaries of State
approved a plan that would create four regional primaries _ East,
South, Midwest and West. The first would be in March, the last in
June. The Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary would remain in
February. Every four years the regional primaries would be rotated
so that each region would have a chance to go first.
</P>
<P>
   If some system agreeable to everyone isn't approved by the
political parties and state legislatures, the primary system is
only going to get worse, says Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Florida lawmakers are working on a bill that would move
the Sunshine State's primary to the last Tuesday in January _
making it before New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   briancrowley(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
