u f BC-IMF-EUROPE-540&AMP;ADD-NY     03-13 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-EUROPE-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS HE WILL ACCEPT GERMAN CANDIDATE FOR IMF POST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER and JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Monday told Germany's
chancellor that he would accept Horst Koehler as the new head of
the International Monetary Fund, ending a heated diplomatic contest
over who would lead the institution that battles global financial
crises.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's apparently reluctant support virtually assures that
Koehler, a former German finance official who is now president of
the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, will win the
top post at the fund.
</P>
<P>
   But the huge rift that opened during the selection process _
during which Clinton refused to support Germany's first nominee and
developing nations attempted to install their own candidate _
leaves open many questions about how the much-criticized
institution will change, and the tradition-bound method by which
its leaders are chosen.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews on Monday, senior administration officials who had
been far from enthusiastic about Koehler last week were beginning
to tout his strengths, describing him as ``an important player'' in
the economic unification of Germany and in the creation of the
European Monetary Union.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago his name was not even on the short list of
finance ministers, central bankers and European politicians judged
by the U.S. Treasury and European officials to have the political
influence and judgment for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's approval seemed driven more by a sense that Clinton
could not turn down a second German candidate, and one endorsed
directly by the German chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago Clinton rejected the selection of Caio
Koch-Weser, Germany's deputy finance minister. That led one of
Schroeder's top advisers, Michael Steiner, to complain that the
United States ``sees its global role not only in the military area
but also in setting the rules of globalization through the IMF.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Germany won its struggle. Clinton and Treasury
Secretary Lawrence H. Summers concluded that they could not violate
the 50 year-old, unwritten rule that allows Europe to fill the IMF
post, while the United States appoints the head of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said Clinton had spoken
to Schroeder on Monday afternoon from Cleveland, where he was
speaking to promote his plan for expanded prescription drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president told Chancellor Schroeder that the United States
was prepared to support Mr. Koehler as the new head of the IMF,''
Lockhart said. ``The president and Schroeder agreed that Mr.
Koehler should come to Washington to meet with the IMF board,
particularly with the developing countries,'' Lockhart said. They
also agreed that Koehler ``should retain the talented management
team at the IMF.''
</P>
<P>
   That was thinly-veiled code to suggest that Stanley Fischer, the
No. 2 official of the fund and the man promoted by African and
Middle Eastern nations for the top job, should remain in place.
Fischer, formerly chairman of the economics department at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, was the IMF architect of the
bailout of Asia during the economic crisis that began in the summer
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's decision came only hours after all 15 nations within
the European Union on Monday endorsed Germany's new candidate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the administration has learned repeatedly in the past five
years _ first when the Mexican peso collapsed, then when Asia's
tigers, Russia and Brazil saw their economies implode in quick
succession _ the United States has a huge stake in who heads the
IMF.
</P>
<P>
   In return for providing emergency funds and arranging bailouts,
the fund can command huge changes in a country's economic policies.
Sometimes it is heeded, as it was in the case of Thailand and South
Korea, two of its biggest success stories. Sometimes its
prescriptions touch off riots and political instability; it was
widely criticized for hurting Indonesia's poor while saving the
banks that lent the country money. Without question, the IMF's
prescriptions in Indonesia sped the departure of its longtime
dictator, President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, however, the fund has met considerable political
resistance and little success. It has repeatedly delayed disbursing
funds until Moscow fulfilled its economic commitments. And Koehler
will find himself maneuvering with Russia's acting president,
Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   That will be an important test because Koehler's current
institution, the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development,
watched loan after loan to Russia go bad, and often found itself at
the losing end of negotiations with Russian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler presided over a large-scale write-off of Russian loans
in 1998 that led to the bank's first-ever yearly loss. But it has
since returned to profitability, and Koehler has sought to refocus
the bank of small-business loans and smaller scale development
projects since then.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton clearly endorsed him before hearing his
views on the IMF's future. In the conversation with Schroeder, one
official said, ``the president said we need to engage about what
his vision will be. And Schroeder said `We'll do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, 57, never topped the list of European candidates to
head the IMF. When Michel Camdessus announced his retirement last
fall, Koehler's name was among those briefly floated among European
officials. But Germany decided to push Koch-Weser. One reason was
almost certainly domestic politics: Koch-Weser was chosen
personally by Schroeder to serve as the No. 2 official in the
finance ministry, while Koehler held the same job under Helmut
Kohl, the long-time German chancellor whom Schroeder defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler comes closer to meeting the litmus test the Treasury
Department set for any new IMF director. He has a higher political
stature than Koch-Weser, Clinton administration officials said. He
was the financial point man during the unification of East and West
Germany, overseeing West Germany's program to quickly integrate the
East by unifying the currency on terms favorable to the East and
channeling tens of billion dollars in development aid to help
development in the Eastern half of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler was also the top international official in the German
finance ministry when European countries agreed on the terms of
monetary union in 1992. That showed he had much more experience
than Koch-Weser dealing with currency matters _ a crucial part of
the IMF's duties. Koch-Weser focused almost exclusively in internal
management and poverty relief programs during his 25 years at the
World Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
