u p BC-CLINTON-EMAIL-NYT &LR;      03-13 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EMAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE AND CLINTON'S CRITICS FEUD OVER LOST E-MAIL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration and some of its
Republican critics are quarreling over misdirected White House
e-mail messages that were not produced when they were subpoenaed in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began, congressional investigators believe, when
someone deep inside the White House held down the shift key too
long.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that simple keystroke error that mislabeled an
e-mail server as ``MAIL2'' instead of ``Mail2,'' two years' worth
of e-mail messages that had been sent to top officials in the White
House from the outside were not properly stored in the
administration's mainframe computer. Even critics of President
Clinton call it ``inadvertent human error.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though it began as an innocent mistake, the glitch took
five months to fix. That meant that when administration officials
sought to dig up that e-mail in 1998 to comply with a variety of
subpoenas, the computer search missed potentially relevant
documents dealing with campaign fund-raising abuses, the Monica
Lewinsky affair and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   Was the e-mail incriminating messages with implications for
central figures in those scandals, or was it just idle thoughts or
random observations from outsiders irrelevant to the matters at
hand? That remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But computer specialists who helped set up the White House
computer system say administration officials were slow to fix the
problem. They believe that many of the e-mail messages still exist,
caught up in an electronic limbo. Because of that, the computer
error has surfaced as the latest dispute between the administration
and its fiercest critics, who have been playing cat and mouse for
years over White House records.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., issued a subpoena last week to
determine whether White House officials knew about the computer
problem while he and others were seeking administration e-mail as
part of their investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only conclude that you are personally content with what
is, in effect, a purposeful effort to keep documents from Congress,
the Department of Justice and various independent counsels,''
Burton, chairman of the House Government Reform and Oversight
Committee, wrote last week to Beth Nolan, the White House counsel.
``While it may serve a variety of political interests to do
nothing, it does not serve the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has confirmed that there was a problem with the
computers but vehemently denies that it intentionally withheld
information from investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burton has a long history of making partisan allegations that
don't survive the test of time or the facts,'' said a White House
spokesman, Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Making the matter worse are allegations lodged by
Northrop-Grumman employees who were hired by the administration as
consultants to work on the computer system. They say that they
brought the problem to the attention of White House employees in
June 1998, but the problem was not fixed until that November. They
said they were sternly instructed to keep the matter to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Crabtree, the White House's customer-support branch chief,
warned that if they told anyone there would be a jail cell with
their names on it, according to the accounts of three contract
employees. Crabtree, who now works at the Labor Department, did not
return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Lambuth, one of the contractors, said in papers filed last
week in Federal District Court that she and other contractors used
to meet in a park near the White House and in a nearby Starbucks to
discuss the e-mail matter away from their supervisors. She became
convinced, she said, that the White House took its time in fixing
the problem to keep damaging e-mail under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   Lambuth's sworn statement was part of a lawsuit filed against
the White House by Judicial Watch, a conservative legal
organization that has been strongly critical of Clinton. The suit
concerns the mishandling of FBI files by the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   Concerning the missing e-mail, Lambuth said that one contractor
who inspected some of the communications said they contained
information concerning a variety of Clinton administration
controversies, including the Lewinsky matter and Vice President Al
Gore's involvement in campaign fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl L. Hall, a former White House employee who has filed suit
against the White House on another matter, said in court papers
that the number of missing e-mail messages probably exceeded
100,000 and included missives sent to Clinton, Hillary Rodham
Clinton and hundreds of top aides. Hall, who oversaw the computer
contractors, said one person who viewed the e-mail described some
of the messages as ``incriminating.''
</P>
<P>
   She has not named the worker who made that claim. It remains
unclear whether the e-mail messages were comments from members of
the public on news of the day or private communications between
government bureaucrats outside the White House and presidential
aides.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Klayman, who heads Judicial Watch and believes the worst,
called on Robert W. Ray, who took over from Kenneth W. Starr as the
independent counsel investigating the Clinton White House, to delay
issuing any reports until he determined whether he had all the
missing e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's office has acknowledged it is aware of the e-mail dispute
but has given no signs that the matter will slow his investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we are looking into the allegations regarding the
e-mails and we're taking steps to deal with the allegations,'' said
Julie Thomas, associate independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department lawyer, James Gilligan, who appeared in
court last week on behalf of the White House, said in documents
that the administration had not retaliated against any workers or
covered anything up.
</P>
<P>
   He filed papers that called the e-mail matter, which was first
reported in The Washington Times, ``another distraction'' and
another example of Judicial Watch ``chasing the morning
headlines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
