<HEADER>
A5842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TRIBUNE-NEW-MEDIA-ART     03-13 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-NEW-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASTION OF OLD MEDIA VALUES TRANSFORMS ITSELF INTO A NEW MEDIA
CHAMPION
</HEADLINE>
  (With TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The announcement Monday that the Tribune Co. was
acquiring the Times Mirror Co. elicited this response from Esther
H. Dyson, the high-technology pundit: ``So one newspaper buys
another: so what?''
</P>
<P>
   For Dyson, a seer of the new economy, the merger amounted to a
marriage between survivors of a fading world. The parent company of
the Chicago Tribune, which resides in a stately but fortress-like
Gothic tower, is tying the knot with the parent company of the Los
Angeles Times and Newsday, which has been run by a former General
Mills executive, Mark H. Willes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here in Chicago, the Tribune Co. has been quietly
transforming itself in recent years into what its executives say is
a new media company that funnels old media content into television,
cable, radio and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Before the deal, the Tribune Co. had 22 television stations,
reaching more than a third of U.S. households. There were four
radio stations, an entertainment unit, a venture capital arm, and
an educational publishing unit.
</P>
<P>
   The company was an early investor in America Online and Yahoo,
and owns a 25 percent stake in the WB television network and a 29
percent stake in cable television's Food Network.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring Times Mirror would add three of the nation's best
known newspapers to that portfolio: Newsday in New York, The Los
Angeles Times and the Baltimore Sun. The Tribune Co.'s
coast-to-coast empire would include a newspaper and television
station in three of the nation's largest markets: New York, Chicago
and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our new company will be the best positioned local market media
company for the future,'' said John W. Madigan, Tribune chairman,
president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune shares dropped on news of a deal, but the company has
been a winner on Wall Street in recent years, largely because it is
trying to meet the convergence of old media and new media head on,
even if not everyone is noticing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very smart guys up there in Tribune Tower,'' said
Robert A. Davis, a former assistant metro editor at the Chicago
Tribune. ``They look like ram-rod flannel wearing suits, and they
are, but they're smart. There's a long reputation of conservatism,
but these guys are out there rocking 'n' rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal, however, took many here by surprise, even those within
the Tribune organization. The company had been betting heavily on
television and Internet properties, and now, a decade after selling
the New York Daily News, it was buying up huge newspaper properties
in some of the nation's biggest markets.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune executives say the merger fits into their larger scheme,
which is to leverage old media newspapers, with their prized
content, into new media television, cable and internet outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives say that the new company, which will be called
the Tribune Co., will have the clout to sell advertising nationally
for its regional newspapers, television stations and its Internet
outlets. The company would also create cross-marketing agreements
among its properties, and find synergies in a world-class news
gathering force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I think about it the more this furthers the path they
began around 1989 to control as much content as humanly possible,''
said Jeff Borden, a reporter at Crain's Chicago Business who has
covered the Tribune company for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The new media format that the Tribune Co. is championing,
however, is also raising some concerns among journalists who worry
that the quality of newspapers will suffer in a world driven by
profits and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune has a reputation not only for being a fierce
cost-cutter and union buster, but for putting greater and greater
emphasis on entertainment and business.
</P>
<P>
   Some reporters and editors in Chicago have complained about the
company's drive to merge its newspaper, television and Internet
properties into one giant media conglomerate where television
reporters share office space with newspaper reporters, story ideas
are shared among once competing papers and bureaus are
consolidated.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Tribune Media Center houses reporters and
editors from the Chicago Tribune, the Orlando Sentinel and several
television stations; in the Tribune newsroom, CLTV, a local cable
station owned by the company, has set up shop to interview
reporters live.
</P>
<P>
   Others say the Tribune Co. is remaking itself into an
entertainment company. The Tribune's entertainment arm used to
produce Geraldo Rivera's daytime talk show, and these days,
reporters at the Chicago Tribune often joke about how ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer,'' the popular WB television show that runs on many
of the Tribune stations, fattens their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a conference call with reporters, Tribune executives
talked about how their new enterprise would create a platform for
new electronic commerce businesses to be formed by the company,
selling everything from travel destinations to information.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Smith, publisher of the Chicago Tribune, however, says the
company is not surrendering its integrity or chipping away at good
journalism. It is, he says, simply finding new synergies and a new
way to deliver valuable content to readers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's true the Tribune newspaper margins have improved
significantly over the last decade,'' he said. ``But we have more
journalists today than we had a decade ago, and more talented
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans to develop a national newspaper, but the
company wants a world-class news gathering organization where
newspaper, television and Internet reporters share information and
real estate, and even cross-over into one another's space.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are issues to work through,'' Smith said. ``Sometimes we
compete, sometimes we cooperate. Sharing news resources across
print and broadcasting helps make our coverage stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the Los Angeles Times was planning a renovation, and
the Tribune Co. had already suggested that its KTLA television
affiliate take a look at the plans to see whether it wanted to
incorporate itself into the Los Angeles newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts say they were surprised by the deal because
the Tribune Co. had been concentrating on broadcast and Internet
properties, but the Times Mirror newspapers fit nicely into the
company's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``To draw an analogy, you've got radio and television companies
trying to grab broadcast spectrum, I see this as trying to grab
spectrum,'' said John Morton, who covers the newspaper industry as
an independent analyst. ``They're adding newspapers in major
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Madigan said Monday that the merger gives the Tribune a ``major
national footprint'' in the United States, because of its powerful
brands in New York, Chicago and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will have papers with a nationwide circulation
of 3.6 million, and its television stations will reach more than
38.4 million households. On the Internet, it already ranks as one
of the top 20 news and information Web sites, with more than 3.4
million unique visitors each month.
</P>
<P>
   Madigan, who noted the Tribune's early investment in America
Online and its alliance with Time Warner in the WB network,
encouraged comparisons to AOL's acquisition of Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it pushed us along, but it validates a lot of
things we're investing in,'' he said. ``We think that's a wonderful
transaction and both of those companies are great partners of
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has been trying to sell its new media identity to
Wall Street. Its annual report is filled with details about the
company's $250 million in profits from its early investment in
America Online, its investments in other Internet properties such
as iVillage.com and Peapod Inc. The company was an early investor
in a venture to put classified advertising on the Internet, and is
trying to advance interactive and digital television capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not some navel gazing company,'' said Borden at
Crain's Chicago. ``They've bought back 5 million shares of their
own stock this year and they have been very aggressive,
particularly on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to integrating the Times-Mirror newspapers, top
executives say they will use their purchasing might to lower costs,
and they will pool advertising strength to attract national
retailers. No layoffs are planned at any of the major newspapers,
but Smith, the publisher of the Chicago Tribune, said that while
there are no immediate plans to merge bureaus, he did not rule it
out.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Tribune newspapers now operate as a family, with a
good deal of consolidation. ``It's like brothers,'' he said. ``They
can work effectively together to deliver better news.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
