<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TRIBUNE-IMPACT-ART-NY     03-13 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-IMPACT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER ANNOUNCEMENT IS BAD NEWS FOR TRIBUNE SHAREHOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (With TRIBUNE-TIMESMEDIA) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tribune Co.'s agreement to buy Times Mirror spelled bad news
for Tribune shareholders on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Already battered on fears that earnings growth will slow in the
newspaper industry, Tribune's stock more than 17 percent Monday to
$30.8125, its lowest level in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   But some big investors and stock analysts said worries that the
$6.45 billion deal would hurt Tribune's profits were overdone. If
the deal is completed, Tribune will have both a newspaper and a
television station in the three largest advertising markets in the
United States _ New York, Los Angeles, and Chicago. Tribune already
owns a newspaper and station in Chicago, as well as the Chicago
Cubs and several other newspapers and television stations
nationwide. Times Mirror publishes the Los Angeles Times and
Newsday, among other papers.
</P>
<P>
   The combination would probably be attractive to advertisers and
give Tribune a head start in the furious competition to build
local-interest Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hinge that turns this deal is the new media potential
threading Chicago, Los Angeles, and New York, three massive local
markets,'' Leland Westerfield, a broadcasting and publishing stock
analyst at PaineWebber. ``Creating a new media network of behemoth
local markets offers tremendous potential to advertisers.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Westerfield said Tribune would be able to sell
advertising across its newspaper and television stations in the
same way that Clear Channel Communications and CBS sell across
their radio stations and billboards. That combination has worked
well for Clear Channel and CBS, two of the best-performing and
highest-valued media companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a brilliant deal,'' said Mario Gabelli, the mutual
fund manager. ``Tribune understands the benefits of cross-ownership
in a market.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabelli said his funds bought 500,000 shares of Times Mirror on
Monday, which he plans to exchange for Tribune shares, as well as a
smaller amount of Tribune shares.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Tribune said they were also surprised by
investors' reaction Monday. ``We expected there would be some
decline in our stock price, but nothing like we have seen today,''
said Donald C. Grenesko, Tribune's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there is an overreaction.'' Grenesko said. ``The
multiple we paid is very reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Tribune's board has authorized the company to buy back up to
$2.5 billion shares of stock, a hefty amount considering Tribune's
market capitalization is now $7.3 billion. Grenesko said Tribune
might begin those repurchases as early as Monday, although the
company will have to stop any buyback when it begins its tender
offer for Times Mirror shares, probably next week.
</P>
<P>
   Grenesko said he thought investors had misunderstood Tribune's
warning that the merger would cause its reported earnings per share
to drop by 16 percent this year. That is mainly because of the
accounting effects of goodwill, the amount in excess of assets
being paid for Times Mirror and no reflection on Tribune's
operations or cash profits. If goodwill is factored out, the deal
will increase Tribune's cash earnings per share beginning next
year, the company said. Over the long run, the company said the
deal should increase its earnings growth rate by 1 to 2 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Times Mirror, Tribune has ``better management and
probably better growth,'' said Mark Greenberg of the Invesco
Leisure Fund.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of the newspaper industry, Gabelli said he
expected ``a lot of conversations will take place,'' and that more
deals would eventually follow.
</P>
<P>
   Among other media companies, those that own newspapers and
broadcast stations, like Gannett, are more likely to be buyers,
while newspaper-only companies, like Knight-Ridder, are likely
sellers, Mr. Greenberg said. Gannett rose 43.25 cents to $66
Monday, while Knight-Ridder jumped $2.375 to $47.50. Gannett and
Knight-Ridder both declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
