<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5850 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-FUNDRAISIN     03-13 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-FUNDRAISING-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ON HOW FUND RAISING FOR MRS. CLINTON AFFECTS PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Fla., S.D., Pakistan, India)  (js) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While President Clinton was engaged in an intense
debate with his advisers about whether to stop in Pakistan during
his upcoming visit to South Asia, a group of Pakistani-Americans in
New York with a keen interest in the decision raised $50,000 for
the Senate campaign of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing illegal about the Feb. 22 fund-raiser, a
$1,000-a-plate dinner of barbecued chicken kebab, spicy goat curry
and rice at a house on Staten Island. All the donors were U.S.
citizens, the organizers said. And no evidence has emerged that
Hillary Rodham Clinton, who told people at the dinner that she
hoped her husband would visit Pakistan, had influenced her
husband's decision last week to do so. A White House spokesman,
Mike Hammer, said, ``The first lady's views were not part of the
decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fund-raiser still illustrates a unique aspect of Mrs.
Clinton's candidacy: While her husband still occupies the White
House, people may seek to influence his policies by making
donations to her Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton spent more than two hours at the fund-raiser, the
organizers said, listening to the concerns of the
Pakistani-Americans, and left before the meal was served. Her hosts
were a group of Pakistani-Americans who wanted to press the case to
the first lady that her husband should visit Pakistan and that his
administration should become engaged in finding a solution to the
war in Kashmir, a territory claimed by both Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the event's organizers, Suhail Muzaffar, a businessman,
and Asim Malik, a doctor from Long Island, New York, said $50,000
was the minimum amount required before Clinton's aides would add
the event to her schedule. The donors were primarily from the New
York metropolitan area, but some came from New Jersey and Maryland,
Malik said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Mr. Clinton announced that he would stop in Pakistan
for a few hours during his visit to the region, which begins
Saturday. The decision was a difficult call because of the intense
rivalry between India and Pakistan and the strife between the two
nations over Kashmir, among other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's hosts moved the dinner to an earlier date so that
it would take place before the president's trip, organizers said.
The fund-raiser was organized by the Pakistani community on Staten
Island, and the Pakistani-American Physicians Political Action
Committee, or Pak-Pac, as it is known. Her appearance there was
first reported by newspapers in India.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it went very well, in terms of the message and the
timeliness of it, especially in terms of the president's going to
the region,'' Muzaffar said. In her remarks at the event, Muzaffar
recalled Clinton saying, ``I would hope the president would go'' to
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, confirmed that remark
and said that she had also told the group that the president wanted
to make the stop in Pakistan. Wolfson also confirmed that the
campaign usually asks for a minimum of $50,000 in exchange for
Clinton's appearance at a fund-raiser. Asked if Clinton had
conveyed the views of the Pakistani-Americans to her husband,
Wolfson said, ``Everyone in the administration, including Hillary
and the president, hoped that he could go, and said that.'' Wolfson
added that Indian-American groups had also contributed to Mrs.
Clinton's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Pakistani leaders on Staten Island were working with
other ethnic leaders in the borough on a fund-raiser for Mrs.
Clinton that would address issues facing a spectrum of immigrants,
including Arabs and Africans, as well as Pakistanis, said Abdul
Rehman, who was a member of the reception committee at the dinner.
But then, with President Clinton's trip to the region approaching,
he said, the visit to Pakistan became a central focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot deny that the fact that she's the president's wife
makes a difference,'' Malik said. ``But also as a woman, she can
feel more pain for the victims of Kashmir, the women and
children,'' he added, explaining why most Pakistani-Americans are
endorsing her.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The presidential trip was not the only reason the Pakistanis
have for backing Clinton's Senate bid, the event's organizers said.
Pakistani taxi drivers and street vendors in New York City are
generally not happy with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, her Republican
opponent, they said. Both the drivers and the vendors have been the
targets of stricter regulations under Giuliani's ``quality of
life'' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner for Clinton was attended by Lanny J. Davis, who as a
lobbyist for the Pakistani government urged the president to visit
the country, but Davis said he played no role in arranging the
fund-raiser. He called $50,000 a ``minor event'' compared to the
amounts Indian-Americans give to campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who was a special counsel to Mr. Clinton in the aftermath
of the 1996 Democratic fund-raising excesses, vigorously rejected
any suggestion that somehow it might be considered unseemly for the
Pakistani community to raise money for Mrs. Clinton. `` It is no
different from what Jewish, Italian or Irish-Americans do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indian-Americans are generally better organized politically than
their Pakistani counterparts, and they lobbied against the visit to
Pakistan. Indian-Americans have given large amounts of campaign
money to a variety of lawmakers. For instance, Frank Pallone, a New
Jersey Democrat who was a founder of the India caucus, one of the
most powerful in Congress, has received tens of thousands of
dollars in campaign contributions from Indian-Americans who live
outside New Jersey. An Indian-American doctor in Florida, Zachariah
Zachariah, raised more than $500,000 from Indian-American doctors
for President Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Indians and Pakistanis have squared off before in Senate
contests, most notably four years ago in South Dakota. The
Pakistani-American community poured money into the campaign of U.S.
Rep. Tim Johnson, a Democrat, in his successful effort to oust Sen.
Larry Pressler, the Republican author of legislation that had cut
off U.S. military aid to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   But full immersion in the U.S. political game is new for most
Pakistani-Americans. ``We have never been part of the political
system,'' said Malik, of Old Westbury, N.Y. ``And very slowly,
we've realized you have to be part of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Mrs. Clinton could not stay for the fund-raiser's
dinner, she made a good impression on her hosts, Malik said,
telling them that once she was elected they should come to see her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to do that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
