<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      03-13 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE MEETS MAYORS; SHIFTING FROM MCCAIN TO GORE; NEVADA FOR GORE; 
BUSH ON DEBATES; WASHINGTON RACE WAS CLOSE; SIGHTS SET ON HYDE'S
SEAT; 
SENATE CANDIDATE IN JAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORE MEETS MAYORS
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore met Monday night in Nashville with 30
mayors from across the country. His campaign is hoping they will
provide a counterweight to the many Republican governors who are
working for Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. The mayors included
Dennis Archer of Detroit, Jerry Brown of Oakland, Calif., Sharpe
James of Newark, Wellington Webb of Denver, Marc Morial of New
Orleans and Thomas M. Menino of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   SHIFTING FROM McCAIN TO GORE
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore's campaign, which has spent the last week
trying to impress Sen. John McCain's voters, announced Monday that
McCain's Mississippi coordinator, Jim Bass, had moved to the Gore
camp. But at Bass' news conference in Jackson Monday, none of the
assembled political reporters had heard of Bass or knew that McCain
had a Mississippi organization. McCain had not visited the state to
campaign for Tuesday's primary, and had not opened a headquarters.
Bass said he had run for a state Senate seat a dozen years ago _ as
a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA FOR GORE
</P>
<P>
   Nevada had its Democratic caucuses Sunday and Vice President Al
Gore beat former Sen. Bill Bradley, 92 percent to 8 percent. About
1,025 of Nevada's 377,000 registered Democrats showed up. Under the
state's winner-take-all system, Gore won 29 delegates to the
nominating convention this summer.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH ON DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush again rebuffed Vice President Al Gore's
offer to suspend all advertising and hold twice-weekly debates.
``There is going to be ample time to debate,'' Bush said. ``The
best time to debate is when people are paying attention. As much as
we wish, America is now going to go into a little hibernation
period when it comes to politics. They are going to go into the
summer months and go on vacation with their families.''
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON RACE WAS CLOSE
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain fell just short of a moral victory in
Washington state, as election officials announced that he had lost
the overall vote total in the Feb. 29 primary by a fraction of a
percentage point, or 2,302 votes. Gov. George W. Bushwas declared
the top vote-getter, with 402,278 votes, or 30.72 percent, to
399,976, or 30.55 percent for McCain. Vice President Al Gore
received 310,403 votes, or 23.71 percent, to 162,721, or 12.43
percent, for Bill Bradley. The only votes Republicans use for
selecting delegates are those of self-declared Republicans, and
Bush won this tally easily, 284,046 votes to 191,098 for McCain.
The officials said that the final vote would be certified next
week.
</P>
<P>
   SIGHTS SET ON HYDE'S SEAT
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to topple one of the biggest names in Congress, two
relatively unknown Democrats are competing for the nomination to
oppose Rep. Henry Hyde, the Republican who represents an affluent
suburban district west of Chicago. Brent Christensen, a 37-year-old
lawyer, first met Hyde when, as a college student in the 1980s, he
delivered a pizza to the congressman. Christensen won The Chicago
Tribune's endorsement for the Democratic primary over Thomas
Cramer, 52, a business consultant who ran against Hyde two years
ago. Both Democrats have sought to portray Hyde, a strong opponent
of legal abortion, as out of step with a district that they regard
as moderate on social issues. Hyde, who led the House members who
prosecuted President Clinton at his Senate impeachment trial, faces
no opposition in the Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE CANDIDATE IN JAIL
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Wightman-Cervantes, one of five Democratic challengers for
the seat held by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, was arrested
at his Dallas home on Thursday night and is now serving a 90-day
jail sentence for contempt of court. The sentence, which
Wightman-Cervantes had unsuccessfully appealed to the Texas and
U.S. Supreme Courts, grew out of a longstanding dispute with a
local judge, David Godbey. Though another judge had hinted at a
shorter jail stay if the candidate apologized to Godbey,
Wightman-Cervantes told The Associated Press, ``Never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
