<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5858 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRIA-$ADV19     03-13 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRIA-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALARM BELLS IN AUSTRIA: WILL TOURISM FALL OFF?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 19) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ In the past, when Austrian students rarely
finished their studies at the university where they started, they
liked to talk of doing the theater semester in Vienna, and the ski
semester in Innsbruck. Indeed, Austria's rich combination of
cultural attractions and outdoor activities has made it a leading
destination not only for students but for millions of foreign
tourists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So anything that threatens tourism, which by last year was
earning Austria about $14 billion a year, has enormous
reverberations. Alarms began to sound when foreign visitors started
canceling plans after ministers from the anti-immigrant party of
Jorg Haider were included in the governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The 14 other nations of the European Union reacted by
downgrading relations with Austria, and the United States and
Israel recalled their ambassadors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Haider resigned at the end of February as head of the
Freedom Party, the party's ministers remained in office, and the
resignation did little to change critics' minds about the
government.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prominent figures like the president of Portugal, Jorge Sampaio,
and the actress Catherine Deneuve refused to attend the elegant
Vienna Opera Ball on March 2; Gerard Mortier, the innovative
Belgian artistic director of the venerable Salzburg Festival, made
noises about resigning before his announced resignation date; and
the Austrian pianist Andras Schiff, who was scheduled to play at
the Vienna Festival this summer, announced his intention of
canceling his Austrian appearances one by one until the political
situation was more to his liking. The rock singer Lou Reed also
canceled an appearance scheduled for later this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most troubling, major international corporations, big
contributors to Vienna's hotel and convention industry, were said
to be canceling business meetings in Austria. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not that Austrian tourism has been thrown into crisis. Eva
Draxler, spokeswoman for the Vienna Tourist Board, acknowledged
that as of Feb. 21, 20,000 overnight stays in Vienna had been
canceled for this year, and a further 10,000 for the year 2001. But
in a city that boasts 7.6 million hotel bookings in an average
year, that amounted to roughly one-quarter of 1 percent of this
year's total, and one-tenth of 1 percent of next year's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Salzburg, the shock of the strong international reaction was
quickly softened by Mortier's announcement that he would not be
leaving prematurely after all: a rally in February in Vienna, in
which more than 200,000 Austrians protested the new government, had
obliged him to rethink his departure, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And at least one report of a canceled corporate convention was
premature. In February, Vienna newspapers reported that Novell, the
American software company, had canceled a five-day convention at
the Austria Center convention hall; city officials lamented the
loss of about $5 million. But Novell denied the report, saying that
Vienna was still one of four European cities being considered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is disruption,'' Draxler said, ``but not to the extent
we expected.'' In Europe, she said, the strongest reactions were in
Belgium, France and Portugal. Belgian school authorities quickly
ordered school ski trips to Austria canceled, and the foreign
minister, Louis Michel, made his widely quoted statement that it
would be immoral to ski in Austria this winter.
</P>
<P>
   In reaction, the Austrian secretary of state for tourism, Mares
Rossmann, a political ally of Haider's, appealed to Austrians to
boycott Belgian chocolate _ prompting Belgian youths who took part
in the anti-government demonstration in Vienna in February to hand
out chocolates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some travel agents in the United States and elsewhere have
detected a shift away from Austria. ``Our bookings are a little
more mixed than usual,'' said Julia Ann Liantonio, spokeswoman for
the Euro Lloyd travel agency in New York, which specializes in
trips to Central Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While Austria remains the agency's most popular ski destination,
she said, bookings to Switzerland and Germany are up. But Germany
is drawing more attention than usual this year because of the
Oberammergau Passion Play beginning in May and Expo 2000, beginning
in Hanover in June. ``It could be a coincidence,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian travel industry is responding. The Vienna Tourist
Board, said Draxler, has written to 4,000 travel agencies
worldwide, assuring them that Vienna is a hospitable place to
visit. American travel agents were invited to a reception at the
Waldorf-Astoria in New York early this month featuring the Vienna
Boys Choir and the Salzburg Puppet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   On its Web site, the board has posted a message saying it is
``quite aware that our country carries the burden of a deplorable
past'' and understands international concern over the makeup of the
new government. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johannes Davoras, spokesman for Austrian Airlines, said that
despite scattered cancellations, Austrian will expand service to
the United States, inaugurating direct flights from Vienna to
Chicago and Washington next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2127EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
