<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     03-13 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NBA HOISTS A COLOSSAL AIR BALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past few years, there has been the vague sense that the
National Basketball Association had run out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Now the NBA seems to be confirming it. Not only are television
ratings down, but the league has also revealed its own internal
crisis of confidence with a misguided attempt to force microphones
and cameras on players and coaches who do not want them.
</P>
<P>
   Monday the league announced fines of $100,000 for Seattle and
Toronto because their coaches, Paul Westphal and Butch Carter,
refused to be miked last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's lockout was hardball business. This is blatant
overreaction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion by Westphal is stunning. Here is a guy known for
his conservative views, but the league has turned him into a
regular Patrick Henry. On Sunday, Westphal vowed to pay the
$100,000 himself, rather than saddle his owners, saying: ``I follow
my conscience by refusing to do less than my best during the heat
of battle. The league wants me to allow my private strategies,
insights, relationships and speech to be monitored, then eventually
owned by others.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal does not want some network official dredging up his
conversations with players that hitherto may have overheard by only
a few fans sitting nearby. Who knows, maybe some hustler in the
league would find a way to sell the sound bites over the Internet.
The league says ``trust us,'' but solid citizens like Westphal and
Carter are obviously not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept a failure of a type,'' said David Stern, the
commissioner, in a telephone interview Monday from Denver, where he
was attending a league marketing meeting but taking time to respond
to the coaches' insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were all on the same page on this. We are in a
new generation that is used to being interactive. We want our fans
to be as close as the people in the $1,200 seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Russ Granik, the deputy commissioner, noted that since December
the league has been miking coaches and players who volunteered.
Granik also said that the league planned to put a camera in the
locker room at halftime for no more than 15 to 30 seconds ``just to
show the players arriving.''
</P>
<P>
   There is concern among coaches and players, however, that the
league's entertainment division, run by Adam Silver, is gaining
power from the basketball wing. Whether that is true or not, it
isn't hard to imagine the forces of interaction whispering into
Stern's ear: ``Listen, nobody cares about our players. Michael
Jordan doesn't even show up for his new job in Washington. We've
got to do something. Nascar is putting cameras in its stock cars.
Professional wrestling is more popular than we are. We're competing
against lowlifes like Jerry Springer and get-rich-quick quiz shows.
Basketball is boring. We need some buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   For all that, Stern and Granik should have anticipated the
response from their basketball people. Coaches still have the right
to snarl at players, who still have the right to snap right back,
without the league canning sound bites. Stern insisted that coaches
can always turn off the mike ``if they have something they don't
want to get out,'' but it doesn't sound that simple to Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent the last two and a half years earning the respect of
the guys in that locker room. I can't afford to lose their
respect,'' Carter said, worrying that some kind of verbal exchange
``could do a ton of damage to a young coach like myself.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing wrong with miking a coach or a referee who
wants to be miked. It was fun when that old ham Tommy Lasorda
turned on his clean vocabulary for the viewers, or the hockey
referee Kerry Fraser told a captain that his options were either a
goon or a skater serving a penalty, ``Personally, it's a
no-brainer.'' Granik pointed out that, with all the sensitive
electronic gear at courtside, we already hear plenty. So why pick a
fight with the talent?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our coaches are comfortable with being miked,'' said
Michael H. Goldberg, the executive director of the National
Basketball Coaches Association Monday. ``But if a coach honestly
believes his performance is impacted, he shouldn't have to wear a
mike. I'm not sure the owners have thought this through.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe they did. Some of the new owners are instant
millionaires via the Internet, and know there are fortunes to be
made marketing snippets of information and sound and image. Bird
and Magic and Michael don't count anymore. Now the league plans to
continue threatening coaches every Sunday for $100,000 a shot,
essentially screaming to the world, ``It's even worse than you
imagined.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
