<SLUG> BC-YAHOO-YAHOO </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Yahoo Goes Live Online With Own Finance Show  &HT;     By Verne Kopytoff 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Departing from a tradition of relying on other companies to create
content for its Internet portal, Yahoo yesterday launched its own
Web finance show that will allow users to see live interviews and
news reports about business.
<P>
   The show, called ``Yahoo FinanceVision,'' will be broadcast
eight hours a day, from 6 a.m. to 2 p.m. PST, Monday through Friday
on Yahoo's Web site. The programming will mimic cable television
financial news with company profiles and on-air hosts conducting
live interviews of corporate executives and analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The show will primarily be done out of studios in New York at
the major stock exchanges and from a studio near the company
headquarters in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to count this as a major departure for
Yahoo,'' said Robert Sterling, an Internet analyst for New York
market research company Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``FinanceVision'' is a rare example of Yahoo creating
its own content and a milestone in the company's entry into Web
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling said the show appears to be aimed at office workers who
have high-speed Internet access. The show's chatty and informal
interviews, he said, appears to be aimed at a younger audience.
Viewers can e-mail questions to guests during live interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Mallet, president and chief executive of Yahoo, was more
muted in assesing ``FinanceVision.'' While he called the show
``dynamic'' and a great convenience to the public, he said the show
represents ``evolutionary, not revolutionary change'' for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the content, Mallet said, comes from Yahoo's partners
like TheStreet.com, the online financial site, and Business Week.
He said Yahoo is merely providing a new way to distribute the
information that those companies create by offering links to their
articles and interviewing their reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mallet added that Yahoo is considering launching other original
broadcast shows but would not say what topics they would cover.
Charlene Li, an Internet analyst with Forrester Research, predicted
that one of the shows will focus on sports.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Verne Kopytoff at verne &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
