<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-ETRADE_ </SLUG>
 SF CHRON  
 E-Trade Expands Services  &HT;     By Carolyn Said 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
E-Trade Group is getting physical.
<P>
   The online broker and bank bought ATM operator Card Capture
Services yesterday for an undisclosed amount and plans to convert
many of CCS's 8,500 ATMs to E-Trade-branded financial kiosks.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the kiosks will let E-Trade banking customers do
simple transactions such as making deposits. Eventually, the
machines will let customers access their brokerage accounts and
even make trades.
</P>
<P>
   The kiosks will give E-Trade, the second-largest online broker,
a way to cross-market its various financial services and a physical
presence to help in its competition with leading online broker
Charles Schwab, which has more than 300 branch offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lets us create an environment where you have both high
tech and high touch,'' said Mitchell Caplan, chief banking officer
of E-Trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area, where E-Trade has ``a huge number of customers for
both the bank and the brokerage,'' is a ``completely logical choice
for the first machines,'' Caplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Converting the ATMs to handle E-Trade banking will would &LR; 
 &LR; happen within 90 days, Caplan said; the brokerage capabilities
will follow within months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This provides more ubiquity. You have to give (customers) the
opportunity to transact whichever way they prefer,'' said Dan
Burke, senior analyst at Gomez Advisors in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   CCS is the largest independent operator of ATMs in the United
States and also has machines in Canada and Mexico. The Oregon
company operates 900 ATMs in California, 300 of them in Northern
California. Its model is to sell ATM terminals to stores, such as
Chevron, Safeway and Rite-Aid, and then sign a long-term contract
to maintain them and process transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held CCS last year earned $4.4 million on revenues of
$72 million.
</P>
<P>
   Menlo Park's E-Trade moved into banking with its June
acquisition of Virginia's Telebanc, the nation's largest
Internet-based bank, for $1.8 billion in stock. It plans to rename
the enterprise E-Trade Bank this month, Caplan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a problem for online banking because customers can't
make a deposit,'' said William Wong, vice president of research at
Josephthal &AMP; Co. in New York. ``They don't want to mail the check
in _ it's not timely. That's true for the brokerage business as
well _ if you want to open an account or add funds, you don't want
to have to mail a check in.''
</P>
<P>
   Caplan said E-Trade was attracted by CCS's ability to update its
ATMs remotely from a central location. The firm's technology allows
it to easily add new features and services to ATMs, as well as
deliver targeted coupons and advertisements to its entire network,
certain regions or individual machines.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Grana, CCS chief executive and president, said he expects
merchants to welcome the idea of converting their ATMs to E-Trade
machines. ``By replacing an ATM that just dispenses $20 bills with
a financial kiosk, the retailer is offering a whole new suite of
products and services to customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another move into brick and mortar, E-Trade is planning to
set up a walk-in office on Manhattan's Madison Avenue by the end of
the year, The Chronicle reported last month. But sources said the
store will serve as a high-profile branding device, rather than the
first in a chain of storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers think E-Trade still needs to venture further into
the world of ``stores with doors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they really want to make hay, they have to set up branch
offices,'' said Brook Newcomb, senior analyst with Forrester
Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``A lot of people still have an
inclination to do business with someone who has a physical
office.''
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade fell 75 cents, to $25.75, in Nasdaq trading yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Carolyn Said at csaid &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
