<HEADER>
A5867 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ODDTAX-ODDTAX_SFCHRON     03-13 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ODDTAX-ODDTAX </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Vendors Attack Transient Merchant Tax, License  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Southern California entrepreneur Mike Frankovich was incensed when
he heard he would have to pay $500 to the city of San Francisco for
a license to sell novelty goods at a trade show in the city, as
well as a 10 percent tax on any revenue above $5,000 in sales.
<P>
   ``San Francisco is gouging vendors who come to the city for just
a few days,'' he fumed. , &LR; ``This is unfair; I already pay state
sales taxes and have a California seller's permit.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, San Francisco Supervisor Mark Leno proposed a measure
to suspend the city's ``transient merchants'' code, which has been
on the books for 40 years or more. Originally, the specified fee
and taxes were designed to make traveling salesmen, like
shirtmakers shirt-makers  &LR; and art dealers who sell out of a hotel
room for a few days, pay something back to the city.
</P>
<P>
   The little-known tax was not seriously enforced for many years.
But when Susan Leal took over as city treasurer and saw the rules
on the books, she began enforcing them in 1999. And not just in
hotels, but at Moscone Center and the Bill Graham Civic Auditorium.
That brought howls from visiting trade show exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   Most big conferences and conventions, such as those that host
architects, dermatologists and geneticists, don't sell goods over
the conference table. But the few who do were often outraged.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco International Gift Fair holds two large
conventions each year in San Francisco, and President Michael Dean
said hitting trade show exhibitors with special fees in a few
cities like San Francisco and Seattle is ``a real minus.'' Besides
the cost, he said, ``It's an administrative nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 500 exhibitors who sold hardware and software at
last year's MacWorld Expo at Moscone Center also attacked the local
levies.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco city and business leaders have been listening.
They definitely don't want to kill the goose that lays a fortune in
eggs. The convention business last year contributed more than $2
billion to the local economy, according to the San Francisco
Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The city benefits directly in various ways. For example, it
collects rent of 25 cents per square foot per day at Moscone
Center. If the space were filled all the time, it would generate
$91 per foot per year, or more than $5 million a year for the
600,000-square-foot facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other California city imposes a transient merchants' tax,
and that posed a competitive disadvantage,'' said John Marks,
president of the San Francisco Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau. ``We
don't want someone to be dissuaded from booking San Francisco
because of the perception we have an archaic tax that is not
imposed elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno said the transient merchants tax ``is definitely a
stumbling block to holding a convention in San Francisco.'' His
proposal to suspend it will likely be heard by the supervisors'
Small Business Committee in a month. Then a public hearing would be
scheduled, with the suspension of the transient merchants tax
possibly coming as early as May.
</P>
<P>
   Little opposition to Leno's proposal is likely. Not only is the
levy a political and business embarrassment, it is costly to
administer and generates little money for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, San Francisco generated a piddling $41,234.38 from 88
transient merchants transactions. Leal, who maintains that her
office is ``neutral'' on the tax, said she began enforcing it
simply because it is the law.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say the measure is hard to enforce, especially
the 10 percent tax on gross receipts over $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to rely on sellers' honesty and integrity,'' said tax
collector Richard Sullivan. ``We don't want to send people back to
Minnesota or New York to verify sales figures.''
</P>
<P>
   While visiting merchants may soon be getting some tax relief, no
immediate tax break is contemplated for local businesses. In
addition to state and federal taxes, they pay a 1.5 percent payroll
tax and gross receipts tax ranging from 1.23 percent to 3 percent
of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
