<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5868 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NASDAQ-NASDAQ_SFCHRON     03-13 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-NASDAQ </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 All Aboard the Nasdaq Express  &HT;     By Arthur M. Louis 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
For the past couple of years, experts have been warning that the
technology-laden Nasdaq stock market is grossly overvalued, and
that you would be foolhardy to risk your money there.
<P>
   If you followed that advice, chances are you still are driving a
Ford Taurus, while your foolhardy neighbor is tooling around town
in a flaming red Porsche Carrera.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Nasdaq composite index roared past the 5,000
milestone for the first time, just 10 weeks after passing 4,000 and
18 weeks after it topped 3,000. Although the highly volatile index
plunged below 5,000 yesterday, finishing at 4907.24, it still has
gained 21 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the other major indexes have performed poorly.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, far less heavily weighted with
tech stocks than the Nasdaq, has skidded 6 percent since year
- &LR; end. The Dow Jones industrial average, with an even smaller tech
contingent, has tumbled 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you had invested $50,000 two years ago in the average Nasdaq
stock, you would be sitting on nearly $140,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Some big-name Nasdaq stocks have performed far better than that.
A $50,000 investment in Cisco Systems two years ago would be worth
more than $300,000 now; in Qualcomm, $1.1 million; in JDS Uniphase,
nearly $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   It's natural for tradition-minded marketwatchers to denounce
this sort of explosive price action as a `'bubble'' or ``mania.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite is selling at nearly 400 times earnings for
the latest 12 months, while tradition holds that multiples greater
than 40 should be considered lofty, if not vertiginous.
</P>
<P>
   But when the phenomenal price increases continue week after
week, month after month, year after year, making a lot of people
rich, you have to consider the possibility that what's happening
has some substance to it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, quite a few market watchers have capitulated to the
trend and are publicly exclaiming that perhaps the whole thing
actually makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   While that may be an ominous sign _ once the market reaches
unanimity, prices often move violently in the opposite direction _
the arguments for a continuing Nasdaq bonanza are, at least,
rational. Whether they turn out to be correct remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The principal argument is that today's price-earnings ratios are
irrelevant because nobody can gauge the future earnings of
America's booming high-tech juggernaut. By the same token, nobody
can tell for certain which companies will be tomorrow's winners and
which _ if any _ will be losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these companies have very uncertain earnings futures _
it is very difficult to know what earnings will be in 15 to 20
years,'' says Lynn Reaser, chief economist of the Bank of America
Asset Management Group.
</P>
<P>
   For some stocks, perhaps 400 times earnings today will seem like
a bargain tomorrow, some investors reason. It may even be that
almost any price is reasonable when you are buying technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the future can be fully discounted when we don't
know what the future is,'' says Alfred Goldman, market strategist
with A.G. Edwards &AMP; Son, in St. Louis. ``Don't argue with a
well-established trend. If you want to play, you've got to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks _ collectively known nowadays as the ``new
economy'' _ also are supposed to be less vulnerable to
interest-rate increases than the old-economy stocks that make up
the bulk of the other major market averages.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big issue now because the Federal Reserve has raised
interest rates by a full percentage point since mid-1999 and is
expected to raise them significantly more starting as early as this
month in its crusade to cool the economy and forestall inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Old-economy companies borrow more heavily than new-economy
companies, and that tends to crimp their earnings more. New-economy
companies generally finance their expansion with stock rather than
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Acuff, market strategist for Salomon Smith Barney in
New York, points out that when the Fed is particularly hawkish on
inflation, companies with substantial annual growth in unit sales
tend to fare best, because they don't need higher prices to
increase profits.
</P>
<P>
   Most technology companies fit that description, Acuff observes,
while old-economy companies do not.
</P>
<P>
   However, San Francisco money manager Stewart J. Pillette
predicts that tech companies will suffer eventually if old-economy
companies get squeezed by higher rates and cut back their purchases
of services and equipment. ``The old economy buys the new economy's
stuff,'' Pillette observes.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates still aren't high enough to entice investors to
take substantial amounts of money out of the stock market and
invest it in fixed-income securities. The 30-year U.S. Treasury
bond, for example, is yielding only a bit more than 6 percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, many investors simply are taking money out of
old-economy stocks and buying new-economy stocks because that is
where the action is.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Bakar, director of research with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist, a major
underwriter of high-tech securities, insists that ``over the longer
term, Nasdaq will continue to outperform the Dow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bakar concedes that ``things don't go up forever _ you can get
corrections of 10 percent to 15 percent in a short period of
time.'' But he adds: ``People will then step back in and say the
fundamentals haven't changed, there is still huge potential out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Danville retirement planner Richard DelMonte acknowledges that
he has been continually amazed by the Nasdaq skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``But five years from now, I expect it to be a lot higher than
it is now,'' he says. ``It could grow faster than the Dow for the
next 10 years. It is a lot more indicative of the dynamism in our
economy than the Dow or S&AMP;P.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Schlossberg, an economist with Wells Capital Management,
concedes that there is ``a downside risk'' in the Nasdaq market
because ``valuations are so high.''
</P>
<P>
   But he won't bet against further strong price gains, because the
tech story is just too compelling. ``We are in the midst of an
information-based revolution,'' he observes.
</P>
<P>
   As hot as technology's prospects may be, Bank of America's
Reaser advises caution and discrimination. Don't assume that every
tech stock will continue to soar, she observes. Be picky.
</P>
<P>
   ``One should look at the companies to make certain they have a
solid business plan, some earnings prospects and are not vulnerable
to competition or product obsolescence,'' Reaser says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't just assume that because they have gone up 10 percent in
the past week, they will go up 50 percent in the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Arthur Louis at alouis &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
