<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FLORIDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SEES OPENING IN FLORIDA, AND WORKS TO WIN THE STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Six months ago, most polls showed that Vice President Al
Gore had no hope of winning Florida in a general election over Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas. Not only was Gore unpopular, but Bush had
an ace in the hole _ his brother, Jeb, the state's popular
governor, and his political organization.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Gore is even with, if not leading, George Bush in most
national polls, and that is trickling down. Jeb Bush is running
into local political squalls. And Gore is suddenly thinking that
Florida, a conservative swing state, may be up for grabs in
November.
</P>
<P>
   While Florida has voted for a Democratic presidential candidate
only twice in the last 30 years, one of those times was in 1996,
when it gave the edge to Bill Clinton _ and his running mate, Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Monday marked Gore's seventh visit to Florida in the last 12
months, and he is coming back Tuesday night to Tallahassee to watch
the primary returns from Florida and five other Southern states.
Ten days ago Gore visited Jacksonville, where he discussed
education, and he was here Monday discussing health care, Medicare
and Social Security, crucial subjects in a state where one in five
people is at least 65 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to visit so often, and to watch the returns here,
is a strategic one. Gore is going to contest this state and devote
time and money here. If nothing else it tells Bush that he needs to
earn, rather than take for granted, a victory in Florida, which has
25 electoral votes, the nation's fourth-largest total.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the frisson of Gore's play for the state is the
speculation that one possible choice for a vice presidential
running mate is Sen. Bob Graham of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton carried the state in '96 and that's the reason
they're there,'' Whit Ayres, a Republican pollster who specializes
in the South, said of the Gore campaign. ``They're starting with
those states that Clinton carried at least once. It becomes a lot
more competitive if he puts someone like Bob Graham on the ticket.
But it is in play.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, visiting the Jackson Memorial Medical Center here with
Gore Monday, brushed aside questions from reporters about whether
he would accept the No. 2 slot. But while introducing Gore to an
audience of 150 health-care professionals, Graham said Florida
would be more than a battleground state. ``It's going to be a
foundation for the Gore victory and the Gore administration,''
Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   A Mason-Dixon poll conducted last week showed Bush with an
8-point lead over Gore in Florida with either Ross Perot or Pat
Buchanan running on the Reform Party ticket. The margin of error
was 6 points.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Coker, managing director of the Mason-Dixon poll, said that
the gap between Bush and Gore had closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My read is that Gore shouldn't write off Florida,'' Coker
said. ``It shouldn't be a key component to his Electoral College
majority. But he could win it if Bush starts to tank nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush said that he and his brother were ready and confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to win,'' the Florida governor said of his brother
on Sunday. ``He's got lots of support. The state will be
competitive. We're not going to take it for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's supporters speak of a competitive attitude, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992 Bill Clinton gave up on Florida, withdrew his
campaign, didn't advertise and ended up losing the state by a
narrow margin,'' Graham said. ``Clinton will say now that the
biggest mistake he made in '92 was that decision on Florida. Six
months ago, Al Gore was getting the same advice _ spend your time
and resources elsewhere. I think now, clearly, Florida is
winnable.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats see an opportunity to undermine George Bush's support
because of some dissatisfaction with Jeb Bush on affirmative
action. He has proposed a plan to abolish set-asides and
preferences for minorities in admissions to public colleges and in
state government hiring, although he would guarantee that the top
20 percent of all high school graduates could go to state colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hispanics are strongly behind Jeb on affirmative action,''
Coker said. ``They have prospered in the state without those
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Butterworth, the state attorney general, who leads Gore's
campaign in Florida, said that another problem for the vice
president would be a perception by some voters that the state would
benefit more under a Bush administration because of the brotherhood
bond. Butterworth said it would be his job to convey that Florida
had benefited under the Clinton administration and would continue
to do well under a Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that Gore was addressing the main issues that
would appeal to Florida's independents and moderates who may have
strayed to Sen. John McCain of Arizona earlier this year when
George Bush tacked to the ideological right.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Bush became the conservative, you saw the shifts among
Florida's centrist voters _ women, moderate Democrats and those in
metro areas,'' Coker said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is trying to capture those voters with a focus on issues
like health care, education and gun control. On Monday Graham said
that Gore had offered a detailed health-care plan and that Bush had
not, and he drew sly attention to a perceived Bush weakness by
suggesting that Gore has a stronger command of policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might say his program is actually written down in
understandable language on pieces of paper,'' Graham said. ``We're
still waiting for a set of signals from cyberspace as to what the
other candidate's health-care program is going to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
