<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Reluctantly Supports German to Head IMF
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton told Germany's chancellor that he would accept
Horst Koehler as the new managing director of the International
Monetary Fund, ending a heated diplomatic contest over who would
lead the institution that battles global financial crises.
Clinton's reluctant support virtually assures that Koehler, a
former German finance official who is now president of the European
Bank for Reconstruction and Development, will be named to the post.
</P>
<P>
   China Accord Text to Be Released
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to pressure from Congress, the Clinton administration
plans to release the full text of an agreement it negotiated with
China on its entry to the World Trade Organization, reversing a
decision to keep it classified until China completed it talks with
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   GM and Fiat in Cooperation Deal
</P>
<P>
   General Motors and Fiat of Italy announced a deal to cooperate
broadly in Europe and Latin America in purchasing and the
manufacture of heavy components like motors and gear shifts. The
deal will give GM a 20 percent stake in Fiat's auto division, worth
$2.3 billion, in exchange for a 5.15 percent Fiat stake in GM. The
deal gives Fiat the chance to sell the remaining 80 percent of its
car division to GM in three and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Drops Sharply; Dow Rises
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index suffered its biggest loss in more
than three weeks, sliding 141.38 points, or 2.8 percent, to
4,907.24. The Dow Jones industrial average gained 18.31 points, to
9,947.13. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 11.45 points,
to 1,383.62.
</P>
<P>
   Another Big Bank Merger in Japan
</P>
<P>
   Sanwa Bank of Japan is negotiating to join the merger of Asahi
Bank and Tokai Bank, executives close to the deal said. The
combination would create the third-largest bank in the world, with
assets of $979 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Aetna Plummet 9 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed investors drove shares of Aetna down $5.25, or 9
percent, to $50.75, after Aetna rejected an offer to hold
discussions on a tentative takeover bid valued at $9.9 billion.
WellPoint Health Networks and the ING Group of insurance and
financial services companies. ING said that it was still interested
in buying the nonhealth business of Aetna, which has also attracted
other potential bidders. WellPoint bowed out.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft to Back Keyword System
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is expected to announce that it is backing a keyword
system that enables Internet users to navigate the Web without
typing in the cumbersome addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to Nasdaq Conversion
</P>
<P>
   Alan Davidson, a board member of the National Association of
Securities Dealers, said that he would urge brokerage firms to vote
against the plan to convert its Nasdaq stock market into a
for-profit company. The remarks by Davidson suggest that he will be
pitted against the NASD board in a monthlong campaign for the votes
of small member firms.
</P>
<P>
   $9.3 Billion Software Merger
</P>
<P>
   I2 Technologies, a software manufacturer, plans to buy Aspect
Development, a competing maker of business-to-business electronic
commerce software, for $9.3 billion in the largest merger ever in
the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur Ross to Leave Rothschild
</P>
<P>
   Wilbur L. Ross Jr., one of the best-known investors in troubled
corporations, said he was leaving the investment bank Rothschild to
form his own investment firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
