<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FIAT-GM-NYT &LR;      03-13 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIAT-GM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SEE TAKEOVER OF FIAT IN DETAILS OF DEAL WITH GM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TURIN, Italy _ General Motors and Fiat announced a strategic
cooperation deal Monday that some analysts called a prelude to a GM
takeover of the Italian industrial giant's troubled automotive
operation. Fiat officials stressed that they expected their
business to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement provides for both partners to collaborate broadly
in Europe and Latin America in the buying and manufacturing of
heavy components like motors and gear shifts. It will give GM a 20
percent stake in Fiat's auto division, worth $2.3 billion, in
exchange for a 5.15 percent share in GM for Fiat.
</P>
<P>
   It also will give Fiat the option to sell the remaining 80
percent of its car division to GM in three and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the deal would bring both companies savings after
the third year of $1.2 billion annually, divided 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits for Fiat are a capital injection by GM, in which
Fiat becomes the largest single investor, and the steady hand of GM
in helping Fiat expand markets, most notably in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   For GM, the advantages appeared to lie in gaining access to
Fiat's small-car technology, with the possibility of acquiring all
of Fiat's car business.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat officials, for their part, said the deal gave Fiat the
opportunity to continue its independent path. Paolo Fresco, Fiat's
chairman, said the agreement assured the ``maintenance of
decision-making control'' in Fiat's hands. Had Fiat wished to sell
the auto business, he said, it would have done so already.
</P>
<P>
   But some experts said the deal really only made sense as a
precursor to a full takeover of Fiat's auto business by GM.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the end of the game,'' said John Lawson, an auto
industry analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Valerio Castronovo, an Italian industrial historian and author
of a history of Fiat, called the deal a ``betrothal, that will one
day become a marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate effects of the deal will be the creation of
two joint ventures: one for buying; the other for developing and
building motors and related components. But the companies said they
would also be studying ways to save money by allowing their finance
arms to cooperate and by developing joint platforms, global
communications systems and the introduction of some Fiat-built cars
into the United States, including the Alfa Romeo and Maserati.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat now sells only its Ferrarri sports cars in the United
States, a market it effectively vacated in 1995, when it sold its
last Alfa Romeo models there.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat will bring its worldwide capacity into the components
venture, and GM will bring its operations in Europe and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Fiat executives said the companies expected that the next
generation of GM and Fiat small cars would share a single platform
by about the middle of the decade. Fiat expects to show an Alfa
Romeo sports model at the Detroit auto show in 2001 and begin to
sell it through GM dealers thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   For Fiat, Italy's biggest corporation, an alliance with a
foreign partner has been seen for many months as essential for
long-term survival. Its car business, historically volatile, has
been losing money and market share in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest in a consolidation of the global auto
industry, that was given a push forward last year by the merger of
Daimler Benz and Chrysler. But in announcing the deal at Fiat's
headquarters here, both companies emphasized that they saw the
future more in terms of networks of strategic alliances than in the
formation of globe-girdling empires.
</P>
<P>
   The global auto business, Freco said, ``is moving toward a world
of networks, not empires,''
</P>
<P>
   John F. Smith Jr., GM's chairman and chief executive, praised
the deal as a ``historic alliance'' between two of the world's
oldest car makers. But he said it was the latest in a string of
industrial alliances in which GM has taken an equity stake in its
partner, including older agreements with Isuzu and Suzuki, and a
more recent link with Subaru.
</P>
<P>
   As laid out by Fiat executives, Monday's deal signaled an effort
to find a middle path between a full sell-off of the auto business
and complete independence.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Fiat group reported a 45 percent drop in profit
last year, the car division, which for the first time ever
accounted for less than half of the group's roughly $50 billion in
revenue, returned to profitability after a year of losses. In the
last quarter of 1999, operating profit rose to $569 billion,
against a loss of $57 billion the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Fiat's car unit, producing fewer than three million cars a
year, lacks the global power of GM, Ford or Toyota and faces
powerful new alliances like DaimlerChrysler and the combination of
Renault and Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Fiat executives emphasized that the link with GM did not
mean Fiat was withdrawing from cars. Paolo Cantarella, Fiat's chief
executive, said the companies were ``cost-side allied, revenue-side
competitors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
