<HEADER>
A5893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-PLAYERS-ROBBED-NY     03-13 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PLAYERS-ROBBED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS' MINOR LEAGUERS TANGLE WITH ARMED ROBBERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Aaron Miles plays second base in the Houston
Astros' minor league system, but he was forced to take on another
role Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Miles, five other minor league players for the Astros and a
woman were victims of an armed robbery at their motel late Sunday
night, and he wound up struggling with one of two robbers for a gun
before the police crashed through a window and shot and wounded the
intruder.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman, who was shot six times, was listed in critical
condition at Orlando Regional Medical Center Monday. Joe Brown, a
hospital spokesman, said the gunman had not yet been identified.
</P>
<P>
   The other robber escaped, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Miles was bitten on the back of his neck in his tussle with the
robber, while the other five players and the woman were uninjured,
the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros declined to make any of the players available for
comment Monday, and efforts to reach them at the motel were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   But Tim Purpura, the Astros' assistant general manager, said,
``It was an unfortunate situation, but we were lucky that
everything came out the way it did.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred at a Holiday Inn on Route 192, a main road
in Kissimmee, several miles from the Astros' spring training
complex. About 80 of the Astros' 110 minor league players stay at
the motel.
</P>
<P>
   Miles was in Room 252. The other five players and a female
friend of one of the them were in the next room, 254, with the door
open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a dormitory situation,'' Purpura said, explaining
why the door was open. ``They're real comfortable with each other.
In one room they're watching TV. In another room they're playing
Play Station, just hanging out. It's a real community
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said the two robbers burst into Room 254 between
10:30 and 11 p.m. Using plastic ties that lock when put in place,
the two men tied up the five players and the 23-year-old woman, put
duct tape on their mouths, ransacked the room and bundled together
money and other items of value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the two gunmen get what they want, they leave the room,''
Commander Fran Iwanski of the Kissimmee Police Department said.
``The men inside are easily able to free themselves and lock the
door. One of the men picks up a phone to warn his friend next door.
No one answers the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point the guy tried to call 911. For some reason, it
didn't go though. He calls downstairs to the desk, who in turn
calls police and we respond.''
</P>
<P>
   The two robbers had moved to Room 252, where they burst in and
found Miles alone.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Jeff Bogen arrived at the motel a few minutes after 11
p.m. and was on the second-floor balcony when, he said, a man
emerged from Room 252. The man leaped over the rail, the officer
said, and a semiautomatic handgun fell from his waist or jacket.
Bogen said he lost sight of the man, who escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Room 252, meanwhile, Miles saw a chance to gain control
of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The player felt he had a chance to maneuver the gun out of the
hand of the gunman and was able to get his hand on the gun,''
Purpura said. ``He tried to steer the gun away from himself and get
control, and they went back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Houston minor league player said that while Miles held
on to the gun with both hands, the gunman repeatedly punched him
with his free hand. At one point in the struggle, Purpura said,
Miles got the robber against the wall, knocked him to the floor and
was on top of him. But the man still held a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Iwanski said the police officers who were standing outside the
room could hear the struggle. When they heard Miles yell for them
to come into the room, two officers, Peter Szlezak and Glenn Ford,
broke the large window next to the door and climbed through.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they get in,'' Iwanski said, ``they see them still
struggling on the ground. The officers yell for the gunman to give
up and release the gun. He won't release the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers began shooting, wounding the robber, who was taken
by helicopter to Orlando Regional, where he underwent four hours of
surgery. Miles, 23, received a tetanus shot and antibiotics for his
neck bite and was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the mental trauma of it, they're all in great
shape,'' Purpura said.
</P>
<P>
   The other five players were the infielders Morgan Ensberg, 24,
and Keith Ginter, 23; the outfielders Derek Nicholson, 23, and Eric
Cole, 24; and catcher Michael Rose, 23.
</P>
<P>
   Police identified the woman as Alicia Szczerba of Valrico, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Purpura said the team's minor league players have stayed at the
Holiday Inn for seven springs. He said the team had no problem with
the motel, but he also said that both the motel and the Astros
would increase security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a crime of opportunity,'' he said. ``They saw
some rooms open and they were prepared to do what they did. Whether
it was our guys or someone else, they were ready to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
