<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-MARINO-RETIRES14-     03-13 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MARINO-RETIRES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marino holds back tears as he makes retirement official
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ It was one thing to make the decision, to
formulate the words in his head. It was another to actually have
them come out of his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Dan Marino did it was last Thursday. He was
sitting in the kitchen of his Weston home, having breakfast with
his wife, Claire, when he asked his parents, visiting from
Pittsburgh, to join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, 'It is time; it is time to retire,''' Marino
recalled Monday. ``It wasn't a big deal or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that moment wasn't a big deal. But the second time Marino
said the words _ at 10:08 a.m. Monday _ it certainly was.
</P>
<P>
   Fans stood across the street from the Dolphins' training
facility, waving signs, wearing his number and chanting his name.
The players' parking lot was filled with 13 television satellite
trucks, ready to beam his words all over the country. And inside
the auditorium, more than 150 journalists waited along with former
Dolphins coach Don Shula and former teammates _ from Mark Clayton
to Zach Thomas _ for Marino to enter and repeat what he had said to
his family four days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Not a big deal?
</P>
<P>
   Marino knew better. He spent parts of two days trying to write
his speech. And Sunday night, as he pictured himself delivering it,
he kept telling his wife, ``I can't cry.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. But it was a struggle from the moment he stepped to
the lectern, pulled out his notes, took a deep breath and, without
wasting any time, made it official. After two decades of racking up
numbers that looked like they belong on a car odometer _ 61,361
yards and 420 touchdown passes _ he was calling it quits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank you all for coming,'' he began. ``After 17
years, I would like to announce my retirement from the Miami
Dolphins. After playing this game of football for most of my life,
this was an extremely difficult situation. But I know I made the
right decision for me and my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his eight-minute prepared speech, Marino's voice
sounded hoarse, as if it were on the verge of cracking. He coughed.
He cleared his throat. He bit his lip. He tried to avoid looking at
his family, knowing that if he caught a glimpse of his wife, who
kept wiping away tears with a tissue, he also might lose composure.
</P>
<P>
   When he thanked his five children, he caught his 10-year-old son
smiling, laughed and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not easy, Joe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not much about the end was easy. He didn't get the fairy tale
ending like John Elway or Michael Jordan. He didn't get his
championship ring. Instead, he spent the final season dealing with
the most frightening injury of his career _ nerve damage in his
neck that prevented him from throwing a football _ and the doubts
of everyone from the media to fans to his head coach.
</P>
<P>
   It ended not in glory, but with a 62-7 loss to Jacksonville in
the second round of the playoffs. And it was the two months after
that game _ the time spent trying to decide whether to retire,
continue with a team that clearly no longer wanted him on the field
for anything other than tribute ceremonies, or head elsewhere _
that Marino on Monday called the toughest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really struggled with this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Steelers called him to talk about coming back to
his hometown. The Minnesota Vikings wooed him, not only offering a
one-year contract but also offering to allow him to fly home after
every game and return on Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   He almost accepted that offer, he said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times I told Claire we were going,'' he said, ``and
two hours later I said, 'No, I don't think I can go.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Marino decided it was time to retire _ a decision he
insists won't change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not play football again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Being close to his wife and children was a factor. But the main
reason, he explained, was the signal he was getting from his
38-year-old body _ especially the legs that are covered with scars
from six knee surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kept coming back to how my legs felt during last season,
going through the neck injury, not knowing whether I was going to
be able to throw the football,'' he said. ``Claire and the kids
were great. They wanted me to play, to be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The day Hank Aaron announced his retirement, baseball's home-run
champ said: ``You can only milk a cow for so long, then you're left
holding the pail.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino could relate Monday. The NFL's long-ball king _ he threw
78 more touchdowns than anyone else in league history _ decided he
had squeezed as much out of his body as he could. He said that
although he never won a title, he felt lucky to have played the
game for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many people have an opportunity to spend 17 years of their
life doing what they truly love to do,'' he said. ``And I stand
before you today, I can say that I had been blessed with a career
greater than I could have ever imagined ... I am going to miss
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As he glanced at his notes and rattled off a list of things he
will miss, Marino's voice sounded strained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to miss everything about it,'' he said. ``I am
going to miss the friends that I made over this time. I am going to
miss all the good times that we have had together. But, most of
all, I am going to miss Sunday afternoons.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part of the day might have come after his speech _
after he finished thanking everyone from Shula to the equipment
staff, but conspicuously missing former Dolphins coach Jimmy
Johnson and current coach Dave Wannstedt _ when Dolphins owner
Wayne Huizenga stepped to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga spent the past few weeks trying to accomplish a
difficult task: pave the way for Wannstedt to start his tenure with
a new quarterback, but make sure a rift didn't develop between the
franchise and its most beloved player.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly into his speech Monday, he made an apology of sorts _
not for what happened the past two months but for what didn't
happen in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest disappointment that I have as a team owner and as
a longtime Dolphin fan is that you never won the Super Bowl,'' said
Huizenga, who bought the team before the 1994 season. ``There is no
one more deserving of winning that championship than you, and I
just wish that we could have gotten that for you.''
</P>
<P>
   After telling a few jokes and praising Marino for his work on
and off the field _ including the establishment of the Dan Marino
Foundation to benefit children's charities _ Huizenga then
presented Marino with some parting gifts, beyond his obvious Pro
Football Hall of Fame induction in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really is no way we can thank you for what you've
done,'' he said. ``But we can try.''
</P>
<P>
   Huizenga said that no Dolphin will ever wear No. 13 again, that
Marino will be inducted into the team's honor roll at halftime of
the first regular-season game and that a street next to the stadium
will be named after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, by the way,'' he said, ``it just might pass by the new
statue that will be erected there in your honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino knew beforehand that Huizenga might retire his number.
Still, as the owner made these gestures, Marino rocked back and
forth, repeatedly taking deep breaths. When Huizenga finished, the
men hugged and Marino returned to the lectern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' he said, his voice cracking. ``I guess we are going to
open it up for questions and answers. Not any tough ones, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino then spent the next hour patiently answering questions.
He recalled his favorite moment _ a touchdown pass to Mark Duper to
beat the New York Jets in 1985. He talked about his future, saying
he might work as a TV analyst in the near future and that one day
he could see himself following in Michael Jordan's footsteps and
becoming an owner or working in a front office.
</P>
<P>
   He only ruled out two things: playing football and coaching it.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, Marino had relaxed. He analyzed his own performance
for the day _ saying delivering that eight-minute speech was
tougher than any of the 37 fourth-quarter comebacks he led _ and
joked about what it will be like to have a statue next to Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just make sure that it's good-looking and has a nice, tight
belly,'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   There is one thing it won't have: a Super Bowl ring.
</P>
<P>
   That missing piece of jewelry, Marino said, is ``the only
reason'' he thought about going to Minnesota. He wanted to give it
one more shot. But then he thought about the inevitable shots to
his body and decided ``it is time.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he said those words, it was a big deal. Big enough to
prompt live coverage on two networks and every local affiliate. Big
enough to bring reaction from Al Gore, Jeb Bush and Bob Graham. Big
enough to make Marino _ a player known for his emotions once he
walked off the field _ struggle to keep from crying.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5897 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MRSCLINTON-FUNDRAISIN     03-13 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-FUNDRAISING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ON HOW FUND RAISING FOR MRS. CLINTON AFFECTS PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Fla., S.D., Pakistan, India)  (SUBS to clarify references to Mrs. Clinton) 
(js) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While President Clinton was engaged in an intense
debate with his advisers about whether to stop in Pakistan during
his upcoming visit to South Asia, a group of Pakistani-Americans in
New York with a keen interest in the decision raised $50,000 for
the Senate campaign of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing illegal about the Feb. 22 fund-raiser, a
$1,000-a-plate dinner of barbecued chicken kebab, spicy goat curry
and rice at a house on Staten Island. All the donors were U.S.
citizens, the organizers said. And no evidence has emerged that
Hillary Rodham Clinton, who told people at the dinner that she
hoped her husband would visit Pakistan, had influenced her
husband's decision last week to do so. A White House spokesman,
Mike Hammer, said, ``The first lady's views were not part of the
decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fund-raiser still illustrates a unique aspect of Mrs.
Clinton's candidacy: While her husband still occupies the White
House, people may seek to influence his policies by making
donations to her Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton spent more than two hours at the fund-raiser, the
organizers said, listening to the concerns of the
Pakistani-Americans, and left before the meal was served. Her hosts
were a group of Pakistani-Americans who wanted to press the case to
the first lady that her husband should visit Pakistan and that his
administration should become engaged in finding a solution to the
war in Kashmir, a territory claimed by both Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the event's organizers, Suhail Muzaffar, a businessman,
and Asim Malik, a doctor from Long Island, New York, said $50,000
was the minimum amount required before Mrs. Clinton's aides would
add the event to her schedule. The donors were primarily from the
New York metropolitan area, but some came from New Jersey and
Maryland, Malik said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clinton announced that he would stop in Pakistan for
a few hours during his visit to the region, which begins Saturday.
The decision was a difficult call because of the intense rivalry
between India and Pakistan and the strife between the two nations
over Kashmir, among other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's hosts moved the dinner to an earlier date so that
it would take place before the president's trip, organizers said.
The fund-raiser was organized by the Pakistani community on Staten
Island, and the Pakistani-American Physicians Political Action
Committee, or Pak-Pac, as it is known. Her appearance there was
first reported by newspapers in India.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it went very well, in terms of the message and the
timeliness of it, especially in terms of the president's going to
the region,'' Muzaffar said. In her remarks at the event, Muzaffar
recalled Mrs. Clinton saying, ``I would hope the president would
go'' to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, confirmed that remark
and said that she had also told the group that the president wanted
to make the stop in Pakistan. Wolfson also confirmed that the
campaign usually asks for a minimum of $50,000 in exchange for Mrs.
Clinton's appearance at a fund-raiser. Asked if Mrs. Clinton had
conveyed the views of the Pakistani-Americans to her husband,
Wolfson said, ``Everyone in the administration, including Hillary
and the president, hoped that he could go, and said that.'' Wolfson
added that Indian-American groups had also contributed to Mrs.
Clinton's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Pakistani leaders on Staten Island were working with
other ethnic leaders in the borough on a fund-raiser for Mrs.
Clinton that would address issues facing a spectrum of immigrants,
including Arabs and Africans, as well as Pakistanis, said Abdul
Rehman, who was a member of the reception committee at the dinner.
But then, with President Clinton's trip to the region approaching,
he said, the visit to Pakistan became a central focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot deny that the fact that she's the president's wife
makes a difference,'' Malik said. ``But also as a woman, she can
feel more pain for the victims of Kashmir, the women and
children,'' he added, explaining why most Pakistani-Americans are
endorsing her.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The presidential trip was not the only reason the Pakistanis
have for backing Mrs. Clinton's Senate bid, the event's organizers
said. Pakistani taxi drivers and street vendors in New York City
are generally not happy with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, her Republican
opponent, they said. Both the drivers and the vendors have been the
targets of stricter regulations under Giuliani's ``quality of
life'' efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner for Mrs. Clinton was attended by Lanny J. Davis, who
as a lobbyist for the Pakistani government urged the president to
visit the country, but Davis said he played no role in arranging
the fund-raiser. He called $50,000 a ``minor event'' compared to
the amounts Indian-Americans give to campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who was a special counsel to Clinton in the aftermath of
the 1996 Democratic fund-raising excesses, vigorously rejected any
suggestion that somehow it might be considered unseemly for the
Pakistani community to raise money for Mrs. Clinton. `` It is no
different from what Jewish, Italian or Irish-Americans do,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indian-Americans are generally better organized politically than
their Pakistani counterparts, and they lobbied against the visit to
Pakistan. Indian-Americans have given large amounts of campaign
money to a variety of lawmakers. For instance, Frank Pallone, a New
Jersey Democrat who was a founder of the India caucus, one of the
most powerful in Congress, has received tens of thousands of
dollars in campaign contributions from Indian-Americans who live
outside New Jersey. An Indian-American doctor in Florida, Zachariah
Zachariah, raised more than $500,000 from Indian-American doctors
for President Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Indians and Pakistanis have squared off before in Senate
contests, most notably four years ago in South Dakota. The
Pakistani-American community poured money into the campaign of U.S.
Rep. Tim Johnson, a Democrat, in his successful effort to oust Sen.
Larry Pressler, the Republican author of legislation that had cut
off U.S. military aid to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   But full immersion in the U.S. political game is new for most
Pakistani-Americans. ``We have never been part of the political
system,'' said Malik, of Old Westbury, N.Y. ``And very slowly,
we've realized you have to be part of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Mrs. Clinton could not stay for the fund-raiser's
dinner, she made a good impression on her hosts, Malik said,
telling them that once she was elected they should come to see her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to do that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
