<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-POPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE POPE'S APOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, March 14: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of his 21-year papacy, John Paul II has attacked
the inhumanity of communism and, more recently, the costs of
unbridled capitalism. Now, in the twilight of his career, he has
delivered a solemn apology for the errors of the Roman Catholic
Church over the last 2,000 years. The pope's act of repentance,
delivered as part of the liturgy of Sunday Mass in St. Peter's
Basilica, was a courageous and historic declaration that many of
his own cardinals and bishops opposed.
</P>
<P>
   In calling for a church-wide ``purification of memory,'' John
Paul acknowledged the mistakes and cruelty imbedded in church
history, including the Inquisition, the forced conversions of
native peoples in Africa and Latin America, and support of the
Crusades, whose victims included Jews, Muslims and members of the
Eastern Orthodox church.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul's statement not only reaches back across the centuries
to redress the wrongs of the church, but also looks ahead by
clearing the air for his successors. As long as it was burdened by
its failure to reckon with past misdeeds committed in the name of
Catholicism, the church could not fully heal its relations with
other faiths. John Paul has now made it easier to do that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the things he did not say bear note. The apology was
expressed in broad terms. It was offered on behalf of the church's
``sons and daughters,'' but not the church itself, which is
considered holy. Nor did John Paul directly address the sensitive
issue of whether past popes, cardinals and clergy _ not just
parishioners _ also erred. The pope's apology for discrimination
against women is welcome but difficult to square with his continued
opposition to abortion and birth control, and to women in the
priesthood. Regrettably, he made no mention of discrimination
against homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Another widely noted omission was the lack of a specific
reference to the Holocaust. Rabbi Marvin Hier, dean of the Simon
Wiesenthal Center, expressed regret at that omission but called the
pope's sweeping reference to mistreatment of Jews by Catholics a
``bold and important step forward.'' It comes two years after the
Vatican's ``call to penitence'' on behalf of Catholics who remained
silent in the face of the Holocaust. That earlier statement was a
moving denunciation of anti-Semitism and the Holocaust, but it fell
short of candidly acknowledging the failure of Pope Pius XII to
speak out against the Nazi genocide. John Paul's visit to Israel
next week will provide a striking opportunity for him to address
the suffering of Jews in the Holocaust and the Vatican's role in
the war years.
</P>
<P>
   Bent by age and illness, John Paul is no longer the energetic
leader who did much to speed the demise of communism in Eastern
Europe. But as he demonstrated on Sunday, he still has the strength
of heart and mind to confront the historical deviations of the
Catholic Church and to prepare it for the changes that will come in
its third millennium. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2214EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
