</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 03/13/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- March 13, 2000 -- FALL-FASHION -- From the
Fall 2000 ready-to-wear season show in New York. From left,
variations on fall themes: Michael Kors's coat combined two trends,
style and fur. Right, a different take on coats and patterns by
John Bartlett. (Marilynn K. Yee/G. Paul Burnett/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PLANT CITY, Fla. -- March 13, 2000 --
FLA-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS -- Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, left, running
for the Republican presidential nomination, poses with his brother
Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida at the Strawberry Festival in Plant City
on Sunday. The first to grant vouchers to students whose schools
fail standardized tests, Florida will soon be the nation's largest
testing ground for a school voucher program. Florida's plans are a
model for a national program proposed by Gov. George W. Bush, the
likely Republican presidential nominee. (David Mills/The Lakeland
Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BEDFORD, N.Y. (top), CLARKSTOWN, N.Y. -- March 13, 2000
-- NY-SENATE-STYLE -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York, running
for the U.S. Senate from New York, during a news conference Monday
discussing increasing gasoline prices in Bedford, N.Y.. At bottom,
Giuliani's rival, Hillary Rodham Clinton, during a campaign stop at
Valley Cottage Elementary School in Clarkstown, N.Y. Clinton's
style of running for higher office could hardly be more different
than that of Giuliani. In the case of these two candidates seeking
to succeed Daniel Patrick Moynihan, this is a matter not of
happenstance, but of design. (Joyce Dopkeen, top, Ruby
Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- March 13, 2000 -- PHOTOGRAPHING-NEWYORK --
Photographs of West 52nd Street in Manhattan taken by Percy Loomis
Sperr. In an ambitious effort to expand an already vast photo
archive showing practically every street in New York City as long
ago as the 1870's, the New York Public Library is preparing to
repeat the process to match many of the 54,000 old views with
contemporary ones. Some 30,000 pictures already in its collection
were taken by Sperr in the 1930's and 40's. The updated portrait of
New York would to some extent retrace his footsteps. (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HOUSTON -- March 13, 2000 -- SCI-MOON-METEORITES-2 --
Edgar Mitchell and fellow crewmen of Apollo 14 going over lunar
rocks recovered during their mission in 1971. One gram of moon soil
-- or regolith, as lunar dirt is called -- collected by members of
the mission, has only now been put to a rigorous analysis, which
has revealed what may be a surprising new chapter in the history of
the solar system. (NASA/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ON THE SURFACE OF THE MOON -- March 13, 2000 --
SCI-MOON-METEORITES-1 -- Edgar Mitchell on a moonwalk during the
Apollo 14 mission. One gram of moon soil -- or regolith, as lunar
dirt is called -- collected by members of the mission, has only now
been put to a rigorous analysis, which has revealed what may be a
surprising new chapter in the history of the solar system.
(NASA/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 13, 2000 -- TOSCA-OPERA-REVIEW -- Carl
Tanner and Amy Johnson in Puccini's ``Tosca'' at the New York City
Opera. The director Mark Lamos's updated production of Puccini's
``Tosca,'' which was introduced last season at the New York City
Opera and re urned on Friday night, is over all a striking work of
music theater which gives this repertory staple the shocking look
of 1930's Fascist Italy. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) AUSTIN, Texas -- March 13, 2000 -- BUSH-REFORM -- For
Gov. George W. Bush, reform has been a matter of legislative
proposals rather than an overriding political philosophy, which
might explain why few people in Texas would have picked the word
reformer when asked to describe the governor. Bush during his
victory rally last Tuesday after winning the majority of states in
the Super Tuesday round of presidential primaries. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- March 13, 2000 --
SCI-EVOLUTIONARY-PSYCHOLOGY-2 -- Dr. Lea Cosmides and her husband,
Dr. John Tooby, both professors at the University of California at
Santa Barbara, are widely regarded as intellectual leaders of the
evolutionary psychology school. ``Psychologists should be
interested in evolutionary biology for the same reason that hikers
should be interested in an aerial map of an unfamiliar territory
that they plan to explore on foot,'' wrote Cosmides, Tooby, and Dr.
John Barkow in the introduction to ``The Adapted Mind: Evolutionary
Psychology and the Generation of Culture.'' (Courtesy of John
Tooby/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- March 13, 2000 -- SCI-EVOLUTIONARY-PSYCHOLOGY
-- Dr. Craig T. Palmer co-author of ``A Natural History of Rape:
Biological Bases of Sexual Coercion.'' When Palmer co-author Dr.
Randy Thornhill proposed in a recent book that rape was best viewed
as a sexual act with its roots in evolution, it set off a squall of
protest from feminists and social scientists. (M.I.T. Press/New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- March 13, 2000 -- TYNAN-SONG -- Ronan Tynan
on a recent visit to Manhattan. Tynan is one of the three Irish
tenors now making the St. Patrick's Day rounds in American concert
halls and on public television. ``I'm a very happy man, extremely
so,'' says Tynan, whose list of accomplishments goes far beyond his
singing. (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- March 13, 2000 -- INTERNET-ARTS-BOS
-- Jacob Bouvrie, a 21-year-old electrical engineering student at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, shows off a hard drive
that stores 200 CD's. A music aficionado and a musician himself, he
owns several hundred CDs. Like most students, he moves frequently,
and he is tired of lugging around all that plastic. The solution?
He converted his CD collection to a digital file format called MP3,
a relatively simple process. He now stores his music on his
computer. ``Every time I change dorm rooms, I just carry my hard
drive with me,'' he says. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DAVIE, Fla. -- March 13, 2000 -- FBN-MARINO-MIAMI-2 --
Fans outside the Miami Dolphins training facility show their
support for quaterback Dan Marino, Monday. Marino, the NFL's most
prolific passer, retired Monday after 17 years as quarterback of
the Miami Dolphins. (Gary I. Rothstein/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DAVIE, Fla. -- March 13, 2000 -- FBN-MARINO-MIAMI --
Miami Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino pauses while reading a
prepared statement announcing his retirement from the NFL at the
Dolphins training facility Monday. Marino, the NFL's most prolific
passer, retired Monday after 17 years as quarterback of the Miami
Dolphins. (Gary I. Rothstein/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- March 13, 2000 -- SCI-MARS-GEOLOGY-2-B&AMP;W --
The north and south poles of Mars are vastly different, as revealed
recently in highly detailed pictures from the Mars Global Surveyor.
In this series, the texture of the north polar ice cap, top, is in
a region of low flat plains. The close-up at bottom reveals why
scientists call the region ``cottage cheese.'' (NASA, Malin Space
Science Systems/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- March 13, 2000 -- SCI-MARS-GEOLOGY-1-B&AMP;W --
The north and south poles of Mars are vastly different, as revealed
recently in highly detailed pictures from the Mars Global Surveyor.
In this series, the texture of the south polar ice cap, top, is in
an area of cratered highlands. The close-up at bottom reveals why
scientists call the region ``Swiss cheese.'' (NASA, Malin Space
Science Systems/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
