<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-N     03-13 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IT'S ONLY WORDS, BUT WORDS ARE ALL THEY HAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The post-Boomer Esiason Era has begun at ABC's ``Monday Night
Football.'' Too bad all that nastiness he described going on behind
the scenes didn't spill over on the air. Once upon a time it did.
Remember when the love affair was over between Howard Cosell and
Don Meredith? They didn't hide their hatred.
</P>
<P>
   And Cosell ripped all his old friends in his memoirs and railed
about the jockocracy. Danger! Unpredictability! It's a
back-to-the-future prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Don Ohlmeyer, who produced ``Monday Night'' from 1973 to 1976,
is back to save the franchise and find new partners for Al
Michaels. He task is tough. ``Monday Night'' was an aberration 30
years ago, a true event that didn't have cable, home video, the
Internet and professional wrestling against it.
</P>
<P>
   If Ohlmeyer doesn't provide inspired choices, people will wonder
why ABC deemed Esiason expendable. The lineup of usual suspects is
not overwhelming. None will cause angry viewers to blast the screen
with rifle fire.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Johnson's stint on Fox's Sunday studio show demonstrated
his candor, but success on a 60-minute studio program with three
talkative partners does not necessarily translate into greatness
over three hours in the game booth.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells? He defined mediocrity at NBC in the studio and on
games in 1991 and 1992; the Parcells that television may never get
is the one who saves his best stuff for off the air, or in
off-the-record conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Marino? Why would the newly retired Dolphin be better than
Esiason was? The last thing ABC needs is someone with no television
experience. Being an articulate interviewee does not magically
translate into great game analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Young? Not yet retired, he is being considered because of
his so-so stint as an analyst for ABC's postseason studio programs.
Definitely not ready to step into the league with Fox's John Madden
and NBC's Phil Simms.
</P>
<P>
   If you're dipping into the past, then bring back Keith Jackson,
Cosell's and Meredith's partner in ``Monday Night's'' inaugural
season in 1970 before being shoved aside for Gifford. If you're
dipping into the Walt Disney family, then shift Stuart Scott and/or
Sterling Sharpe from ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Some other choices:
</P>
<P>
   JIM ROME _ He never played the game, but once wrestled on the
air with Jim Everett after deriding the quarterback as ``Chrissie
Evert.'' The host of a syndicated radio show and Fox Sports Net's
``The Last Word'' is young, bearded, opinionated, speaks his own
language of ``smack'' (an on-line glossary is 23 pages long and is
almost as incomprehensible as Scott's personal patois) and could
succeed Cosell as, simultaneously, the most-hated and most-liked
sportscaster in America if given the ``Monday Night'' platform.
Pull Paul Maguire off ESPN's Sunday night telecasts and the team is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE JUDY _ Nastier and tarter than Cosell, she wouldn't
hesitate criticizing players, especially the whiners, fakers and
malcontents. Would Marino do that? I hear Judy telling Michaels,
``Shut up, Al, can't ya hear me talking?'' or asking, ``Is Aikman
thick? Do I have to repeat that a screen pass is stupid on
third-and-2? Or do I have to explain it again?'' Teaming her with
Dr. Laura Schlessinger would relieve Michaels of any need to speak
and capture more female viewers. But your hair might hurt after
three hours with them.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAM BENNETT _ The loquacious conservative politician, former
Cabinet member and crusader for virtues in American life would be
perfect for ``Monday Night'' in an era of players being charged
with domestic abuse and murder. His partner, Bob Dole, would speak
only about players whose initials are E.D.
</P>
<P>
   TERRY BRADSHAW _ Probably impossible to pry from ``Fox NFL
Sunday,'' Bradshaw is a latter-day Meredith: a corny, rambunctious
Southerner who likes to sing. He never wowed anyone at CBS with his
game analysis, but the new ``Monday Night'' won't be about Xs and
Os; it'll be freewheeling entertainment that needs someone who was
recently re-created as a Claymation action figure. And ``Monday
Night'' needs a bald man, to erase the memory of Cosell's rug.
</P>
<P>
   ART DONOVAN _ Who defines old-time football values better than
the legendary Fatso, perhaps the greatest storyteller in the NFL
Films archive? Is anyone funnier than the crew-cut, former
Baltimore Colts defensive tackle? Plus, he's drunk enough beer to
be both analyst and human suds sponsor. For real beer-belly
machismo, hire him in tandem with another NFL throwback, Chuck
Bednarik, who might give Michaels a nasty concussion (as he gave
one to Frank Gifford, who served ``Monday Night'' for 28 years) to
enforce his air time.
</P>
<P>
   BILL MAHER _ The host of ABC's ``Politically Incorrect'' would
usher in a revolutionary new format. Not three, four, five in a
booth, but six around a circle. He, Michaels and four weekly guests
(chosen from a pool to include Sandra Bernhard, Tommy Lee, Laura
Ingraham, Kenneth Starr, Meat Loaf, Leon Spinks, Barry Switzer and
Dr. Joyce Brothers) would spend their three hours dissecting
third-down pass efficiency, uniforms and Al Davis' haberdashery.
</P>
<P>
   THE ROCK _ The inevitable choice to compete for young male
viewers against wrestling at 9 p.m. on Mondays and blunt the impact
of the World Wrestling Federation's planned XFL. So what if he
speaks of himself in the third person? ``The Rock says Keyshawn
Johnson is in motion and that if I get him in the ring next week,
I'll whip his butt for that holdout! Al?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
