<HEADLINE>
NITWITTY `SON OF THE BEACH' SETS ITS SIGHTS BELOW THE BELT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who have spent time watching ``Baywatch Hawaii'' _ and we
know who we are _ might be wondering why Howard Stern decided to
back a comedy series that spoofs one of the best self-parodies
anywhere on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Stack, co-creator and star of ``Son of the Beach,''
explains: ``It's `Get Smart' on the beach. Inspector Clouseau of
the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Stack and Stern didn't exactly aim to lampoon
``Baywatch.'' They wanted to recapture the irreverent humor of the
old Don Adams spy comedy and more recent satires like ``Airplane''
and the underappreciated cop spoof, ``Police Squad!'' But they
didn't want to recreate the same characters.
</P>
<P>
   So Stack kept coming back to this idea of a lifeguard who was
more than just a lifeguard. A nitwit in the tradition of Maxwell
Smart and Frank Drebin, he manages to right wrongs and survive
life-threatening situations by dint of sheer stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Notch Johnson, head of a lifeguard unit _ he loves
showing off his unit _ that patrols the sandy strand of Malibu
Adjacent. He also manages to solve murders, bring down drug lords
or, in the case of Tuesday's premiere on the FX cable network,
break up a Cambodian sex-slave ring.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing seems to be off limits to Stack and his co-creators,
David Morgasen and James R. Stein. There are enough Johnson jokes
to keep a locker room of junior high kids snickering for weeks, but
if ``Son of the Beach'' stays strictly below the belt with its
humor, even Howard Stern's hard-core fans may eventually tune out.
On second thought, no they won't.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, ``Son of the Beach'' isn't targeting the ``Masterpiece
Theatre'' crowd. It wants men who like their TV metaphor-free, and
preferably with lots of cleavage. In this case, both qualities are
supplied by Jaime Bergman and Leila Arcieri. Bergman plays the dumb
blonde, B.J. Cummings, who wouldn't know a metaphor from pinafore.
You can probably guess how she got her name. Arcieri plays the
jive-talking ``lifeguard from the inner city,'' Jamaica St. Croix.
Rounding out this group of beach bozos is Roland Kickinger, playing
a ripped Schwarzenegger type named Chip Rommel, an ``exchange
lifeguard'' from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   A new addition to the unit is wholesome, all-American Kimberlee
Clark, the only one with enough brains to take an IQ test. Stack
calls her the Barbara Feldon character, and Kim Oja (pronounced
OH-yah) seems right for the part.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's nemesis is a crooked mayor named Anita Massengil (Lisa
Banes), who thinks ruining Johnson's career will aid her
congressional aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the amusing names, ``Son of the Beach'' specializes in
low-brow humor of questionable taste. It is suitable accompaniment
to mindless, sexist stuff like FX's ``The X Show,'' which airs
immediately afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The potential problem is that it's dumb funny, not smart funny.
This may be what FX is looking for as it tries to become known for
something other than reruns of somebody else's shows. But Stack has
proven he's considerably smarter than Notch Johnson, having hosted
the clever make-believe talk show, ``Nightstand with Dick
Dietrick'' on E! Entertainment Television. If Stack wants to make
an impression beyond the six episodes already in the can, he'd be
wise to aim higher than the crotch.
</P>
<P>
   Son of the Beach. Half-hour comedy series about a dimwitted
lifeguard who manages to succeed in spite of himself. Starring Tim
Stack, Leila Arcieri, Lisa Banes, Jaime Bergman, Roland Kickinger
and Kim Oja. Premieres Tuesday night on FX cable. Parental
guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
