<HEADLINE>
RAPTORS AND SONICS ARE FINED $100,000 EACH
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tension has deepened between the National Basketball
Association and its coaches over the issue of requiring miniature
microphones to be worn during telecasts, with the league imposing
fines of $100,000 apiece Monday on the Toronto Raptors and the
Seattle SuperSonics for the defiant actions of their coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Carter of Toronto and Paul Westphal of Seattle balked at
the league's mandate to wear the mikes during Sunday's regionally
televised game in Seattle, bringing punitive measures by
Commissioner David Stern, who has promised more substantial fines
if coaches fail to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy, one of the more vocal critics on the issue, was
scheduled to be miked Tuesday night when his Knicks play the
Houston Rockets at Madison Square Garden. He said he would wear the
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already stated my objections,'' Van Gundy said. The
executive board of the National Basketball Coaches Association
implied Monday that it may take legal action to prevent the league
from forcing coaches to wear microphones.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Wilkens, the Atlanta coach and the organization's
president, and several officials of the unit, including Nets Coach
Don Casey, participated in a conference call on the issue along
with Michael Goldberg, a Manhattan lawyer who is the association's
executive director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough of them feel strongly about it that we feel duty-bound
to support them,'' Goldberg said. ``If the league insists on
maintaining this stance, the association will have no choice but to
explore all the options available to it to support its members who
do not wish to be miked while they coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Many coaches have objected to the use of microphones because of
privacy issues related to their jobs. In a statement released
Sunday, Westphal, who said he would personally pay the fine imposed
on his team, said: ``The league wants me to allow my private
strategies, insights, relationships and speech to be monitored,
then eventually owned by others. I am being asked to choose between
compromising the competitive integrity of the game or seeing my
ownership fined $100,000. I cannot accept that this great league
would want to force such a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has created a division in the league office as well,
according to one Eastern Conference team official, who did not want
to be identified. He said there was a concern among some league
officials that the move is an overreaction to low ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was given birth by the league's entertainment division.
NBC was informed in November of the plan to use microphones during
telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all fairness, this issue is not a television issue,'' said
Dick Ebersol, the NBC Sports president. ``This is all part of an
Internet strategy _ and not a bad one to be pursuing at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol said the network was taking great pains to be sensitive
to teams and coaches during the process, and that it was not
counting on the microphones to rescue slumping ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we put it on the air, it's later in the game,'' he
said. ``We don't put strategy on the air. We don't go inside the
huddle during a timeout because that wouldn't be fair to the
coaches. We're looking for personalities and intrigue. But it's all
adjunct to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players have been emboldened to support their coaches on
the microphone issue. Carter, the Toronto coach, said Sunday that
the team's two veteran leaders, Charles Oakley and Antonio Davis,
did not want him miked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought it was an invasion,'' Carter said. ``I can't
afford to lose the respect of my players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' Allan Houston said: ``It's still a sport. And there
are still certain things that should be shared internally between
players and coaches, players and players, that I don't think other
people should have to hear.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
