<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANDERSEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT, ANDERSEN JOIN TO OFFER TECH TO LARGE CORPORATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Microsoft and Andersen Consulting agreed Monday to
create a $1 billion, Seattle-based joint venture that will offer
Microsoft technology to large corporations, adding 300 to 500 jobs
in the Puget Sound area over the next three years as it ramps up.
</P>
<P>
   The company, to be called Avanade (``av-uh-NAHD'') and
eventually to employ about 5,000 people, is among the largest
partnerships ever undertaken by either Microsoft or Andersen, an
$8.3 billion management and technology-consulting company based in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Avanade marks the first time Andersen has embraced one company's
technology fully, and heralds an unprecedented assault on
traditional Unix and mainframe strongholds based on Microsoft's new
Windows 2000 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big _ really big,'' said Mitchell Hill, the Andersen
Consulting partner and 12-year Seattle resident who will serve as
Avanade's chief executive. Steve Ballmer, Microsoft's chief
executive, said, ``This is a part of the market we've never been
able to form a partnership to serve super, super well.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Andersen committed to training 25,000 of its
consultants _ nearly one-third of its staff _ in using Windows
2000, SQL Server database, Exchange Server e-commerce software, and
DNA 2000 development tools. About 3,000 of those will form a
Microsoft consulting division within Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will put $385 million in cash into Avanade, while
Andersen will contribute employee training, services and
intellectual property valued at more than $600 million. Avanade
will hire a total of 5,000 people, staffing offices with at least
200 people each in San Francisco, New York, Dallas, London, Paris,
Frankfurt, Sao Paulo, Singapore and Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said he expects the company to generate revenue of $1
billion within the next three years and to go public within two.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer said the venture's primary competitor will be IBM Global
Services. Antitrust regulators must approve the venture before it
can proceed, but the company expects to be operational within
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Until the debut of Windows 2000 last month, Microsoft's attempts
to break into the largest, most demanding computing environments _
challenging competitors like IBM, Sun Microsystems and Oracle _
were often fruitless. Now, ``Andersen sees Windows 2000 as a change
in the value of Microsoft and its value to the Fortune 1000
customer space,'' said Geoff Nyheim, Microsoft's director of global
partners.
</P>
<P>
   The market for Avanade's services could reach $15 billion in two
years, Andersen estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the new company's name combines the word avenue,
referring to ``the journey our clients have to go on,'' and the
word promenade, referring to ``a place _ and the place for the
global economy is the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Wire service material is included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
