<SLUG> BC-CT-POLICE-TRIAL-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT POLICE OFFICER CONVICTED IN FATAL SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Conn. _ The first Connecticut police officer to be
charged with murder for fatally shooting a suspect while on duty
was acquitted of murder Monday and instead convicted of a lesser
charge of intentional manslaughter, ending yet another trial in a
racially charged police brutality case.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Scott B. Smith, 28, of the New Milford, Conn.,
police, faces a sentence of five to 40 years in prison for killing
Franklyn Reid, a fleeing suspect, by shooting him once in the back
after chasing him along a local highway and pinning him to the
ground on Dec. 29, 1998. A conviction of murder could have carried
a sentence of life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's jury verdict in state Superior Court here ended a
three-week trial that had drawn relatively little national notice,
overshadowed by the much higher-profile police brutality cases in
New York involving the death of Amadou Diallo and the assault on
Abner Louima. Like the officers in those cases, Smith is white, and
like the victims in New York, Reid was black.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the officers in the New York cases, however, Smith seemed
favored by public sentiment in Litchfield County, and prosecutors
were not under extraordinary pressure to charge him.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's decision to acquit on the most serious charge but
convict on a lesser one spurred mixed emotions that left spectators
on both sides of the courtroom nearly speechless. Elation among
Smith's supporters as the forewoman said ``not guilty'' quickly
turned to dismay at ``guilty.'' Smith looked toward the ceiling and
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the courtroom, where Reid's family and
their supporters sat, faces etched with tension burst into relieved
smiles at the guilty verdict. The silence was broken by the Rev.
Henry Price of Hartford, one of several black ministers who had
attended the trial diligently. ``Justice is finally done,'' he
declared.
</P>
<P>
   After closing arguments last week, Judge Charles D. Gill
instructed the predominantly white jury to consider two lesser
manslaughter charges, granting the prosecution's request over the
objections of Smith's defense lawyer, John J. Kelly. That decision
proved crucial, and the jury returned its verdict after
deliberating for a total of about two days.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the jurors seemed relieved as they left the
building without speaking to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In charging the jurors on Thursday, Gill told them that if they
were to find Smith not guilty of murder, they should consider two
lesser charges: intentional first-degree manslaughter with a
firearm, or reckless manslaughter with a firearm. The crucial
difference, Gill said, was the distinction between intent and
recklessness, and he told the jurors they could convict on one but
not both of those counts.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the manslaughter charges seemed to offer the jury an
alternative to two unpalatable options: convicting a police officer
of murdering a fugitive ex-convict who had a knife in his jacket
pocket when he was shot, or acquitting a white officer of shooting
to death a black suspect under circumstances that many witnesses
described as clearly not warranting deadly force.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reid, who had served time in prison for stabbing one of his
uncles and having a sexual relationship with a minor, was wanted
for failing to appear in court to face charges of harassment and
violating his probation. He was driving through New Milford on Dec.
29, 1998, and jumped out of his car and ran away when he was
spotted by a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and a partner later saw Reid near a gas station on Route
202, and Smith ran after him. Several eyewitnesses testified that
they thought the chase was over and that Smith had his suspect
pinned to the ground. The prosecution said Smith had his foot on
Reid's back and his gun pressed against Reid's spine when he fired
the fatal shot.
</P>
<P>
   Smith testified that he shot Reid only after Reid resisted being
handcuffed and made a sudden move as if to reach for a weapon. He
testified that Reid had been up on his knees, not lying on the
ground, and had given the officer an intimidating stare. Later
investigation determined that Reid had a small knife in the pocket
of his jacket, which he was not wearing when he was shot but which
was found near his body.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, Reid's mother, Pearlylyn Reid, thanked
the judge, prosecutors and witnesses. ``Thanks a trillion trillion
trillion times to the jury for your courage to do the right thing
of convicting Scott Smith for the public execution of Franklyn
Reid,'' she said, adding: ``He should be treated like any other
citizen when he is sentenced to prison. He is not above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, John A. Connelly, also praised the jurors,
saying they ``showed a great deal of courage and they returned an
appropriate verdict.'' Connelly would not say what penalty he would
recommend at the officer's sentencing on May 5.
</P>
<P>
   Smith remains free on $250,000 bail. He left the courthouse with
his family and lawyer, declining to speak to reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
