<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MCHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL KINGS GET CAUGHT IN AVALANCHE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Kings were not in the running for Ray Bourque,
but they are very interested in the way Colorado has sprinted past
Edmonton since last week's trade for the future Hall of Fame
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche won its fifth straight Sunday night, an impressive
3-1 victory over Philadelphia. It puts Colorado two points ahead of
the Oilers in the Northwest Division and sets up a first-round
playoff matchup with the No.6 Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deadline is 3 p.m. today, but the Bourque deal is
expected to have the biggest impact on the West. Defending Stanley
Cup-champion Dallas has made some moves, but top seed St. Louis has
stood pat. The two also played Sunday and the Stars won 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Bourque, who at age 39 still has great skill and
an incredible work ethic, blends perfectly with a team that is
getting hot. The Avs jumped far in front of Edmonton in January,
when they spent most of the month at home. But they were passed in
February by the pesky Oilers, who were riding the hot goaltending
of Islanders castoff Tommy Salo.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are back, healthy and happy. Captain Joe Sakic even
offered Bourque his C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went on a surge in January and then February was just a
terrible month,'' Sakic said. ``I don't know why. We kinda hit the
wall. We've been playing better. We just weren't a confident hockey
team. Our confidence is back. Obviously, with the way we've played
lately and with this trade, we're going to have a dressing room
that really believes in one another now.''
</P>
<P>
   And watch out if the Avalanche get to overtime. In the
four-on-four format, they could go with a lineup of future Hall of
Famers: Sakic, Bourque, Peter Forsberg, goaltender Patrick Roy and
500-goal scorer Dave Andreychuk, who also came over from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   All this, of course, has Edmonton general manager Glen Sather a
little upset. He doesn't have the resources to swing a big deal,
getting only tough but limited defenseman Igor Ulanov from Montreal
for Christian Laflamme.
</P>
<P>
   Sather knows Bourque probably will retire after the season, but
that doesn't help him now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the whole idea of renting players,'' he said.
``Somehow we have to push the trading deadline back a month, but
the Players Association, of course, would have to agree to that.
I'm sure Colorado made the deal because we're making them nervous.
I'm not so sure it'll work anyway. All those stars they have there
now will be bumping into one another.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, there is a Kings connection with Bourque. In 1979,
the Boston Bruins sent goaltender Ron Grahame to the Kings for
their No.1 pick (eighth overall), which turned out to be Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   SITTING IT OUT
</P>
<P>
   San Jose was a major player at the deadline the past two years,
getting Vincent Damphousse last season and Bryan Marchment and Joe
Murphy in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Sharks probably will slip in with the final
playoff spot but are expected to go out in the first round. Like
the Kings, they have shown interest in gritty veterans like Shayne
Corson and Kelly Buchberger, but both now are off the market.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks, however, might benefit from the Bourque trade
anyway. They do not play the Avalanche again this season, but
Colorado still has three games remaining with Edmonton and one with
Calgary and the Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Those are San Jose's top playoff competitors. In fact, the
Sharks played Calgary on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   While Marchment provided solid defense and heavy hitting after
coming over from Tampa two years ago, this had been a lost season.
He is just returning from his third major injury of the year. He's
had knee, ankle and groin problems.
</P>
<P>
   A SURE THING
</P>
<P>
   Most of the season, the Florida Panthers appeared to have the
easiest road to a division title. The Washington Capitals have
created quite a pot-hole.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers' once insurmountable lead in mid-January is gone.
Last week, the Capitals beat Florida at home to take sole
possession of first place in the Southeast Division.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is 20-6-4 since trailing the Panthers by 16 points,
14-2-3 at home since Christmas and 9-0-1 in its past 10 against
division opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Florida came back to beat Tampa Bay two nights later but then
lost to lowly Chicago on Saturday to give the Panthers a 3-8-1
record in their past 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   A division title means home ice advantage in the first round and
an excellent chance against Ottawa, which won't catch Toronto in
the Northeast. But now the Panthers are fifth and could wind up on
the road against No.4 Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want Florida to use a win to springboard where they
could regain their confidence,'' Washington coach Ron Wilson said
after beating the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely disappointing,'' Florida's Ray Sheppard
said.``I think every guy in the room knows how far ahead we were,
and to now be in a dogfight, it should serve as a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most prominent players to suffer during the slump is
the league's leading goal scorer, Pavel Bure. Against Washington,
he was held to just two third-period shots. Bure, once second in
the NHL with a plus-30, is a minus-9 in the past 10 games. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Sports Editor Matt McHale covers the Kings for the Daily
News. The NHL Column appears every Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
