<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-R-FBN-MARINO-ART-1STL     03-13 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-FBN-MARINO-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
61,361 YARDS LATER, MARINO TAKES HIS FINAL STEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Subs for graphics note). (See also FBN-MARINO-MIAMI) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT3 and NYT4, and graphic, are being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By CHARLES NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ As Dan Marino gave his farewell speech Sunday
after 17 years as the Miami Dolphins quarterback and the National
Football League's most dominant career passing record-holder, he
tried to avoid making eye contact with his wife, Claire, who sat
sobbing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling Claire that I can't cry during this thing,''
Marino said after formally announcing his retirement at the
Dolphins' training facility at Nova Southeastern University. ``I
felt many a time like crying, but I was able to hold back. Tried to
make a few jokes and keep it loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino, whose NFL career records include most touchdown passes
(420), most passing yards (61,361) and most completions (4,967),
said he decided to bring his playing career to a close at age 38
mostly because of his health. He has had six knee operations,
ruptured an Achilles' tendon and last season suffered a scary neck
injury that sidelined him for five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are physical limitations I would have had to deal
with,'' he said. ``It kept coming back to how my legs felt during
last season going through the neck injury and not knowing whether I
was going to be able to throw the football.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Dolphins indicated by their long, awkward silence that
their interest in Marino had waned, he was temporarily invigorated
by an offer from the Minnesota Vikings. Coach Dennis Green was so
interested in Marino that he offered to let him fly home after
every Sunday game and not return until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Marino said he had gone through a number of emotional swings
before deciding last Thursday morning to retire. ``There were times
I told Claire we were going and two hours later I'd say, `No, I
don't think I can go,''' he said. ``It is the toughest thing I had
to deal with professionally in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Marino said that if the Dolphins had shown as
much enthusiasm for his continuing to play as the Vikings had, he
would likely still be a Dolphin. ``He probably would have gone to
training camp, to see how he felt physically, and then take it from
there,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins have been widely perceived by their fans as
bungling the handling of Marino's status, and hundreds of fans
showed up to give No. 13 a raucous sendoff.
</P>
<P>
   The team's owner, H. Wayne Huizenga, tried to defuse some of the
tension by making several announcements: retiring Marino's No. 13
jersey; saying that a statue of Marino would be placed at Pro
Player Stadium next to one of Don Shula, the Hall of Fame coach;
naming a street near the stadium after Marino, and saying he would
install Marino into the Dolphins' Ring of Honor at their first home
game next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it simply, Danny, nobody did it better than you; you
are the greatest quarterback ever,'' Huizenga said before the pair
hugged.
</P>
<P>
   Shula attended Monday's announcement, as did former Dolphins
Mark Clayton, Dwight Stephenson, Jimmy Cefalo, Kim Bokamper and Joe
Rose. Jimmy Johnson, the recently retired Dolphins coach, was
conspicuously absent, and his successor, Dave Wannstedt, stayed in
the background and left quickly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Johnson and Marino became particularly
acrimonious last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just have to say that our relationship was up and down
at times,'' Marino said. ``We had some great, great days together
and some fun times. And times I wasn't very happy here while he was
coaching, and that is just being honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, a former tight end who became a local television
broadcaster, caught the first touchdown of Marino's NFL career in
1983 against the Raiders, after the rookie from Pittsburgh relieved
David Woodley. But Rose, Marino's roommate on the road,
particularly recalled an occasion when they woke up in Baltimore on
game day to find it snowing hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like a four-touchdown day,'' Rose quoted Marino as
saying. ``I said, `You've got to be kidding me.' But that was just
the kind of confidence he had. And he went out and had a great
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, who teamed with Mark Duper to catch 1,030 of Marino's
passes for 16,743 yards and 134 touchdowns, said they used to kid
the quarterback that they were saving his reputation with acrobatic
catches taken from defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd tell him that he'd be nothing without us,'' Clayton said.
``He'd dispute that. He'd say, `No, no, no. You didn't make me. I
make you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said that he and Duper became so comfortable with Marino
that sometimes the quarterback would abandon the usual play calls.
``He'd just say, `Get open, the ball's coming to you,' '' Clayton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Marino was the last of five quarterbacks taken in the first
round in 1983. But that 27th pick soon had Shula's eyes bulging.
Marino passed for a league-record 48 touchdowns in 1984, then had
44 two seasons later, making him the only player in NFL history to
throw at least 40 touchdown passes twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never felt you were out of a ball game with Dan Marino as
your quarterback,'' Shula said. ``Today is the celebration of a
great career _ an unmatched career, really.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
