u s BC-FBN-FREEMAN-MARINO-CO     03-13 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREEMAN-MARINO-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURPLE WOULD NOT SUIT THE GAME'S TOP PASSER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was January in Jacksonville when Dan Marino saw his mortality
flash before him as if he were watching a loud movie in Dolby
stereo. His knees had been operated on so many times that they had
aged in dog years. Marino called those operations ``oil changes.''
His throwing elbow pained him so much, he could barely bend it. And
his arm strength, well, reaching the sideline with one of his
bullets used to be easy; now it took a presidential order.
</P>
<P>
   The signals were there, screaming. He knew it. He was a goner.
The Jaguars had destroyed Marino and the Dolphins, 62-7, in the
second round of the playoffs. In the locker room after the game,
one of Marino's teammates asked him what he was going to do. It was
an awkward question at an awkward time. Marino didn't answer. He
didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   He was making plans to spend time playing golf, maybe do a
little television commentary and definitely spend a lot of time
with his family. Then his phone started to ring. It was Minnesota
Coach Dennis Green, laying down the purple carpet, courting Marino,
begging him to play. Marino was intrigued and entranced. The
Dolphins did not want him, and there were those Vikings wide
receivers, Cris Carter and Randy Moss, to sweeten the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Marino went back and forth. One minute he was telling his wife,
Claire, he was going to do it; two hours later he would change his
mind, deciding it was too risky. Then, he would think about his
friend John Elway, raising that Lombardi trophy over his head after
all of those years of getting so close, and Marino would change his
mind yet again, thinking that one more run was not out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   The knees were suddenly young again. The arm had a little more
pepper in it. Marino was at the stage a lot of great players reach;
they know in their hearts it is time to leave the game, but the
aura of football can be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I really struggled with this,'' Marino said Monday at his
news conference in Davie, Fla., at times fighting back tears.
``This has been the toughest moment of my life as far as dealing
with playing football or retiring. After the season I pretty much
thought that I was not going to play anymore. I felt that way for a
while. I think it is because of the physical aspects of the game.
It kept coming back to how my legs felt, going through the neck
injury, not knowing whether I was able to throw the football.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Green, and all of that changed. But Marino did the
smart thing, not succumbing to what would have been a difficult
dream, leading Minnesota to a Super Bowl victory.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the great news of this day. There won't be those
distorted images of Marino playing in a purple Vikings uniform, his
knees wobbly. Or talk of how he should have ended his career in
Miami, the way there was constant blathering about Joe Montana, the
longtime San Francisco 49er, ending his days in Kansas City. Or
Johnny Unitas, who ended his Hall of Fame days in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Marino came in a Dolphin, and he will leave one. That, by
itself, is a remarkable achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Green's attempt to snag Marino was a smart one, but even he
conceded that seeing Marino in a Vikings uniform would have seemed
strange. ``Dan would have had to do what so many guys are doing
now,'' Green said, ``and that is change teams at the end of a
career.''
</P>
<P>
   When Marino is eligible for the Hall of Fame in five years, it
may be the easiest decision voters ever had. Marino threw more
passes for more completions for more yards and more touchdowns than
anyone else. His 33,508 passing yards in the 1990's are the most in
a decade for any quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to imagine another quarterback duplicating the kind
of success Dan had,'' Don Shula, his former coach, said. ``I know I
won't see it in my lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino's retirement is sad in many ways. The game loses one of
its classiest stars, a man who has donated more time and money to
charity than almost any other player the league has seen. His arm
is ranked in the top 10, but so is his heart.
</P>
<P>
   After 17 years as a Dolphin, this should have been Marino's day.
Instead, he had to share the airways and talk shows with seeding
news from college basketball's national tournament. Who goes to
what bracket in what city from what conference _ can someone wake
us for the Sweet 16, please? The greatest quarterback ever was
elbowing for room on ``SportsCenter'' with Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Marino is almost pitied because he was so
productive, yet unable to win a championship. That fact will stick
to his resume forever, almost overwhelming the miles of passing
yards he has thrown and the oodles of touchdown passes he has
whirled through the sky. Most people in football will never
consider him the best because he failed to get fitted for a Super
Bowl ring.
</P>
<P>
   Yet none of that erases his greatness. It is difficult to
believe there were draft-day doubts 17 years ago about Marino. Some
scouts worried that mechanical flaws in his throwing motion might
be too difficult to correct. Such thoughts seem silly now,
especially since Marino became known for a deadly, quick release.
</P>
<P>
   Silly, yes. As silly as Marino in a Minnesota uniform. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
