<HEADER>
A5933 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-BOEING-SPACE-SPI &LR;      03-13 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-SPACE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING WOES MOUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boeing's once-docile union of white-collar engineers has been on
strike now for more than a month; airplane deliveries are slipping
again, and some industry analysts have significantly cut their
estimates of the company's first quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't bad enough, Boeing's Sea Launch program suffered
a high-profile setback this weekend when a rocket carrying a $100
million communications satellite fell into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Though the rocket failure had nothing to do with the strike, it
does add to the company's recent problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would be fair to say Boeing is in trouble,
but they are certainly having their share of difficulties, some of
them self-inflicted,'' Paul Nisbet, analyst with JSA Research, said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Added another industry analyst, who did not want to be quoted by
name:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to get calls from concerned shareholders,
asking us what is wrong at Boeing.''
</P>
<P>
   But he and other analysts said Boeing, and Sea Launch, will be
okay in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Launch is a joint project that uses a Russian-Ukrainian
rocket called Zenit to launch satellites from a platform in the
Pacific near the Christmas Islands about 1,400 miles southest of
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   After two straight successes, the third Sea Launch rocket failed
Sunday. It carried a satellite for the ICO Global Communications
system.
</P>
<P>
   The rocket crashed back into the ocean about 2,600 miles
downrange after reaching an altitude of more than 100 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Albaugh, president of Boeing's space group, said in a
statement Monday the Sea Launch partners will conduct a full
investigation. He would not speculate on what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts downplayed the setback.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space launch business is high risk,'' said Peter Jacobs of
Seattle's Regan MacKnzie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should not have any long term implications. The Sea
Launch venture has the potential to be a very good business for
Boeing down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   But it does mean that two of Boeing's most important new rocket
programs are grounded at a time the company is trying to establish
itself as the world's leader in the space-launch business.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's Delta 3 program has been delayed by back-to-back
failures. The first rocket blew up in 1998 and the second failed to
put its satellite into the proper orbit last year.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts believe Boeing will have to use a dummy payload
on the next Delta 3 launch attempt later this year to now prove the
rocket's reliability to customers.
</P>
<P>
   The first Sea Launch rocket also carried a dummy payload. The
second rocket successfuly placed a communications satellite into
orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are both new programs,'' said analyst Nisbet. ``This is
not uncommon.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Sea Launch setback comes at a time when Boeing is
feeling the results of a strike by many of its engineers.
</P>
<P>
   As the strike entered its 34th day Monday neither side showed
signs of new flexibility and no new talks were scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The stand-off continues to place a drag on airplane deliveries.
Boeing has only delivered two airplanes in March and 16 since
employees walked off their jobs on Feb. 9, according to Peter
Conte, a Boeing spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The union doubts Boeing has even made all of those deliveries,
questioning how the manufacturer can deliver airplanes with most of
its Seattle-area technical workforce on strike.
</P>
<P>
   Both camps also continued to disagree over how many Boeing
employees remain on strike. Boeing said 15,000 engineers and
technical workers were on strike as of March 9, while union leaders
estimated 18,000 workers were involved.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are battling over union demands for greater
guaranteed raises, the protection of existing benefits, lump-sum
bonuses, as well as other contact proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, on the other hand, wants its technical workers to begin
paying healthcare premiums, and accept other changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still time to resolve this strike with only light to
moderate damage,'' said Richard Aboulafia, senior aviation analyst
with the Teal Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it goes on, the cost could be potentially ruinous. In
the short term, deliveries and revenues will slip. Pure and
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Of more lasting concern, he said, is a possible ``brain drain''
at Boeing with its best engineers finding other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a hot market out there for engineers,'' Aboulafia
said. ``We could see a hollowing of the Boeing work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have cut their estimate of Boeing's first quarter
earnings, which are due out next month, by 20 percent or more
because of the strike. Much of that lost revenue, they said, is due
to planes not being delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had been expected to earn about 54 cents per share for
the first quarter, based on the average earnings estimate of
analyst surveyed by First Call. Some analysts, however, said they
will cut their estimates by at least 20 cents because of
strike-related issues, such as the undelivered airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   But Nisbet said Boeing should be able to get all its planes
delivered once the strike ends, which means year-end financial
results are not likely to change.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strike, he said, ``Boeing is doing the right
things.''
</P>
<P>
   That view was echoed by another analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that comes to mind is, `can Boeing make planes
at a reasonable cost to earn a profit in the commercial airplane
business?' The answer is becoming yes,'' this analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there is a growing frustration on Wall Street that the
striking engineers don't really know what they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they want money, they want respect,'' said the
analyst, who asked not to be quoted by name. ``But that's difficult
for shareholders to get their arms around.''
</P>
<P>
   Nisbet said the strike might even benefit Boeing in the long
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they bust the union, they might be better off,'' he said.
``I don't see much sympathy (on Wall Street) for the union on
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jacobs said Boeing will have to work hard once it
settles the strike to regain lost momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing will be challenged to get the production lines back on
track once this strike is settled and regain the productivity
improvements it was able to achieve throughout 1999,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Boeing will have to repair the relationship with its
engineers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company can't afford to have long-term morale problems
with its work force if it is going to achieve the long-term goals
it envisions,''' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
