u f BC-TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR-2     03-13 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-TIMESMIRROR-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBUNE CO. TO MERGE WITH TIMES MIRROR IN $6.45 BILLION DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 4th graf, The proposed acquisition ..., to CORRECT
closing figures for Tribune shares on Friday and Monday.)  (ART
ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER and LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of the nation's largest newspaper companies, the Tribune Co.
and Times Mirror Co., both built around newspapers that helped
define the brawling, partisan days of 19th-century journalism,
announced Monday that they would merge. The deal ends 119 years of
ownership of The Los Angeles Times by the Otis and Chandler
families.
</P>
<P>
   The new company would seek to replicate in cities like New York
and Los Angeles the Tribune's success in offering many kinds of
media to the Chicago market. The idea is to create a network of
regional media hubs where advertisers are matched with audiences
through newspapers, television broadcasts and Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which will retain the Tribune Co. name, will own 11
daily newspapers, 22 television stations and four radio stations.
The company's newspapers would have a combined circulation of 3.6
million copies, ranking third among newspaper companies after
Gannett and Knight Ridder. Tribune's television stations reach 38.4
million households.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed acquisition of Times Mirror by the Tribune Co. was
greeted with deep skepticism by investors; Tribune shares, which
had closed Friday at $37.1875, fell swiftly to $27.75 as trading
opened, and closed at $30.8125, down 17 percent. Shares of Times
Mirror soared $37.6875, to close at $85.625.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the Tribune's corporate heirs of Robert McCormick and
James Patterson, whose pugnacious conservatism often enraged their
barrel-chested union town of Chicago, are buying out and the
corporate heirs of Gen. Harrison Gray Otis and Harry Chandler, who
used The Los Angeles Times as a political hammer, helping fashion
the southern California desert into the nation's second-largest
city.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune's offer of $6.45 billion in the stock and cash deal _
not including the assumption of $1.8 billion of Times Mirror debt _
also puts an abrupt end to the mercurial five-year stewardship of
the Times Mirror chairman, Mark H. Willes. A former cereal company
executive, he brought an almost religious fervor to his quest to
streamline the company, challenging the newspaper industry to
reinvent itself, increase its audience, and toss out its
shibboleths _ notably the historic separation of the news and
business divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The essential details of the deal were arranged by members of
the Chandler family, without Willes' knowledge, according to both
Willes and Thomas Unterman, the former chief financial officer of
Times Mirror who was a primary adviser to the Chandler family
trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts dismissed the flight from Tribune stock as a
short-sighted reaction, particularly considering the success the
company has achieved in its hometown. Peter P. Appert, an analyst
at Deutsche Bank, said ``the 30-percent-plus profit margins it has
had in Chicago demonstrate the leverage that can be achieved owning
both broadcast and a major newspaper in one market. This gives it
the same potential in Los Angeles and New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies overlap in several markets. Tribune bought KTLA in
Los Angeles, now a Warner Bros &UR; . &LR;  affiliate, in 1985. Tribune owns
WTIC, a Fox affiliate in Hartford, Conn., the location of Times
Mirror's Hartford Courant, and WPIX in New York. Newsday, the
second largest among Times Mirror newspapers with a circulation of
575,000, is based in suburban Long Island, within WPIX's viewing
area.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulations prohibiting dual ownership of a daily
newspaper and a broadcast television station are not expected to be
a problem, at least not immediately. If a company that owns a
television station in a market later acquires a daily newspaper in
that market, it can wait until its existing license expires before
seeking a waiver. None of the licenses in Hartford, New York or Los
Angeles expire before 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Appert said he believes that the dual-ownership rules are likely
to be shelved well before then.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Friday's closing stock prices, the offer for Times
Mirror consists of $3.79 billion in common stock and $2.66 billion
in cash. The cash represents a tender for about 28 million shares
at $95 per share, The remaining 40.8 million shares would be
exchanged, with Tribune offering 2.5 shares for each share of Times
Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   In the deal, Tribune was always the suitor. The courtship began
last spring when John Madigan, Tribune's chief executive,
approached Willes to discuss some types of partnership, Willes said
in an interview Monday. But when Madigan raised the prospect of a
merger, Willes said he passed on the offer because he did not
believe that a merger would be acceptable under the terms of the
Chandler Trust, which represents the interests of the Chandler
family in the company. Within days of that discussion, Willes sent
a letter to Madigan telling him so. The two did not discuss the
idea again, said Willes and several other people close to the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Then in October, there was a major distraction for Times Mirror
executives, as a decision by Kathryn M. Downing, Willes' handpicked
successor as publisher of the L.A. Times, provoked a firestorm
within the newsroom. Downing, without the knowledge of the top
editor Michael Parks, agreed with the owners of Staples Center the
new downtown arena that the Times would share the profits of a
special Sunday magazine devoted to coverage of the center's
opening.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing furor, Downing apologized for the apparent
conflict, which she agreed endangered the newspaper's editorial
credibility. Willes also said the move was a mistake, but continued
to back Downing.
</P>
<P>
   That storm was beginning to die down in January, when Madigan
and Fuller approached two Times Mirror trustees, William Stinehart
Jr. and Warren B. Williamson, and asked if they could meet. The two
agreed and, over lunch at the California Club, a restaurant in
downtown Los Angeles, Madigan made a case for combining the two
companies. Stinehart and Williamson, said people close to the
talks, were intrigued by the idea and agreed to present it to
members of the Chandler family.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they also hired bankers from Morgan Stanley to
explore other opportunities. But after a review of possible
partners, Unterman, the adviser to the family, said ``there was no
comparable match with the same breadth or size.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second week of February, a group of trustees went to
Chicago for a day-long presentation by the Tribune Co.'s senior
management. Using charts and graphs, the Tribune executives argued
that combining the Tribune's mix of television and newspaper assets
with Times Mirror's newspapers made sense. As importantly, said
people close to the talks, Tribune executives were suggesting that
they were willing to pay a hefty premium.
</P>
<P>
   The profit potential of the dual newspaper-and-television cities
was ``what caught the Chandler family's interest,'' said Unterman.
Once the trustees returned to Los Angeles, a legal team began
researching whether such a merger was doable under the terms of
their trust.
</P>
<P>
   But Times Mirror was not the only partner the Tribune Co. was
interested in. The company was also holding discussions with
television broadcaster Chris Craft Industries, a 50 percent
stakeholder in the UPN Network. Such a merger would bolster the
Tribune's broadcasting holdings. But ultimately the Tribune Co.
decided against a Chris Craft deal, said a person close to the
talks, because broadcasting properties were easier to buy and an
acquisition would have a negative impact on the company's future
earnings. The Tribune's attention quickly turned to Times Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, trustees for the family trust unanimously voted
to pursue Tribune Publishing's offer, which then included a mix of
stock and cash. (The family preferred stock because the transaction
would be tax-free for them.) But it was only on Feb. 28 that
Stinehart, at the trustees urging, approached Willes about their
intent, said people close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was totally surprised,'' said a person involved in the
talks. ``He was deeply hurt and antagonistic to the idea.'' But
within two weeks, the deal was done and the boards met well into
Sunday night to approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, as Tribune executives spent the day in Los Angeles
answering the questions of analysts and reporters, Times Mirror
journalists from the L.A. Times and Newsday, not to mention The
Baltimore Sun, questioned each other, and their bosses, about their
future. There was concern in some quarters, according to one Times
journalist, about whether the Tribune Co. would offer the same
benefits as Times Mirror.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the gossip, speculation and worry was an undercurrent
of sorrow. ``It is a sad thing, in the sense that endings are
always somewhat sad, and this is the end of an important historical
era,'' said Tim Rutten, the city/county bureau chief at the Times.
``The Chandlers have been an important force in the life of Los
Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``there is a part of Los Angeles still governed
by the ethos of developer _ the quick buck, opportunism and
dynamism that goes with it. We're never been very good here at
stewardship. This is a melancholy example of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unease was widespread. One reporter in a Newsday bureau, who
asked not to be identified, said, ``We could also be getting a new
publisher sitting in Melville, and that could mean changes all down
the line.'' Newsday's headquarters is in Melville, N.Y., on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune executives said in a conference call that they planned
no immediate changes in the executive ranks at any Times mirror
newspaper. And Willes made it clear he had no intention of staying
with the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Madigan, Willes said, ``John has done a really
wonderful job of running that company. I've been used to being CEO
long enough that I'd just as soon not be something other than
CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   Willes, who had been openly emotional in his meetings with
employees during the day, said that his personal disappointment was
that he would not preside over what he believed would be a robust
renewal in the Times' profits, which had fallen below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frankly an enormous personal disappointment that I didn't
have a couple more years to let everybody see how profound the
changes have been and how strong the base is on which were
growing.'' He added, ``What I would like my legacy to be is that I
cared so deeply and so profoundly about the role of newspapers in
society that I was willing to take whatever brickbats or criticism
anybody had to hurl at me, for the sake of finding ways to extend,
significantly extend, both the reach and the breadth and the depth
of what we do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
