<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY LAWMAKERS SEEK SUSPENSION OF GASOLINE TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Responding to the recent jump in the price of
gasoline, legislative leaders from both major parties called Monday
for the suspension or even repeal of the state's gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the leaders of the Democratic-led Assembly and the
Republican-controlled Senate is intended to defuse what many
believe will be a major pocketbook issue in this year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   The price of gasoline has risen sharply over the last few
months, and many lawmakers here and across the nation fear voter
reprisal in November if they do not move to address the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The average price of a gallon of regular unleaded gasoline in
the state is now around $1.50 _ up from about $1.25 in December.
The main reason was a move last year by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries to force up the price of crude oil by
limiting production.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani joined the chorus of
lawmakers Monday calling for elimination of the federal and state
tax on gasoline. He also sought to put Democrats on the defensive,
blaming President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore for the
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who will face Hillary Rodham Clinton in a bid for the
U.S. Senate this year, said that people were being ``absolutely
economically ruined by the policies of the Clinton-Gore
administration with regard to gasoline.''
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, the situation has led to dueling proposals, with
Democrats and Republicans attempting to outflank each other on the
politically charged issue in a year when all 211 members of the
Legislature are up for re-election. But no matter which party gains
the upper hand, consumers are almost certain to benefit, because
legislation seems imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic speaker of the Assembly, Sheldon Silver, made the
opening bid when he proposed eliminating the state's 4 percent
sales tax on gasoline in July and August, the height of the summer
travel season.
</P>
<P>
   Silver urged adoption of the measure Monday, saying it would
save drivers $63 million over the two months and encourage them to
travel to New York's vacation destinations. Silver's plan would
also give all localities the option to eliminate their local share
of the gas tax, which ranges from 3 percent to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a tourist state from eastern Long Island to
Niagara Falls,'' Silver said. ``This proposal will make it more
attractive for people to get in their cars and vacation in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority leader of the Senate, Joseph Bruno,
immediately countered with his own plan, calling for the complete
elimination of the state's sales tax on gasoline. His plan would
save motorists about $300 million a year, and it would also allow
localities to repeal their portion of the tax.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said that the state could afford to provide the tax cut
because his aides estimate that the state will have a budget
surplus of more than $1 billion at the end of the fiscal year. ``We
think that that money really belongs to the taxpayers,'' Bruno said
of the surplus. ``We have to come up with appropriate ways to
return it to the taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan is the latest in a rapidly growing list of tax-cut
proposals and spending items that the lawmakers have placed on
their agenda even before budget negotiations have begun in earnest.
The measures will likely lead to weeks, if not months, of
maneuvering between the two houses and Gov. George E. Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, Pataki, a Republican, said that he, too,
favored the elimination of the state's gasoline tax. But he warned
that there had to be trade-offs for it in the negotiations over a
new state budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the strength of the state's economy,'' he said, ``we
could afford a tax cut that would get rid of the state's sales tax
on gasoline for years to come, but not if we're going to go on
spending binges in other areas, not if we're going to pass other
massive tax cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats in the Assembly also called Monday for a $1.3
billion rise in state spending in aid to schools, more than triple
the increase that Pataki has proposed, setting the stage for a
protracted budget fight.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans in the Senate, for their part, proposed a $900
million increase in state spending for primary and secondary
education, placing even greater pressure on Pataki to move well
beyond the $355 million, or 2.8 percent, increase he has proposed
for schools.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Democrats are also proposing that the state
provide $500 million to help school districts across the state
repair or replace crumbling buildings. ``It makes sense to invest
in our children,'' Silver said Monday afternoon as he unveiled his
education plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
