A5941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FALL-FASHION-ART-NYT &LR;      03-13 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FALL, LADYLIKE CHIC, MINUS THE STARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After being abroad in the land of fashion, with a suitcase and
Marianne Faithfull singing ``The Ballad of Lucy Jordan'' in your
head as you drive around Paris, it is hard to come back to New York
and the reality of clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Paris changes your perspective every six months, or at least
reminds you that the reason people follow fashion as they would a
twister hurtling across a plain, churning up everything in its
path, is that it produces emotions that can transcend such mundane
questions as ``What will I wear tomorrow?'' Fashion in Paris, and
to a lesser extent in Milan and New York, asks the question, ``Who
do I want to be?''
</P>
<P>
   That was the spirit, if not the message, of the fall 2000
ready-to-wear season, which, for the buyers and journalists who
attended the shows _ and who will spend the next few months placing
orders or deciding which looks they want to promote _ ended 10 days
ago in Paris. Certainly a lot of retailers came away from the
collections with a sense of optimism. After the Chanel show, with
its almost jubilant flaunting of scarves and other feminine symbols
that haven't been seen on the runway in a while, Tina Johnson, the
president and chief executive of Saks Fifth Avenue, said, ``I think
a woman is going to feel beautiful again.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Kaner, the fashion director of Neiman Marcus, expressed a
similar sentiment, saying, ``I think there's a real return to
pulled-together dressing.'' By this she meant a proliferation of
suits with coordinated blouses or turtlenecks, stockings with
open-toed shoes or spiky sandals, and coats _ with fur, with
gold-embellished belts or just swinging open in plain tweed _
coats, in any case, that say, ``I'm a put-together girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Gilhart, a longtime buyer for Barneys New York, singled
out the collections of Yves Saint Laurent and Dries van Noten for
their sense of refinement and color, and said of Viktor &AMP; Rolf's
first ready-to-wear collection: ``I tried on a lot of their coats.
They make you feel as if you're standing two inches taller.'' She
added: ``I think the designers who really grab your attention are
the younger ones, like Viktor &AMP; Rolf and Nicolas Ghesquiere at
Balenciaga. It's the people who don't have six collections under
their wing. They're just doing their own thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, what Gilhart and her retail sisters are saying is
that the collections that succeeded are the ones that give you the
possibility to be something else _ to be beautiful, to look like
the quintessential coordinated lady heading off to Le Cirque 2000,
or to simply feel a few inches taller.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Chanel show, which for many summed up the
collections, with its chaotic mix of separates, its lanky sense of
sophistication and its open-ended interpretation of what is
feminine, Karl Lagerfeld said: ``In the past, the shows used to
relate to life. Now, the moment they relate to life, they look too
commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   So even a designer as established as Lagerfeld knows he has to
push things. It is true that many of the shows this season seemed
calibrated to get people's attention by presenting clothes that
were pointedly, even extravagantly, unwearable, like those in John
Galliano's show, which were purposefully oversized to make the
models appear as though they were wearing Mommy's swanky threads.
</P>
<P>
   But if you were to place in the hands of a mildly interested
fashion observer two photographs, one of a perfectly nice tweed
coat and the other of a coat trimmed fancifully with fur and
dragging indifferently across the ground, as if the occupant were a
weary romantic waif _ Mimi of ``La Boheme'' _ the odds are the
person would choose the latter as the more interesting. The fact
that the new fall fashion can elicit a purely emotional response,
beyond questions of commerce or practicality, is the most powerful
message of all. Who do you want to be?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a lot of themes emerged from the shows. Expect to see
an abundance of tweeds and houndstooth checks, often in blown-up
configurations, like those in John Bartlett's show. Just about
every designer, it seemed, dabbled in herringbone _ Marc Jacobs,
Tom Ford at Gucci _ while chevron stripes and old-fashioned argyle
patterns turned up in fur and knits, most vividly at Michael Kors.
Separates in crocodile and intarsia _ a technique of piecing
together fabrics to form a printlike pattern _ were ubiquitous, but
likely to be costly.
</P>
<P>
   Suits are making a comeback, though it remains to be seen if
women, only recently liberated from their jackets, will accept the
notion of a structured look, predominantly in a single color like
charcoal or camel. Some of the new suits and coat dresses, with
their razor-sharp shoulders and neat-as-a-pin sobriety, strangely
conjured up images of secretaries or 1960s-era airplane hostesses.
Both Gilhart and Andre Leon Talley, editor at large of Vogue, said
they detected something of this in Ghesquiere's suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually used navy blue, which is not a color we saw a lot
of,'' Gilhart said. As it happens, Cristobal Balenciaga, in the
60's, designed flight attendant uniforms for Air France.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Susan Cianciolo seemed to be on a similar
wavelength with her plain, almost wholesome version of dressing up.
But such clothes require a knowledge of the arcane subtleties of
fashion, which are usually too obscure or marginal to put across
without sounding like an idiot. As Gilhart advised, in retail
parlance, ``You have to have a really good sense of direction.''
</P>
<P>
   A more accessible look, one advanced with convincing clarity by
Jil Sander, is a slim monochromatic suit with the skirt pegged to
just below the knees and worn with high heels of a slightly 1940's
genre. At the opposite extreme of the suit and silhouette story
were Lagerfeld's jackets (or knee-length coats) over a fuller
skirt. Lagerfeld has been touting the idea of wearing a fitted,
small-shouldered jacket with a more voluminous skirt for the last
couple of collections, including his spring haute couture show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time,'' Kaner of Neiman Marcus said, ``he got it right.''
The look is softer.
</P>
<P>
   By now, one probably has heard enough about ladylike chic to
have developed an aversion toward it. Obviously there are a lot of
ways to approach this style _ with a sense of let-them-eat-cake
luxury, with a sense of camp (think Gucci's quilted caramel leather
coat with overtones of early 1970's jet-set glam).
</P>
<P>
   Or with the knowing spirit of individuality. The telling detail
of Miuccia Prada's collection was the simple grosgrain ribbons _
the kind you used to find in the waistbands of skirts _ that closed
many of the coats. The effect hinted of something poor, raw.
</P>
<P>
   At Balenciaga, the unfinished element was the fraying edge of a
blouse, the tattered bits of yarn and fur piled on the shoulders of
a top. At Comme des Garcons, it was a jacket bursting with stuffing
_ another myth, another image of women exploded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
