<HEADLINE>
MALCOLM WILSON, FORMER GOVERNOR OF NEW YORK, IS DEAD AT 86 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Malcolm Wilson, who spent 15 years as Nelson A. Rockefeller's
lieutenant governor and one year as governor of New York, died
Monday at his daughter's home in New Rochelle, N.Y.. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Long the understudy (and after 36 years of state service in
all), Wilson finally became governor in November 1973, when
Rockefeller resigned, and inherited a growing fiscal crisis. A year
later, Wilson was swept from office in the post-Watergate
Democratic landslide, losing to Hugh L. Carey by more than 800,000
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a consummate parliamentarian, Wilson spent 20 years in
the State Assembly and then, as lieutenant governor, presided over
the State Senate. His command of the rules was such that, even as
they complained, Democrats could not help but express admiration
for Wilson's political skills.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who often lapsed into Latin and kept an unfailingly
cheerful mien in public, often gave the impression of being too
erudite, too much the gentleman and too lacking in concern for
appearances to play the roughhouse game of politics. In the
mid-1970s, he refused his aides' pleas to give up the narrow ties
he wore, then badly out of fashion, insisting that they were still
perfectly good.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George E. Pataki on Monday described Wilson as ``a
wonderful human being,'' who, to his detriment, disdained talk of
politics and the careful positioning politicians engage in. He
recalled that in the 1974 campaign, reporters peppered the governor
with questions about President Ford's pardon of Richard M. Nixon.
Wilson disagreed with the pardon, said Pataki _ who was then a
young lawyer working on Republican campaigns _ but Wilson would not
say so because he thought it irrelevant to his post.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of political issues that could have been
attractive and could have helped him in the campaign,'' Pataki
said. ``But what he wanted to focus on was policy.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, at age 24, Wilson was first elected to the Assembly
from a district that included his hometown, Yonkers. Using skills
acquired as a member of the Fordham University debating team and an
eye for detail, he became known for his ability to get his bills
passed. One of the best known created the Higher Education
Assistance Corp., which made college loans widely available for the
first time in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, he threw in his lot with Rockefeller, scion of the
nation's wealthiest family, who had never before run for office.
Wilson became a political tour guide of sorts, driving Rockefeller
about the state to introduce him to local chieftains eager for a
fresh candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly and just the two of them, they made the rounds in
Wilson's own car in order not to flaunt the novice's immense
wealth. Wilson sold his man, who then insisted that Wilson be
chosen as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Some looked upon Rockefeller as a sacrificial lamb to run
against Gov. W. Averell Harriman, the Democratic incumbent. But
Rockefeller beat the odds and Wilson stood in his shadow for the
next nearly 15 years. Although the law severely limits the
lieutenant governor's executive functions, Rockefeller put Wilson's
vast expertise and connections to use by making him a member of his
inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   Through those years, the two men publicly differed on only one
issue of principle. Unlike Governor Rockefeller, Wilson _ a Roman
Catholic _ opposed the legalization of abortion. He was generally
considered a conservative but, rejecting such political labeling,
he defined himself as ``an economic conservative and a human-rights
liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Forever loyal, he never spoke ill of the ever-upward spiral of
spending and debt under Rockefeller that led to the fiscal crisis,
though friends and aides said it doubtless contradicted his own
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   As the enduring No. 2, Wilson always presented a proper, for the
most part amiable, face to the world. At the same time, it was no
secret in Albany that he would not mind dropping the ``lieutenant''
from his title once Rockefeller moved on to indulge his well-known
higher ambitions. As he waited, Wilson presided over the Senate
with a ready gavel and an intimidating command of Robert's Rules of
Order.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his mastery of the state budget, Wilson had a hand in
shaping the Governor's priorities. It was he who persuaded
Rockefeller to press for federal revenue sharing to help states
that were in financial straits, an idea Rockefeller successfully
pushed after Nixon won the White House in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   At age 59, Wilson, by then a grandfather, got his big chance
when Rockefeller, his presidential ambitions thwarted, grew bored
with state government and resigned. (The following year, President
Ford named Rockfeller as his vice president).
</P>
<P>
   One of Wilson's worries as governor was the growing practice by
local governments, particularly New York City, of financing local
government expenses with a dubious array of fiscal gimmickry. At
one point, he admonished, there must come the day of reckoning, as
New York City soon learned when it came near financial collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But the first piece of the fiscal crisis to break into view
occurred in Wilson's own bailiwick, at the state's Urban
Development Corp., which flirted with bankruptcy _ an issue Carey
used against him in the 1974 campaign. After taking office, Carey
accused his predecessor of having tried to hide the severity of the
crisis, and asserted that Wilson's outgoing administration had
granted him ``limited access and little rapport'' during the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   After losing office, Wilson was at first an active political
fund-raiser and a sought-after speaker at party functions. But
increasingly, liberal Rockefeller Republicanism fell from favor,
and Wilson faded from the political scene. He returned to his law
practice and served as chairman and chief executive officer of the
Manhattan Bank for Savings from 1977 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, the former Katharine McCloskey, died in 1980. In 1991,
Wilson underwent surgery for an aortic aneurysm, then experienced
serious complications. Since then, he had lived with his daughter
Katharine Wilson Conroy, a lawyer and former member of the New
Rochelle City Council. In addition to Conroy, he is survived by
another daughter, Anne Matthews of Freehold, N.J., and six
grandsons.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Malcolm Wilson was born Feb. 26, 1914, in New York City,
one of four children in a family of Irish and Scottish ancestry.
His first name eventually disappeared, to distinguish him from his
father, Charles H. Wilson, a patent attorney who had made an
unsuccessful run for the Assembly in 1912. His mother, Agnes,
served as a member of national Republican women's groups and as a
district party leader in Yonkers, where the family moved in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Wilson graduated from Fordham Preparatory School at 15,
Fordham College at 19 and Fordham Law School at 22, in 1936. He
spent his entire legal career with the White Plains firm that would
become Kent, Hazzard, Jaeger, Greer, Wilson &AMP; Fay, becoming a
partner in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   He enlisted in the Navy in 1943 and oversaw a gun crew on an
ammunition ship that shuttled across the Atlantic and supported the
landings at Normandy and Anzio. He kept his Assembly seat, winning
re-election in absentia, and returned to New York in 1945 with the
rank of lieutenant junior grade.
</P>
<P>
   As a government official, aides said, Wilson was addicted to
detail and studied tomes of reports that caused lesser mortals to
doze off. His discourses on the affairs of state tended to be
soporific, although no Albany insider would have disputed his
ability to grapple with complex issues.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wilson had a distaste for the oversimplification so
common to politics. Beware of simple answers, he warned, quoting
the Swiss historian Jacob Burkhardt: ``The essence of tyranny is
the denial of complexity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
