<SLUG> BC-NY-MALPRACTICE-DOCTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI AND BRUNO BACK BILL TO LET PATIENTS SEE MALPRACTICE DATA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George E. Pataki and the majority leader of
the State Senate, Joseph L. Bruno, threw their support Monday
behind a proposed law that would give patients access to
information about doctors whose insurance companies had settled
malpractice claims against them.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, Bruno and Pataki, both Republicans, joined
Democratic Assembly leaders who passed a similar proposal last
year. That proposal died in the Senate, where Bruno tightly
controls all legislation, and many Democrats concluded that Bruno
had opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno, though, said the issue was still being worked out.
``We've always had an interest in helping patients get access to
information they ought to have,'' he said. ``We've sort of been
there, but somehow, these things are hard to put together, and be
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said Monday that he also supported the creation of a
database of malpractice records. Several lawmakers said he had
signaled his approval in earlier conversations with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept I think is important, that if some doctor has a
horrendous record, that a patient can get that information,''
Pataki said. ``Now, the details have to be worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno and Pataki have made their endorsements while a diverse
group of patients and advocacy groups have demanded the right to
obtain confidential information about doctors. Under current law,
malpractice settlements are frequently not made public, and
information about lawsuits can be scattered in several counties.
Hospitals' disciplinary actions against doctors are usually kept
confidential.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed law to make such records available to the public,
commonly known as Lisa's Law, is named for Lisa Smart, who died in
1997 during routine gynecological surgery at Beth Israel Medical
Center in Manhattan. An assisting surgeon during the operation, Dr.
Marc Sklar, was on probation with the state at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Sen. Kemp Hannon, a Republican from Nassau County and
chairman of the Health Committee, submitted a bill that critics
said did not go as far as the Assembly's bill in disclosing
confidential information about doctors. It would require only the
disclosure of a verdict in a malpractice case, even though most
claims are settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   Hannon said Monday that he would amend his bill to extend the
disclosure requirement to malpractice settlements after consulting
with Senate leaders. ``It's a question of getting agreement from
all parts of the Senate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael S. Murphy, a spokesman for the Medical Society of New
York, which represents 30,000 licensed doctors, said the society
opposed releasing information about individual malpractice claims
because it could be misinterpreted. ``Our concern is, taken
individually, malpractice cases bear no correlation to physician
competence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But several advocacy groups praised political leaders Monday for
taking a step toward protecting patients' rights and improving
health care. ``Both the governor and senate majority leader have
correctly diagnosed the problem,'' said Blair Horner, legislative
director for the New York Public Interest Research Group.
``Consumers need better access to information.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
