<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS TRADE TALKS HIT SNAG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ The Angels' search for starting pitching became
that much tougher over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees continue to have interest in Jim Edmonds
because they are short in the outfield, but their concerns about
the pitching staff have become just as big, diminishing the Angels'
chances of getting Ramiro Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Ed Yarnell, whom the Yankees are counting on to win a
job in the starting rotation, was hammered for 10 runs and eight
hits in one inning. It was his first start of the spring because
he's been bothered by back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, who can both start and pitch out of the bullpen, is
insurance for Yarnell, as well as 37-year-old David Cone. But even
if the Yankees don't need him to fill a need in the starting
rotation, Mendoza is a vital part of their bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Yankees are not happy with their current
situation in left field _ a platoon of Ricky Ledee and Shane
Spencer _ Yankees manager Joe Torre is saying he'd settle for the
current state of the outfield in order to keep the pitching staff
intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, pitching is what our strength has been,'' Torre told
the New York writers. ``Can we become a better offensive team?
Possibly. But at the expense of your strengths? Then you have to
make a decision. ... I'm a little reluctant to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to trade Mendoza, Yankees GM Brian Cashman is now
talking with other clubs in the hopes of putting together a deal
involving the Yankees, Angels and a third club.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Edmonds continues to live in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says I'm going to be traded, but the front office
says I'm not,'' Edmonds said. ``Who do you believe?''
</P>
<P>
   ORTIZ HURTING: Pitcher Ramon Ortiz will travel to Los Angeles
today to be examined by Dr. Lewis Yocum. Ortiz, counted on to be in
the starting rotation, was scratched from his scheduled start
Monday against the Chicago Cubs because of stiffness in his right
arm.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz threw about 30 warmup pitches when he told manager Mike
Scioscia and pitching coach Bud Black that his arm didn't feel
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't seem very serious, but it's spring right now,''
Scioscia said. ''He had a little bit of discomfort trying to get
loose. He's been throwing very good and very hard. It was good to
take a step back.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
