<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAMPAIGN FINANCE BATTLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, March 14:
</P>
<P>
   The general election campaign has gotten off to an unusually
fast start, and it has done so under a cloud of suspicion created
by Attorney General Janet Reno's incompetent and politically biased
response to the campaign finance abuses of the 1996 campaign. The
prospective Republican nominee, Gov. George W. Bush, has every
right to take advantage of news reports that Reno protected Vice
President Al Gore from the searching inquiry recommended by senior
Justice Department officials. That said, Bush's fully justified
criticism of Clinton-Gore fund-raising in 1996 should not divert
attention from the fact that in the 2000 campaign debate Gore is
right about how to fix the campaign finance laws, and Bush is
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has learned the hard way about the need for reform. He let
himself be used by President Clinton to raise huge amounts of soft
money. He will be haunted the rest of his career by his appearance
at the Buddhist temple and by his assertion that there was ``no
controlling legal authority'' to prevent fund-raising telephone
calls from the White House. Since the independent counsel law has
lapsed, any lingering questions about the 1996 campaign should be
resolved by the Justice Department's campaign finance task force
under new leadership chosen from the department's professional
ranks. If Gore has legal liabilities there, he will have to address
them.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, voters should insist that Bush match the commitments
being made by Gore __ as well as Bill Bradley and John McCain _ to
fix the existing law. The vice president wants to outlaw unlimited
soft money contributions to the parties by corporations, unions and
wealthy individuals and to move toward full public financing. Bush
opposes public financing and has even chosen not to accept the
spending limits set under current law as a requirement for getting
federal funds. Bush would also exclude wealthy individuals from the
ban on soft money contributions, a step that would keep the special
interest money flowing.
</P>
<P>
   There was a clear tactical imperative to Gore's admitting to his
1996 fund-raising ``mistakes.'' But that does not detract from the
importance of his pledge to make campaign finance reform a major
theme of his campaign. His promise means that even with Bradley and
McCain out of the race, the nation's election laws will remain at
the top of the issues agenda for 2000. Gore needs to improve his
proposals by suggesting new enforcement powers for the Federal
Election Commission, which would help prevent future attorneys
general from blocking investigations of their own party. Bush, for
his part, needs to couple his criticism of Gore with proposals that
would really improve campaign finance laws instead of perpetuating
loopholes for the wealthy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
