<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALFRED NEAL, 87, AN ECONOMIST WHO INFLUENCED TRADE POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alfred C. Neal, an economist whose interest in developing the
global economy influenced United States trade policy in the 1950s
and 1960s, died March 8. He was 87 years old and lived in Sarasota,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal, who was one of 11 children, got early exposure to
free-enterprise realities when he was 10 years old and began
delivering milk, using a pony and a cart, to other families in his
hometown of Kentfield, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   As a college student, he arrived at the University of
California's Berkeley campus in 1929, just weeks before the stock
market crash that led to the Great Depression. As a result, Dr.
Neal's career became focused around the prevention of similar
catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the economic theory at the time contended that
peacetime economies were doomed to failure, Dr. Neal worked to find
alternatives to war that would permit businesses to flourish. Among
those was the concept of a controlled recession that would affect
some people, but not all, for a brief period of time, and prevent
deeper economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   After Berkeley, he studied at the London School of Economics,
where Harold Laski, the political theorist and socialist, was one
of his professors. Dr. Neal earned his doctorate from Brown
University.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II he worked at the Office of Price
Administration, moving on to the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the war he became the first president of the
Committee for Economic Development, a nonprofit organization of
economists and company executives that tried to foster progress
around the world. He worked with many prominent economists,
including Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal's sister, Carolyn N. Hedley, said: ``The Depression
left deep impressions on Al. When he graduated from Berkeley, all
of the graduation speakers just spoke in despair and said we
couldn't live without wars, that if you didn't have a war raging
the economy would go to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   With Arthur Burns and Donald Watson, Dr. Neal wrote ``Modern
Economics,'' which became widely used in the 1940's as a basic
textbook. He retired in 1976 from the Committee on Economic
Development, and is credited with influencing the creation of the
European Economic Community; helping to rebuild the German and
Japanese economies after World War II; and getting the United
States off the gold standard. He advised President Dwight D.
Eisenhower, President John F. Kennedy and President Lyndon B.
Johnson on trade as a member of several commissions.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the Committee on Economic Development, ``he was
unique in his ability to bridge the gap between the ivory tower and
the marketplace,'' said Sol Hurwitz, who worked with Dr. Neal on
the committee. ``He brought business leaders together with
economists, and the two sides actually developed a healthy respect
for one another _ and they learned from one another,'' Hurwitz
said.
</P>
<P>
   He took pride in the committee's counterparts in Japan, Germany,
and Sweden, among other countries, and worked to strengthen them.
He also had a knack for persuading the committee's trustees to come
to an agreement on something. ``He didn't simply wait for a
consensus to unfold,'' Hurwitz said. ``With a twinkle in his eye,
he would tell them what the consensus ought to be and would bring
them around to his way of thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the office, Dr. Neal, who had no children, loved to
entertain with clambakes held in his backyard in Harrison, N.Y.,
where he lived for many years before moving to Sarasota in 1997. He
was also knowledgeable about wine, and shared his insights with his
siblings. ``After a while, we knew a good Margaux,'' Dr. Hedley
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Dr. Hedley, of Sarasota, he is survived by three
sisters, Stella Hadley, of Petaluma, Calif.; Rose Nelson of Azalea,
Ore.; and Jeanne Doellstedt of Richmond, Calif.; and two brothers,
William, of Novato, Calif., and James, of Santa Rosa, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-13-00 2316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000313.0496 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-13 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-PRIMARY-BALLOT-475     03-13 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRIMARY-BALLOT-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI URGES REVAMPING OF GOP PRESIDENTIAL PRIMARY RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki on Monday urged a revision of
the presidential primary rules that so embarrassed his Republican
Party this year, proposing to make the ballot simpler and to make
it far easier for candidates to enter contests.
</P>
<P>
   But one change that he proposed could meet resistance in the
Legislature. It would make New York's primary a winner-take-all
Republican contest like California's, an idea opposed by the state
Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's bill would put all recognized candidates on the
ballot, ending the requirement that they gather thousands of
signatures, a certain number in each congressional district. That
process has proved difficult for many candidates, particularly
insurgents, and has been described as the most difficult system in
any state for getting on the primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's bill would also eliminate the listing of delegates'
names on the ballot _ with the candidates listed below in tiny
print _ in favor of having voters cast their ballots directly for
candidates. The structure of the ballot in the March 7 primary was
widely derided as confusing and intended to benefit the party
favorite, George W. Bush, who had the best-known slate of
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a week ago, the governor's aides had said they
were unsure that he would act on the matter at all and that there
was no hurry because the next presidential primary was now four
years away. But last week, his fellow Republican, Bruno, called his
party's primary system ``absolute nonsense'' and said he would seek
to change it, whether the governor did so or not.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he had decided to move quickly, after all,
Pataki, speaking at a news conference in the Capitol, said: ``It's
the right thing to do. Obviously, there's no primary for four
years, but why not do it now?''
</P>
<P>
   In most respects, Pataki's proposal jibes with Bruno's, and if
experience is any guide, they are likely to reach a compromise this
year. Bruno said Monday that he had not seen the governor's
proposal but that he generally liked the sound of it.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said last week that he did not favor a winner-take-all
system. In fact, he said, he disliked the fact that New York's
system had awarded Bush 67 delegates and 26 to Sen. John McCain,
though the popular vote was much closer, 50 percent to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, each party gives the others free reign to set
their own ballot access rules, so that if Bruno and Pataki reach
some agreement, the Democrats who control the state Assembly would
go along with it. Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver's office declined
to comment Monday on the governor's bill. The Democrats'
presidential primary rules are much like what the governor has
proposed for the Republicans, though the primary is not a
winner-take-all contest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ballot access first became a political issue in the 1996
campaign, when the state's Republican establishment, united behind
Bob Dole's presidential campaign, tried to keep Steve Forbes off
the primary ballot. After taking considerable abuse over that
effort, Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, then the state's most powerful
Republican, and Pataki, both seeming contrite, said the rules
should be changed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the state eliminated many of the highly technical rules
for gathering petitions to win a place on the Republican ballot. In
1999, the state cut the number of signatures needed by 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as McCain found this year, obstacles remained. It is hard
for an insurgent to find the troops to circulate petitions, and
hard to find enough Republicans in some districts to sign them.
There are also many surviving technical rules that allow an
opponent to challenge petitions in court, in the hope of knocking a
candidate off the ballot: the person signing must list the city or
town of residence, not the village; the person circulating the
petition must live in the same congressional district as the people
signing that petition.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of Pataki, who headed the Bush campaign in New
York, the Republican State Committee went to court to challenge
McCain's petitions in the hope of knocking him off the ballot in
many parts of the state. But a federal judge ruled against the
entire system and ordered McCain placed on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   With good-government groups and newspaper editorials railing
against New York's system, McCain turned it into a potent symbol of
the fear with which some party leaders viewed his underdog
candidacy. He derisively referred to New York's governor and its
Republican Party chief, William D. Powers, as ``Comrade Pataki and
Comrade Powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the governor's plan, any candidate who has qualified for
federal matching funds, or who is deemed by the state Board of
Elections to be a generally recognized candidate, would win an
automatic place on the ballot. Candidates who do not make it
through either of those routes could still reach the ballot through
the difficult petition process.
</P>
<P>
   Good-government groups that have demanded such election changes
welcomed Pataki's proposal. But they asserted that it should be
extended to elections for state offices, where a dizzying array of
highly technical rules are still used to keep challengers off the
ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
