u a BC-NY-MURDER-NYT &LR;      03-13 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS TO DNA AND FAMILY'S PERSISTENCE, MAN IS CHARGED IN A 1979
MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ When Carolyn Gregory appealed to an old
friend in public office to help reopen the 20-year-old case of her
sister's unsolved murder, it was not the advent of new DNA-matching
technology that inspired her. It was the ache of another year gone
with no answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get it resolved before her daughter Lakisha's 23rd
birthday, because her mother did not see her own 23rd birthday,''
said Gregory, whose sister, Diane, was killed at 22. ``Lakisha
wanted to have a dinner to mark the occasion and I wanted to have
some information to give her.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Gregory got her wish. She was told that DNA collected
from bloody linens and a shard of glass found in her sister's
apartment matched a DNA sample taken from a jailed robber, Walter
Gill. It was the first DNA match in a cold murder case _ unsolved
and inactive _ since legislation was passed last fall allowing the
state to create a criminal offender databank from DNA samples of
convicted felons.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the first news in the murder case that Gregory had
heard in decades. In August 1979, her sister, Diane Gregory, the
single mother of Lakisha, then 2, was found stabbed to death in her
apartment on South Second Avenue in Mount Vernon, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   At first there were leads, and the police kept the Gregory
family informed. Carolyn Gregory, just a year older than her
sister, took on the job of helping her distraught mother cope and
raising Lakisha. After a year, there were no arrests, no more leads
and no more calls from the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard,'' said Gregory, 44, who attended a news
conference here Monday in which the Westchester district attorney,
Jeanine F. Pirro, announced that Gill would be charged with
intentional murder. Gov. George E. Pataki also attended, and called
for expanding the DNA database and eliminating the statute of
limitations for some felonies.
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to her mother, Pauline, and her niece, Lakisha,
Gregory fought back tears and said she was grateful that a suspect
had finally been named.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part of this was having her daughter grow up
without a mom and not knowing who did this,'' said Gregory, who
wore a gold pendant shaped like a broken heart that read ``Big
Sis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was a suspect,'' she said. ``We assumed that it was
someone she knew that we knew. We never felt safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in September, Gregory, an administrator for a turnstile
manufacturer, called her old friend, Steven D. Horton, who is now a
Mount Vernon councilman. Horton went to school with the Gregory
sisters and lived around the corner from them. He is Lakisha's
godfather.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Horton kept in touch with the Gregorys, who
moved to New Rochelle soon after the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called me and said it was the 20th anniversary of Diane's
murder,'' Horton said. ``It dawned on me that the family hadn't
really put it behind them in all that time. I had gone on with the
business of living, but the family hadn't been able to turn the
page.''
</P>
<P>
   So in the fall, Horton went to see Mount Vernon's police
commissioner, Gertrude LaForgia, who was just putting together a
cold case squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to laugh,'' Commissioner LaForgia said. ``I said, `We
just put together a case squad going back to 1980 and now you are
asking me to go back to 1979.'''
</P>
<P>
   She put the Gregory case on the list at just about the time the
criminal offender database was approved. Gill, who has been
convicted of nine felonies and eight misdemeanors since 1969 and is
serving a 10- to 20-year term in Sing Sing Correctional Facility in
Ossining, was among the first group of inmates asked for blood
samples.
</P>
<P>
   Gill, 49, knew Gregory, though the police would not disclose the
nature of their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that Gill knew, when the blood was taken a few
months ago, that he would be caught,'' Pirro said. ``He wasn't
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he confessed to the murder, said Commissioner LaForgia,
who would not discuss a motive.
</P>
<P>
   When Lakisha turns 23 on April 9, she will have the dinner party
she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think now it will probably be a little larger than we
thought,'' Gregory said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
