<HEADER>
A6091 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NASA-MISSIONS-HNS &LR;      03-13 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-MISSIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA'S MARS FAILURES PUT UNDER MICROSCOP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cheaper, faster, better strategy that successfully propelled
NASA to Mars with a small roving robot three years ago crumbled
just as spectacularly because it took success for granted,
according to two reports released by the agency Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The more exhaustive study, conducted by a nine-member panel led
by Marshall Space Flight Center Director Art Stephenson, was
initiated after the losses of NASA's Mars Polar Lander on Dec. 3
and the Mars Climate Orbiter on Sept. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Valued at a combined $372 million, the two failures have thrown
into disarray NASA's long-term efforts to determine whether Mars
was once warm and wet enough to support life. The program gathered
public and political momentum July 4, 1997, when NASA's $262
million Pathfinder mission reached an ancient Martian watershed
with a small camera-equipped robotic rover.
</P>
<P>
   NASA Administrator Dan Goldin pledged to make changes in
response to the findings released Monday, but he vowed to stick
with the strategy he brought to the agency in 1992 of stepping up
the frequency of planetary missions by scaling back costs of
expensive missions.
</P>
<P>
   A year after his arrival at NASA, the agency lost a $1 billion
orbital probe as it neared Mars when a fuel line ruptured.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people have said loudly and clearly they desire a
government which costs less and does more. NASA has heard that
message and embarked on a fundamental cultural change over the last
several years,'' Goldin said. ``We knew this change would not be
easy. These reviews have identified where we can and must do
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldin has assigned NASA's chief engineer, Brian Keegan, to
coordinate the development of a corrective strategy by mid-summer.
Much of the effort will borrow from Monday's second report,
compiled by Tony Spear, who managed the Pathfinder mission before
he retired from NASA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to slow down, not rush too quickly into important
programs and projects, plan and implement them more carefully, and
move away from fixations on cost and near-term gain,'' Spear said.
He urged NASA to do more to foster the risk assessment skills of
its future managers.
</P>
<P>
   The reviews of the recent Mars probe failures concluded that
NASA had become too absorbed with meeting cost and schedule
objectives as it attempted ever more ambitious missions. The
failure to assess the risks with sufficient vigor was accompanied
by a lack of engineering oversight, lapses in communication among
top managers and failures to deal with a shortage of experienced
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The oversights caused the Climate Orbiter to reach Mars after a
nine-month journey from Earth on a trajectory that was too low as
it attempted to maneuver into orbit. The spacecraft either broke up
in the thin Martian atmosphere or skipped off into a useless orbit
around the sun.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the same team of investigators determined that an
embarrassing mix-up between NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory and
its contractor, Lockheed Martin Astronautics, over the use of
metric and English measurements led to the navigational errors.
</P>
<P>
   The error in trajectory went undetected and built up gradually
over time through the frequent maneuvers required by the Climate
Orbiter during its lengthy journey from Earth. The probe's
asymmetric shape required the frequent maneuvers, a factor the
investigators found was not communicated to the mission's
navigational experts by the probe's designers.
</P>
<P>
   The oversight was compounded by confusion among workers and
managers over their responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``To exacerbate this situation, the mission was understaffed,
with virtually no Jet Propulsion Laboratory oversight of Lockheed
Martin Astronautics' subsystem developments,'' the report
concluded. ``Thus, as the mission work force was reduced and focus
shifted from spacecraft development to operations, several
mission-critical functions _ such as navigation and software
validation _ received insufficient management oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   The space agency has yet to report on the cause of the Polar
Lander's loss _ investigators may be unable to pinpoint the cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander was last heard from moments before it was to
separate from the rocket stage that delivered it from Earth and
begin its high-speed descent to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   As a cost- and weight-saving measure, the spacecraft was not
equipped with a radio transmitter that could have relayed
information on the spacecraft's fate. Nor was it equipped with a
radar system that would have enabled the spacecraft to maneuver
away from hazardous terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The probe was designed to land on the Martian south pole with
small braking rockets. Equipped with a robot arm, the Polar Lander
was to dig into the terrain in search of suspected frozen water in
the subsoil.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's report, investigators faulted the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory for failing to engage veteran spacecraft engineers,
quality assurance personnel and other experts from outside the core
Climate Orbiter and Polar Lander teams in the two missions until
the Climate Orbiter loss.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency has yet to formulate a change in its Mars
exploration efforts in the wake of the two losses. However, plans
to use robots to gather Martian rock and soil samples and return to
Earth by 2008 now appear unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest budget, NASA will seek money to begin work on a
network of communications satellites around Mars that could be used
to improve the success of future missions.
</P>
<P>
   At least one expert believes NASA must improve the way it
conducts its low-cost missions if it wishes to continue its studies
of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of faster, better, cheaper is not that you do
things sloppy,'' said Louis Friedman, the director of the Planetary
Society, a private, California-based, pro-space organization whose
founders include the late astronomer Carl Sagan. ``You have to go
back to the basics and do what people want from NASA. They want it
to be cutting edge, taking risks and exploring the frontier. But
they want a competent NASA.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
