<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER14-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVENTURES IN THE SKIN TRADE  &HT;       
  
</HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT OSTLER  
 c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today only, feel free to stop just about anybody on the streets of
San Francisco and ask him or her about that troublesome pimple on
your chin.
<P>
   Chances are, he or she will be a dermatologist, 15,000 of whom
wrap up their convention in town Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They're not all in the cosmetic end of the biz, but many of them
are wrinkle shrinkers, and they have been studying at the feet of
Dr. Seth Matarasso, whose office is known to every celeb and
socialite in the city as the Fountain of Youth.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest face-fix substance is botox, botulism toxin, which
is injected into muscles in the upper face, paralyzing them and
causing wrinkles to disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Matarasso goes through more boxcars of botox per year than
any other doctor in America, except for one guy in Miami. I'm
trying to persuade Dr. M to write his story, ``Pumping Botox.''
</P>
<P>
   He says the big trend in faces is the quick fix, because a lot
of people can't hide out in Acapulco while the scars heal.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you'd like to invest in my new chain of drive-thru
wrinkle-relaxing clinics: Botox-in-the-Box.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; THE OPERATOR  &LR; of Becky Mertens' BART train from the East Bay
announced Monday morning, ``Attention BART passengers: For your
safety and the safety of others, please do not put your head
between the train doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some guy just likes the wind in his face.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; O.J. FAME:  &LR; The gift that keeps on giving.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fuhrman, the infamous ex-L.A. police detective and a
co-star of the O.J. Simpson trial, was in San Francisco over the
weekend promoting his new book.
</P>
<P>
   Fuhrman popped into Andrea E Soci Custom Tailoring on Union
Square and dropped a couple thou on a pair of Italian-fabric suits.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mark and tailor Andi Valo sauntered over to Postrio, maybe
the city's best restaurant, for a long lunch discussion about
Mark's wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Read that and other heartwarming stories of Simpson-trial
characters in my upcoming book, ``Thank$ a Million, O.J.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DANCE WITH PLANTS  &LR; and sponsor grants.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the truly hip will do tomorrow night at the Cow
Palace, at the Friends of Recreation &AMP; Parks Preview Party, an
early look at the S.F. Flower &AMP; Garden Show. The money goes to
grants for neighborhood parks near you (tickets $150, call
415-750-5441).
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Cow Palace rest rooms were switched around for
some reason for the Friends event, and women were startled to walk
into a rest room that had urinals, each filled with potted flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Most women don't realize how common that is. We guys think plain
urinals just look, you know, tacky.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; LATE SATURDAY  &LR; night, after her show at the Orpheum, Liza Minnelli
stepped out of the Globe restaurant on Pacific for a sidewalk
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Three women on the sidewalk did a double-take, said hello, told
Liza they like her work. Most stars would smile or nod, then turn
away. Liza joined the group and immediately was giggling with the
girls like they were her best buddies.
</P>
<P>
   Liza is old, she's overweight, she has been through throat and
hip surgery and she's launching a comeback, singing tunes from her
dad's movies. She should call it the ``What the Hell World Tour.''
We should all be so gutsy.
</P>
<P>
   Liza turned 54 on Sunday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want to do for your birthday?'' a friend asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to laugh,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; SKIN DOC  &LR; footnote: Sources at two big downtown restaurants tell me
that the dermatologists are incredible drinkers, quantity and
quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go for our most expensive wine,'' a GM said.
</P>
<P>
   That works well. Many rich folk who get face-lifts also own
interests in wineries. So the money they spend on wrinkle work
boomerangs back to them in wine sales. It's called karma.
</P>
<P>
   Or: You scratch my back, I'll sand your face.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; A SUBWAY  &LR; to Chinatown. Sounds like a cool novel title.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, city transportation people have been quietly
planning that subway. I guess they hold underground planning
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good idea, but why not spend more money and dig tunnels
and parking lots under the entire city, and declare the surface
streets a car-free zone?
</P>
<P>
   Cars are trouble. The Wall Street Journal reports that San
Francisco drivers have more car crashes per capita than Los Angeles
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, Fifth and Mission, a woman sat through an entire
green light, gabbing on her cell phone. Then the light turned red
and she glanced up, realized her silly goof and hit the gas, as
pedestrians danced out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   I can't wait for the new computer-and-Internet-equipped cars.
Pedestrians won't be killed, they'll be deleted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Scott Ostler's column appears Monday through Friday. You can reach
him at (415) 777-7031, fax him at (415) 896-1107 or send him an
e-mail at  &LR; ostler &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
